<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES 7, INDIANS 1 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Like superpowers in the baseball world, the Yankees
and the Cleveland Indians are wary of each other, their resources
and abilities comparable, their recent history tense. Before the
Yankees even earn a chance to win the World Series and establish
themselves as one of the greatest teams of the 20th century, they
are probably going to have to beat Cleveland in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how many games the Yankees win in the regular
season, the Indians present a major obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   But not Tuesday night. Behind the pitching of Andy Pettitte and
a lusty 12-hit outbreak that included six for extra bases, the
Yankees were 7-1 winners over Cleveland to give them a split of the
two-game series at Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte allowed just six hits in improving to 12-5, and Chuck
Knoblauch, breaking out of a recent offensive funk, had two hits,
including his sixth home run.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland assumed an early lead after Jim Thome, their most
productive hitter, was hit by a Pettitte fastball on the right
wrist in the first inning. Thome was forced to leave the game; An
X-ray revealed no fracture.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman's subsequent sacrifice fly scored Vizquel. But
Ricky Ledee doubled home Chad Curtis in the Yankee second, and in
the third, Tino Martinez laced a single off Cleveland's Dave Burba
(10-7) to snap the tie. Martinez doubled to open the sixth inning,
then scored when Darryl Strawberry followed with a double.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Strawberry was replaced by a pinch-runner, the
strongest indication to date that the Yankees are growing more
concerned with the condition of his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, who had singled in the third, drove his home run
leading off the seventh. Knoblauch, whose average dipped to .259
last Thursday, has hits in his last five games and has consistently
hit the ball hard.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte retired 12 consecutive batters at one point, and
cruised to his fourth complete game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' record of 66-21 matches the best mark in the 20th
Century after 87 games. They are on a pace to win 123 games and to
shatter both the major league mark of 116 victories by the 1906
Chicago Cubs and the American League mark of 111 victories, set by
Cleveland in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   If the playoffs were to start today, the Yankees would play the
A.L. West leader in the first round, while Cleveland would play
Boston. If Cleveland slumps a bit, the Yankees may again play the
Indians in the first round.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
