u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WOMEN-GOLFERS-ART     07-15 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOMEN-GOLFERS-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRIENDLY MERGER OF GENERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Walking back from a water cooler near the
third tee at the Wykagyl Country Club on Tuesday, Nancy Lopez
handed Se Ri Pak a cup of water. ``Here, let me buy you a drink,''
Lopez said with a big smile. Smiling back, Pak took the cup and
thanked her playing partner.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of many lighthearted moments between the 41-year-old
Lopez and the 20-year-old Pak in a practice round for this week's
JAL Big Apple Classic that provided a merging of two generations of
golfing sensations: the most charismatic women's golfer over the
last two decades, and the young South Korean player who has stunned
the golf world with her electrifying and record-breaking play in
the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my idea,'' Lopez said later. ``I asked Se Ri at the
Jamie Farr tournament if she would play a practice round with me
here at Wykagyl. We played together the last two days of the LPGA
Championships, but this was much more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans who missed them Tuesday will get another chance later
this week, under more competitive circumstances. Lopez and Pak will
be paired together, along with Hiromi Kobayashi, in the first two
rounds of the tournament on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with Pak and Lori Kane of Canada, Lopez constantly
flashed the smile that has endeared her to millions of fans during
her tenure as one of the sport's most popular ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Lopez patted Pak on the back and elicited smiles
from the South Korean, who over the last two weeks has won the U.S.
Women's Open and the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic; in the latter, she
shot a round of 61 that was the lowest score ever in the Ladies
Professional Golf Association, and finished at 23 under par, tying
the tour record.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez knows what that kind of breakthrough is like. In her
rookie year of 1978 she won nine tournaments, including five in a
row, the third of which came at Wykagyl. She has won 48 tournaments
over all in her storied career, but has struggled recently, missing
the cut in her last three outings. They included the U.S. Open, in
which she has finished second four times but has never won. It's
the most significant omission from her Hall of Fame resume.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no professional jealousy evident Tuesday as Lopez
walked and talked with Pak, although Lopez admittedly did most of
the talking. ``I told her to have fun like I did when I was her
age,'' Lopez said. ``And I think she will because she's got a great
attitude and she's giggly like me. She's very relaxed and smiles a
lot between shots, but then she's all business when she gets ready
to hit her shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Lopez offer any advice to Pak?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I did tell her not to let the media and others take up
too much of her time,'' Lopez said. ``I told her that can burn you
out. But mainly I told Se Ri to enjoy herself and to laugh a lot,
which she does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Asked if she could compare her meteoric start in 1978 to Pak's
overnight success this year _ she has also won a second women's
major tournament, the McDonald's LPGA Championships in mid-May _
Lopez said: ``I think it's tougher for her, coming from another
country and not understanding or speaking English very well. But
she seems to handle the pressure very well. And I think she's great
for women's golf because we seemed to have hit a lull until Se Ri
came along.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak, wearing a white baseball cap and wraparound sunglasses,
admitted that playing the practice round with Lopez was both
relaxing and fun. ``She's so nice to people, and I want to be like
her,'' Pak said. ``She's always smiling and always seems to be
having fun. And she's such a nice person. She told me that I have
many years ahead of me and just to play my game and not to push
myself. And she told me to be happy and to have a good time when
I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Pak needed a role model for how to endear herself to the
fans, then she could have no better playing partner. Lopez, who has
not played in the JAL Big Apple since 1996, frequently stopped to
sign autographs and to chat with spectators during the practice
round.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, whose two consecutive victories have vaulted her to the top
of the LPGA prize money list with earnings of $645,170, said she
became a big fan of Lopez three years ago. ``I just started playing
golf at 14,'' she said in halting English, ``and when I was 17 I
was watching a women's tournament at home and saw Nancy Lopez. She
was always smiling and seemed to be having a good time. And I
decided then I wanted to be like her.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks the 5-foot-6-inch Pak has done a good job in
emulating Lopez's game in her prime. Oddly enough, she has had only
three top-10 finishes, all of them tournament victories.
</P>
<P>
   The age differential of 21 years seemed to be lost on both Pak
and Lopez Tuesday. But Pak alluded to it later, saying, ``She was
winning tournaments before I was born.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Lopez won her first professional event in 1978, a few
months before Pak turned 1. But she was runner-up in her first U.S.
Women's Open in 1975 at the age of 18, two years before Pak was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her parents, Pak also brought her pet 10-week-old beagle
to Wykagyl. The dog's name?
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy,'' Pak said with another smile.
</P>
<P>
   An apt description for Pak and her practice partner on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
