<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHEELS KEEP SPINNING AFTER BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets, through no fault of their own, are giving a
whole new meaning to the term ``sandwich generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets still haven't found a way to be as veteran, as skilled,
as wise or successful as the Atlanta Braves, the perennial National
League East leader and the game's standard setter for the better
part of a decade. That much was clear when the second-place Mets
opened a two-game series with the Braves at Shea Stadium on Tuesday
night knowing that only a sweep could get their 11{-game deficit
down to single digits. That is now impossible in the wake of a
listless 4-2 loss to John Smoltz, the Mets' fourth loss to the
Braves without a victory in less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Mets in the National League East stand
the Philadelphia Phillies, a team that appears ready and able to
wrench the tag of most precocious from the Mets. The Phillies, who
come to Shea for a four-game series beginning Thursday night, won
on Tuesday night and are in a virtual tie with the Mets for second
place. They are a new threat in the already crowded field of
wild-card contenders.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets look at the Phillies, they undoubtedly see spunk
and talent. In essence they see themselves two or three years ago.
Such is the fate of a crowned prince growing a little long in tooth
when it comes to great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   So who can blame the Mets if all they feel in the heat of July
is the frustration and exhaustion of a chase that never seems to
end. The Braves, as designed by General Manager John Schuerholz and
Manager Bobby Cox, rarely allow teams to shed their apprentice
mind-sets or to stop emulating an organization that refuses to be
caught.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the public perception is that the Braves have proved little
because of only one World Series victory among an unprecedented six
straight division titles. And yes, the mercenary Florida Marlins
did manage to buy their way past the Braves and into a World Series
title before disbanding.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you'd better believe that the teams that have done the
bulk of the chasing understand and appreciate the special nature of
the Braves' consistency. The Braves, neither smug nor sufferers of
false modesty, certainly do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like everybody who is on the verge of a potential
breakthrough is designed either to beat us or keep up with us,''
said Tom Glavine, one of the many stars in the Braves' radiant
galaxy of Cy Young-caliber pitchers. ``Every time somebody makes a
move, you hear `in order to win we've got to beat the Braves.'
That's a huge compliment to this organization and what we've been
able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a huge headache for the club most relied upon to stop
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the last four and a half years, that task belonged
more to the Mets than to any other team. It was a challenge picked
up but ultimately unmet by the old-school manager, Dallas Green. It
was a mission avidly sought but unfulfilled by the resurgent
general manager, Joe McIlvaine.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets are in the second season under their new-age
manager, Bobby Valentine, and McIlvaine's assistant turned
replacement, Steve Phillips. Their moves have been plentiful, some
inventive, even daring _ witness the trade for the all-star catcher
Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for all their trying the Mets still only know two
constants: their ever-changing look and the Braves' refusal to be
caught.
</P>
<P>
   When you are forever the speck in the rear-view mirror, the
frustration tends to wear. Or as Valentine plaintively said on
Tuesday: ``We know we can play with them. To win games, you just
have to play well, to make a break or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, of course, have had precious few breaks, especially
while being swept in three games in Atlanta before the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   That flogging pushed the Mets 12{ games out, a devastating
turnaround considering that they had pulled to within five games of
the Braves on May 31 after winning nine in a row, including
Piazza's first seven games with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets are farther out than they were when Piazza was
obtained May 22, when the deficit was nine games. The trade,
intended to rock the N.L. East race, turned out to be just another
dust-up on the periphery of the Braves' universe, a passing fancy
that neither dislodged the Braves nor changed the fortunes of the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still 11 games back, not 3 or 4,'' the veteran Mets
reliever John Franco said with a sigh. ``They've maintained their
level and we still have, not a long ways to go, but without a
doubt, a ways to go.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
