<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA TRIES TO MAKE BEST OF TOUGH YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Today is the two-month anniversary since Bobby
Bonilla, Gary Sheffield, Charles Johnson and Jim Eisenreich joined
the Dodgers as part of the big Mike Piazza trade.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Bonilla had just his third two-RBI game since
joining the club. But it was the sharp single he had in the seventh
inning that the team hopes is a better indicator of his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily look at the little things, I'm just
concentrating on how I feel,'' said Bonilla, who came off the
disabled list July 3 after missing two weeks with an intestinal
infection. ``Right now, I'm just trying to keep more things from
breaking down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, 35, had 97 RBI last season for the Florida Marlins. But
after undergoing offseason surgery to repair his left wrist and
left Achilles' tendon, Bonilla never has gotten going this year.
When Bonilla went down with the intestinal problems, he also was
checked for colon cancer, which proved negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people forget all that I've been through,''
said Bonilla. ``They just look at the numbers. There is a lot more
to it than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Like making the switch to left field to accommodate rookie third
baseman Adrian Beltre. Most in the organization thought he was too
big and too slow to change positions, but so far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first concern was having him go back on balls,'' said Manny
Mota, who is helping Bonilla work on defense. ``That is the biggest
test for his heel. He moves well side to side. So far, so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Like reliever Jeff Shaw, Bonilla is eligible to demand a trade
at the end of the season because he came to the Dodgers in the
middle of a multiyear contract. But unlike Shaw, who is certain to
get a raise with that leverage, Bonilla is staying put. He has two
years left at $6 million per season, part of the lavish deal he
received from Marlins owner Wayne Huizenga. He knows he couldn't
get it again on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where am I going?'' Bonilla said. ``The best thing I can do is
stay healthy and help this team get back in the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Strangest sight of the day: Dodgers GM Tom Lasorda
giving a motivational speech in center field Tuesday afternoon to
youngsters at the baseball camp of former longtime coach Mark
Cresse, who Lasorda fired late last month. Cresse arranged to use
the field before he was let go.... The last three Giants shortstops
played with the Chicago Cubs earlier in their careers _ Rey Sanchez
(1997), Jose Vizcaino (1991-93) and Shawon Dunston (1995).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
