<HEADER>
A5279 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      07-15 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   Age took its time &QL; 
in catching Nicklaus
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHEN Joe Lunchbucket quits his job, he is considered in a state of
grace if he gives his boss two weeks' notice. Jack Nicklaus gave
the fans _ the only boss he ever really had _ two years. If we work
it right, two years will be enough.
</P>
<P>
   You don't adjust overnight to the idea of the PGA Tour without
Nicklaus. Of course, he won't just drop through a trapdoor and
disappear. He will play in the occasional Open Championship, and a
few Senior events, picking his spots. No one ever more fully earned
that right.
</P>
<P>
   He has given himself plenty of time to arrange his exit and to
do it gracefully, a Nicklaus trademark. Two weeks ago, he withdrew
from the British Open because of a bum hip. He hadn't missed a
British Open _ or any of the last 154 majors _ in 36 years. So a
decision he had circled before now became firm. At 58, in less than
perfect health, he knew it was time to rejoin his age group. The
transition will be a gradual one. He will not play again in 1998
after he competes in the U.S. Senior Open in late July.
</P>
<P>
   When the historians rank Nicklaus among the icons of golf, it
won't be his endurance that they praise. He will be cherished for
his consistency, his precision, his gift for winning the big ones.
He was touched by the starlight. If the fans loved him any less
than they loved Arnold Palmer, their affection for Jack grew with
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Master of the majors
</P>
<P>
   He won 18 majors, including the Masters six times, the last at
46. His prime was as prime as it gets. This was one Jack who went
up the hill and never really came down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fact that he was winning at 46 didn't make him
immortal. At roughly the same age, George Foreman was boxing for
millions. Satchel Paige pitched in a World Series. George Blanda
came off the bench to throw a touchdown pass. Gordie Howe slammed a
rival into the boards and slapped home a goal. Jerry Lee Lewis
married a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Jack didn't climb the Himalayas or wrestle an alligator. So what
did he do that made him so special? Simply this: He played his game
better, in his 40s, than anyone else had ever played theirs. Now, a
dozen years later, the news of his departure from the tour still
has the capacity to sadden his fans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the week he won his sixth Masters, everyone wanted a
piece of him. He was virtually out of radio contact with Planet
Earth. I surveyed friends and strangers, wondering, If you could
ask Jack Nicklaus one question, what would it be?
</P>
<P>
   The best one was, ``What does a person do with six identical
green jackets?'' The obvious answer was that he waits each year
with great enthusiasm for St. Patrick's Day. To my surprise, Jack
said it was no problem, mainly because the lords of Augusta
National never gave him another after the first one. At the time,
Jack weighed 220 pounds, and his coat was from Pudge City.
</P>
<P>
   If the jacket doesn't fit ...
</P>
<P>
   He shed 25 pounds, and at the ceremony after his second victory,
the coat no longer fit. The club officials borrowed one that had
belonged to a distinguished member, now deceased, Tom Dewey, the
former governor of New York who lost the historic 1948 presidential
election to Harry Truman. In the end, Jack had a coat tailored for
him by Hart, Schaffner and Marx. It was a 42 regular and still
hangs today, alone, in his locker at Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Jack came within two strokes of leading the 1998
Masters before finishing in a tie for sixth. He does not get the
length on his drives that he once did. But now and then, he can
reach back and find the power of old. The past few years, he worked
harder on his short game. He had never really needed one.
</P>
<P>
   He never lost his competitive edge, or his mental edge. His
concentration was so total, said his fellow pros, that a 747 could
crash two blocks away while he was putting and he wouldn't hear it.
</P>
<P>
   It may or may not be generally known, but Nicklaus has always
been nearsighted and colorblind. At Augusta, they put up the
numbers in green and red, and Jack never knew where he stood. When
he started his own tournament, they painted the scoreboard in red
and black, so he could see who the leaders were. In hundreds of
tourneys, for more than 40 years, his name was often among them.
</P>
<P>
   Golf opened the doors that made Jack a multimillionaire. In a
sense, he turned the American dream on its head. Most middle-aged
men hope they become rich so they can play golf and escape the
pressures of their 9-to-5 lives. But Jack enjoys the time he spends
in his office, checking out the Nicklaus empire. Today, he plays
business. It is his escape from golf.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he and we will find out how much the world of golf will
miss having Nicklaus as a client and a patron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
