 GRIFFEYUS 2 HOMERS POWER SEATTLE (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.1998 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; P &QR; SEATTLE Q With one swing of the bat, Rangers shortstop Kevin
Elster brought
hope to a team that looked tired and listless last night.
 &QL; P &QR; Minutes later, Mariners center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. crushed
that hope
with one more lethal swing of his bat.  &QL; P &QR; GriffeyUs two-run homer
in the seventh inning, his second of the night,
brought a Rangers comeback to a grinding halt and carried Seattle
to a 6-3 victory at the Kingdome.  &QL; P &QR; The two home runs gave Griffey
39 for the season, one fewer than St. Louis
first baseman Mark McGwire and four more than Chicago Cubs
outfielder Sammy Sosa in their three-way pursuit of Roger MarisU
home run record.  &QL; P &QR; RHeUs a good player. Those things are going to
happen,S Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. RSometimes you just have to tip your cap to a
player like that.S  &QL; P &QR; Meanwhile, Juan GonzalezUs pursuit of Hack
WilsonUs record of 190 runs
batted in has come to a standstill. He is stuck on 101 after not
driving in a run on the six-game road trip.  &QL; P &QR; The Rangers finished
the trip with a three-game losing streak. They had a
chance to move back into first place in the American League West
but instead remain one-half game behind the Anaheim Angels, who
lost to Oakland. The Rangers return home tonight to play the
Baltimore Orioles, who are riding a six-game winning streak.  &QL; P &QR; The
Rangers managed two hits through six innings against Mariners
starter
Jeff Fassero. They trailed 4-0 going into the seventh before
Gonzalez led off with an infield single. After he was forced at
second by Ivan Rodriguez, Will Clark doubled to right-center field,
putting runners on second and third.  &QL; P &QR; Mike Simms struck out, but
Elster golfed a 2-1 pitch over the right-center
field fence, cutting the Mariners lead to 4-3.  &QL; P &QR; It was obvious
that the MarinersU seventh would be crucial. They had Alex
Rodriguez, Griffey and Edgar Martinez coming up against Rangers
starter John Burkett. If the Rangers had stopped them, the top of
the order was coming up in the eighth and a rested John Wetteland
was waiting in the bullpen.  &QL; P &QR; RCertainly, when you get back to
within 4-3, youUd like to have a 1-2-3
inning,S Oates said. RIt didnUt work out that way.S  &QL; P &QR; Rodriguez
hit BurkettUs first pitch on the ground through the middle for a
leadoff single. Oates assigned left-hander Scott Bailes the task of
dealing with Griffey. One night earlier Bailes was asked to do the
same thing and got Griffey to hit a grounder to first.  &QL; P &QR; This time
he smashed a two-run blast into the right-field bleachers. The
Rangers never recovered.  &QL; P &QR; Burkett took the loss, dropping his
record to 5-10 with a 5.72 earned-run
average.  &QL; P &QR; RI thought Burkett threw the ball pretty good against a
pretty good-hitting
ballclub,S Oates said. RBut we didnUt get anything going except for
the one inning.S  &QL; P &QR; The Mariners struck quickly against Burkett in
the first with the help of a
mental mistake by Rangers third baseman Fernando Tatis when Joey
Cora hit a 1-2 pitch on a line into the right-field corner. Cora
went for a triple and should have been out. But Tatis took a strong
relay throw from second baseman Mark McLemore too far in front of
the bag, allowing Cora to slide around the tag. He scored on
RodriguezUs ground out.  &QL; P &QR; The Mariners added three runs in the
third inning, the first coming on
GriffeyUs home run into the right-field seats. Martinez singled to
center, David Segui doubled off the top of the wall in right-center
field and Jay Buhner smacked a two-run single up the middle, giving
the Mariners a 4-0 lead.
</P>
