<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S 2 HOMERS POWER SEATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With one swing of the bat, Rangers shortstop Kevin
Elster brought hope to a team that looked tired and listless last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Mariners center fielder Ken Griffey Jr. crushed
that hope with one more lethal swing of his bat.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's two-run homer in the seventh inning, his second of the
night, brought a Rangers comeback to a grinding halt and carried
Seattle to a 6-3 victory at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The two home runs gave Griffey 39 for the season, one fewer than
St. Louis first baseman Mark McGwire and four more than Chicago
Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa in their three-way pursuit of Roger
Maris' home run record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player. Those things are going to happen,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said. ``Sometimes you just have to tip
your cap to a player like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Juan Gonzalez's pursuit of Hack Wilson's record of
190 runs batted in has come to a standstill. He is stuck on 101
after not driving in a run on the six-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finished the trip with a three-game losing streak.
They had a chance to move back into first place in the American
League West but instead remain one-half game behind the Anaheim
Angels, who lost to Oakland. The Rangers return home tonight to
play the Baltimore Orioles, who are riding a six-game winning
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers managed two hits through six innings against
Mariners starter Jeff Fassero. They trailed 4-0 going into the
seventh before Gonzalez led off with an infield single. After he
was forced at second by Ivan Rodriguez, Will Clark doubled to
right-center field, putting runners on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Simms struck out, but Elster golfed a 2-1 pitch over the
right-center field fence, cutting the Mariners lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious that the Mariners' seventh would be crucial. They
had Alex Rodriguez, Griffey and Edgar Martinez coming up against
Rangers starter John Burkett. If the Rangers had stopped them, the
top of the order was coming up in the eighth and a rested John
Wetteland was waiting in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, when you get back to within 4-3, you'd like to have
a 1-2-3 inning,'' Oates said. ``It didn't work out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hit Burkett's first pitch on the ground through the
middle for a leadoff single. Oates assigned left-hander Scott
Bailes the task of dealing with Griffey. One night earlier Bailes
was asked to do the same thing and got Griffey to hit a grounder to
first.
</P>
<P>
   This time he smashed a two-run blast into the right-field
bleachers. The Rangers never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett took the loss, dropping his record to 5-10 with a 5.72
earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Burkett threw the ball pretty good against a pretty
good-hitting ballclub,'' Oates said. ``But we didn't get anything
going except for the one inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners struck quickly against Burkett in the first with
the help of a mental mistake by Rangers third baseman Fernando
Tatis when Joey Cora hit a 1-2 pitch on a line into the right-field
corner. Cora went for a triple and should have been out. But Tatis
took a strong relay throw from second baseman Mark McLemore too far
in front of the bag, allowing Cora to slide around the tag. He
scored on Rodriguez's ground out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners added three runs in the third inning, the first
coming on Griffey's home run into the right-field seats. Martinez
singled to center, David Segui doubled off the top of the wall in
right-center field and Jay Buhner smacked a two-run single up the
middle, giving the Mariners a 4-0 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
