<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JENKINS-BRITISHOPEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLD, HARD FACTS ABOUT ROYAL BIRKDALE 
BY BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Behold the sand lizard, the marsh pennywort
and the common toad. They know many things. Proprietors of the sand
dunes at Royal Birkdale, they scoff at your ski hats and overcoats.
It is summer, they say. Come take a refreshing dip in our 41-degree
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   I am inside the press tent at the British Open golf tournament,
which will begin Thursday, allowing that the players can keep their
feet. The wind outside is howling, freezing, unforgiving. The skies
are leaden and the forecast is for ``Get inside, laddie, you'll
catch yer death o'cold.''
</P>
<P>
   And it couldn't be more perfect. The Masters is a warm, still
afternoon at the cathedral. The U.S. Open means gorgeous layouts
and elaborate clubhouses. The British Open is a stark, flat course
in the middle of nowhere, with your hat blowing off and your ball
about two feet deep in a patch of reeds. There isn't much reward
afterward, either, although the Brits don't need much _ just a
scotch without ice or a lukewarm beer.
</P>
<P>
   To find this place, you take the three-hour train ride from
London to Liverpool, where you resist the temptation to find
Michael Owen's place or the Beatles' old hangouts. Pressing on
southward, make a hard left at Bootle, continue earnestly through
Old Roan, and stop when you hear the cheery tune of the willow
warbler. If he's in concert with the coots and mute swans, all the
better. The first hole can't be far away.
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of Birkdale _ aside from some of the richest
golf lore of modern times. It doesn't have that brown, bone-dry
look you associate with St. Andrews or Royal Troon. It is
spectacularly green, thanks to the heavy rains of spring. ``I've
never seen it so green,'' marveled Mark O'Meara yesterday. ``The
course is in incredibly great shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The fairways may be gorgeous, but the thick, absurdly high rough
makes the Olympic Club's look like your bedroom carpet. Thursday's
first round can't come soon enough for the players, because they're
fresh out of balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hit it 30 yards off line and the wind blows it over
some sand dune and you can't even see where it lands, there's no
point in even looking for it,'' said U.S. Open champion Lee Janzen,
who ought to know. He lost five balls in a practice round (not to
be outdone, Tom Lehman lost six). And it's not just the search that
unnerves these guys; they get to freeze along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think even par could win the tournament,'' Janzen said.
``And I'll be amazed if somebody gets through it without a
double-bogey.''
</P>
<P>
   The course is noted for its exotic, carefully preserved
wildlife. As the lizards and toads could tell you, there are two
categories of British Open winners around here: those who
completely lost it afterward, to the point of giving up the game,
and those who were flat-out the best players in the world at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The first category is occupied solely by Ian Baker-Finch, who
won the 1991 tournament and then suffered the strangest golf
breakdown anyone could recall (see the British Open notebook).
</P>
<P>
   The other list would be Arnold Palmer, Tom Watson, Lee Trevino,
Johnny Miller and Peter Thomson, the great Australian player who
won two of his five British Open titles here in 1954 and 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In a tournament in which everything is done just so, in the fine
British tradition, Thomson caused a scandal in '54 when he casually
backhanded his final putt into the hole. The notion was somewhat
cavalier, as he won it by just one stroke, and British TV
commentator (and former Ryder Cup player) Peter Alliss called it
``the confidence, stupidity or arrogance of youth.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared to the Palmer sensation in '61. In
a single weekend, Palmer made the Open fashionable for American
players and hit the greatest golf shot of all time. That's what
they say around here, anyway. It was the essence of Arnie, that's
for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Welchman Dai Rees by a stroke on the final day,
Palmer drove deep into the right rough on 15, about 120 yards from
the green. It was raining, the wind was up, and the ball had
settled beneath a bush, and it was an uphill lie. The only
conceivable play was a little wedge to safety. Instead, Palmer
pulled out a 6-iron and addressed the ball like a man trying to
pummel a rattlesnake. Photographs show a huge chunk of Lancashire
earth being uprooted by the swing _ and the ball came to within 15
feet on a small, plateaued green. Two putts and three holes later,
Palmer had won the tournament. By one shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits are not given to overstatement, but they broke all the
laws here. They actually mounted a plaque to commemorate that shot,
a flat piece of stone with Palmer's name and the date engraved. As
the modern-day players passed by yesterday, they stopped out of
curiosity. Surveying the situation, imagining themselves as Palmer,
they could only laugh, out of sheer respect.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Birkdale is where Lee Trevino outdueled Liang Huan Lu, a
gentleman from Taiwan, in 1971. Trevino was hot, the way only a
natural-born hustler gets hot, having already won the U.S. and
Canadian Opens. While Mr. Lu, as they called him, politely doffed
his porkpie hat to the crowd, Trevino was a fountain of wisecracks.
``We put down my bag to hunt for the ball,'' he'd say after driving
into the thick rough. ``Found the ball, lost the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the course on which Johnny Miller shot a final-day 66 to
win what seemed like his 418th golf tournament and a lot of blond,
mop-haired kids said to themselves, ``That looks easy. Could I do
that?'' (Answer: No.) It was 1976, a tournament that also marked
the arrival of 19-year-old Spaniard Seve Ballesteros, who hit an
astonishingly creative and difficult bump-and-run shot between two
bunkers to birdie the 18th hole and tie for second with Jack
Nicklaus. With full grasp of the moment and what it meant to
European golf, Miller putted out ahead of Ballesteros to allow this
exciting kid the final stroke.
</P>
<P>
   The next Royal Birkdale episode was 1983, when Tom Watson hit
the second greatest shot of all time. By local standards, of
course. In the third round, Hale Irwin had a cinch tap-in at the
14th hole and simply fanned, missing it completely with a
left-handed swipe. ``The only thing worse,'' said Irwin, ``would be
to lose by one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, thanks to Watson, is exactly what happened. Needing a
par-4 on No.18 to secure the victory, Watson lined up a two-iron
from 213 yards on his second shot and drilled it to the heart of
the green. The shot of his life. ``The shot I'll take to the
grave,'' he has often said.
</P>
<P>
   That was Watson's fifth British Open title, leaving him one
short of the record held by British legend Harry Vardon and others.
He has not won one since, but he keeps coming back. The tradition
and all that. I suspect he misses the pennywarts as well.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
