<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS OUT OF CONTROL AS A'S, ROGERS CRUISE 
BY NANCY GAY
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Terry Collins' face said it all, the pained
expression of a frustrated man simmering in his own stomach acid.
It became clear in the opening inning Tuesday that his first-place
Angels were bent on self-destruction, as soon as shortstop Gary
DiSarcina launched a routine putout throw to first base that almost
sailed into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get beat, you get beat. You can't give away runs,''
Collins, the Angels manager, concluded in a huff. And that about
sums it up.
</P>
<P>
   Three messy errors spelled three unearned runs Anaheim could not
afford. All the while, the A's were getting in their licks _
finally _ enough to give a shaky Kenny Rogers the early cushion he
needed and more than enough for an impressive 6-2 victory before
10,231 sun-splashed spectators at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rogers surrendered only four hits and three walks in
earning his ninth win, he left the game after six innings with a
stiff left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``My legs didn't feel good from the beginning and I could feel
it tightening up in that (sixth) inning,'' said Rogers, whose
earned-run average dipped below 3.00 (2.92) for the first time
since April 8. ``I just wanted to finish the inning. Give it a few
days and it'll be OK. I won't miss a start.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, too. After the three-game implosion against the
Rangers, the A's have done an admirable about-face, much of it
because of fine starting pitching. Until Rogers departed early, A's
starters had tossed at least seven innings in each outing since the
All-Star break, and they have allowed only three earned runs in 43
innings during that span.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has been under fire, but a flicker of life appeared
in the form of Tim Worrell. The right-handed reliever, picked up
Sunday from Cleveland for a player to be named, made his A's debut
and got his new team out of a huge jam in the eighth, when Anaheim
mounted its only real threat.
</P>
<P>
   With two runs in and Garret Anderson on second with one out,
Worrell fell behind 3-1 on catcher Phil Nevin before recovering to
strike him out. Worrell then got pinch-hitter Orlando Palmeiro to
fly out to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job, getting those last two outs for us. It was
nice for him to get his feet wet,'' said A's manager Art Howe, who
can't help but feel energized by the way his A's are tackling the
division leaders.
</P>
<P>
   They were 1-for-11 against the Angels in 1997, and had lost 14
of their past 15 against them before an ego-building three-game
sweep at Anaheim to end the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's five in a row against the AL West front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team's exciting. We have a lot of confidence right now,
and we know we're in the middle of things,'' said Matt Stairs, who
drove in Rickey Henderson with a single to left in the three-run
first and hit a two-out RBI single in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people take us lightly, we're gonna catch people in this
pennant race,'' Stairs said.
</P>
<P>
   Sense the change? There's some swagger in the A's clubhouse, and
it's about time. As they scurry toward the .500 mark, the A's are
realizing that the deficit between third place and first may be as
few as seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to where we were before the break, and we've got a
chance to go forward,'' Howe said. ``Seven out _ that's only a week
of work.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly has not been a good week for the Angels, who have
dropped four of their past six games since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we owe them a lot,'' Stairs said. ``They kind of
embarrassed us last year _ not kind of, they did; I mean, they
kicked our ass last year. So this is revenge. We wanted to come out
and play well, get to them early and we did.'' &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
