<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHTMARE OVER FOR BAKER-FINCH 
BY BRUCE JENKINS
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN NOTES-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ As he walked up the 18th fairway, he swore
he could hear applause in the distance. It was just a weekday round
at Royal Birkdale, nobody in the stands, but for Ian Baker-Finch,
nothing in golf can be ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   This was a month ago, the first time Baker-Finch had played the
course since his spectacular British Open victory in 1991. He shot
a 29 on the front nine that day, finished with a 66, and further
established his reputation as one of the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
   And then he fell apart _ in ways even the most brutal hackers
couldn't understand. Baker-Finch went from a first-rate pro to a
guy who was lucky to shoot 85. He missed 32 straight cuts on the
PGA Tour. He hit a ball at St. Andrews, in the 1995 British Open,
that went 170 yards dead to his left. He went through dozens of
coaches, psychologists, hypnotists; nothing worked. In fact, it got
worse. In last year's British Open at Royal Troon, he shot a 92 _
the worst score by a past champion in modern times. He was gaunt,
hollow-eyed and terrified, at one point hitting a pitiful little
dribbler on what was supposed to be a lofty pitch shot.
</P>
<P>
   And the week after that tournament, he played a casual round
with a friend on his home course, Sanctuary Cove on the Gold Coast
of Queensland, Australia. He shot a 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to do,'' he said, ``is be able to change my
name, come back in a different body, and go play without the
pressure of being Ian Baker-Finch.''
</P>
<P>
   The source of his problems has never been fully explained.
Friends say Baker-Finch is a man of great humility and simply isn't
comfortable with the pressure of competing in majors. It is well
established that while his game is a disaster in public, he plays
beautifully in private _ and he's comfortable with that. Now
retired from the Tour at 37, with a life in broadcasting and course
design, Baker-Finch will be at Royal Birkdale this week as a member
of the ABC television crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relaxed,'' he said before his departure from the United
States. ``I'm really enjoying life again.''
</P>
<P>
   They have always welcomed Baker-Finch around here. They remember
the tender scene of his acceptance speech in '91, the big smile on
his face and the sight of his young daughter, Hayley, happily
tossing sand in a nearby bunker. And then knew he was coming last
month. That  &LR; was  &LR; applause Baker-Finch heard, because club
officials had rigged up loudspeakers to play a tape of him walking
up the 18th in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' Baker-Finch said. ``The staff had all
gathered at the windows of the clubhouse, and they were applauding.
It was a marvelous moment, one I will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ON SECOND THOUGHT: A trip overseas gives you a new perspective
on things _ the recent U.S. Open at the Olympic Club, for instance.
In the Sunday Telegraph, sportswriter Derek Lawrenson described
Olympic as a ``tricked-up'' course that eliminated the use of the
driver. He called the tournament ``utterly wretched'' and quoted
Irish golf architect Pat Ruddy as saying, ``It was like turning up
to watch a piano concerto, only to find that the pianist is playing
with half the keys missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many players, particularly those outside America, hold the
British Open in the highest regard. ``You obviously take any major
that comes along,'' said Ernie Els, ``but the British is (begin
ital) the (end ital) Open championship. The crowds are much larger,
and when you see those stands and feel the atmosphere, all the
history _ it's just different from any other tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   MISCELLANY: Don't miss Tiger Woods if the wind's at his back. He
hauled out his driver in a gale during Monday's practice and hit a
457-yard drive on No. 8. . . . Woods is still playing with four
bodyguards, just as he did at Royal Troon last year. Some feel it
isn't necessary, in light of the polite British crowds, but ``I
feel it's justified,'' he says. ``I don't know how many players get
death threats, or stuff of that nature, but I do.'' . . . Els, who
played the U.S. Open against his physicians' advice, is still
having problems with his back. He plans to take a one-month layoff
after the British Open. . . . No Michael Jordan or Pete Sampras in
big-time golf. The last 15 majors have been won by 15 different
players.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are waning for Colin Montgomerie, who has missed four of
the last six British Open cuts despite being the leading player in
Europe for five years. Trying to be a nice guy, Montgomerie injured
his ankle tripping over a stone as he attempted to sign autographs
during the recent Irish Open. . . . Jack Nicklaus' son, Gary, had a
shot at qualifying at nearby Hillside until he bogeyed the last
three holes, fell into a seven-way playoff and saw a single
qualifying spot go elsewhere. . . . Nick Faldo, battling a nasty
case of golfer's elbow, says he won't know until Thursday morning
if he can play. In practice rounds, he has been putting with one
hand, setting up fairway shots on a tee, or not hitting the ball at
all, just visualizing a shot and walking to where he believes it
would have gone. A Guardian headline called it ``Virtual Faldo.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
