<SLUG> BC-GLF-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
</HEADLINE>
  
 Summer and sports gut-punch England (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ A spot of bother.
</P>
<P>
   A bloody shame, too.
</P>
<P>
   Upon the eve of one of England's most revered athletic
tournaments, the Open (not the British Open, mind you; it's the
Open, and only ninnies from America call it anything else), British
athletes have had some lamentable times lately on the playing
fields, be it Eton or beyond.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost, of course, was the early departure from the
World Cup. It wasn't that England was a pre-tourney favorite. But
the fact that subsequent results showed no team was clearly
dominant, coupled with the fact that the Brits were ousted from
their national passion by the hated Argentines on a dreadful
shootout, has created a sour regret among Her Majesty's subjects.
</P>
<P>
   As Oliver Holt, London Times columnist, put it, ``It is now
clear they could have beaten them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the blasted French won the thing. British fans and press
have given their Channel brothers a perfunctory salute, but the
politeness hardly hides the sneering contempt the limeys feel
toward the bloody frogs.
</P>
<P>
   British newspapers were filled with haughty dismissals of the
laissez-faire attitude of the French toward futbol until the host
country suddenly in the last week found it fashionable to exult
publicly over the appearance in the finals of ``Les Bleus.''
</P>
<P>
   The French, of course, maintain the only contributions to soccer
made by the English in the 32 years since they last won the Coupe
du Monde have been ``les hooligans.'' So pass the champagne, Clive,
and shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Brits had a nice ride at Wimbledon with a
fresh-faced youngster named Tim Henman, who reached the semifinals,
where an Englishman has not won almost since Stonehenge was merely
an idea sketched in Bronze Age mud.
</P>
<P>
   But Henman lost, too. Again, ``Rule Britannia'' stayed stuck in
the throat.
</P>
<P>
   The story was the same for what is known as motorcar racing. The
annual British Grand Prix for Formula One cars was held at
Silverstone on Sunday in a wretched storm that wiped out all but
nine of the 22 entrants.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was German Michael Schumacher, who mastered the mud
far better than the three entrants from the United Kingdom, where
mud was invented.
</P>
<P>
   Another wheeled sport gave hope, however. The Super Bowl of bike
racing, the Tour de France, began Sunday in Dublin, of all places,
where the first day was won by a Brit, of all people.
</P>
<P>
   The tour organizers thought it would be tres chic to put the
prologue segment in a different country every year to help with
hype. It worked brilliantly Sunday because Chris Boardman,
Britain's 1992 Olympic cycling gold medalist, won the segment as
well as major face time on TV and in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Boardman took a header into a concrete wall that
split open his helmet, knocked him cold, sent him to the hospital
and ended his tour. He's OK, which is more than can be said for the
British sporting psyche.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes perhaps the final chance for international sporting
redemption. Starting Thursday, the British specialty of stiff upper
lips will be of tremendous value, because it might be the only
weapon of consequence against elements straight out of an Irish sea
chantey.
</P>
<P>
   While it is true that Opens are almost always wind-whipped and
frost-nipped, the 127th annual version that begins Thursday at the
Royal Birkdale Golf Club holds all the allure of an NFC playoff
game in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The club is on the shoreline outskirts of this semi-tony
Lancashire resort town about 40 minutes north of Liverpool. It is
neither the most glamorous nor historic site for this tourney, but,
hard by the Irish Sea in the middle of Britain's most wretched July
since 1980, it could become the most ghastly in terms of damage to
par.
</P>
<P>
   The winds that nearly wrecked the Grand Prix on Sunday were
recorded at 55 mph here among the grass-covered sand dunes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the winds calmed some Tuesday, Tom Lehman went out for a
quick nine holes of practice at Birkdale and had to quit after
eight. He ran out of golf balls. Lee Janzen and David Duval lost
five balls each.
</P>
<P>
   The last major tourney before golf's big-timers come to the
Northwest for the PGA next month might be cause for so much
exasperation that it might seem a pleasure to slam a tee shot 30
yards into the heart of a big Douglas fir.
</P>
<P>
   For the locals, the saving grace in this imminent tale may well
be found in the person of Lee Westwood, the precocious 25-year-old
Brit who is playing about as well as anyone in the world right now.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 270 days Westwood has won tournaments in Spain,
Japan, Australia, Germany and the United States. Saturday in
Scotland, in conditions similar to what will be found here this
week, Westwood won the Loch Lomond World Invitational tourney by
four strokes.
</P>
<P>
   As fellow islander Colin Montgomerie put it last week at Loch
Lomond, ``Lee has become the man to beat at every tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   That could well be true. Then again, he's British. That's not a
good sign this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's not been a summer, either, which is an even
worse sign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
