<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAULBALL: SEAHAWKS SPARE NO EXPENSE IN BUILDING INTEREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Sam Adams glares into the camera and bellows, ``We're
alive and kicking. What's up? Are you?''
</P>
<P>
   This eye-bugging challenge by the Seahawks' fifth-year defensive
tackle is the most-lasting image of the club's new $1.5 million
advertising campaign. Adams and 10 of his teammates are featured in
TV and radio spots intended to rejuvenate interest in a franchise
that has been floundering for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the latest indication of how much life has changed
under the do-it-now and damn-the-cost ownership of Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to do good things, quality things and do it the right
way,'' club president Bob Whitsitt said yesterday. ``Right now,
we're very excited about what's going on. But we know we have a lot
of work to get the community excited and aware and educated. This
is just one more example of trying to create that excitement and
that awareness that's important to get a focus on football.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Allen had just exercised his option to purchase the
Seahawks from Ken Behring after voters passed a ballot measure to
fund a new football stadium. NFL owners did not approve the sale to
the billionaire co- founder of Microsoft until late August.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months of almost constant change and unprec- edented
upgrades have followed.
</P>
<P>
   The club has hired 30 new employees _ from vice presidents, to
assistant coaches, to ticket sellers, to a new mascot. The team's
headquarters is in the early stages of what will be a
multi-million-dollar renovation and eventual expansion. And for the
second straight offseason, Allen allowed club management to spend
freely in acquiring free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've added a lot of people, but we're bringing it to Paul
Allen's standard of operation,'' vice chairman Bert Kolde said.
</P>
<P>
   The fear when Allen's group took control of the club was that
most longtime employees would be fired. Only a handful have been
asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the emphasis has been on creating a marketing
department and bolstering a ticket-sales staff that weren't needed
when the Seahawks were attracting sellout crowds in the late 1980s
and early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Seahawks had three vice presidents _ Randy
Mueller, Gary Wright and Mickey Loomis. Now there are eight,
including Harry Hutt, senior VP/marketing and operations; Duane
McLean, VP/ticket sales; Scott Patrick, VP/corporate sales; and
Nathaniel ``Buster'' Brown, VP/chief financial officer, who
replaced Loomis in May.
</P>
<P>
   This is a franchise that deteriorated under the tight- fisted
ownership of Behring and saw its fan base erode during too many
seasons of poor on-field performances and too many off-field
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of characterize it as, we've transformed the
franchise,'' Kolde said. ``We did some marketing research a couple
of months ago and what it showed was that the general perception of
the Seahawks as a franchise was very mediocre, kind of moribund, no
personality or attitude or aggressiveness. We decided to try and
adjust all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The TV ads are helping _ with ticket sales and in projecting the
players as people. Last week, 450 new season tickets were sold,
Whitsitt said. That pushes the total to almost 42,000 _ still a far
cry from the 61,500 that used to be the norm, but also a
significant improvement from the all-time low of 37,000 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good look. It gets the Seahawks out there,'' Whitsitt
said of the slick spots that feature players running through the
streets of Seattle. ``It lets the fans know our players a little
bit as people. It's a lot of fun. I'm really happy with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Publicis in less than two weeks, the campaign is one
of the largest efforts in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Widmaier, director of corporate communications for the
NFL, said the league does not chart costs of advertising by its
teams, but the Seahawks' budget is ``an --------------------
impressive figure'' and clearly among the highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've said all along, and we meant it, `If you've got Paul
Allen to be an owner, you'll get a lot more than you bargained
for,''' Whitsitt said. ``He will over-deliver and do things
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
