<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT GIANTS IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After three and a half months and eight and a half
innings, Dodger Stadium finally was rocked to its core.
</P>
<P>
   It happened Tuesday night as Raul Mondesi scored on a wild pitch
by San Francisco's closer Robb Nen that gave the Dodgers a 2-1
victory and a crowd of 41,513 a chance to let loose.
</P>
<P>
   It happened because they realized that regardless of how
disappointing this season has been, the Dodgers have shaved 3{
games off the Giants' wild-card lead in the past six games.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly it seems they have more to come back for today than
Orel Hershiser's first start here since leaving the Dodgers in
1994. They still trail division-leading San Diego by 12{ games but
are only 4{ back of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi reached base after doubling off the glove of a diving
third baseman Bill Mueller. Giants reliever John Johnstone (2-5)
then intentionally walked Gary Sheffield before giving way to Nen.
Eric Karros struck out and pinch hitter Matt Luke should have ended
the inning with a ground ball to short. But Rey Sanchez bobbled the
ball in a hurried attempt to get a force at second.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie third baseman Adrian Beltre was next and got ahead in the
count 1-0. Nen's next pitch was a breaking ball away and ticked off
the glove of catcher Brian Johnson. The ball rolled 15 feet from
home plate, but it was enough to score Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked in the victory was Scott Radinsky, who blew
away the Giants in the final two innings for his fourth victory in
eight decisions. Radinsky, who had six blown saves during two
months as the Dodgers' closer, was brilliant in holding down the
Giants after Charlie Hayes tied the game at one in the seventh with
an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Radinsky struck out five overall and held off the Giants until
Nen's wild pitch scored Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   For six innings, the only run was a fifth-inning homer by
catcher Charles Johnson, who looks like he might be climbing out of
one of his painful-looking batting slumps. Johnson entered the game
just 2 for 19 on this homestand, but he lined a sharp single to
left to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Johnson who went hitless in 35 at-bats after
reaching base on his first at-bat as a Dodger. He broke that slump
with a May 28 home run against Cincinnati. Tuesday, he came up
again in the fifth with two outs and drove a 1-0 fastball from Mark
Gardner 433 feet into the left-field stands for his 12th home run.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, who was shelled for seven runs and nine hits July 4,
the last time he faced the Dodgers, pitched the sixth, then gave
way to Steve Reed. He retired all six batters he faced before
turning the game over to Johnstone.
</P>
<P>
   For six innings, Chan Ho Park looked like the big-game pitcher
of a year ago when he was 5-0 in July and finished tied for the
team lead with 14 victories. He entered the game with a 5-0 record
at Dodger Stadium and was undefeated here in his last 10 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the time he cruised, striking Hayes to end the second,
Brian Johnson to end the fifth and Sanchez to end the sixth. And
though he has been receiving 7.53 runs support per outing, Park
looked like he could make Charles Johnson's home run stand up. One
reason was his control. Park did not walk a batter until he reached
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   But he walked Barry Bonds and Jeff Kent to open that inning.
Park appeared to make the play of the night when he fielded J.T.
Snow's tapper to the mound and fired to second to begin a double
play. Stan Javier was next and Park walked him after getting ahead
in the count 1-2. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   As Park walked off, he did not acknowledge the crowd and when he
reached the dugout, he fired his glove at the back wall.
</P>
<P>
   One batter later, the Dodgers' lead was gone. Antonio Osuna took
over and Hayes drove an 0-1 fastball into left field for a base
hit, scoring Bonds. Osuna then hit Brian Johnson on the top of the
right shoulder. Johnson hit the ground and for a moment it looked
serious. But Johnson got up and walked to first.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers stuck with Osuna. They wanted to keep Radinsky
for left-handed hitters Bonds and Darryl Hamilton for the eighth
inning. Osuna struck out pinch hitter Mueller to end the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Radinsky came on for the eighth and did allow a single to
Sanchez. But he struck out Hamilton and Bonds. Kent, who hit a home
run Monday, was next and Radinsky struck him out to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
