r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     07-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' JULY NO JUNE BLOOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital) Streams of unconsciousness while wondering how much
pocket cash Michael Eisner carries with him: (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Memo to the suits in charge of Disney Sports, the guys at the
top of the Angels' food chain, not Bill Bavasi or Terry Collins:
</P>
<P>
   Those things on the floor at the bottom of your feet are the
arms of your pitching staff. They've actually been falling now for
more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't exactly take a baseball purist to recognize that the
Angels' June boom was one of those kismet-like moments in time.
Despite a staff that was half-injured and half-humble, the Angels
won 22 games in June.
</P>
<P>
   This was gravy. This was a blessing from the baseball gods for
Collins and his players. The Angels' upper echelon, however, looked
at it and decided that all was well and that there was no need or
hurry to spend some bucks and acquire an extra arm.
</P>
<P>
   Now, naturally, the same no-names and retreads who rescued the
team in June are having problems in July. This was predictable.
Omar Olivares was cut loose by Seattle, a team as shorthanded as a
renaissance-era statue. Jarrod Washburn is a rookie. To think they
would keep going like the Eveready Rabbit was incredibly
short-sighted.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the market has been empty. There are eight or nine
teams that would be happy to accept cash and/or an A Level prospect
in exchange for a 30-ish pitcher who can give the Angels some
innings and their current rotation some rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have let Texas get back into the A.L. West race. The
Rangers have already had their slump, and in general they are a
better team than the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   If management can't spring the bucks for another pitcher right
now, it might as well forget about it until 1999. ...
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda acknowledged this week, for the first time, that
his age is a factor in his staying on as the Dodgers' general
manager, both in terms of what's good for him as well as the club.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the Foxies and Dodgers president Bob Graziano
wanted to keep him on, he would welcome having an assistant G.M. to
handle some of the paper workload.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he's sensitive to some fan and media concerns that
he's only interested in what the Dodgers do today, and not
tomorrow. ``I want to get this team to the point where it is
competitive for the next five years and beyond,'' said Lasorda.
``No one cares more about what happens to this franchise as I do.''
...
</P>
<P>
   Brian Bohanon, the pitcher acquired from the Mets to fill the
Dodgers' fifth spot in the rotation, allowed three home runs in
Sunday's loss to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   His next start? Friday in St. Louis against Mark McGwire. Maybe
Busch Stadium fans in left field should be equipped with flak
jackets. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Who's Who nature of the U.S. basketball team headed to the
world championships six of the 15 players played in the CBA last
year stands in contrast to the pace of NBA veterans and rookies
currently dropping by the FILA Summer Pro League at the Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Mason played Tuesday, on the heels of Lamond Murray, the
O'Bannons, and a variety of other former UCLA stars. The NBA Stars
and NBA Rookies teams play in tonight's doubleheader starting at 5
p.m., with Jalen Rose and Tracy McGrady among those scheduled to
play. ...
</P>
<P>
   I think it's safe to say that Bob Davie's reign as the football
coach at Notre Dame will end after his second year.
</P>
<P>
   The age discrimination trial currently under way in South Bend
has underscored exactly what kind of person Davie is. Joe Moore,
the former line coach who filed the suit, testified that Davie was
at the core of former Lou Holtz assistants who undermined Holtz at
the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   And in response to the suit, Davie testified that he didn't fire
Moore because he was old, but because he struck players and didn't
wash his car often. Well, one of those players Davie said was
struck testified in the case for Moore. All this supports a bunch
of stories about Davie that circulated before he was hired.
</P>
<P>
   It's both ironic and comforting to know that the only college
football program more screwed up than USC is Notre Dame. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's one vote for the Mighty Ducks to hire Butch Goring as its
new coach. The former King center and why hasn't his jersey been
retired? lasted slightly more than one season as the Bruins' head
coach in the mid-80s. He's since put in many good years in the
minors perfecting his craft.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if any coach can win given Disney's spending
restraints, but I'd love to see Goring get the opportunity. ...
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how many of those people newly infatuated by soccer
during the World Cup will now start attending Galaxy games?
</P>
<P>
   Not many. The one aspect of the World Cup that has made me tune
in every four years, and tune out soon thereafter, is the
understanding that this is the best tournament on the planet played
by its best talent.
</P>
<P>
   After watching Z.Z., Ronaldo and the Laudrop brothers, how am I
supposed to ratchet down my expectations for the MLS, with its
over-the-hill imports and handful of American headliners, or any
visiting club teams from Mexico and South America?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer: I won't. I will wait for the next World Cup.
...
</P>
<P>
   True story. Late in the second half of the Brazil-Netherlands
game, my 6-year-old son came into the house and demanded control of
the TV remote.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if he would watch the end of the soccer game with me
before returning to Nickelodeon. He agreed, reluctantly. I spent
the next few minutes trying to explain the game and that these were
two of the best teams in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't they call time outs?'' Chris asked me as the medics
ran on the field with a stretcher. I tried to explain penalty time,
but gave up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is the clock running the wrong way?'' my son asked a few
moments later. Not having a clue myself, I advised him to watch the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes passed. Three. Four. Five. Finally, my son sighs and
says, softly, ``This is pretty boring.''
</P>
<P>
   You know, you just can't fool kids.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
