<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5313 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SPI &LR;      07-15 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE GOLF SCENE HAD NICKLAUS' STAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We were one of his first dates. Before he became a certifiable
golf legend, unbelievably wealthy or even the Golden Bear, Jack
Nicklaus and Seattle were an item.
</P>
<P>
   But his hip hurts now, forcing him to skip next month's PGA
Championship at Redmond's Sahalee Country Club, as well as this
week's British Open. His record 146 consecutive majors played, 154
total, is history. End of era.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say what's more disconcerting: That Nicklaus, at
58, is finally showing his age; or the realization that the game's
greatest player likely has swung his last competitive club in our
neighborhood, fueled by his announcement that he won't play past
2000 in any major or regular tour event.
</P>
<P>
   Once he steps out, we will have to rely on memories when we
think of Jack Nicklaus. Ours are superior to most. In Seattle, we
saw him at his best and _ few people can make this claim _ his
worst.
</P>
<P>
   He sampled our fairways in 1962, 1963 and 1965, competing in the
Greater Seattle Open. On his first trip here, the 22-year-old tour
rookie got Tiger Woods treatment. Curious stares, overflow
galleries, the golf messiah label. Every move and word was
recorded. Nicklaus Will Check In Today, declared one P-I headline.
</P>
<P>
   He did not disappoint. Three months after recording his first
pro victory at the 1962 U.S. Open, he collected his second win at
Broadmoor Golf Club. He shot 67, 65, 65 and 68 for a 15-under-par
265 total to beat the late Tony Lema by two strokes. Nicklaus was
rewarded with $4,300 and breakfast at the Space Needle, at the
height of the World's Fair. He shared his golf vision, one that
would prove unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Broadmoor press corps, Nicklaus mesmerized his
audience with his disarming honesty and confidence. ``Sure, I'm
going for titles and records, the same as Arnie (Palmer) and Gary
(Player),'' he said. ``The money and the other good things come
with the titles. It's a little early for me to be thinking about
records yet, but I'm sure going to go after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six years later, the Nicklaus message remains unchanged.
At the U.S. Open in San Francisco last month, he was asked to
reflect on his magical career and said simply, ``I came along and I
got to be king of the hill. I think it's important to get to the
top.''
</P>
<P>
   What was different at Broadmoor and Inglewood was his appearance
and nickname. He was chunky and wore a crewcut. He would not become
the Golden Bear, a dashing figure, until later touring Australia,
when a Melbourne sportswriter decided the visiting golfer resembled
``a cuddly, golden bear.''
</P>
<P>
   At Broadmoor, Nicklaus drew a number of labels that didn't
stick. Baby Beef. The Baby Bull of the Buckeye State. Ohio Fats.
The Fat Kid from Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   His immense popularity was obvious from the start. Wrote late
P-I columnist Royal Brougham: ``When Jack Nicklaus larruped one of
his 300-yard drives straight down the middle of the fairway in
Wednesday's warmup, the roar from the gallery made you think Roger
Maris had just hit a home run in the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Nicklaus only fouled them off. He had a bad case
of the hooks and four-putted his first hole at Inglewood Country
Club. He shot 77 and 72, and missed the cut.
</P>
<P>
   His despair was captured in a P-I front-page headline: Nicklaus
11 Strokes Behind. He had gone 28 tour events before missing his
first cut, and an injury was responsible. After Inglewood, he
wouldn't miss another cut for two years. But to the dismay of
organizers of the 1963 Greater Seattle Open, he had bombed.
</P>
<P>
   After apologizing to the tournament committee for his lackluster
performance, Nicklaus faced reporters. Making no excuses, he scored
points with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really sorry I couldn't have played better,'' he said. ``I
always enjoy coming to the Northwest to play and I wanted to do
everything I could to help the tournament. I'm just hitting the
ball so bad and I couldn't make a putt from eight inches. But I've
had 77s before and I'll probably have them again. It's just one of
those things and there's nothing you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus also promised he would return to Seattle and redeem
himself in 1964, when the tournament shifted back to Broadmoor. He
never made it, taking the week off instead.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years before Nicklaus re-entered the Greater Seattle
Open, which had returned to Inglewood. He was hardly on a mission.
Once in the area, he went fly-fishing and relaxed. Little was made
of his earlier failure at the Kenmore course. In fact, the P-I
picked him to win the 1965 event. There were no arguments from the
rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Nicklaus is the best golfer who ever lived,'' golfer Doug
Sanders said on the eve of the event. ``He's going to stay at the
top as long as he wishes. Who's better? He can murder you with his
tee shots, is a master of the wedge and a fine putter. Jack might
as well throw his irons away. With his woods, who needs an iron?
He's young and he's strong. Nicklaus has overtaken Arnie Palmer and
nobody will ever catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   In this tournament, at least 16 guys did, including Sanders.
Nicklaus shot 69, 74, 72 and 70 for a 3-under 285 and $1,407
payday. He finished in a seven-way tie for ninth place; Sanders
lost in a playoff to Gay Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus bypassed the 1966 Greater Seattle-Everett Open, the
last showing before the event was disbanded and a 32-year tour void
set in. He returned in 1981 and 1984 to play in fund-raising
exhibitions, drawing big crowds at Seattle Golf Club and Sahalee,
but it wasn't quite the same. He set the course record at Sahalee,
shooting 5-under 67, a mark that still stands.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the PGA Championship headed for the Redmond course
this summer, Nicklaus felt no special tug to show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played it once, and I don't hardly remember it,'' he said
candidly in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, however, is doing his part to re-establish the tour in
the Seattle area. He has designed the Snoqualmie Ridge Tournament
Players Course, now under construction and expected to host a
late-summer PGA stop, possibly as soon as next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need something in the Pacific Northwest,'' he said. ``It
certainly has a lot of people who like to play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, a significant number of them took up the game after
watching a chubby kid with a flattop and big swing march down our
fairways.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
