A5340 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWEST-AZR &LR;      07-15 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORD $2.5 MILLION FINE FOR AMERICA WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 and MARY JO PITZL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   America West Airlines has agreed to pay the largest fine in the
history of U.S. aviation to settle allegations of lax maintenance
and operations violations.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.5 million civil penalty involves 26 planes, one-quarter
of the Phoenix-based carrier's fleet, the Federal Aviation
Administration said Tuesday. Safety officials found, among other
things, that 17 of America West's Airbus A320s flew without
``significant structural inspections.''
</P>
<P>
   America West officials characterized its problems as procedural
oversights and maintained that the airline is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best safety record in the industry over the past
15 years,'' said America West Chief Executive Officer &UR; Richard
Goodmanson. ``In all our discussions, safety never came up.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA settlement totals $5 million, but federal regulators
agreed to waive half of that if the carrier meets various
maintenance terms of the settlement over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a big deal here that's going to require
quite an effort by the air carrier,'' said Tom Stuckey, the FAA's
acting deputy director of flight standards.
</P>
<P>
   America West flew more than 41,000 hours over two years in
violation of Federal Aviation Regulations. The airline ignored at
least some of the requirements, the FAA said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it was an inadvertent omission,'' Stuckey
said. ``But after we pointed out problems, there were some
additional flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carrier did not feel that those inspections needed to be
accomplished, &UR; or they were devising a plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Schiavo, a former inspector general for the U.S. Department
of Transportation and a critic of the FAA's safety record, agreed
that the airline has a good safety record. It ranks second best,
behind Southwest Airlines, for its rate of accidents and incidents,
she said in a telephone interview from her home in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   But she said the fine is evidence of a tougher FAA.
</P>
<P>
   Schiavo said the $5 million fine, even if only half of it is
collected, is ``phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's settlement does not clear America West from stepped-up
safety surveillance instituted in June.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, federal regulators will be watching the nation's
ninth-largest carrier more closely than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that . . . this is a brand new program tells you this
would be the safest airline to fly, not the other way around,''
Goodmanson said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement centers on 26 of America West's 104-aircraft
fleet. The FAA singled out 17 Airbus A320s, which flew without
visual structural inspections; eight Boeing 737s, which were
missing cargo netting; and one Boeing 757, which was missing an
elevator actuator, which controls the jetliner's tail flap for
ascent and descent.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring those inspections could be disastrous in the worst
case, Schiavo said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, America West was cited for failing to inspect the
fuselage skin around the cargo and crew doors of 17 Airbuses. These
inspections can turn up cracks, which, left untended, could be
deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cracks in the fuselage are not like dings in the paint,''
Schiavo said. ``They have literally brought down planes.''
</P>
<P>
   That happened in 1988, when an Aloha Airlines jet's top peeled
back, sucking a flight attendant out to her death.
</P>
<P>
   If cargo netting isn't properly installed, bundles and bags can
shift about in flight, throwing a plane off balance. In 1987, Fine
Airlines crashed in Miami when a cargo load shifted on takeoff,
sliding to the back of the plane and tilting the plane's nose
upward. The plane crashed, killing the crew and several people on
the ground, she said.
</P>
<P>
   America West noted that although one of the actuators for the
tail-flap mechanism was not working, the backup was. But, Schiavo
said, redundancy is the key to airline safety, and without a
backup, the critical tail unit was at risk. The tail allows a plane
to climb, descend and maintain flight.
</P>
<P>
   America West operates 27 Airbus A320s, which it began flying in
the early '90s. The carrier also operates 64 Boeing 737s and 13
Boeing 757s.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA settlement made no mention of the 737-100 used to
shuttle the Phoenix Suns basketball team to and from games. The
jetliner, one of the oldest in its fleet, had problems with its
turbulence-controlling yaw damper. The airline also failed to keep
up on maintenance of the aircraft by failing to respond to
airworthiness directives from the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nonsense, complete nonsense,'' Goodmanson said. ``The
plane has virtually been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be totally confident to put my wife and kids on the plane
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   America West has five days to pay the fine. Goodmanson said the
airline, which reported revenue of $1.9 billion and a profit of $75
million last year, won't have a problem paying the amount.
</P>
<P>
   If America West doesn't meet the requirements of the settlement,
it will have to pay the full $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The money will go to the U.S. Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants said they felt vindicated by the FAA's action
since it was clear that the problems stemmed from inspection
lapses, not labor troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, America West officials blamed the FAA's heightened
scrutiny, in part, on its ongoing labor negotiations with pilots
and flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's Stuckey said the labor dispute flagged regulators to
potential problems, but was not the cause of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McGlashen, president of Council 66 of the Association of
Flight Attendants, said Tuesday's move ``dispels any misconception
that the airline's troubles with the FAA are the result of
protracted negotiations with its flight attendants.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me be clear,'' McGlashen said. ``We don't negotiate
safety. We don't use safety issues as a way to gain negotiation
leverage. It never has been or will be in our plan. We don't
conduct concerted plans to call the FAA.''
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants are scheduled to sit down next month with
company officials and a federal arbitrator to discuss compensation
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Steinman, head of the airline's pilot union, said the
settlement shows that the FAA's allegations must be taken
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged that steps have already been taken, but I would
urge our management to exceed the regulatory requirements,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the largest fine ever agreed to by an airline. While
higher fines have been assessed, they have all been negotiated to
smaller amounts. For example, Eastern Airlines was fined $9.5
million but settled for about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said the only penalty larger than the America West
sanction was a $5 million fine against a company that wasn't an
airline _ Chrome Alloy, a repair company based in Illinois. &QL; 
 &UR; Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at 444-8975 or at
kerry.fehr &LR; pni.com via e-
 &UR; mail. &QL; 
 &UR; Mary Jo Pitzl can be reached at 444-8963 or at maryjo.pitzl &LR; pni.com
via
 &UR; e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
