<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY HOMERS TWICE AGAINST RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Normally, reaching the 3,000-hit plateau is an
achievement to cherish because of its historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Ken Griffey Jr., though, to make getting halfway
there just as memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey picked up his 1,500th and 1,501st career hits Tuesday
night in the same manner he's engaged baseball _ with power, grace
and plenty of oohs and aahs.
</P>
<P>
   His second home run of the game _ a two-run shot in the seventh
inning _ propelled the Mariners past the Texas Rangers 6-3 at the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it so many times. He's the best player in the
game,'' M's manager Lou Piniella said. ``He can beat you many ways.
... Junior is Junior. What can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   For as much as the Mariners' two-game sweep of the Rangers was
the Griffey Show, they also can talk of how much better the club is
playing. Tuesday night's victory was the latest in an installment
of Mariner baseball that's featured timely hitting, solid defense
and strong pitching.
</P>
<P>
   M's left-hander Jeff Fassero (9-5) earned his fourth straight
victory. He struck out six and allowed just five hits through eight
strong innings. Mike Timlin pitched the ninth for his third save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been too bad after the All-Star break. So we'll
see,'' said Fassero, who helped the M's creep to within 11 games of
first-place Anaheim in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been throwing the ball well and I've been getting some
runs, which help. . . . Right now, we've got to go one team at a
time. We've got to get over Oakland first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners remained at the bottom of the division _ four games
behind Oakland. However, the M's have hardly looked like a club
floundering in the cellar of late.
</P>
<P>
   They completed a critical six-game stretch with a 4-2 record
(2-2 against Anaheim and 2-0 vs. second-place Texas). Optimism
around this team is like a pimple on an adolescent boy.
</P>
<P>
   It won't go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is good to see. You've got to start somewhere. We've got
to build on this. But things are looking more positive,'' Piniella
said, pointing out the Mariners have five games left on this
11-game homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're starting to realize that if we can do certain
things, we have a chance,'' Timlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cora got the Mariners off to a fast start. He opened the
first inning with a triple and scored moments later. Then,
Griffey's first homer opened the door for a big third inning.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Griffey smacked Texas starter John Burkett's
fastball deep into the right-field bleachers. Leading 2-0, Edgar
Martinez promptly singled and David Segui doubled. Jay Buhner
knocked in Martinez and Segui with a sharp single up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners led 4-0 that quickly and Fassero kept the Rangers
at bay through six innings. His hard slider kept batters off
balance, and Fassero kept his fastball down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when he gets through the first few innings, he's going
to have a good night,'' M's catcher Dan Wilson said. ``He got
through the first three without any damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero allowed just two runners to get in scoring position
until the top of the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and two runners on base, Fassero fell behind Kevin
Elster. Then, Fassero watched his 2-1 pitch sail over the
right-center-field wall. Elster's three-run homer cut the Mariners'
lead to 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why (Junior's) second (homer) was the greatest,''
Fassero said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners finally chased Burkett in their half of the seventh
after Alex Rodriguez's leadoff single. Texas manager Johnny Oates
immediately called upon left-hander Scott Bailes to face Griffey.
</P>
<P>
   Bailes, though, lasted only as long as Griffey's fourth at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey launched Bailes' offering down the right-field line. It
was Griffey's 39th home run this season, increasing his American
League-leading total and pulling him within one of St. Louis
slugger Mark McGwire for the major league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey has 87 RBIs after his fourth two-homer game of the
season and 31st of his career.
</P>
<P>
   After Griffey's homer, Dan Patterson came on and ended the
Mariners' seventh-inning barrage. Burkett (5-10) gave up nine hits
and five earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes good contact,'' Timlin said of Griffey. ``There are
times when he swings and you say `What's he swinging at?' Then, he
hits one out on the next pitch. He's incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
