<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5370 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY HENRY SCHULMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
Ugly 9th Does In Skidding Giants  c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    LOS ANGELES _ The Giants had failed in so many ways on this
horrific road trip to start the second half, but the one fate they
dodged was a ninth-inning suicide.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything in due time, friends. Everything in due time. The
losing streak hit five Tuesday night when closer Robb Nen, pitching
for the first time since he gave up three runs in the All-Star
Game, threw a wild pitch with the bases loaded and two out in the
bottom of the ninth. Raul Mondesi scored from third for a 2-1 Los
Angeles Dodgers victory, to the surprise and delight of 41,513 at
Chavez Ravine.
</P>
<P>
   But things never should have gotten that far. After Nen relieved
John Johnstone and fanned Eric Karros for the second out,
pinch-hitter Matt Luke hit a routine grounder to short. Extra
innings, right?
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Sanchez booted the ball, picked it up and tried to flip it
to Jeff Kent at second for the force. The throw was a little wide,
and Kent dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases now loaded on Sanchez's error and .170-hitting
rookie Adrian Beltre at the plate, Nen tried to throw a 1-0
fastball down and away. It was too far down, and too far away.
Catcher Brian Johnson tried to backhand the ball, but it flew past
him to the backstop. Game over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw it hard, but I've gotten that pitch before,'' Johnson
said. ``My responsibility is to knock the ball down, but I didn't
do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Nen could have pointed a finger toward Sanchez, whose error
extended the inning, but he did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game. It's going to happen sometimes,'' Nen
said. ``This was my fault. I blame myself. I tried to keep the ball
away and it got too far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnstone took some blame himself for allowing the one-out
double to Mondesi that got the rally started. Mondesi hit a shot
that third baseman Bill Mueller deflected toward the left-field
corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get my end of it done,'' Johnstone said. ``I threw a
bad pitch and Mondesi hit a double. I don't know how Billy even saw
it. Mondesi roped it down the line. I've got to be better than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   That should become the Giants' slogan as this nine-game
nightmare of a trip wears on.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have not won since June 5, and the five-game losing
streak matches their longest of the season. They fell eight games
behind the first-place San Diego Padres in the National League
West. Perhaps more significant, their lead in the wild-card race
shrank to a half-game over the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, the third-place Dodgers climbed within 41/2 games
of the Giants in the West. The Giants are 2-9 on the road against
their West Division rivals, the only victories coming in the
season's first week at expansion Arizona. They are 0-2 here, 0-3 at
San Diego and 0-3 at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But numbers are not the name of the game for the Giants right
now. The only equation they must solve is how to win again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not happy to be eight games out and we're not happy with
the way we've started the second half,'' Johnson said. ``The
biggest key for us is to get our house in order. We're not playing
well as a team. We must play well if we want to be in the pennant
race. We're going to see in the next few days, the next week, what
this team is made of.''
</P>
<P>
   The ugly ninth inning marred what had been a picturesque game.
</P>
<P>
   Starting pitchers Chan Ho Park and Mark Gardner engaged in a
who-blinks-first display of terrific pitching until Dodgers catcher
Charles Johnson put the first run on the board in the bottom of the
fifth. With two out, he pulverized a first-pitch breaking ball high
into the left-field pavilion, 435 feet from the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants tied the game at 1-1 in the seventh on a two-out RBI
single by Charlie Hayes off reliever Antonio Osuna, who had just
relieved Park. The inning began with Park walking Barry Bonds and
Kent, but J.T. Snow stunted the rally by checking his swing on a
3-1 pitch and bouncing it to Park, who threw to second to start a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   As they used to say in the Roger Craig era, the Giants' daubers
have to be getting down a bit. They are not botching game after
game with silly mistakes, nor are they stepping to the plate
without a clue. Yet they are still not winning, which takes a toll
on the psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every loss can gnaw at you,'' Johnstone said. ``It's tough,
especially with the position we're in, us chasing the Padres and
the Dodgers chasing us.''
</P>
<P>
   Never this season has the chase for a single victory seemed so
futile. &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
