r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCANDAL-SIGHTSEERS-SF     07-15 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDAL-SIGHTSEERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D.C. SIGHTSEERS FLOCK TO STARR GRAND JURY COURTHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC SANDALOW  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Along Pennsylvania Avenue, the television satellite
trucks lined up outside the E. Barrett Perryman Federal Courthouse
stand as monuments to the capital's appetite for scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Tour buses slow as they pass the courthouse, so guides can tell
visitors from around the world that this is where a grand jury is
listening to evidence about President Clinton and a 24-year-old
former intern. Dozens of television cameras capture the comings and
goings at five entrances.
</P>
<P>
   Though no longer regarded as ominous a threat to the Clinton
presidency, l'affaire Lewinsky remains a fixture on the Washington
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Networks dutifully show pictures of witnesses summoned by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Questions about sex are a
routine part of Mike McCurry's daily White House press briefing.
Republicans regularly cite the controversy as a wild card that
could help them in the November elections. The Internet boasts at
least eight Web sites dedicated to Monica Lewinsky, as well as a
search engine that provides nothing but information about her.
</P>
<P>
   Even if most of America has tired of the once-titillating sex
scandal, those inside the beltway suggest there is no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like getting on an escalator,'' Brookings Institute
presidential scholar Stephen Hess said. ``Once you get on, you
can't just turn it off.''
</P>
<P>
   As Starr's investigation enters its seventh month, the buzz
inside Washington is that he is reaching the end, and the
developments of the next few weeks may determine whether the
scandal becomes an important chapter of American history or merely
an asterisk on Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is eagerly _ or fearfully, according to some _ awaiting
a report from Starr that could set off impeachment hearings by the
House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility is so ripe that Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., recently told Republican colleagues not to stray too far
from the Capitol during the August recess.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton's allies say they can imagine nothing
that Starr might present that would persuade members of Congress to
go after a popular president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is basically over as far as the American people are
concerned,'' said former White House attorney Lanny Davis, who said
he was speaking for himself and not for the administration.
``They've already assumed the worst case . . . and they've already
decided it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republicans may have no appetite for a politically
gut-wrenching process that could have the unintended effect of
elevating Al Gore to the presidency shortly before the next
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office has refused to discuss the timing or the
substance of its report or, for that matter, whether it will submit
a final report at all. Starr's representatives refused to return
repeated phone calls Tuesday, but a spokesman for the office
recently told the Los Angeles Times that the team would not be
pressured to rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize the need to get this done as quickly as possible,''
said Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly. ``We have taken the brunt of
complaints that this is taking a long time, but that's a hit we
have to be prepared to take to fulfill our oath to carry out the
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings inside the courthouse are off limits to the
public, but dozens of journalists outside keep close tabs on who
has testified.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Tripp, the former White House employee who secretly
recorded 20 hours of conversations with Lewinsky, spent her fifth
day before the grand jury Tuesday, and is expected back for at
least another day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is that Starr has few witnesses left to call
_ except for Lewinsky and Clinton, although Starr surprised
observers when it was revealed Tuesday that he had subpoenaed Larry
Cockrell, head of the Secret Service's presidential detail, and
several other agents.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has been negotiating with Starr since January and is
apparently still at odds over what she is willing to share with
prosecutors. Starr will soon have to decide whether to grant
Lewinsky immunity to compel her to testify or indict her and head
for trial.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the Tripp tapes, Lewinsky's value to Starr is
uncertain. In the event that she does testify, the president's
lawyers will no doubt bring up her deposition in the Paula Jones
case, in which she denied under oath that she ever had a sexual
relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been asked several times to testify and declined,
according to several reports, which presents Starr with another
quandary. It is not clear that he has the legal authority to compel
Clinton to testify, although Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said Sunday
that Clinton's refusal to honor a subpoena could be grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And so Washington waits, really without any idea what will
happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't even want to venture a guess,'' said Republican
National Committee spokesman Mike Collins. ``Truth is, no one
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you when it will definitely be over,'' said Michael
Barone, Washington editor of Reader's Digest and the author of the
Almanac of American Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two and a half years. That's when (Clinton's) term ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 0343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
