A5397 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALMON-DAMS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALMON-DAMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAMS TO BE TORN DOWN TO HELP SAVE SALMON  
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BARNUM  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NELSON, Calif. _ Winding through rice fields and almond
orchards, Butte Creek seems an unlikely spot for a salmon
restoration effort that has captured the imagination of
environmentalists and drawn the attention of the highest levels of
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But in a few months, the last of four small irrigation dams will
be torn down just outside this town, and a 20-mile stretch of Butte
Creek, which has the largest remaining population of spring-run
salmon in the state, will be restored to unimpeded flows for the
first time since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   In a state long wracked by divisive conflicts about water, the
$9.5 million dam-removal project is being heralded as a model of
collaboration among farmers, urban water districts and government
agencies to protect an imperiled species.
</P>
<P>
   ``This demonstrates the possibility of finding a new equilibrium
on the landscape,'' Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt told a crowd
of 100 gathered beside McPherrin Dam Tuesday. ``It is a message
that needs to be held up to the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he stepped onto the concrete structure and, surrounded by
TV cameras, took a few symbolic whacks at it with a sledgehammer.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt and many environmentalists also view the removal of dams
along Butte Creek as part of a blossoming national movement to
reassess the need for structures that were once thought to be a
permanent part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Like busy beavers, Americans have constructed roughly 75,000
large dams and 2 million small dams along the country's waterways.
And to be sure, there is still talk, particularly among farmers
here in the Central Valey, of building new ones to meet the demands
of a growing population.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time of heightened concern about the environmental
impact of damming rivers, whether it is to generate electricity or
to supply water, small- to medium-size dams are coming under new
scrutiny by federal agencies and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   At least 20, mostly small hydroelectric dams, have been
destroyed in recent years or scheduled for destruction. The largest
of those is a 160-year-old dam along the Kennebec River in Maine
that federal energy regulators decided last fall should be taken
down.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decade, the operating licenses of 250
hydroelectric dams, including 146 in California, will expire. And
as part of the relicensing of those facilities, federal regulators
will invite debate over whether the environmental costs of the
structures outweigh their usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the beginning of a new era,'' said Rebecca Wodder,
executive director of American Rivers, an environmental group.
``Federal agencies had viewed dams as a fixture. There is now a
recognition that dams can have a finite life cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   And there may be no better example of that recognition than
Butte Creek, said Marc Reisner, the author of ``Cadillac Desert,''
the best-selling account of Western water wars, and a consultant on
restoration projects along Butte Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most actively deconstructed river in the country
right now,'' Reisner said. ``There are more dams coming down on
this than any other river.''
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for tearing down dams along Butte Creek was the
plight of the spring-run salmon, once the most abundant of four
runs of chinook salmon in the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The spring run once migrated by the hundreds of thousands far up
the Feather, Sacramento and San Joaquin rivers each spring. Adult
fish would hold over during the summer months in the cold water
near Mount &UR;  &LR; Shasta and Mount Lassen, and spawn from August to
October.
</P>
<P>
   But Shasta and Oroville dams have confined the fish to the lower
reaches of the Sacramento and Feather rivers, where they are forced
to share a spawning habitat with fall-run chinook salmon and are
losing their unique genetic identity.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the spring run could soon be listed as an
endangered species by both federal and state officials.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four Sacramento Valley streams that still support a
genetically distinct spring run population, Butte Creek is the
largest, with 7,500 fish returning in 1995. The removal of dams
will open up an additional 20 miles of Butte Creek to salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Canal Water District, which supplies water to farms
in Butte and Glenn counties, had used the dams to move water from
irrigation canals on either side of Butte Creek. Without the dams,
the district had to find a way to move the water.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the solution, the district constructed a diversion
that takes water under the creek. The cost of construction was
shared equally by the water district, government wildlife agencies
and urban water districts, including the Metropolitan Water
District in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great project,'' said Richard Golb, executive director
of the Northern California Water Association, which represents
farmers. ``A couple of years ago, doing something like this would
have been taboo. But there is a different ethic in this region
about environmental stewardship.''
</P>
<P>
   But some local farmers are wary, saying the new system is still
untested. Moreover, they are skeptical that the solution that has
worked here could be as successful elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the salmon, but we still have to make it work,''
said Laverne McPherrin, a second-generation rice farmer who owns
1,800 acres just east of Butte Creek and whose McPherrin Dam is one
of those coming down in coming months. ``We'll see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
