<HEADER>
A5555 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYSIN-ART-EDMONTON-70     07-15 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYSIN-ART-EDMONTON-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 50-YEAR TREK THROUGH THE TERRITORY OF THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT ) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ ``He just thought it was awful,
nowheresville,'' William Burroughs said of Edmonton, the boyhood
home of his great friend and collaborator Brion Gysin. Indeed, when
a 16-year-old Gysin boarded a cattle car and headed east, he left
behind this land of his ``exile'' and never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   But the memories remained. As Gysin emerged as a creative force,
he invoked, as if haunted, the vast horizons of the Canadian
prairie in his early Surrealist paintings and later desertscapes of
the Sahara and in his prose works, perhaps most significantly his
autobiographical novel, ``The Process.'' Gysin died in Paris in
1986 at the age of 70, the places of his childhood by then no more
than fragmented dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton is no longer nowheresville. The cattle town of 58,000
that Gysin fled in 1931 has exploded into an urban center just shy
of one million, brimming with oil wealth and maintaining a sturdy
intellectual life. And though Gysin shunned this ``wrong place''
that pummeled away at his psyche, the city is embracing Gysin as a
native son with the first major North American retrospective of his
works, at the Edmonton Art Gallery through Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The show, ``Brion Gysin: I Am That I Am,'' examines the output
of a painter, writer, sound poet (in which works are chanted), tape
composer, lyricist and student of magic who became a cult icon not
so much for the impact of his works as for the scope of his ideas.
The exhibition traces Gysin's career over 50 years: his involvement
in Surrealism in Paris in the 1930's, his painting in Tangier in
the 1950s, his development of the ``cut-up process'' with Burroughs
at the ``Beat Hotel'' in Paris, his calligraphic abstractions in
the 1960s and later his photo and text collages, which he laid over
grids created by a rubber roller. Nestled among the 200 works is a
Dreamachine, a device that when viewed with the eyes closed is
reputed to produce alpha waves that hit the optic nerve and induce
visions. On the back wall of the main gallery hangs the show's
undisputed centerpiece, ``Calligraffiti of Fire,'' an enormous
calligraphic painting in the style of a Japanese makemono, or
folding book, which is read from right to left across 10 canvases.
It was Gysin's last work; Burroughs wept at the sight of it.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Bruce Grenville, a curator originally with the
gallery and now with the Vancouver Art Gallery, and Jose Ferez
Kuri, an independent curator who also works with William Burroughs
Communications in Lawrence, Kan., the exhibition borrows heavily
from the collections of the Musee d'Art Moderne, the Pompidou
Center and the Galerie de France in Paris, as well as the Los
Angeles County Museum of Art and the Spencer Museum of Art at the
University of Kansas in Lawrence. It is scheduled to travel to
galleries across Canada; negotiations are also under way for venues
in Mexico City, Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The seed for Gysin's repatriation was planted by John Geiger, an
Edmonton writer who first came across Gysin's name _ and an
allusion to Alberta _ in 1991 while bingeing on works by Burroughs
and Paul Bowles. Stunned by his discovery, Geiger confirmed the
Edmonton connection through a friend, Chris Cran, a painter from
Calgary and a Burroughs fan himself. Geiger then contacted James
Grauerholz, Burroughs' companion and manager, hoping simply to
acquire a piece of Gysin's art. By the end of the conversation, he
had been persuaded to write Gysin's biography and invited to meet
Burroughs, who gave the project _ and Geiger _ his blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Geiger is the author, with the anthropologist Owen Beattie, of
``Frozen in Time: The Fate of the Franklin Expedition'' and ``Dead
Silence,'' both of which deal with fatal Arctic explorations, and
for him there was an obvious link to Gysin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a connection, I think, between these `strange and
dangerous voyages' and the explorations to unknown places
undertaken by Burroughs and Gysin,'' Geiger said. ``All the
geographic places on the earth have already been visited, so the
only places left to explore are those places in the mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gysin, born in England to Canadian parents in 1916, returned
with his newly widowed mother to her parents' home in Ontario at
the end of World War I, eventually journeying to Edmonton in 1921.
His mother, a dominating woman with aristocratic pretensions,
fretted about her son's literary interests, fearing them to be
``the breeding ground for atheism'' and concluding that ``his only
hope of salvation was the English Catholic atmosphere.'' She
arranged for him to spend two years at Downside, an English public
school. Gysin became an artist upon graduating in 1934. That same
year he moved to Paris, where he was an associate of Picasso, Dali,
Duchamp, de Chirico, Man Ray and Max Ernst, who were all dabbling
in Surrealism at the time. But he also kept company with Gertrude
Stein, Natalie Barney and Alice B. Toklas, whom the Surrealist
power broker Andre Breton disdained. The drawings Gysin contributed
to an important Surrealist group exhibition at the Galerie aux
Quatre Chemins in 1935 were removed, on the orders of Breton _ and
without explanation _ the day of its opening. Gysin always
suspected that Breton had reacted against Gysin's homosexuality.
The expulsion was the first of many disappointments that followed
Gysin throughout his career and, for the developing artist, it had
the effect of a curse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After receiving a Fulbright scholarship for ``The History of
Slavery in Canada,'' which he wrote while in New York, Gysin moved
to Morocco in 1950 at the invitation of Paul Bowles. He stayed
there for parts of the next 23 years, seduced by the ``wild west of
the spirit'' and intrigued by the magic of Middle Eastern folk
religions. He transferred this mysticism to his paintings, which he
overlaid with Arabic script and Japanese calligraphy to form a sort
of cabalistic grid that had the look of language. It was a conceit
that he would use throughout his life, eventually inscribing the
grid on a rubber roller and using the design as a unifying
background _ rather than foreground _ upon which images and texts
were laid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, while cutting a mount for a drawing, Gysin sliced
through a pile of newspapers and, piecing together the fragments at
random, invented what would come to be known as the ``cut-up
process.'' He applied the technique first to a mass of essays that
were to become Burroughs' groundbreaking novel, ``Naked Lunch.''
Later he used it with ``The Third Mind,'' an ambitious
collaboration intended as an exploration of the cut-up method and
an expansion on the idea that when two minds work together, a third
mind results. Other Beat writers followed Gysin's lead, and cut-ups
soon became a sort of manifesto for the abandonment of the literal,
the mundane.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1960s, Gysinmania had set it in. The man seemed to be
everywhere _ planted in Room 703 of the Chelsea Hotel in New York
with the poet John Giorno, whom he introduced to sound poetry and
LSD; showing the Rolling Stones around Morocco; immersed in
conversation with his close friends David Bowie and Iggy Pop;
touring with Patti Smith and her band in Amsterdam. Twelve years
after his death, Gysin's influence is palpable in the works of a
new generation of artists and musicians who have transmuted his
ideas into inventions of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a ventriloquist of ideas,'' Geiger said. ``He planted
these radical, experimental ideas with others, and then they were
the ones who would write the songs and paint the pictures and write
the books. You get all these people who are Brion's children in a
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
