<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5560 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORBIDDEN-BROADWAY-$A     07-15 1268
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBIDDEN-BROADWAY-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPOOF KEEPS PACE WITH BROADWAY'S EXCESSES AND EGOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gerard Alessandrini sat quietly in his seat at the
Minskoff Theater, ruminating on the strange spectacle before him.
``Into the fire!'' sang a swarm of English aristocrats, prancing
madly around the stage in ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.'' Alessandrini
studied the scene with the focused air of a junkman scrutinizing
the wreck of a 1959 Plymouth and wondering what it might be worth
if broken down for parts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he turned and shrugged. ``I don't know,'' he said
slowly. ``I might be able to do something with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alessandrini, 44, has been Broadway's premier parts collector
for a long time. Since 1982 he has been presenting a series of rude
yet ultimately affectionate cabaret-style satires on the Broadway
scene under the moniker ``Forbidden Broadway,'' which he created,
writes and directs. At one time, he also performed in it.
</P>
<P>
   The current incarnation, the year-and-a-half-old ``Forbidden
Broadway Strikes Back!,'' will be replaced by a new edition at the
end of September, and Alessandrini is on the prowl for fresh
material and new cast members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time to put another one out there,'' he said. ``But
we're not sure of the title yet. Maybe `Bride of Forbidden
Broadway.' Or we're thinking perhaps `FB2000,' to get us in on this
millennium thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alessandrini had taken in the performance of ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel'' during its previews last fall, part of the constant
round he makes of musicals. Who can say what shows will emerge as
fodder for satire?
</P>
<P>
   A few months later he sat in on a rehearsal in the ``Forbidden
Broadway'' performance space, the Stardust Theater, in the basement
of a Broadway-themed diner next door to ``Cats'' at the Winter
Garden. Upstairs, waiters were slinging burgers around the
retro-style coffee shop while, down a stairway to the right of the
entrance, the ``Forbidden Broadway'' ensemble was trying to figure
out a way to get Leonardo DiCaprio into the ``Titanic'' number.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbidden Broadway,'' which gets under way at 8:15 most
evenings, is performed in a two-tiered, L-shaped basement space
that has been painted black and pink and strung with lights and
sound equipment. The stage fills one wall, a piano positioned to
one side of it, for the show's musical director, Matthew Ward. Rows
of tables feed out from the stage and line the second tier, where
patrons can order drinks and, if they wish, dinners before the
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we might be able to do something with Leo spitting
off the side of the ship,'' Alessandrini called out from his seat
at one of the tables. This was greeted with glee by the cast
members, who immediately began to compete in distance spitting.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Alessandrini said, was that a scene from the Broadway
musical ``Titanic'' would be interrupted by an actor pretending to
be DiCaprio, who is ``filming a movie on the other side of the
ship.'' Lori Hammel, playing one of the elderly Victorian
passengers on the ship, would then cast off her old-lady gown and
become the young, ravishing Kate Winslet.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about this?'' she asked, turning toward the room with an
ecstatic look on her face and raising her arms high behind her head
in a parody of Ms. Winslet hanging off the ship's prow in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's perfect!'' Alessandrini shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' musical had become little
more than the occasion for a brief song by a dandy who is ridiculed
for his ornate costume by Rosie O'Donnell (played by Christine
Pedi). But Alessandrini still had hopes of bringing the show some
larger presence in the revue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't find my Julie Taymor!'' yelled Ms. Hammel from
backstage. An understudy was practicing walking on all fours, with
a wooden-handled plumber's helper in each hand, turning him into
something that looked not unlike a giraffe for ``The Lion King''
parody.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of this show is cut and paste,'' Alessandrini said.
``If the composers knew what we did with their songs . . . Well,
it's pretty informal. We kind of do it like summer camp around
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind each edition is to capture the current Broadway
Zeitgeist and to poke fun at the state of the theater by adding
new, rude, sometimes bawdy lyrics to the music from the shows. The
subject matter is calibrated to be inside enough for regular
theatergoers and broad enough for tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Cabaret'' parody, a somewhat rude one, was about how the
musical had been turned into a ``porno show,'' with the ``Forbidden
Broadway'' cast members dancing suggestively around the stage in
leather briefs.
</P>
<P>
   A second consideration is to look at the personalities involved
in Broadway shows, particularly if they have become controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each edition, the tone of Broadway seems to have changed and
our show takes on that tone,'' Alessandrini said. ``The last time
we did it, everything was so influenced by `Rent' and all of
Broadway seemed to have a youth feel to it, so that came across in
the show. We'll see what happens this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of the revue over the years have closely paralleled
those of Broadway, he added. When Broadway was in the doldrums,
people didn't seem all that interested in trudging uptown (the
company was then on West 72d Street) to see a satiric revue about
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good time for us now, perhaps the best time we've ever
had,'' Alessandrini noted. ``And artistically, we're a better show
now because there are so many more musicals to choose from. Never,
since `Forbidden Broadway' started, have we had a period where we
had to change the show as frequently as we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   He attributes this both to Broadway's current production boom
and to the company's move a year ago from the Triad Theater on 72d
Street to its new home in the heart of the theater district.
</P>
<P>
   The revue has a cast of four _ in addition to Ms. Hammel and Ms.
Pedi, Neal Mayer and William Selby _ with two understudies. ``We're
a shoestring operation,'' Alessandrini said. ``You can sometimes go
backstage and find producers sewing buttons onto costumes.''
</P>
<P>
   The director started ``Forbidden Broadway'' when he was two
years out of the Boston Conservatory of Music, not far from his
hometown of Needham, Mass. ``I really did want to be a legitimate
writer of musicals, and I still want to do that,'' he said. ``But I
haven't been working on it as much as I'd like. This isn't the
season for it. It's too busy, too many shows, too much work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Alessandrini will spend time this summer directing a new
musical, ``In the Beginning,'' at the Maine State Summer Theater in
Brunswick. Based on the early books of the Bible, it is a project
that he and the composer Maury Yeston have been working on.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he wants to add a few new skits to ``Forbidden Broadway
Strikes Back!'' this summer _ perhaps even one from ``The Scarlet
Pimpernel,'' which was nominated for three Tony Awards this year,
including one for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a number that I'd really like to use,'' Alessandrini
said, based on the song ``Into the Fire'' that he had heard all
those months ago at the preview.
</P>
<P>
   He looked hopeful. ``You see, instead of heading into the fire
of the French Revolution, we could have our cast dressed up in
fancy clothes and singing about how certain Broadway books and
scores should be thrown into the fire.'' He was grinning happily.
``I think we can make that work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
