<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5562 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUCTION-TRENDS-$ADV19     07-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-TRENDS-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUIET NEW BREED OF AMERICANA BUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The scene was a salesroom at Christie's in New York
on June 18, the prize an 18th-century Newport chest signed, labeled
and dated by one of America's greatest cabinetmakers, John
Townsend. At first, hands and paddles shot into the air as 10
people swiftly bid the masterpiece up to $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   But then an air of secrecy descended on the room as the
telephones took over: five unidentified bidders, then three, then
two competed until the hammer fell on the last bid, for $4.7
million. It was the second-highest price ever paid for a piece of
American furniture and the third highest paid at auction for any
piece of furniture. (The costliest American piece was a Newport
desk that was sold for $12 million in 1989; a year later, an
Italian cabinet brought $15 million.)
</P>
<P>
   In one stroke, the sale underscored two trends now in evidence
at auction houses: a surge in prices for Americana, and a growing
demand for anonymity by a new generation of wealthy collectors.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the buyers bidding at Christie's last month fit the
picture of these collectors: largely self-made millionaires in
their 40s and 50s who have reaped their fortunes in industry, on
Wall Street or in real estate and who do their buying discreetly.
</P>
<P>
   Things were different a decade ago when buyers like Eddy
Nicholson set the tone at auctions. A New Hampshire-based
industrialist and investor, Nicholson, who often paid $1 million or
more for tables, chairs and chests, would signal his bids with
folded arms or a nod from where he stood at the back of salesrooms.
(He sold his collection in 1995.) Today it is a rare auction when
major buyers like the oil heir Robert Bass, the computer magnate
Anthony Wang or the Tour de France champion Greg LeMond are seen
bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Why the secrecy?
</P>
<P>
   John Hays, who heads American furniture sales at Christie's,
attributes today's covert style to a more competitive market.
``There are many more players in the field than there were 10 years
ago,'' he said. ``The old guard has not disappeared, and there are
new buyers at every sale. So you never know who might come from
left field and bid against you.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple who bought the Newport chest agree, up to a point. In
a telephone interview, the wife, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that she and her husband, who are both New
Englanders in their early 50s, are more concerned about security
and privacy than competition.
</P>
<P>
   And they have a passion for Americana, she said. The couple have
been collecting Americana for 20 years, focusing mostly on New
England furniture, and the Townsend chest, because it is so rare,
offered a ``once in a lifetime opportunity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trophy piece,'' she said. ``My husband loves the
chunky feeling of 18th-century pieces, the turned legs, the ogee
bracket feet. And I love the gunkiness on the underside; that
remains basically untouched.'' The raw wood on the base of the
chest, made in 1792, shows 200 years of dust, glue and insect
marks, revealing, she said, ``the life of the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Before they buy furniture, ``we first have to love the object,''
she continued, ``and our response has to be instantaneous.'' Then
they study everything known about a piece and compare it with
others at museums to better understand why different materials were
used, who had to be employed to make the piece, how it had fit in a
household and who had owned it.
</P>
<P>
   There is more to be discovered about Townsend, his work and his
role in Newport, R.I., society in the late 18th century. And that
may now happen. Morrison Heckscher, the curator of American
decorative art at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, who is an expert
on John Townsend, says the museum plans to do an exhibition on him
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no better craftsman in 18th-century America,'' he
said. ``And there are more signed and documented pieces by him than
any other American cabinetmaker of the period.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum owns 3 of the 25 pieces signed by Townsend _ a chest,
a table and a clock _ as well as others attributed to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to bring together most of the documented pieces
so that people can see the breadth and quality of his work,''
Heckscher said. ``And it would be important to answer some of the
big questions that haven't been asked yet: for whom was this
furniture made and why was there a market for such pieces for so
long _ 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hays of Christie's hopes more Townsend pieces surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying a great piece of American 18th-century furniture is
like collecting a rare baseball card of Mickey Mantle or even Tom
Seaver, the ultimate when I was 12,'' he said. ``When you have a
chance to complete the set, to get the best of the best _ you go
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
