<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 09:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5563 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHISTLE-THEATER-LONDO     07-15 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLE-THEATER-LONDON-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LLOYD WEBBER STILL HAS TROUBLE WHISTLING DIXIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ For some while now, Andrew Lloyd Webber has been
planning what he calls a ``continuation'' of ``The Phantom of the
Opera.'' But isn't that what his new musical, ``Whistle Down the
Wind'' at the Aldwych Theater, could be said to be?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the two shows' settings could not be more different:
a gilt-edged fantasia of the Paris Opera House, as opposed to a
rural Louisiana backwater, circa 1959, where the new show takes
place.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the first time, however, Lloyd Webber's interest lies in
rewriting the primal tale of beauty and the beast: the outsider
shunned by society who is redeemed by young love (and a soaring
soprano).
</P>
<P>
   ``Whistle Down the Wind'' may take as its source the Mary Hayley
Bell novella that inspired the beloved (in England, anyway) 1961
Bryan Forbes film starring Hayley Mills and Alan Bates. On this
hearing it is about a haunted man _ known, indeed, as The Man and
portrayed by Marcus Lovett, an American veteran of several Lloyd
Webber musicals _ in none too sublimated thrall to a virginal
girl-woman, the impressionable teen-age Swallow (Lottie Mayor).
</P>
<P>
   But here, ``the music of the night,'' as the ``Phantom'' lyric
puts it, has been supplanted by what a Jim Steinman lyric terms
``the nature of the beast.'' ( Steinman, who has been with the
project from the beginning, was in fact approached by Lloyd Webber
more than a decade ago to be his collaborator on ``Phantom'' but
declined because of recording commitments.)
</P>
<P>
   What, then, of the nature of ``Whistle Down the Wind''? Lloyd
Webber was not pleased with an earlier incarnation directed by
Harold Prince in Washington in late 1996. That explains why the
London production boasts a fresh cast, book, creative team (headed
by Gale Edwards, the director) and even, with its three new songs,
score.
</P>
<P>
   The result, though, poses obstacles beyond the burden of a
levitating set (by the usually estimable Peter Davison) that looks
like a cheesy knockoff of John Napier's monstrously dazzling manse
in ``Sunset Boulevard.'' For one thing, it is asking a lot to
expect a cast of mostly Britons to inhabit Southern Gothic terrain
that often recalls Tennessee Williams at his more rabid.
</P>
<P>
   All the best efforts of the dialect coach, Joan Washington,
never convince us that Ms. Mayor's affectingly sung if wanly acted
Swallow _ the oldest of three children to mistake Lovett's
muscle-bound convict for Jesus _ has been any nearer a Bible Belt
of God-fearers and snake wrestlers than, say, Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is at too many removes from an approach that seems
pretty inauthentic to begin with, as the show's view of race
relations unnervingly makes clear: a mixed-race crew of sprightly
tots cavort about, making a mockery of the civil rights struggles
that were still to come.
</P>
<P>
   The score, much of which a surprisingly unmusical cast can't
really sing, amounts to faux rock-and-roll. What is absent is the
melodic revelation of character that has distinguished this
songwriter in happier form. ``With One Look,'' Norma Desmond's
opening volley in ``Sunset Boulevard,'' could only belong to a
narcissist nearing madness: the song is at once macabre and witty
and comes with built-in bravura. But most of the new show's
would-be anthems, greaser numbers and forays into scorching pop
truly sound as interchangeable as Lloyd Webber's detractors are
forever claiming all his work is. The exception: ``When Children
Rule the World,'' a song guaranteed to make a despot out of any
adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whistle Down the Wind'' boasts no shortage of Big Themes _
death, guilt, innocence and blame, among them. But the book, by Ms.
Edwards, Lloyd Webber and Patricia Knop, rarely rises above the
likes of ``The world is a confusing place sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also the line, ``Everyone dies, even the cat.'' Wait a
minute. Weren't cats supposed to be ``now and forever''?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
