<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAU16-COX     07-15 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAU16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Atlantic University up for promotion
 &HT;    By Don Horine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This could be the week that Florida
Atlantic University in Boca Raton gets the title of research
university, allowing it to expand its graduate programs, compete
for grant money and eventually collect higher tuition from
undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan being considered by Florida's Board of Regents,
FAU would be one of three schools in the second tier of Florida
research universities. The first tier _ the University of Florida,
Florida State University and the University of South Florida _
would be classified as national research universities.
</P>
<P>
   The plan proposed by Chancellor Adam Herbert pleases FAU
President Anthony Catanese and other FAU officials. They see the
school's continued growth as a state-designated research university
as good for Palm Beach County because it would fuel economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   But can Florida afford to have six public research universities?
And what would be the effect on undergraduate students, who make up
77 percent of FAU's 20,000 students?
</P>
<P>
   These two questions haven't been discussed by regents since
Herbert made his proposal in May. The regents, meeting in
Tallahassee through Friday, have indicated they like the proposal
and will incorporate it into their five-year plan.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert's proposal assumes that students benefit by attending a
research university. Consequently, if the legislature approves,
tuition will go up 5 percent for schools like FAU and 10 percent at
schools such as Florida and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Faculty research, according to conventional wisdom, expands the
frontiers of knowledge and helps professors keep abreast of
developments in their fields.
</P>
<P>
   But a commission appointed by the Carnegie Foundation concluded
in January that most undergraduate students at research
universities receive a poor education. That's because these schools
emphasize research at the expense of teaching by keeping top
instructors from the classroom, leaving undergraduate students to
take classes from graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   When commission Chairwoman Shirley Strum Kenny outlined the
criticisms at a regents meeting in May, Florida's public university
presidents said little. Later, it became evident why. They don't
believe that Florida universities have the faults cited by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got more than 31,000 undergraduate students,'' said John
Lombardi, president of the University of Florida. ``I'm going to
overlook them?''
</P>
<P>
   Catanese said he thought Florida universities were doing a
better job with undergraduate education than other universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Kenny's) using too broad a brush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the more research that a Florida public university does,
the more likely it is that its undergraduate students will be
taught by graduate students.
</P>
<P>
   At FAU, graduate students teach 11 percent of the undergraduate
classes. At UF, it's 19 percent. At the University of West Florida,
one of four ``comprehensive universities'' in Herbert's plan, it's
just 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Catanese called the proposed lineup of research universities ``a
fair assessment of where everybody is right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But having three national research universities in Florida, none
of them in South Florida, bothers Mitch Maidique, president of
Florida International University in Miami, and Regent Jon Moyle of
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Moyle has proposed that Florida set up four national research
centers _ in Tallahassee, Gainesville, along Interstate 4 and in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Moyle's proposal hasn't gotten any support. Catanese notes that
FAU, FIU and University of Miami officials are forming a
consortium, called the I-95 high-tech corridor, to work together to
seek federal and state support for research that would attract and
spawn high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Catanese said, FAU might climb to the national
research level, but he's willing to wait.
</P>
<P>
   FAU officials believe a research university designation will
help FAU attract even more research grants, which already bring in
close to $25 million a year. It also will strengthen FAU's case for
expanding its graduate education program, which now offers 15
doctorate and 47 master's degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the roughly $15 million FAU takes in each year in
federal research grants comes from its ocean engineering
department. That department received $5.8 million in 1996-97 from
the Office of Naval Research, most of it to build small automated
submarines to look for underwater mines and gather other
information useful to the military.
</P>
<P>
   FAU's two other large recipients are brain researcher Scott
Kelso, whose Center for Complex Systems received $1.1 million in
1996-97, and communications researcher Bill Glenn, who received
$839,390 to work on new high-definition television technology.
</P>
<P>
   Catanese has talked for years about his vision of creating
another Silicon Valley here. He and other FAU officials contend
that if FAU is allowed to expand its graduate programs, high-tech
companies will come because they want advanced training available
for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our region has a population that has a high demand for
graduate education programs,'' said FAU Vice Provost Nathan Dean,
who oversees graduate studies and research. ``It's a critical
factor in the economic development of the region.''
</P>
<P>
   FAU's research park already has attracted several small
high-tech companies. When the 52-acre park is completed in a year,
it will employ about 1,000 people in high-tech jobs, according to
director Jerry Merckel.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study done for the Business Development Board of Palm
Beach County acknowledged that the lack of a research university in
the county hurts the area's ability to attract high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   But the study by SRI International's Center for Economic
Competitiveness in Arlington, Va., found that what the county most
needs to compete is more trained technicians _ training that is
primarily done by high schools and community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   FAU is scarcely mentioned in the report. In fact, the report
recommended that an engineering school be encouraged to set up a
satellite campus in Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   FAU already has a fairly large graduate engineering program,
offering doctorate degrees in seven fields (computer science,
computer engineering, electrical engineering, mechanical
engineering, mathematical sciences, ocean engineering and physics)
and master's degrees in four others. FAU has a priority request to
the regents to offer doctorates in two other technical fields:
chemistry and biology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear from FAU,'' said Larry Pelton, the business
development board's president, who said no one from the university
sits on the group's 34-member board. ``FAU is not going to attract
the industries by themselves. It's a whole equation. They need to
partner with us and industry. Maybe the two of us ought to be
talking about this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   John Wiesenfeld, dean of the College of Science, says FAU's
graduate program is the most important factor in the county's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to compete for basically low-level industrial
jobs, you've got to realize you're competing with Malaysia, Latin
America and a lot of other regions, and you're competing by and
large on the cost of labor,'' he said. ``You want to compete where
it's not how fast you are, how many components you can turn out.
You want to compete in how smart you are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
