<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE     07-15 1718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q. Did any of the pilots who flew in the Berlin Airlift win any
medals or commendations for their efforts?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. In fact, provided they qualified in terms of time and
duty, everyone who participated in the airlift was eligible to
receive a Humane Action Medal and/or a Berlin Airlift Device, said
Joseph Studak of the Berlin Airlift Veterans Association in Austin,
Texas. In all, some 28,000 people in all duty specialties in the
Army, Navy and Air Force were honored, said Studak, a retired Air
Force lieutenant colonel. To qualify for the Airlift Device (worn
with the Army of Occupation Medal), a person had to serve at least
90 consecutive days in direct support of the airlift, which took
place June 26, 1948, to Sept. 30, 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In baseball, a K is used as a symbol for a strikeout. How did
that come about?
</P>
<P>
   A. When Henry Chadwick invented a scoring system in 1861, he
came up with a series of letter symbols, primarily for ease and
speed in recording the action: A for a putout at first base, B at
second, and C at third; F for a caught flyball; S for a sacrifice;
and, because he already had used F, L for a batter who had fouled
out (L from the last letter of ``foul''). Chadwick picked K for
struck out and in 1883 explained the decision: ``It was the
prominent letter of the word strike, as far as remembering the word
was concerned.'' Over time, Chadwick's system was superseded by
elements of other scoring systems, but the K remained.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there any record showing how much money distillers and
brewers of alcoholic beverages contribute to national political
candidates in both major parties?
</P>
<P>
   A. The most recent information available about beer and liquor
campaign funding, as reported by the Encyclopedia of Congressional
Money and Politics, is for the 1994 elections. These were the top
10 contributors: National Beer Wholesalers Association, $1.24
million; Anheuser-Busch, $335,470; Joseph E. Seagram &AMP; Sons,
$216,770; Wine &AMP; Spirits Wholesalers of America, $191,460;
Brown-Forman Distillers, $149,475; Gallo Winery, $141,708; Wine
Institute, $136,710; Heublein, $89,970; Florida Distillers Co.,
$89,940; and Smirnoff/Inglenook Distributors, $77,150.
</P>
<P>
   Top Senate recipients: Dianne Feinstein (D-Calif.), $108,134;
Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.), $66,450; Kay Bailey Hutchison (R-Texas),
$60,250; Jim Sasser (D-Tenn.), $53,704; and Richard Bryan (D-Nev.),
$44,430. Top House recipients: Dick Gephardt (D-Mo.), $121,950; Vic
Fazio (D-Calif.), $56,050; Dan Rostenkowski (D-Ill.), $51,000; Sam
Gibbons (D-Fla.), $41,750; and Steny Hoyer (D-Md.), $40,250.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $4.36 million donated by the beer, wine and liquor
industries, it was almost an even split to Democratic candidates
($2,184,493) and Republicans ($2,173,360).
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``The MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour'' on PBS used to be one of my
favorite news programs. It's now ``The NewsHour With Jim Lehrer.''
What happened to Robert MacNeil?
</P>
<P>
   A. He's still involved with MacNeil-Lehrer Productions in
Arlington, Va., in which both men have been active for 15 years,
said company publicist Susan Trabucchi. But the former ``NewsHour''
anchor generally keeps a low profile, rarely accepting speaking
engagements or appearing before a camera. His primary focus of late
has been writing, Trabucchi said, with a novel, ``Breaking News,''
expected to be published by Doubleday in late October.
</P>
<P>
   He also is planning two programs for PBS, one a sequel to his
broadcast, ``The Story of English,'' about 11 years ago. The sequel
will examine the American language. The other series is the
nine-hour-long ``Shakespeare,'' which MacNeil described as an
examination in a contemporary manner of ``why this 400-year-old
dead, white male, so anachronistic in many ways, remains the
world's supreme and best-loved author and, recently, Hollywood's
No. 1 screenwriter.''
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil has children in Denver, Boston and London, as well as
brothers in his native Nova Scotia, so he and his wife travel
frequently. New York is their permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does it mean when someone tells you to ``mind your p's
and q's''?
</P>
<P>
   A. There are numerous theories, but Facts on File Encyclopedia
of Word and Phrase Origins narrows them down to what it calls the
three top contenders:
</P>
<P>
   (1) Children learning to write English are told to be careful
not to reverse the knobs on the letters and make p's look like q's,
and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   (2) In the days of lead type, apprentice printers were told to
be careful in picking out type, especially since a typesetter had
to read letters upside down and backward.
</P>
<P>
   (3) British tavernkeepers had to be careful when figuring up
customers' monthly bar bills not to confuse p's (pints) and q's
(quarts).
</P>
<P>
   Q. How were DNA samples taken from the remains of the body of
the former U.S. Unknown Soldier killed in Vietnam? Testing enabled
the military recently to identify the remains as that of Air Force
1st Lt. Michael Blassie.
</P>
<P>
   A. Genetic samples were extracted from bones in the Tomb of the
Unknowns. To make the match, those samples then were tested against
DNA samples from family members of seven of nine American soldiers
shot down near An Loc in South Vietnam in mid-1972. Blassie's
family had pushed the Defense Department to disinter the remains
and perform the genetic testing.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why do military jets, including those reconfigured from
commercial aircraft, fly so much higher than commercial jets?
</P>
<P>
   A. Except for high-performance aircraft, they don't, says Lt.
Col. Steven Brown of the Air Force military liaison to the Federal
Aviation Administration in Atlanta. The normal cruising altitude of
military planes is between 28,000 and 35,000 feet, or whatever is
assigned by air traffic controllers at the time. Those military
planes that are derivatives of commercial planes actually are
structurally identical, with only the interiors reconfigured, so
their altitudes and other performance capabilities are the same.
</P>
<P>
   There are exceptions, such as the SR-71, which can fly much
higher, Brown added. Needless to say, there's no commercial
derivative of the SR-71.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are raw potatoes safe to eat? I'm concerned because of all
the news about E. coli.
</P>
<P>
   A. Raw vegetables and fruit that come in contact with the feces
of animals harboring E. coli 0157:H7, or with feces from unclean
hands of infected workers, could be a source of this organism, said
Judy Harrison of the University of Georgia Department of Foods and
Nutrition. Like any other raw agricultual commodity, potatoes could
be contaminated with types of bacteria or bacterial spores, but the
risk is minimal, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison advises handling potatoes just like any other fresh
fruit or vegetables: wash them under fresh, running tap water; use
a clean vegetable brush, if you wish; and peel them if you want to,
since that can help remove surface contamination. But peeling will
eliminate a source of fiber from your diet.
</P>
<P>
   Q. In the qualifying stages of the World Cup (as opposed to the
finals recently played in France), all countries are entitled to
enter their national team except for Great Britain, which enters
four separate teams: England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   A. In soccer, England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland
always have been separate entities, instead of coming under the
U.K. banner as they do in the Olympics. For various reasons, most
of them political and turf-related, they have fielded separate
teams and there have been few public calls to merge. Each has its
own federation and professional league.
</P>
<P>
   The animosity isn't as bad now as it has been historically, but
Scottish fans still indulge in a familiar chant, ``Stand Up If You
Hate England.'' England and Scotland, which played the first known
international match in 1872, discontinued their annual match in
1989. Their last meeting was a 2-0 win by England in the 1996
European Championships, and the all-time record between the two is
fairly close: England leads 44-40, with 24 ties.
</P>
<P>
   Q. This year's was the 16th World Cup. Of the 15 played
previously, the countries in this year's cup account for 13
champions: Brazil, 4; Italy and Germany, 3 each; Argentina, 2; and
England, 1. Who won the other two?
</P>
<P>
   A. Uruguay won twice, in 1930 (defeating Argentina, 4-2) and in
1950 (defeating Brazil, 2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Q. A recent Q&AMP;A mentioned female FBI special agents. What are
the qualifications necessary to become one?
</P>
<P>
   A. This is a good time for qualified women (and men) to apply
because ``the FBI is hiring,'' said agency spokeswoman Celestine
Armstead. Those with at least three years of skilled professional
experience, in such fields as engineering or computers, and those
proficient in foreign languages, especially Spanish, are
particularly in demand.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for training as a special agent, an individual, male
or female, must be a U.S. citizen, or a citizen of the Northern
Mariana Islands, and have reached his or her 23rd _ but not 37th _
birthday. Candidates must be completely available for assignment
anywhere in the FBI's headquarters or field offices; pass a
polygraph examination, a drug test and a color vision test; and
must hold a degree from an accredited college or university. Other
eligibility requirements also apply.
</P>
<P>
   Details are available from FBI field offices.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What does the A&AMP;W of A&AMP;W Root Beer stand for?
</P>
<P>
   A. A(llen) &AMP; W(right). Roy Allen mixed up his first batch of
root beer in June 1919 in Lodi, Calif., selling a mug for a nickel.
Frank Wright, an employee from Allen's original Lodi location,
became his partner in 1922 and they combined the initials and
formally named the beverage A&AMP;W Root Beer. In 1924, Allen bought
Wright's share of the business to actively pursue a franchise sales
program and had the name A&AMP;W Root Beer, and the A&AMP;W logo, legally
trademarked.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
