<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Mom rates Meijer a mortal sin
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If you grew up in Catholic schools in the '60s,
sins had letter values: N, V and M, short for ``no sin,'' ``venial
sin'' and ``mortal sin.'' I pored over my rate-that-sin
assignments, scribbling N, V or M next to the sin described.
</P>
<P>
   Watching The Lawrence Welk Show, for instance, would merit an N.
Stealing your brother's Beatles lunch box would be a V, and
skipping Sunday Mass to catch a matinee of The Valley of the Dolls
would definitely be an M, maybe a double M.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years my mother has made an addendum to litany of
mortal sins: shopping at Meijer.
</P>
<P>
   When the 201,000-square-foot behemoth opened at East Stroop Road
and Wilmington Pike in 1991, Mom vowed she'd never shop there. She
didn't like the size of it, and she hated the thought of Meijer
squeezing out the smaller grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Mom knew she could never go back to the kind of mom-and-pop
store she grew up with: Amann's grocery store at Tacoma Street and
Carlisle Avenue in the East Dayton neighborhood now known as Linden
Heights. During the Depression, the Amanns gave families a break by
charging by the month. The kindly Bud Amann kept accounts in a
spiral notebook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those days are long gone,'' Mom concedes. We all know the
mom-and-pop store _ heck, anything short of Cub Foods _ is headed
for the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't blame Mom for not wanting to shop in a place with all
the ambience of a dirigible hangar. I became a Fulmer convert.
Everyone was friendly, and you could browse its homey 33,000 square
feet without feeling dizzy and disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   The store was bustling Tuesday afternoon _ busier than usual,
alas _ with shoppers taking advantage of the 20 percent
stock-reduction sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this store closing?'' a woman asked, looking disheartened
at the news. ``This was a nice store.''
</P>
<P>
   Chalk it up to the times. In the end even Mom has been forced to
sin occasionally. ``They're the closest store, and they have the
cheapest cat food,'' she explained, in tones reserved for the
confessional. For the most part, she still patronized the smaller
Kettering groceries. One by one, they closed. Bob's Food Warehouse.
IGA Foodtown. Groceryland. Wilmington Heights Market. They weren't
Amann's corner store, but still the kind of places where you could
order Jim's secret-recipe ham salad, and be recognized as a
regular.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, during a dinner at my parents' house, Mom greeted
us with the doleful news: ``I've shut down my fifth grocery
store.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Black Widow of South Dayton supermarkets has struck
again. Fulmer Supermarket in Beavercreek, where she has shopped
seven years, is going out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Mom's sure it happened because of competition from Meijer and
the new Kroger at Woodman and Dorothy Lane. We suspected another
culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they should put up wanted posters, 'Do not let this
woman shop here,' '' Debbie said.
</P>
<P>
   My husband jumped in: ``The manager could get on the PA system
and announce, `Vera McCarty, you are not authorized to shop in this
store. Return to your vehicle immediately.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Where should Mom shop now? Dot's? Lofino's? Dorothy Lane Market?
(Gasps all around the table.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Do those guys a favor,'' Dad admonished, ``and don't shop
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep, Mom's going to have to face facts: If she wants to torpedo
Meijer, her only recourse is to become a regular customer
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-14-98 2054E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
