<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heaven on American Frontier
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ While helping a friend move a fortune in antique
guns this past Independence Day weekend, I concluded that America's
western
</P>
<P>
   expansion would have been the best time to be alive. Actually, I
had that thought when I first read Zane Grey and Jack London as a
boy. But handling guns that were actually owned and used by
pioneers, outlaws and lawmen on the western frontier brought it all
back.
</P>
<P>
   Those guns were the everyday, indispensable tools of men and
women who settled this nation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the guns that fascinate me about this period of history
_ it's the freedom, challenges and opportunities of the western
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women on the frontier survived on their wits and
skills. Those who couldn't cut it either died or they returned to
the protective
</P>
<P>
   embrace of land already settled.
</P>
<P>
   Even those Americans who failed to settle on rich farm land,
establish big ranches or strike gold must have lived a life of
adventure that more
</P>
<P>
   than compensated for frontier hardships.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest Americans who moved into the western wilderness
lived without government rules, regulations, taxes or laws. There
were no
</P>
<P>
   traffic laws, no disturbing the peace laws and no product
liability laws.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, for the earliest pioneers, there were no laws at all.
Therefore, there were no law enforcement officers, lawmakers,
lawyers or
</P>
<P>
   judges. It wasn't civilization, but it might have been heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow I can't envision heaven as a place where angels are
required to wear seat belts, where St. Peter writes tickets for
jaywalking and where
</P>
<P>
   clouds have tags that warn ``Do Not Remove Under Penalty of
Law.''
</P>
<P>
   As America's western settlers began to clump together in
frontier towns, they had to decide what behavior was intolerable.
Stealing a
</P>
<P>
   man's horse or shooting someone in the back who didn't deserve
it were generally sufficient reasons to permanently exile the
wrongdoer to Boot Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier justice was short and sweet. Law-abiding townsfolk
would have thought it insane to support a convicted killer for 20
years worth of
</P>
<P>
   legal appeals. Then again, they also probably executed a few
innocent folks.
</P>
<P>
   It's also interesting to recall the priorities of frontier
settlers when they established a new town. Businesses were
established by
</P>
<P>
   entrepreneurs. The town's residents provided their own shelter.
The first tax-supported employee was a teacher or a marshal. The
first
</P>
<P>
   tax-supported building was either a school house or a jail.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of a frontier town might come together to build a
church, but the preacher was expected to support himself.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, of course, but the quality of a city's
police and schools probably remains a good gauge of a community.
</P>
<P>
   Members of America's Libertarian Party also must believe that
the period of America's western expansion was the best time to be
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Libertarians believe in a world where individuals live without
government interference.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement of principles, Libertarians say they believe
``that all individuals have the right to exercise sole dominion
over their own
</P>
<P>
   lives, and have the right to live in whatever manner they
choose, so long as they do not forcibly interfere with the equal
right of others to
</P>
<P>
   live in whatever manner they choose.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the tricky part, of course. Laws are needed to establish
rights and law enforcement is needed to prevent the strong from
exploiting the weak.
</P>
<P>
   Civilization requires government, rules, regulations and laws.
There's no way around it.
</P>
<P>
   But the early settlers of America's West enjoyed a brief period
of real freedom, although this also was a time when Native
Americans lost freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
