<HEADER>
A5597 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE     07-15 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS16-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'm from Ohio, and our family always thought Roy Rogers was
born in Portsmouth, on the Kentucky border east of Cincinnati. But
articles after Rogers' died said he was born in Cincinnati. Can you
shed any light?
</P>
<P>
   A. Leonard Franklin Slye (Rogers' birth name) was born Nov. 5,
1911, in Cincinnati. He later would write jokingly that his birth
site was visited each spring by one million people, because the
modest brick tenement that was his first home stood on what later
would be about second base of Riverfront Stadium (now Cinergy
Field).
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to the story, and it may be the light you're
looking for. When Leonard was a small child, his father, Andrew
Slye, who worked in the Cincinnati factory of the United States
Shoe Co., became impatient with life in the city and moved his
family by houseboat to Portsmouth, on the Ohio River. They lived
there for several years before moving again, in 1919, this time to
a farm in Duck Run, Ohio. When Leonard was 17, the family moved
back to Cincinnati, and in 1930 they moved again _ this time to
California.
</P>
<P>
   After a time working as a seasonal migrant fruit picker, Len
Slye, as he called himself, turned to singing, and later to movies.
He was known briefly as Dick Weston, then Roy Rogers. You know the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where can fans send cards to Dale Evans to express sorrow
about the death of her husband, Roy Rogers?
</P>
<P>
   A. The address: 15650 Seneca Road, Victorville, CA 92392.
</P>
<P>
   Q. With all the publicity about the Volkswagen Beetle coming
back, and the announcement by Volkswagen of a fund to pay laborers
who worked for the company under the Nazis in 1944-45, I'm
wondering if it's true, as I have heard: Did Adolf Hitler play a
prominent role in introducing the original VW Bug?
</P>
<P>
   A. While in prison in 1924, Hitler read the biography of Henry
Ford and became fascinated with the idea of a car every worker
could afford. You might say the germ of the VW story dates to 1933,
when Hitler became Germany's chancellor. Among his Depression
projects was a network of superhighways, the autobahns. To
complement these new roads, he asked German auto manufacturers to
build a small car with specific requirements: It had to accommodate
a family of four or five, be low in initial cost, and be able to
cruise all day at high speeds on the autobahn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Ferdinand Porsche, an automotive engineer who ran his
own consulting engineering company, was commissioned to design the
automobile. He already had developed a design for the NSU company,
so he used that as the basis for the Hitler car. In 1938, a factory
was started in Wolfsburg, Germany. Hitler wanted to call the car
the KdF-wagen (from Kraft durch Freude, or ``strength through
joy''), but the public quickly dubbed it the People's Car, or
Volkswagen, and the name stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Of the murders committed in the United States, what are the
most commonly used weapons (guns, knives, poison and so on)?
</P>
<P>
   A. The most recent statistics, released Sept. 28, 1997, are for
1996, and are from the Justice Department and the Federal Bureau of
Investigation publication Crime in the United States (1996). They
show that of 15,848 murder victims, these were the weapons used,
the number of victims, and their percentage of the total: firearms,
10,744, or 67.8 percent; knives or cutting instruments, 2,142,
13.5; personal weapons (hands, fists, feet, which includes
pushing), 939, 5.9; blunt objects (such as clubs, hammers), 733,
4.6; strangulation, 243, 1.5; fire, 151, 1; asphyxiation, 92, .6;
narcotics, 32, .2; explosives, 14, .1; and poison, 8, .1. Of the
remaining victims, the weapon was ``other'' or not stated, and
includes drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When John Tyler ran for president, his slogan was ``tippy
canoe and Tyler, too.'' What did that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. The first part of the slogan, which was the rallying cry of
Whigs in the presidential campaign of 1840, was Tippecanoe. It
referred to the victory by Gen. William Henry Harrison in 1811 over
an Indian uprising headed by the Shawnee chief, Tecumseh, at the
Tippecanoe River in Indiana. Harrison was the one running for
president, and Tyler was his running mate. Tyler became president
when Harrison died shortly after his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What's the latest on the disappearance of Madalyn Murray
O'Hair, the atheist?
</P>
<P>
   A. O'Hair, along with son Jon Murray and adopted granddaughter
Robin Eileen Murray O'Hair, have been declared ``incapacitated'' by
a probate judge in Austin, Texas, where the family lived. Austin
police say their file remains open. The three disappeared in August
1995, and it isn't known whether they are dead or alive. If alive,
O'Hair would be about 80 now.
</P>
<P>
   Theories about their fate range from kidnapping, robbery and
triple homicide to the belief that O'Hair went to San Antonio to
die and that Jon and Robin are in hiding _ possibly overseas _ and
living off money siphoned from accounts of atheist organizations
controlled by the Murray O'Hairs. One of those organizations has
reported more than $600,000 missing.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development is that the O'Hair family's five-bedroom
house in Austin is for sale. Ali Hassibi, a renter of the house,
said he thought he could buy it at a bargain price, given its
notoriety. Wrong, he says he discovered; the house is listed for
$267,500. Because of the family's disappearance, any sale must be
approved by two courts.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which island in the Azores was affected by the earthquake
July 9? News reports have not been specific.
</P>
<P>
   A. The hardest-hit of the archipelago's nine volcanic islands
was Faial, where authorities said about 500 homes were destroyed,
with damage initally estimated at $64 million. Eight people were
killed in rural villages on Faial's eastern coast, said Helena Vaz,
spokeswoman for the Azores Civil Protection Service. The magnitude
5.8 quake was centered in the Atlantic Ocean 12 miles off Faial.
Other Azores islands rocked by the quake included Pico, Sao Jorge
and Terceira, where the U.S. Air Force has a base. The islands are
about 800 miles west of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I thought people born between 1917 and 1924 were the
so-called Social Security ``notch babies.'' But Q&AMP;A recently
reported the years as 1917 through 1921. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A. The dictionary (Random House Unabridged) defines ``notch
baby'' as ``a person who was born in the U.S. between 1917 and 1921
and as a retiree received lower cost-of-living increases in Social
Security than others after Congress readjusted Social Security
benefits in 1977.'' The American Association of Retired Persons
says the notch is 1917-21, as does the Social Security
Administration. That is the period when a transition formula was
applied to those receiving benefits, said agency spokeswoman Patti
Patterson, who added that ``anyone born after 1916 is affected by
the change in the way benefits are figured.'' Although several
advocacy groups have extended the years ``as a way to involve more
people and make their case stronger,'' there's no direct reason to
do so, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The TREA Senior Citizens League of Washington, which refers to
individuals born from 1917 through 1926 as forming the notch,
apparently is one such group. It supports a cost-capped solution to
what it calls the ``inequity of benefits,'' and endorses HR 3008,
which proposes to provide a $5,000 lump-sum payment or increased
monthly benefits through 2002 to those born in the notch _ whatever
it is defined to be.
</P>
<P>
   As Q&AMP;A pointed out previously, members of Congress have
introduced 118 pieces of notch-reform legislation since 1981. None
has been passed into law.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
