<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5600 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEBCAM16-COX     07-15 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBCAM16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Picture this: Web cams proliferating
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse and Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Homer Ramby credits the ``WayneCam'' with an
extra big turnout for this year's Wayne Twp. Volunteer Fire
Department Fish Fry.
</P>
<P>
   The camera, perched atop a telephone pole at Miami and Main
streets a block from the firehouse, uploads an image of downtown
Waynesville onto the Internet every 20 minutes, where it can be
seen by anyone sitting at a computer from Switzerland to Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good publicity,'' said Ramby, a 57-year-old volunteer
firefighter who set up the cam site
(www.interaxs.net/pub/wtfd/livecam.htm) in August. ``You can check
24 hours a day and see what downtown Waynesville looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   If that prospect doesn't thrill you, then try the late-night
scene at the Walnut Hills Bar on Dayton's Brown Street
(www.walnuthills.com), where patrons may be sampling one of the
tavern's 100 brews or listening to alternative rock music. ``It
feels like you're in the bar, and that's the idea,'' said co-owner
Dennis Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   From small towns to hip urban watering holes, web cam sites are
proliferating on the Internet faster than the most voracious
cyberspace voyeurs can double-click. Communities, businesses and
not-so-private people are linking camera views to computers with
the aim of promoting, advertising or, in some cases, exposing
themselves for 15-megabytes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ringley, whose Jennicam page (www.jennicam.org) is the
best-known of all the web cam sites, lures half a million viewers a
week who are either bored, or lurid, enough to watch her putter
about her Washington, D.C., apartment and occasionally step out of
her shower undressed.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of web cam sites capturing everything from
building construction (like Wright State University's new academic
building at www.media.wright.edu/raidercam.html) to live births,
from toilet stalls (don't ask) to college dorm rooms, from mundane
business offices to dramatic water falls
(www.fallsview.com/falls.html).
</P>
<P>
   What's perhaps more amazing is that so many techno-peepers are
tuning into so little, said Bryan Pfaffenberger, an Internet
historian at the University of Virginia and author of Protect Your
Privacy on the Internet (John Wiley, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the whole web cam site phenomenon puts its finger on
some sort of need that computer users have to extend their
perceptions to far-away locales _ even if what they see is
completely boring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a trend that's certain to accelerate as the price of
cameras continues to tumble and software becomes even easier to
install, experts say. Two years ago, the equipment and software for
a web cam site cost as much as $5,000. Today, you can set up a site
for less than $200. The smallest cameras, some as cheap as $50, are
now about the size of colored markers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cameras are only going to get smaller and cheaper. I think
every kid is going to get one _ and sneak it into his big sister's
room,'' quipped Jim Sterne of Target Marketing, an Internet
marketing consultant firm based in Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   At the Walnut Hills Bar in Dayton, which launched its web site
two weeks ago, a sign is going up to warn patrons that their suds
sipping and socializing may be viewed 'round the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as my parents aren't surfing the Net, it's fine with
me,'' said Greg Cassimatis, a 23-year-old regular who often shares
a table in full view of the bar's web cam.
</P>
<P>
   The candid shots at Walnut Hills, which change every two
minutes, are part of a new web page that includes a menu, a jukebox
list, a beer page, a chat room, links to The Grateful Dead websites
and a Dear Abby knock-off authored by bartender Mike Altomare,
dubbed ``Ask Big Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Walnut Hills Bar has alway been a pretty hip place, and
this is hip,'' Stewart said. ``This crowd is into computers,
tattoos and alternative music.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart admits he still doesn't know what purpose is served by
turning his barroom into a fishbowl, but he's fascinated by the
creative possibilities. ``We're kids playing, is what we are,'' he
said. ``We're just having fun with it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so in Waynesville, where town officials tend to be very
serious about their WayneCam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are curious about Waynesville,'' said Village
Manager Kevin Harper. ``We have a reputation for being the antiques
capital of the world, and I think people like to get on our website
and see what they're getting into.''
</P>
<P>
   During the town's annual Sauerkraut Festival, an extra cam is
mounted atop the Sauerkraut Ball trailer, alternating views every
10 minutes with the WayneCam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be hundreds of miles away and be able to see
hundreds of thousands of people having a good time,'' Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   But as a publicity tool, Sterne says, web cam sites are only as
effective as the advertising and Internet search engines that
promote them. Otherwise, he says, it's like having an unlisted
phone number in the Yellow Pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing that, if you build it, they will come,''
he said. ``You have to tell people (your web site) is there.''
</P>
<P>
   It might also help to give viewers something to watch. The
WayneCam, for instance, shows a two- or three- block stretch of
Main Street, where only the cars and ant-like pedestrians change
every 20 minutes. To protect privacy, the camera is far enough away
that faces and car licenses can't be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Boring? Maybe, but Ramby says the site has had more than 28,000
``hits'' from computer users in 39 countries, including Switzerland
and Germany. ``We had one person say it looked like such a nice
town they were thinking about moving here because of the cam,''
Ramby said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Ely, a spokeswoman for Wright State University, wasn't
sure why anyone would want to watch the web cam trained on
construction of the school's new academic building. ``We never
looked at this thing until you called,'' she said. ``Who would want
to watch them construct a building?''
</P>
<P>
   But then she and her staff discovered a movie at the same web
site (www.media.wright.edu/sitecam/movies/crane2.mov) that records
a crane accident at the building site. ``Then we were all in there
watching the crane fall over _ and over and over and over,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pfaffenberger said Wright State may have the makings of a
world-class web cam site. ``You really start to get a lot of hits
on your site, it seems, if it's especially and exquisitely
pointless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
