<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HM016-COX     07-15 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HM016-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HMO dispute less than expected
 &HT;    By Earl Golz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumers apparently aren't as upset with the
treatment they get from health maintenance organizations as some
thought they were.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after Texas started a landmark independent review
program for consumers who want to dispute HMO treatment denials,
only 147 complaints have been filed with the Texas Department of
Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department officials had predicted they would see
4,400 complaints by the end of the year _ about 30 times the number
of complaints that have been filed to date.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, not one lawsuit has been filed alleging medical
malpractice by HMOs in the first year that Texans were permitted to
do so
</P>
<P>
   The Texas program, through which arbitrators give binding,
independent reviews of HMO and insurance company treatment denial
decisions when consumers complain, is one of the first in the
country. Reacting to consumer complaints, lawmakers approved the
program in 1997 and it went into effect in November.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Department officials said Monday they could not
provide a breakdown of complaints by company.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. David Sibley, R-Waco, said the numbers show that
problems about HMOs aren't as bad as some have suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would have to say all the talk by the HMOs last
session about how the sky was going to fall was exaggerated,''
Sibley said. ``And I'm happy for them. The whole purpose of what we
did last session was to have physicians and patients make the
decisions, not HMO bookkeepers.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the first 147 cases filed, the independent review by doctors
of the Texas Medical Foundation upheld the HMO in 67 cases and the
patient in 52 cases. The remainder are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   The slim number of complaints ``makes a lot of folks wonder
whether there were the serious problems that everybody alleged that
there were,'' said Jeff Kloster, general counsel for the Texas
Association of Health Plans, which represents HMOs and insurance
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason there may be so few medical malpractice suits is
because suits must involve allegations that occurred after
September 1, 1997, which limits the number of cases that can be
filed, Kloster said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HMOs may be ``more conscientious'' in resolving
issues before they reach the independent review stage, said Lisa
McGiffert of Consumers Union in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that the numbers are rising, however: By May 15,
about 70 complaints had been filed; since then, the total number
has more than doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another reason why the number of complaints is relatively
low is simply that consumers don't know about the program, even
though HMOs are supposed to notify consumers about it.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer is preparing to send
bulletins to HMOs and health insurance companies reminding them
that patients should be informed of the independent review process
if a decision by the HMO goes against them on a treatment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Have a dispute with your HMO over treatment?
</P>
<P>
   If a patient or a patient's doctor disputes denial of treatment
by an HMO or health insurance company, he or she may appeal the
decision orally or in writing to a company representative.
</P>
<P>
   The company representative must include the reasons of the
outcome of the appeal. The consumer must also be notified of the
right to seek review of the denial with an independent review
organization under the Texas Department of Insurance program. A
decision by the review organization is binding on both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Further information on the process is available by calling the
Texas Department of Insurance at 322-4266 or (800) 578-4677.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SEWAGE16-COX     07-15 1995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SEWAGE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colonia conditions across Texas
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KYLE, Texas _ Eight-year-old Tracema Castillo got the shot. So
did schoolmates Jose Camputo, Erika Vega, Christopher Chavez and
John Leafty. ``It didn't even hurt,'' said Justin Heiman, 7.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, almost 100 students in the first and second grades
at Tom Green Elementary School in northern Hays County were
vaccinated against hepatitis A one day in April.
</P>
<P>
   Why? They live in neighborhoods with leaking septic systems and
poor drainage. That means an elevated risk of contracting the liver
disease, which, although rarely fatal, causes yellowing of the skin
and eyes, nausea and vomiting. Seven cases have been reported in
that area of Hays County since October, prompting county officials
to sponsor the vaccination program.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: Substandard sanitation is not confined to the
border with Mexico. Look no farther than Central Texas. In fact,
more and more subdivisions with ramshackle housing, leaking septic
systems and muddy roads are springing up all around the state,
especially in rural areas beyond the regulatory reach of cities.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, these subdivisions are not eligible for
relief under a $479 million government program that finances
construction of water and sewer systems in the state's poorest
areas. That is because the program focuses on subdivisions built
before 1989 and located primarily in the border region and a few
other areas with high unemployment and low incomes.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for the spread of substandard housing is that
counties, unlike cities, have few powers under state law to
regulate development.
</P>
<P>
   Their authority was constrained even more by a 1995 court
decision in a case involving Travis County and a bank in Elgin.
Under the ruling, which hinged on the meaning of the word ``and,''
developers do not have to file subdivision blueprints if they are
not building streets or other public areas.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling has prompted more and more developers to build
subdivisions without streets. They do so by carving their tracts
into parcels that look like a flag atop a pole. The house or mobile
home occupies the flag section of the lot, while the pole section
is a driveway leading to an existing public road. Such subdivisions
have numerous closely spaced and parallel driveways leading to the
road.
</P>
<P>
   The flag-lot approach allows developers to avoid the cost and
delay associated with building streets and preparing subdivision
blueprints and maps, known as plats.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Hays County and elsewhere oppose the practice
because it leaves them unaware of the subdivisions until they take
shape, making it difficult to oversee drainage, water service,
septic-system plans and other matters. Such subdivisions sometimes
end up with inadequate septic systems, poor drainage and dirt
driveways that serve as streets and become impassable by school
buses and emergency vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling that allows flag-lot development does not apply
to areas subject to a city's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Different rules also apply in the border region. The state
Legislature has granted those counties much broader regulatory
duties in an effort to curb the spread of substandard developments,
known as colonias. For example, developers may not sell residential
lots without water and sewer hookups, drainage and roads _ a
requirement that does not apply in the rest of the state.
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected ordeal
</P>
<P>
   The implications of the state's buyer-beware policy on rural
land development took Janet Williams, Amy Norwood and other
residents of the 35 South Ranches subdivision by surprise. The
subdivision is a flag-lot development of about 60 mobile homes in a
former pasture five miles east of Kyle and 20 miles south of
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 34, a vendor of office products and toys, bought a
five-acre lot in November 1996. Norwood, 34, a junior high school
journalism teacher, bought a seven-acre lot.
</P>
<P>
   The developer informed them and other buyers that each would be
responsible for building a private driveway. But the buyers had no
idea how much time, work and money it would take to tame the black
clay soil east of Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   Norwood estimated that she has spent more than $3,000 on gravel,
tractor rentals and fuel. She and a friend did the work themselves.
The job is only half finished. Still, her driveway, which is more
than 1,000 feet long, is far superior to the rutted paths leading
to her neighbors' mobile homes. Norwood has also excavated a
channel across her yard to divert runoff that was eroding the drain
field of her septic system.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' car has become mired in mud several times when rain
made her driveway impassable. That has caused her to miss work.
Norwood, whose driveway runs next to Williams', has given her
neighbor permission to use the better route. Other neighbors are
using it too.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen households in the subdivision have problems with
their septic systems, in some cases as a result of improper
installation by the developer, according to the Hays County
Environmental Health Department. Erosion gullies have formed in
drain fields, and the soil is often damp and foul-smelling,
residents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked out there one day last summer and I sank up to my
knees,'' Williams said. ``It just swallowed me.''
</P>
<P>
   Norwood said odors come and go. ``On some days you can smell it
up through the drains in the house, like when you brush your
teeth,'' she said. ``I bought this place because it was going to be
my dream home. It hasn't turned out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel almost embarrassed that I allowed myself to
be taken advantage of. But if there were other laws and
regulations, maybe it wouldn't happen to somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   A question of costs
</P>
<P>
   The developer, William Swinney of Del Valle, who also installed
the septic systems, could not be reached for comment. His lawyer,
Lamar Hankins, said it was not Swinney's fault that homeowners have
failed to build driveways that stand up to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the developer pays the costs up front and recoups the
costs in the sale of lots, or you develop in this fashion and the
homeowner is responsible for taking care of drainage issues and
driveway issues,'' Hankins said. ``Mr. Swinney did this to save
money.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the septic systems, Swinney denied that any were failing
when he testified in December before Hays County commissioners,
who, in a rare exercise of judicial power, issued a subpoena
compelling him to appear.
</P>
<P>
   However, Swinney later agreed to make improvements and offered
to relinquish his state license as a septic tank installer,
according to records at the Texas Natural Resource Conservation
Commission. The agency investigated following a complaint by Hays
County authorities.
</P>
<P>
   One county's challenge
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen subdivisions in Hays County have similar
problems. During a recent tour, County Commissioner Jeff Barton
drove his pickup past shacks, dilapidated mobile homes and
sewage-tainted roadside ditches.
</P>
<P>
   Green Pastures, developed in the 1970s, is a jumble of 760
mobile homes, many with leaking septic systems. Drugs, gangs and
poverty are endemic. The county is gradually paving the roads at
taxpayer expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Central Texas you have counties willing to take on
regulatory obligations, yet the state won't give us the same
authority border counties have to stop the problem before it gets
extreme,'' Barton said. ``It's scandalous, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The flag-lot approach keeps officials in the dark until it is
too late to manage growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We find out about it when houses are on the ground and people
are living there and they apply for a septic tank permit,'' Barton
said. ``That's a pretty uncomfortable position if they're in a
flood plain or the lot's too small for a septic tank.''
</P>
<P>
   Hays is one of the state's fastest-growing counties, with a
population that soared from 65,000 in 1990 to nearly 100,000 today.
The population is projected to rise as high as 165,000 by 2010,
with most of that growth occurring outside cities' jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Hays County commissioners have adopted the boldest set of
development and subdivision rules of any county in Texas in an
effort to prevent flag lots and other substandard development. But
with counties lacking clear legal authority, the rules rest on thin
legal ice, Barton acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Substandard development is also a problem in more than two dozen
other counties near metropolitan areas, according to the Texas
Conference of Urban Counties.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide trend
</P>
<P>
   County commissioners and ordinary citizens have complained about
shoddy development in widely scattered areas outside Lubbock,
Houston, San Antonio and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flag lots are popping up all over the place,'' said Donald
Lee, executive director of the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows exactly where or how many, Lee said, because the
developers must file only a metes-and-bounds description of the
lots _ confusing and thick with legalese and surveyors' references
to trees, fences and other landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Without a map of the subdivision, it's tough to plan government
services. For example, the new households are not automatically
added to the 911 emergency system for police, fire and medical
calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you get a phone call and the computer doesn't know where
the phone call is coming from,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, emergency vehicles sometimes cannot navigate the
substandard driveways. Residents typically start using a common
driveway _ a road by any other name _ that they then expect the
county to maintain, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The meaning of `and'
</P>
<P>
   The trend can be traced to a deceptively simple court ruling in
a case called Elgin Bank of Texas vs. Travis County.
</P>
<P>
   The bank wanted to sell parts of a 150-acre tract without filing
a subdivision plat with the county. The county balked.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals in Austin sided with the bank, which
intended for each lot to have direct access to an existing road.
The court, pointing to the wording of the state's local-government
legislation, ruled that such a blueprint is required only when the
landowner is dividing land ``to lay out lots . . . and to lay out
streets'' or other public areas.
</P>
<P>
   The county had argued that the word ``and'' should be construed
as having the same meaning as the word ``or.'' The court ruled that
this could be done only to prevent an absurd result but that no
such result arose from the ordinary reading of ``and.''
</P>
<P>
   Most counties are urging the Legislature to revise the law to
close what they are calling the Elgin Bank loophole. A smaller
number, including Hays, want lawmakers to grant broad land-use
controls to counties, or at least powers equivalent to those
already given to border counties.
</P>
<P>
   The counties' efforts failed during last year's legislative
session, but a new push is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate and building industries don't want counties to
get too much power, contending that some areas of the state should
remain off-limits to stringent land-use controls. Industry
officials say the number of developers who build shoddy
subdivisions is small and the vast majority practice sound
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Association of Builders would go along with requiring
platting in almost all cases. But the trade association wants an
exception for lots bigger than five acres. Such lots are already
exempt from platting requirements when they are in cities'
jurisdictions. The association opposes granting all counties the
broader authority held by border counties.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Erben, director of legislative affairs for the builders'
group, said the question is one of balance: ``How do you punish
irresponsible subdividers without burdening quality developers?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
