<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ It was like getting a message from a tree -- a
historic and greatly beloved tree. My son and I couldn't find the
Caroline Avenue oak when we were in Mobile, Ala.,driving blindly
around streets no longer familiar. When we saw a big stump, we
decided disaster had come to Mobile's most famous tree, also called
the Duffee oak, and stopped looking. It's funny how a tree can
bring people together. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ If you grew up in Catholic
schools in the '60s, sins had letter values: N, V and M, short for
``no sin,'' ``venial sin'' and ``mortal sin.'' In recent years my
mother has made an addendum to litany of mortal sins: shopping at
Meijer. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ While helping a friend move a
fortune in antique guns this past Independence Day weekend, I
concluded that America's western expansion would have been the best
time to be alive. Actually, I had that thought when I first read
Zane Grey and Jack London as a boy. But handling guns that were
actually owned and used by pioneers, outlaws and lawmen on the
western frontier brought it all back. (Nethaway, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
