<HEADLINE>
NEWS AND NOTES ON NEW YORK AREA BUSINSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Jersey Sees Fall In Jobless Rate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Even as unemployment rose nationally in June,
New Jersey's jobless rate fell to the lowest point in eight years,
4.8 percent, the State Labor Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Employers in the state added 3,700 new jobs in June, pushing the
unemployment rate down two-tenths of one percent. The service
sector grew by 5,000 jobs, but the number of manufacturing jobs
declined by 900, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, New Jersey is on a pace to create 65,000 to 70,000
jobs in 1998. In 1997, 80,000 jobs were created, the most in 12
years, said Joseph Seneca, chairman of the New Jersey Council of
Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the unemployment rate rose 0.2 percent in June, to
4.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   HMV to Enter Harlem
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ HMV Worldwide plans to open Harlem's first music
superstore next year, on West 125th Street next to the Apollo
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The store will have 15,000 square feet of retail space and will
employ over 100 people, the company said Tuesday. Groundbreaking
will be held on Monday, and the store is expected to open in the
middle of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   HMV Worldwide, which is based in London and has its North
American headquarters in Toronto, is the world's largest music
retailer with 270 stores. Sixteen of them are in the United States,
including four superstores in Manhattan at Herald Square, Fifth
Avenue, 8th Street and Lexington Avenue and 72d and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The Harlem store will be part of the Harlem USA development, the
long-delayed entertainment-retail complex that will occupy most of
the block bounded by 124th and 125th Streets and Eighth and St.
Nicholas Avenues. Other businesses scheduled to open there include
the Gap, Chase Manhattan Bank, Radio Shack and Watch World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it is a good commercial opportunity _ it's not just a
neighborhood, it's a big city in its own right,'' said Stuart
McAllister, the chief executive officer of HMV's chief executive.
``And not to sound too altruistic, but we think it's important to
give something back to the community that has sponsored one of the
greatest art forms to come out of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Casino Firms Settle Fight
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Las Vegas-based casino operators settled their legal
differences Tuesday and agreed to jointly develop a hotel-casino in
Atlantic City's marina district, an official of one of the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The $750 million project by the two companies, Mirage Resorts
Inc. and the Boyd Gaming Corporation, will include a 1,200-room
hotel and 100,000-square-foot casino on a 25-acre parcel, said
Ellis Landau, Boyd's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will contribute $150 million apiece to the
project, Landau said, although Boyd's contribution will be all in
cash, while Mirage's share includes the land, valued as $90
million, plus $60 million in cash. He said the remaining $450
million would be financed by loans or possibly bonds. A name has
not been chosen for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to break ground in September 1999 and open by
2002 provided the necessary approvals are granted, including a
decision by the United States Army Corps of Engineers on a $330
million road-and-tunnel project linking the marina district to the
rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The companies originally agreed to a slightly smaller project in
May 1996, but Boyd sued Mirage in February after Mirage terminated
the deal. Yesterday's agreement does not address a suit in which
Circus Circus Enterprises of Las Vegas also accused Mirage of
backing out of a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Roffman, a gambling analyst with Roffman Miller
Associates in Philadelphia, said yesterday's deal was a step toward
transforming Atlantic City into a destination resort to better
compete with Indian-owned casinos in Connecticut and destinations
like Las Vegas. But, Roffman cautioned, ``None of this is going to
happen until 2002 anyway, and by then we could be in a severe
recession.''
</P>
</TEXT>
