<HEADLINE>
WESTWOOD FAVORITE OF PLAYERS IN OPEN; KUCHAR PONDERS TURNING PRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Asked to pick a favorite for this year's
British Open, many players have named Lee Westwood, who has won
three times in his last four starts on the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   At age 25, Westwood has risen to No. 7 in the world ranking, and
the native of Worksop, England, will be a crowd favorite when the
tournament begins Thursday at Royal Birkdale Golf Club, about a
two-hour drive from Westwood's home. But if Westwood is having
trouble handling growing expectations, he refuses to show it. He
has talked as confidently as he has played, and he is driven to be
the world's best player.
</P>
<P>
   ``What other people expect doesn't really bother me,'' said
Westwood, who is coming off last week's victory at the Standard
Life Loch Lomond Invitational in Scotland. ``I'm not afraid of
winning. I won't be nervous coming down the stretch if I'm winning.
That is my ultimate aim, to be No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons have been made between Westwood and Tiger Woods, one
of the contenders Westwood hopes to beat this week. Westwood
admitted that Woods' emergence as a force in professional golf
helped inspire the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you get sort of a rivalry anywhere, it brings the
whole bunch on,'' Westwood said. ``There are so many good players
in Europe and around the world under 30, it can't help but spur
everybody else on. I don't think it's any coincidence that with
Tiger winning the Masters last year, you've seen a big improvement
in my game, David Duval's game, Justin Leonard's game, Ernie Els'
game. When one does something, it drags everybody else along. I
think it can only be good for the game worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kuchar, the 1997 U.S. Amateur champion, is torn between
returning for his junior year at Georgia Tech, or turning
professional. After strong showings at both the Masters (tied for
21st) and the U.S. Open (tied for 14th), Kuchar has thought more
about leaving school, and he is eager to see how he fares at the
British Open. Kuchar will make a decision about his status later
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm dead in the middle,'' said Kuchar, of his
decision on whether to turn professional or return to school. ``It
seems to be all I think about. It is hard to get focused on playing
golf when everybody wants to know what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At home, I really can't get away from it. The phone doesn't
stop _ agents are calling, sponsors are calling. It seems that's
what everybody wants to talk about. There are so many positives
about going back to school, and so many positives about going pro.
I don't know what's going to happen.'' Faldo Is Planning to Play
</P>
<P>
   Unless he suffers another setback before Thursday, Nick Faldo
plans to play in the British Open. Faldo's injured right elbow has
responded well to treatment, and he was upbeat following today's
practice round.
</P>
<P>
   ``My elbow is feeling great,'' said Faldo, a three-time British
Open champion. ``It must be the 200 autographs I'm signing warming
it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
