r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-TRADES-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      07-15 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-TRADES-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADES NOT ALWAYS AS THEY SEEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Get past the newfangled purples and teals of today's
uniforms and Major League Baseball is pretty much the same game on
the field as it was 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the field, however, the game has little resemblance to
its forerunner in the 1950s. For that matter, working in a front
office now isn't even close to what it was just 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A general manager can get burned now if he isn't on top of every
intricacy of a player's contract. For that matter, any GM must know
even the simplest of rules or he can look foolish.
</P>
<P>
   As an example we offer Los Angeles' interim GM Tommy Lasorda,
who could end up with some ugly, runny egg on his face after his
Paul Konerko and Dennis Reyes for Jeff Shaw trade with Cincinnati
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda was unaware that because Shaw was traded in the middle
of a multiyear contract he can demand a trade or become a free
agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   So while Lasorda was bragging about how cheap he had landed Shaw
for the next two years, plus an option season, he had no idea that
he can lose his new closer outright after this season.
</P>
<P>
   In order to save face and justify giving up Konerko and Reyes,
the Dodgers will have to renegotiate with Shaw, whose salary will
probably jump from under $3 million to over $5 million next
season. &QL; 
The trading deadline without requiring waivers is quickly
approaching. Between now and 9 p.m., July 31, several trades should
take place, most within the final 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The usual trading will take place, where contending clubs, or
those believing they can, will swap young talent for a veteran for
the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary, the contending clubs will try and low-ball
while the clubs near the bottom of the standings will hold out for
more value. The Diamondbacks, who have several players who could
help a contender, are in an enviable position.
</P>
<P>
   They can sit back and wait on offers, sifting through the bad
ones and trying to up the ante from the serious clubs. The players
who have generated some talk include center fielder Devon White and
catchers Jorge Fabregas and Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondback who has created the most fuss is left-hander
Brian Anderson, who had a 1.80 ERA in 10 postseason innings last
year. But the Diamondbacks have no desire to deal Anderson, who at
26 could be a vital part of Arizona's pitching staff for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's front office will hold out for the most trade value.
The Diamondbacks are in such a desirable position, they don't have
to make a move. They can play out the season and keep White and the
others if they feel another club is trying to screw them.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks can hold out because they are one of the big
players in the majors. They have money rolling in by the bushel and
don't need to pare payroll in order to keep the profit margin
high. &QL; 
Not so fast &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is where trading in the 1990s is so different from just a
decade ago. Time was when a low-end club would trade for the simple
reason of acquiring young talent for the future.
</P>
<P>
   The wretched Atlanta Braves of 1987 dealt veteran starter Doyle
Alexander to Detroit for a Double-A pitcher named John Smoltz.
Alexander wound up going 9-0 in 11 starts and the Tigers ended up
winning the American League East by one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to a time when you'd pick up a phone, call someone,
make a deal and boom, that was it,'' Diamondbacks assistant general
manager Sandy Johnson said. ``It was done and both parties were
happy. It's all different now.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you have clubs trying to move expensive mistakes they may
have made a year or two earlier. Small-market clubs also try to get
something for star players who are eligible for free agency,
players they know they might not be able to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Like the impending monsoons, the trading season is around the
corner. Get ready, it could be a wild time. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
