</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-GATEWAY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Wheeling and Dealing PCs  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No down payment. Low monthly payments. Trade it in for a new one
after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like financing for a car, but in fact it's a
ground-breaking program by Gateway that lets consumers get a new
personal computer without having to spend $1,500 to $2,000 up
front.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway's move, along with a program by Dell Computer that lets
consumers lease new PCs instead of buying them, are being
scrutinized by the rest of the industry as companies seek new ways
to attract first-time buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Dell and Gateway, the second- and fourth-largest PC-makers in
the United States, sell systems directly to consumers by phone and
over the Internet. They don't have to deal with middlemen or retail
stores, making it easier for them to introduce novel financing
plans.
</P>
<P>
   With trade-in options and different types of leases, they hope
to entice consumers who are reluctant to shell out big bucks for
something that is guaranteed to become obsolete in just a few
years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new financing programs are designed to appeal
to buyers who don't have a lot of cash but can manage payments of
less than $50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The affordability coupled with obsolescence protection is
striking a chord with consumers,'' said Bart Brown, vice president
of home marketing for South Dakota-based Gateway. ``The program has
been successful beyond our wildest forecasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Your:)Ware financing program _ promoted through a
slick TV advertising campaign _ seems to have invigorated Gateway.
Since the program was announced at the end of May, Gateway's stock
has soared 44 percent. It closed yesterday at $61.88, up $2.13.
</P>
<P>
   The Your:)Ware program lets you finance a new multimedia PC over
two, three or four years, at interest rates as low as 14.9 percent.
For $49.95 a month, over four years, you can get a Pentium II 300
megahertz PC with 32 megabytes of memory, a five gigabyte hard
drive, a DVD drive and a 15-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The total price of the system, including financing, comes to
just under $2,400, which is a lot to pay for those specifications.
But the deal also gives you unlimited free Internet access through
Gateway's own Internet service. Based on an average cost of $20 a
month, that works out to $960 worth of Internet access over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Any time after the first two years, you can trade in your system
for a new one and get a trade-in allowance equal to the blue book
value of your computer (typically less than one-third of its
original price).
</P>
<P>
   Dell's Personal Lease program works just like a car lease. For
example, you can get a Pentium II 300 system that retails for
$1,699 for $64 a month over three years. That comes to a total of
about $2,300. At the end of the lease you can either return the
system and walk away, lease a new one, or buy the computer you were
leasing for 15 percent of the original purchase price (in this case
$255).
</P>
<P>
   Dell started its leasing program last August, but at that time
only offered a two-year lease and required an initial payment equal
to the first-and last-month's payments. In March, the company
eliminated the up-front payment and added a 36-month option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we came up with the modifications we've seen a doubling
of customers, and it continues to grow month over month,'' said
Mike Watt, chief operating officer for Dell Financial Services, the
company's financing arm.
</P>
<P>
   One recent customer, C.D. Rowsell of Hayward, said he decided to
lease a Dell Dimension computer after checking out the company's
leasing plan on the Web. And he's happy he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a state-of-the-art machine (with a 400 MHz Pentium II),
the monthly outlay isn't huge, and it was easy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts see the programs, especially Gateway's, as a way for
PC-makers to establish long-term relationships. In addition to
gaining repeat business through trade-ins, the company can use the
Your:)Ware program to sell upgrades and new services, such as
customized technical support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that PC companies want to turn their
customers into annuities,'' said analyst Scott Miller of Dataquest.
``They don't want to have to resell people every three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said it's ``exceptionally important to watch how Gateway
does with this. It's a complicated undertaking, and I'm not
convinced that this model is where the industry will end up. But
they're moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-09-98 2111EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
