<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-GAMING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF GAMING GRABS YOU, CHECK THESE TITLES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By MICHAEL SAUNDERS   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eyes that feel sandblasted. A persistent dull throb in the mouse
hand. Laundry collects in a corner that is on its way to being
declared a domestic Superfund site, and come to think of it, you're
getting pretty ripe, too.
</P>
<P>
   These are the unmistakable signs of a serious addiction.
</P>
<P>
   But what games are good enough to trigger that I-gotta-play
response, the kind of yearning that makes some game fanatics blow
off dates and forget other important things, like eating and work?
</P>
<P>
   Lately, I've been getting grainy eyed over real-time strategy
games. I was strung out on Total Annihilation for a while,
determined to rack up victories against the evil Core. It didn't
help that Cavedog Entertainment just released an expansion pack
with more missions, maps, and new machinery. Dark Reign fed my
temporary need for interplanetary domination with its excellent
sound and graphics; it, too, has an expansion available, and
Activision promises even more versions of this award-winning game.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is often an addiction unto itself, with its surplus of
minutiae and useless facts that blur the line between jockdom and
geekhood. Baseball games torque the geek quotient up several
notches, as in the case of Microsoft's 1998 edition of Baseball 3D
and the forward-looking All-Star Baseball 99 for the Nintendo 64
system.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is a stat-freak's dream, player and team performance
broken down into several hundred categories. This is definitely a
game to warrant buying several extra memory modules to hold all
that data. Baseball 3D is among the best-looking sports games on
the market, with accurate renderings of all major-league stadiums
and detailed high-polygon player models that do everything except
adjust their cups at the plate. According to the box, all this
realism requires a system with a Pentium 133 chip or better, 16
megs of RAM, and a 2 meg 3D card. We ran it on a P-166 with 16 megs
and found the action sequences annoyingly choppy. A P-200 with 32
megs handled the game nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Between bouts of galactic conquest and attempted triple plays,
it has been hard to escape the Play-Station game N2O: Nitrous
Oxide. This is a pure fast-twitch fiber workout; the only strategy
is to stay alive while spiraling through the iridescent gut canal
of some huge beast. (OK, maybe they're just tunnels, but indulge my
little ``Fantastic Voyage'' fantasy.) While your skimming
hovercraft is blasting nasty intestinal flora and fauna,
high-energy dance beats from the Crystal Method pump out of the
speakers. This game sounds amazing routed through a home theater
sound system.
</P>
<P>
   After having gone through a Final Fantasy VII binge when the
game was released for PlayStation, I expected the new PC version to
collect dust in the ever-expanding in-basket. Cloud, Barret, Tifa,
and the rest of the crew still offer some of the most engaging
gameplay ever designed for any format, and the PC version's
graphics approach console quality. The heart of the game is the
rich storyline, which remains unchanged, so this game might trigger
more people to find out what the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC;  Call it what you will _ the Evil Empire, maker of Windoze,
foister of Internet Explorer upon hapless millions _ but when
Microsoft wants to do something right, it usually gets it done.
</P>
<P>
   Our uncharacteristic largesse was prompted by the high-wow
factor of Microsoft's site terraserver.microsoft.com, which, in
typically low-key Microsoft fashion, claims to be the world's
largest online database. With 1.01 terabytes of info harnessed on
linked hard drives (about 100,000 copies of ``Moby-Dick,'' if you
really need to know), it contains satellite photographs of much of
the United States, and most large cities in Europe, Africa, and
Asia. Click on a region or enter a city to get surprisingly clear
images. The pictures are of Cuban Missile Crisis resolution,
meaning I was able to make out the car parked in my driveway but
couldn't read the license plate. For that, one would need access to
the newer sky spy imaging technology that enables the government to
count nose hairs on a chosen target.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to smile and wave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC;  If computers, sheep, and cows can be cloned, why not food?
</P>
<P>
   Top Secret Recipes (topsecretrecipes.com) is the Web's home of
food fakery where aspiring cooks can create accurate copies of
well-known fare. The site is designed for cooks of varying skills,
so there's a copy of Kraft's Macaroni and Cheese not far from four
copies of soups made by Al Yeganeh, the real-life Soup Nazi, of
``Seinfeld'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Celtic Antoine Walker has agreed to help Electronic Arts
plug its next sports title, NBA Live 99, scheduled to ship later
this year for Nintendo 64, PlayStation, and PC platforms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-09-98 1326EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
