<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: STOPPING BABIES FROM CRYING; ELECTRONIC SCHEDULER; 
PREVIEWS FOR PHOTOGRAPHERS; TALKING DOORBELL; PATENT INFORMATION ON
THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's summer, and the living is supposed to be easy. For new
parents, Donald Spector's recently awarded patent could ease the
wails of a crying baby.
</P>
<P>
   Spector, who lives in Union City, N.J., invented a
voice-activated sound-and-light box that attaches to a crib. Or
rather, it is cry-activated. When a baby wails, a sound-activated
switch turns on a light inside the box. The light shines through a
semireflective mirror on the box's front. Behind the mirror is a
slot for a picture. The box also has a recording and playback
system.
</P>
<P>
   Spector's idea is that new parents will slip a photo of Mom into
the picture slot, and Mom or Dad will record a soothing message for
the baby. Thus, when the infant cries, his wails light up the box
and start the playback. The child sees Mom's picture, hears her
voice, and, Spector hopes, stops crying. Spector received patent
5,774,861.
</P>
<P>
   Let the Calendar Do the Scheduling
</P>
<P>
   Lots of people go on vacation in summer, making it difficult to
schedule work meetings. Gregory Fitzpatrick and Marvin Williams,
two Texas inventors working for IBM, have patented a solution _ an
electronic calendar that monitors other electronic calendars,
detects when dates are available and fits in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The invention uses electronic calendars that are part of a
networked system of computers. First, the person initiating the
meeting enters the date, time and duration of the proposed meeting
into his electronic calendar. If a conflict exists for any of the
expected participants, the software notifies the person who entered
the request.
</P>
<P>
   It then monitors the electronic calendars of the other
participants, detecting when the conflicting events are rescheduled
or canceled. When that happens, the electronic calendar schedules
the proposed meeting on the agendas of everyone involved.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick and Williams received patent 5,774,867, which was
assigned to IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Getting a Picture of a Picture
</P>
<P>
   Photo-taking increases in summer as people spend more time with
their families, outdoors or on vacation. Minolta hopes to make
taking snapshots easier with a camera that lets photographers
preview their pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroshi Ootsuka, a Minolta employee from Toyokawa, Japan,
invented a camera that has conventional controls for film speed,
shutter speed and exposure. A photographer can set those controls
and then check to see whether the photo he is about to take will
really look the way he expects.
</P>
<P>
   The camera picks up the image of the intended photograph and
displays it on a monitor. The photographer can examine the proposed
picture and change the camera's setting if desired. The camera then
takes up the role of a conventional camera, recording the image on
film. Ootsuka received patent 5,774,754, which was assigned to
Minolta.
</P>
<P>
   A Doorbell With a Voice
</P>
<P>
   Barbecues in the back yard and picnics in the park take people
out of their homes in summer. What if friends or neighbors stop by?
With Todd Housely's invention, when they ring the doorbell, they
won't hear a chime. Instead, they'll get a voice message. When a
visitor pushes the doorbell, a signal is transmitted to a
programmable doorbell controller. The controller contains a
recording of a voice message. When the signal is received, the
controller activates a playback of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Housely also designed a recording system that lets a visitor
leave a message. The visitor presses a recording button installed
near the doorbell, and an adjacent microphone picks up the spoken
message and transmits it to the controller, where it is encoded and
stored. Housely received patent 5,774,039.
</P>
<P>
   Coming Soon: Patents on the Web
</P>
<P>
   The Patent and Trademark Office has announced that it will make
patent and trademark data available free on its Web site before the
end of the year. The agency says that the full text of trademarks
will be posted on the site in August. Drawings from trademarks and
the full text of 2 million patents issued since 1976 will be added
in November. The drawings included with patents will be available
next March.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the agency's site, www.uspto.gov, offered only
abstracts _ the brief description of an invention that appears on
the first page of a patent. But the agency has offered free access
to the full text of AIDS-related patents since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-12-98 1834EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
