<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-STREAMING-SOFTWAR     07-15 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-STREAMING-SOFTWARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR STEPS FORWARD FOR STREAMING TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The streaming technology that allows music and video to be sent
over the Internet to personal computers is still a curiosity as a
medium and a puzzle as a business.
</P>
<P>
   But Real Networks Inc., the leader in streaming software, is
making announcements Monday that represent steps toward developing
both the medium and its business model further, industry analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   The company is releasing a test, or beta, version of its desktop
and network server software that employs a new standard for
streaming technology, Synchronized Multimedia Integration Language,
or SMIL (pronounced smile.)
</P>
<P>
   In the industry, the hope is that the new format, recommended by
the World Wide Web Consortium, a nonprofit arbiter of technical
standards for Internet software, will open the way for a flood of
streaming-media programming _ as did agreement on Hypertext Markup
Language, or HTML, the document format for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   SMIL should allow Web programmers to put video, audio, text and
charts into an integrated presentation that can be broadcast live
or on demand to Internet-connected personal computers. Until now,
streaming technology has tended to be used to send standard radio
or television programming over the Internet, like video of a sports
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Real Networks' deployment of SMIL is an important step
toward moving streaming technology to become a real new media,''
said Jae Kim, an analyst for Paul Kagan Associates, a research firm
in Carmel, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks' latest version of its desktop software for
receiving streaming media, Real Player G2, has ``channels'' to link
users to Internet broadcast sites of more than 60 media companies
including CNN, ABC, Fox, ESPN, CBS Sportsline, Sony CMPnet and The
Wall Street Journal. Real Player is distributed free from the
company Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The channel feature is the Seattle-based company's effort to
become a gateway, or portal, for steering users to other
programming. The steering strategy, if successful, will bring in
added revenues and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks software is used on more than 80 percent of the
Web pages with streaming media, and Real Networks said it had more
than 26 million registered users, up from 7 million in April 1997.
``After the Web browsers, we have by far the largest base of
users,'' said Rob Glaser, chairman of Real Networks.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. bought a 10 percent stake in Real Networks last
July, before the company went public in November. Under securities
law, Microsoft has to hold onto its shares for a year, meaning it
can sell at the end of this month. Glaser declined to comment on
whether Microsoft, whose Netshow product competes with Real
Networks, might sell off its holding.
</P>
<P>
   Real Networks' stock closed last week at $34.75 a share,
compared with its initial public offering price of $12.50. The
company will lose $10 million on revenues of $54 million this year,
estimated David Readerman, an analyst at Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities. By 2000, he projected, the company will earn $12
million on revenues of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-12-98 1746EDT &QL;
</P>
