<HEADLINE>
TELECOMMUNICATIONS: JUSTICE DEPT. VS. THE BELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Multibillion-dollar mergers are the most glamorous events in the
telecommunications business. But potentially the most important
development in the industry continues to be the legal battle
between the Bell local phone companies and the Justice Department
over the soul of the Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The battlefront last week was in New Orleans, where the 5th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals heard arguments in the government's appeal
of a December decision that would give the Bells what they most
desire: immediate entry into the $80 billion long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   That decision, issued mere hours before the end of the year by
Judge Joe Kendall of U.S. District Court in Wichita Falls, Texas,
never went into effect. For now, the Bells must wait for approval
from the Federal Communications Commission before selling
long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells' case may well end up before the Supreme Court and
remain unresolved for a year.
</P>
<P>
   But for communications regulators, carriers, investors and
customers the case will remain critical. That importance could be
seen in the identity of the lawyers who made the main arguments on
Thursday: Laurence Tribe from Harvard University for the Bells and
Joel Klein, head of the Justice Department's antitrust division for
the government.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells, led by SBC Communications Inc., have made a shrewd
argument. Basically, they contend that the U.S. Constitution does
not allow Congress to act as if it were a judge, namely U.S.
District Judge Harold Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Greene supervised the breakup of AT&AMP;T in the 1980s into a
long-distance company, now named AT&AMP;T Corp., and seven Bell local
phone companies. The split was part of a consent decree that the
old AT&AMP;T agreed to in an antitrust settlement with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The consent decree and Greene's rulings gave the Bells legal
monopolies on local phone service in their regions. The catch was
that the Bells were not allowed to sell long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   A main goal of the 1996 telecommunications act was to foster
competition in local phone markets. But the Bells had to be enticed
to give up their monopolies and to open their networks so that new
companies could come into the local market without rewiring
buildings across. So Congress provided a way for the Bells to get
into the long-distance arena.
</P>
<P>
   But the path is not easy. The law said that once a Bell had
convinced the FCC that it had opened its network, the Bell would be
allowed to sell long-distance service. (No Bell has yet passed that
test.)
</P>
<P>
   As the telecommunications bill became law, Greene vacated the
consent decree. So the Bells basically traded a regulatory regime
governed by the consent decree and Greene for one governed by the
Telecommunications Act of 1996 and the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   That trade gave the Bells an opportunity, one they have
exploited. When the consent decree and Greene's orders were keeping
the Bells out of long distance, they had little real argument.
After all, through their former parent company, AT&AMP;T, they had
agreed to a court-supervised settlement that made their independent
existence possible.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Bells are arguing that the telecommunications act
unfairly singles them out. Barring the Bells from the long-distance
market until they satisfy the FCC is a punishment, they argue, and
Congress has punished the Bells without a trial. When a legislature
(like Congress) punishes someone without a trial, it is known in
legal parlance as a bill of attainder, and bills of attainder are
specifically barred by the Constitution.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Very few people expected SBC to succeed when it first made that
argument. After all, the Bells seemed to support the act at its
passage. And everyone knew the Bells were a special regulatory
case, right? Wasn't that the whole reason they were under the
consent decree?
</P>
<P>
   But Kendall agreed with the Bells that as a matter of law, the
history was irrelevant. The consent decree had been vacated. He
agreed with the Bells that it was fundamentally unfair that
Congress had allowed non-Bell local phone companies like GTE Corp.
into the long-distance market without restriction while the Bells
were forced to pass severe regulatory tests.
</P>
<P>
   Klein argues that the long-distance restrictions are not a form
of punishment, but rather a sort of regulation. With their sheer
size and geographic concentration, the Bells merit especially close
attention from Congress, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, SBC is sparing no opportunity to paint itself as the
champion of constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never want a situation where Congress can single out for
penalties any single group,'' said James Ellis, the company's
general counsel. ``If it can happen to us, they can do it to
less-advantaged groups.''
</P>
<P>
   A difference, of course, between the Bells and less-advantaged
groups is that the Bells are one of the most formidable lobbies in
Washington. With employees and local ties in hundreds of
congressional districts across the country, they wield an influence
that by many accounts surpasses that of the long-distance giants.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Kendall's ruling holds up on appeal, it will let
the Bells rush into long distance without necessarily giving up
their grip on local markets. They would take billions of dollars in
revenue directly away from the likes of AT&AMP;T and MCI.
</P>
<P>
   And they would be happy with no glamour at all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-12-98 1657EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
