<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERACTIVE-ADCOL-550&AMP;AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AD GIANT FORMS INTERACTIVE DIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A giant agency is forming a division to specialize in
interactive marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is Ammirati Puris Lintas, one of four worldwide
networks owned by Interpublic Group of Cos. Ammirati Puris, with
billings estimated at $4.4 billion, has opened a division named APL
Digital, which will seek to harness the new media ``to bring brands
closer to consumers,'' said Martin Puris, the chairman, chief
executive and chief creative officer at Ammirati Puris in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Internet began to assume prominence along Madison
Avenue three or four years ago, it would not be surprising if
people were to ask, to paraphrase a line from an old commercial,
``Ammirati Puris, what took you so long?''
</P>
<P>
   An in-house group, Ammirati Puris Lintas Online, has given the
agency ``interactive capability since the beginning of 1995,'' said
Brian Cauley, president at APL Digital, ``so it's not as if we've
just discovered it.''
</P>
<P>
   But about three weeks ago, he added, the Ammirati Puris
worldwide operating board decided ``to formally set up an Internet
capability and subbrand it as APL Digital.''
</P>
<P>
   APL Digital is the ``first subbrand ever for the Ammirati Puris
Lintas network,'' Cauley said. ``That's an indication of how
important this move to digital communications is.''
</P>
<P>
   APL Digital has 140 employees in offices in Hong Kong, London,
New York and Sydney, Australia; plans call for offices to be opened
in additional cities before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of APL Digital is indicative of the growing ardor
among traditional agencies to stake a claim to cyberspace. But many
involved in interactive advertising, electronic commerce and the
Internet continue to disparage the digital efforts of the Madison
Avenue mainstays, asserting that they are not as nimble or skilled
as the crop of fledgling independent agencies that were founded
recently to specialize in digital communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's baloney,'' Cauley said. ``We all know what the Web is
about: commerce, customer service and a more efficient distribution
of information.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the game is who's going to do those things better,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Puris took issue with the widespread belief that Madison Avenue
is, to quote the headline on an article last month in the trade
publication Brandweek, ``Missing the E-Boat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it represents a fundamental change,'' Puris said.
``And we've been in pitches with the independents _ and we've
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cauley acknowledged, ``there is some truth'' to
assertions that more than a few traditional agencies had tarried in
dedicating resources to the interactive realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who work in new media are always a little bit
`Come on, let's move faster,''' he added.
</P>
<P>
   APL Digital is doing worldwide work for two clients, Compaq
Computer Corp. and Iridium LLC. In this country, the interactive
unit is handling assignments for Aetna Inc., Ameritech Corp., Lego
Group, the Nickelodeon cable television network owned by Viacom
Inc., Unilever and United Parcel Service of America.
</P>
<P>
   In a staff memo last week announcing the promotion of Cauley,
39, to president at APL Digital from executive vice president and
managing director, Puris projected the unit's revenue at $10
million; Cauley estimated billings at $20 million to $30 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Cauley, as part of his promotion, joins the New York management
committee of Ammirati Puris and the worldwide operating board.
Other top officers of APL Digital include Mark Avnet, senior vice
president and director for production and technology; Lynn Bolger,
senior vice president and media director, and Bruce Ledbetter,
principal technical strategist.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of what APL Digital does ``is hard-core Web
site development,'' Cauley said. Examples include a 12-language
site for Iridium (www.iridium.com) and an e-commerce initiative for
Compaq (www.directplus.compaq.com). The remaining APL assignments
are centered on ads for Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the announcement of the formation of APL Digital
came a month after Compaq, a big technology account of Ammirati
Puris, moved the creative and media portions of its account, with
billings estimated at $250 million to $300 million, to DDB Needham
Worldwide in New York, part of Omnicom Group. Ammirati Puris
retained the direct marketing and interactive parts of the account.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Internet clients at Compaq tend to be different from our
advertising clients,'' Cauley said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever manner in which interactive marketing is handled, Puris
said, one verity remains: ``You still have to go on the Internet
with an idea. Without one, it doesn't work any better than a
billboard outside of La Guardia Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-12-98 1654EDT &QL;
</P>
