 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Big wedding generates news, gossip, photos 
By Frances Katz  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a good bet that the new wife of James Brolin, aka Barbra
Streisand, will probably not change her name. For the uninformed,
the celebrated singer and actress, wearing (what else?) a Donna
Karan wedding dress, tied the knot last week with longtime
boyfriend Brolin.
</P>
<P>
   If, by chance, your invitation got lost in the mail or your
helicopter was in the shop that day, you can find plenty of Barbra
wedding news and info on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine has the exclusive story and pictures of the big
day at http://www.pathfinder.com/people/sp/streisand/index.html.
The site is short on photos, but more are scheduled to come soon,
with the approval of the Brolins themselves. But in the meantime,
you can read a blow-by-blow, minute-by-minute account of who was
there, what they wore and what they ate (appetizers included sushi,
pizza, and roasted small potatoes filled with caviar, creme fraiche
and dill). The People site is just filled with juicy gossip, info
and tidbits that both the rabid fans and the merely curious will
adore.
</P>
<P>
   But will the couple live happily ever after? People has set up
message boards for visitors to voice their opinions. Fans of the
couple can also see if the couple's astrological signs are
compatible (Streisand's a Tauras, Brolin's a Capricorn) at
http://astrozine.com/preview002/feature4.html.
</P>
<P>
   Streisand's wedding is also a time to reconsider the star's life
and career. Fans of the singer can check out Barbra Streisand.com
(http://www.barbra-streisand.com) The site is primarily devoted to
her latest CD, ``Higher Ground'' but does include some comments
from Barbra herself as well as a place to sign up to get the latest
Streisand dish. It's a little bit out of date, but it's the real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   There are an astonishing number of fan pages devoted to creative
and interesting tributes to Barbra. The Streisand Myths and
Misinformation page
(http://acs2.bu.edu:8001/(tilde)pimentel/myths.html) is devoted to
debunking the many myths surrounding the singer. From here we can
learn that Barbra doesn't have an official fan club or an e-mail
address _ and no, she's never had her nose fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known Barbra fan site, which turns up on nearly
every Web page devoted to her, is the Barbra Streisand FAQ
(frequently asked questions) at
http://members.aol.com/markjayeye/bjsfaq. This is an amazingly
complete listing of Streisand's professional life and works. There
are no pictures, but the information here is exhaustive. Another
America Online member has another page devoted to Streisand's
musical career at http://members.aol.com/barbramusc/index.html with
some great vintage black and white photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some people who take Streisand very
seriously, there are others who don't mind having a little fun with
the icon. Mr. Showbiz has a fun site at
http://www.mrshowbiz.com/games/linked/hi/153.html that shows
visitors all the men (and there are quite a few) with whom Barbra
has spent time over the years. Memo to James Brolin: This is one
Barbra site you might just want to skip.
</P>
<P>
   Just say no: View the ads for President Clinton's new anti-drug
campaign. 
http://ww.msnbc.com/modules/videogallery/antidrug_campaign_video_gal
 lery.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Groovy, baby: The University of Virginia's online exhibit ``The
Psychedelic '60s: Literary Tradition and Social Change'' covers
everything from the Beat Generation to Vietnam.
http://www.lib.virginia.edu
</P>
<P>
   /exhibits/sixties/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Sushi site: Everything you ever wanted to know about sushi: from
eating it to making it. http://www.stickyrice.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
