<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PORN-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY INTERNET CASE COULD BE FIRST AMENDMENT LITMUS TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAN FREEDMAN   
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is not exactly ``Star Wars,'' but an intense
battle in cyberspace is coming to a head in the fast-growing
suburbs of the nation's capital. It pits the American Civil
Liberties Union against conservative anti-pornography crusaders.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the decision by the public library board of Loudoun
County, Va., which voted 5-4 last October to install so-called
blocking software to deny public library patrons access to computer
Internet sites featuring ``child pornography,'' ``hardcore
pornography'' and ``material deemed harmful to juveniles'' under
Virginia law.
</P>
<P>
   Library users calling up such sites are met with a computer
screen declaring ``Violation! Violation! Violation! Access to this
site has been blocked.''
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU and a local group, Mainstream Loudoun, are suing the
library's trustees in federal court in suburban Alexandria, Va.
They charge that the policy violates library patrons' First
Amendment rights because the software, X-Stop, designed by Log-On
Data Corp. of Anaheim, Calif., blocks not only pornographic sites
that have no constitutional protection, but sites that do have such
protection, such as sites maintained by the Yale University Biology
Department and the San Francisco Examiner and San Francisco
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A highly trained, professional librarian can make those
distinctions,'' said Ann Beeson, the lead ACLU lawyer in the case.
``Blocking software never could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Located northwest of Washington, Loudoun County is the scene of
exploding growth as bedroom communities spring up to replace the
small-town and rural-farming traditions that were the hallmarks of
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Henderson, Loudoun County library director, said last
November his staff tested X-Stop after it was installed and found
it blocked 57 sites that had nothing to do with pornography,
including the home page for the pacifist Society of Friends, also
known as the Quakers.
</P>
<P>
   The policy puts librarians ``in the position of being parents,
and it makes second-class citizens out of those not affluent enough
to have this technology in their home,'' he said. People who rely
on the library for the Internet ``have a different level of access,
and I'm not comfortable with that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after a specialist tinkered with the software, it still
blocked the Zero Population Growth web site and the Mormon Church
page on preventing masturbation.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Black, a Virginia state legislator and library board member
who voted for the policy, said that right now, ``99.9 percent'' of
sites blocked by the software clearly are pornographic. ``And even
if the software blocked some sites that didn't need to be blocked,
the fact is there is no other solution,'' he said. ``We've had very
few complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Bass, the lawyer for the board, said the controversy is less
about the First Amendment than ``whether constitution compels
libraries to facilitate federal felonies. There's no question that
obscenity and child porno is not protected speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Pornography viewing in libraries is not the board's only worry,
he added. Under sexual harassment law, permitting library users to
view pornography might enable employees to sue the county for
failing to do anything about a ``hostile work environment,'' Bass
said.
</P>
<P>
   Depositions in the case are continuing and absent a settlement,
it is likely to go to trial this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Intervening on the side of the plaintiffs are eight others, all
of whom contend that the blocking software unconstitutionally
restricts access to their work. They are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jonathan Troyer, whose ``Safer Sex Page'' gives advice on
sexuality to gay and bisexual teen-agers;
</P>
<P>
   _ John Ockerbloom, whose page features books ``from Ulysses to
Little Red Riding Hood'' that have been subject to censorship;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Maryland Chapter of the American Association of University
Women, which promotes education and pay equity for women;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rob Morse, columnist for the San Francisco Examiner;
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeremy Myers, an 18-year-old offering advice and book
references for gay and lesbian teen-agers;
</P>
<P>
   _ Sergio Arau, a Mexican painter and rock singer known as ``El
Padrino'' whose artworks are displayed on the Internet;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Renaissance Transgender Association, a support group for
those switching sexual identities;
</P>
<P>
   - And Jonathan Wallace, whose on-line publication ``The Ethical
Spectacle'' examines Internet censorship issues.
</P>
<P>
   The lead plaintiff, Mainstream Loudoun, has its own lawyer and
is not represented by the ACLU.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court last year threw out a federal ban against
transmitting indecent materials to minors. The justices said the
prohibition was overly broad and would cut out a multitude of
constitutionally protected speech aimed at adults.
</P>
<P>
   But the Loudoun County case is the first test of what, if any,
limits there are on the Internet in an institution that for
generations has been the average person's most common point of
access to information: The public library.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it is being closely watched by organizations ranging
from the American Library Association, which supports the ACLU
position, to the American Center for Law and Justice, founded by
conservative tele-evangelist Pat Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   Other conservative groups are supporting the Loudoun County
Library Board, including the Family Research Council, led by former
Reagan administration official Gary Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Most other conflicts involving blocking software have been
resolved without litigation, according to Beeson. After ACLU
complaints, library systems in Boston and in Kern County,
California agreed to give patrons the option of using the software
during Internet searches if they desired.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU also is involved in a case in Livermore, Calif. where a
local parent, identified only as ``Kathleen R.'' is suing the local
library system in California Superior Court in Alameda County for
not employing the software.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Corn-Revere, lawyer for the Mainstream Loudoun group,
recalled the statement by the late Justice Potter Stewart that he
could not define pornography, ``but I know it when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   By using the blocking software, he said, Loudoun County's
version would be ``we know it without looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 1902EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
