<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Improving Anti-Smut Software  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I'm using CyberPatrol Internet blocking software, but to my
dismay, it doesn't seem to be blocking inappropriate sites that are
accessed through search engines like Yahoo. Do you know of any
other software that will prevent my teenage son from accessing sex
sites this way?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: &LR;  Actually, CyberPatrol will block access to a site reached
through a search engine as long as it's on the list of sites for
which the software has been programmed to look for. Unfortunately,
no blocking software is going to be able to keep up with the
explosion of raunchy Web sites. (Sex is one of the top growth
industries of the Internet.)
</P>
<P>
   However, you can make CyberPatrol block results of searches for
specific words, like ``sex.'' Here's how: First, go to the IRQ Chat
button in the CyberPatrol main screen and add the words you want to
block. Then, go back to the main screen and click the button for
WWW, FTP and Other. On the left side of the dialog box that
appears, click the check box labeled Apply IRQ keyword filters to
URL names.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've done this, a search for ``sex'' in most search
engines will come up empty. Keep in mind, though, that you'll also
be blocked from sites about about Middlesex, England; poet Anne
Sexton; or other sites containing the naughty word.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I would like to know how to put a GIF image in my signature
so that it appears on all my outgoing e-mail. I use Microsoft
Outlook Express.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; It can be done, but it takes a few steps. First, you'll
need to create an HTML file containing the image and your
signature. (The signature actually is just your name and other
personal information, not a real signature.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have Microsoft Office 97, you can use Word to do the job.
Open Word and start a new document. Choose Picture from the Insert
menu, then click from File. Locate the GIF image file on your hard
disk and insert it into the document. Then enter your signature
above or below the image. Finally, choose Save as HTML from Word's
File menu, give the document a name and save it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now open up Outlook Express. Choose Stationery from the
Tools menu to bring up the Stationery dialog box. In the area
titled, ``When composing new messages use,'' click This Stationery.
Then click Select, browse the hard disk for your new HTML document,
and select it.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. Every new message will contain the image and
signature, which can be received by anyone with a mail program
capable of handling HTML. By the way, don't forget to turn off any
other e-mail signature you may have created, to avoid a conflict.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Lately, every time I boot up my computer, the time is
wrong. The problem is that the computer's clock is slowing down.
What gives, and how can I fix it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Your system's battery probably is wearing out. And if it
fails, you may have trouble booting up your PC. My suggestion is to
take the computer to a qualified technician for a battery
replacement. You can do the job yourself, but it involves finding
the right kind of battery and backing up crucial system information
before removing the old one. FYI, most batteries are under $20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; Is there any way to compose and read e-mail without first
having to go online?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Sure. Just choose the Work Offline or Go Offline option
offered in the File menu of most e-mail programs. You then can read
any messages that previously have been downloaded, as well as
compose new messages, which will be sent the next time you go
online.
</P>
<P>
   If you use America Online, you can use FlashSessions to go
online automatically at scheduled times, download new messages
you've received and send out any you've written offline.
</P>
<P>
   Travel Update: A couple of weeks ago, I told someone they'd need
special phone plugs when connecting to the Internet in Europe.
Reader Charles Mills wrote in with this nifty piece of advice:
``Check out www.kropla.com. It appears to be a nonprofit site
devoted to answers to every question you could ever have about
foreign phone and power plugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tip of the Week &QC; If you're a heavy PC user, keep your system
running fast by defragmenting (optimizing) your hard drive once in
a while. Windows' Disk Defragmenter can be found by clicking
Start/Programs/Accessories/System Tools. The Disk Defragmenter will
tell you whether your disk needs optimizing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 2327EDT &QL;
</P>
