 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Motorola To Acquire Starfish  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Motorola said Tuesday it has agreed to acquire Starfish
Software, developer of the popular Rex personal organizer as well
as technology for linking wireless devices to computers.
</P>
<P>
   Starfish, based in Scotts Valley, will become a wholly owned
subsidiary of Schaumburg, Ill.-based Motorola pending regulatory
approvals. Starfish chief executive Philippe Kahn will be president
of the subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola President Bob Growney, who joined Kahn for the
announcement last night in San Francisco, said the cash-and-stock
deal values Starfish at several hundred million dollars. Exact
terms weren't disclosed because Starfish is a private company.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement comes as Motorola grapples with a tumultuous
reorganization brought on by weakness in its semiconductor business
and a 98 percent plunge in profits in its most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Growney said Motorola will build Starfish technology into
wireless devices that exchange information with each other as well
as with a variety of information sources including personal
computers, the Internet and wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complementary visions of our two companies _ to create an
environment in which consumers can literally take their world with
them _ makes this union not only logical but extremely powerful,''
said Growney.
</P>
<P>
   Starfish, which boasts about 100 employees, had been on track
for an initial public offering. But Kahn said the deal with
Motorola _ which came together in the past month _ was too good to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going for an IPO, we can focus on the technology
we're building and be part of the company that ships more than half
of the wireless devices in the world,'' he said. ``At the same
time, Motorola has been a little bit beaten up, so we'll take their
undervalued stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Motorola may benefit from having a nimble player
like Starfish in its stable _ a company that has a track record for
quickly deploying new technology. The Rex, a credit card-sized
organizer, is its best success to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starfish has continuously demonstrated its ability to
effectively advance technology solutions for swift market
development,'' said market analyst David Coursey.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Starfish owns a number of patents on technology for
linking wireless devices, which Motorola will now own.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn co-founded Starfish in 1994, shortly before he was ousted
as chief executive of Borland International. He had founded Borland
in 1982, and grew it into the world's third-largest software
company on the strength of database and spreadsheet products.
</P>
<P>
   Borland went sour in the 1990s, however, as its products were
eclipsed by other software that worked better with Microsoft
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 2326EDT &QL;
</P>
