<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT UNVEILS ON-LINE HOME-BUYING SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WARREN WILSON   
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Placing another long-term bet on the Internet,
Microsoft Corp. Monday unveiled a new service that aims to link
buyers, sellers, brokers and lenders through an easy-to-use Web
site called HomeAdvisor.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is hardly the first to spot the Internet's potential
in a data-intensive field such as real estate. Already, home buyers
can tap into a multitude of local and national sites that offer a
wealth of listings and other information.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's software expertise could give it an advantage in
offering unique user-friendly features, and in any case it intends
to work with existing players as much as it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an outstanding proposition'' for the broker, said
Microsoft's Ian Morris, lead product manager for HomeAdvisor.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers pay nothing to have their properties listed on
Microsoft's site, along with all the contact information. Visitors
to the site can describe what they want and instruct HomeAdvisor to
send an e-mail message when new properties are listed that meet
their criteria. They can easily e-mail the listing agent or send
the listing to the agent they're already working with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make it easy for agents to sell more homes faster,'' Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor aims to make money in two ways: advertisements and
loan-origination fees when it helps match buyers with mortgage
lenders. In theory, the lenders will get enough extra business to
make it worth their while to give Microsoft a cut of the loan fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenders obviously have to believe we're going to add a lot of
value,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   But buyers are increasingly going online for mortgage
information, so smart lenders are looking for services such as
HomeAdvisor that can help them garner more of that traffic, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   HomeAdvisor includes a number of features that Morris believes
aren't available elsewhere: such as the ability to compare two
homes side-by-side; a ``defect detector'' database that helps
buyers spot problems from foundation cracks to electrical shorts;
and a tool that lets a borrower say what is most important in a
mortgage loan _ low monthly payment or short payoff time, for
example _ and ranks available mortgages accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best site I've ever seen,'' said J. Lennox Scott,
president of Seattle-based John L. Scott Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
   It includes a wealth of information _ not just about properties
but about surrounding communities and nearby schools, for example,
Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   And, by helping link buyers with listing agents, it's an
excellent ``connectivity'' tool and very ``friendly'' to the
real-estate industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is what we look forward to _ meeting more people''
through HomeAdvisor, he said. ``Real estate is a personalized
service industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is jumping aboard just yet, however.
</P>
<P>
   While several multiple-listing services around the country are
charter participants, the Kirkland, Wash.-based Northwest Multiple
Listing Service isn't among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the idea of the broker making contact with the
customer,'' president Jack Johnson said. Accordingly, Northwest
Multi-List allows its broker-members to post its entire database on
their sites, and about 35 brokers now do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``HomeAdvisor is a wonderful site,'' he said, and Northwest
Multi-List hasn't ruled out participating in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely enthusiastic about the Internet,'' he said.
``We're watching with great interest what's going on in other parts
of the country, in particular with these national real-estate
sites. We've just chosen at this point in time not to put our
information on there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 2136EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
