<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-REALTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT OFFERS HOME-BUYING SERVICES SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JENNIFER BABSON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. launched Monday a new Internet site -- called
HomeAdvisor -- that touts an array of home buying services, from
listings and primers on the purchase process to demographic data on
local neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may also connect with lenders through the site, a
service that allows Microsoft to collect a minimal fee for acting
as a mortgage broker.
</P>
<P>
   The software giant's entry into the home buying business has
rekindled a debate over the propriety of home listings in an
increasingly crowded and competitive on-line marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   To the chagrin of some critics, the site does not include homes
that are for-sale by owners, though it does claim to have about
400,000 Realtor-listed homes displayed.
</P>
<P>
   With a paucity of homes listed on its site, it's not clear
whether Microsoft will be able to make a dent in the real estate
market. After proposing an alliance with Massachusetts' largest
real estate listing service recently, the latest entrant into the
cyber real estate market was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: MLS Property Information Network Inc. already has a
relationship with realtor.com, which with 1.2 million listings,
operates the largest real estate web site in the nation. The
National Association of Realtors has a financial stake in that
site.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's courtship did provide PIN with an unintended
fringe benefit: the leverage to demand its longtime web partner pay
a fee, about a $1 per listing, for the privilege of posting about
90 percent of PIN's nearly 80,000 annual residential listings on
its web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time we will not be cutting a deal with
Microsoft,'' said Court Dwyer, president and CEO of PIN, which is
the byproduct of a merger earlier this year between Bay State MLS
and the Greater Boston Real Estate Board's MLS 1 division.
</P>
<P>
   Sniffed Michael Keller, vice president of marketing at Real
Select, which operates realtor. com. ``One of the most recent
entrants is very late to the game and is joining a very large sea
of competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Resistance on the part of various real estate boards has forced
Microsoft to court local and regional real estate companies across
the country in search of on-line inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ``Preview'' by Microsoft, the site is still grappling
with some glitches. An early review of the site, while graphically
pleasing, proved arduous and frustrating: data on home listings was
nearly impossible to obtain, and numerous delays made surfing
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that there were some issues today there is no
doubt about it,'' said Microsoft spokesman Larry Cohen. ``It's like
the final test phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Significant explosions in both the real estate market and the
World Wide Web have led to a proliferation of on-line real estate
centers and services. Many real estate agencies have their own
sites, and most national brokerage firms also have a presence on
the web. Newspaper-linked sites, such as The Boston Globe's
boston.com, offer classified real estate ads on-line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there are more and more players entering the
field,'' said Alison Berkley, group product manager for Intuit,
which touts similar mortgage and homebuying services on the
Internet. In addition to advertising about 600,000 homes, Quicken
markets the wares of 11 lenders. If a deal originated by Quicken
closes, the company derives a fee of just under one half a
percentage point, and passes a $225 rebate to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Since Quicken came on-line last November, about ten new home
buying web sites have been launched, Berkley said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Tutunjian, manager of five Boston real estate offices for
Hunneman/Coldwell banker, believes that Internet marketing does
make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how we get a lot of our out of state contacts,'' he
said. ``But unless you are part of other links, you kind of get
lost.'' hunneman.com, a web site serving 72 Hunneman offices in
Massachusetts, gets about 18,000 hits per week, according to
Tutunjian.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 2007EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
