<HEADLINE>
NEW SPIN ON THE 'NET: USER-FRIENDLY WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WENDY TANAKA   
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Just a few short years ago, many corporate Web
sites were merely on-line business cards that posted an address,
phone number and company facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first effort was a marketing effort,'' said Susan
Weinstein, vice president of the on-line financial services group
for Wells Fargo Bank in San Francisco. ``It was designed on the
brochure model because nobody knew any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed in the past few years. Now businesses have
souped up their sites to include hundreds, and often thousands, of
intricately designed, interactive Web pages full of information
about a company's products, services and subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   But more information can make Web sites overwhelming and
unwieldy.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Snyder of User Interface Engineering, a company that
tests Web sites for ease of use, said businesses often make the
mistake of setting up Web sites before determining what they want
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies fall into the trap of developing a Web site around
their organizational chart,'' said Snyder, a principal at the North
Andover, Mass., firm, which also tests software usability. ``So
they're designed from the company looking out. A lot of companies
don't ask themselves what's in it for the user.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder also said companies erroneously think their Web sites are
extensions of their marketing and advertising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is different from advertising, which controls
everything the user sees and in what order,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jakob Nielsen was in charge of Web site testing at Palo Alto,
Calif.-based Sun Microsystems Inc. and has written two books on Web
sites. He said Internet users don't want to be entertained on the
Web: They want solid information, and they want it fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is about, `Get in, get out quick,''' Nielsen said.
``People will invest just a few seconds in glancing at your stuff
to see if it's useful to them.''
</P>
<P>
   All this has not fallen on deaf ears at corporations. Most have
revamped their Web sites at least once, making them easier and
faster to navigate.
</P>
<P>
   They have accomplished this by making graphics less elaborate,
developing hyperlink labeling that clearly states what the user
will get once he or she clicks on the link, and developing
personalized Web pages that act like bookmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gold Rush is over to get on the Internet,'' said Mark
Crumpacker, chief executive of San Francisco-based Studio Archetype
Inc., which has designed sites for United Parcel Service Inc.,
BankAmerica Corp. and 3Com Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people want objective reasons to have a Web site,'' he
added. ``A lot of them want to quantify the net effect it's having
on their brand. They're adding a ton more functionality when they
come back a second time.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Wells Fargo's Web site (www.wellsfargo.com) began as an
on-line business card in 1995, its pages have been revamped
continually since then. Weinstein said the bank has followed three
basic guidelines: Get rid of clutter, keep the message simple and
don't bury information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things used to be buried seven layers down,'' she said. ``The
goal is to get (information) to a higher level so customers can get
things with fewer clicks.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Customized pages are another trend in Web site redesign.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Chicago-based United Airlines created a page
called ``Personalize'' that bookmarks other pages on the company's
site (www.ual.com), such as the airline's frequent flier or
reservation pages.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Tony Molinaro said the new ``Personalize'' page
allows customers to instantly call up the pages they use the most
and eliminate the laborious process of clicking through several
screens to get to information.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's ``Personalize'' page was created in response to
customer feedback, Molinaro added. ``Everybody said, `I don't want
to wade through the same screens over and over again,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Flanders, co-author of ``Web Pages That Suck,'' a guide
to developing attractive, user-friendly Internet sites, said Web
sites shouldn't pose obstacles to getting information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond four clicks is bad,'' Flanders said. He likened the
experience to shopping. ``When you go to Wal-Mart, you don't find
barbed wire fences'' around the store.
</P>
<P>
   United hopes the easier access will help the Web site account
for more of the airline's total ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Molinaro said, United expects to sell about $200
million worth of tickets through its Internet site. That's twice as
much as last year, and about 2 percent of United's total ticket
sales, Molinaro added. ``Our goal is to get to 10 percent of total
sales over the next five years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many companies are finding more ways to cut costs by
selling their products over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   AMP Inc., a Harrisburg, Pa., company that sells electrical
equipment to the computer, telecommunications and automotive
industries, put its catalog on line in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company said it now spends half as much _ $8
million _ producing traditional paper catalogs, because more
customers are buying AMP's products through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our electronic catalog today is one of the best reaches to our
customers in getting them updated information instantly,'' said
Jerry Kopenhaver, marketing manager of AMP's Web site catalog.
</P>
<P>
   International Data Corp. estimates that the number of Internet
users in the United States will increase from about 30 million in
1997 to nearly 102 million by 2002. And the percentage of users who
buy on line will grow from 36 percent to about 50 percent. In
addition, IDC estimated that total dollars spent on Internet
transactions will grow from $4.3 billion in 1997 to more than $54
billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Despite reports of cost savings from doing business on the Web,
the jury's still out on whether companies are getting good returns
on what they spend to develop their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Business Marketing, a trade magazine in Chicago, estimated that
Web site development costs for small businesses are averaging about
$44,500. Medium and large businesses are paying on average $99,750
and $302,975, respectively, for their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Maddox, editor of trade magazine Interactive Media &AMP;
Marketing, said it's too difficult to figure out whether companies
are getting a good return on their investment because using the Web
as a business tool is such a new concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, nobody really knows what the return is,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most companies aren't making money. Most are barely breaking
even after having a Web site for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-13-98 1620EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
