<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY15-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Danged if technology don't giveth and taketh away 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I recently decided to join hands with those living in the latter
part of the 20th century and get cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   For the past couple of years I've suffered along with rabbit
ears. But I live in an area where broadcast reception isn't that
good. One of the few channels I can get is a public TV station that
seems to have a long-term contract with a gardening expert who
spends most of his air time explaining how to make homemade
mosquito repellent using soap, lemon juice and chewing tobacco. I
don't have a garden and, over time, the gardening expert has become
more annoying than mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
   So, about a week ago, I set off on my great cable adventure.
What happened has very little to do with cable TV or the companies
that provide it. I could have just as easily been trying to contact
an insurance company or any other big business that uses an
automated voice mail system. Instead, what I found reminded me of
the price of technology, the price that doesn't appear on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   On my first attempt to call, I got the company's voice mail
menu. You've run into them several times a week yourself, so I
won't spend much time describing it. You are asked a series of
questions, and you're supposed to respond by pressing one of the
keys on your telephone's touchpad. I follow directions OK, and I
finally reached a question that asked me to enter my home telephone
number. I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not a valid number, please enter it again,'' the
recorded voice told me. I did, figuring that I had misdialed. ``I'm
sorry, that is not a valid number. Please hold for a
representative.''
</P>
<P>
   I held through two country songs and what seemed to be an
orchestral treatment of the Beatles' ``Norwegian Wood.'' Finally,
the music stopped. By now, I was in one of my obsessive moods. I
didn't much care about cable TV, I just wanted to complain to a
human. But, instead of a real live human, I heard a recorded voice
again: ``Please enter your home telephone number.'' Like a fool, I
did. And, like a predictable machine, the recorded voice said:
``That is not a valid number.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, because I am a certified TechnoBuddy, I came up with the
perfect answer for fooling the machine. I hung up, called again,
and _ when asked to enter my home telephone number _ I entered
someone else's number and figured I could explain my subterfuge
when I finally reached a human. Danged if it didn't work. There was
no ``This is not a valid number'' message. Instead, I worked my way
_ happy in the way that only the gainfully dishonest can be _
through the menu, all the way to the questions about whether I
wanted new service, or to change my existing service.
</P>
<P>
   Just about then, the recording asked me, and I swear it is true,
to ``enter your home number.''
</P>
<P>
   I eventually got cable TV service. But the topic of this sermon
is technology, not cable TV. My experience with the voice menu
system reminded me of an old truth: For everything that technology
gives us, it also takes something away.
</P>
<P>
   I say old truth because it stretches back as far into history as
the invention of the written language. Up until that time, it was
common to create long, epic poems that were memorized and told
aloud. But that skill gradually faded away as writing let us record
the information and save our memories. That's just one example. You
can come up with dozens of examples of your own. For instance,
until recorded music was common, families would sit around the
piano and sing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying that writing has eliminated memorizing poems. And
people still sing at home. But both skills have withered because a
new technology forced out an old one. It would be difficult to be
against recorded music or the written language. But it is
important, I think, to understand that it does happen.
</P>
<P>
   We _ as humans and especially as Americans _ spend a lot of time
glorifying technology. And sometimes the glory is well earned. But
we also need to remember the price tag. And, in the case of the
company that uses a high-tech voice messaging menu instead of
humans to deal with customers, the price tag can be really high.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that saved the cable company from losing a
customer was a fellow in overalls who knows a lot about homemade
mosquito repellent.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted appreciates hearing from you but cannot respond to
all e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
