<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE15-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Money tips can make for a better trip 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's say you and your family are heading off on a dream
vacation next week. After years of excuses, you've decided to spend
what a good used Toyota would cost to go to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   You've made flight and hotel reservations and gotten over your
personal reservations about traveling to any spot on the globe
where snails are eaten. But now you need a little last-minute help.
After all, you'll be dealing with languages other than Southern
American and currencies you've never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the World Wide Web can come in handy. You'll find
several sites that can cushion the culture shock of an overseas
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start with the problem of money. Figuring out conversion
rates can help you judge whether you're getting a good deal (stay
away from money-changer booths at airports) and also let you start
adjusting mentally for shopping trips. You'll want to have a firm
idea whether that 487-franc dinner in France is a bargain or
whether you'd be better off buying a loaf of bread and some cheese.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best currency converters on the Web is the Universal
Currency Converter at http://www.xe.net/currency/. Unlike using a
chart you've found in a newspaper or even on the Web, this
converter will do the math for you. Simply enter the amount of
money and the currency on one side of the chart, and select the
currency you'd like it converted to on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Let's use that 487-franc dinner as an example. You'd type in 487
in the left-hand box and select French francs, then select U.S.
dollars in the right-hand box. Press the button called Perform
Currency Conversion and _ in just a second or two _ you'll find the
tab for that meal is $79.89 (based on the currency exchange rate on
the day I tried this site).
</P>
<P>
   The nice thing about this converter is that it is amazingly
complete. Most world currencies are available. And, you can set the
page, if you'd like, to use languages other than English. If you're
really traveling to some exotic locations, you'll be able to use
the full version of this page (with 180 different currencies) at
http://www.xe.net/currency
</P>
<P>
   /full/. But, if the currencies you need are in the main page,
you'll find it is easier to work with since you won't have so many
possible currencies to plow through.
</P>
<P>
   Since the really good sites on the Web can get overcrowded and
slow, let's look at one more currency converter before moving on.
It's called Homer: Currency Conversion and can be found at
http://www.rmg-c.se/rmg
</P>
<P>
   /currency.htm. This site works much like the first one, so you
don't need additional instructions, just some spending money.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's tackle the language problem. If you're lucky, you
won't need to be fluent in the language of the country you plan to
visit. Especially in Europe, the natives are likely to have a
better command of English than you'd expect. But you'll want to
brush up a bit, just to show you're not the typical ugly American
who firmly believes that if you talk loud enough, they'll
understand.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best places on the Web to brush up on languages _
including some you'd expect, such as French, Italian and German,
and some you wouldn't, like Farsi, Finnish and Tagalog _ is at the
excellent Languages for Travellers site at
http://www.travlang.com/languages/. Don't expect to do the few
simple exercises and then be able to get a job as a translator.
But, if you pay attention, you'll be able to order dinner, find a
bathroom and book a hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   If your language needs are more extensive, you'll want to check
out a page full of links to literally hundreds of Web pages
offering everything from instant translations, to dictionaries, to
explanations of the fine points of grammar. It is, logically
enough, called Language and Translation Links and is located at
http://www.geocities.com/Athens/Acropolis/3137/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
