<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CLINTON-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES LIMITING LIABILITY FOR YEAR 2000 COMPUTER 
SOLUTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Addressing the potential computer crisis in 2000
for the first time, President Clinton said on Tuesday that he would
propose legislation to limit the liability of companies that share
data about solutions if the information proves faulty.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the United States would contribute $12 million to a
World Bank program to help developing nations deal with the
potential computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a speech before the National Academy of Sciences,
warned of ``gaping holes'' in efforts by government and private
industry to prepare their computer systems for the end of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the nation's computers into compliance is one of the
greatest technological challenges in history, the president said.
Failure, he added, will result in ``a series of shutdowns,
inaccurate data, faulty calculations'' that could affect government
functions from the payment of Medicare claims to control of the
nation's air traffic system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said there was a ``pressing need for action'' at all
levels of government and in the private sector to deal with the
so-called millennium bug, which prevents computers from recognizing
the beginning of a new century. Most older computers are programmed
with two digits for the year in the date field and will not
automatically recognize ``00'' as 2000. They may think it is 1900,
with potentially catastrophic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The current official estimate of the cost of bringing the
federal government's computers into compliance is $6 billion, but
most experts consider that figure far too low.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems unbelievable, but it's only 535 days from now, at the
stroke of midnight, when we will usher in a new year, a new
century, a new millennium,'' the president said. ``It is fitting,
if more than a little ironic, that this same stroke of midnight
will pose a sharp and signal test of whether we have prepared
ourselves for the challenges of the Information Age.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Good Samaritan'' legislation Clinton said he would submit
to Congress is intended to deal with the fear of many companies
that they will face expensive lawsuits if they provide information
about their computers' year 2000 compliance that proves wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which is still circulating in draft form, would not
relieve companies of liability for failures of hardware or software
intended to address year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   Already there is a burgeoning legal specialty of year 2000
liability litigation that is discouraging companies from freely
sharing data, according to Michael Aisenberg, a Washington lawyer
working with the administration on the proposed legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of litigation is already putting a chill on
technology initiators, who are worried they'll be sued if their
year 2000 disclosures turn out to be wrong or don't work,''
Aisenberg said. He said that granting liability relief for
well-intentioned data sharing has bipartisan support on Capitol
Hill, but could face stiff opposition from the product liability
bar.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the potential legal costs arising from year 2000
problems range as high as $1 trillion, Aisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and other administration officials expressed optimism
that the United States can bring its ``mission critical'' computer
systems into compliance before the ball drops in Times Square next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have made it clear to every member of my Cabinet that the
American people have a right to expect uninterrupted service from
government, and I expect them to deliver,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   But the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, has a markedly more pessimistic view of the federal
government's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   As of last month, only about 40 percent of the 7,336
most-critical government computer systems were prepared for
December 31, 1999, according to the GAO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless progress improves dramatically,'' the agency declared
in a report issued June 10, ``a substantial number of
mission-critical systems will not be year 2000 compliant in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., has studied the problem for the
past several years and gives the federal government a failing grade
for its progress so far.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview that he has been pressing Clinton to
personally address the millennium bug as a means of concentrating
the minds of federal bureaucrats. ``I think this is a major step
here,'' Horn said. ``The denial is over. They hadn't done anything
up to now to share with the American people what this problem is
all about. Now they have to keep at it and not assume the nation
heard it because he gave one speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Some federal agencies are better prepared for next year's turn
of the calendar than others, administration and congressional
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those relatively well along in their efforts are the
Social Security Administration, the Veterans' Administration, the
Environmental Protection Agency, the Federal Emergency Management
Agency and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But other agencies are ``substantially challenged,'' according
to John Koskinen, the administration's year 2000 czar.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are the Departments of Defense, Health and Human
Services, Education, Transportation, Energy, Education and the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen said that the United States is further along than 90
percent of nations and that many countries have failed to take even
preliminary steps toward compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great risks internationally,'' he said. If the
Singapore stock exchange fails to open on Monday, Jan. 3, 2000, for
example, the repercussions will be felt throughout the global
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows,'' Koskinen said, ``what the end of next year
will look like.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 2000EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
