A5782 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-SPAM-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPAM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Net Heavies Tell FTC How To Slam Spam  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A coalition of Internet heavyweights, led by America Online and
AT&AMP;T, has submitted a report to the Federal Trade Commission urging
a major crackdown on unsolicited junk e-mail, or ``spam.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ad-Hoc Working Group on Unsolicited Commercial Email, which
was formed at the request of the FTC a year ago to come up ways to
put a lid on spam, is proposing that federal and state regulators
be given the authority to prosecute spammers who ``forge'' e-mail
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial e-mailers sometimes ``forge'' their return addresses
_ making it look as if the message came from AOL or other popular
online services _ to trick consumers into opening their mail. Many
of these messages promote get-rich-quick schemes, pyramid
operations and sex sites.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that different from old-fashioned junk mail that looks
like it's from the government or might contain a check. But unlike
junk mail sent through the post office, e-mail spammers can send
out millions of pieces at virtually no cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This form of elusive behavior is costing everyone _ the
system, individual consumers _ a great deal of money and frustrates
consumers' ability to limit messages they don't want,'' said
Deirdre Mulligan, staff counsel of the Center for Democracy and
Technology in Washington, D.C., and principal writer of the 32-page
report.
</P>
<P>
   The rampant use of forged addresses and e-mail containing
fraudulent material prompted the FTC to request a report from
industry leaders last summer. The ad hoc group of 40 companies and
organizations also includes IBM, Microsoft, MCI, the American Civil
Liberties Union and the Direct Marketing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our core concern is with e-mail that has deceptive content,''
FTC attorney John Rothchild said. ``Anything that allows companies
to steal money from unsuspecting consumers through scams _ whether
by direct mail or e-mail _ is a major concern to us. There are a
large number of old-fashioned pyramid schemes online that are
camouflaged as business opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothchild said the five-person FTC is studying the report and
will comment soon.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to giving states the ability to prosecute spammers,
the report recommends that Internet service providers make
widespread use of filtering software to weed out junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``These measures could significantly reduce the volume of spam
on the Internet,'' said Richard Buchband, general counsel of Juno
Online Services LP, a provider of free e-mail. ``Until now, the
most effective way to stop spammers was by suing them.''
</P>
<P>
   New York-based Juno, which boasts 5.4 million users, has sued
eight junk mailers since 1997 to bar them from hawking
get-rich-quick schemes on its e-mail service or from forging Juno
e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   Although Juno, AOL and others have successfully sued spammers
off their sites, the strategy is costly and doesn't shield
consumers from the scores of online mass marketers who aren't taken
to court, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 10 billion pieces of junk e-mail a year are
clogging up Internet pathways and individuals' e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting outcry among consumers has prompted several pieces
of anti-spamming legislation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Netizens Protection Act, sponsored by Representative
Christopher Smith, R-N.J., would amend the Telephone Consumer
Protection Act of 1991, which bans unsolicited junk faxes, to also
regulate junk e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Senate unanimously passed a provision of the
Consumer Antislamming Act, co-authored by Senator Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., that would fine junk e-mailers up to $15,000 if
they mask their identities with forged addresses. The bill
prohibits the unauthorized switching of telephone service providers
for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The ad hoc group's report encourages Internet service providers
and Net surfers to employ a combination of litigation and software
filters for ``temporary relief from (junk) e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But it admits that isn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite some service providers' best efforts to litigate
(spam) off the Internet, some senders are quick to target other
service providers when faced with a judgment forbidding them from
targeting a specific provider,'' the report stated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 2151EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
