<SLUG> BC-CPT-SPAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC URGES CONSUMERS TO WATCH OUT FOR `DIRTY DOZEN' E-MAIL SCHEMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By NICOLE TSONG   
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After examining over 250,000 e-mails from around
the nation, the Federal Trade Commission on Tuesday warned e-mail
users about the 12 most common fraudulent get-rich schemes being
touted by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the ``dirty dozen'' e-mails bear a close resemblance
to unsolicited offers already conveyed by telephone and regular
Postal Service mail.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 e-mail examples were collected at an FTC e-mail address
created to study and help prevent e-mail fraud. The address,
uceftc.gov, receives 1,000 to 1,500 e-mails daily.
</P>
<P>
   Jodie Bernstein, director of the FTC's Bureau of Consumer
Protection, said fraudulent e-mail is easy and inexpensive to send
_ and e-mail addresses are accessible for anyone who has access to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   David Medine, associate FTC director, said it's easy for senders
of unsolicited e-mail to harvest e-mail addresses because ``anytime
you put your address out there on the Internet, there are automated
programs capturing those e-mail addresses and adding them to a
list.''
</P>
<P>
   The jargon of cyberspace identifies unsolicited e-mail as
``spam.'' Its senders are ``spammers.'' Using the address lists,
spammers solicit by sending spam.
</P>
<P>
   The schemes are not new, Bernstein added, and many of them are
simply modified for the new medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many spammers who make deceptive claims in their e-mail simply
imitate what they see others doing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the FTC's ``dirty dozen,'' listed in order of
frequency.
</P>
<P>
   _ Business opportunities: They offer a lot of money for a small
amount of time and money that are usually too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   _ Making money by sending bulk e-mail: They offer money for
simply e-mailing a lot of people, but bulk e-mail violates e-mail
service rules for most Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chain letters: Chain letters generally claim to make money
simply by sending the letter to a certain number of people.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work-at-home: Two popular versions for making money from the
comfort of home include envelope stuffing and craft assembly, but
``nobody will really pay you for stuffing envelopes, and craft
assembly promoters usually refuse to buy the crafts, claiming the
work does not meet their `quality standards,''' Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Health and diet: Bogus cures offered via e-mail, guaranteed to
cure all ills.
</P>
<P>
   _ Currency trading: These deals offer the chance to ``make
unlimited profits exchanging money on world currency markets,''
Bernstein warned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get something free: Computer or phone card offers are common
in this scam. The consumer is urged to sign up for membership fees
but then receives nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investment opportunities: The senders suggest they have inside
financial information or they promote high rates of return with no
risk.
</P>
<P>
   _ Descrambler kits to allow you to receive cable TV signals
without paying subscription fees. The kits generally do not work,
and stealing cable signals is against the law, Bernstein said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guaranteed loans or credit: Promoters may offer credit cards,
regardless of credit history for a fee, or offer home-equity loans
that turn out to be lists of lending institutions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Credit repair: For a fee, the sender offers to clear up a bad
credit record.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vacation prize promotions: Deluxe vacations for a cheap price
which never turn out to be the luxury vacation touted by the
advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 1755EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
