<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MILLENNIUM-BUG14-     07-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MILLENNIUM-BUG14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES BUSINESSES TO DEAL WITH YEAR 2000 BUG
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By ANDREW J. GLASS  
c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning that the millennium bug ``is not one of the
summer movies, where you can close your eyes during the scary
parts,'' President Clinton on Tuesday urged the business community
to fix their computers before they disrupt the nation's economic
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any business that approaches the new year armed only with a
bottle of champagne and a noisemaker is likely to have a very big
hangover on New Year's morning,'' Clinton said in a long-awaited
speech on the Year 2000 computer problem at the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The president also promised to send Congress legislation that
would protect firms sharing advice on upgrading computers from
lawsuits stemming from use of the material.
</P>
<P>
   When midnight strikes on Jan. 1, 2000, programs that identify
dates by only their last two digits may recognize the ``00'' as the
year 1900. The bug threatens to cripple government agencies,
industrial firms, banks, hospitals and financial exchanges around
the world that use computer calendars to monitor their operations.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, key Republicans on Capitol Hill have been
urging Clinton to put the full weight of his office behind a
high-profile campaign to alert Americans to the threat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded Tuesday by praising the Republicans for their
efforts as they sat in the first row of the auditorium. ``This can
be a model of partnership,'' the president asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the thousands of retired computer authorities whose help
could prove vital, Clinton announced that the Labor Department had
established a Year 2000 talent bank to hook up experts on the
computer glitch with people who need their aid. And Clinton also
noted that the Justice Department ruled earlier this month that
``competitors who merely share information on how to solve this
problem are not in violation of the nation's antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get that message out there loud and clear: no one
should be afraid to help another company to deal with this
challenge,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Another key goal of Clinton's speech was to remove the Year 2000
problem from the political agenda. Any massive disruption in
commerce could potentially harm the chances of Vice President Al
Gore, the administration's lead player on technology issues, in his
forthcoming bid to succeed Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In introducing Clinton, Gore said: ``The year 2000 problem is a
management challenge and a programming challenge. It must not be a
political football. We need bipartisan cooperation to solve the
year 2000 problem, not political rhetoric. More than anything else,
the year 2000 problem has revealed how interconnected and
interdependent we have become.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the president sought to temper a sense of urgency
with a dose of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we act and not be in denial,'' he said.
``It is also very important that we avoid overreaction from people
who hear, 'Oh, my goodness, this problem is out there.' And so we
have to do both things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Steven Horn, R-Calif., who chairs a House subcommittee that
has been probing the federal response to the Year 2000 problem,
said he told Clinton after the speech that ``Franklin D. Roosevelt
would have been proud of you, because what the nation needed to
hear at this time was a ``fireside address' on this critical
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a true emergency,'' agreed Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah,
who chairs a special Senate panel on the Year 2000 computer
problem. ``I won't nit-pick on whether he should have spoken out
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said ``a private foundation will soon announce a major
effort to coordinate a nationwide response at all levels of
society.'' He said the group was seeking to recruit ``a major
industrial figure'' to lead a broadly based campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some time ago, Bennett had scheduled his own speech on the
problem, to be delivered on Wednesday to the National Press Club
under the working title of ``Paul Revere and Not Chicken Little:
Who's Sounding the Call for the Year 2000 and Who's Not.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'll have to revise that speech,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
