<SLUG> BC-CPT-CHIP-MACHINES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER-CHIP MACHINE SUPPLIERS STUCK IN DOLDRUMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By WENDY TANAKA   
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The companies that make the machines that make
computer chips are weathering the worst industry slump in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current environment is one of the toughest, most
unforgiving that I have ever seen,'' said James Morgan, chairman
and chief executive of Applied Materials Inc. of Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose-based Dataquest Inc. estimated that
semiconductor-equipment sales would decline 17.3 percent this year.
The industry's revenues fell 7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, things were flying pretty high,'' said John Field,
vice president of marketing and OEM sales at Asyst Technologies
Inc. in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our industry has taken a pretty steep southward direction,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   An industry in despair is the theme at the Semicon West show,
the largest annual gathering of semiconductor-equipment makers,
which continues through Wednesday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blame a host of factors for the slump, including an
over-supply of chips and the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most equipment makers have predicted
lower-than-expected earnings, which have led them to cut costs
dramatically by slashing employees and reducing expenses for
business travel, industry conventions and other items.
</P>
<P>
   This is going to be ``a pretty bleak year,'' said Gene Norrett,
a Dataquest analyst who follows the semiconductor industry. ``We
don't see much improvement of the financials till mid- to late next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Applied Materials, the world's largest semiconductor equipment
maker, said Friday its third-quarter earnings would fall about 5
cents a share because of reduced orders.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Applied Materials announced plans to eliminate 1,000 of
its 15,000 workers through attrition and a voluntary severance
program. Last month, Novellus Systems Inc. of San Jose said it
would cut about 180 employees, or 10 percent of its work force. Two
weeks ago, Asyst let go 10 percent, or about 60, of its workers due
to sluggish orders for its equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Norrett noted that businesses readying their computer systems
for the so-called millennium bug and countries converting to the
new European currency would also hurt sales of semiconductor
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Norrett explained that after businesses bought the software to
accommodate these changes, there wouldn't be much capital left over
to buy new computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole food chain is affected,'' Norrett said.
</P>
<P>
   One area in which equipment makers aren't making cutbacks is
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Field of Asyst said an industry retreat was the perfect time to
test new technologies that a company could launch when the market
strengthens.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not coming up with new products, you're dead in
technology,'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 1332EDT &QL;
</P>
