<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITING LOW CHIP PRICES, INTEL EARNS LESS THAN FORECAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. reported a 29 percent drop in
second-quarter earnings Tuesday, a greater-than-expected decline
that the leading maker of computer chips attributed to weakened
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is regarded as a bellwether of the computer
industry, also said that it did not expect to see a significant
improvement in its third-quarter financial results.
</P>
<P>
   Intel reported its earnings after the stock market closed, and
its shares fell slightly in after-hours dealing. Investors had
recently pushed Intel and other technology stocks higher on
optimism that the company's results would portend a rebound in
growth.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ending on June 27, Intel earned $1.17 billion,
or 66 cents a fully diluted share, compared with $1.645 billion, or
92 cents a share, in the comparable period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue totaled $5.93 billion, compared with $5.96 billion in
the first quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp., which tracks earnings
estimates, had expected Intel to earn 68 cents a share. The
so-called whisper number, offered by analysts to clients orally,
was 70 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel's earnings fell two cents short of the consensus,
analysts said there were no major surprises.
</P>
<P>
   But in a reflection of the anxiety surrounding Intel's
prospects, its shares declined $1.6875 Tuesday in regular Nasdaq
trading, to $80.6875. In after-hours dealings, once the earnings
figures had been released, the shares eased further to $80.125.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's earnings have suffered in recent quarters from cuts in
the prices of chips to meet new competition and a supply glut of
personal computers in the hands of distributors and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said gross profit margins were reduced because of
write-downs of inventory, reflecting weaker selling prices at the
end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley, said that
without these write-downs, Intel would have earned 71 cents a
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more important,'' he said, ``is that the outlook going
forward continues to be in line with our expectation that the PC
inventory correction is in the process of ending, and Intel will be
one of the big beneficiaries.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said that the inventory write-downs reflected some
weakness that should have been anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a sigh of relief that things are not falling off
a cliff in the second half,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with S.G.
Cowen Securities Corp. ``But people should remember this company is
a far way from the halcyon days of the early '90s.'' Peck said
Intel is ``not going to show earnings growth in 1998, and '99 may
be tough as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The company reported that shipments of microprocessors were down
slightly in the second quarter from the first quarter of 1998, but
that sales of products based on its newer P6 design continued to
grow while Pentium processor-based products declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite a difficult environment for the computing industry,
Intel has made significant strides toward increased productivity,
just as we have worked to renew growth,'' Craig R. Barrett, Intel's
president and chief executive, said in a statement. ``We have cut
costs, extended our product line, and are ahead of schedule in
using new manufacturing processes. As a result, we have increased
Intel's competitiveness substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Intel has seldom had to lower prices because
consumers were willing to pay more for its newest,
highest-performance chips. But while a portion of the market will
still pay high prices for the fastest microprocessors, the personal
computer industry's fastest-growing segment has been sub-$1,000
machines.
</P>
<P>
   After letting Advanced Micro Devices Inc. and National
Semiconductor Corp. get an early lead in that market, Intel
responded with the low-cost Celeron chip, but that chip had a slow
start.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-07-14-98 2104EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
