<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ADVICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK OFFERS ADVICE FOR FOREIGN BUSINESS EXECUTIVES IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When New Yorker Larry Wang stepped off the plane in Taipei,
Taiwan, back in 1990, he had only the vaguest notion of how to fit
into Taiwanese business and society.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no role model I could take a lead from,'' he
recalls. ``That first year, I kept my head down, working on my
language skills. Every day, I was in over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Wang, a grandchild of Chinese immigrants, is fluent in
Mandarin as well as English. Holding an MBA from UCLA's Anderson
School, he is also now head of an international headhunting firm
based in Oakland and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in Taipei and the past 3-and-1/2 years in Hong
Kong, Wang has international experience to burn _ and share. He
shares it as the author of a new book, ``The New Gold Mountain,'' a
how-to aimed chiefly at Chinese Americans interested in pursuing
careers in mainland China, Taiwan and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we had a lot of value-added information,'' says Wang,
founder and principal in Wang &AMP; Li Asia Resources, during a visit
to San Francisco. ``And I wanted to tell this story, which I
thought was untold.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 37, structured ``The New Gold Mountain'' around interviews
with executives at multinational corporations who have relocated to
greater China. Before East Asia's economies were disrupted by the
current fiscal crisis, the region led the planet in growth for a
decade as the world economy became more globalized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gold Mountain'' is a traditional Chinese name for prosperous
North America. The ``New Gold Mountain'' is Wang's hopeful
characterization of business opportunities in greater China. Such
opportunities, he maintains, are especially good for bicultural,
bilingual people of Chinese descent and other Asia-philes who speak
at least one Asian language.
</P>
<P>
   Despite high levels of education among Chinese Americans, they
still face a glass ceiling in U.S. business, Wang says. ``That's
not a criticism of the United States, that's just the way it is,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Gold Mountain,'' stuffed with anecdotes and data,
includes chapters such as ``The Outlook for Key Industries,'' ``The
Ten Most Often Asked Questions'' and ``The Financial Payoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang accentuates the positive in the book as evidenced by its
upbeat subtitle: ``The Success of Chinese Americans in Greater
China.'' Even so, he allows that the expatriate life in Asia is not
for everyone, writing hard-headed chapters such as ``Do You Belong
in Greater China?'' and ``The Realities to Face (Or Why Some Don't
Make It).''
</P>
<P>
   Difficulties notwithstanding, people who make successful lives
abroad, Wang says, ``are open-minded and like to live day to day.''
More often than not, he adds, they are also ``young and mobile, and
willing to go in-country.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Tsai, a senior executive in Wang &AMP; Li's Oakland office _
and a veteran of a six-year stint in wide-open Taiwan _ says: ``You
can be in your late 20s and 30s, and be hands-on (in Asia). You can
make decisions on projects that in the U.S. would go to a manager
in his mid-40s. There's not this bottleneck at upper senior
management.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Gold Mountain'' includes detailed comparisons of the
four major cities of greater China: Beijing, Shanghai, Taipei and
Hong Kong. Appendixes compare Asian supermarket prices of Western
products like M&AMP;Ms and Vidal Sassoon shampoo, list salary ranges,
give essential tax information and sketch cultural characteristics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're expecting a bustling place with the night life of
Hong Kong, Beijing will disappoint you,'' Wang writes. ``It's much
more residential. Although the night scene is growing, it's much
more limited and not as centrally located as in Hong Kong and
Shanghai.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang concedes that the year-old East Asian fiscal crisis has
roiled the region but says that mainland China and Taiwan have
suffered less than most. For companies wanting to do business in
that part of the world, he says, a long-term commitment is
essential for when the rebound comes.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, whose own commitment to Asia is long-term, returns to the
United States ``four or five times a year,'' he says, adding that
``with the Internet, travel, voice mail and video conferencing,
Asia's not as far away as it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he muses, he'll probably have an epiphany and move
back to the States. ``But for me, it hasn't happened yet,'' he
says. ``I wonder about the transition back. Am I going to get
bored? There's so much energy and juice in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   (Information on ``The New Gold Mountain'' is available by
telephone at 510-893-8700 and on the Internet at www.wang-li.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
