<SLUG> BC-SF-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOMING SAN FRANCISCO ECONOMY CREATES 100,000 JOBS IN ONE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco's robust economy created more than
100,000 jobs in the area between March 1997 and March 1998,
according to a survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly report, issued by the Bay Area Council, said this
was the third consecutive 12-month period that the nine-county
region produced at least 100,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bay Area economy continues to drive California's economic
growth and to lead the way for the nation,'' said Sunne Wright
McPeak, president of the council, a San Francisco-based nonprofit
public policy organization made up of corporate chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, the region's employers are continuing to hire new
workers as they continue to pursue market opportunities,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the council's report, business services _ which
includes photocopying stores, computer programming companies and
advertising firms, among others _ led the job growth, accounting
for slightly more than half of the 100,000 new jobs. Other sectors
of the economy that showed strong job growth were durable goods
manufacturing, insurance, real estate, wholesale trade and
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the general good news, Bay Area exports, which rely
heavily on a struggling Asia, continued to falter, with the March
1997 to March 1998 period showing no increase over the $47 billion
figure for the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The semiconductor equipment industry, which has many companies
headquartered in Silicon Valley, has been hit hardest by the
downturn in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The report also addressed the issue of the Bay Area's housing
crunch and how the dearth of affordable homes may hurt the region.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Fassinger, co-author of the council's survey, said if more
new homes aren't built closer to work places soon, some Bay Area
residents may choose to move away.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short-term, the Asian economy is creating bumps,''
Fassinger said. ``But in the long-term, our competitiveness inside
the United States will depend on the housing market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1238EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
