<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-BIBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPOCRISY IS A SIN _ AND THAT'S THE GOSPEL TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLYDE WADSWORTH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Spurred by the religious right, Republicans in
Congress are waging a Bible-thumping crusade this summer against
lesbian and gay Americans.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leaders have branded gay people as sinners. They have
stalled the ambassadorial nomination of gay philanthropist James
Hormel and promised to kill a presidential executive order that
bars discrimination in federal workplaces against gays and
lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the Bible defines this practice as a sin,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott explained in a recent column sent to
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Mississippi Republican, speaking on a conservative
television talk show a few weeks ago, described homosexuality as an
addiction that can be treated like alcoholism or kleptomania.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, quoted
Bible verses that he said showed homosexuality is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible is very clear on this. In fact, I can give you a
reference if you like _ one of many _ but it is very clear on this.
Now, both myself and Sen. Lott believe very strongly in the Bible.
... I abide by the instructions that are given to me in the
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited what he said were several references to homosexuality
in the New Testament books of Romans, Timothy and First
Corinthians.
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear the echo of Southern conservatives who
earlier this century described interracial marriage as a sin and
racial segregation as part of ``God's plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey, of course, made a name for himself years ago by referring
to Barney Frank, a gay Democratic congressman from Massachusetts,
as ``Barney Fag.'' He quickly apologized and, incredibly, explained
the epithet as a slip of the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just pretend for a Christian second that legislators Lott
and Armey actually believed in the Constitution's separation of
church and state. Let's pretend that Senator Lott, for example, had
a rational, secular basis for refusing to allow the full Senate to
vote on Hormel's nomination as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just imagine that in their personal lives, citizens Lott
and Armey practiced what they preached _ that they conformed their
every back slap and thank-you-ma'am to the literal word of the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no more bacon, rare steak or cheeseburgers for
Dick Armey, the Texan. The dietary laws of the Old Testament forbid
them.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no more polyester blends for Trent Lott. The Book
of Leviticus, not to mention good taste, prohibits the wearing of
mixed fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   The New Testament also poses a number of thorny problems for
Lott and Armey. Gentlemen, say goodbye to your rising salaries and
pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Accumulating wealth is, according to scripture, out.
</P>
<P>
   Passing judgment on others is also discouraged. And when you
feel that urge to discriminate against your gay neighbors or
nominees, don't forget the Golden Rule.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there's that pesky New Testament command
against hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the most difficult command of all for Lott and
Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Political lackeys of the religious right have a penchant for
quoting biblical verses that support their mid-20th century, middle
class (dare I say) lifestyle, and ignoring passages that condemn
the sins of greed and self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   But there is hope for political hypocrites such as Lott and
Armey. Hypocrisy, like opportunism and demagoguery, is a disease of
the body politic. It is treatable. We must work with these
Republican leaders to control their problem. They will thank us
someday.
</P>
<P>
   (Examiner contributor Clyde J. Wadsworth is a San Francisco
attorney and volunteer counsel for the Lambda Legal Defense and
Education Fund, a civil rights organization.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
