<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANOE-ADVENTURE-2ND &LR;  &UR;      07-15 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANOE-ADVENTURE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 LAKE UMBAGOG, N.H.: ... my boat.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I like to tell people that's when we met.''
</P>
<P>
   A tree swallow skims past the nose of the canoe, picking off
mouthfuls of insects, its wingtips feathering the surface of the
lake. Above the tree line a great blue heron slowly flaps its broad
wings. A blackbird bobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here three years ago, it was the fall and the eaglets
were old enough to catch their own food,'' Desmarais says. ``One of
the adults caught a fish and flew to the nest to eat it. The
eaglets _ they were as big as the parent _ started squawking and
squawking for the fish. Finally the adult swooped down and gave it
to them.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses. ``I have never seen that kind of behavior before and
never since. Nature is meant to be harsh, and the eaglets are meant
to fend for themselves. I learned something about being a father
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Photography wasn't something Art's father taught him, but
construction was. Roland Desmarais, a field engineer, steered Art
toward the pit by telling him it represented a solid, stable
living.
</P>
<P>
   Art entered the army after high school and was carting bricks by
age 20. When he became a foreman at 27, his father came down to the
work site and taught him how to measure the slope of pipe as it is
being laid, an exacting process known as ``shooting elevations.''
</P>
<P>
   Art is not sure that construction is what he wants to teach
Alex. But he wants to share the experience of searching a distant
shore for a particular scene or image.
</P>
<P>
   As the canoe proceeds, Art and his son begin playing a familiar
game: Be the first to spot wildlife. Normally as sharp-eyed as his
father, Alex is sluggish today, and Art gently chides him as he
points out loon after loon.
</P>
<P>
   Art tells Alex to look for animal parts _ moose ears, loon
beaks, deer eyes _ and not the whole animal. Alex spots an osprey's
nest through the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al, you think we see much, think about how much we miss,'' Art
says. ``There is an entire universe of things happening here that
we have no idea about, right behind the line of trees.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex squints toward the horizon. He focuses on a dark stain in
the distance, stark against the gray sky, and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the eagle's nest, Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The return of bald eagles to Lake Umbagog is part of a larger
story of the near-extinction and repopulation of the bald eagle in
the lower 48 states.
</P>
<P>
   The national bird has been under attack for most of the
country's history. Throughout the 1800s, land cleared for
agriculture destroyed the eagles' natural habitat, and farmers shot
them, mistakenly thinking they posed a threat to livestock.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, only &UR;  &LR; 417 eagles lived in the continental United
States; today, there are more than 4,500. Most wildlife biologists
credit the comeback to the 1972 banning of DDT, a pesticide that
caused eagles to lay thin-shelled eggs that broke before hatching.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to coax bald eagles back to New Hampshire have had
limited success compared to neighboring Maine, whose craggy coasts
and system of lakes are home to 150 to 200 nesting pairs.
</P>
<P>
   The open water, abundant fish, and isolation of Lake Umbagog
provides an ideal setting for eagles, who mate for life, to raise
their young.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late '70s, the Audubon Society, armed with a network
of volunteers like Art, has monitored the lake in search of nesting
eagles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, two birds began collecting branches at the forking head
of an ancient pine tree just yards from the Maine border _ the same
tree that a thinning population of eagles had abandoned 40 years
before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art saw a newspaper article about the return of the eagles to
Lake Umbagog and bought a canoe to search for them. He has filled
shoeboxes with images of eagles, yet returns to the lake an average
of 15 weekends a year.
</P>
<P>
   He knows what shot he is still searching for: ``He's just coming
up out of the water, a fish in his talons,'' Art says, his eyes
blazing &UR; . &LR;  ``He's looking right down the lens, right at me _ he's
flying right at me.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot has not come _ yet. But the image of it floating around
the next bend warms him through winter mornings so cold that water
splashed into the canoe freezes before hitting the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The canoe approaches the nesting area spotted by Alex. The
wildlife has disappeared and the air is still; this is eagle
territory. Art, his eyes focused on a black mass near the nest,
aims his camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Check your shutter speed, Al, that's what you want to check,''
he whispers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the lens the mass takes shape. The eagle is preening
itself, its head hidden under its wing _ a dark silhouette
contoured by ruffling feathers.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle raises its head.
</P>
<P>
   Art steadies the camera against his nose. His son mirrors his
father's movements. Art fingers the shutter release, the autofocus
lens clicking with tiny corrections.
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, he and his son put their cameras down without
taking a picture.
</P>
<P>
   Art looks at Alex.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sometimes miss a lot when you look through the camera,''
he explains, eyes still on the eagle. ``You forget to enjoy what
you're seeing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
