<HEADER>
A5962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-ART-B     07-15 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOWERS EMBRACE GURU'S MESSAGE OF LOVE AND COMPASSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (k and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHLAND, Mass. _ They came from near and far to hug their
``mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people, including devotees from New Hampshire and
Rhode Island and even California, packed the steamy gymnasium at
the David Mindness Middle School here to wait hours for a hug from
the holy woman from India many affectionately refer to as their
spiritual mother.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no ordinary embrace. Mata Amritanandamayi, a guru
whose name translates to ``mother of immortal bliss'' envelopes
followers in a warm hug meant to provide divine healing and
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The line to receive a blessing from the ``hugging guru'' more
commonly known as Amma snaked down one side of the sweltering
basketball court July 9. One-by-one, they fell into her arms. She
gently massaged their backs and spoke soothing words into the ear.
Some walked away laughing; others crying.
</P>
<P>
   It went on like this for hours, well past midnight, inside the
cavernous gym adorned with multi-colored Indian textiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had her arms wrapped around me and she was laughing and so
happy and it felt like I was taking in love,'' said Mariana Luz,
after Amma hugged her and her two children, Keisha, 9, and Tobi, 7.
Luz, who lives in Amherst, had heard about Amma from her
chiropractor.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of about 50 people from the Amherst area who rode a
bus for two hours to see Amma. ``I didn't know what it was like,
but I figured I'd give it a try,'' Luz said. ``There's a real
positive energy in the room. It's really wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   In India, where she grew up in a destitute family, Amma, 44, is
considered a ``living saint,'' for both her spiritual talents and
her work for the poor. She has helped establish orphanages, schools
and hospitals. In this country she has started soup kitchens in
several cities.
</P>
<P>
   In Ashland, like everywhere else Amma goes, volunteers did a
brisk sale of Amma videotapes, compact disks, tapes, and posters
along with jewelry and other handicrafts. The proceeds are used to
fund Amma's charitable projects.
</P>
<P>
   From a very young age, Amma says she has been moved by the
experiences of the suffering and the poor. Her followers say Amma's
power and appeal stem from a sense that she radiates unconditional
love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love is the foundation of the world,'' Amma is fond of
repeating. ``Where there is love, there is peace. Where there is
selfishness, there is misery and suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Amma first came to the United States 11 years ago. Ever since,
her annual nationwide tours have drawn huge crowds. She even
attracts a steady number of groupies who follow her from
city &UR;  &LR; to &UR;  &LR; city. During some appearances, Amma, who is said to need
only two hours of sleep a night, has hugged several thousand
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel like I'm a big baby and she's my mommy,''
Louie Mezei of Upton said, describing what it's like to get a hug
from Amma.
</P>
<P>
   Amma appeals to people like Mezei, a psychotherapist who has
been at several of the guru's appearances, who say her spirituality
goes beyond dogma or any one set of beliefs. Mezei, who is Jewish,
does attend Shabbat services, but also practices Buddhist
meditation and takes instruction from a Zen teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Although born a Hindu, Amma believes all religions are equally
worthy. ``There is no harm in having many religions and faiths,''
Amma tells those who come to her teachings. ``But it is harmful to
think they are different, and that one faith is higher and another
lower. See the unity in them and the great ideals which they
teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Viveka Villarin flew from San Diego to Boston and then rented a
car to come see Amma Thursday night and also to take part in a
retreat with the guru this weekend. After being blessed by Amma,
Villarin, an actress and dancer, said she was filled with an
overwhelming feeling of ``bliss, joy and love. Wouldn't you want to
get some more that too?''
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, Camille Numrick, who drove from
Providence to Ashland for a hug from Amma, has gone all across the
country to see the guru. ``As they say in India I wanted to be in
the presence of a master,'' said Numrick, who is career services
director at Community College of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a living example of what she talks about _ compassion,
love and self-realization,'' said Numrick, who has even spent a
month in India living in Amma's ashram. ``And she's always telling
us we can have that and with faith and trust many of us realize we
can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; _Dissidents in the Greek Orthodox Church claimed victory last week
at a national church convention when they won passage of a
resolution asking the Greek archbishop to reinstate four priests
fired last year from Hellenic College and Holy Cross School of
Theology.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, passed at the clergy-laity conference in
Orlando, Fla., seeks the appointment of an independent task force
to review the controversial firings at the Brookline school.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A spokesman for Archbishop Spyridon, who had the four men
fired last July, told reporters in Orlando that Spyridon, the
leader of the nation's 2 million Greek Orthodox, had no plans to
return the priests to the school.
</P>
<P>
   But church officials told conference attendees that they will
heed the concerns of dissidents, some of whom accuse Spyridon of
not respecting the grievances of lay church members.
</P>
<P>
   _After making controversial comments regarding divine punishment
on central Florida, religious broadcaster Pat Robertson is donating
money and supplies to fire victims in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Operation Blessing International, Robertson's
humanitarian aid organization, delivered $25,000 and 40,000 pounds
of food to an Orlando, Fla., charitable group. Robertson, through a
spokesman, denied that the assistances had anything to do with his
earlier comments about Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   During last month's annual Gay Days celebration in Orlanda,
rainbow-colored flags flew from utility poles in the city's
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would warn Orlando that you're right in the way of some
serious hurricanes, and I don't think I'd be waving those flags in
God's face if I were you,'' Robertson reportedly said June 8 on his
television program on the Christian Broadcasting Network.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson later said his comments were taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
