<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOMETHING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARY' IS LOWBROW, GROSS _ BUT HILARIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY 
Directed by: Bobby and Peter Farrelly 
Screenplay by: Peter and Bobby Farrelly, Ed Decter, John J.
Strauss 
Starring: Cameron Diaz, Matt Dillon, Ben Stiller, Lee Evans, Chris
Elliott, Lin Shaye, Brett Favre, Jeffrey Tambor 
Running time: 119 minutes 
Rated: R (strong comic sexual content and language) 
Three Stars 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad taste kings Bobby and Peter Farrelly sink to new heights of
vulgar fun in ``There's Something About Mary.'' You name the
offense, especially along political gender lines, and this new film
commits it. But while it's dumb and even dumber than a lot of
gross-out comedies, it'll have the last laugh on all of them. It's
hard to describe just what's so funny that it comes sneaking in
under your radar to make you laugh as often as ``There's Something
About Mary'' does. It's not as funny as its trailer makes it look,
but it won't leave you wondering where its brainless yuks are.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, there's nothing amusing about the ability of Cameron
Diaz's pretty Mary to attract fixated stalkers. But then writing
isn't the strength of this film. The devising of riotous sight gags
is. Matt Dillon's mustache and toothily insincere grin alone will
make you guffaw. As a lowlife private eye sent to Miami to find the
girl of Ben Stiller's dreams, Dillon's gumshoe double-crosses
Stiller by falling for Mary and making a play for her while keeping
Stiller away.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller is no slouch at physical comedy, either, from the moment
he kicks the film off in an '80s prologue. Looking like Austin
Powers in braces and a simian posture, Stiller's lovesick nerd
blows his big chance to take Diaz's school beauty to the prom when
he does himself a mischief by a too-careless zipping of his zipper.
The subsequent combination of humiliation and yearning is all he
needs to keep the flame alive for years. When a colleague
encounters Diaz at a convention, and tells Stiller where she may be
found, that's all he needs. From there, he works his way through
mishaps from arrest to dog bites, with time out for a masturbation
sight gag unrivaled by even the most enthusiastically scatological
comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon should do more comedies. His bottom-feeding gumshoe is
the most entertainingly outrageous thing in the film, even though
it runs on too long and mires him in repetiton. Stiller is glum
fun, even when he's lumbered with sentimentality, as he slouches
toward happiness with occasional timeouts to hide in the bushes.
Diaz soldiers gamely through her assignment, sunnily and chirpily
remaining oblivious to her role as a magnet for nutcakes. The film
throws to the winds any remote chance to remain on the right side
of political correctness by unleashing its mayhem on an obviously
stuffed dog, too. You won't be proud of yourself for laughing at
the staunchly lowbrow ``There's Something About Mary,'' but laugh
you will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
