<HEADER>
A5975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFLECTIVE-TECH-BOS &LR;      07-15 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFLECTIVE-TECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM LOOKS TO MELD FASHION, FUNCTION INTO PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ To display his company's product at its best,
Adam Rizika first turns off the showroom lights.
</P>
<P>
   Then he takes out a flashlight and begins spotlighting, one by
one, windbreakers, T-shirts, motorcycle jackets, backpacks, shoes,
shorts, armbands, even life preservers.
</P>
<P>
   All bear well-known brands _ Banana Republic, Nike, Adidas, L.L.
Bean, Eddie Bauer, and others. And each, as the light catches it,
flares into brightness, brought to radiance by a powdery, high-tech
material called Illuminite.
</P>
<P>
   This reflective fabric treatment is manufactured by Reflective
Technologies Inc., a company that Rizika, 36, launched in 1993 with
his brother, a cousin, and a friend who he met at the Sloan School
of Management at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Now housed in back-street industrial space, Reflective
Technologies boasts global ambitions, seeing worldwide markets for
a product that promises clothing manufacturers the opportunity to
sell safety along with good looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact you combine function with fashion adds genuine
value,'' says Matthew Austin, Reflective Technologies's director of
global marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Finer than beach sand, the core ingredient of Illuminite is made
in the company's factory here from glass and aluminum. It then is
shipped to textile finishing companies where the tiny, shiny
particles, each about the thickness of a fine human hair, are mixed
with dyes and a patented clear glue and printed onto fabrics in a
multitude of patterns and colors.
</P>
<P>
   The final result is clothing which, worn at night, stands out
when illuminated by car or truck headlights. To launch the product,
Reflective Technologies has focused on apparel for runners and
bicyclists who, especially in cities, train mostly at dawn or after
dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The winter cyclist is always concerned about safety,'' said
Elena Alfaro, clothing manager at Wheel Works, a cycling specialty
shop where Illuminite-treated jackets made by Bellwether Inc. of
San Francisco have been a slow but steady seller.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminite reflective fabric's market debut in 1995 was met with
favorable reviews from cycling and running magazines, and won
acclaim in Popular Science magazine as one of its ``top 100 new
products'' for 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And, after production start-up kinks were resolved, sales showed
early promise, rising from $700,000 in 1996 to about $3 million
last year, according to Rizika.
</P>
<P>
   But revenues this year, projected at about $4.5 million, may be
falling a bit behind expectations, as shoppers blink at the high
price of Illuminite-treated products.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Illuminite treatment is expensive, pushing
the cost of lightweight fabric from an average of $2.50 a yard to
between $11 and $14 a yard.
</P>
<P>
   Translated to the sales rack, that adds between $15 and $30 to
the price of a nylon windbreaker which, without treatment, would
probably sell for about $40, clothing manufacturers say.
</P>
<P>
   This high cost blocks all hopes of ever getting Illuminite into
mass-market stores such as Sears, Macy's, or T.J. Maxx. At the same
time, some apparel specialists say, Reflective Technologies's focus
so far on the amateur athletic market may be blocking Illuminite
from building a fashion reputation.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for companies that specialize in cycling or runners'
gear. ``Illuminite fits very well into our picture, where our
market tends to be conservative and not onto fashion trends,'' says
Adam Howes, apparel products manager at Performance Cycling Co. in
Durham, N.C., which sells by mail order and through 38
company-owned stores.
</P>
<P>
   But John d'Arbeloff, owner and president of Railriders
Sportswear, a clothing maker, said once runner-cyclist markets had
had a crack at the new product in 1996 and 1997, sales slumped and
retailers lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wildly excited about the concept,'' d'Arbeloff said.
``The problem was the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, d'Arbeloff dropped his outerwear Illuminite lines
this year, but does plan this fall to introduce Lycra tights with a
reflective Illuminite stripe down each leg. ``I think it will do
huge numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other early casualties, Rizika acknowledges, included Nike Inc.,
which was Reflective Technologies's second customer in 1995 when it
brought out jogging shorts made with Illuminite fabric, and Adidas,
which put out a jacket made with the material.
</P>
<P>
   Rizika says both say they would reconsider if Reflective
Technologies got big enough to promote in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Now that moment is at hand, in a deal that promises both lower
costs and product exposure around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Reflective Technologies in April signed a long-term licensing
agreement with a Taiwan textile mill, Formosa Taffeta Co. Ltd.,
giving that company production and marketing rights for Illuminite
in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Rizika said Taiwan's lower labor costs should cut the cost of
Illuminite-treated nylon or cotton-polyester blend by as much as 50
percent, to about $6 or $7 per yard.
</P>
<P>
   Proximity to the major clothing production shops in Thailand,
Indonesia, and China will mean further savings in both labor and
shipping costs for the apparel companies that market worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   And Formosa Taffeta, which has 60 salespeople _ 20 times more
than Reflective Technologies's sales force _ will be promoting the
Illuminite name in all its markets.
</P>
<P>
   A Fall River textile company, Duro Industries Inc., which now
makes all Illuminite-treated fabric, will retain that business for
US production of nylon, cotton, and cotton-polyester blend fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, negotiations are under way with other mills to add
fabrics _ including PolarTec fleece, made by Malden Mills
Industries Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The reflective powder itself will continue to be made in
Cambridge and be shipped to the producing mills. The process now
employs eight of Reflective Technologies's 22 employees. A second
production shift is planned this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The company's revenues now are derived mostly from the sale of
treated fabric _ with about one-fourth of sales attributed to the
fabric itself and the balance to the Illuminite treatment.
</P>
<P>
   With production beginning in Taiwan, Rizika says he expects
revenues this year to hit about $4.5 million and rise in 1999 to $7
million _ with the share from fabric resale falling to less than 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held, Reflective Technologies does not report
earnings, but Rizika said he expects 1998 to be the company's first
profitable year.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, as production expands and costs drop, the
company is pushing to become recognized as a brand and to get
Illuminite used on a broader variety of garments and other goods _
including infant wear, military outerwear, and a variety of outdoor
applications including raincoats and umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   The late-summer edition of the popular One Step Ahead baby
products catalog features Illuminite jackets for $39.95 and caps
for $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge this year is moving from the running market to
all these other markets,'' Rizika said.
</P>
<P>
   One eye-catching use introduced earlier this year: Dog coats and
vests made with Illuminite reflective fabric, marketed by Glow Dog
Inc. of Concord, Mass., whose founder, Beth Marcus, is a Reflective
Technologies stockholder.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus also is planning a series of children's Halloween capes _
in red, blue, or black _ that could be ready by fall and sell for
$15.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Rizika says the US Military Academy at West Point has an order
pending with Duro, a regular Army supplier, to produce fabric to
make jackets for its 4,000-member cadet corps.
</P>
<P>
   And talks are under way with Totes Inc., the largest US umbrella
company, to use Illuminite reflective treatment on some of its
product line.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, the marketing director, hopes that affiliations with
such name brands as PolarTec and Totes will help build Illuminite's
own brand visibility. ``We would like to be known in our field as
GoreTex is in its field,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Reflective Technologies also has launched a European sales
program aimed at sports-oriented outerwear in Germany and Italy.
And the company is targeting rainwear companies that sell in
northern Europe, where in the depths of winter night begins at 3:30
p.m. and lasts until after breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope,'' says Austin, ``is that by next winter the vast
majority of Danish commuters,'' most of whom bicycle at least
partway to work, ``will be wearing Illuminite rain capes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
