<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOLL-WEEVIL-ART-BOS &LR;      07-15 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLL-WEEVIL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE HAS THE BOLL WEEVIL ON THE RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LETTSWORTH, La. _ Since the boll weevil crossed from Mexico
into Brownsville, Texas, in 1892, American cotton growers and
entomologists have spent a century battling the pest, and at long
last victory seems at hand.
</P>
<P>
   As surely as the weevil spread across the southeastern quarter
of the country, destroying billions of dollars in crops and
thousands of jobs, a scientific counterattack that began in North
Carolina in 1978 is slowly beating the varmint back.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia already have
effectively eliminated the boll weevil, and now other major
cotton-producing states in the South are moving to join the
regional crusade known as the Boll Weevil Eradication Program.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many, especially those whose livelihoods are tied
to the land, the eradication program is a magic bullet, the
agricultural equivalent of Dr. Jonas Salk's polio vaccine.
Nevertheless, some farmers are unwilling to pay the price of the
program, which currently consists of blitzing cotton fields with a
potent pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   If all of the cotton-growing states coordinate the effort, the
weevil will be wiped out in five years, said Bob Odom, commissioner
of the Louisiana Department of Agriculture &AMP; Forestry, holding up
the five digits of his left hand for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   But in states such as his own, the issue is still a subject of
political debate, a source of controversy over costs and funding.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find state funds for the project, Louisiana
legislators last month attempted to dedicate $13 million to the
eradication program from the revenues of slot machines being
proposed for race tracks. The measure created an unusual alliance
between gambling-friendly legislators from the bayou country of
south Louisiana and the more conservative representatives of the
cotton-producing, Baptist territory in north Louisiana who are
nominally opposed to gambling.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the bill failed, but the agriculture department
found other sources of money and the session ended with
high-spirited legislators pulling an electric keyboard onto the
floor and singing the ode to the boll weevil by New Orleans
musician Fats Domino:
</P>
<P>
   ``Just lookin' for a home,
</P>
<P>
   got no place to roam...''
</P>
<P>
   For a tiny beetle, the boll weevil has dealt out tons of misery.
Though half the size of a housefly, the weevils have literally been
able to nip vast cotton crops in the bud. As John Andries, director
of Louisiana's boll weevil eradication program, explained, the
weevil pounces on new cotton plants and pierces the bud with its
sharp snout.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them, its like eating filet mignon,'' Andries said. Once
the bud is punctured, it falls to the ground and never produces a
cotton boll.
</P>
<P>
   The weevil also uses the plant for other purposes. ``Cotton is
the only plant the boll weevil can use for reproduction,'' said
Craig Roussel, the state horticulturalist. ``Cotton is its only
host.''
</P>
<P>
   The current assault on the boll weevil, through the concentrated
effort to kill the pest during the winter as well as the regular
doses of the pesticide during the growing season, is far more
sophisticated than the early efforts at control.
</P>
<P>
   When the boll weevil first appeared, a US Department of
Agriculture farm bulletin in 1902 recommended the use of molasses
to attract the weevil to arsenic poison. A year later, a government
entomologist lamented ``that there is not even a remote probability
that the boll weevil will ever be exterminated.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1917, the weevil had spread across the Gulf Coast states,
from Texas to Georgia, where cotton production fell by 30 percent.
There were tales of field hands being paid a bounty of one penny
per weevil captured. Odom, the Lousiana agriculture commissioner,
remembers turning a hand crank as a boy on his family's farm in
Claiborne Parish to scatter a crude poison called ``Black Annie''
on the cotton plants.
</P>
<P>
   When Georgia sponsored a public demonstration of aerial spraying
in 1924, more than 10,000 spectators showed up with high hopes of
eliminating the pest. Through the years, various chemicals were
used by the crop dusters. At a huge cost to the farmers, the boll
weevil was arrested, but nothing seemed to work on a widespread
basis until the southern states and cotton organizations began the
coordinated eradiction program.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, the program still faces obstacles on the local
level. Because the cotton growers are called upon to split the cost
of the program with the state _ a commitment that would cost each
farmer $15 per acre of cotton each year for the five years _ it
must be approved by a referendum. A statewide vote in 1995 failed
to reach the required two-thirds threshold for approval.
</P>
<P>
   Cotton farmers across the river in the fertile Mississippi Delta
also rejected the concept at first, though a new referendum, fanned
by the eradication program's success in other southern states, is
planned there soon.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Odom speculated that Louisiana growers
originally voted against the program because of its cost and ``that
age old thing, suspicions about 'the government is here to help
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   To jump-start the program in Louisiana, farmers have been
divided into two zones, a cotton-growing corridor along the Red
River in the central part of the state and the Mississippi River
delta area of northeast Louisiana. The eradication program was
eventually approved in the Red River zone, and is now in its second
year of activity.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in northeastern Louisiana will hold another referendum
in September, and state agricultural authorities are using a
long-range economic argument to push hard for passage of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   During the past four years, Louisiana farmers have opted to
plant less and less cotton because of the high costs of production
and low prices. Only 440,000 acres of cotton were planted in the
state this year, compared to more than 1 million acres in 1995.
According to projections by the state agriculture department, the
shift from cotton acreage to corn costs the local economy $500 per
acre.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers continue to resist this economic argument as well
as the prospect of paying $15 per acre a year to eradicate the
weevil, but the eradication program has its advocates in men such
as Paul Roy of Pointe Coupee Parish, who farms nearly 3,000 acres
at a point where the Red and Atchafalaya Rivers converge with the
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Roy has only 250 acres in cotton this year, ``down from what
it's been,'' he said. ``The biggest deterrent has been insects.
They can get in your pocketbook.''
</P>
<P>
   He supported the eradication program in both referendums and
believes it already is paying dividends. His farm, as well as the
cotton fields owned by his neighbors, is being blitzed
systematically by cropdusters spraying Malathion, a pesticide that
has been used in home gardens for years and is now regarded as the
final exterminating agent for boll weevils.
</P>
<P>
   The state controls the program, following each flight by
computer to determine if the spraying pattern is effective and
monitoring each field with lime-colored traps designed to catch
random weevils. If more than two weevils show up in a single trap,
it triggers intensified spraying.
</P>
<P>
   Control has been taken away from the whim of the farmer, and
under the program every acre of cotton in the zone is treated. The
universal program is designed to eliminate the possibility that
weevils might thrive in one farm neglected by its owner while
neighboring farmers invest heavily in efforts to control the pest.
</P>
<P>
   On Roy's farm the other day, the presence of weevils was
negligible. When he tried to control the weevils himself, Roy said,
``It was unreal, the costs were enormous. I would shake every time
I saw the entomologist.'' Though he is now paying handsomely into
the program, he said, ``I'm looking down the road. I know the
eradication program is a bump in the road, but when we get over it,
it will be clear sailing. I think this is going to prove that a
government program can work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
