<HEADER>
A5978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANOE-ADVENTURE-2TAKE     07-15 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANOE-ADVENTURE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING PICTURE-PERFECT MORNINGS IN THE NORTH WOODS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANIEL A. GRECH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE UMBAGOG, N.H. _ Art Desmarais and his son, Alex, drop their
canoe into the murky waters of Lake Umbagog, a wildlife refuge in
northern New Hampshire, as the sky softens just before daybreak on
a bitterly cold June morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's overcast,'' Desmarais tells Alex, pushing the canoe from
the shore. ``Perfect for shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dull morning light, they are a taciturn pair, the spindly
40-year-old father and the soft-eyed 14-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few hours ago, Art Desmarais was supervising Big Dig
utilities work in downtown Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Although construction is in Art's blood, he settled on his
avocation at an early age; by age 10 he was taking snapshots of
beavers with his Kodak Instamatic camera.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Alex is 14, and approaching some of life's crossroads,
Art senses a need to impart the kind of wisdom his father passed
on. He wants to show him how balancing work with other interests
can bring solace to a man, and to prove to Alex that even the most
placid souls can harbor a grand passion.
</P>
<P>
   Art's passion is locating New Hampshire's only nesting pair of
bald eagles and capturing them on film from the perfect angle, in
full, resplendent beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Alex will join his father's quest.
</P>
<P>
   The younger of two Desmarais children, Alex has always been a
quiet child, carefully protected by Art and his wife, Doreen. Now,
both parents want to start preparing him for life on his own.
</P>
<P>
   One recent night, shortly after Art arrives home from work, he
and his son load a truck with camera equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Construction work is not unlike photography,'' says Art.
``Your day is planned before it starts, but you need to be ready
for anything that might come up. You have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   On this morning, as he has for close to a decade, Art rises at 2
a.m. from his bed in Northwood, N.H., and travels through the night
to photograph bald eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the early start, a foray to scout moose crossings near
the lake is several minutes too late;he finds mud tracked across
the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wildlife never wait,'' Art tells Alex as they slide the
canoe off the truck's roof.
</P>
<P>
   They carry the canoe to the lake shore. Alex stocks it with a
cooler of Pepsi _ his father's chief addiction along with menthol
lights _ and a 60-pound battery for the small hand-held motor Art
uses now that arthritis in his back keeps him from rowing. Art
huddles over a closely guarded plastic container filled with camera
equipment, adjusting straps and setting meters in a hallowed
morning ritual.
</P>
<P>
   They set off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relaxing at his favorite diner in Boston before his night shift
on the Big Dig, Art says: ``Photography's about seeing the world
with the eyes of a child, with emotion and with wonder. Each animal
I photograph has a different flavor _ the eagle is awe, the bear is
intimidation, the deer is shyness. In a strange way, these animals
are a reflection of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Art is a relentless observer. His vision pervades his life, even
when he is at work in the construction trenches of Boston.
Photography sharpens his focus on the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People cross the street into the financial district like some
giant flock of birds,'' he says. ``We might take away a sidewalk
and they will try to walk there anyway, they are so used to their
daily patterns. But you've got to be there early to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   He spreads glossy images on the table. Art photographed what he
calls his ``big three'' before eagles even began nesting at the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   Two were taken in September 1987, with warm lake water and a
predawn fog in the trees. In one, three rocks jut from the water in
front of a small island of green shrubbery, a white mist obscuring
a valley in the background. Another looks like an unfinished
painting: a half-submerged moose in mid-bite, a bleached patch of
light hovering above the moose's pricked ears.
</P>
<P>
   The third picture of a spring sunset in 1988 also seems
otherworldly: A spattering of dark clouds, with red and orange
edges, and pastel streaks across the lake in the foreground.
</P>
<P>
   Desmarais calls these shots ``targets of opportunity.'' Most of
his other shots required a fisherman's patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to put yourself in proximity to see something and
sooner or later it happens,'' he explains. ``I might sit for five
hours and watch salmon roll down the river without getting a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do I see when I look at these pictures?'' he asks
himself. ``I see awesome creatures specifically designed to do
certain things. I see the awkward cupped horns of a moose so he can
hear his mate. I see his very long legs, like stilts, so he can
walk through the mud.''
</P>
<P>
   Art looks up from his prints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Photography for me isn't a hobby,'' he says, ``it's a way of
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After he and Alex have been on the water several minutes,
Desmarais tells of YT, a photogenic male eagle who died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``YT seemed to prance in front of the camera. Sometimes I
thought he knew I was taking his picture,'' he says. ``I was up
here in September of '92, canoeing around the nest. I got up real
close, within 20 feet _ you have no idea how big the tree actually
is until you get close _ and YT was about 50 feet up on one of the
branches. I put down my camera and looked at YT, and YT looked at
me, and I could see his yellow eyes. Then YT reached down and
pulled out a big feather from his wing'' _ Desmarais gestures with
his hands two feet apart _ ``and he let it drop right next to my
boat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
