<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-15 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A REPORTER OF THE OLD SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- When Doug Crocket died, he took with him an
awesome and valuable secret: how to have fun in the news business,
a trade he adorned for most of his life, which ended last week at
70 in a Massachusetts hospital. Doug had fun because he distorted,
embroidered, exaggerated, mangled, stretched, and twisted the
events of the day, but only AFTER he had filed a thorough, fair,
and accurate story about them.
</P>
<P>
   What he called ``whomping up'' a story did not mean making it
up, but squeezing into it enough emotion to appeal to readers, whom
he regarded as family. Afterward, over strong drink, he would
regale colleagues about the perils, real and imaginary, he escaped
in his daily odyssey. Hyperbole was his hallmark in depicting
outrages perpetrated by editors, called by the old New England
epithet, ``chowderheads,'' or, if he felt kindly, ``bubbleheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he feared editors. We all did when crime and three-alarm
fires superseded spin and press conferences in defining news. When
private grief outranked public policy, general assignment reporters
outnumbered analysts and specialists, who were, in Crocket's view,
``reporters afraid to ask dumb questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Angry cops and random hazards made fear part of our lives, but
created camaraderie, too. Doug was the morale officer, reciting
hilarious accounts of his first-person stunts. He entered a
log-rolling contest and lived to tell the tale. He was truly
fearful of being assigned to bat against the Red Sox reliever, Dick
Radatz.
</P>
<P>
   He would have admired his obit. ``Mr. Crocket wasn't a
journalist. He was a reporter,'' Tom Long wrote. ``A reporter of
the old school: a tough-talking sweetheart.'' His publisher, Bill
Taylor, said, ``Doug was one of the true `Globies,''' a breed quick
to complain but with loyalty as deep as the Quincy quarries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Daniel Patrick Moynihan wrote in Commentary that ``the
`working press' (as it liked to call itself) was surprisingly close
in origins and attitudes to working people generally. They were not
Ivy Leaguers. They now are or soon will be.'' I protested, citing
White House reporters like the AP's Frank Cormier of Northwestern,
Peter Lisagor of the Chicago Daily News and Michigan, and Matthew
V. Storin of The Boston Globe and the University of Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   But Moynihan was prescient. The path to press glory soon
detoured from police precincts to little magazines whose writers
talked only to people who wanted to talk to them, who avoided the
gritty reality of general assignment. In Doug Crocket's day, there
was only one Walter Lippmann, an Olympian oracle. Today, the
precocious punditry of ``little Lippmanns'' infests cable
television.
</P>
<P>
   Crocket's working-class origins and attitudes might not fit in
today. He would certainly not be allowed to greet half the females
in Area Code 617 with, ``Hi there, Miss Teen-Age America!''
</P>
<P>
   Storin, his editor, said, ``Doug was right out of `The Front
Page.' He was the ultimate street reporter who could talk to anyone
and get anyone to talk to him.'' And leave 'em laughing. In the
1920s, ``The Front Page'' succeeded as drama because it mirrored
reality. Amid boozy high-jinks, the autobiographies of Ben Hecht,
Gene Fowler, and Stanley Walker ultimately confessed that their
jaded cleverness was a cover for raging sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   In the Crocket era, every reporter was part cynic and part sob
sister. Doug was born for the assignment of Globe Santa, the
charity his newspaper inherited when The Boston Post folded in
1956. Since then, thousands of children have enjoyed Christmas
because of contributors moved by the Globe Santa staff, of which
Doug was the Dickensian stalwart.
</P>
<P>
   The prose was purple and persuasive. Some of his old
runningmates read it skeptically, but weakened. During one
Yuletide, an old pal sent Globe Santa a check, which Doug listed
atop the Christmas Day list: ``Fat Kid: $500.'' And the Fat Kid
wept.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
