A5980 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-15 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG TALK LEAVES EMPTY FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After testing all the teachers, ranking all the students, and
revising all the curricula, one barrier will remain to meaningful
education reform in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   After cutting state income taxes, rebating some of the state
surplus, and doubling personal tax exemptions, one obstacle will
continue to stymie the achievement of Massachusetts children in the
classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Too many kids go to school every morning in this Commonwealth
with an empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The US Department of Agriculture puts the number of underfed
children in Massachusetts at 62,000. The doctors, nutritionists,
and social workers who have just completed a survey of hungry
children across the state under the auspices of Tufts University
and Project Bread put a price tag of $40 million-$50 million beyond
current expenditures on eliminating what is both an educational
impediment and a moral disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Too much of the discussion about education reform has consisted
of blaming the teachers. &UR;  &LR; Alas, hunger does not yield as easily to
demagoguery as the reputation of public school teachers. Its
causes, however, are plain and its solution even simpler than a
standardized test. All that's needed is the political will, an
ingredient shamefully lacking in a state experiencing such flush
economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Deep within the state budget on its way to Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci's desk this week is a mere $2 million to expand school
breakfast and summer meal programs for poor children. It is not
nearly enough, but it was not easily secured.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham championed the need to
finance programs to increase participation in school and summer
breakfast programs. Sixty percent of the children eligible for
school breakfasts are not receiving them and a stunning 90 percent
eligible for partially subsidized meals are not getting them. ``It
was not easy to get the money we did get. There is a great fear up
here of creating a new entitlement,'' Birmingham said of the
atmosphere on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of $2 million might increase outreach efforts and
establish a few pilot programs to reach hungry children, but
Massachusetts has a long and distinguished record of doing more
than the minimum for its most vulnerable children. When the federal
government reduced its commitment to the nutritional program for
Women, Infants and Children (WIC) in the 1980s, Governor Michael
Dukakis and the Legislature bridged the funding gap for
Massachusetts families. When the number of uninsured children began
to climb with the cost of health care in this decade, state
lawmakers devised a means to extend medical coverage to the
unprotected. Just this week, the Center for Disease Control and
Prevention ranked Massachusetts first in the nation in immunizing
its children.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need a pilot program to prove what our mothers taught
us: Breakfast is the most important meal of the day. What we need
is a year-round universal school breakfast program that offers a
morning meal to every hungry child in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   That will be the recommendation of those who participated in the
statewide survey of hunger in Massachusetts, but the researchers'
report may come too late. By autumn, when its study is due to be
released, the mania for election-year tax cuts and tax rebates
consuming the gubernatorial candidates and the leadership of both
parties might well have overtaken this opportunity to address the
needs of poorly nourished children.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, voters will not turn down a few hundred dollars in
tax cuts _ for many working families it represents a sizable
savings _ but it is a misreading of the public mood to think that
taxpayers are unwilling to share the wealth with children when
education continually tops the priority list in voter survey after
voter survey.
</P>
<P>
   The public understands better than its elected representatives
that the fever that fueled Citizens for Limited Taxation for more
than a decade has long since subsided. Barbara Anderson's anti-tax
group is on the verge of going out of business this summer, after
all, citing public indifference to the cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts electorate is anything but indifferent to the
issues that surround the education of our children. For months now,
we have heard those with their hands on the public purse strings
insist that Massachusetts children need the brightest teachers and
the highest standards in order to learn. Isn't it reasonable to ask
whether they don't also need a full stomach?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
