</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO TO POPE: THIS CARDINAL WAS NO SAINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My mother has been blessed with an interesting life. Sitting at
my kitchen table last week, she noticed a brief news item about the
proposed canonization of the Croatian Cardinal Alojzije Stepinac.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I worked in Belgrade in 1950, there was a campaign to get
the US to free Stepinac,'' she said. ``Every Serb we knew said if
Stepinac was released from jail, they would tear him limb from
limb. It was said he burned down churches full of Orthodox Serbs
during the war. Odd choice for a saint.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd choice, indeed. But the current pope's heartfelt
anti-Communism _ the same belief that prevents him from canonizing
the martyred Salvadoran bishop Oscar Romero _ may elevate Stepinac
to the ranks of the elect. A fervent Croat nationalist, Stepinac
served a pro-Nazi, Croat puppet state during World War II. There is
scant evidence that he spoke out against the horrifying anti-Serb
atrocities committed during the war. Speaking to The Washington
Post, a Croat journalist explained that Stepinac preferred the
``criminal'' Ustachi terrorists governing wartime Croatia to the
``anti-Christ'' fighting the Nazis _ the anti-clerical Communist,
Josip Broz Tito.
</P>
<P>
   Should Stepinac become a saint, he would join a motley crew.
Isabella I of Spain, champion of the Inquisition, is also up for
sainthood. For several decades, conservative prelates have been
hoping to canonize the controversial wartime Pope Pius XII,
although there seems to be little likelihood of that happening
soon.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when saints were chosen by acclamation, or by
vox populi. St. Francis of Assisi and his spiritual sister Clare
(curiously, the patron saint of television) were canonized almost
immediately after their deaths in the 13th century, but less worthy
candidates abounded. Local heroes and potentates could jawbone
their way to sainthood. ``Clearly, some form of quality control was
needed,'' writes Kenneth Woodward, author of the insider's guide to
sainthood, ``Making Saints.'' In the 16th century, the church
instituted a formal system of nominations and a host of
bureaucratic hurdles for would-be divines.
</P>
<P>
   And yet peculiarities remain. In 1969, the Vatican turfed out 60
saints from the liturgical calendar, including the mythical St.
Christopher, whose image I carry in my wallet. Popular favorites
like St. Nicholas, a.k.a. Mr. Claus, and St. George of England were
downgraded. Now Pope John Paul II is approving saints at a pace
faster than any of his predecessors. It's said that he loves to
``carry a saint in his pocket'' _ sometimes two or three _ on his
frequent foreign travels.
</P>
<P>
   In America, as elsewhere, this had produced some anomalies. For
instance, the Pope was unable to beatify Father Junipero Serra
during his California visit in 1985 because Native American
activists accused the famous missionary of mistreating the Indians.
In 1987, the same year he beatified Serra from the Vatican, John
Paul also beatified Philadelphia heiress Katharine Drexel, who led
dramatic ministries to Native Americans and blacks earlier in this
century. Yet even after being honored, Drexel is almost completely
unknown in her native land.
</P>
<P>
   Who's next? Two obvious candidates are Mother Teresa and ``Good
Pope John'' XXIII, who convened Vatican II. Just a few months ago,
New York's Cardinal O'Connor threw his ecclesiastical weight behind
the candidacy of Dorothy Day, the charismatic founder of the
Catholic Worker movement. Day's admirers have been reluctant to
push her nomination, believing that the money spent on a
canonization _ often $1 million or more _ would be better used to
help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   If selected, Day would be a most modern saint. As a young woman,
she had an abortion and later bore a child out of wedlock, sins she
deeply regretted in later life. Author Woodward points out that
Day's spiritual journey imitates the model Catholic life of St.
Augustine. ``Sinner turned saint is what everybody loves,''
Woodward says. ``She's kosher on that score.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Worker volunteer Frank Donovan, who knew Day, recalls
that ``she would often say, `Don't call me a saint! I don't want to
be dismissed that easily.''' Day's extraordinary life work can
never be dismissed. Let's just hope she's not walking alongside
Cardinal Stepinac when the next saints go marching in.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
