<HEADER>
A5989 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-15 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD RIDDANCE, TINA BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'd prescribe a year of The New Yorker for Mr. David Nyhan,''
says the postcard animal dressed up as a doc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mail the card below. You get the world's best cartoons. And
the world's best magazine.'' Then, (big type, please, in a catchy
fuchsia panel: ``WITH TINA BROWN AS EDITOR.''
</P>
<P>
   Err, scratch that. Ms. Brown has moved to the synergistic worlds
of publishing books, magazines, press releases, screenplays, and
all the rest that goes into the business of film (don't call it
movies).
</P>
<P>
   And good riddance, say I.
</P>
<P>
   Because she tarted up The New Yorker. For my money, she took the
venerable mag downmarket, injecting all that glitz and glitter and
groany prose about s-e-x.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she did it without my money. Which is why I am a
lapsed New Yorker subscriber, a conscientous objector in the war
Tina waged to lower the beltline of journalism's
never-too-high-to-begin-with standards. I abstained, after her
downward market trek became apparent, despite enticements like the
low-ball, one-year, 46-issue subscription for $19.98, wherein ``I
save over $124 off the cover price.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why The New Yorker is still bleeding cash. She took
circulation for the Newhouse Bros. loss leader up to 800,000 from
500,000. She got a lot more people in the lower end of the media
food chain talking about this or that that cropped up in her
feverishly massaged pages.She did photography, fashion,
(itals)daring.(unitals) But she drowned it in flirtations with sex.
All kinds, manner of, and cul-de-sacs. The magazine, under Brown's
tenure, became a bit of a sex rag. Not totally and exclusively. But
sufficiently to import wholesale the rather sick cultural values of
the glossy magazine enclaves of Manhattan and Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   May I suggest something heretical to Mr. S.I. Newhouse, admiral
of the journalistic fleet at Advance Publications and Conde Nast? A
lot of us reasonably intelligent and sensible folk, who have the IQ
and wherewithal to deal with your storied magazine, did not like
her act.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine chain's boss of bosses offered her another
five-year contract, so he obviously liked what she was doing, even
though the magazine lost torrents of money. But out here where the
folks live, the magazine's covers and features frequently exuded
the rotting stench of sex-for-sale. It's hard enough in the
contemporary media supermarket to find products not drenched in
sleaze.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a supermarket in America that does not stack the Cosmo
girl's breastbone at eye level in every checkout aisle? Don't the
grownups of America understand the concept that sex has become more
important as a marketing tool than as a reproductive technique?
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, some clever, some crude, Tina Brown steered her
writers, artists, and editors in the direction of the pubic
regions. I'm not making any personal or Freudian judgments. Don't
know her, don't expect to.
</P>
<P>
   ``She constantly put new geist in the Zeitgeist,'' reported The
New York Times of Tina's turns at the Tatler, Vanity Fair, and The
New Yorker. Hmmm. The zeitgeist is ``the general intellectual,
moral and cultural climate of an era,'' says my friend Mr. Webster.
</P>
<P>
   If the Times is correct, that places Tina Brown at Ground Zero
of the cultural meltdown that characterizes modern English
language-printed communications. What a legacy: I took the New
Yorker magazine lower, and sold more copies doing it.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, she dusted out the cupboards, aired the linen,
opened the windows, and otherwise spiffed up a dingy, creaky, musty
old B&AMP;B of a cultural magazine. No doubt a lot of what she did
needed doing.No doubt some of the enmeies she made in the process
are mere old-guard types gnashing their fillings over progress,
modernity, trendiness, political correctness, etc.
</P>
<P>
   But gossip, glitter, and a tropism for deadly earnest
discussions of Sexsexsexsexsex and more so quickly pall. There is
not a single subject about which so much is written, to so little
avail.
</P>
<P>
   The animal kingdom _ and the plants too, for all I know _ play
their part in the great sexual game, and none of them need literary
guidance in how to conduct their mating rituals. Tina certainly
knew how to generate the buzz. And she certainly knew how to sting,
as her fearsome reputation attests. But for those of us who didn't
like this Oxford-educated British lady poking around in our
erogenous zones, trying to stir us in the direction of talking
about or buying subjects or something we'd otherwise abjure, I say
bring on the David Remnick renascence. He's only the fifth editor
since Harold Ross's brilliance enlived American culture, beginning
in 1925. I'll keep my fingers crossed, and my postcard handy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
