<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COWBOY-ZOO-DIRECTOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIAN RUTLEDGE BRINGS A BIT OF THE WEST TO AN EASTERN ZOO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 &HT;     (Attn.: Colo.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``Needles, do your trick!'' Brian Rutledge commands.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the living room carpet of the house trailer, Needles
the tabby cat doesn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sit!'' Rutledge tries.
</P>
<P>
   Needles still doesn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do your dog thing!''
</P>
<P>
   Needles still doesn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not gonna do it, are you, Needles?''
</P>
<P>
   Needles finally sits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good cat,'' Rutledge purrs. ``Good cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is domestic life in Franklin Park, where it's not always
easy to tell where the zoo leaves off and the zoo director's
residence begins. But departing a 110-acre spread in Colorado to
live in an 800-square-foot trailer in the heart of Boston doesn't
mean a man has to leave his livestock behind, does it? Just listen
and you might hear one of Rutledge's 21 sled dogs yapping from
somewhere yonder in their kennel. Or look out toward the paddock
and you might spy Miss Bekka Jack, the 18-year-old cutting horse
that belongs to Rutledge's wife, Kathleen Brennan Rutledge. ``A
good cuttin' horse, but not a great cuttin' horse,'' Brian Rutledge
muses.
</P>
<P>
   Highly energetic and supremely self-confident, Rutledge, 46, was
hired nearly two years ago at $140,000 a year to restore Greater
Boston's hapless Franklin Park and Stone zoos and thereby save us
from what he calls our ``eco-ignorance.'' He's been marketed by his
employers as a tall-in-the-saddle savior, and Lord knows he looks
and sounds the part: Western hat, cowboy boots, measured twang,
etc. His wife, a former Ford model to whom he's been married for
four years, wears a fringed buckskin jacket she says he made when
he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   And darned if he hasn't created a small urban ranch inside the
72-acre Franklin Park Zoo. OK, it's not exactly big sky country,
not when you find yourself being awakened in the morning by the
not-so-gentle jangle of an ice-cream truck. The Rutledge range
looks more like something you'd find in, say, back-roads Worcester
County, what with its horse trailer, its shed (which contains four
dog sleds and one Western saddle), its Chevy Tahoe sport utility
vehicle, its assorted animals, and the L-shaped beige trailer,
which squats beneath the tall white oak trees. Oh, and don't forget
the TV satellite dish. ``Rodeo only comes on Prime-star,'' Brian
Rutledge explains.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, even though Franklin Park isn't a place where the
deer and the antelope play _ at the moment, the zoo displays
neither _ it does offer certain unique vistas. ``I love looking out
the window and seeing the zebra,'' says Kathleen Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   As for life inside a dwelling that resembles a bowling alley,
the 6-foot-1 husband and the 5-foot-9 wife are apparently making
do. While the couple isn't known for painting the town red _ their
idea of a good time is to drop in at Doyle's Cafe in Jamaica Plain,
the quintessential neighborhood saloon _ Kathleen Rutledge at least
got red paint on some of the trailer's muted interior walls.
West-of-the-Mississippi decor includes a lamp fashioned from deer
antlers, a Native American dream catcher, a poster for a Western
art exhibit in Tulsa, and a small gathering of Kathleen's
still-life photographs of the West. There's simply not room for a
whole lot more in a home where the hat rack _ a Nordic Track
exerciser _ takes up significant space.
</P>
<P>
   Truth to tell, Brian Rutledge confesses, he uses the rent-free
trailer, which the zoo purchased for him, as little more than a
bunkhouse. He is Zoo Man to his wife's Dog Woman, sometimes riding
Miss Bekka Jack to his office a few hundred yards away while she
spends much of her day tending the 13 Alaskan huskies and eight
malamutes the couple races competitively, primarily in Colorado.
Significantly, their fenced yard includes a picnic table and a gas
grill. ``I can't even cook in the house,'' says Brian Rutledge, who
recently purchased an outdoor Dutch oven. ``I can cook outside, but
not inside.''
</P>
<P>
   So what would you expect from someone who spent his boyhood
summers camping deep in the Michigan woods with his family? Who was
called ``Animal'' by his friends, but not for the usual reasons?
Who cowboyed in Colorado as a teenager, bought himself a horse upon
graduation from high school, and majored in animal behavior in
college? Who trains and rides cutting horses, raises and races sled
dogs, and bought himself and his wife matching spurs as a wedding
gift?
</P>
<P>
   The way Zoo Man figures it, there wasn't much choice but to
settle into Franklin Park. Most major zoological parks provide an
on-site home for their director, in no small part because, as Brian
Rutledge himself puts it, ``running a zoo is more like running a
ranch than running a widget factory.'' Besides, having upward of a
couple of dozen dogs in tow might tend to scare off the suburban
Welcome Wagon. ``Who'd want us as neighbors?'' Kathleen Rutledge
asks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when he arrived in Boston in September 1996, having
resided in Colorado for a couple of years after spending 13 years
as director of the Baltimore Zoo, Brian Rutledge initially thought
he might try honest-to-God rural New England living. ``I went out
the first day to look for an area with cows,'' he recalls. ``I got
all the way to Pittsfield before I saw any cows.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you just can't get out of the city quickly here,'' he
adds. ``In Baltimore, I could drive 28 miles out of the city in 35
minutes. You'd need a helicopter to do that here. If we lived
outside the city, I'd have to leave for work at 5 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Rutledges have all of Franklin Park's 500 acres as
their back yard. ``I'd rather have a small home with lots of land
than the other way around,'' Kathleen Rutledge declares. ``My life
is outbuildings. I get more upset if the barn's messy than the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely, however, that a cougar will bring down a mule
deer a few yards from their home, as it once did in Colorado. Their
property in the Centennial State _ which they still own, and which
they revisit about twice a year _ backs up onto some 80,000 acres
of federal land.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rutledge himself admits that the confinement of trailer
life occasionally makes him a tad stir-crazy, although he's more
likely to carry on about Boston traffic or the fact that the locals
seem to him incapable of saying please and thank you. He says he'd
like a larger, permanent home on the zoo grounds, a place to meet
and greet zoo supporters and financial angels. Such a structure,
however, is not in the immediate future for a pair of zoos that are
being raised from the dead to the tune of an estimated $100 million
over 10 years, despite the fact that zoo officials say attendance
and revenues have roughly doubled during Rutledge's brief tenure.
``We owe the taxpayers a great zoo before we worry about building a
residence,'' says Grace Fey, who chairs the board of directors of
Zoo New England.
</P>
<P>
   But for now trailer life suffices for the man who confidently
sees himself as the builder of the first two great zoos of the next
century and who says he took the job so it wouldn't be filled by
``someone who would just take a stab at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't a mission,'' Brian Rutledge announces as he sits in
his minuscule living room, ``if you don't have something to give
up, is it?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
