<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-HOTDOGS-BOS &LR;      07-15 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HOTDOGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS STILL RELISH HOT DOGS AS A SUMMER TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's be frank, as it were: Summer is the season of the hot dog.
About 35 percent of America's annual platter of 20 billion hot dogs
are eaten between Memorial Day and Labor Day, according to industry
data. So maybe that's what's meant by ``the dog days of summer.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the aroma of sizzling pups has begun to waft over
the landscape, taking its place alongside suntan lotion and freshly
mowed grass as a significant smell of summer. But if a hot dog
seems a simple pleasure to most of us, connoisseurs of this
particular type of cooked sausage know differently. In short,
there's more to hot dogs _ a.k.a. franks, frankfurters, wieners,
weenies, red hots, and so forth _ than meets the tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Every junk-food trend spotter knows that 1992 marked the
emergence of ``low-fat'' hot dogs (3 or fewer grams of fat), while
1995 signaled the arrival of that apparent oxymoron, the ``no fat''
hot dog (less than 0.5 gram of fat). But while such so-called
``better-for-you'' franks were able to grab some quick market
share, they've now leveled off at between 10 and 15 percent of all
US sales.
</P>
<P>
   The king of American dogs remains the beef-pork combination,
which accounts for about 60 percent of US retail sales. Beef is
next at approximately 25 percent, with poultry representing about
12 percent. But there are sharp regional differences. At Star
Markets, for example, beef franks represent about 70 percent of all
frankfurters sold, with beef-pork accounting for most of the rest.
``That's true throughout New England,'' says Jim MacDonald, Star
vice president for perishable merchandising. ``We're an area that's
not so much beef-dominant as pork-resistant.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Matt Monkiewicz, who is hot dog product
manager at Kayem Foods Inc. in Chelsea, Mass. Monkiewicz, who
represents the fourth generation of his family to make dogs, points
out that Kayem's beef-pork franks, sold largely to delicatessens,
outsell the company's beef line.
</P>
<P>
   And please don't talk to him about turkey dogs or chicken dogs.
``Poultry is a little less firm, a little mushier,'' he contends
politely. ``You don't get the juiciness you get with pork and beef.
That's really not the kind of product we want under the Kayem
label.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hot dogs and there are hot dogs. And then there are
more hot dogs. Kayem alone makes 108 varieties, ranging from 5 to
12 inches in length. Odd dogs you might find in a local grocery
store include buffalo dogs, vegetable dogs, and tofu dogs. There
are kosher dogs, too, of course. On the road, you might encounter
the likes of chili dogs, Chicago dogs, Coney Island dogs, nacho
dogs, and sauerkraut dogs. Most hot dogs are stripped of their
skins after they're cooked during processing, although many
aficionados prefer a hot dog that arrives in a natural casing, i.e.
an exterior made of animal intestines.
</P>
<P>
   Hot dogs have a deserved reputation as a high-fat food. Beef and
pork dogs contain the most fat (usually about 12 to 22 grams),
while beef franks have somewhat less (7 to 17 grams). Hot dogs
aren't recommended for someone trying to cut down on salt: Most
contain between 300 and 700 milligrams of sodium.
</P>
<P>
   However, eating a chicken or a turkey dog isn't always a low-fat
experience. Example: A 1.5-ounce Applegate Farms beef frank
contains 7 grams of fat, while a Weaver 1.6-ounce chicken frank has
9 grams. But maybe the fat factor doesn't matter to people, what
with only 10 to 15 percent of US hot dog sales being of the low-fat
or no-fat variety. ``There's a certain perception out there that a
hot dog ain't a hot dog if you take the fat out,'' points out Janet
Riley, an executive of the National Hot Dog &AMP; Sausage Council, a
trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to cook a dog _ grilling, boiling, broiling,
steaming, microwaving and deep-frying. The major methods are
boiling and grilling, but Julia Child feels that appearance should
dictate preference. ``Grilling hot dogs _ or even sauteing them in
a pan _ makes them look nicer, don't you think?'' advises the
Cambridge food doyenne. ``And if they're grilled or sauteed,
they're better split because, again, they look better that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dressing the dog'' is important, too. Ketchup is popular among
kids, of course. But it's also big among Gen Xers, according to
research done by National Foods, the maker of Hebrew National
franks. Folks from ages 55 to 64 much prefer mustard, the company
says.
</P>
<P>
   Preferences for certain toppings vary by region as well. Ketchup
rules in the north-central United States, for example, while
mayonnaise is popular in the South and West. According to Kayem,
mustard is New England's most popular dressing, followed by
ketchup, then relish.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the roll? Squishy American-style hot dog rolls
prevail, but there are backers of sesame seed, poppy seed, kaiser
rolls, potato rolls (in Philadelphia), and sourdough rolls (in San
Francisco). But please: no sun-dried tomato rolls, not even in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hot Dog &AMP; Sausage Council says that eating a
standard hot dog and bun should require no more than five bites.
And the organization also advises against wine with hot dogs,
instead suggesting beer, soda, lemonade, or ice tea. We would say
hot dogs go fine with anything but wine.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the frankfurter are in dispute. Was it born in
Germany in Frankfurt am Main or in Austria in Vienna? Scholars
disagree only slightly less vehemently than the two cities do.
</P>
<P>
   On this side of the Atlantic, debate flourishes over the
addition of the bun. Were sausages in a roll first served in New
York City's Bowery during the 1860s by a German immigrant operating
a pushcart? Or were they initially offered at a Coney Island stand
in 1871? And what about the story that the first hot dog on a bun
was served at the 1904 World's Fair in St. Louis? Or the one about
the editorial cartoonist who coined the term ``hot dog'' after he
saw wieners served in buns at New York's Polo Grounds ballpark in
1901?
</P>
<P>
   If you want to impress your friends while standing around the
backyard grill this summer, tell them stuff like this:
</P>
<P>
   _If Americans will indeed eat 20 billion hot dogs this year,
that's about 75 for every man, woman, and child in the country.
</P>
<P>
   _Major league baseball fans are expected to eat 26 million hot
dogs at ballparks in 1998, only a few more than Babe Ruth allegedly
ate at a single sitting. (Actually, he supposedly downed 12.)
</P>
<P>
   _Yes, Oscar Mayer Foods, the nation's largest hot dog producer,
still maintains a Wienermobile. These frankfurter-shaped
promotional vehicles have been around since 1936, and this is the
sixth generation of the car.
</P>
<P>
   _The famous Hot Dog Festival held each July in _ naturally _
Frankfort, Ind., draws some 15,000 folks who eat about 12,000 hot
dogs. But that's barely a mouthful compared to the approximately
75,000 dogs devoured by some 32,000 people at the recent Hot Dog
Safari held at Suffolk Downs in East Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
