<HEADER>
A5997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKBOOKS-HNS &LR;      07-15 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKBOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER COOK BOOKS SHOW HOW TO PREPARE LIGHT AND EASY FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the season of eating light.
</P>
<P>
   That can mean one of several things: eating lower-fat foods
because you need to fit into that bathing suit or shorts, lower
bulk food because your digestion seems to slow in the hot months,
or just less complicated food because you have so many more things
to absorb your time than being stuck in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your selection, here's a rundown on the latest crop of
cookbooks that will hit one or more of those categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entertaing Light &AMP; Easy,'' by Laurie Burrows Grad. Simon &AMP;
Schuster. 399 pp. $25.
</P>
<P>
   Any author who begins with one of my favorite diet quotes
(``Never eat more than you can lift.'' _ Miss Piggy) is OK in my
cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Grad is a restaurant critic for Buzz magazine after 17 years as
food editor of the Los Angeles Times. ``Light and easy'' are her
watchwords. They've popped up in one of her previous cookbook names
and in the title of a cable TV show she once hosted, so we know she
takes them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, her healthy-eating recipes are a lot more time
consuming than tossing a marbled steak on the broiler, ladeling
cheese sauce on the broccoli and putting dollops of whipped cream
on the pie, but if you eat her way you'll probably live longer so
you'll have the time to cook.
</P>
<P>
   She uses her own recipes as well as techniques and recipes from
noted chefs and food experts she's come across professionally,
people such as Molly O'Neill of The New York Times and chef Nobu
Matsuhia of Nobu's in New York. In more than 175 recipes, Grad
provides such toothsome dishes as potato-zucchini pancakes, beef
burgundy with porcini mushrooms, rack of lamb with pistachio-mint
crumb crust and butterflied turkey breast with orange mustard glaze
and raisin bread stuffing.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than a collection of recipes, however. Grad
includes with many of them cooking notes, variations, and do-ahead
prep. She also provides tips on entertaining light, suggested full
menus, and a guide on how to modernize and streamline your kitchen
without going into debt. A solid how-to book on many levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool Kitchen,'' by Lauren Chattman. William Morrow &AMP; Co. 164
pp. $22.
</P>
<P>
   This is a first-cookbook effort for the former pastry chef at
Nick and Toni's restaurant in East Hampton, N.Y. Her premise is
good eating without a lot of cooking, especially in hot weather. To
that end, Chattman has put together 125 recipes for salads,
sandwiches, desserts, sauces and the like. The result is an
imaginative collection, although a bit spare for the hefty price
tag.
</P>
<P>
   I see the ingredients lists and the instructional pages (how to
peel a mango, how to poach boneless chicken breasts, etc.) as the
most valuable portions.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who have resolved to put together one of those
hot-day meals you've heard about on the TV Food Network or seen in
a magazine but find your shelves bereft of some key indgredients,
Chattman provides a good pantry list of basics to keep on hand:
bottled veggies, dried fruits, herbs and chilies, oils and so on.
Such staples, you'll find, aren't confined to summertime use. Among
her intriguing recipes: double orange sundaes, tomato-feta sauce,
roast beef and rosemary mushrooms on focaccia, avocado dip with
chipotles and lime, and wasabi mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``101 Essential Tips: Barbecuing,'' by Marlena Spieler. DK
Publishing Inc., $3.95.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of a series of ``101 Essential Tips'' books
published in various countries by the Dorling Kindersley Ltd.
company of London and overseen by series editor Bella Pringle.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same company that produced the brilliant, oversized
``Ultimate Chocolate Cookbook'' earlier this year. But in the
``101'' series the slick-paper books are compact (5x7 inches) and
brief (72 pages), yet packed with smart color photographs that both
illustrate and guide the user.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Barbecuing'' edition contains good tips on barbecue
equipment, hygiene and procedures, instructions on the uses of
rubs, marinades and sauces, and lots of recipes.
</P>
<P>
   This is a no-brainer: Get the book! And if you want to know more
about DK Publishing and its products, check the World Wide Web site
at http://www.dk.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Secrets of Fat-Free Indian Cooking,'' by Priya Kulkarni and
Anita Ranade. Avery Publishing Group. 228 pp. $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   A common perception of Indian food is that, with its emphasis on
vegetables and legumes and use of small amounts of meat, it is by
definition low-fat. To some extent that is true, but like any
cuisine there are regional variations. And in that variety, you'll
often find milk and cream, nuts, butter and other ingredients
fairly high in fat and cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Kulkarni, who lives in Virginia, teaches Indian cooking classes.
Co-author Ranade, who lives in Oregon, holds a university degree in
food and nutrition. They boast that most of their collection of 150
recipes have less than two grams of fat per serving.
</P>
<P>
   They've avoided the usual trap of making things low-fat by
taking away the parts that taste good. Instead, they've paid a lot
of attention to cooking methods (steaming, roasting, pan browning)
that can maintain flavors while getting rid of fats; herbs you
don't commonly use but that can enhance flavors with virtually no
calories, fat or cholesterol; how to shop for better uncooked
ingredients (even what to order and what to avoid in Indian
restaurants), and other smart stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William M. Dowd is associate editor of the Times Union. He also
is the restaurant critic and periodically reviews new cookbooks.)
</P>
</TEXT>
