<HEADLINE>
BEACON CAPITAL ROLLING TOWARD PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Starting over isn't nearly so hard when people want to throw
money at you.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after completing the $4.4 billion sale of Beacon
Properties Corp., Alan Leventhal is building a new Boston-based
real estate business at breakneck pace _ and going public again is
considered only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom had said Leventhal's new Beacon Capital
Partners would launch an initial public offering of stock by the
end of this year or in early 1999. Now the soft stock market for
office-oriented real estate investment trusts, or REITs, may push
an IPO deeper into next year, observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal had barely turned the Beacon Properties keys over to
Sam Zell's Equity Office Properties Trust when Leventhal and chief
deputy Lionel Fortin started planning a new real estate vehicle
last winter. Within nine weeks, they raised $420 million in a
private equity offering for Beacon Capital and have since issued
another $50 million in stock as partial payment for real estate.
</P>
<P>
   File that as another example of how capital formation for REITs
has accelerated so dramatically in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1993 when Leventhal had first discussed raising public
money for Beacon Properties. Ten months later, the IPO got off the
ground and the company had raised less than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Leventhal, Fortin, and a large group of former Beacon
Properties managers can point to a track record: earning a
compounded annual return of 42 percent for public investors during
the company's three-year public life from 1994 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal says 60 percent of institutions that invested in
Beacon Properties have put money into the new Beacon Capital.
Wellington Management Co. is listed in documents as the company's
largest investor, owning a 10.9 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   The track record was certainly a plus. But investors who
eventually bought into Beacon Properties years ago could appreciate
its top-shelf portfolio of real estate, including local jewels like
Rowes Wharf and One Post Office Square.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who took a piece of Beacon Capital's private offering
this spring bought into a blind pool. There was no real estate,
just a pile of money from the offering and a management group
prepared to invest it.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they have spent a lot of it in East Cambridge, Mass.,
including $123 million for Technology Square, a group of buildings
whose current tenants are Polaroid Corp. and the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Square is the kind of property Beacon Capital has
been seeking: real estate with expiring leases and value-added
potential. Leventhal thinks he can refurbish the buildings, which
currently command rents as low as $6 a foot, and lease them in the
$24 per foot range. The topper: Seller Prudential Insurance Co. of
America agreed to take $50 million of Beacon Capital stock as part
of the payment.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Beacon Capital deal, a $91 million purchase of office
and research buildings in suburban Dallas two weeks ago, brings the
spending total to about $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   Private REITs usually can borrow to pay for up to 60 percent of
their assets, which would allow Beacon Capital to buy about $1
billion of real estate before requiring a new round of funding.
Analysts presume that would be the time Leventhal would want to go
public, if public REIT stock prices were strong.
</P>
<P>
   Ask real estate analysts about Beacon Capital and they will
scratch their heads on one point: Why did Zell shell out billions
for Beacon Properties and not insist on some kind of noncompete
agreement to sideline Leventhal, who at one time was expected to
become a director of Equity Office Properties?
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal says Beacon Capital is no competition for Zell and
isn't even looking for the same kind of property. ``We're really
competing in a different niche in the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another point of view: Zell just wanted to buy Boston
Properties's assets and little else. ``He thought he would have to
give them jobs and was happy to find out he didn't have to,'' said
Fred Carr of the Penobscot Group, a real estate investment advisory
firm in Boston. ``Sam just breathed a big sigh of relief and did
the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
