<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-WORKERS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINORITIES AT FLORIDA PLANT SUE OCEAN SPRAY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; VERO BEACH, Fla. _ In this city of 17,000, where the
grapefruit crop is king, seasonal workers who pick, process, and
pack fruit make up a high concentration of the work force.
</P>
<P>
   As with the nation's 2 million farm workers, many live in
poverty, in a region whose pristine coast is lined with gated
mansions and luxurious retirement homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people for generations have been picking or processing
fruit here,'' said Milton Thomas, director of economic development
at the Vero Beach Chamber of Commerce. ``It is a way of life,
albeit a poor way of life, and it has been the norm.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a $3.5 million discrimination lawsuit that has shaken
officials at Massachusetts-based Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc., 34
African-Americans and one Hispanic say they are looking to the
legal system to change that norm. The group of current and former
employees alleges racial bias and sexual harassment by a company
that has been credited with setting labor standards in this rural
city 65 miles north of West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit has focused attention on the fine line &UR;  &LR; between
employment opportunities and exploitation in a region where the
only alternatives to processing or packing for undereducated
workers are low-paying jobs in the fields or in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed June 15 in federal court in Fort Lauderdale,
alleges that white workers with little or no education rarely
remain in menial positions, but are groomed for higher-paying work
while their minority coworkers remain behind. It says the plant has
had only one minority manager in its 20-year history _ an
African-American male who quit after about 15 months on the job.
And it accuses a white manager of groping five black women and
threatening their jobs if they complained.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by the accusations, Ocean Spray last month dispatched
Annmarie Lewis, corporate human resources manager, from its
Lakeville, Mass. headquarters to look into the claims. She
concluded that some of the plaintiffs have themselves been
promoted. But plaintiffs contend that despite these promotions, no
minorities hold jobs paying $13 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The company also noted that it has a system for reporting
harassment complaints, but that the women did not use it.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit notwithstanding, Ocean Spray, a privately &UR;  &LR; held
growers' cooperative with $1.44 billion in 1997 revenues, is known
in Vero Beach for good benefits and competitive wages. Company
supporters say that during peak grapefruit picking season, from
September through May, an entry-level worker &UR;  &LR; can earn more than
$21,000 including overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small plant and (managerial and skilled) positions
do not open up often,'' said Lewis. ``We've recently filled a
position with a black candidate who will be a trainer.... These
allegations are not true.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit against Ocean Spray is hardly the first to take an
employer to task &UR;  &LR; in Indian River County. A flurry of civil-rights
suits have been filed recently against companies and
municipalities, including telephone company BellSouth and Subway
sandwich shops. The cases suggest a rising militancy among workers
who see few opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Local officials point to what they call the guerilla tactics
of a Fort Lauderdale attorney as the source of employers' recent
legal challenges; African-Americans in neighboring communities
contend people simply want their due.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray's Vero Beach plant employs 75 people year-round,
including 15 minorities. At peak grapefruit season, its work force
swells 60 percent to 120, representing the addition of a seasonal
work force, mostly black, that returns year after year.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs, both full time and seasonal, contend there are no
minority electricians, waste-water operators, or A-level mechanics,
whose starting hourly wages range from $13.37 to $14.94. Company
officials argue there are only seven or eight of those coveted
positions, and once people are promoted or hired to fill such
posts, few leave.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-acre site on which Ocean Spray built its citrus division
20 years ago is a tranquil spot, surrounded by citrus groves,
cabbage palm, and turkey oak laced with Spanish moss. Drive east,
toward the coast, and the region's wealth is apparent. There, along
the Treasure Coast, in a county that produces 30 percent of the
world's fresh grapefruit and most of the nation's grapefruit
concentrate, prosperity reigns.
</P>
<P>
   Turn west, past the citrus groves into the unincorporated city
of Gifford, and the scene changes. The city, home to some seasonal
workers, stands in stark contrast to the fashionable condominiums
and elegant stucco homes along the Atlantic coast. Shabby trailers
and modest houses dot the streets of this community of 8,000 whose
dusty walks recall an earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While development companies and agricultural expansion have
transformed large sections of Indian River County, turning a mostly
rural region into a big player in the global fruit market, Gifford
has stayed pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   Said the chamber's Thomas: ``The area known as Gifford is
probably more like it was in 1956 than any other place in'' the
county.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Ocean Spray, employees seem to be of two minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working here nine years, and there's bad and there's
good,'' said Milton Johnson, a blender in his early 30s. ``That
doesn't mean things can't be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
