<HEADLINE>
SAILORS' SPIRITS ARE HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT   AND BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whitney Connor and Elizabeth Kratzig, the Olympic sailing
hopefuls from Mystic, Conn., are back from two months of racing and
training in Europe, not with wins, but with a lot of confidence
from what they called ``world-class competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel really good,'' said Kratzig. ``This is the first time
we have competed in big European regattas, so we accomplished what
we went over to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, she said, that meant checking out their new 470 sailboat
that they had never raced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of changes in the sail and mast setup that made
a big impact on or speed, so at the end we were going really
fast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The two, whose goal is to compete in the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney, also had a chance to work on their large-fleet skills.
``Regattas in the US only have about 25 boats, but in Europe they
have 60 or more so you have to change tactics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kratzig said the biggest win was at the Regatta Week in Kiel,
Germany, where the team finished 10th overall out of 60 boats. To
top it off, Kratzig said, ``the Ukrainian women were ranked number
one, and we forced them to tack away.''
</P>
<P>
   The team is back in the US for more training, before they resume
racing at the end of the summer _ first to Spain for the World
Championships, then to Florida for the ``pre-pre'' Olympic trials,
then to Australia in December and January for three regattas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wolters on way back
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kara Wolters, who averaged 9.8 points and 5.2 rebounds last fall
in her rookie season with the ABL's New England Blizzard, is
expected to be back to full strength by the time training camp
opens on Sept. 28. After helping the US Women's National Team to a
gold medal in the World Championships in June, Wolters underwent
surgery on July 2 to tighten ligaments in her left shoulder, which
should keep that shoulder from popping out of joint. Wolters had
the same surgery on her right shoulder before her freshman year at
the University of Connecticut, so says of her recovery, ``I know
what to expect.'' ... Joan Benoit Samuelson and Kathrine Switzer
were two of the inaugual inductees last weekend to the Distance
Running Hall of Fame in Utica, N.Y. Samuelson, the 1984 Olympic
gold medalist in the marathon, and Switzer, the first official
female entrant in the Boston Marathon in 1967 and a promoter of
women's running ever since, were joined by marathoners Bill
Rodgers, Frank Shorter and 79-year-old Ted Corbitt, a 1952 Olympian
and later an ultramarathoner. For 21 years, the city has hosted the
Utica Boilermaker road race, the largest 15-kilometer road race in
the country ... Jean Clark, a freshman forward for the University
of Connecticut women's basketball team who missed most of the
season because of chronic stress fractures in both legs, is going
back home to California and will not return to the team ... Tracy
Ducar, a 1991 graduate of North Andover High who was a standout
goalkeeper there and for perennial national champion North
Carolina, will back up University of Massachusetts grad Brianna
Scurry when the US Women's National Team plays in the upcoming
Goodwill Games ... The second annual Crusade for Health night
features the 11-1 Boston Renegades vs. the Atlanta Classics at 7:30
p.m. Friday at Bowditch Field in Framingham. The program, sponsored
by MetroWest Medical Center, aims to help preteens make healthy
lifestyle choices. Call 508-870-0057 for tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
