<SLUG> BC-WOM-WITTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC SPEEDSKATER CHRIS WITTY NOW A WORLD-CLASS CYCLIST, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The track is the same oval shape.
</P>
<P>
   The race is at the same breakneck speed.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes pull energy from the same muscle group _ the
quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   So Chris Witty, who has a world record and two Olympic medals in
speedskating, figured, what the heck? Why not give bicycle racing
on the track a try?
</P>
<P>
   She has, and now is on her way to showing up at the Olympics
again _ this time in Sydney, in the year 2000, and wearing racing
shorts instead of a skinsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Cycling isn't a new sport to Witty, who has used it as
cross-training to complement her speedskating. But it's taken a
back seat the last two years, when she was understandably devoted
to her winter sport. She set a world record in the 1,000-meter
speedskating race in Calgary in November 1997, then she went on to
win silver and bronze medals in the Olympics in Nagano in February.
(Her 1,000-meter world record remained intact, because even the
gold medalist couldn't break it.)
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to the spring: Witty has again traded her blades
for wheels and moved inside to compete on the velodrome, a steeply
banked bicycle track.
</P>
<P>
   After the Olympics, Witty raced in two World Cup bike races in
Europe, and finished in the top 10 in both. In a national
competition in Indianapolis in May, she won both the 500-meter race
and the match sprint. She finished the season earlier this month by
winning the 500-meter race at the National Championships in Frisco,
Texas, and finishing second in the match-sprint race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of rested for a few days (after the nationals) and am
just taking a break,'' Witty said last week from her home in Corona
Del Mar, Calif. Well, resting except for a quick jaunt up to
Calgary this week to get a little skating in before the cycling
events in the Goodwill Games July 25-26 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's on to the World Championships in Bordeaux, France, at
the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   So don't for a minute put Witty in the same class as basketball
superstar Michael Jordan, who tried his hand at minor league
baseball four years ago before returning to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, speedskating and bicycle racing seem to have had a
natural symbiotic relationship over the years. Of the eight
althetes who were two-sport Olympians, four were competitors in
bicycling (summer games) and skating (winter games). The
double-dippers included Connie Carpenter Phinney, the late Art
Longsjo, Arnold Uhrlass, and Connie Paraskevin-Young. Five-time
gold medalist speedskater Eric Heiden made the 1980 Olympic bike
racing team as an alternate (the US boycotted the Moscow games that
year), and went on to compete in the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Witty, 23, almost made it to the Summer Olympics in 1996, but
she was only chosen as an alternate after being edged out by
Paraskevin-Young. No hard feelings, though: Paraskevin-Young is now
Witty's coach.
</P>
<P>
   Witty said that even though she started skating when she was 8,
it wasn't until she was 16 that she devoted more time to cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been used for cross-training in the summer,
because they didn't have indoor ice, and you use the same quad
muscles,'' she said. ``A lot of the leg and lower-body strength is
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But the strategies, she said, are not at all similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very different, because in the match sprint in
cycling I'm going against somebody,'' Witty said. ``On the ice, I'm
just racing against the clock ... all the events are time-trial
events, so you have that time-trial mentality and preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Paraskevin-Young, whose husband Roger met Witty in 1992 when he
was coach of her junior worlds team, said she thinks the winter
Olympian is definitely on track for the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot has happened since (Chris started),'' said
Paraskevin-Young. ``She's matured mentally and physcially, and that
will continue. She's already at the Olympic level, so with an
athlete like that it's a matter of where and how she chooses to
spend her time and energy.''
</P>
<P>
   And the beauty, she said, is now thatthe Summer and Winter
Olympics are staggered to be held every two years, Witty has a
break of four years between each event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is a different ballgame now,'' said
Paraskevin-Young. ``Sure, it was done in the past, but it was more
difficult when you had Olympics in the same year.'' Which is
probably why, of all the eight dual US Olympians, only one _ Eddie
Eagan _ medaled in two sports (he had a gold for boxing in 1920,
and a gold in the bobsled in 1932).
</P>
<P>
   Witty, an admitted nonstop athlete, said she uses the gap not to
slack off, but to develop another sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good they are staggered, so I can take a couple of years
to figure out the sport before the next Olympics,'' she said. If
there's any downside, she said, it's that competing year-round
means she has little time to take a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's difficult mentally, especially because you have
to travel so much that you're never home,'' said Witty, who last
visited her parents and three brothers in April in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   No argument from Paraskevin-Young, who bagged skating when she
grew weary of the nonstop competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly why I quit, I wanted an offseason,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
