<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTWOOD IS BRITISH OPEN HEIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Lee Westwood is the rising star of European
golf, perhaps the next Nick Faldo. The English have adopted him as
their new patron saint, a player who has casually stepped to the
forefront as Faldo struggles to regain the form that lifted him to
No. 1 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Just examine the recent record. Westwood has wandered around the
globe, winning seven times in seven countries since October.
</P>
<P>
   This is similar to the diversity exhibited by Ernie Els, who has
won the US Open twice in the past four years. It's the form showed
at Royal Birkdale 22 years ago by young Seve Ballesteros, who
stamped his imprint on the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   Just three months past his 25th birthday, Westwood is England's
new star, the latest in a succession that includes Tony Jacklin,
Sandy Lyle, and Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Will Westwood take his anticipated place in the world order as
the 127th British Open begins Thursday at the windy Lancashire
links hard by the Irish Sea? He has won in Spain, Japan, Australia,
the United States, Germany, England, and, most recently, Scotland,
where he prevailed by four shots in the Loch Lomond tournament
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a man confident enough to break the hoodoo that
has prevented any golfer in Europe from winning the event before
the Open and then the Open itself, it is Westwood, whose confidence
is one of the most striking of his characteristics,'' wrote John
Hopkins in The Times Tuesdayof London Tuesday. ``He looks
questioners straight in the eye, speaks his mind and demonstrates a
maturity and composure that are far beyond many of his age.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood's win at Loch Lomond elevated him to No. 7 on the world
list as he displaced Colin Montgomerie atop the European Tour
rankings, where Montgomerie has reigned for five years. Westwood,
who grew up in the small town of Worksop near Nottingham about a
two-hour drive from Royal Birkdale in the British Midlands, handles
questions easily and has savvy that belies his boyish looks.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a British writer Tuesday if he reads all his
mounting press clippings, Westwood said he does. He also indicated
that he ``has a list'' of those who write negatively about him.
``You're not on it,'' he said to the writer. ``Yet.''
</P>
<P>
   How high are his expectations here? ``I don't have any
expectations, really,'' answered Westwood. Tuesday ``I treat it
like any other tournament. First, I try to make the cut. If I'm in
there with a chance on Sunday, I'll give it a go. If I do get the
opportunity, I hope to take it. I just try and not make any stupid
mistakes. I've been in contention. I would say I've won more
tournaments when I've been in contention than I've lost. I've been
in four playoffs and I've won three of them, so ...''
</P>
<P>
   This is why Jose Maria Olazabal of Spain, who was on the
victorious European Ryder Cup team with Westwood last fall, has
commented on his demeanor. ``When I look at him, I think first of
his composure,'' said Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Westwood can hammer drives, play aggressively on and near the
greens, and is prepared to define his career in terms of winning
major championships. ``I won't be nervous coming down the stretch
if I'm leading,'' said Westwood, who would be the first from Great
Britain to win at Royal Birkdale, which is hosting its eighth Open
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid of winning. I'm not afraid of losing. If I
don't win the Open this year, it won't be the end of the world to
me. I would dearly love to win it, but it's not life-and-death.
It's only a game at the end of the day. I've sacrificed quite a lot
of things already. This is my ultimate aim _ to be No. 1. You know,
sacrificing going out getting drunk on a Friday night with the lads
isn't a lot to sacrifice. I can save a few quid as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood, who won at New Orleans the week before the Masters,
loves links-styled courses. ``I would like to see us play more
links golf,'' he said. ``I had a pretty good record when I was an
amateur on links courses. I think we should probably play more of
them. I think most of the Europeans have played so many in the past
that you never really forget how to play links golf. It's either
suited to your game or it's not. I'm trying to go into it positive,
thinking I can play links golf.''
</P>
<P>
   As Montgomerie has said, Westwood ``has become the man to beat
at every tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Westwood is taking it all in stride. ``Nothing bothers me,'' he
said. ``There's more media attention. I was 12th in the world last
week. I'm seventh this week. It's too short a time spell to treat
it differently. I'm still the same person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
