<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-WORKERS-2     07-15 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-SPRAY-WORKERS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 VERO BEACH, Fla.: ... can't be changed.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Added Charles Huntington, 28, another blender: ``It's a good
place, and just like any other place, we have problems, but we
always get over them.''
</P>
<P>
   The two full-time workers, covered in protective overalls and
hardhats, blend tons of ripe grapefruit each day using high-tech
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   During peak grapefruit season, trucks laden with fruit roll into
the company yard. There, ``kickers'' board trucks and literally
kick remaining fruit from the back of the vehicle onto a chute. The
grapefruit then pass along a conveyor belt, where ``graders'' check
for blemishes and rot, and cleanup crews clear the floors of rotten
grapefruit pulp and rind. According to the plantiffs, most of
these &UR;  &LR; workers are minorities. &UR;  &LR; The company said it could not
confirm the racial breakdown of employees.
</P>
<P>
   It is this alleged division of labor that has sparked tensions
at Ocean Spray's citrus division, causing African-American workers
to allege in the 27-page complaint that ``blacks are employed in
only dangerous and back-breaking positions regardless of experience
and seniority.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a problem, we want to fix it,'' Nancy McDermott,
senior vice president for company operations and human resources,
said from Ocean Spray's satellite office in Plymouth, Mass. ``We're
frustrated. We do not know the truth. As best as we can determine,
there are no records of people coming forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Lockhart, one of the plaintiffs, claims he came forward
many times but no one listened. A 20-year employee who started as a
fruit kicker, Lockhart, 44, alleges he performed just about every
job at the plant during his tenure but his efforts were
unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even worked as a supervisor for second shift for two years,
but I never got the title of supervisor or the pay,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart admits that his responsibilities _ and his wages _ have
increased over time, from $5 per hour as a fruit kicker in 1978 to
$12.45 per hour today as a production coordinator. And although
Lockhart describes himself as the highest-paid African-American
employee at the citrus plant, there is more bitterness than pride
in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   A high &UR;  &LR; school graduate who says he was a supervisor in the
military, Lockhart alleges that a white worker who did not have a
diploma or Lockhart's experience was groomed by management for a
supervisory job and promoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had this job I'm in now for six years, but I want to move
up,'' he said. ``I'd like to be a full supervisor.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ike Jones has a similar story to tell. He started at the
company 12 years ago, fresh out of high school. Although Jones, 29,
of Fort Pierce, now works as a shipping clerk, he says he has
watched white workers with less on-the-job experience move further
in less time.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also accuses a white manager, identified in court
papers as Michael Saunders, of touching and making lewd remarks to
five African-American women and then threatening them with job loss
if they complained.
</P>
<P>
   Said Natalie Camper, a Massachusetts workplace expert who has
conducted diversity and sexual harassment training at Vero Beach
and other Ocean Spray plants: ``I can't imagine (Ocean Spray
making) many stupid responses to (employee) complaints at that
plant because everybody there has been educated.''
</P>
<P>
   But a second lawsuit filed in a Florida state court by Diane
Hinton, 44, of Wabasso, alleges she was threatened with loss of her
job in 1996 after complaining that Saunders had grabbed her
breasts. Saunders was later fired, according to the plaintiffs'
Fort Lauderdale lawyer, Barry Mandelkorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Saunders chose to resign in May,'' insists Ocean Spray's
Lewis. Saunders could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray officials argue all was quiet until six months ago,
when the company received a telephone call from Norman Ganz, a Fort
Lauderdale lawyer who has filed at least nine discrimination suits
against employers in the Indian River County area. The Ocean Spray
action brings that number to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray's McDermott says the company began negotiating with
Ganz but broke off talks when it became apparent that ``we would
not be allowed to talk to employees and really get to the bottom of
the charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers say the company offered a monetary settlement _ if the
plaintiffs resigned. After declining the offer, the plaintiffs
filed in federal court. They also retained Mandelkorn, another Fort
Lauderdale lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The switch in attorneys occurred after a federal magistrate in
the spring recommended that a US district judge fine Ganz $116,000
for ``guerrilla litigation'' and ``terrorist tactics'' in a
civil-rights lawsuit he brought against Subway.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say Ganz built a lucrative practice primarily with
civil-rights cases in a county still marked by both subtle and
not-so-subtle discrimination. And, they say, he commanded large
settlements by scaring employers into settling.
</P>
<P>
   Ganz, who has moved out of his Fort Lauderdale office, could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Ocean Spray plant won't say so directly, but
there is a general feeling there that the company's legal problems
were brought about by Ganz's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is very puzzling and confusing,'' said Ted
Kucinsky, the citrus division's plant manager. ``It really makes
you wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Gifford, Barbara King, 45, owner of Barbara King's
Beauty Supply Co., says she wasn't surprised by the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't go into a job expecting to stay at the bottom,''
King said from her perch behind the counter of her one-room stucco
shop along dusty Martin Luther King Blvd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
