NYT-07-15-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6044 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CZAR-ROYALTY-0716-COX     07-15 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZAR-ROYALTY-0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN A ROYAL TEST CASE, RUSSIAN 'PRINCE' SEEKS TO RECLAIM LOST
ESTATE
 &HT;    With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PETROVSKOYE, Russia _ Looking more like the servant than the
master of a Tolstoy novel, Yevgeny Meshchersky fingered his
moth-eaten trouser leg as he surveyed his ancestral home: a palace
with no roof, no windows and overgrown with summer weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Meshchersky moved his family onto the decaying estate outside
Moscow about 18 months ago in an act of defiant homesteading,
adopting the title of prince but the life of a pauper.
</P>
<P>
   A former engineer in a Soviet-era ceramics factory in Ukraine,
Meshchersky, 47, claims direct lineage to one of old Russia's
prominent aristocratic families, whose tree reaches back some 800
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of my children is here on the land where their
ancestors are buried,'' he said as a July rainstorm pelted the
vegetable patch outside his broken-down mansion.
</P>
<P>
   He vows to restore the 18th-Century estate to its former glory
despite the Russian government, which contends he has no legal
rights to the property no matter what his last name.
</P>
<P>
   The lot of Russia's former nobility has gained renewed attention
with this week's controversy-tainted burial of the nation's last
czar, Nicholas II, and his family in St. Petersburg, 80 years after
their murder by a Bolshevik firing squad.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Soviet Union disintegrated in 1991, the descendants of
Russia's imperial ruling class have made a half-hearted comeback
attempt. In a country where the Communist Party remains a political
power, nobility has delicately articulated its legal rights and
social standing taken in the Bolshevik revolution of 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few like Meshchersky are trying to assert their
birthright in concrete terms.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Nobility Assembly, established in 1990, now counts
10,000 registered members in Russia and estimates that there are
another 100,000 Russians with lineage to the bygone bluebloods --
in a country of 147 million. Another 20,000 to 50,000 Russian
nobility live abroad, according to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group, which supports the establishment of a
constitutional monarchy in Russia, are assisting Meshchersky in his
test case.
</P>
<P>
   Post-communist Russia has not yet enacted any significant
restitution laws regarding the era of Soviet rule. Lower courts
have rejected Meshchersky's claims to the land. His case is now
before the supreme court.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the burial of the czar's remains isn't as simple as
putting some bones in the ground, Meshchersky's land grab has
implications beyond mere property law. At issue is what role, if
any, nobility should play in the new Russian democracy and who
rightfully owns much of the land in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Moscow Times warned in an editorial that
Meshchersky's case could set a dangerous precedent. ``Russia simply
cannot afford the instability that would result'' if he won his
case, the newspaper said. ``Where would it end?''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the sensitive question of Russia's royalty and
their place in society, neither President Boris Yeltsin nor
Patriarch Alexy II, head of Russian Orthodox Church, plan to be at
the burial of the last czar on Friday. Neither will some of the
more prominent direct descendants from the Romanov family in a
dispute over whether the bones have been correctly identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicholas II was not a good czar and he betrayed his people.
But our predecessors swore an oath to him, and so we must pay him a
final tribute,'' Meshchersky said. ``I think the president and the
patriarch are betraying the memory of the czar.''
</P>
<P>
   A serious public debate on restoring the monarchy in Russia is
premature, said Prince Nikolai Romanov, head of the Association of
the House of the Romanovs, a group of descendants of Nicholas II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia is facing now numerous other problems that need to be
considered, and are acute,'' he told a news conference in St.
Petersburg earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Meshchersky calls for restoring the ``ancient traditions''
and he presumes to act as lord of the manor for the village of
Alabino, which has spilled onto his family lands in the eight
decades since his family fled it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the right to act as judge and peacemaker for the people
here,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   With a hint of sarcasm, many villagers refer to him as prince.
Yet few seem to oppose his effort to claim the estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problems with the prince. If he thinks he has
rights to the land, he should take it. Who knows these days, maybe
I could find documents that I am a prince,'' quipped Nikolai
Dulnev, a 37-year-old laborer, as he emerged from the village's
grocery story.
</P>
<P>
   Meshchersky maintains a stiff upper lip, despite the miserable
conditions on the estate, which was completed in 1780 and abandoned
early in the Russian revolution by his great-grandfather and other
distant relatives.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family -- wife Ludmilla, and four children ages 20 to
5 -- live in one of four mansions that surround the central,
column-studded palace, which was largely destroyed when Red Army
soldiers bombed it to scavenge for building materials.
</P>
<P>
   In Communist times, one of the mansions served as the village
post office and for a few years housed medical staff who worked at
the local clinic. But largely they were flop houses for drunks, and
the land became a dumping ground for rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Meshchersky said it was painful to see the ruins for the first
time three years ago, but he proudly notes that more than 70 years
of neglect under Communism couldn't erase it entirely.
</P>
<P>
   History here is too deep, he said. Napoleon made his calamitous
retreat from Moscow on a road that ran near the estate, about 25
miles west of Moscow. Thirty French soldiers were held in the
stables as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you can't eat history and Meshchersky has been forced to
become a subsistence farmer in order to feed his family, who
endured a difficult winter. The building has only wood-burning
stoves and a makeshift electrical connection to run a few lights.
</P>
<P>
   Meshchersky vows to stay on, saying that ongoing occupancy of
the estate is crucial to his legal case and to his agenda for
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My genes allow me to run the country,'' he said. ``I know what
is needed for my lands, and I know what the country needs for its
rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
