<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-15 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ Senate Republicans produce
their HMO bill. Democrats hold a ``forum'' to tout their own
proposal as the president and the AMA meet to praise the Democratic
plan. And the AFL-CIO starts a TV ad campaign aimed at particular
districts. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RDP (Washington) _ A roundup of items items on the
House vote to ban transportation of minors across state lines to
get abortions, a Senate vote on restoring farm subsidies, a House
committee vote on census sampling, campaign finance votes in House,
and the Senate Intelligence committee questioning the head of the
Pentagon agency responsible for safeguarding technology exports.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RENO (Washington) _ The attorney general testifies
before the Senate Judiciary Committee, which asks her about
campaign finance, Secret Service, etc. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-THREAT (Washington) _ Speaker Gingrich and and Minority
Leader Gephardt announce the results from a bipartisan commission
studying national defenses against missile threats to United
States. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in Kenneth Starr's
investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   USAF-PILOT-TRAINING (Mt. Home, Idaho) _ All across the country
the Air Force is scrambling to find or expand the airspace and
bombing ranges they say they need to train their pilots. But the
Air Force's plans are running into fierce opposition from ranchers,
environmentalists, Shoshone-Paiute Indians, commercial airlines and
people settling in fast-growing metropolitan centers, especially
out West where neighborhoods refuse to tolerate low-flying jets and
sonic booms that crack windows. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT (Dallas) _ Record heat continues in Dallas, with 49
deaths in Texas and surrounding states attributed to temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-THREAPY (Undated) _ Tests on mice show that
Angiostatin, which blocks formation of blood vessels that feed
tumors, is far more effective in combination with radiation
treatment than when used alone. The researchers say this could lead
to a ``clinically feasible'' treatment strategy that could be
particularly useful in brain, head and neck cancers. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ In the wake of the an IMF accord, the
Russian Parliament begins its debate of measures aimed at easing
the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-IMF (Washington) _ Republicans, under pressure, vote in
committee on various proposals to get some money to the IMF. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND (Belfast) _ Irish developments following the funeral of
the three young boys killed in an arson fire. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-CEASEFIRE (Nairobi) _ The Sudan People's Liberation Army
declares a three-month cease-fire in southwest Sudan to allow
deliveries of relief food to hundreds of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FORD-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Ford's profit rose 6.7 percent in the
second quarter, topping estimates, as strong sales of high-profit
vehicles in North America and aggressive cost reductions helped the
company set a quarterly record for automobile earnings. By Barnaby
J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Apple will report earnings this
afternoon and is expected to announce a result of 33 cents a share.
By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Compaq posts an operating profit of
2 cents a share for the latest quarter, better than the
expectations of analysts, who had predicted the company would only
break even. The earnings include two weeks of results from Digital
Equipment, which Compaq acquired June 11. Including charges for
firing workers and restructuring, Compaq had a loss of $2.33 a
share. During the quarter, Compaq struggled to reduce inventory
while price cutting ate away most of its profit. By Lawrence M.
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Kodak posts a 35 percent gain in net
income, reversing a six-quarter earnings decline, aided by cost
cuts, which offset lower revenue. Excluding a charge, profit was
$1.38 a share, well above expectations. The stock jumps as much as
10 percent. By Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
