<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FEC-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        BERKLEY LEADS MONEY RACE IN CONGRESSIONAL CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 15 -- Despite an embarrassing admission last
month that she told her former boss at the Las Vegas Sands Casino
to do favors for local politicians, Nevada Democrat Shelley Berkley
is winning the race that fuels successful congressional campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley, a University of Nevada regent, is among 12 candidates
vying to fill the Las Vegas congressional seat being vacated by
two-term Rep. John Ensign, R-Nev. Ensign is leaving the 1st
District post this year to challenge Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Some political pundits speculated that Berkley, the heir
apparent to fill Ensign's seat, was politically damaged after she
admitted in June to telling a former casino executive to do favors
for Las Vegas politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley told Las Vegas Sands Chairman Sheldon Adelson in a 1996
memo that he should contribute to the political campaigns of local
judges because they would return the favor. Adelson criticized her
for suggesting the contributions.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, Berkley was secretly tape recorded by a friend
during a telephone conversation about her efforts to convince
Adelson to do favors for two local county commissioners, including
giving one a daiquiri concession and hiring the uncle of the other
to help obtain building permits for the construction of the $2
billion Venetian casino-hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But Berkley's admission doesn't seem to have hurt her
fund-raising ability. She has raised more than 10 times the amount
of money as her primary opponent and almost five times as much as
the two front-running candidates for the Republican nomination,
according to new financial disclosure reports due today at the
Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC reports detail how much money a candidate for federal
office has raised, who contributed and where the campaign funds
were spent. The FEC quarterly report covered the dates April 1
through June 30.
</P>
<P>
   While a well-funded campaign does not always guarantee a win,
money is needed to buy high-priced television advertising time.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley has raised about $354,000 this year, $179,000 of which
she collected in the last three months. Her fund-raising total has
hit $768,000, and she has $546,000 cash on hand. Berkley's
contributor list reads like a medical or law directory, although
she also received more than $12,000 in the past three months from
people associated with the hotel-and-casino industry.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the notable individual contributors to Berkley's
campaign include Las Vegas Dr. G. Michael Singh, $2,000, and MGM
Grand executive Alejandro Yemenidjian, $2,000. Berkley also
received $5,000 each from a number of political action committees
(PAC), including the United Steel Workers of America and the
Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   She also received $5,000 from Reid's Searchlight Leadership Fund
PAC and $1,000 from Massachusetts Democratic Rep. Barney Frank's
campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   Berkley's Democratic primary opponent, local hotel-casino
floorman Clay Baty, has raised a paltry $520 over the past three
months, bringing his year-to-date campaign fund raising total to
$3,520. Baty lists $1,500 cash on hand, nearly equal to the $1,155
in loans made to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The two front-runners for the GOP nomination, former Judge Don
Chairez and Prime Cable Account Executive Esther Quisenberry, are
neck-and-neck as they try to raise campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   Chairez has raised $81,000, all during the second quarter of
this year. He has spent very little on his campaign, presumably
saving it for a big television buy right before the primary.
Chairez has $77,000 cash on hand, including a $25,000 loan made to
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Quisenberry raised $52,000 during April, May and June -- giving
her a year-to-date total of $81,000. But Quisenberry has spent
$38,000, leaving her campaign with $43,000 cash on hand, a little
more than half of what Chairez has in the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
