<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-TV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV VIEWS SHOULD PREPARE FOR THE WORST THIS FALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Actors, producers, executives, flaks and other
television types are gathered in Pasadena, Calif., this month for
one reason: to descend upon TV critics and convince them that their
shows _ all of their shows _ are destined to be great hits.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of shows. That would be a lot of hits. But here is
a question from a newcomer: If all these shows are hits, where do
all the lame ones come from?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some of these bad shows look good on paper. Most turn out
to be merely bland _ think ``Step By Step'' _ which run their
course over several months or seasons without distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Some become epic failures, like ``Supertrain'' or ``Cop Rock''
or ``Hello, Larry,'' the vehicle MacLean Stevenson used to wreck
his career. There should be something in his honor, the MacLean
Stevenson (Memorial) Award for disastrous professional moves. Past
winners would include Wayne Rogers, Shelley Long, David Caruso and
this year's designee, Susan Molinari.
</P>
<P>
   While there are many good shows that fail for lack of audience
or backing (``Murder One,'' ``Nothing Sacred''), most cancellations
show some promise in production, but never mature artistically or
commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are those that don't have a shot, which begs the
question: ``What were the makers thinking?'' Brace yourself for
some scary bad shows coming out of California this fall.
</P>
<P>
   (``Fantasy Island''? ``Hollywood Squares''? Again? Can remakes
of ``Man From Atlantis'' and ``Holmes and Yoyo'' be far behind?)
</P>
<P>
   But these pale in comparison to The Worst Ever, the singular
show that can be identified objectively. The star was Jackie
Gleason. The show was ``You're in the Picture,'' born Jan. 20,
1961, died Jan. 20, 1961. It lasted only one episode.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1960, CBS had a bomb on its hands with its 9:30
p.m. Friday slot in ``Mr. Garlund,'' a tepid adventure starring the
unforgettable Charles Quinlivan (OK, I never heard of him, either).
Stories of intrigue around international business did not grab an
audience, even after the name was changed to ``The Garlund Touch''
a few months after its premiere. By January, the show was axed and
CBS had a half hour to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Who could fill it better than the star of ``The Jackie Gleason
Show'' and ``The Honeymooners''? Gleason could make people laugh
just staring into the camera. That would have made better
television than ``You're in the Picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Here was the premise. Four celebrity panelists _ Arthur
Treacher, Keenan Wynn, Pat Carroll and Jan Sterling _ stuck their
heads through cutouts (the kind you see at a fair or ballpark). The
difference was that the panelists didn't know what the scenes were
accompanying their faces. They would ask questions to host Gleason
who would provide clues. Once a cutout was identified, they moved
on to the next cutout.
</P>
<P>
   This was live television. The thought behind this was the witty
Gleason could ad-lib his way through a humorous half hour. It
turned out the only thing funny was that it ever got on the air.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, Gleason, apparently recovered from his brief bout
of insanity, did something brilliant: He said CBS blew it, and
apologized. ``Honesty is the best policy,'' he said. ``We had a
show last week that laid the biggest bomb. I've seen bombs in my
day, but this one made the H-bomb look like a two-inch salute.''
May the wretched shows that come out this fall die as noble a
death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
