A6086 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI &LR;      07-15 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CRITICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK LLOYD WRIGHT NEXT SUBJECT FOR KEN BURNS ON PBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Genius is a lot like spaghetti sauce.
Refreshing, piquant, and the thing that makes all the difference
between simple and simply divine. But sometimes it can be awfully
messy.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Lloyd Wright, always happy to admit his genius, was a
three-napkin mess maker in his personal life. America will soon
realize just how messy; Wright is the next entry in the Ken Burns
body of work on PBS (scheduled Nov. 10 and 11).
</P>
<P>
   Burns notes that the great architect once said he purposely
chose ``honest arrogance'' over ``hypocritical humility'' as the
guiding principle of his personality. To someone like Wright, a man
who abandoned his family and courted scandal the way most people
shop for groceries, honest humility wasn't even an option.
</P>
<P>
   Burns yesterday said Wright was American in every way _ ``a
perfect symbol of the genius, the conflict and the inspiration of
the century, what we call the American century.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour biography of Wright doesn't stint on the ugly
stuff, but Burns said questions about personality and art always
crop up when studying the lives of great individuals. He said the
good and the bad must be taken in balance. In other words, we don't
have to like the guy, but, Burns concluded: ``You stand in a Wright
building and it's like the difference between a guy who paints and
Rembrandt.''
</P>
<P>
   For a look at genius less messy, PBS's ``American Masters''
series profiles Leonard Bernstein (scheduled Oct. 28). Though
Bernstein had his moments of self-doubt and despair, his brother,
Burton, remembers him as a happy, curious musical genius. ``He was
omnivorous in his intellectuality and his love of everything,'' he
said. ``That is the key to Lenny.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's helpful hint: How to address a prince who also happens
to be a TV producer. Publicity material identifies Prince Edward,
seventh in line to the English throne, as Edward Windsor, founder
of Ardent Productions. PBS publicist Harry Forbes advised the
teeming masses of TV critics gathered in Pasadena that, in
addressing the prince, ``It's not Prince Edward, it's not Mr.
Windsor, it's just Edward.''
</P>
<P>
   Allrighty then. As for ``Crown and Country,'' a six-part
exploration of England's great historical sites, including a few to
which he was given extraordinary access, Edward didn't really say
much. Royal mum's the word, except for Edward's expectation that
Americans are willing to give him the benefit of any doubt about
his qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our country we just have hang-ups about titles, which I
don't think you have so much in this country,'' he said. ``So if I
come to this country and talk to people about producing programs,
people will just accept that that's what I'm here to talk about. In
Britain, if you've got a title, then you obviously don't have any
brains.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired of all those British accents on ``Masterpiece Theatre''?
PBS said it is creating ``Mobil Masterpiece Theatre's American
Collection'' to bring American literature to U.S. audiences. Nine
films over three years are on the drawing board, including Willa
Cather's ``The Song of the Lark'' and Langston Hughes' ``Cora
Unashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Network Television has signed Burt Reynolds to star in
three pictures about a tough but honest cop who is framed by his
department, goes to jail, gets out and goes searching for the only
witness who can clear him. Reynolds also directs the first of this
``Hard Time'' trilogy, due to premiere Dec. 13, and it's one of the
reasons he took the TNT offer.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said he's also indebted to Ted Turner for the fact that
young people seem to know who he is, even if they haven't seen
``Boogie Nights,'' the film that resurrected his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Turner seemed to have Clint Eastwood and Burt Reynolds
film festivals on the weekends,'' Reynolds said, ``and I feel very
grateful to him for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
