<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: 
 EXPERIENCING ITALY THROUGH STONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Ever since she was a mere 64 years old, Sylvia Jaffe has been
traveling to Pietrasanta, Italy, leading a group of fellow
sculptors to ply their art where Michelangelo once worked his magic
in marble.
 &HT;    Jaffe is a sculptor/instructor at the Boca Raton Museum of Art
in Florida, who again will lead a group of artists to the Tuscany
region of Italy in August and September.
 &HT;    She has had students as young as 30 and as old at 93 with skill
levels of all ranges, including beginner.
 &HT;    She has spent 20 summers in Pietrasanta, as she says, ``learning
from master artisans and inspired by the mountains of stone around
me ...
 &HT;    ``This is not a package trip,'' Jaffe stresses. But she has made
arrangements for the students to stay in one of two Pietrasanta
hotels and to work in a fully equipped marble studio five days a
week.
 &HT;    ``We share the cost of renting cars while in Italy,'' she says.
``On weekends we travel to nearby cities and towns where we visit
museums, churches and other points of interest. Sometimes during
the week we break early for a picnic or take walking tours of other
artists' studios. This year's itinerary includes a two-day trip to
Rome.''
 &HT;    Students will select their own stones, which are cut to size and
placed on their own personal work tables for the 20 working days.
 &HT;    Trained artisans are available to the students. Spouses who
don't participate can make use of nearby golf courses, tennis
courts or swimming pool. Sometimes they join painting workshops.
 &HT;    Those involved in past workshops speak highly of the experience.
``The weeks spent in Pietrasanta were the epitome of intense work
and enjoyment,'' says former student Victor Gross. ``From the
morning carving, to the group lunch, to the afternoon working, to
the good food and wine, what could be better?''
 &HT;    The total cost of Jaffe's workshop _ including tuition, studio,
accommodations and airfare _ is about $6,000 for the month. For
details, call (561) 394-3284 or visit
www.powersite.net/web/sculpture on the Web.
 &HT;    
 ANOTHER ITALY  
 &HT;    The Frontiers tour company is offering a trip that mature
traveler are sure to love: ``World War II Battlefields, Gardens and
Antiquities,'' from Sept. 25 to Oct. 4.
 &HT;    The area between Rome and Naples is where the U.S. and Allied
armies fought arduous battles during World War II, but it also
contains celebrated gardens, classic antiquities and picturesque
villages such as Ravellow.
 &HT;    Brig. Gen. Christopher Dunphie, military historian, author and
lecturer at Military Staff College, is the host of this tour that
also explores three key battle sites: the Salerno beaches, the
Monte Cassino Monastery and the Anzio Break-out.
 &HT;    The estimated price is $6,500, double. For more information,
call (800) 245-1950.
 &HT;    
 ALL-ABOARD DISCOUNTS  
 &HT;    _ The Verde Canyon Railroad, (800) 293-7245, located in
Clarksdale, Ariz., gives mature travelers a $3 discount off its
usual adult coach fare of $36 for its four-hour tour of the scenic
Verde Canyon.
 &HT;    _ The Mt. Hood Railway and dinner excursion train, which
operates out of Hood River about 60 miles east of Portland, Ore.,
offers seniors a $3 discount off its normal $22.95 excursion rate
and $3 off its $24.95 special-events rate.
 &HT;    Special events go on all summer and include exciting staged
train robberies, apple festivals and a Native American celebration.
Call (800) 872-4661 for details.
 &HT;    
 CRUISING ALONG  
 &HT;    In New York City, a Circle Line cruise of New York Harbor is a
must for any visitor. The full island cruise costs mature travelers
just $16, about $6 off the regular price.
 &HT;    All cruises, including the Sunset/Harbor Lights Cruise, offer
senior discounts. These leave from Pier 83 at W. 42nd St.
 &HT;    Also planned this year are specialty cruises to Bear Mountain
State Park. For more information, call (212) 563-3200.
 &HT;    _ Join a Bat Watching Excursion with Capital Cruises in Austin,
Texas. Seniors pay $6.50 compared to the usual price of $8 for the
hour-long tour that leaves from the Capital Cruise Dock on
Town-Lake Road. For more information, call (512) 480-9264.
 &HT;    
 AN OLYMPIC DEAL  
 &HT;    The Inn at Jim Thorpe, named for the Olympic Pentathlon athlete,
is nestled in the foothills of the Poconos and is also the home of
some good deals for seniors ages 55 and older.
 &HT;    The Discover Jim Thorpe package offered by the inn, (800)
329-2599, includes accommodations for two nights, continental
breakfast, dinner for two on one night and admission to several
local historical sites, including the Asa Packer Mansion and Old
Jail.
 &HT;    Prices range from $169 for a standard room to $255 for a suite.
 &HT;    If you prefer a straight discount without the extras, you can
rent a room for 30 percent off the rack rates, which range from $65
to $250 midweek (Sunday through Thursday).
 &HT;    
 MARINE WORLD  
 &HT;    Visitors ages 60 and older save $5 off the $29 admission to the
new Marine World Theme Park (formerly Marine World Africa USA) in
Vallejo, Calif., 30 miles northeast of San Francisco.
 &HT;    The remodeled, refurbished park offers 16 new rides, Dolphin
Harbor to showcase seven bottlenose dolphins and a high-action
stunt show called ``The Curse of the Lost City.''
 &HT;    Travel to the park is possible aboard Amtrak, Gray Line, the Bay
Area Rapid Transit or on the Blue &AMP; Gold Fleet from San Francisco.
For more information, call (707) 643-6722.
 ----- 
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Gene and
Adele Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St.,
14th Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send the Malotts a postcard from
your trip with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you
find for seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to the Malotts by electronic mail.
The address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on
your keyboard.)
 &HT;    _______ 
 &HT;     (The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
