<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-A-WASHINGTON-SUMMER-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    TWO COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By DAVID E. SANGER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Washington has always been a city of multiple personalities.
 &HT;    There is monumental Washington, the mecca for tourists who line
up for the White House tour, wander the statue-lined halls of
Congress and cram the National Air and Space Museum.
 &HT;    There is green Washington, the leafy parks and residential
neighborhoods of Northwest, and the jogging routes through Rock
Creek Park and along the C&AMP;O Canal.
 &HT;    And there is dysfunctional Washington, the world's most famously
mismanaged capital, parts of which are plagued by crime, troubled
schools and deeply impoverished neighborhoods where few tour buses
stray.
 &HT;    But this city of a thousand movie scenes defies typecasting. In
a long afternoon stroll, it is easy to move from the new Franklin
D. Roosevelt Memorial, past the Watergate (known to a new
generation of scandal buffs as the home of Monica Lewinsky), up
through Georgetown and into the woods near the vice president's
official residence. There, deer still wander, only three miles from
the White House.
 &HT;    In the summer, Washington changes hands. Congress is itching to
get out by late July, and by early August, the Red Line, the subway
artery for the city's standing army of lawyers, deal makers,
journalists and bureaucrats, is overrun by tourists headed for the
Mall and the National Zoo. (Alas, only one of the city's two famous
pandas has survived the rigors of Washington life.)
 &HT;    For visitors, getting in and out of Washington is becoming
easier. The recently renamed Washington Reagan National Airport
finally has its new (if somewhat garish) main terminal, and without
stepping outside, you can catch Metro trains to downtown. But for
cheaper airfares, check out the more-distant Baltimore-Washington
Airport.
 &HT;    For train travelers, Amtrak lowers rates in summer (especially
for kids) and it drops you exactly where you want to be: the
refurbished Union Station, within sight of Capitol Hill. The
station is filled with boutiques and places to eat, and is a
retreat from the Washington heat.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    For a touch of 1870s Paris, the National Gallery's East Building
is presenting ``Manet, Monet, and the Gare St.-Lazare,'' through
Sept. 20.
 &HT;    Some of the paintings are familiar: the eerie ``Chemin de Fer''
along with 19 other of Manet works, many inspired by scenes just
outside his studio. There are also 14 works by Monet, and five by
Gustav Caillebotte. Admission is free. Hours: Monday to Saturday 10
a.m. to 5 p.m., and Sunday 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Information: (202)
737-4215.
 &HT;    Just off the Mall, and into the air-conditioning, a visitor
might start at the National Portrait Gallery, Eighth and F Streets,
N.W., for ``Celebrity Caricature in America,'' a collection of
show-biz drawings by Al Hirschfeld, running till Aug. 23. Don't
miss the portrait of Babe Ruth.
 &HT;    Then drop in at the National Museum of American History, 14th
Street and Constitution Avenue, N.W., to check out the re-creation
of an El Monte, Calif., sweatshop, part of ``Between a Rock and a
Hard Place: A Dialogue on American Sweatshops,'' an exhibit through
Oct. 30 about how immigrants have been treated on American shores.
 &HT;    At the Freer Gallery of Art, on the Mall at 12th Street and
Jefferson Drive, there is a new exhibit of Islamic art, featuring
calligraphy from the Koran and manuscripts that date from the ninth
century. Calligraphy aficionados will also find early 17th-century
works from Kyoto, Japan. The Freer's permanent exhibit of Japanese
screens is among the best this side of the Pacific.
 &HT;    These museums are open 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. daily. Information:
(202) 357-2700.
 &HT;    From now until Oct. 24, the Folger Shakespeare Library, 201 East
Capitol St., S.E., is showing ``Papers and Porcelains,'' a
collection of late 18th- and 19th-century tinted sheets, pastoral
and military scenes. Open Monday to Saturday 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.;
(202) 544-7077.
 &HT;    Wolf Trap, the open-air concert center in nearby Vienna, Va.,
has a jammed summer schedule, ranging from jazz to Mozart. Mary
Chapin Carpenter sings on July 17, 18 and 19 at 8 p.m. ($30 and
$18), and Ray Charles on Aug. 11 ($27 and $16).
 &HT;    The Wolf Trap Opera Company turns to Mozart's ``Abduction From
the Seraglio'' on July 24, 26, and 28 ($45). It is the perfect
Washington opera: Nasty villains and a wise ruler who, in a
reminder of a less voluble age of government, sings not a word.
 &HT;    For tickets to any Wolf Trap performance and schedules, call
(800) 955-5566 from 10 a.m. to 9 p.m. daily, or visit
www.wolf-trap.org on the Web.
 &HT;    The fast way to Wolf Trap is the Orange Line to West Falls
Church, where a shuttle bus leaves every 20 minutes for $3.50 round
trip.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    The Smithsonian's Air and Space Museum has its usual permanent
array of aircraft and temporary shows.
 &HT;    The ``Star Wars: The Magic of Myth'' exhibit, on through
October, is free, but tickets must be picked up starting at 9:45
a.m. or in advance through Protix, (800) 529-2440, for a $3.25
service fee.
 &HT;    Anyone with a real aviation bug, however, should make it out to
the Garber Preservation, Restoration and Storage Facility in
Suitland, Md., east of the city. This is where the Smithsonian
keeps 90 percent of its aircraft and rockets, and where its staff
restores old planes, buffs up rocket engines and pieces together
propellers. Some buildings are open as a no-frill museum.
 &HT;    Reservations are required two weeks ahead for tours, at 10 a.m.
daily plus 1 p.m. on Saturday and Sunday, lasting three hours;
(202) 357-1400.
 &HT;    At the National Zoo, the 3000 block of Connecticut Avenue, N.W.,
just north of the Woodley-Zoo subway stop, Amazonia is a magical
rain forest complete with dense vines, vegetation and aquatic life
and plenty of microscopes for hands-on exhibits.
 &HT;    A new exhibit, ``Birds of Paradise Lost,'' is filled with song
birds from Hawaii, including the brilliant orange iiwi. The zoo is
open daily 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. in summer. Admission is free, but
parking costs $1 to $10; (202) 673-4800.
 &HT;    Some of the better hiking adventures are near downtown. My
4-year-old son, Andrew, delights in the paths, streams and old
stone bridges behind Dumbarton Oaks.
 &HT;    The museum, (202) 339-6400, with its collection of Byzantine and
pre-Columbian art, is open only from 2 to 5 p.m. Tuesday through
Sunday ($1 contribution) and the gardens 2 to 6 p.m. daily ($4
admission), but the paths, which reach down into Rock Creek Park,
are accessible any time from the back of Montrose Park, next to
Dumbarton Oaks on R Street in Georgetown.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    The Grand Hyatt, 1000 H St., N.W., near 11th Street, has 900
rooms and is well situated: above Metro Center, where all the
city's subways come together.
 &HT;    Summer rates range from $139 to $290 depending on availability,
based on double occupancy. It also has a series of good restaurants
in a cool atrium that is a popular escape from the summer heat;
(800) 233-1234, fax (202) 628-1641.
 &HT;    The Washington Westin, 2350 M St., N.W., is equidistant from
downtown and Georgetown and has 263 modern rooms. Summer rates are
$109 on weekends, $179 during the week. Try the Cafe on M for lunch
and the M Street Grill, by the inner courtyard, for more formal
fare; (800) 848-0016, fax (202) 857-0127.
 &HT;    Budget: Each of the 195 rooms has a full kitchen at the St.
James Hotel, 950 24th St., N.W., an all-suite hotel. Continental
breakfast is included, and there is a good outdoor pool. Rates
begin at $89 on the weekends, and $125 during the week. It is a
short walk to the Kennedy Center, and even shorter to the Foggy
Bottom Metro station; (800) 852-8512, fax (202) 466-6484.
 &HT;    Luxury: Hotel George, 15 E St., N.W., near North Capitol Street,
is a four-month-old 139-room luxury ultra-modern contemporary hotel
on Capital Hill, near Union Station. In July and August, rates are
reduced to $109 (from the usual $185 to $240), and suites start at
$200, including Continental breakfast and parking; (800) 576-8331,
fax (202) 347-4213.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    One of the best new restaurants in Washington is Greenwood at
Cleveland Park, 3529 Connecticut Ave., N.W., a small place named
for its chef, Carole Wagner Greenwood. It serves an eclectic mix of
California-style seasonal cuisine, like smoke salmon stack with
avocado goat cheese for an appetizer, and lightly grilled tuna
filet served very rare.
 &HT;    Dinner for two with a modest bottle of wine came to $96. Open
for dinner daily, except Monday; (202) 833-6572.
 &HT;    Citronelle, in the Latham Hotel at 3000 M St., N.W., in
Georgetown, is making a comeback after a total renovation. A former
assistant White House pastry chef, Ann Amernick, does the desserts.
 &HT;    Dinners run north of $70 to $75 a person with wine, but it's
worth it, and there is plenty of people-watching. Try the red
snapper or the lamb, and the almond polenta for dessert. Daily
dinner except Sunday; (202) 625-2150.
 &HT;    Great Japanese cuisine can be found in a tiny sliver of a
restaurant called Makoto, 4822 MacArthur Blvd., N.W., north of
Georgetown. It has a sushi bar tended by several chefs trained in
similarly wonderful holes-in-the-wall in Tokyo.
 &HT;    At the restaurant's four tables, you can get the chef's special
six- to 10-course meal for $38 a person. Closed Monday and for
lunch Sunday; (202) 298-6866.
 &HT;    There are plenty of vegetarian selections at the Lebanese
Taverna, 2641 Connecticut Ave., N.W. Try the mehshi bel zeit _
eggplant, zucchini and bell pepper stuffed with rice and spices.
There is pleasant sidewalk dining at lunch and dinner, but
reservations are available only to 6:30 p.m. Dinner is about $20 a
person, without drinks; (202) 265-8681.
 &HT;    Asian cuisine of all kinds can be found at Oodles Noodles,
downtown at 1120 19th St., N.W. The Malaysian shrimp is spicy and
the pad Thai is delicious. Lunch or dinner for two with drinks is
about $30; (202) 293-3138.
 &HT;     (David E. Sanger is a Washington correspondent for The
Times.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 David E. Sanger  
