<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CZAR-ROYALTY _ PETROVSKOYE, Russia _ This heir to Russian
royalty lives in a palace without a roof, with no windows and the
plumbing shot on an estate strewn with garbage. His government says
he has no legal claim to the property no matter what his last name.
Still, Yevgeny Meshchersky, 47, a former engineer in a ceramics
factory, remains wedded to his land and vows to restore the family
estate to its former elegance. Since the Soviet Union disintegrated
in 1991, royalty has made a half-hearted comeback in Russia,
seeking to reassert its legal rights and property taken in the
Bolshevik revolution of 1917. The lot of the Russian nobility and
their descendants has gained renewed attention with this week's
(Fri. July 17) burial of Russia's last czar, Nicholas II, and his
family. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH _ WASHINGTON _ A Senate Republican task force, responding
to the political potency of the health care issue, unveils its
version of ``patients' rights'' legislation to deal with consumer
complaints about the managed care industry. Democrats complain that
it omits a provision allowing patients to sue HMOs for medical
decisions that prove harmful, and that it includes tax-free
``medical savings accounts'' that some believe would lead people to
skimp on preventive care. Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, is a task force
member. (Harlan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-BUGS _ WASHINGTON _ The National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, which hopes during the next decade to retrieve
samples of the stuff asteroids, comets and other Solar System
objects are made of, had better be very careful to avoid
contaminating Earth with extraterrestial germs, a committee of the
National Academy of Sciences warns in a report being released
Wednesday. The chances of encountering outer space microbes are
very low, the committee said, but too little is known about some
asteroids to rule out the presence of life forms and two moons of
Jupiter _ Europa and Ganymede _ have ``significant potential'' of
harboring living entities. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 500).
</P>
<P>
   REINSURANCE _ WASHINGTON _ The House Banking and Financial
Services Committee meets Wednesday to mark up a bill that would
establish a federal program to provide reinsurance for state
disaster insurance programs. (Shook, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ Following sighting and manhunt for Eric Robert Rudolph
in the mountains of western North Carolina,. Rudolph is wanted by
the FBI for the bombing of an abortion cliknic in Birmingham and
three Atlanta bombings. (Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DRUGBUST _ FBI announces arrests and confiscation of a major
amount of drugs in Atlanta. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAACP NATIONAL CONVENTION
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore will announce
Thursday a $1.4 billion partnership between the U.S. Small Business
Administration and the NAACP as part of the White House's efforts
to greatly increase lending and spur economic development in the
African-American community. In addition, Gore announced a new pilot
loan program that will be test marketed in Atlanta, Austin, Fort
Lauderdale among other cities. His speech will be focused on
bridging the ``opportunity gap'' between whites and blacks. Will
also focus on what Gore's image is in the Civil Rights community.
(Carr, Cox News Service). 40.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-SPOTLIGHT16 _ ATLANTA _ Blacks and politics, advancing
Vice President Gore's speech on Thursday. Note that Wednesday
workshop is on ``The black vote, where is it?'' (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-NOTES16 _ ATLANTA _ Convention highlights, including Tavis
Smiley from BET, Benjamin Hooks. (RHill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10-15.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-FARM _ ATLANTA _ Story focusing about probably the plight
of the black farmer. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NAACP-DAY16_ ATLANTA _ The best of what's happened during the
day's events. (Oglesby, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MORIAL _ NEW ORLEANS _ This city is enjoying a renaissance _the
economy is recovering from the devastation of the oil bust, and
violent crime, the city's most nagging nemesis, is down
dramatically. Residents here give a much of the credit to Mayor
Marc Morial, the dapper, 40-year-old son of the city's first black
mayor, Dutch Morial, who served from 1978 to 1986. The younger
Morial is settling into his second term as mayor, a position given
to him in February by more than 80 percent of the voters. His
landslide victory was almost unprecedented here. A Q&AMP;A. (Rochell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY SERIES
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-SUSTAINABILITY _ How can we best prepare for tomorrow
in today's booming economy? President Clinton's Council on
Sustainable Development has become a blueprint for how things will
work in the 21st century. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-HOME _ How to cut down costs and improve the
environment in your home, such as installing water-saving plumbing
or lighting fixtures that use less energy. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily
News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-PROFILE _ Profile of Gary Couch, a former head of
development for General Motors who stepped down to pursue the
high-tech world of composites, viewed as a cutting-edge technology
that could put Dayton back in the forefront of automobile
manufacturing. (Dempsey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   PROSPERITY-US _ How we have changed. Today's subject: Gadgets.
They're everywhere. From cordless phones, fax machines, beepers,
etc., we have become slaves to our technological toys. (Dempsey,
Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   GOV-CAMPAIGN _ Gubernatorial candidates Garry Mauro and George
W. Bush file campaign expenditure reports, as do all other
statewide candidates. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HMO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Consumers apparently aren't as upset
with the treatment they get from health maintenance organizations
as some thought they were. Eight months after Texas started a
landmark independent review program for consumers who want to
dispute HMO treatment denials, only 147 complaints have been filed
with the Texas Department of Insurance. (Golz, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
