<P>
   NY-TUNJAV (New York) _ Some 6,000 people live in a 16-block
enclave hemmed in by the Lincoln Tunnel, the Jacob Javits
Convention Center and two of Manhattan's most famous boulevards,
34th Street and 42d Street: Macy's Row and, now, Disney Drive. And
the population is growing, slowly.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDOLINI-DESIGN (New York) _ Annette Roque, ``not an
off-the-rack kind of girl,'' has a not-off-the-rack apartment, too,
a two-bedroom penthouse in TriBeCa (view of the Woolworth Building
included) that is exotic without actually looking like Trader
Vic's, and has been swathed in an otherworldly collection of
fabrics by Muriel Brandolini. By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-CUP (Undated) _ As the final match of the 15th World Cup
was being played out in France on Sunday, a full third of the
planet's population tuned in to witness the host nation's
surprising capture of the most coveted trophy in the world: a
thick, drippy, solid-18-karat-gold abstraction of two Atlaslike
athletes shrugging the globe. Created by the Italian sculptor
Silvio Gazzanigga in 1974 to replace the original, which was
retired to Brasilia in 1970, the priceless Cup is passed like a
torch from victor to victor every four years. By Cathy Lang Ho.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-PACKAGES (Undated) _ Americans are used to big boxes
packed with cereal or cookies, but mostly with air. But it's a
surprise to see the same packaging strategy from the computer
industry, which constantly boasts of miracles of compression. Why
does a program such as Windows 98, recorded on a single CD-ROM,
arrive wrapped in a box that measures 8 inches by 10 inches by 2
inches and includes a manual, a clutch of coupons and a cardboard
stiffener folded with origami cleverness? By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-BOXWOODS (Oldwick, N.J.) _ Say ``boxwood,'' and what
comes to mind are Colonial Williamsburg's precise edgings, green
billows at English country houses _ in short, an air of tradition
and control. Boxwood has tempted the gardener's shears since
Egyptians first clipped formal hedges around 4000 B.C. By Mac
Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-GARDENERS (London) _ Exchanging guns and knives for
trowels and shovels, seven prisoners from HM Prison Leyhill in the
Cotswolds won their second gold medal last week at the Hampton
Court Palace Flower Show, the Royal Horticultural Society's summer
extravaganza. Their exhibit _ called ``Take a Walk on the Wild
Side'' _ consists of a woodland garden of wild flowers and grasses
under linden and beech trees, with a stream flowing under a stone
bridge. By Paula Deitz.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
