</P>
<P>
   In order to carry DTV channels, cable operators say, they would
have to drop less popular outlets such as C-SPAN, enraging some
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Fritts, president and chief executive officer of the
National Association of Broadcasters, said, ``We are delivering on
our pledge to bring a new generation of digital television to
American consumers this fall. The FCC has a responsibility to
ensure that cable systems will not impede customers from receiving
the full benefits of this new technology.''
</P>
<P>
   But Decker Anstrom, president and chief executive officer of the
National Cable Television Association, the chief industry trade
group, said his members will oppose any rule that requires them to
carry both the new digital and the current signals on their cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This double-dose of must-carry would surely result in (some
current) cable networks being dropped in many places and would
again relegate cable networks to second-class citizenship,''
Anstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a federal mandate later this year, the cable industry
wants to negotiate a deal on digital carriage issues with the
broadcasters.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC hopes a compromise will spare the agency the need to
choose a winner. Absent such a deal, it is virtually certain that
the loser will fight on in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   History seems to favor the broadcasters. When the Atlanta-based
Turner Broadcasting System sued the FCC over its rules requiring
cable systems to carry the current analog broadcasts, the Supreme
Court in 1997 upheld the commission's rules on a 5-4 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the federal regulators lack the luxury of time.
Wide-screen DTV sets from several of Japan's biggest electronics
firms are to be loaded on ships bound for U.S. ports in early
August. These first-generation sets will be large projection units
and will retail for $7,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the FCC has ordered the four major networks _ ABC,
CBS, NBC and Fox _ to begin airing DTV programs in Atlanta and the
nation's other top 10 markets, covering 30 percent of U.S.
households, by Nov. 1. Since nearly 70 percent of all viewers
subscribe to a cable service, if the systems fail to link up
seamlessly, the huge commitment by the broadcasters and the set
makers to DTV may be imperiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this debate to focus and first and foremost on
consumers,'' said FCC Chairman Bill Kennard. In calling the FCC's
July 9 request for industry comments ``an important step in
focusing debate on how best to bring a digital signal to
Americans,'' Kennard noted that the debate has been and will
continue to be ``intensive and fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoed FCC Commissioner Susan Ness, ``I have absolutely no
preconceived ideas on how this should come out.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two sides grapple, the FCC must also decide several
related issues:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether to let cable operations degrade the DTV signal to save
precious bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether rules should cover only the main digital signal or
include the multiple programs that DTV technology permits as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On which ``tier,'' or subscriber pricing level, of a cable
system digital programming should go.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether to grant small-market cable operators special waivers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennard also plans to call both sides together shortly to urge
them to speed up their dealings on yet another still missing piece
of the DTV puzzle: how to ensure that the engineering
specifications of digital-ready cable boxes mesh with DTV
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   A snag has arisen, because Hollywood, which has a big financial
stake in the movie rental business, wants strong safeguards adopted
to bar commercial piracy of digital images that, in theory, can
produce an endless chain of perfect copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely a huge problem for us,'' said Jack Valenti,
head the Motion Picture Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   But must-carry remains an even bigger problem -- with no easy
solutions in sight.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, most industry experts agree, as cable systems
invest in more bandwidth and as better compression techniques
become widely available, the holy war with the broadcasters over
must-carry could well end in an honorable cease-fire. But, for at
least for the moment, a peace that would let the FCC off the hook
appears to be a fuzzy spot on a distant DTV horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
