<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-AIDS-FUTURE-ART-B     07-15 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-FUTURE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMPLER REGIMENS COMING IN THE AIDS DRUG QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is available on request via E-mail by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ When it comes to AIDS treatment, timing and luck are
still as important as virology, immunology, and clinical research.
But that may be changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of the lucky ones,'' AIDS activist Mark Harrington
told a rapt audience at the 12th World AIDS Conference here.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Harrington's AIDS began to worsen ominously two years
ago, a process specialists call disease progression, researchers
came up with a potent triple-drug cocktail, a regimen that has all
but eliminated the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) from his
system and rescued his dying immune system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have progressed at a better time,'' Harrington
said, flashing a slide of his rejuvenated lymph node tissue. ``My
immune system is coming back to life.''
</P>
<P>
   A 49-year-old Rhode Island woman we'll call Christine is lucky
too, in a less dramatic way. Unlike Harrington, she couldn't defer
AIDS treatment until the triple-drug therapy came along. ``She was
progressing so rapidly that we had to layer in each new drug as it
was available,'' said her AIDS physician for the past 10 years, Dr.
Kenneth Mayer of Brown University.
</P>
<P>
   Usually HIV responds to that kind of sequential drug treatment
by developing resistance to each drug in turn, eventually using up
all options. But thankfully, and for reasons no one can explain,
Christine's virus did not become drug resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, she has begun developing the abnormal fat
deposits that are cropping up in about 20 percent of patients on
long-term triple-drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   In a more precarious situation is Spencer Cox, a colleague of
Harrington's in the New York-based Treatment Action Group. Like
Christine, he has been heavily treated for HIV _ but now he's
resistant to most of the available drugs. Last December he took
himself off treatment to wait for researchers to come up with a
recipe for a new cocktail that will suppress the HIV in his system,
now hovering at a worrisome 230,000 viruses in each milliliter (1/5
teaspoon) of his blood.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he's hopeful. ``I tend to find the gray cloud in
every silver lining, but I came away from Geneva feeling pretty
optimistic,'' Cox said last week.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone. Physicians who treat HIV patients and search for
better therapies say they feel optimistic too _ even though nothing
that came out of the Geneva conference tips the balance away from
timing and luck in AIDS treatment and toward reliable, sure-fire
options for individuals at every stage of HIV disease.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's a case for pessimism, too.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, new drugs in the pipeline appear at least as
potent as current drugs, but they may not come in time to help
those whose current therapy is failing them _ about half the most
intensively treated patients. Also, no imminent drugs represent a
truly new class capable of attacking HIV at a different point in
its life cycle. Thus, it's possible that patients whose virus is
resistant to current drugs will be resistant to new versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my disappointments was that there wasn't more about new
treatments that would benefit those with advanced AIDS,'' said Dr.
Harvey Makadon of Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is also still a matter of luck which patients will respond to
current anti-HIV cocktails as dramatically as Harrington did. All
the world's virologists cannot explain or predict why some people's
HIV can be suppressed indefinitely (so far) to a tiny residuum,
while in others the virus roars back.
</P>
<P>
   Nor can the cleverest immunologists say why treatment returns
some patients' ravaged immune systems to virtually normal, like
Harrington's, while others' appear beyond redemption.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the frustrating unknowns, many see the glass as
half-full. ``For the individual, there's still a certain amount of
caprice,'' Mayer acknowledged. ``But in the aggregate, we now can
treat HIV as a chronic, difficult, but manageable infectious
disease. That's real progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the positive new signs:
</P>
<P>
   --Much simpler HIV regimens. Instead of the onerous 20 to 30
tablets that patients are now told they must take without fail
morning, noon, and night, it will be possible to swallow three or
four pills a day, split into morning and evening doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a massive reduction in the number of
pills,'' said Dr. Julio Montaner of the University of British
Columbia. ``We have nearly a half-dozen drugs that lend themselves
to once-daily dosing.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier regimens make it more likely people will take their
medicine faithfully, lowering the risk of treatment failure. That
should also diminish the risk that people will develop
omni-resistant viral mutants that, scientists now know, can be
transmitted sexually.
</P>
<P>
   --More choices. Drugs in the pipeline, and others not far
behind, introduce the possibility of effective regimens that don't
require protease inhibitors, the potent antivirals that made the
big difference two years ago in combination with older drugs. If
so, protease inhibitors can be held in reserve for those whose
virus rebounds after first-line therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``protease-sparing'' regimens may also provide an
alternative for patients like Christine who suffer lipid
abnormalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will soon have some really intriguing new choices _ for
beginning therapy or switching therapy _ that look equal or better
in potency to the current gold standard,'' said Dr. R. Scott Hitt,
a Los Angeles AIDS doctor who chairs President Clinton's Advisory
Council on HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   --Immune reconstitution. Researchers are heartened by signs that
current treatments allow patients' immune systems to recover more
completely than they expected. Even many whose virus rebounds seem
to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first conference in which there was any optimism
about the immune system's ability to kick in,'' said Dr. Calvin
Cohen of the Community Research Initiative of New England. ``There
was always this feeling that the immune system was doomed to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are rushing to exploit and augment this immune
recovery, so that even if HIV cannot be eradicated from every last
cell in most patients, it might be controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington articulated the question in many people's minds:
``Are we willing to settle for lifelong therapy, or treat until the
immune system can control whatever residual HIV remains? Do we need
to delete every last...infected cell?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
HIV DRUGS IN THE PIPELINE &QL; 
 &QL; 
Clinical trial results on four new drugs promise additional options
soon. But all work in the same ways as existing drugs, so patients
who have developed resistance to standard drugs may also be
resistant to these. &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Efaverenz (Sustiva)  &QL; 
DuPont Pharmaceuticals  &QL; 
Non-nucleoside reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent HIV suppression, even in two-drug combination; Works in
cocktails without a protease inhibitor, saving those drugs for
later. Side effects similar to standard drugs; can alter mood.  &QL; 
Only once daily  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--1592 (Abacavir)  &QL; 
GlaxoWellcome  &QL; 
Nucleoside analogue reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent antiviral in three-drug cocktail, even without a protease
inhibitor. Promising in children failing current treatment. May get
into central nervous system. Side effects resemble standard drugs,
but 3 percent suffer allergic reaction that can be fatal if 1592 is
restarted.  &QL; 
Twice daily, no food/water restrictions  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Adefovir (Preveon)  &QL; 
Gilead Sciences  &QL; 
Nucleoside analogue reverse transcriptase inhibitor  &QL; 
Preliminary studies suggest antiviral efficacy, though perhaps less
potent. As a nucleotide, may work against virus resistant to
nucleosides. Some patients suffer kidney toxicity.  &QL; 
Probably once daily  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Amprenavir  &QL; 
GlaxoWellcome/ &QL; 
Vertex Pharmaceuticals  &QL; 
Protease inhibitor  &QL; 
Potent effect in two-drug combination with Abacavir in small
trials. Three-drug combination with nucleosides showed durable
effect. Penetrates into central nervous system. Side effects
similar to other drugs in this class.  &QL; 
Probably twice daily, no food/water restrictions  &QL; 
 &QL; 
SOURCES: Respective pharmaceutical companies, presentations at 12th
World AIDS Conference, interviews with conference participants &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6252 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TESTS-ONLINE-ART-     07-15 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TESTS-ONLINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB OFFERS QUIZZES, PUZZLERS AND SURVEYS ON EVERY IMAGINABLE
TOPIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (also see sidebar, CIR-TESTS-SITES)  
 (bl)  
 By KATIE HAFNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bored with chat? Tired of shopping on the Web? Sick of e-mail
from your relatives? How about taking a test?
</P>
<P>
   That's right, a test.
</P>
<P>
   The World Wide Web has become a breeding ground for
psychometricians, professional and otherwise, who are filling
cyberspace with thousands of tests that you can administer to
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to log on these days without being collared by
someone with just a few questions that purport to test your
intelligence, your emotional well-being or your predisposition to
depression, alcoholism, hypochondria, diabetes or attention deficit
disorder. The odd thing is that people seem to like to take these
tests.
</P>
<P>
   In a world in which children spend years suffering through
tests, why adults would take them for fun is a mystery. But there
is something alluring about an optional quiz, with its promise of
ranking you in terms of your lovability or likelihood of having a
heart attack. Just look at the number of quizzes in magazines, on
television and radio, and now, in spades, on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Aptitude tests with actual relevance to the workaday world are
still hard to find on line. Someday, certainly, it will be possible
to take the SAT on the Net. But not yet, because the College Board,
which administers the test, still considers the Net insufficiently
secure.
</P>
<P>
   But late at night or on a rainy day, the Net offers a chance to
quiz yourself silly, to find out how you rank in every imaginable
context.
</P>
<P>
   And on the Web, there are no visible proctors or stopwatches in
evidence, and no one to raise an eyebrow at your response to a
question about your sexual habits. For instance, you might scoff at
Mensa, the organization of self-anointed geniuses, but it is
difficult to turn down the chance to spend three minutes on a test
to see if you would be admitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the idea of being able to confront your deepest fears
in private,'' said Jim Goldberg, a 51-year-old management
consultant in Sonoma, Calif., who took the Mensa test. ``And it's
comforting to know that even if I do score like an intellectual and
emotional misfit, it can remain my own little secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg is one of a small group of people recruited by
Circuits, in a purely unscientific fashion, to explore the Web's
variety of tests. The group included a doctor, a lawyer, a British
civil servant, a writer, a consultant, a German freelance
journalist and an Internet project manager.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group recently chose from a dozen or so Web-based
tests _ including a test that promised to gauge IQ, an emotional
quotient test and a karma calibrator _ and sampled whatever struck
their fancy. By day's end, all had discovered that they were
geniuses but also emotionally dysfunctional karmic failures.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult to know how private an online test really
is, or what kind of data the test is collecting _ particularly when
it starts out by testing knowledge of your name, address and
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   The first stop for Robert Wallich, 39, an earnest civil servant
in London, was the Karmometer. The test can be found on the Random
House page for Laura Esquivel's novel ``The Law of Love.'' It
promises to tell you how karmically evolved you are, as well as
your chances of finding your soul mate in your current lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The test includes this question: ``It is the Golden Age of Spain
and you are a valiant captain in Cortez's army. You are rewarded
for your bravery in the conquest of Mexico with a house atop an
ancient pyramid of great religious significance.''
</P>
<P>
   Your choices: (a) Accept the house. You deserve it. (b) Offer it
back to the aboriginal people. (c) Keep the house but free your
slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karmically challenged'' was the verdict for Wallich, who chose
(a) when the karmically correct answer was presumably (b). (The
Karmometer's creators do not supply the correct answers, preferring
perhaps for test-takers to divine them.)
</P>
<P>
   Regine Wosnitza, on the other hand, a 39-year-old freelance
journalist in Berlin who is a firm believer in reincarnation and
the powers of karma, was disappointed in the Karmometer for a
different reason. ``The questions themselves, I thought, were
fairly primitive and had nothing to do with real karma theory,''
she said. Like Wallich, Ms. Wosnitza was told that she would have
to wait until her next lifetime to find her soul mate. ``Of course,
I am not too happy about that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Wosnitza nor Wallich thought to purchase Ms.
Esquivel's novel from the Random House site.
</P>
<P>
   Susan McCarthy, 43, a science and humor writer in San Francisco,
tried her hand at a New Age IQ test. Her score: Very Good. ``This
score was despite my refusal to agree that alien spaceships landed
at Roswell,'' Ms. McCarthy said. ``I said it was a high-altitude
weather balloon, and they told me that was wrong. It's not wrong at
all. I have references, but there was nobody there to fight with.''
</P>
<P>
   Few could resist the emotional intelligence quiz. This test,
which is offered on the Utne Reader's Web site, was written by
Daniel Goleman, who covered behavioral science for The New York
Times for a number of years. Not surprisingly, it is based on
Goleman's best-selling book, ``Emotional Intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The test includes such stumpers as this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine you're an insurance salesman calling prospective
clients. Fifteen people in a row have hung up on you, and you're
getting discouraged. What do you do?
</P>
<P>
   (a) Call it a day and hope you have better luck tomorrow. (b)
Assess qualities in yourself that may be undermining your ability
to make a sale. (c) Try something new in the next call and keep
plugging away. (d) Consider another line of work.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Scoring well on that question _ the ``correct'' answer is (c) _
and most others on the test isn't easy. The median score of the
volunteer group was 60 out of a possible 200. That could lead a
cynic to wonder if the test is aimed, ever so subliminally, at
suggesting to people that they bolster their emotional wherewithal
by reading the book.
</P>
<P>
   Handily enough, the book is available straight from the Utne Web
site, through a direct link to Amazon.com. Many of the wandering
test takers complained about the thinly disguised effort at
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kirk Neely, an endocrinologist who lives in Portola Valley,
Calif., is an easygoing 44-year-old whose happy domestic life _ he
has been married for more than 18 years _ is something to which
many of his friends aspire, but he flunked the emotional test with
a score of 80. ``I was honest about my probable behavior,'' he
said. ``When I went back and answered the way sincere
self-improvers would probably want you to behave, I got a 180.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence tests on the Web are something else altogether. The
widely adopted, if also controversial, Wechsler and Stanford-Binet
IQ tests are hard to find on line, if they are there at all. Still,
dozens of Web sites say they offer a test of basic intelligence,
and those tests appear to be enormously popular.
</P>
<P>
   One cottage purveyor of IQ tests says he gets more than 200
e-mail messages each day regarding his tests. This kind soul, who
administers his tests from his home in China, reminds his visitors,
in large type: ``LOW POINTS DO NOT NECESSARILY MEAN YOU ARE NOT
SMART.''
</P>
<P>
   One particularly easy test that supposedly gauges intelligence
can be found at www.iqtest.com, where several of those smarting
from a slap from Goleman's test found salve for their psyches. In
contrast with Goleman's workout, this test is hard to flub. One
random stab at the multiple-choice answers yielded an IQ of 103,
well within the average range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early questions were at the level of my 9-year-old,''
Neely said. ``The later ones were more subtle and thus more
satisfying. The following slowed me down: `Does an inside-out
left-handed glove fit a right hand?' and `Can your niece be your
aunt?' I kept thinking, from the odd groups I've seen, it must be
possible.'' Neely reported scoring a remarkable 158, which put him,
he said, ``somewhere between Plato and Darwin.''
</P>
<P>
   When a couple of stragglers clicked on the IQ test site, they
were startled to see that it had been hijacked by a hacker
threatening (with many misspellings) to ``reveal the IQ scorez of
all the pplz I hate,'' including President Clinton, Monica Lewinsky
and all French people. Where the warm and welcoming words of the
iqtest.com folks had been stood a collection of white type on a
black background, filled with menacing gibberish. About 24 hours
later, the site was restored, leaving no trace of the hacker's
presence. Such are the potential hazards of an idle traipse through
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Tobias, 54, a lawyer in Oakland, Calif., turned to the
Web site of the New York University psychiatry department, where he
found a test to screen for attention deficit disorder. ``It told me
that my procrastination was a possible symptom of attention deficit
disorder that perhaps should be evaluated by a psychiatrist,''
Tobias said. Neely and Goldberg were told the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Procrastination and disorganization are my major faults,''
Neely said. ``If my major faults actually indicated ADD, 70 percent
of the adult population would be on Ritalin.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Lenard Adler, director of the New York University
Hospital for Joint Diseases' Attention Deficit Disorder Center,
which sponsors the test, cautioned that the Web-based test is ``not
in any way, shape or form meant to be diagnostic.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobias noted, with disappointment, that the psychiatry
department offered a telephone number for referrals _ to the
Attention Deficit Disorder Center. Still, Tobias, a relative
newcomer to the Web, said: ``The Web is an interesting place for an
ADD screen. When I first encountered it, I thought Web surfing
itself might be symptomatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the recruits enjoyed the tests. Tobias said, ``I don't
see myself as a big test-taking, games-playing kind of guy,'' and
he recommended against seeking out Web tests. ``Don't bother,'' he
said. ``The tests I took struck me as simple-minded, commercial or
both.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Wosnitza said she loved them ``although I do not
necessarily believe in them, even if they turn out good results for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lebkowsky, ``the Internet guy'' for the Whole Foods Market
in Austin, Texas, also enjoyed the tests and aced every probe. ``I
found out that I have excellent karma and can find my soul mate,''
he said. ``I also got five of five correct on the Mensa test. I now
know that I am truly an excellent person. However, my stomach's
still growling, my deadlines are still hanging over my head, and
I'm still prone to the same anxieties and depressions. Now what?''
</P>
<P>
   Lebkowsky, 49, might consider pointing his browser toward the
New York University depression screening test. Or perhaps he should
quit while he's ahead and log off.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
