<HEADLINE>
YOUTH PROGRAMS TEAR DOWN WALLS OF PREJUDICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW BRADY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smart. Bookish. Boring.
</P>
<P>
   As stereotypes go, the Asian-American one doesn't seem half bad.
</P>
<P>
   But as high school senior Ryan Cuffee learned this summer, such
stereotyping can cut as deep as any remark about his
African-American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it in a joking manner, but it's wrong,'' said
Cuffee, who loves in Arlington, Texas. ``I never really did it
much, but I've stopped doing it now. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cuffee, the revelation came not from a textbook or TV show,
but through intense, structured interaction with students from
other cultures at a camp called Anytown Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Anytown Texas is among summer programs that seek to heal the
wounds of the past and present through the lives of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of such programs find that targeting young people
offers the best chance of creating a society free of racial,
religious and economic stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are talking about attitudes and changing and opening
minds, I think we have a better chance with young people than with
folks my age,'' said Emily L. Trantham, executive director of the
Fort Worth/Tarrant County Region of The National Conference for
Community and Justice, formerly The National Conference of
Christians and Jews. The nonsectarian group has hosted Anytown
Texas for 16 years and provides other programs for youth and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think young people are trying to understand who they are,
and who others are and where they fit in, and what kind of adult
they want to be,'' Trantham said. ``They are making decisions about
these kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar thinking lies behind the Ulster Project, begun 24 years
ago by an Anglican priest in the Republic of Ireland in an effort
to ease tensions between Catholics and Protestants in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, about 760 Catholic and Protestant students from
Northern Ireland come to the United States for one month of
interaction with American teens.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington is one of 24 cities to host an Ulster group.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, 16 teen-agers and two adult counselors from
Northern Ireland arrived in Arlington for a month of activities.
</P>
<P>
   The trip gives the teens a chance to experience another culture
and to step back and get a different view of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up hearing that another bomb's gone off, or another
soldier has been shot,'' said Cheryl McCutcheon, 20, counselor for
the girls in the group. ``Then you realize, `That's not happening
in other countries.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that Protestants and Catholics do not fight all
the time in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up mixing with both groups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Mathys, president of the Ulster Project-Arlington, said that
the struggle in Northern Ireland is really political rather0tT9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
