<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVERTING YOUR CLOSET TO CEDAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927 .) 
 (ART ADV: How-to graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (JT)  
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lining a closet with aromatic cedar strips is an easy and
worthwhile project for any homeowner to undertake. The fragrance
will keep clothes smelling fresh and the natural resins in the
cedar, although not insecticides, will repel moths. Unlike moth
balls, the cedar will not have to be replenished.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, the closet must have a door that closes to make
a snug seal against the stops. You can't use just any kind of cedar
either. It must be Eastern Red Cedar, often called ''aromatic
cedar.'' Fortunately, most lumberyards and home centers stock this
particular cedar. Usually it is sold prepackaged in 1/4-inch thick
strips cut and grooved for closet installation. Each package has
enough wood to cover about 16 square feet
</P>
<P>
   The tools and skills required for this job are basic ones.
You'll need a hammer, colored paneling nails (they should be about
the same shade as the cedar), a nailset, a trim saw and a miter
box, a caulking gun with a cartridge of construction adhesive, a
level, a chalk line and a ruler or steel tape. Depending on the
closet's size, you'll probably be able to line it in a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by emptying the closet. Remove the clothes pole, shelves,
and the baseboard and ceiling moldings, as well as the clothes and
any storage boxes. In order to capture the cedar fragrance, you
must line the entire closet, including floor, ceiling, and the
inside surface of the door. So measure the height and width of the
four walls (include the door) and the length and width of the
ceiling. Use these measurements to calculate the surface area of
the entire interior. Buy enough cedar to cover this area.
</P>
<P>
   The cedar strips in the package will be about 3 1/2 inches wide
and will vary in length (usually pieces 48-, 32- and 16-inches
long). For most of the job, you will only cut the strips to length.
Closer to the ceiling, however, the gap between the last few boards
and the ceiling may be narrower than 3 1/2 inches. Here you'll have
to rip (cut the strips lengthwise) the boards to fit.
</P>
<P>
   Open all the packages and sort the strips according to size. Set
aside a few boards that are straight-grained and knot free _ these
will easier to rip _ to install near the ceiling. Note that the
strips have a rough and a smooth finished side. The smooth side
should always face out.
</P>
<P>
   In the closet, find the center of each wall stud and also the
ceiling joists. You can use a stud finder for this, or you can
drill a series of small holes in line along the wall until you
locate the framing members. Studs are usually located 16 inches
apart on center, so when you find one, you can easily measure to
find the others. Snap a chalk line to mark their location from top
to bottom. Also snap lines for the joists.
</P>
<P>
   Nail the first cedar strip to the back wall about 1/2 inch from
the floor with the grooved edge down. Use the level to make sure
this first row is perfectly horizontal; if it is not, then the
entire job will be out of square. Nail the boards to the studs,
using the nail set to drive the nail heads flush with the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Apply of few dabs of construction adhesive to the back (rough
side) of the next strip and press it in place above the first row.
The grooves on the edge of this board should mate with the tongue
of the board under it. Continue adding boards to build successive
rows.
</P>
<P>
   With the construction adhesive, it is not necessary to nail
every piece. Nail only a few here and there to hold the rows in
place until the adhesive sets. Remember to check that each row is
level. The end boards do not have to fit directly against the
adjacent wall. You can leave a 1/8 gap to allow for expansion. The
gap will be covered by the pieces on the neighboring wall.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the walls first before installing cedar on the floor and
ceiling. You may leave a small gap where the walls and floor meet.
This can be covered with strips of molding. For molding you can rip
one-inch strips of cedar, or you can buy quarter round molding at
the lumberyard. .
</P>
<P>
   Panel the door last. When covering the door, be sure to leave a
gap around the perimeter to allow the door to close against the
stop molding.
</P>
<P>
   The cedar should not be painted or finished in any way. This
would seal in the natural oils and keep the cedar fragrance from
circulating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
