<HEADLINE>
YOUTH PROGRAMS TEAR DOWN WALLS OF PREJUDICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW BRADY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smart. Bookish. Boring.
</P>
<P>
   As stereotypes go, the Asian-American one doesn't seem half bad.
</P>
<P>
   But as high school senior Ryan Cuffee learned this summer,such
stereotyping can cut as deep as any remark about his
African-American heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it in a joking manner, but it's wrong,'' said
Cuffee, who loves in Arlington, Texas. ``I never really did it
much, but I've stopped doing it now. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cuffee, the revelation came not from a textbook or TV show,
but through intense, structured interaction with students from
other cultures at a camp called Anytown Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Anytown Texas is among summer programs that seek to heal the
wounds of the past and present through the lives of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of such programs find that targeting young people
offers the best chance of creating a society free of racial,
religious and economic stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are talking about attitudes and changing and opening
minds, I think we have a better chance with young people than with
folks my age,'' said Emily L. Trantham, executive director of the
Fort Worth-Tarrant County Region of The National Conference for
Community and Justice, formerly The National Conference of
Christians and Jews. The nonsectarian group has hosted Anytown
Texas for 16 years and provides other programs for youth and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think young people are trying to understand who they are,
and who others are and where they fit in, and what kind of adult
they want to be,'' Trantham said. ``They are making decisions about
these kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar thinking lies behind the Ulster Project, begun 24 years
ago by an Anglican priest in the Republic of Ireland in an effort
to ease tensions between Catholics and Protestants in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, about 760 Catholic and Protestant students from
Northern Ireland come to the United States for one month of
interaction with American teens.
</P>
<P>
   Arlington is one of 24 cities to host an Ulster group.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, 16 teen-agers and two adult counselors from
Northern Ireland arrived in Arlington for a month of activities.
</P>
<P>
   The trip gives the teens a chance to experience another culture
and to step back and get a different view of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``You grow up hearing that another bomb's gone off, or another
soldier has been shot,'' said Cheryl McCutcheon, 20, counselor for
the girls in the group. ``Then you realize, `That's not happening
in other countries.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that Protestants and Catholics do not fight all
the time in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   She grew up mixing with both groups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Mathys, president of the Ulster Project-Arlington, said that
the struggle in Northern Ireland is really political rather than
religious and that it can teach the United States much about its
own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do is look at what happened recently in
Jasper,'' Mathys said. ``It is sort of humbling when they are
looking to us to help break down barriers when we are still
struggling 130 years after the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   Trantham said she believes that the fast pace of life impedes
understanding among various cultures in American life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking specifically about stereotypes,'' she said. ``I
think particularly in this day and time, when we are absolutely
bombarded with so much information, we have to be able to quickly
categorize in order to kind of keep our sanity about this world we
live in,'' she said. ``But in doing so we may categorize in a way
that is wrong .... It's not having the opportunity to really get to
know someone who is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a year, Trantham organizes a six-week interfaith dialogue
involving seminary students from various faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, during the first session, some students want to
engage in theological debate. But instead, Trantham said, the
students must talk about themselves and their backgrounds: where
they grew up, number of family members, etc. In the second session,
the conversation turns to superficial religious issues. By the
third session, ``We start probing with some questions where we know
people will have differences,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The approach seems to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will have one or two who feel comfortable talking about
anything, anywhere, with anyone,'' she said. ``Most of us are not
like that. I think most of us, before we want to become intimate
with anyone, want to know a little bit about that person, want to
know some of the things we share in common, want to know that what
we think and what we feel will be respected and listened to.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar approach is taken at Anytown Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Cuffee said that when his mother first approached him about
going, he declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go. I figured it would be a waste of time,''
he said. ``I didn't like the fact that I would be gone for a week
with people I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He went anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Now he calls it the experience of a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did he make a lot of friends, but he also gained
insights into the dynamics of human relationships and learned that
any cultural barrier can be overcome with time, compassion and
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons were summed up for Cuffee on the next-to-last day of
camp.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Thursday, and the students were instructed to divide
into racial groups: African-American, Asian, Irish, German.
Interaction was permitted only within racial groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were black, you could not look at, talk to, address any
kind of white person,'' Cuffee said. ``It was difficult. ... You
got to know these people, and then for somebody to tell you could
not be friends because they were a different race _ it was very
difficult to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   The segregation was supposed to last all day. It lasted about 30
minutes, until one of the campers led the group in a rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wanted to do it in their hearts, but they were
pretty much afraid or scared of what would happen to them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The joy of breaking down the walls and the feeling of
camaraderie as the campers reunited is an experience Cuffee said he
will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the experience of a lifetime,'' he said. ``If you are
not educated about another race or another group, you are not going
to be open to them. People fear what they don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
