<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEDONA-ARIZONA-ART-2T     07-15 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEDONA-ARIZONA-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDUCTIVE SEDONA WOOS TOURISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photos available on NYT photo service) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEDONA, Ariz. _ When pioneer T. Carl Schnebly settled in 1902
amid the spectacular red rocks and deep canyons that dominate this
enchanting landscape, he suggested Schnebly Station as the name for
a new post office.
</P>
<P>
   Too long to fit on cancellation stamps, the government informed.
</P>
<P>
   So T. Carl instead named the community after his 25-year-old
wife. And almost a century later, given its widely diverse appeals
_ and especially its mystical lures _ we can only imagine that
Sedona Schnebly was a woman of multiple personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sedona and the adjacent Oak Creek Canyon recreation area,
sandwiched a two-hour drive north from Phoenix or 2 1/2 hours south
from the rim of the Grand Canyon, hosts 5 million annual visitors _
remarkable considering the greater Sedona population is only
16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some gravitate here _ for a fortnight or a lifetime _ because of
Sedona's growing status as a premier arts center.
</P>
<P>
   Others pause to splash in old-fashioned swimming holes carved
between towering cliffs; to explore ancient Indian ruins by foot,
Jeep or horseback; to gaze upon a dazzling array of twinkling stars
from a cabin or campground beside Oak Creek; to languish in the lap
of luxury at the appropriately named Enchantment Resort.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number come to regenerate their spiritual being at
``power vortexes'' said to rival England's Stonehenge, the Pyramids
of Egypt and Australia's Ayers Rock among the world's strongest
energy fields.
</P>
<P>
   Forever hovering above all these pursuits _ literally and
figuratively _ are brilliantly hued cliffs and rugged sandstone
spires sculpted over millions of years by ocean tides and desert
winds, their shapes inspiring monikers such as Cathedral Rock,
Courthouse Butte, Madonna and the Nuns, Coffee Pot, Snoopy and Bell
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   First-time visitors spend hours, even days, focusing on these
red rocks from hot-air balloons, helicopters or Jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   Countless others, even those who have never approached Arizona,
admire their splendor from a living-room recliner or a theater
seat.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 full-length films have been filmed entirely or in
part here _ from 1932's ``Riders of the Purple Sage'' to 1985's
``The Karate Kid'' and with stars that include John Wayne, Shirley
Temple, Henry Fonda, Joan Crawford, Elvis Presley and Robert
DeNiro.
</P>
<P>
   Though current movie trends aren't always compatible with
Sedona's dedication toward preserving its natural wonders
(``Today's action-oriented directors ask us if they can blow up the
rocks,'' one tourism official says, sighing), rare is the day that
the land doesn't serve as a backdrop for television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Or the inspiration for a myriad of lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
POWER OF THE ROCKS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the ``home of the famous 101 omelettes'' _ among them
asparagus and turkey; peanut butter, jelly and banana; corned-beef
hash; and cottage cheese and blueberry _ the Coffee Pot Restaurant
represents a Sedona institution.
</P>
<P>
   Brochures and pamphlets stationed in its foyer also hint at the
newest rage, promoting ``Spiritual and Psychic Readings by
Solomon,'' ``Mystic Tours With Rahelio'' and ``Angelic Healings and
Past Life Regression'' clinics scheduled at the Center for the New
Age along Arizona Highway 179.
</P>
<P>
   Recent network tabloid television reports disturb civic leaders.
``They make it seem like we're the land of the kooks, and that's
just not so,'' one resident says.
</P>
<P>
   Elija Barkham, who conducts vortex tours for the Sedona Red Rock
Jeep Company, concedes, ``There is a lot of New Age garbage here.''
But don't get the wrong impression: Barkham, who moved to Sedona
from Great Britain, is a devoted believer in the power of the
rocks. ``I couldn't guide these tours if I didn't get a physical
and spiritual awakening,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Barkham has ample company: The Anasazi Indians considered this
red-rock country sacred ground thousands of years ago. More recent
meditators became known as ``channelers''; so the joke goes,
``Sedona is the only place in America with no TV stations and 1,500
channels.''
</P>
<P>
   It is believed that the term ``vortex'' was first applied here
in 1980 by lecturer and former Sedona resident Page Bryant, who _
based on scientific fact or modern mythology, take your pick _
identified a limited number of area locations she claimed represent
ideal meditation sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Bell Rock, are considered ``up-flow'' vortexes:
Supposedly these enable us to evaluate our lives from an elevated
plane. ``I've taken people to Bell Rock without telling them
anything, and they say, `Wow, I feel I've just had a shot of
caffeine,''' Barkham says.
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Cathedral Rock, are ``in-flow'' vortexes: They
are said to facilitate introspection and an understanding of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another vortex, the Sedona post office, ``is supposed to be
a place of confusion,'' Barkham says. ``There must be something to
it because there are more dings in cars there than at any other
place in town.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid is that traffic flow also is heaviest at the post
office. Indeed, is there logic in any of this? Barkham stands
beside a gently flowing stream at Red Rock Crossing, one of
Arizona's most-photographed sites, on a glorious morning _ 70
degrees; a soft breeze; shade trees shielding the sun _ and peers
up at majestic Cathedral Rock. Nearby, three fishermen perched on
boulders make their casts as if posing for a Norman Rockwell
painting. A young couple spreads a picnic lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are your inner feelings at this moment?'' Barkham
inquires.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth, it's very peaceful,'' comes the reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got it! You understand the vortex!'' Barkham beams.
</P>
<P>
   Why spoil the moment?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the myths are not told and the songs are not sung, then the
land will die,'' Barkham says wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INDIAN CULTURE AND HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some might argue that this emphasis on vortexes as a tourist
attraction commercializes or makes light of hallowed Indian
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the native way is to never make judgments, and I will not
condemn any teaching or any individual where the spirit and heart
honors the beauty of the land and the beauty of living,'' says
Uqualla, a Havasupai Indian who serves as Enchantment Resort's
cultural ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone who comes to Sedona is going to be spiritually
elevated,'' Uqualla says. ``But if this New Age opens a door, it
can be good.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uqualla, raised by his medicine-man grandfather on the floor of
the Grand Canyon, celebrates the red rocks, too, especially within
the walls of Boynton Canyon _ another designated Sedona-area vortex
_ where Enchantment is situated.
</P>
<P>
   In full ceremonial dress, he recounts stories of tribes that
roamed this land: the Anasazi, the Sinaguan, the Yavapai (his
cousin tribe) and the Apache. He introduces hiking trails that lead
to Honanki and Palatki, 800-year-old cliff dwellings adorned with
petroglyphs and pictographs, symbols created by pigment rubbed into
the rock.
</P>
<P>
   Jeep tour companies also conduct guided tours that focus on
these sites and on Indian culture and history. A half-hour
excursion to the south leads to Montezuma Castle, the oldest and
best-preserved cliff dwelling in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we can only bring a voice to the beauty of this land,''
says Uqualla. ``I realized many years ago that nature is more
powerful than man can ever be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
AH, OAK CREEK CANYON &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nature is especially powerful here. And generous. Not only are
the rock formations unique, but Sedona is surrounded by the
1.8-million-acre Coconino National Forest. Overall, the area
includes seven major biological communities ranging from desert
grassland to pine-fir forest.
</P>
<P>
   Every approach is tinged with drama. Arriving from the south,
motorists frequently pull to the shoulder of Arizona Highway 179,
mesmerized by their initial glimpse of fire-red Bell Rock and
Courthouse Butte. Those advancing on Arizona Highway 89A from
Jerome, a ghost of a town perched on Cleopatra Hill 35 miles to the
west, delight in panoramic views of the Mogollon Rim, the southern
escarpment of the High Colorado Plateau into which Oak Creek Canyon
is cut.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Oak Creek Canyon. One of America's most heralded scenic
drives _ an extension of Arizona Highway 89A north from Sedona
toward Flagstaff _ twists through a gorge whose depths reach 2,500
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Whether for practical transportation or as a day trip, this
journey is a highlight of any visit. The canyon road, guarded by
enormous cottonwood and sycamore trees, rises almost 2,000 feet
from Sedona's 4,500-foot elevation. Names attest to the rugged
terrain and/or rich tradition: Bootlegger and Banjo Bill
campgrounds; Grasshopper Point; Buzzard Ridge; East Pocket Knob.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that Zane Grey was moved to write ``Call of the
Canyon.'' Now, rustic lodges beckon stressed-out travelers whose
concept of re-energizing involves not a vortex but settling into a
hammock on a creekside patio, paperback in hand. Others find
shelter in one of six campgrounds operated by the National Forest
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Slide Rock State Park, located eight miles north of Sedona along
State Highway 89A (but with about a quarter-mile walk from the
entrance to Oak Creek), is exactly as the name implies: a natural
water slide especially popular with kids in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing north, a succession of stomach-churning switchbacks
ascends to the Oak Creek Canyon Vista. Views are stunning from this
6,407-foot elevation. But then, almost every road _ paved or gravel
_ or footpath opens up a treasure chest of scenic wonders.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, humans aren't alone in feasting off the land.
Animal and plant life abound: Almost 200 bird species, more than 50
types of mammals, 80 types of fish, amphibians and reptiles and
more than 500 species of seed plants have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A CENTER FOR THE ARTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, given the natural beauty and cultural
legacies, that Sedona has emerged into a center for the arts? Its
status as a haven for painters and sculptors, actors and musicians
long preceded the New Age invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood discovered Red Rock Country in the 1920s, especially
as a venue for cowboy movies. Over time, Lucille Ball, Orson
Welles, Jane Russell and Walt Disney were among celebrities who
called Sedona home, and several modern-day notables live quietly in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Surrealist painter Max Ernst settled here in 1950. When he and
sculptor Nassan Gobran sought a forum to demonstrate their skills,
they chose an old barn on the edge of town. Thus, the Sedona Arts
Center was born. And the ``Art Barn'' remains at the heart of this
community as a headquarters for classroom instruction and a
showcase for aspiring artists young and old.
</P>
<P>
   Most workshops now last several weeks, with topics ranging from
creative sculpture, advanced pottery and mask-making to songwriting
and acting. Craig Thompson, the Arts Center's executive director,
says plans are to create, as he terms it, ``the equivalency of an
Elderhostel program where anybody could come here for as short a
time as one or two days to a week and take classes.''
</P>
<P>
   The center also stages theatrical productions and sponsors
regular art exhibits, and a blueprint is established for a newer,
larger complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboy Artists of America was founded here in 1965, and
Southwestern, Western and American Indian arts continue to
flourish. More than 40 galleries represent nationally and
internationally known artists; many are situated in the fascinating
Tlaquepaque Arts and Crafts Village on Arizona Highway 179 just
south of the Uptown Sedona shopping district.
</P>
<P>
   Aesthetic appreciations are evident in other ways, too, among
them the striking Chapel of the Holy Cross, a huge sculpture
perched on a spur of red rock 200 feet above the desert floor and
visible to passersby on Arizona Highway 179 south of town. The
chapel is open year-round, and a glass enclosure affords sweeping
views.
</P>
<P>
   Annual arts-related events include the nationally acclaimed
Sedona Sculpture Walk (Oct. 2-4), which features more than 100
participating artists; the Sedona Arts Festival (Oct. 10-11); and
Jazz on the Rocks (Sept. 26), whose headliners have included Dizzy
Gillespie and Nancy Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting pop, rock, jazz and classical artists perform regularly
in the summer, and a new amphitheater is under construction.
Readers of American Style magazine recently tabbed Sedona among the
nation's top five arts destinations, behind only Santa Fe, Seattle,
New York and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Though the arts scene is varied, a common impetus is evident.
``Certainly the red rocks are an inspiration to many artists,''
Thompson says. ``Most come here for a vacation and fall in love
with the place, then years later they come back to live.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`A DELICATE ENVIRONMENT' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No matter which of Sedona's many personalities we explore, we
discover its soul imbedded in the red rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Its future, too.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Yadon, chairman of the Sedona-Oak Creek Canyon Chamber of
Commerce and owner of the luxurious Canyon Villa Inn, applauds the
emphasis on culture and tradition. And of a New Age to which he
admittedly doesn't belong, Yadon says, ``Many people come here to
find themselves, and I know it's heartfelt.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as he promotes these lures, Yadon says, ``We're in a
delicate environment. This environment is our main product. Above
all, we must respect and preserve this product.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the land is what makes this place truly
special.''
</P>
<P>
   One can only imagine that Sedona Schnebly is smiling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
