<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COBBLER RECIPES ARE JUST PEACHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not sure where the first peach cobbler came from. I suspect
it was baked a long time ago when a cook like me, who couldn't bake
to save his soul, tried to make a pie and it fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than toss it out, he just lied and said he intended the
crust to be down in the filling. I would have done the same.
</P>
<P>
   I love peach cobbler, but I must say I am not too selective. I
enjoy the rich recipes with brown sugar crumbles on top, but I also
dive into the foil-pan, soupy-insides, cafeteria kind.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbler isn't supposed to be gourmet food. It is a quick,
inexpensive way to salvage the peaches that are going bad right
before your eyes. It's what you make when you just have to get rid
of those dusty cans in the pantry; it is what you make when you
don't have the skill and patience to roll out a 1/8-inch-thick
crust with fluted edges.
</P>
<P>
   It is also what you make right after you've been to the Parker
County Peach Festival in Weatherford, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   You can't drive through Parker County these days without your
mouth watering. The Peach Festival was last weekend, and I'll bet
there are hundreds of people sitting at home now, watching their
peaches go brown.
</P>
<P>
   I don't blame them. Parker County peaches are seductive. You
must have them, even if you don't know what to do with them.
</P>
<P>
   This year's crop is bountiful, the growers say. But the peaches
are kind of small. Instead of being the size of oranges, as they
usually are, they have been reduced to the size of healthy plums
because of the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness the festival people have come out with a cookbook
this year. It wasn't ready when I went looking for it, but the
folks at the Weatherford Chamber of Commerce told me the cookbook
has the same categories as the Peach Festival Food Competition.
</P>
<P>
   Those categories include cakes, sweet breads, pies, cobblers,
candy, miscellaneous, and children younger than 15.
</P>
<P>
   Children under 15 are hard to cook, I would think.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the chamber sent me an advance copy of the cobbler
recipes. Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   JO ANN GLENN'S BUSY DAY PEACH COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 heaping teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   4 cups Parker County peaches, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in 2-quart baking dish. Combine dry ingredients,
reserving 1/2 cup sugar and cinnamon for peach mixture. Stir
remaining dry ingredients into melted butter in baking dish. Add
milk and stir again. Bring fruit, 1/2 cup sugar and cinnamon to
boil. As soon as it boils, take off the heat and pour over batter.
Do not stir. Bake at 350 degrees for 30 minutes or until crust is
golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   JENNIFER SUTHERLAND'S PEACH COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crushed corn flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   9 fresh peach halves
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Generously grease 8-inch square pan.
In large bowl, beat butter, brown sugar, lemon peel and lemon juice
until light and fluffy. Add flour, baking soda, salt, cinnamon and
nutmeg to butter mixture; beat until well-blended. Stir in cereal
until mixture resembles coarse crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   Press half of mixture in bottom of greased pan. Arrange peach
halves, cut side down, over crust. Sprinkle with remaining crumb
mixture. Bake at 350 degrees for 45-50 minutes or until golden
brown.
</P>
<P>
   MICHELLE WRIGHT'S PEACH COBBLER
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sliced fresh peaches
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup margarine
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Put 1/2 cup margarine in baking dish; set in 350-degree oven to
melt while preparing the following ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Mix sugar, baking powder, flour, milk and salt together. Pour
mixture over melted butter; do not stir. Put peaches on top of
this. Bake in 350-degree oven for 45 minutes or until brown.
</P>
<P>
   Here is another recipe, but this one didn't come from
Weatherford. I'm not sure where it came from, exactly. I got it off
the Internet, and I seldom know where I am while on the Internet.
There were several just like it, and the addition of the Cheddar
cheese is intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   PEACH COBBLER WITH CHEDDAR BISCUITS
</P>
<P>
   1 quart peaches, sliced
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Cheddar biscuits:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup biscuit mix, such as Bisquick
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mild Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Place the peaches in a greased
baking pan. Mix the sugar, cornstarch and salt, then sprinkle over
the peaches. Sprinkle the lemon juice and almond extract over the
peach mixture. Bake for 15 minutes. Meanwhile, make the biscuits by
combining all the ingredients, stirring well. Remove the baking pan
and drop the dough onto the hot peach mixture and bake for an
additional 20 minutes or until the biscuits are done. Serve warm
with whipped topping or ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
