<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-VIDEOPHONES-ART-2     07-15 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIDEOPHONES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOPHONES EVOLVE, SLOWLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (Also see CIR-VIDEOPHONES-SEX)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1996 comedy ``Mother'' may be one of the only films to have
a running joke about videophones. In the movie, a 30-something
sports agent played by Rob Morrow tries to foster family unity by
handing out the gadgets to his closest relatives. His brother,
played by Albert Brooks, refuses even to unpack his, but the title
character, played by Debbie Reynolds, gamely does her best. But
despite all the instructions from her son and all the contortions
she goes through, she can manage to send only a fuzzy picture of
her neck or headless torso. ``I told him I like this,'' the mother
confesses, ``but it's driving me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony, of course, is that videophone technology more
properly belongs to the mother's generation than to her sons'.
First introduced by AT&AMP;T at the 1964 World's Fair, videophones _
sometimes called ``granny phones'' _ are perhaps the
longest-running source of disappointment for the consumer
electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
   While expensive videoconferencing systems using costly,
high-speed data lines have found some acceptance in the corporate
world, the market for home videophones, the Holy Grail of gadgets,
is a battleground littered with four decades of failures by some of
the world's biggest names in electronics and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of the videophone has persisted, nudged along by
science fiction (``Star Trek''), comic strips (``Dick Tracy'') and
intermittent releases (AT&AMP;T's first marketing effort in Pittsburgh
in 1970 and its videophone 2500 in 1992).
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, several companies have bravely moved into
the consumer videophone market, fortified by a new international
technical standard for video calling, more powerful computer chips
and the prospect of high-speed home Internet links.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them seem to have learned an important lesson from the
crushed dreams of the past: they are not claiming to have a product
that will change the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very realistic: it's not a mass-market product,'' said
Daniel Flohr, president and chief executive of C-Phone, a
videophone manufacturer based in Wilmington, N.C. ``Everyone's not
going to run out to get one.''
</P>
<P>
   The current efforts to make the sort of phones used by the
Jetsons fall into two camps: television-based systems and
computer-based systems. C-Phone and ViaTV units are literally black
boxes, each stuffed with a microprocessor and a tiny camera, that
use regular television sets for their visual display and
conventional telephone lines for transmission. (Both also run up
normal long-distance charges.)
</P>
<P>
   ViaTV's maker, 8X8, also offers a higher-priced variation that
does not require a television. With its tiny liquid crystal display
screen, the 8X8 Desktop Videophone comes the closest in appearance
to the popular image of the videophone.
</P>
<P>
   Both the 8X8 ViaTV (which is also sold by 3Com as the Bigpicture
TV Phone) and C-Phone are no more difficult to set up than a VCR.
Either box is linked to a television set and connected to the
telephone world through a separate cable that plugs into a standard
phone jack. Once wired, neither unit interferes with normal
television or telephone operation.
</P>
<P>
   All calls begin as voice-only connections. Then, assuming the
other party is willing and able to reveal all, buttons are pushed
and a video image appears within 30 seconds or so.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, the computer-based systems _ including
Microsoft Net Meeting, CU-SeeMe, 3Com Bigpicture videophones, IRIS
Phone, VDO Phone Professional and the Intel videophone _ turn
relatively powerful personal computers (generally with at least a
Pentium processor and 16 megabytes of memory) equipped with
cameras, microphones and other equipment into videophones. The
hardware is supplied with some of the software packages.
</P>
<P>
   If you already have a suitable, fully equipped computer _ which
could represent an investment of $1,500 or more _ video calling can
be relatively inexpensive. One of the most popular software titles,
Microsoft's Net Meeting, can be downloaded free. Television set-top
or desktop videophone units, by contrast, can cost as much as $650.
</P>
<P>
   Some video-calling programs operate over the regular phone
network. Others trade predictability and quality for lower
operating costs by moving through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet video calling is much trickier. To start with, most
users must set up the time for the call in advance. Most PC-based
videophones will work only after both users log into special
directory servers known as Internet Locator Servers. There are more
than 200 such servers for Microsoft's Net Meeting alone, and the
listings on those confirm the suspicions that transmissions of
sexual encounters are a leading use of the technology. ``If I were
a cynic, I would say the whole VCR industry was launched by a very
similar thing,'' said Net Meeting product manager Tom Laemmel.
``But good came out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   What hooked Bruce Powell, a Web site designer in Tiburon,
Calif., was the chance to keep in better contact with his
mother-in-law in Nancy, France. ``If you're calling a family
member, it just makes a huge difference to be able to see each
other,'' he said. Given his profession, Powell first tried the
Internet-based system CU-SeeMe. ``When you're dealing with
technophobes like my mother-in-law, using CU-SeeMe is totally out
of the question,'' he said. ``It's just much too complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell then bought a pair of 8X8 Via TV unit; one was soon on
its way across the Atlantic with a French translation of the
installation instructions. His 77-year-old mother-in-law, with some
help from an adult son, plugged in her unit without incident. They
generally exchange video calls once a month. They have found that
video calls tend to last longer than regular phone conversations,
so the American and French sides of the family alternate placing
the calls and paying the intercontinental toll charges.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An interview over Powell's videophone system demonstrated some
of the lingering problems with such systems. First, rapid motion
overwhelms them. As Powell's 3{-year-old son flitted in and out of
the picture, the machine rendered him in coarse pixels _ the same
effect deliberately used in television documentaries to obscure
identities.
</P>
<P>
   Even a conversation with the more sedate Powell had its
shortcomings. Creating and moving images places heavy
data-processing demands on the unit. Because the video image must
first be compressed for transmission and then expanded for viewing,
the resulting picture lags well behind the accompanying voice,
making it look as though Powell was starring in a badly dubbed
foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   But the image and voice quality on the 8X8 units and C-Phone is
clearly better than anything traveling over the Internet. Even over
the fairly controlled high-speed link provided by Microsoft's
internal corporate network, the voice of Laemmel during a
videophone interview was slightly distorted, and his image was
sometimes dark and blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly all consumer videophone systems, Net Meeting
transmits, at best, only half the number of frames per second that
broadcast television uses, making all action look slightly odd.
</P>
<P>
   But things really fell apart when Laemmel continued the
interview through a second computer linked to the Internet through
a standard, consumer-speed dial-up modem. Some sentences became
incomprehensible because of lost or distorted words, and the video
often blacked out or froze. ``The fact we're going over the
Internet makes it sort of a crap shoot,'' Laemmel said.
</P>
<P>
   Current users can get better still images. Nearly every system
can produce still images of very high quality that users can easily
create with snapshot or freeze-frame commands. Many of Powell's
calls, for example, turn into variations of slide shows as wiggly
babies are lifted to the camera and frozen electronically or older
children's drawings are given the same treatment.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of talk about overcoming the remaining technical
hurdles to make videophones a mass consumer product, but even that
may not guarantee success.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mantei Tremaine, a sociologist and computer scientist at
the Drexel University College of Information Science and Technology
in Philadelphia, has studied videophones for more than nine years.
What she has found is that the psychological barriers are almost as
daunting as the technical ones.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, for example, while she was on the faculty
of the University of Toronto, she studied employees at a small
company after two corporate offices were connected with a
videophone system. In time, she found, all nonmanagerial employees
disabled the visual connection, often by taping over the camera
lenses or pulling out wires. ``Everything was disconnected,''
Professor Mantei Tremaine said. ``This is how people felt about the
video.''
</P>
<P>
   The resentment stemmed from many factors. An early study
conducted by AT&AMP;T found that people took an average of 11 rings to
answer a videophone call _ often, they were tidying up their
personal appearance and desk before answering. (The cartoon
character Jane Jetson avoided the problem by donning a special mask
before answering her videophone.)
</P>
<P>
   But the professor saw that users grew used to the videophones.
No longer mindful, some users chatted away unaware that their beer
bellies were poking out from shirts. Male managers unnerved female
secretaries by speaking too close to cameras, unintentionally
``creating those powerful close-ups you see in romantic movies,''
Professor Mantei Tremaine said.
</P>
<P>
   But she found that one issue, privacy, ultimately loomed above
all else. ``People who didn't use videophones were worried about
having their privacy invaded,'' she said. ``And people who did use
them feared they were invading someone else's privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Already there are issues developing about whom you will let see
your image on video calls. CU-SeeMe, for example, operates special
servers that allow many users to participate in video-and-voice
chat sessions. Forrest Milkowski, co-founder of White Pine
Software, the company that developed and markets CU-SeeMe, says
there was already resentment toward users who pointed their cameras
at, say, a houseplant. ``If you don't show your face, people find
that insulting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there will very likely be a lot of users who do
not want just anyone taking a peek. Dottie Lassen, a hospital
kitchen worker in Lebanon, N.H., and her 29-year-old son, Jason,
who lives in Los Angeles, were each given C-Phones after using them
on a television talk show late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the two have used the units about a half-dozen times
to stay in touch, and Ms. Lassen has been pleased with the results.
``It's truly amazing,'' she said, but that does not mean she would
ever use videophones exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't pick it up and talk to just anyone,'' she said. ``I
wouldn't want strangers to see how my house is set up, to see where
my windows are, see the counter where I put my purse. Video calls
are really personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Videophones are also demanding. During a video call, it is
impossible to sift through e-mail, fold laundry or scan the
newspaper without those activities being noticed. Yet the current
technology often has the perverse effect of making everyone seem
inattentive. Since the cameras and display screens are set apart in
all videophone systems, fakery is the only tool for people who want
to appear as if they are hanging onto every word. Rather than
actually looking at the image of the person talking, a listener who
wants to seem engaged must stare directly into the camera lens.
</P>
<P>
   But neither technical nor psychological barriers are likely to
deter efforts to make the videophone succeed. Last December,
Kyocera introduced a wireless videophone in Japan. At two frames
per second, its black-and-white images barely offer any sense of
motion. But at least it keeps up the proud gadget tradition
videophones began back in 1964.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6360 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-VIDEOPHONES-SEX-N     07-15 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIDEOPHONES-SEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEOCONFERENCING'S KILLER APP: SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (sidebar with CIR-VIDEOPHONES)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Videophones add a new dimension of anxiety to the familiar
problem of the phone ringing while you are in the bathtub. It turns
out, however, that thousands of people actually look forward to
video calls while they, and their callers, are undressed.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as is typically the case with a new technology, early
adopters of videoconferencing have discovered that the so-called
killer app is sex. From Kansas to Kiev, Internet users are
enthusiastically embracing Net-based videoconferencing that allows
them to play show-and-tell with other uninhibited souls.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. and other companies that make videoconferencing
products say that while sex-related applications are a very visible
use of the new technology, the most common applications are indeed
for business: conducting meetings, collaborating on work projects
and telecommuting, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also some people _ thousands, actually _ who use
the technology to exhibit themselves, in real time, without clothes
and to watch others doing the same. All it takes is a recent-model
personal computer, an Internet connection, conferencing software, a
microphone and a video camera.
</P>
<P>
   For voyeurs, even less equipment is needed. Thousands of
commercial sex sites on the Internet _ some broadcasting from
elaborate studios in Las Vegas or New York, others from a simple
Web camera in a woman's bedroom in Iowa _ offer live video to
customers, who need only a credit card and a standard Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live videos are almost a necessity if you're going to have a
successful subscription site,'' said Mark Tiarra, chief executive
of Tiarracorp of Midland Park, N.J., one of the largest providers
of design services to adults-only Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   But for two-way video and audio, it gets a bit more complicated.
One of the most popular software packages for Internet
videoconferencing is Net Meeting, which is free from Microsoft. To
promote the software and make it easy for software users to find
one another, Microsoft has set up a half-dozen Internet Locator
Server computers.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably 200 public locator servers on the Net. And
those are just the public ones. There may be thousands more on
private, corporate networks, or, perhaps, run by sex-related
businesses that make them available to subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   At the servers run by Microsoft, users are asked to assign
themselves to one of three categories: Business, Personal and
Adults Only. The Adults Only site is a catalog of lusts. (No child
pornography was encountered or offered.) The Personal section
appeared to be nearly as heavily visited by sex-oriented users as
the Adults Only area, although a few users specifically requested
``family oriented'' or ``clean'' chat. The Business category
appeared, almost surprisingly, to be almost entirely business
oriented.
</P>
<P>
   On one morning this week, the Adults Only directory on a server
run by Microsoft was fully populated with users who had registered
their home countries as Canada, China, Germany, Italy, Portugal,
Taiwan, Korea, Australia, Mexico, Norway, Peru, France, Spain,
Switzerland, Japan, Britain, Venezuela, Russia, Chile and Turkey,
among others. Users from the United States accounted for about half
of the connections.
</P>
<P>
   Net Meeting users register to be included in a directory that
displays names, e-mail addresses, home locations and special
interests. On the Adults Only directory, very few people use their
real names or e-mail addresses, opting instead to advertise their
own physical attributes, attitudes and sexual proclivities. About
half the directory entries on a recent visit showed a small camera
symbol, indicating that someone at that address was willing to
broadcast pictures of himself or herself while in conference.
Conferences can involve two people or a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   The rest indicated that they were open to audio exchanges _ in
essence, to talk dirty to one another, using the Internet instead
of a telephone. There are no long distance charges on the Internet
beyond the basic cost of the Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Laemmel, a product manager specializing in Net Meeting, said
Microsoft did not encourage the use of its products or condone the
use of its software or servers for what he called risque
activities. ``We realize it is a problem, and we're looking for
technology to solve the problem,'' he said. But he added, ``We're
not in the business of trying to police the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Laemmel said users offended by the solicitations of sex-hungry
Net Meeting users have several options to avoid them, such as
screening out other directory entries and getting an unlisted
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use Net Meeting with my mom all the time, and frankly, it
could be embarrassing if she saw all the directory listings,'' he
said, but they bypass the directories and call each other directly.
``Luckily, she never even logs on to the Internet Locator Server.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
