<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERB-BASIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIL IS BASIC FOR FRAGRANT SAUCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL NUCKOLS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basil is a bushy annual with fragrant leaves. It is native to
India, Africa and Asia but is cultivated widely. It can reach 2
feet in height.
</P>
<P>
   Growing conditions: Plant in rich, slightly moist soil; needs
plentiful sunlight. Plant from transplants in late spring through
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Companion plants: Tomatoes, peppers
</P>
<P>
   Food pairings: Tomatoes, garlic, pasta, cheeses; chicken, fish,
vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Caveats: Treat for worm damage with ``Bacillus thuringiensis''
</P>
<P>
   TOMATOES AND OLIVES WITH HERBS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup drained kalamata olives, pitted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup drained, pitted and chopped imported green olives
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds tomatoes, cored and quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Cook parsley
and garlic in oil, stirring frequently, for about 2 minutes, until
garlic is golden. Do not let it brown.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce heat to medium. Stir in olives. Cook, uncovered, for 3
minutes, stirring frequently. Add tomatoes and cook, stirring, for
about 2 minutes, or until tomatoes are warm. Add basil, chives and
pepper. Cook about 30 seconds, until herbs are wilted and fragrant.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 113 calories, 6 grams fat, 13
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 461
milligrams sodium, 52 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Herbal Palate Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   by Maggie Oster and Sal Gilbertie
</P>
<P>
   (Storey, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKY WHITE BEAN SPREAD WITH ROASTED GARLIC AND BASIL
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 6 cups
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dried white beans, such as cannellini or Great Northern,
picked over, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 small yellow onion, plus 1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and cut crosswise into 3 pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon liquid hickory smoke flavoring
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   10 large basil leaves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped sage, optional
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cover beans with cold water and soak for at
least 4 hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Drain beans. In a large pan, cover them with fresh, cold water.
Push cloves into the onion half. Add onion half, carrots and thyme
to beans. Bring to a simmer over medium heat. Cover tightly, lower
heat and cook gently, stirring once or twice, until very tender,
about 50 minutes (cooking times vary widely; add more boiling water
and continue to cook as necessary). Reserve 1 cup cooking water.
Discard onion half, carrot and thyme. Drain and cool beans.
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor, combine beans, chopped onion, 2/3 cup of
the reserved cooking water, garlic, lemon juice, salt, smoke
flavoring and pepper. Process until smooth, stopping several times
to scrape down sides of work bowl and adding more cooking liquid if
mixture seems too thick. Transfer to a bowl and stir in basil and
sage. Adjust seasoning. Spread can be used immediately or covered
and refrigerated for up to three days. Return to room temperature
before serving. Serve with pita chips or bruschetta, or spread on
cold lamb sandwiches with sliced tomato and arugula.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Canned beans can be substituted. Use four 15 1/2-ounce
cans, drained; use canning liquid in place of cooking water. Reduce
salt slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 13 calories, trace fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 milligrams cholesterol, 99
milligrams sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Pamela Morgan's Flavors''
</P>
<P>
   by Pamela Morgan and Michael McLaughlin
</P>
<P>
   (Viking, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   PASTA WITH GORGONZOLA SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as a side dish
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup walnut pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup loosely packed basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces Gorgonzola or any blue cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces dried penne, fettuccine or other pasta
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 whole nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Combine oil and garlic. Cut
prosciutto into 1-inch-long shreds. Toast nuts in preheated oven
until they become dark golden, about 15 minutes, then set aside.
Stem and chop red bell pepper. Crumble Gorgonzola and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Sliver basil leaves. Bring 4 quarts water to a rapid boil.
Lightly salt water, then cook pasta according to instructions on
package. When pasta loses its raw texture but is still slightly
firm, set aside 1 cup of pasta water, then remove pasta from heat
and drain.
</P>
<P>
   Return empty pasta pot to stove over high heat. Add olive oil
and garlic. Saute until garlic begins to sizzle but has not
browned. Return pasta to pot and add prosciutto, walnuts, red bell
pepper, three-fourths of the cheese, basil, salt, pepper flakes and
1 cup pasta water. Stir and toss until evenly combined and
well-heated. Taste and adjust seasonings, especially salt. Transfer
pasta to a heated platter or four heated dinner plates. Sprinkle on
remaining cheese and grate a little nutmeg over it. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 682 calories, 43 grams fat, 48
grams carbohydrates, 27 grams protein, 51 milligrams cholesterol,
1,301 milligrams sodium, 57 percent of calories from fat. _ ``Hot
Pasta''
</P>
<P>
   by Hugh Carpenter and Teri Sandison
</P>
<P>
   (Ten Speed Press, $17.95)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
