A6425 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-JESUS-NYTSF &LR;      07-15 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-JESUS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT WOULD JESUS DO?' CAN BE A DANGEROUS QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WWJD is showing up everywhere -- on wristbands, T-shirts and
jewelry -- and on every teenager I meet. Short for ``What Would
Jesus Do?'', WWJD is the latest popular religion fad to engulf
conservative Protestant churches.
 &HT;    The current craze started with a youth group at Calvary Reformed
Church in Holland, Mich. The teenagers dedicated themselves to ask
the question ``What would Jesus do?'' when faced with a moral
decision.
 &HT;    To advertise this commitment, they created bracelets displaying
the letters WWJD. The community embraced the idea and it quickly
spread nationally. To date, more than 14 million bracelets have
been sold.
 &HT;    However popular with trendy Christian teens, the idea is not
new. The youth group was influenced by the 1896 pietist classic,
``In His Steps,'' written by Charles Sheldon. A Congregationalist
minister, Sheldon wrote the book as a series of sermon-stories for
his flock. However, the novel became an all-time religious
bestseller with perhaps as many as 30 million copies in print
worldwide.
 &HT;    The story is simple. On a Sunday morning, ``Into the midst of
perfect accord and concord between preacher and audience, there
came a remarkable interruption.'' A tramp wandered into comfortable
First Church and began to preach.
 &HT;    ``What do you Christians mean by following the steps of Jesus?''
After rehearsing a litany of social ills and repeating the hymn
sung by the congregation he states, ``It seems to me there's an
awful lot of trouble in the world that somehow wouldn't exist if
people who sing such songs went and lived them out. I suppose I
don't understand. What would Jesus do?''
 &HT;    The good church people, moved by the tramp's plea, pledge to
live their lives for a year asking themselves, ``What would Jesus
do?'' And, of course, their lives, town, and indeed, the nation are
transformed.
 &HT;    As literature, ``In His Steps'' is neither memorable -- steeped
in late Victorian romanticism -- nor a likely draw for teenage
tastes. But WWJD enthusiasts do not care. They find the question --
What Would Jesus Do? -- compelling.
 &HT;    WWJD is a better question than those religious conservatives
have asked in recent years -- such as ``Do you support the
Christian Coalition?'' ``Are you for family values?'' and ``Do you
believe homosexuality is a sin?''
 &HT;    An improvement on the right-wing politics afflicting evangelical
churches, WWJD nevertheless raises some concerns.
 &HT;    Critics accuse the WWJD movement of being a smokescreen for the
religious right's political agenda -- an argument I find
unconvincing. Idealistic and sincere, WWJD teens seem unlikely
pawns in a giant right-wing conspiracy.
 &HT;    Rather, their questions are too narrow and individualistic. For
example, the WWJD CD challenges teens to respond as Jesus would
regarding the death of a father, sexual temptation, rejection by
classmates, and ``little things in life ... like a bandmate who
spends too long in the shower.''
 &HT;    Cruising the WWJD website, http://www.wwjd.com, seekers can find
nary a word about politics. WWJD is private piety and reveals a
certain evangelical ennui regarding public policy. These folks do
not want social revolution; they are just trying to cope with small
problems.
 &HT;    That's the problem. Finally, after years of asking bad
questions, evangelicals are now asking a good question. But they
are not asking it in the correct arena. This question should be
asked of American political life.
 &HT;    Charles Sheldon was not so shy. In his book, those who ask
``What Would Jesus Do?'' embrace numerous progressive causes. The
story climaxes when Trade Unionists and Christian Socialists, led
by an Episcopal bishop, organize the ``common people'' into a
socialist cooperative for Jesus (Really. Read the book).
 &HT;    Sheldon was a theological liberal, a Christian Socialist, an
early feminist, a pacifist and ecumenical minister who condemned
racism and anti-Semitism. What would Jesus do? Jesus would vote
Socialist. Jesus would defend the poor, women, blacks, Jews and
oppressed people. Jesus would oppose the military-industrial
complex. Jesus would stand up for gays and lesbians. Jesus would
not buy products made in sweat shops. Jesus would condemn tobacco
companies.
 &HT;    Moreover, Jesus would not market WWJD junk on the web. Jesus
would not join the Christian Coalition. Jesus would not be caught
dead at a Promise Keepers rally.
 &HT;    WWJD is a dangerous question. Odd that evangelicals are asking
it. Seems as if mainline Protestants and Catholics should be. After
all, their churches are already trying to answer it. And, Jesus
promised, his way would be hard and unpopular. It's that other way
-- the broad, trendy and commercially successful one -- that leads
to destruction.
 &HT;    WWJD: Jesus would not ask a question for which he really did not
want the answer.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
