</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE LAND    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A Dearth of Zucchini &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My three zucchini plants have been flowering for the last
several weeks. They have produced only one female flower that
resulted in a zucchini. I had the same problem last year and
harvested only two zucchinis. There are cucumber, pepper, eggplant,
tomato, basil and parsley plants nearby. Can you tell me what's
happening?
</P>
<P>
   A. Are you getting female flowers that don't go on to make
zucchinis? Or are your plants suffering a gender gap?A more common
problem is female flowers that don't produce zucchinis, but both
problems are caused by the same sorts of stress, said Dr. Brent
Loy, a professor of plant biology at the University of New
Hampshire, who has done a great deal of work with the squash
family.
</P>
<P>
   The three most likely culprits are shade (squash is a sun
lover), very hot weather (especially if temperatures do not
moderate at night) and unusually wet conditions. ``If it was very
wet, that might stimulate male flowers,'' Dr. Loy said, adding that
the female ones can abort at such an early stage you might not know
they had ever appeared. But all male flowers are a possibility if
everything goes wrong enough, and that includes starting
transplants and then letting them get pot-bound. ``Plants that have
been stunted by adverse conditions or by delayed transplanting will
tend to produce an abundance of male flowers,'' he said. Squash
plants have to be in pretty good health for the females to form and
prosper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Daylily Care &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I read that Stella de Oro daylilies will bloom all summer if
you deadhead them. So I went out every day and scrupulously pulled
off all the spent flowers. About two weeks later, however, I
started seeing what seem to be big green seedpods developing. What
am I doing wrong? Do I need to literally cut off the spent blooms
with a little bit of stem? And when a stem seems finished, should
it be cut back, too?
</P>
<P>
   A. I suppose this isn't the place to say, ``Don't believe
everything you read,'' but these daylilies, like most perennials
that are supposed to be constant bloomers, are more accurately
described as frequent re-bloomers. They will indeed make flowers
over a long season, but usually in waves, called flushes, rather
than all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Deadheading does help encourage this behavior by preventing the
development of seeds. That means you must remove the fruiting body
when you remove the flower. It is usually quite obvious where the
stem stops and the fruit starts, but just nipping off the critical
lump can leave an unattractive cluster of sticks, so careful
deadheaders clip the whole stem that carried the flower that is now
deceased. In the case of daylilies, of course, you don't want to
remove the larger stalk until all its flowers have had their
chance.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Slug Combat &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Help! The slugs are winning, although I have many tuna
can-beer traps all around my shady Brooklyn backyard and I'm
vigilant about picking them off plants and the soil. I also have a
small pond, with small frogs that apparently don't eat slugs. They
must have a natural predator, right? Are there any other antislug
strategies that I can use without resorting to toxic chemicals?  &QL; 
A. There are several things to try, and a combination will probably
provide the best control. Predators include birds _ the robins that
are lunching on your worms  &UR; do &LR;  have their good side _ and toads,
shrews, turtles and, best of all, garter snakes.
</P>
<P>
   All of these creatures will help, and so will a number of
commercial products. Wide copper strips, for instance, which give
the enemy a small electric jolt, are effective barriers if you have
raised beds or well-separated plants. They don't work in dense
plantings, though, because the slugs just find one place to climb
and then ooze from leaf to leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Diatomaceous earth, on the other hand, is the old-reliable of
organic slug repellents. It looks like dust but is actually a mass
of sharp edges, the shells of tiny sea creatures. DE, as it is
popularly known, is widely available in garden centers and is
nontoxic to animals and fish. It should not be inhaled, however,
because it can damage your lungs; wear a mask when applying it.
Unfortunately, to be effective, DE must be used in unsightly
quantities and renewed at frequent intervals, including after every
rain.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entrant on the organic lists is a slug poison called
Escar-go! The active ingredient is iron phosphate, which does not
harm other organisms and has no ill effects on the soil. I have
been using it this year with good results, though like DE it must
be frequently renewed, and unlike DE it is expensive in the
quantities necessary to control slugs in a large garden.
</P>
<P>
   Escar-Go is white, but it is in pellets, so it's easier to
scatter inconspicuously under plants. Escar-Go is sold by Gardens
Alive, 5100 Schenley Place, Lawrenceburg, Ind. 47025; (812)
537-8650; free catalog. A pound and a quarter costs $9.99 plus
shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
