<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EELS WELL THAT ENDS WELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday July 17)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am trying, but so far I have failed to be catatonically
alarmed by the fact that Florida has been invaded 3-foot-long,
mucus-secreting, fish-eating, poison-resistant Asian rice eels.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is the record heat that has reduced my capacity for
alarm. Or maybe the unchecked wildfires, or the sting rays, or the
state legislature's sales tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Asian rice eels are way down the list
of Reasons to Avoid Moving to Florida At All Costs, which is
probably unfair to new residents, not to mention the eels.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't read the papers lately (and who could blame
you for that?), the Asian rice eel is the latest non-native species
to have moved into Florida for the sole purpose of gobbling up
everything in its path, sort of like real estate developers or
bankers, only with even more slime.
</P>
<P>
   The problem began, as so many problems do, with an aquarium
owner who, in keeping with the more rigorous system of
fact-checking in place at newspapers these days, we will identify
as ``Ned.'' Ned, who for reasons that will become quickly apparent
didn't have many friends, decided it would be ``cool'' to add an
exotic new species to his tropical fish tank, preferably a species
that was about as pleasing and relaxing to look at as one of those
formaldehyde-preserved colons on display at the Smithsonian.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious choice was an Asian rice eel (No, wait! Make
that two!). This creature is, needless to say, considered a
delicacy in certain quarters. What Ned failed to take into account
was that Asian rice eels can grow to be 3 feet long, so it was not
long before Ned's new pets outgrew their aquarium and took over his
living room couch, where they spent their days watching National
Geographic reruns and hoping that Flipper became infested with
parasitic worms.
</P>
<P>
   Ned's pet eels also had quite an appetite, so it was not long
before they had eaten all the other fish in Ned's aquarium, not to
mention the chicken pot pies, tater tots and leftover lasagna in
Ned's freezer.
</P>
<P>
   We have already established that Ned was not the brightest light
on his block, but it didn't take long for an idea to seep through
his concrete-reinforced cranium: Get rid of the eels.
</P>
<P>
   This was not as easy as it sounds. If Ned had been of Asian
descent, he presumably could have popped his pet eels into the
microwave or a tureen of hot broth and, perhaps accompanied by some
jellied octopus or candied sea urchin, made a tasty lunch. But
Ned's tastes ran more to Chicken McNuggets and cheeseburgers, so
the thought of eating his eels never really crossed his mind.
(Besides, there was the very real possibility that wrestling two
3-foot Asian rice eels into a tureen of hot broth might have ended
tragically for Ned, but we will not go into that.)
</P>
<P>
   So what Ned did is what any humane pet owner would do under
similar circumstances: He emptied a 5-gallon jug of swimming pool
chlorine into his aquarium. While this succeeded in making his
aquarium water crystal-clear, it had no noticeable effect on the
eels, other than to improve their backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   Ned poured other poisons into his fish tank, but nothing
bothered the eels, which were reclining contentedly on the couch,
munching pretzels and making sarcastic remarks about Jacques
Cousteau's accent.
</P>
<P>
   At his wit's end (not that far a journey, in Ned's case), he
dumped his eels into Georgia's Chattahoochee River. While this
solved Ned's problem (at least one of them), it created an entire
new set of problems for states from Texas to North Carolina as the
eels bred like, well, eels and ate everything they could wrap their
slimy little eel lips around except Newt Gingrich whom the eels
said tasted like hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   (It should be noted that there is a rock band called the Eels
and their hit single is ``Novocain For the Soul.'' This seems
appropriate, though I'm not exactly sure how.)
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
