<HEADER>
A6446 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHRIMP-RECIPES-TEX     07-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHRIMP-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE WONDER EVERYONE LOVES SHRIMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shrimp is so ubiquitous today that it's hard to imagine when it
wasn't around. As the century closes, even landlocked cities in
broiling climes have a wide choice in every supermarket. And if
supermarkets present shrimp that are a little too processed, Asian
markets offer the same guys with their heads attached. But despite
their availability, shrimp is still special.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply Shrimp'' by Rick Rodgers (Chronicle, $16.95) puts the
little pink jewels in the capable hands of an experienced cookbook
author. What the reader gets is recipes for everything from exotica
such as shrimp and fennel bisque to the more everyday, but
certainly no less luscious, American buttermilk biscuits with Low
Country shrimp and ham.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are clear, precise and very cookable. Whether you
want to impress the neighbors or simply treat yourself, here's the
book to do it.
</P>
<P>
   CILANTRO SHRIMP TOASTS
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 30
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Asian fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped fresh cilantro, including stems
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove, crushed through a press
</P>
<P>
   30 baguette slices, cut on the diagonal 1/4-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable shortening for deep frying
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, process shrimp, egg white, fish sauce, sugar,
salt and red pepper until smooth. Add shallots, cilantro and garlic
and pulse until combined. Transfer to small bowl. Spread shrimp
paste on baguette slices, mounding the paste slightly in the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 200 degrees. Place a cake rack over a baking
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   In a large, heavy skillet, melt enough shortening over
medium-high heat to come halfway up sides, and heat to 360 degrees.
Working in batches without crowding, deep-fry the toast, shrimp
side down, for 90 seconds, spooning oil over the toasts. Turn and
continue frying, spooning some of the oil over the toast, until
golden brown, about 1 minute. Transfer toast to the wire rack and
keep warm in oven while frying remaining toast. Serve immediately,
with the sauce for dipping. (The toast may be kept at room
temperature for up to 1 hour and reheated in a 400-degree oven for
7 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Dipping sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crushed red pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in small bowl, stirring to dissolve
sugar. The sauce can be made up to 4 days ahead, covered and
refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with dipping sauce: 55
calories, 1 gram fat, 8 grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 23
milligrams cholesterol, 190 milligrams sodium, 11 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP AU POIVRE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds large shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon whole black peppercorns, or more to taste, crushed
in a mortar or under a heavy skillet
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cognac or brandy
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped fresh chives or parsley
</P>
<P>
   In large nonstick skillet, heat 1 tablespoon of the butter over
medium heat. Add shrimp, salt and pepper. Cook until pink and firm,
2-3 minutes. Transfer to a plate and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In same skillet, heat remaining 1 tablespoon butter. Add
shallots and cook, stirring often, until softened, about 2 minutes.
Add cognac and cook until almost evaporated. Stir in heavy cream
and increase the heat to high. cook until reduced by half, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Return shrimp to skillet and toss to coat with the sauce. Serve
immediately, sprinkled with the chives.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 448 calories, 31 grams fat, 4
grams carbohydrates, 36 grams protein, 357 milligrams cholesterol,
424 milligrams sodium, 62 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   GRANDMA RODGERS' SHRIMP AND ICEBERG SLAW
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup mayonnaise, cold
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry or cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon grated onion (use a small onion grated on the large
holes of a cheese grater)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon celery seeds
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium shrimp, cooked, peeled and deveined, or
ready-cooked tiny pink shrimp, well-chilled
</P>
<P>
   1 medium head iceberg lettuce, cored and cut into 1/4-inch-wide
shreds, well-chilled
</P>
<P>
   4 ripe plum tomatoes, seeded and cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, whisk mayonnaise, vinegar, onion, celery
seeds, salt and pepper. Add shrimp, lettuce and tomatoes and toss
well. Serve immediately. This salad can be prepared up to 2 hours
ahead, covered and refrigerated. It will wilt slightly, but that is
the way Grandma Rodgers served it.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 226 calories, 18 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 98 milligrams cholesterol,
358 milligrams sodium, 71 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
