<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-OLD-CELLPHONES-AR     07-15 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OLD-CELLPHONES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MANY A DESK, A CELL PHONE GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By DEBRA NUSSBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's fair to say that Jeffrey Kagan of Atlanta is an expert on
telecommunications. He wrote a book on the subject, gives
interviews and speeches and keeps up with the latest trends. But
like millions of other Americans, he faces a communications
conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   What to do with his old cellular phones?
</P>
<P>
   He has six of them crammed in a desk drawer in his office. And
that's after selling two such phones at a yard sale for $5 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the old elephant graveyard, but it's the old cell
phone graveyard,'' he said. ``It's the same as old computers.
Everyone has a corner in their basement for them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee Group, a technology research and consulting company
based in Boston, estimates that out of the 50 million people with
cellular phones, 25 percent have at least one other cellular phone
that is not activated and in use, said Mark Lowenstein, the senior
vice president at the company for cellular research. ``Typically,
those phones are melting in glove compartments or collecting dust
in closets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the first commercial cellular phone call was made in 1983,
sound quality has improved, and the phones have become smaller,
lighter and more affordable. Between 1992 and 1998, the number of
people using cellular telephones tripled, Lowenstein said. Because
of stiff competition among carriers, many people change carriers
and get new phones.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 15 percent of all cellular customers switched
carriers, he said, and in most cases, they got new telephones. The
newer digital telephones, with a longer battery life, more
sophisticated security and enhanced voice-mail, have also sent many
analog phones to the storage closet.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers retire larger phones and get the smaller models.
The cost of most new cellular phones has dropped so much that there
seems to be little point in continuing to use the old ones.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bell Atlantic Mobile will sell a new customer in
New York or New Jersey an analog telephone for $9.99 if the
customer signs a one-year service contract. The company will sell a
digital telephone for $179.99 with a contract.
</P>
<P>
   In some service areas, companies offer a free analog phone with
the contract. Companies recoup their money on the contract charge
and the rates for using the phones.
</P>
<P>
   While some analog phones may be worth $150 to $300, according to
Consumer Reports, the carrier will earn more than $500 a year from
a cellular subscriber who paid little or nothing for the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``With traditional cellular service, you can get the new phone
practically for free,'' Kagan said. ``The phone technology
continues to improve so rapidly that the phones today are much
better than the ones from two or three years ago. Most people would
rather get the new phone. But if the old phone is not broken, you
feel guilty dropping it in a trash can.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are offering trade-ins to new customers or those
who are upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Mobile will give customers a $30 to $50 credit
toward a digital phone if they turn in their analog models. Out of
more than 110,000 new digital subscribers in the last six months,
50 percent turned in their old phones, said Maggie Aloia Rohr, a
spokeswoman for Bell Atlantic Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic Mobile sends the phones to companies that
refurbish them or use them for spare parts, she said. The company
has had several thousand phones reprogrammed to dial only 911 and
has donated them, with the necessary service, to domestic violence
organizations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   So let's say you want to give your phone to charity,
sidestepping your local phone company. It is not all that easy.
Many local charities will not take them, probably because the
recipient cannot use the phone without a service contract. But most
Goodwill Industries stores will take donations of cellular phones
that do not need repairs, said Sheila Holt, a spokeswoman for
Goodwill in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Nextel Communications has offered trade-in programs in some
markets. Customers get $100 to $150 off the purchase of a digital
Motorola cellular phone when they trade in their current cellular
phone and get a contract with Nextel. In the Chicago market, Nextel
is offering 500 free minutes of service for each consumer who turns
in an old phone and signs up with Nextel.
</P>
<P>
   Comcast Cellular Communications is working on a trade-in program
for customers in the Philadelphia area and recently offered a
``buddy'' program to encourage people to keep their old cellular
phone in use, said Melissa Nichols, a spokeswoman. For six months,
starting in October 1997, Comcast offered a six-month contract on
an analog phone for $9.99 a month when the customer purchased a
digital phone and contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are some repair companies, like Recellular,
based in Ann Arbor, Mich., that recycle cellular phones. They buy
used equipment in bulk from carriers, however, and do not take
cellular phones directly from consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven years, Recellular has refurbished more than a
million phones, said Eric Forster, vice president for sales and
marketing. The company then sells the phones to dealers, carriers,
wholesalers and exporters. The majority of the phones go to
companies that sell prepaid contracts with their cellular phones,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forster urged consumers not to throw the phones away because the
nickel-cadmium batteries in some units might pose an environmental
hazard.``Companies need to have phone trade-in programs to keep
these phones out of landfills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Communications Test Design, a company in West Chester, Pa., that
repairs telephone land-line switching equipment, was in the
cellular refurbishing business for two years but stopped in March,
with the exception of a few contracts with carriers. ``The cost of
refurbishing is so high that we weren't making a profit on it,''
said Joe Boyce, the sales manager for that operation. ``Customers
should try to get the carrier to take the phone in trade.''
</P>
<P>
   If you hold on to your old cellular phone, don't count on
finding a neighborhood repairman if it breaks down. ``There's no
such thing,'' Kagan said. ``It's not viable to set up a cell phone
repair shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Many phone plans come with a warranty to cover any breakdowns
and some companies will give you a replacement phone while your
phone is being repaired. After all, they want you to keep making
calls. Kagan's advice is to take the phone back to where you bought
it, rather than trying to find someone to repair it.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can also try to recycle their phones by selling or
trading them to other customers. The Recyclenet Corporation, based
in Ontario, (www.recycle.net) has a Web site where consumers can
advertise free any items they want to sell or trade. Cellular
phones are popular on the Web site, , said Paul Roszel, the
company's owner.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the price tag says, it can be hard to find a
home for an old cellular phone. Jack Stokvis, a consultant in New
Jersey, said he had offered to give his father his cellular phone
but his father didn't want it. His brother, Robert, has two unused
phones; he bought a new cellular phone three months ago that is
small enough to clip to his belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get them so cheaply you end up collecting them,''
Robert Stokvis said. ``It's a waste. They're still good, but who
needs them?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
