<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIRCUITS-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      07-15 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIRCUITS-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (jt)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A Sea and Sun Vacation For Your Trusty Laptop &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm taking my laptop computer to the beach for a month. Do I
need to worry about damage from the salt air?
</P>
<P>
   A. The wind, sun and salt air that all feel so invigorating on
your skin during a beach holiday can have quite a different effect
on your laptop computer. If you've ever seen rust develop on the
metal parts of a bicycle left outside a beach house in the sea air
for a few weeks, you'll know why you should be concerned about the
inside of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, computers work best indoors in an
air-conditioned environment that maintains low humidity and a room
temperature between 65 and 75 degrees. Try to do most of your
computing inside in a cool, dry place, away from direct sunlight.
Too much heat or excess moisture from high humidity can cause
electrical components inside the machine to break down, shortening
the life of your laptop. Salt and sand from the beach can also end
up inside your computer through the machine's floppy drive or
connection ports.
</P>
<P>
   To help guard against the corrosive effects of salt air and
humidity, you may want to invest in a good weatherproof laptop case
for storing your computer. Or you can seal it in an airtight
plastic bag along with a packet of moisture-absorbent material like
silica gel (available at camera and electronics stores). With
proper protection, the laptop should be fine, but just remember to
occasionally unplug, relax and enjoy your vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com or postal mail to Questions, Circuits,
The New York Times, 229 West 43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
