</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTEN UP _ OR NOT _ WITH THESE RECIPES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got two ways to approach eating in this weather. One: You
can eat light to feel light. Or two: You can reward yourself for
getting through another day of this misery by eating something
delicious but decidedly not on the debit side of any calorie
ledger.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a recipe that reader Susie Rainey developed for a
cookbook she is writing. As you can see, it weighs in quite low on
the fat scale.
</P>
<P>
   LOW-FAT SPINACH ENCHILADAS A LA RAINEY-AKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   Enchiladas:
</P>
<P>
   9-ounce package Green Giant Harvest Fresh frozen spinach (no
sauce)
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons nonfat sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce extra-sharp Cheddar cheese, finely shredded
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely diced sweet yellow onion
</P>
<P>
   2 large low-fat flour tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Sauce:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons nonfat sour cream mixed with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   Garnish:
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons diced tomato
</P>
<P>
   Microwave spinach according to directions on package and drain
well in colander. Mash to extract all fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion in a nonstick pan. Remove seeds from jalapenos
before mincing. Combine drained spinach with 4 tablespoons sour
cream, cheese and onions in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Moisten tortillas under running water and shake off excess
water. Fry quickly using nonstick spray on medium heat until hot.
Split spinach mixture in half and spoon into a long mound down the
middle of each hot tortilla. Roll the tortillas around the spinach
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Lay the enchiladas ``seam'' side down on a plate.
</P>
<P>
   For sauce, combine jalapenos with sour cream/water mixture. Warm
quickly in the microwave (20 seconds should do it). It should be
thin enough to pour.
</P>
<P>
   Top the two rolled enchiladas with sauce and garnish with diced
tomato.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 270 calories, 6 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 15 grams protein, 15 milligrams cholesterol,
472 milligrams sodium, 19 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   And on the other side: Joan Hallford of North Richland Hills,
Texas, sends the requested recipe for chocolate Italian cream cake.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE ITALIAN CREAM CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Crisco
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   2 cups flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter, Crisco and sugar together. Add egg yolks, one at a
time, beating after each addition. Sift soda, flour and cocoa
together. Add alternatingly with buttermilk, beginning and ending
with dry ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in coconut, vanilla and nuts. Fold in stiffly beaten egg
whites. Bake in three greased and floured 8- or 9-inch pans at 325
degrees for 25-30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Frosting:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 stick butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   1 pound powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese and butter together. Sift sugar and cocoa, beating
in a little at a time until well-creamed. Add vanilla and pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 762 calories, 42 grams fat, 93
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 151 milligrams cholesterol,
331 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Jack Walter Coots of North Richland Hills would like a recipe he
remembers from the 1920s. It's an old-fashioned banana layer cake
with hard, sugary icing. The bananas are sliced thin and
lengthwise, placed between layers only, with a thin layer of icing.
The top and sides are sealed with the icing that is sort of a
creamy color.
</P>
<P>
   Hurene Morrow of Azle, Texas, is desperate for a coconut
Wheaties cookie recipe. These cookies have no oatmeal or brown
sugar. They are very crisp, and the recipe makes about 6 to 8
dozen. She believes the recipe was from a Wheaties box in the late
1940s or early 1950s. ``The other people who had the recipe are all
dead,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Weldon is requesting a recipe for an Indian corn casserole
that includes bacon and its drippings, corn bread, corn and
jalapenos.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
