<SLUG> BC-BEDSIDE-MANNERS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAKE PATIENTS TEACH MEDICAL STUDENTS BEDSIDE MANNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Amy Kerr was worried about the red rash on her
face. As she sat in her doctor's office explaining her concerns, he
cut her off in midsentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does your husband have a beard?'' she recalled him asking in
February. ``Oh, it's probably just that,'' he said, writing a
prescription. In less than 10 minutes, he was out of the examining
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really annoyed,'' said Kerr, who found out later that
her doctor misdiagnosed her problem, an acne-like infection known
as rosacea. ``It was demeaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Managed care and hospital mergers are putting increasing
pressure on health care professionals to keep costs down. That
means physicians are packing more patients into the day. Manners
sometimes get lost in the rush.
</P>
<P>
   This comes at a time when the health care industry is becoming
more competitive and hospitals and HMOs are fighting for customers.
What they're learning is bad bedside manners can add up to serious
and costly mistakes, from mistaken or missed diagnoses to
dissatisfied patients and malpractice suits.
</P>
<P>
   To improve how doctors juggle efficiency with empathy in the
exam room, medical schools are increasingly turning to professional
patients who play at being sick with everything from hypertension
and diabetes to depression and stress.
</P>
<P>
   Known as standardized patients, they're paid to give aspiring
doctors a chance to practice and polish their clinical and
communication skills.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, almost all of the nation's 125 medical
schools have revamped their curricula to include time spent with
these patients in hopes of developing a human and healing touch in
their students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the medical profession is finally aware that all is
not well with the patient-doctor relationship,'' said Dr. Irwin
Hassenfeld, a professor of psychiatry and an assistant chairman of
psychiatric education at Albany Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the dissatisfaction with physicians ... is (patients)
don't feel they get listened to,'' Hassenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   In today's competitive health care industry, HMOs are
increasingly paying attention to satisfaction surveys and holding
their doctors accountable for how well they listen and communicate
with patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts pressure on physicians to say this is valued and not
just by the individual patient,'' said Linda Morrison, director of
the standardized patient program at Southern Illinois University
School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lessons taught by standardized patient programs are
straightforward: knock before entering the examining room, maintain
eye contact, and acknowledge what the patient is telling you.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone says my mother died three months ago, you just
don't write it down and move on to the next question,'' said Dr.
Henry Pohl, the associate dean for medical education at Albany
Medical College.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other practical considerations that Pohl wants his
students to consider, such as knowing how to protect a patient's
modesty with one of those flimsy paper gowns, remembering to wash
their hands and presenting a competent demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had dress-code problems, hair problems, body odor
problems, perfume problems,'' he said. ``Patients felt
uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Most real patients, however, will keep their mouths shut.
Proponents say that's where the hired stand-ins can make a real
difference by offering students constructive criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a teaching tool,'' said Linda Perkowski, the director of
the standardized patient program at the University of Southern
California. ``It's a safe environment to practice skills.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kerr, the insensitive bedside manner of the doctor she saw
about her skin problem inspired her to try and help medical
students. Now, she heads to Albany Medical College an average of
twice a week to be probed, touched and questioned by aspiring
doctors about imaginary aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the $12-an-hour she earns for her work, Kerr said she
gets the satisfaction of helping future physicians do a better job.
``It gives me the opportunity to try to help them become more
approachable doctors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She plays different roles: an abused woman and a smoker with
hypertension, in hopes of pushing young medical students to realize
that medicine is as much art as science.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
