<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEDSIDE-MANNERS-2NDTA     07-15 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEDSIDE-MANNERS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY, N.Y.: art as science.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beyond the technical know-how, it's the ability to ask the right
questions, listen, and put physical problems into the context of
someone's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eye contact, you need to work on that a little,'' Kerr
told a student after a simulated encounter where she played the
role of a 40-year-old woman with high blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But she praised the student for not being judgmental about her
smoking habit or her lifestyle. ``You didn't lecture me about it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to make such encounters a part of the regular
curriculum at all schools and require doctors to pass a national
licensing exam on their clinical and communication skills.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools already require their students to pass a clinical
competency exam before they graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Such an exam would evaluate students on everything from how well
they listen, to their ability to ask organized questions and
perform routine physicals and histories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians have been too caught up in technology,'' Pohl said.
``Schools haven't focused enough on good old-fashioned ways of
getting information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year for the first time, all foreign medical school
graduates applying to U.S. residency programs have to pass a
clinical test that challenges both medical and language skills
using standardized patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can communicate well with their patients, they're more
likely to come up with the correct treatment,'' said Maysel Kemp
White, the assistant director of education and research at the
Bayer Institute for Health Care Communication in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   She said a ``major reason why doctors are sued is communication
or lack of communication.''
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the communication gap is detailed in numerous
studies and surveys. In an American Medical Association poll of
more than 1,500 Americans, 54 percent said that doctors care less
about people than they used to.
</P>
<P>
   And patients aren't the only ones who feel slighted.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a national poll of 230 physicians found that 61
percent felt medical school or residency programs did not prepare
them well enough to communicate with patients on sensitive topics.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl and other medical education experts believe standardized
patients are part of the answer to bridging the distance between
people and their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standardized patients are real people,'' said Dr. Daniel
Klass, director of the standardized patient project for the
National Board of Medical Examiners in Philadelphia. ``You have to
learn how to apply your medical knowledge with real people.''
</P>
<P>
   By giving students a chance to practice with dying patients,
sexually abused patients or belligerent patients in a simulated
setting, they're less apt to make mistakes when confronted with
real-life problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually people do it better the second time,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Students say they don't mind being put under such scrutiny. Most
of their encounters with standardized patients are videotaped from
a special monitoring room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great way to get actual feedback,'' said Jacquelyn
McConville, a third-year medical student from Long Island. ``The
more we do it, the more comfortable we are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Myers, a medical student from Colorado. agreed. Her
standardized patient recommended she organize her questions a
little tighter. ``I definitely think it's valuable,'' she said.
``There's so much to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers has only to consider her own experience with some
physicians to understand a patient's perspective. ``I've had some
doctors who've had their hands on the doorknob the whole time,''
she said. ``I want somebody who listens to me, who I know is
concerned about me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
