<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     07-15 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK INTO THE MIRROR OF REALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Elizabeth Branch is talking about trying to
save African-American children when the office door squeaks open
and a child _ a chubby-faced toddler _ waddles in and crawls into
her lap.
</P>
<P>
   She embraces him, and he snuggles against her chest as she
gently rubs his back. But Branch is in another place and time,
remembering another boy she met years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager, one of nearly 200 others over the years, had come
to Branch's Alternative School after having been expelled. His
crime: carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me,'' Branch recalls, ``and asked, `What am I
supposed to do? Who's going to watch my back?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Branch, a reading specialist and creator of Man in the Mirror, a
little-known behavioral program that seeks to change the way youths
respond to conflict, is finding it hard to shake that memory
because that boy comes through her doors with haunting regularity,
in many different bodies. What's worse is that his story is almost
always the same.
</P>
<P>
   This is a truth that Branch hopes will finally take hold of her
community, the truth that few people want to accept and to take
responsibility for, or so it seems.
</P>
<P>
   It is a truth that would require a hard look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   But Branch does it. Nearly every day of the week, for the past
five years, she has looked into the eyes of African-American youths
and seen their suffering. In turn, she tries to get them to see
reasons why they should love themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That, she says, requires them to take responsibility for their
actions and to reach inside for what they need to change the way
they respond to others.
</P>
<P>
   Branch's reach, however, is limited. With the exception of some
Fort Worth school and city officials, few have bought into the
program. Funding is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't be about money,'' she says. ``This is about our
children, and we can't wait any longer to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Branch is aware of recent news articles describing a drop in
juvenile crime, but she adds, ``when there is a cold in the
majority community, we've got pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what she means by that.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Branch and her program director, Charles Neal, sat
for one hour in a Tarrant County juvenile courtroom. In that one
hour, they saw eight youths brought before the judge. Six were
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so helpless,'' she said. ``Children look to us for
answers, and it used to be that no matter what they came to us for,
we had an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to ignore the fearful aloneness Branch describes in
the children she sees, because you can see it in their eyes. Not
just eyes that have never known support, but eyes hungry for love,
that force and mystery that we both extol and curse, but which none
of us has ever been able to explain, control or live without.
</P>
<P>
   You listen to Branch, and you know how she must feel. It feels
like the fussing little boy who just crawled into your lap, like
the future seeping through your fingers like water, carrying along
with it dreams, possibilities and hope.
</P>
<P>
   Branch said she believes that Man in the Mirror, which promotes
positive attitudes, independent thinking, high self-expectations,
moral values and hope, can counter the self-destructive behavior of
black youths.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that the past can seldom be undone, but neither does
it have to be all anyone ever sees. Not if we're willing to see
ourselves as we really are. But that requires a look in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
