<HEADER>
A6511 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FISHING-2TAKES-NY     07-15 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FISHING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BIG ONE GETS AWAY, BUT YOU STAY DRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 Rodes Fishburne, a former Alaskan fly-fishing guide, is currently
an associate editor at Forbes ASAP.  
 By RODES FISHBURNE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a big fish. I knew that as soon as it struck. Perhaps it
would be 15 to 20 pounds, maybe bigger. I clenched my jaw as I
tried to maneuver the leviathan toward the boat. This fish could
win me the tournament _ prizes, cash and all the rewards of being
one of the country's best anglers. Then without warning, my fishing
line snapped under the strain with a sickening twang.
</P>
<P>
   I groaned, leaned back in my chair and watched in astonishment
as a message flashed on the screen: ``Your hook didn't set, you
have lost a 24.5-lb. fish.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems there are no guarantees in the world of fishing
software, just as there are none when fishing for real fish.
</P>
<P>
   Think of fishing software _ in this case a bass fishing
tournament game designed to test skills by presenting realistic
fishing situations on a computer screen _ as simulated angling,
where would-be professional anglers try to outwit Artificially
Intelligent (AI) fish.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of a computer trying to tempt virtual fish into
taking virtual lures may seem like a neo-Luddite nightmare come to
life or evidence that computer game developers have gone completely
walleyed. Interestingly enough, it is neither: fishing software is
simply another example of the ubiquitous computer merging with one
of America's favorite pastimes.
</P>
<P>
   The best fishing programs try to teach anglers how to think
about certain fishing scenarios and how to piece the information
into a winning pattern that can be used to catch fish consistently
in the real world.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no guarantee that understanding how to catch
cyberbass in Lake Mead translates into success on the real Lake
Mead _ fish have free will, too _ the games do require you to think
about what you are doing instead of blindly clicking and casting.
</P>
<P>
   Another category of fishing software is river-reference CD-ROMs.
Like their game counterparts, these compendiums are built around
understanding how to fish real rivers. They use practical
information and historical data for each body of water to aid
traveling fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Fishing is like a crossword puzzle. Fit a couple of the pieces
together (water temperature, weather conditions) and you will be
ahead of the crowd. Fishing software can help you to understand,
and even practice, how to put the puzzle together.
</P>
<P>
   It cannot, however, replace the real experience of making your
first cast of the year, releasing a large trout or relaxing in the
great outdoors. Or, for that matter, snagging your hat, falling
into a beaver dam or running out of gasoline miles from the boat
dock.
</P>
<P>
   Pitting Your Wits Against Wiles of the Virtual Trophy Bass
</P>
<P>
   BASS MASTERS CLASSIC: TOURNAMENT EDITION
</P>
<P>
   (THQ Software; $29.95 to $34.95; Windows 95 and 98; to be
released Sept. 8.)
</P>
<P>
   TROPHY BASS 2 DELUXE
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Sports; $29.95; Windows 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's not going to be easy,'' says Shaw Grigsby, an
eight-time Bass Masters Classic qualifier, in the video
introduction to THQ's new bass tournament game. Fair warning
indeed. Built around the premise that you are vying for the title
of best bass fisherman on the planet, Bass Master Classic lets you
test your skills in the Super Bowl of fishing tournaments against
50 top fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   Did I have what it took to catch a cyberbass? Could I outthink
my computer? Well, sort of. My first tournament was on Lake Mead, a
three-day affair that had me zipping over the lake in search of
hungry fish. The early preview copy of Bass Master Classic that I
played uses an over-the-shoulder view of the caster to simulate the
view of a pro fisherman. Controls at the bottom of the screen allow
you to move the boat, set your casting target and watch your depth
finder for changes in bottom structure. A click on the tip button
calls up short video clips featuring Roland Martin, Paul Elias and
Ken Cook, top bass fishermen who try to point you in the right
direction. (According to the manufacturer, the final version of
Bass Masters Classic will have force-feedback support that will
allow the angler to feel a jerk on the joystick when a fish bites.)
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament, players select their fishing equipment
and rig up to seven rods with lures suitable for landing lunkers.
</P>
<P>
   By the virtual second day of my Lake Mead experience, I was in
50th place and still trying to figure out how to tempt a fish into
the boat. In the final two days, I was able to find and catch five
bass off a rocky point that dropped into deep water. The total
weight was 22 pounds _ hardly enough to win the tournament but
enough to keep me from getting demoted to chief minnow dipper.
</P>
<P>
   After Lake Mead, I looked for another tournament to fish and
found Trophy Bass 2 Deluxe. This software package consists of the
previously released Trophy Bass, Trophy Bass 2, the Northern Lakes
add-on pack and a revised how-to section.
</P>
<P>
   Trophy Bass Deluxe has high-quality production values, including
excellent background sounds, like the splash of jumping fish and
the dreaded crack of snapping line. Sierra Sports' game comes with
a list of 50 actual lakes in the United States. I picked Castiac
Lake in California. In the nonvirtual world, Castiac is one of the
best big-bass fishing lakes in the country, yielding largemouth
bass weighing more than 20 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   While the action on the water can be challenging, it is not
impossible to catch fish. Kurt Webber, lead designer for Sierra
Sports, said, ``We wanted to make this game as realistic as
possible without fully reproducing the frustration of going out and
not catching anything.'' Thanks, Kurt.
</P>
<P>
   After studying both photo and topographical maps of the lake, I
staked out my spot in a sheltered cove. I maneuvered the boat by
using the cursor keys while keeping an eye out for fish. Bingo!
Hidden beneath a lush aquatic mat of Lake Castiac vegetation was
the largest digital fish I had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got your number, Bubba,'' I whispered. After quickly
making a few tackle adjustments, I sent forth my first cast. A
``STRIKE,'' the screen flashed. But after rapidly reeling in the
fish, I realized that, just as in real fishing, a little
whippersnapper had beaten Bubba to the lure. Because of the
commotion, my behemoth was gone. Rats.
</P>
<P>
   In both games, pulling the mouse quickly after the fish strikes
performs the crucial maneuver known to anglers as ``setting the
hook.'' That mouse maneuver sounds like a good idea in theory, but
in my enthusiasm to land a pixelated bass, I found myself sweeping
all things unbolted from the top of my desk onto the floor. That
noise, followed by my whoop of ``Fish on'' after I successfully
hooked a bass, made it difficult for me to claim that I had been
working when I emerged from my office at home.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the most interesting and anthropologically fascinating
element of both games is not that you can fulfill your professional
bass fishing fantasy 24 hours a day, or even that you might get so
involved in the game that you accuse your computer of cheating. No,
the most interesting element is that you can fish against other
anglers around the world in Internet tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   I was quite surprised at the number of people fishing and using
chat rooms to talk to one another on line. Judging from their
familiarity with one another, this wasn't an occasional habit.
Turbo Dog, a 30-year-old man from Louisiana, said he fished every
night after work for an hour, via computer. His largest catch to
date: a 22.6-pound bass. And yes, he did print a screen capture to
save the memory. Computerized taxidermy has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   For Fly Fishermen, 5 Rivers
</P>
<P>
   TROPHY RIVERS
</P>
<P>
   (Sierra Sports; $29.95; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   Trophy Rivers is a new twist on the fishing game genre. It is
geared toward fly fishermen and uses rivers, not lakes, as the
water of choice. To be successful, players must learn how to read
water, consider fly-casting styles and match the appropriate fly
with water conditions.
</P>
<P>
   To begin the game, you must choose from among five well-known
North American rivers. There are more than 200 miles of digital
rivers, replete with rainbow, brown and brook trout as well as
Atlantic, chinook and coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth spending some time on the initial selection screen
reading river information, watching the interactive presentation
and examining the overview map for clues on how to approach each
river.
</P>
<P>
   While designing the game, the creators spoke with local river
experts to gather accurate information about specific insect
hatches on individual rivers. If you're on the Deschutes in June,
for example, you want to throw a stone fly, said Kurt Webber, lead
project manager for Sierra Sports. All the rivers have hatches in
the warmer months, so anglers should keep their eyes peeled.
</P>
<P>
   Trophy Rivers' graphics are impressive, with detailed riverbanks
and realistic fishing conditions. Depending on where you choose to
fish, you will be steering a sturdy drift boat or canoe while
scanning the river for likely lies. It is also possible to leave
the boat and wade if you want to work a piece of water over
especially thoroughly or just want to stretch your legs.
</P>
<P>
   Just as in real fishing, it is important to realize the impact
the current has on the way fish position themselves, just as in
real fishing. I found it helpful to position my boat slightly
upstream of visible fish and cast to them downstream when using a
streamer, and just the reverse, casting upstream, when using dry
flies.
</P>
<P>
   Be conscious of spooking the fish: get too close and your quarry
will scatter. (Just like the bass games, the software uses
Artificial Intelligence, or AI, to give fish their brainpower.) And
big fish make last-second runs near the boat _ as if they see a
vision of a crackling cast-iron skillet over a campfire. But Trophy
Rivers lets you release all fish back into the river, as many fly
fishermen do.
</P>
<P>
   Before it starts to sound as though computer fishing is harder
than the real thing, it is worth noting that in the middle of
writing this review, I took an actual fly-fishing trip to
California's Hat Creek. There I rediscovered, to my chagrin, that
live trout still have a far more powerful operating system than AI:
natural intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Guides to Unfamiliar Rivers
</P>
<P>
   FLYWATER INTERACTIVE
</P>
<P>
   (Flywater Publishing; $60; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98, and
Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   HATCH MASTER
</P>
<P>
   (Hatch Master Productions; $49.95; Windows 3.1, 95 and 98.)
</P>
<P>
   The Flywater and Hatch Master software packages provide a
glimpse of a new category of specific reference tools that can be
likened to river encyclopedias. If you have ever taken a
long-distance fishing trip to unfamiliar water and wished you had
some native advice on what to expect, these programs could be a
real boon for you.
</P>
<P>
   Flywater Interactive is a project spun off from the popular book
``Flywater'' (Chelsea Green, 1994), now in its third printing. The
CD-ROM contains 200 new photographs, short video clips, a database
of hatches for the United States and the book's text and photos.
Flywater shines once you have picked a river. Here you get
introductory information, including fishing regulations, a list of
local fly-fishing shops, tips and a chart suggesting which flies
should be used on each river.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs on the CD-ROM capture the beauty of the rivers
of the Rocky Mountains. Grant McClintock, the project's
photographer, spent four months visiting six states, fishing every
one of the 50 rivers and speaking with local guides.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch Master's Yellowstone Edition doesn't have the same quality
of photography as Flywater, but it does offer a wealth of
information about the Yellowstone area. Twenty-three fishing spots
are listed here, including the Madison, the Firehole, Slough Creek
and Henry's Fork. The heart of the Yellowstone software is the
Hatch Analyzer, which uses a matrix of date, weather, season and
snow melt information to determine what might be happening in area
rivers. If you have ever been a novice on a trout river and you're
wondering just what the fish are eating, you will appreciate how
helpful it would be to have the entomological history of a place at
your fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   The Hatch Analyzer made a good number of suggestions, often
numbering a dozen, of specific flies to try. It also gives
information for different times of day _ morning, afternoon and
evening _ which is about as comprehensive as anglers can get until
trout start e-mailing us about what's happening in the river.
</P>
<P>
   Because both packages offer advice on which flies to use on
specific rivers, I thought it would be interesting to see what each
said about a river they share in their database, the Yellowstone
River. For July, Flywater suggested using, among others, an Elk
Hair Caddis, Sofa Pillow or Bitch Creek. Hatch Master suggested an
Elk Hair Caddis, Madam X or Bullethead Rubberleg Salmonfly.
</P>
<P>
   Curious as to what was going on right then on the Yellowstone, I
called Bailey's Fly shop in Livingston, Mont., and asked a guide,
John Bailey, for some real-time information. He said, ``For the
last three years, you couldn't fish the Yellowstone in July because
of high, cold water.''
</P>
<P>
   What does he suggest? ``The river does get a large Caddis
hatch,'' he said; score two points for each program. ``Those
products are great for showing people what the rivers look like
but, before you come, talk to someone local,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
