<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6521 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BELIZE-CYBERCAFE-     07-15 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BELIZE-CYBERCAFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JUNGLE OUTPOST OFFERS BEER, MAYAN RUINS AND THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits) 
(duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
 (bl)  
 By DAN KOEPPEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN IGNACIO, Belize _ Pricey coffee and sleek hardware, enjoyed
by high-tech cognoscenti? Forget it. At Eva's cybercafe in San
Ignacio, Belize, the clientele is frayed; the machines are
weather-beaten, and _ as befits a frontier outpost _ the
refreshment of choice is beer, and plenty of it.
</P>
<P>
   But then, San Ignacio is hardly Silicon Alley. Just 10 miles
from the Guatemalan border, it is the last major town (pop. 7,100)
in Central America's least densely populated nation. Eva's cafe,
although no one seems to remember for whom it was named, has been a
San Ignacio fixture for nearly two decades _ a traditional meeting
place for weary backpackers on transcontinental walkabouts,
archaeologists excavating ruins in the jungles that surround the
town and grizzled expatriates far removed from their native lands.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Jones, 47, a former British army sergeant who is the
proprietor of Eva's, falls into the last category. But in the past
few months, he has seen his ragged bar become a destination for a
new clientele: cyberjunkies. In 1997, he installed a pair of
secondhand 486 computers. Soon, along with a Beliken (Belize's
national beer) and a place to sit, Jones' customers would drop by
for a quick e-mail fix before disappearing into the wild. Then, an
unexpected clientele emerged: local Belizeans, coming from remote
villages _ many with no phones or electricity _ began using the
cybercafe to correspond with friends and business connections all
over the world.
</P>
<P>
   On a day last spring, Jones collected a half-hour's usage fee
from a New York computer technician who had just sent 10 rapid-fire
e-mail postcards _ cutting and pasting the same message into each _
to friends back home. In the tourist season, there is often a line
out the door. Customers line up above an open concrete sewer
channel, waiting to pay $8 an hour for a turn at one of Jones'
terminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know a thing about computers,'' said Jones, who is
perpetually unshaven and has kept his Cockney accent despite 16
years in Belize. ``What I knew about was guns.''
</P>
<P>
   In Eva's earlier days, that was a useful skill. Jones bought the
cafe in 1982, a year after Belize's independence (it had been a
British colony), and his first job was to evict a regular clientele
that was, as Jones puts it, ``not so charming,'' mostly town drunks
and some ill-tempered post-colonials.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Jones began to offer advice to travelers passing through
the town, arranging trips to Tikal, the ruined Mayan city just over
the Guatemalan border, for example, or recommending local hotels.
Most customers stayed for a drink, or a meal, often stopping back
several times as they crisscrossed the country. Over the years,
Jones added a small souvenir stand and an outdoor patio.
</P>
<P>
   In this corner of Belize, Internet access came largely by
chance. An army buddy of Jones, David Cryer, needed work and, being
technically inclined, suggested a trial online run, with the
profits split 50-50. Jones and Cryer bought the computers from
businessmen who had spent some time in Belize and did not want to
haul the machines they had brought into the country back home.
Cryer has since become the town's cyberguru, maintaining the
computers at Eva's and finessing the relationship between the bar
and Belize's moody telephone monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   In the year or so since the computers arrived, Eva's has come to
resemble nothing less than a plugged-in analog to a Wild West
outpost, where residents of vast territories stumble in _ daily,
once a week, every month _ to pick up mail and have a few drinks.
Four times daily, Jones prints out up to 125 pages of messages
addressed to a special general delivery account; the notes are
sorted into folders. Urgent communications are hand-delivered by
four-wheel drive into the bush. Customers pay about 25 cents to 50
cents per page.
</P>
<P>
   On a Tuesday afternoon last spring, the temperature was around
100, nobody was on the street, and a daisy chain of clattering fans
tried in vain to push air around the bar. Gonzalo Pleitez, 24,
tapped furiously at one of Eva's machines. Pleitez had just rumbled
in from his family farm on the Vaca plateau, 20 miles away, in his
1986 Toyota pickup. His message is to an online friend in Long
Beach, Calif. _ a marketing executive with Walt Disney Co. _ who
gives Pleitez informal advice about promoting tours to an ancient
cave on his property.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Pleitez's older brother, William Gonzalez _
members of the family are native Maya Mopan, indigenous to this
part of Belize _ was hunting in the forest when his dog disappeared
into a hole in the ground. Peering in, Gonzalez realized he had
stumbled onto the entrance to a cave 1,000 feet deep. Inside was a
treasure trove of hundreds of intact examples of pre-Columbian
Mayan pottery. The family has been working with preservation
officials to keep the cave intact and open it to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, Pleitez says, is the final component in achieving
that goal. He rattled off a list of benefits: education for himself
and his brother; running water and electricity at the farm, which
currently has neither; better health care for Gonzalez's 7-year-old
daughter; the ability to book visits to the property directly,
instead of through outside agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts more control into our hands,'' Pleitez said. As he
signed off, Terry Powis, 33, a Canadian, arrived. He had just come
in from Cahal Pech, a 2,000-year-old Mayan city under excavation,
where he is field director for the Belize Valley Archaeological
Reconnaissance project. He has a list of things to do: pick up
supplies, visit a few local associates and get on line to
straighten out a student loan billing mess that he has just learned
of back in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   He sips a Beliken and waits his turn. Powis has been working in
Belize for 10 years. Eva's has radically changed the way his 35
archaeological staff members, most of them from the United States,
live their lives in the bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot revolves around our visits here,'' Powis said. ``We've
had romances and breakups, family emergencies and financial
crises,'' he said. Noting that old-fashioned postal mail takes two
weeks to reach the United States and direct-dial phone calls cost
$5 a minute, Powis explains that without Eva's Net connection, ``we
probably wouldn't be communicating at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones wants to usher Eva's customers even further into the
online revolution. Next, he says, is the building of Web sites. The
evening of Powis' visit, Cryer held a meeting to familiarize local
businesses with the Web. The cafe was crowded with visitors from 30
miles around. It was an enthusiastic crowd, but one thing struck
Jones as odd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first night I've ever sold more coffee than beer,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
