<HEADLINE>
UPGRADING TO WINDOWS 98? UPGRADE YOUR VOCABULARY, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(th) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depending on whom you ask, Windows 98 is either the easiest and
most stable operating system upgrade yet for personal computers or
an exasperating experience that plunges many users into the
technical swamps where they have to deal with unfamiliar things
like device drivers, BIOS upgrades, clean installs, registry
corruption and software incompatibilities.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's business as usual for an operating system
upgrade, except that this one is so popular that calls are
overwhelming Microsoft's support lines. In fact, Microsoft did not
expect the sales of Windows 98 to be as healthy as they have been.
</P>
<P>
   Independent market researchers say more than a half-million
copies of the $90 upgrade package were sold in the first few days
after its release on June 25, easily making it the most popular
software product of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Windows 98 was tested by more than 100,000 volunteer
users for many months before the release, reports of trouble with
it began to appear almost immediately after the official
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Several computer makers, including IBM, Compaq, Dell, Toshiba
and Gateway, posted advisories on their World Wide Web sites
cautioning owners of certain models that special steps were needed
to insure a smooth upgrade to Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate computer customers reported that the new software
failed to recognize some peripheral devices, network configurations
and plug-in cards. Consumers have occasionally been baffled by
unusual system crashes; inoperative floppy, CD-ROM and removable
hard drives; balky modems, and erratic performance.
</P>
<P>
   The reports of problems appear to be most prevalent during
upgrades on older computers, rather than with new computers that
have Windows 98 installed at the factory.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft advises the owners of any computer system, but
especially systems that are more than a year old, to check first
with the computer maker or with Microsoft before installing the
upgrade. Microsoft maintains an extensive (and growing) database of
Windows 98 compatibility notes on its Web site
www.microsoft.com/support and at www.microsoft.com/hwtest/hcl.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced computer users know that most new software has bugs,
or glitches. Virtually every software maker maintains a customer
support service to help users overcome problems with installation
and operation.
</P>
<P>
   Operating systems like Windows are extremely complex and have to
be written to accommodate hundreds of third-party hardware and
software products. Windows 98, for example, comes with more than
1,200 drivers that allow different computer components to work with
Windows 98 features.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says the number of complaints from users upgrading to
Windows 98 is significantly lower than for any previous system
upgrade, including the much more radical transition to Windows 95
from Windows 3.1.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anecdotal experience suggests that in any gathering of
recent Windows 98 upgraders, someone has a horror story about a
missing device driver, a laptop that seems suddenly possessed by
evil spirits or even the dreaded Windows ``Blue Screen of Death''
system crash.
</P>
<P>
   To handle Windows 98 problems, Microsoft increased its staff of
technical support workers by 40 percent, to more than 1,000
engineers, before releasing the upgrade. To accommodate consumers,
it has extended its free technical support hours into the weekends
since it started selling the upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But callers often find the free technical support lines, at
(425) 635-7222, to be interminably busy. While the free support
lines were inaccessible, Microsoft was offering swift assistance
for those who were interested in paying for technical help, at
either $35 per call or $295 for a service contract.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials in Redmond, Wash., said that an
unprecedented effort had been made to make Windows 98 software easy
to install and use and that the company had been pleased by the
relatively low number of customer service calls, considering the
number of copies of the software sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made huge progress in the ease of use and capabilities
of Windows PCs,'' said Brad Chase, the Microsoft vice president in
charge of Windows marketing. ``Just compare where we are at today
with where we were with Windows 3.1 and MS-DOS. We know that we
still have a lot of work to do, though.''
</P>
<P>
   With such a large volume of sales with a major Windows release,
Chase said, ``it is only natural that people hear about problems
even if as a percentage of the total they are small.'' But even the
relatively small number of complaints is too many, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials say there have been no reports of errors
leading to the loss of data, which would be the most serious type
of errors. Even so, several computer makers are urging their
customers, especially those with laptop and notebook computers, to
take special precautions before trying to install Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   Directions are typically found on the companies' Web sites. Dell
Computer, for example, warns owners of older Latitude notebooks to
postpone trying to upgrade them until updated software patches are
available later this summer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BEFORE TAKING THE FIRST STEP ...
</P>
<P>
   Here are some tips for a smoother upgrade to Windows 98:
</P>
<P>
   RAM: Windows 98 requires a minimum configuration of 16 megabytes
of RAM (at least 24 are recommended, and 32 are better), a 486DX
microprocessor and at least 195 megabytes of unused hard disk space
(and as much as 295 megabytes). Many users are trying to install
the software on machines that simply can't run it.
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS CHECKERS: Do a complete virus scan of your system. If the
computer is virus-free, then disable any virus-checking software
before installing any new software. Virus checkers will identify
Windows 98 as an intruder.
</P>
<P>
   MAKERS' LISTS: Before you buy Windows 98, call the maker of your
computer, or check the company's Web site, to determine if upgrade
problems have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   PERIPHERALS: If the computer has been upgraded with a video
card, Zip drive or any other plug-in component, check with the
maker of the peripheral before attempting the upgrade to see if new
drivers are needed. Again, many peripheral companies have Web sites
that address Windows 98 upgrade issues.
</P>
<P>
   CLEAN INSTALLATIONS: If possible, do a ``clean install.'' That
involves backing up every bit of important data and all
applications, reformatting the hard disk, reinstalling Windows 95
or Windows 3.1 from the original disks and then upgrading to
Windows 98. The ancillary benefit of a clean install is that it
creates an incentive to weed out unwanted files, improving system
performance.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER INSTALLATIONS: OK, so a ``clean install'' is a lot of
trouble. The next best approach is to install Windows 98 on top of
the existing operating system, trusting Microsoft to handle the
updating of all existing settings automatically. During the upgrade
process, the Windows 98 upgrade Wizard will ask whether the user
wants to make a copy of existing system files, just in case. Say
yes. You can always delete these files later, after Windows 98 has
proved to be stable.
</P>
<P>
   BIOS UPGRADE: In some cases, particularly for laptops, the
computer companies will recommend a so-called BIOS upgrade. The
BIOS, or basic input output system, is the fundamental code that
boots the system, connects the hard drive and manages the
peripheral devices. Many older laptops cannot take advantage of
Windows 98 features without a BIOS upgrade. That cannot easily be
done once Windows 98 is installed. The process typically involves
downloading special software from the computer company's Web site,
saving the downloaded BIOS upgrade software to a diskette and
rebooting the computer from the diskette. Then, if all works as
planned, the software will upgrade itself.
</P>
<P>
   INCOMPATIBILITIES: Check with the makers of any software
applications that you cannot live without and ask about any known
Windows 98 incompatibilities.
</P>
<P>
   TIMING: If you have waited three years for Windows 98, perhaps
another few months won't hurt. Microsoft's first bug-fixing
``service pack'' will be available this fall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
