<HEADLINE>
LEIF ERICSON'S LEGACY ON THE WEB AND WAVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(rm) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tale of the Titanic has drawn a great deal of public
interest since the end of last year, but another North Atlantic
maritime adventure _ and a more successful one at that _ is also
being remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Leif Ericson's discovery of ``Vinland'' during his journey from
Greenland to Newfoundland around the year 1000 is being observed in
a variety of ways on the Web. The Leif Ericson Millennium
Celebration site  &UR; (www.leif2000.org/lemc.dll/Default)  &LR; offers much
information, and a link from the Great Norwegians home page offers
a biography of Ericson , the European who is said to have beaten
Christopher Columbus to the New World by nearly 500 years
 &UR; (www.mnc.net/norway/ericson.htm) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ambitious observers of the event are a group of
adventurers who are setting out to recreate Ericson's journey as
authentically as possible in a replica of a Viking boat. Led by W.
Hodding Carter, 35, a writer, a crew of 10 took off on June 28 from
Nuuk, Greenland, to start a 1,500-mile trip called Viking Voyage
1000. Their final destination is L'Anse aux Meadows, Newfoundland.
Carter first became interested in Ericson's voyage when he read a
book about it in fifth grade. He tried the trip last year but ended
the voyage after six weeks because of a damaged rudder.
</P>
<P>
   Desktop sailors intrigued by the quest can follow along on the
official Viking Voyage 1000 Web site,  &UR; (www.beyond.landsend.com) &LR; ,
which features daily journals, pictures and audio clips from the
ship's crew members. The site, part of the project's sponsorship by
the Lands' End company, also has sections devoted to Viking lore
and ships.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of 10th- and 20th-century technologies melding, the
expedition's ship, an open-decked, 54-foot wooden knarr, is
carrying some sophisticated equipment. ``We have two digital
cameras on board, and we have two laptops that are
water-resistant,'' Carter said via his cellular phone from
Greenland before the launching. ``All the keys are in a heavy-duty
plastic. They seem indestructible with the cases they're in, but
this is a pretty rough boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Rough, indeed. No cruise ship with on-deck shuffleboard and
fancy radar systems for these guys. Navigation will be done the
old-fashioned way, by the sun and stars, along with naval charts,
compasses and a sextant. The boat is powered only by oars or wind;
it has a 35-foot canvas sail.
</P>
<P>
   Crew members will stop on shore an average of every other day to
hike, explore and greet people. Carter said he hoped to complete
the trip in 8 to 10 weeks, but like Ericson, he and the crew are at
the mercy of the elements. ``Some days we can make 100 miles if we
really get lucky, and some days we make about two miles or nothing
waiting for the right wind,'' Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   Several sets of traditional Norse clothes are on board. The
outfits weigh 60 pounds each. ``I plan to try to live in the Viking
outfit for one week,'' Carter said. ``I'm dreading that more than
anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
