<HEADLINE>
OUSTED NEWSPAPER COLUMNIST FOCUSES ON HER POETRY, NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In her writing, Patricia Smith has always played
with fire.
</P>
<P>
   Known as a dynamic performance poet, an iconoclastic writing
teacher and an incendiary newspaper columnist who challenged
attitudes about race as an African-American woman, Smith was
consumed last month in a conflagration of her own making.
</P>
<P>
   Forced to resign June 18 amid a firestorm of controversy as a
columnist for the Boston Globe after she admitted making up
characters and quotes in work that purported to be fact, Smith has
since retreated to straightforward fiction writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm busy working on my novel, looking ahead and not back,''
Smith said in a recent telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake in judgment and freely admitted that,'' she
said. ``I want to move on now. I may never have a better
opportunity than this to write a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   The notoriety of her resignation is a double-edged sword. ``My
agent figures it's a good time now to take the novel proposal to
publishers,'' Smith said. ``There's been some interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 43, spoke in a weary monotone and seemed unnerved about
being in the eye of a storm.
</P>
<P>
   The Smith affair was only one piece in a recent stew of
breakdowns of journalistic standards that set off a round of media
criticism and reflection. The New Republic recently fired writer
Stephen Glass for fabricating parts of 27 articles. A Cincinnati
Enquirer reporter was fired for unethical conduct and the paper
made a $10 million payment to Chiquita Brands. CNN and Time
apologized and retracted a story alleging U.S. commandos used nerve
gas to kill American defectors during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Smith did not wish to discuss these developments or the
counter-accusations that surfaced in the wake of her being forced
to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney and Harvard Law School professor Alan
Dershowitz took Smith's side and accused the Globe of applying a
double standard ``based on race, gender and ethnicity.'' Dershowitz
said the newspaper should have demanded that columnist Mike
Barnicle also resign for allegedly fabricating a demeaning quote he
attributed to Dershowitz several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In extensive follow-up stories it published about its own
internal investigation into the veracity of its columnists, the
Globe concluded that there was no evidence to suggest Barnicle
fabricated quotes or people in his columns. Smith admitted to four
fabrications in columns this year.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the end of the story, though. In a message to
readers published in the Globe, editor Matthew Storin said there is
evidence that 48 additional Smith columns since 1995 might have
contained fabrications. Storin said an investigation is ongoing and
Smith will be asked to review those columns under suspicion for
possible inventions of people whose identities cannot be
documented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't read any of those stories. I don't see any need to
read them,'' Smith said. She said she has not returned to the Globe
offices since she resigned and has not had contact with her former
editors or co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those colleagues and readers who salivated daily at the
thought of my head on a platter, congrats,'' Smith wrote in her
final Globe column on June 19, a piece at once apologetic and
defiant. She has declined to comment in follow-up Globe stories.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
