<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6562 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUSTED-COLUMNIST-2NDT     07-15 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUSTED-COLUMNIST-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 ALBANY, N.Y.: follow-up Globe stories.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the telephone interview, Smith was reluctant to meet the
issue of her Globe ouster head-on. She evaded, deflected and
refused to respond to questions about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk about poetry, my novel and my other writing.
This is not the forum to get into everything about my
resignation,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A sought-after speaker at writing conferences, Smith said her
remarks would remain unchanged. ``I won't say anything differently
because of this,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll continue to say a writer must be fueled by a real love of
writing. You can't let people cage you as a writer,'' Smith said.
``You should write as many ways as possible. I still believe in
blurring the lines between genres.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her final Globe column, Smith said she lacked traditional
journalism training. She took courses at two universities, but
never completed a degree and instead ``was fueled by a heady
mixture of naivete, ambition, and an almost insane love for the
powers of language.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith shaped and reshaped her lyrical, poetic style into a
variety of forms: columns, poetry, screenplays, drama, jazz songs.
``And as accolades poured in, I strained to accomplish more,''
Smith wrote in her final column. Smith had her biggest year in
journalism in 1997, winning an American Society of Newspapers
Editors distinguished writing award (revoked after her resignation)
and being named a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize in commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't establish priorities, and the first casualty was
time,'' wrote Smith, who collaborated with Nobel Prize-winning poet
Derek Walcott on a play, won four national poetry ``slam''
competitions, performed in Brazil and throughout Europe, published
three volumes of poetry and won literary prizes.
</P>
<P>
   She described the fabrications in her column as having arisen
out of the pressure of time to meet myriad writing deadlines and
speaking commitments, which involved frequent travel, and a desire
to make the column sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``From time to time in my metro column, to create the desired
impact or slam home a salient point, I attributed quotes to people
who didn't exist,'' Smith wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She did not elaborate in the telephone interview. But she was
happy to talk about the nonfiction book she recently completed, her
first, ``Africans in America.'' It will be published in October by
Harcourt Brace as a companion work to a four-part PBS documentary
on slavery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was handed all the research from the film and shaped it into
a book,'' Smith said. ``Charles Johnson is a fiction writer who
contributed several short stories to the book. We blur the lines.
It's not totally a nonfiction book or a book of short stories. It's
both.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing project foremost in Smith's mind is her novel,
tentatively titled ``Yummy.'' That was the real-life nickname for
an 11-year-old gang member in Chicago who was executed. Smith said
she plans to base her novel on the youth's life.
</P>
<P>
   Smith knows something of Yummy's world. She grew up on Chicago's
West Side, in a poor black neighborhood. She was the only child of
Annie and Otis Smith, both of whom worked in a candy factory. Her
mother still lives in Chicago. Her father was murdered 21 years ago
during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Smith studied at Southern Illinois University and Northwestern
University, but did not complete a degree. She was a single mother
who raised a son, Damon Smith, now 22, who has a 3-year-old
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she would not dismiss out of hand the possibility of
working again for a newspaper. She said she would wait to weigh any
offers she may receive.
</P>
<P>
   Smith admitted to a twinge of loss at ending, at least for now,
her journalism career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for 20 years and I guess I'll miss it, the way I
would miss selling insurance if I did that for 20 years,'' she
said. ``I'm not panicking over what to do next. I'll keep writing
and look at the possibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
