u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-WEB-CONCERTS-NYT &LR;      07-15 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-CONCERTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB BROADCASTS: BUMPS IN THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(th) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am still trying to repress memories of my own
aborted attempt to use the Internet as a broadcast medium. Back in
1996, I was the host of a weekly online show called ``Web Whirl,''
the goal of which was to take the audience along on a tour of a
dozen or so Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The show didn't work because most home users were at the wrong
end of an information bottleneck. Relying on fickle modem
connections, their online forays resembled uneasy games of Russian
roulette. Would they connect on the first try? Or even the second?
Would their connections fail in the middle of downloading a Web
page? After a few months, the show was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   So when I heard that Intel Corp. was planning to broadcast the
live performances of 300 bands on line this week and call the
adventure a ``music festival,'' my first reaction was skepticism.
After all, not much has changed in the past two years to erase the
obstacles that doomed ``Web Whirl.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, with most home users still relying on finicky modems,
will the so-called streaming video clip from a concert arrive
instead as herky-jerky niblets of image?
</P>
<P>
   I hoped not. But my first glance at the Web page for the
festival (which began Wednesday night and will run through
Saturday) did not reassure me. The broadcast site at
www.intelfest.com instructed me to download the software tool Real
Player from Real Networks so I could hear and see the online
performances. But my first two attempts failed because somewhere
between the computer where Real Player was archived and my own
desktop, the connection failed.
</P>
<P>
   With 300 bands playing live in 20 New York City clubs for the
four-day period, Intel faces an even greater technical challenge.
For each band, the club sets up a microphone to capture vocals and
the softer instruments like flutes and violins, mixing those sounds
at a main sound desk. Another microphone supplied by Intel picks up
other instruments, like drums and guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Then the feeds from both microphones are mixed and prepared for
online broadcast on a personal computer that encodes the sound and
translates it into digital bits. Intel broadcasts the digital
transmission through two dual-Pentium II 333-megahertz servers,
which in turn distribute the signals over the Internet.
Performances at five clubs are also being broadcast in a
simultaneous video feed.
</P>
<P>
   The home users with the best chance of enjoying the performances
are those with newer equipment. While you might technically be able
to connect to the festival's Web site on a poky old 486 machine, I
doubt that you could enjoy the experience with anything less than a
microprocessor that runs at 166 megahertz and employs MMX
technology to enhance audio and video.
</P>
<P>
   As for modem speed? Well, frankly, there is no dial-up modem
that pushes sound and video across the Net reliably enough _ or
fast enough _ to satisfy me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So why bother?'' the curmudgeon in me wondered. The whole
venture sounded like a flashback to the early days of radio or TV,
with the broadcasters relying on an uneasy combination of prayer,
spit and willpower to overcome inevitably choppy transmissions. But
then, those early broadcasts, imperfect though they may have been,
were exciting partly because of the unknown limits of raw
technology. The roughness was fraught with endless possibility.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe I was being unfair to the Internet _ and to Intel _ by
expecting too much too soon from this nascent medium. Why not give
everyone points for trying?
</P>
<P>
   During a similar festival that Intel sponsored last year,
125,000 computer users tuned in, er, connected _ five times as many
as attended the live performances. Weren't those numbers an
indication that the experiment was at least somewhat successful in
increasing people's access to music?
</P>
<P>
   A closer look at the schedule on the festival Web site also
swayed me. The musicians in that eclectic group of 300 bands, whose
sounds include rock, punk, rap, jazz and folk _ would surely not
have agreed to participate in this endeavor if they felt that the
medium failed to convey their message. There must be benefits from
playing to an online audience that would outweigh the apparent lack
of intimacy between performer and listener.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to ask a singer, Victoria Williams, who was scheduled
to perform in the festival live (and on line) at the Bowery
Ballroom on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A few days before the performance, I spoke on the phone to Ms.
Williams to tell her that I had just been listening to the folky,
lyrical stories she sang on ``This Moment in Toronto With Victoria
Williams,'' recorded live in 1995. ``Do you think that you will
interact differently with an online audience?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   There was a moment of silence on the phone that lasted just long
enough to make me wonder if the connection had failed. ``I had no
idea that this is an online concert that I'm doing,'' Ms. Williams
said. ``I thought it was a live concert.''
</P>
<P>
   I explained about the computers that would transmit her
performance across the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean that people are going to be able to watch it on their
computers, but it will sound kind of broken up, with herky-jerky
video?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   I told her I wasn't sure whether the Bowery Ballroom was one of
the five clubs that would transmit simultaneous video. (I quickly
tried to check the Web site for her, but my connection stalled.)
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Williams sounded so unhappy about the possibility that I
felt bad for her. ``Maybe it will all work fine,'' I said, trying
to sound as if I had not lived through the broadcast disappointment
of ``Web Whirl.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, I went on, here was a medium that might have the
power to propel her music to a whole new audience _ to millions of
people around the world who could not physically attend her
concert. Maybe the Internet would prove to be as potent a broadcast
tool as television had been in 1964 when Ed Sullivan introduced the
Beatles to 73 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't that be great?'' I said cheerily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just never seen it like that, but it would be
incredible,'' Ms. Williams agreed. She paused again. ``Or maybe the
band and I could just walk kind of herky-jerky in the club, and
shuffle our feet a bit, to give the live audience the Internet
experience.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
