<HEADER>
A6584 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-$ADV1     07-15 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-$ADV19-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEDIUMS MAKE LIKE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Only a few years ago, John Lithgow was appalled at
the notion of appearing in a television series. A character actor
with a respectable theater and film career, Lithgow viewed the
prospect of appearing on television with a disdain largely typical
among his acting friends. It was a medium that most serious actors
_ and writers and directors _  &UR; left, &LR;  not entered; a refuge for,
let's face it, actors and filmmakers whose careers had hit a brick
wall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two of his longtime friends, the successful comedy writers
Bonnie and Terry Turner, told him they had written the pilot script
for an oddball sitcom, ``Third Rock From the Sun,'' about some
brainy, wacky aliens struggling to be human. Lithgow's film career
had stumbled a bit with potboilers like ``Ricochet'' and
``Cliffhanger.'' He was nearing 50. His agent read the pilot and
laughed. The actor nervously told his friends that he was thinking
of signing on. ``They looked at me like I had gone nuts,'' he
recalled recently.
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow has now won two Emmy Awards for the show, which is about
to enter its fourth season. His salary has hit $150,000 per
episode. And he has hardly suffered any loss of esteem in the eyes
of critics or his fellow actors. ``What in the world was I so
afraid of?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is hardly alone. A tide of movie and theater actors, as well
as established film writers, directors and producers, are surging
into a medium that they once scorned. And just as important, the
gates of movie studios have been flung open to television actors
and writers after decades of not-so-benign neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television was once a real stigma,'' said Sally Field, a
two-time Academy Award winner who began her acting career on 1960s
and 1970s sitcoms like ``Gidget'' and ``The Flying Nun.'' ``You
were soiled goods,'' she continued. ``It didn't matter that you had
a built-in audience. I couldn't get in the door. They told me I
wasn't pretty enough, I wasn't good enough to be in movies. There
was this incredible prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Because of a blend of financial, demographic and,
yes, esthetic factors, this sort of Hollywood wall has collapsed,
resulting in the creation of a kind of mega-entertainment universe:
actors, writers and filmmakers flow back and forth between the
mediums in a way that was unthinkable five or six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the advent of VCR's and cable, half the time you're
watching movies on TV anyway, so the whole distinction between
movies and television has blurred,'' said Marshall Herskovitz,
executive producer of television shows like ``Thirtysomething'' and
``My So-Called Life'' and the director of movies like the recent
``Dangerous Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the world of television commercials and music
videos has, in the eyes of studio executives, become a place to
discover young directors makes the confluence of mediums even more
pronounced. And what about ``The X-Files''? Is it a television
series? A film? A little of both?
</P>
<P>
   But while the flow of talent is going in two directions, the
benefits may not be. In this evolution, television seems to be
flourishing and movies floundering.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, there are plenty of grindingly inane sitcoms on
television, and too many formulaic dramas. But there are also shows
like ``Homicide'' (created by, among others, the acclaimed movie
director Barry Levinson), ``Ally McBeal'' (created by David Kelley,
who moves back and forth), ``E.R.,'' ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'' and
``Frasier.'' Is there any question that they aren't better each
week than most movies? Whatever compromises are made on weekly
television, the talented writers on the best shows have far more
leverage, control and creative freedom than their counterparts in
feature films, where the stars and directors are the ones treated
like royalty by the studios and producers. And the result is a
surprising number of gutsy, superbly written shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago television's value system was to represent
the broadest spectrum of mass American culture,'' said Herskovitz.
``But as the television world became more fragmented, and people
had far more choice, its look became less bland, less middle-of-the
road, more varied. It became safer for people with a more
individual vision to reveal it.''
</P>
<P>
   Individual vision in mainstream films is left to a handful of
directors like Woody Allen, James Brooks, who began his career on
television, and Martin Scorsese, who has signed a deal with ABC to
create a series. The ever-expanding universe of independent films
has nurtured its own handful of auteurs, but they often move
rapidly into the studio system, as in the case of Quentin Tarantino
(``Pulp Fiction,'' ``Jackie Brown''), or have to pay the way for
their own idiosyncratic movies by rewriting studio screenplays, as
in the case of the veteran John Sayles (``Lone Star'').
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many, the quality of Hollywood films has been
diminished by the ballooning expense of making a mainstream feature
(a $70 million film with a star is considered a steal), the
overseas market's increasing craving for action movies, the
obsession with effects-laden films and the abdication of studio
power to big-name stars, directors, producers and even agents. And
many believe that in this new intermingling, movies have adopted
the worst of television while television has adopted the best of
movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more feature films look like episodic television, and
I see a tremendous lack of originality in the way a lot of shots
are composed and the lighting,'' said the director John
Frankenheimer, who has been working in both mediums in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
