</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCH STRIKES PROVERBIAL BLOW FOR THE SWAT TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To spank or not to spank? What kind of a question is that?
</P>
<P>
   My family's favorite proverbs set the tone for our household.
``The rod of correction imparts wisdom, but a child left to himself
disgraces his mother. Discipline your son, and he will give you
peace; he will bring delight to your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about all of that, but he sure will straighten up
and fly right for a few miles. I only mention this because I was
reading about an amazing bit of research the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Some highbrow research group has compiled an impressive stack of
data indicating that a loving whack on the behind won't send Junior
into therapy or turn him into a sociopath.
</P>
<P>
   And get this: Girls who get spankings don't always start barroom
brawls or grow up and marry abusive spouses. Well, I'll be. Do you
know what I find amazing about this research? I'm amazed that
someone spent good money to find out what the casjier over at the
fruit market could have told them for free.
</P>
<P>
   I never really totally bought the notion of time out. Time out
is when you make kids do something really boring, like sit still in
a chair or stand in a corner for a few minutes while they think
about their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Time out is OK for toddlers, but sending a 9-year-old to his
room for punishment is like sending a house dog into the back yard.
On the other hand, if it's 150 degrees like it's been lately, I
suppose that is a pretty severe punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's a bad analogy, but you know what I mean. The
punishment has to fit the crime. Perhaps that's the problem. Maybe
some parents were actually using an iron rod to spank their kids,
and that's why some experts began to offer the nonviolent theory of
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Undeniably, 99 percent of the time, a good lecture and the loss
of privileges will result in the appropriate change in behavior for
most children. However, there is that other 1 percent of the time
when all else has failed and a parent's gotta do what a parent's
gotta do.
</P>
<P>
   The current school of thought is that three or four open hand
swats to the behind of older children or the hand of toddlers is
perfectly acceptable parenting.
</P>
<P>
   However, you may want to check with local authorities and your
pediatrician before you make any decisions on behavior modification
for your children.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't, but it's a good idea. Anything other than an open hand
is dangerous and could cause irreparable harm to your child. One of
my good friends has a noticeable limp because her father used to
beat her with a belt buckle. Of course, people like that don't
listen to child rearing experts anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But if our children don't learn discipline at home, where will
they learn it? Will they learn it inside a jail cell? Will they
learn it in detention hall? Will they learn it from the coach who
benches them for being insubordinate or the boss who fires them for
repeated tardiness? How about from the college professor who fails
them because they didn't turn in their homework?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's all related. We all need to learn the boundaries of
acceptable behavior, and the best place to learn that is at home.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your children don't ever need spanking. Good. Great. Bully
for you. I rarely spank my own children. But when push comes to
shove and I've exhausted every other option, I use my last resort.
It always works. And it's certainly nice to know that I've got a
seal of approval from God _ and a few other experts.
</P>
<P>
   Spare the rod, spoil the child.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
