<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-BUDGET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
DIGLA-WEB (Los Angeles) _ So, you figure Curtis Hanson and those
slacker boys, Affleck and Damon, got lucky when they won best
screenplay Oscars this year, huh? Now you and other budding
screenwriters can show off at least a tad of talent online in the
Rough Cut Screenplay Challenge. By David Bloom. 
. 
PAULS-SOAPS (Los Angeles) _ Agoura actor Paul Satterfield and
singer/songwriter/recovering alcoholic Paul Williams play an odd
couple as new members of the cast of ``The Bold and The
Beautiful.'' By Carol Bidwell. 
. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-2NDTA     07-15 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-2NDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: recent years.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sydney Pollack, a leading veteran filmmaker, believes the
problem goes deeper. ``The biggest impact has been on the attention
span,'' he said. Pollack's company, Mirage, has produced television
dramas on cable and is moving into network television next season
with the series ``The Last Defense,'' about public defenders in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``This generation of kids has grown up with entertainment being
fed to them in a mosaic pattern: they put on a headset and listen
to rock music while watching television without sound and doing
their homework,'' said Pollack. ``Culture now is being communicated
in a mosaic, not a linear pattern. It's MTV sound bites, and that
has influenced the way we make movies. We make pictures in the form
of bites rather than `once upon a time.'''
</P>
<P>
   The results are, at best, ``Pulp Fiction,'' and, at worst, the
dozens of ``Pulp Fiction'' imitations, by young people who don't
have Tarantino's vitality and audacity. Structurally, these
derivative films are often noisy, jagged and loosely plotted and
carry one message from the chest-pounding directors: pay attention
to me and my style. The contrast between these filmmakers and _ to
cite just one golden age of American movie making _ the supple,
emotionally complex narrative style of directors like John Ford,
Howard Hawks and Billy Wilder is a bleak one.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be getting worse. Implicit in Pollack's comments is
the fact that so many movies are now being made primarily for
teen-agers. Movie studios, even more than television companies, are
obsessed with teen-agers because there are so many of them (in the
year 2010 there will be 42 million, up from 38 million last year)
with vast spending power, amounting to $80 billion or more. The
billion-dollar-plus worldwide box office for ``Titanic,'' coupled
with the ascension of Leonardo DiCaprio as a new James Dean, and
the success of teen-age horror films like ``Scream'' and ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer'' will only reinforce the studios'
tendency to recycle masses-friendly concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a tremendous emphasis in the last two years on
the rediscovery of the youth market, and the feature-film industry
is going to turn to one place, television, where all these young
people are,'' said Peter Chernin, president and chief operating
officer of News Corp., which includes Fox Inc. ``So you turn to
`Party of Five' and `Dawson's Creek' and `Buffy, the Vampire
Slayer' and `Friends' and the others.''
</P>
<P>
   With his partner, the director Ron Howard, Brian Grazer is one
of Hollywood's most successful producers (``Liar, Liar,'' ``Apollo
13,'' ``The Nutty Professor''), and their company is producing
three television series next year. When it comes to movies these
days, he said, studios seem to be actually looking to television
for guidance, a dubious tactic. ``Movies,' he said, ``rely so much
on research, on demographics, on who's seeing movies, so when the
movie guys marry that information with what's successful on
television, they say, `Let's rebottle that sensibility into
movies.'''
</P>
<P>
   What this rebottling represents is certainly not auspicious for
films. Studios have been consumed with what Entertainment Weekly
recently called ``the ever-growing slag heap of television shows
being turned into feature films.'' Certainly there have been
commercial successes, like ``The Fugitive,'' ``George of the
Jungle,'' ``Mission: Impossible'' and most of the ``Star Trek''
movies. But there have been far more duds: ``Flipper,'' ``Beverly
Hillbillies,'' McHale's Navy,'' ``Leave It to Beaver'' and ``Dennis
the Menace,'' for example. And coming soon to the local multiplex
are ``The Avengers,'' ``Mod Squad,'' ``Rugrats'' and ``My Favorite
Martian.'' And a half-dozen more television shows are in
development as movies.
</P>
<P>
   If so much of television is such a bad example, why are so many
good filmmakers happily shifting their attention to television? In
addition to directors like Pollack, Levinson and Brooks, reputable
screenwriters like Kevin Williamson, Aaron Sorkin and John Lee
Hancock and top producers like Jerry Bruckheimer, Harvey Weinstein
and Mark Johnson are now going back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, movie people are startled by the speed of
television. ``I couldn't believe how quickly things happen on TV,''
said Mark Johnson, whose producing credits include prominent movies
like ``Rain Man,'' ``Donnie Brasco'' and ``Bugsy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the screenwriter John Lee Hancock, he recently pitched an
idea for a television show about three middle-aged doctors in Los
Angeles. CBS asked for a script to be produced in three weeks.
Hours after the script arrived, Leslie Moonves, the president of
CBS Television, gave the project the green light. It will be
broadcast on Monday nights this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the movie world,'' said Johnson, ``it would take six weeks
just to start finalizing everyone's deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer hunger among network and cable channels for product
and, perhaps most important, the increasing tendency of the studios
to avoid a certain sort of dramatic movie are also crucial factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios are kind of like the cities,'' said Frankenheimer.
``They've wiped out the middle class. They're either interested in
$8 million films or $80 million films. A lot of directors like to
do middle-class movies that are character-based films, about real
people, real issues. A great many of these are being done on cable
TV today.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of HBO's recent successful dramas _ ``Don King: Only in
America,'' ``Citizen Cohn,'' ``Barbarians at the Gate'' and ``Miss
Evers' Boys'' _ are precisely the kind of socially aware,
medium-budget films that flourished in Hollywood in the 1970s. At
that time, in the grip of their own confusion about what was
happening in the nation, studios gave young filmmakers like
Scorsese and Francis Ford Coppola extraordinary freedom. ( Coppola
is also working on a television show.)
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, European television is way ahead of even HBO. For
years, Channel Four in Britain and Canal Plus in France, among
others, have helped finance and produce the kind of character- and
story-driven movies for theatrical release that are made in the
United States by quasi-independent companies like Miramax, Fine
Line and October Films.
</P>
<P>
   Frustration at the feature-film system seems epidemic among even
A-list film directors. ``Movies are becoming, more and more, just
concept pieces, high-energy and high-voltage pieces,'' said
Levinson, who has struggled to walk a delicate line between making
personal films like ``Diner'' and ``Wag the Dog'' and directing
studio concoctions like ``Sphere.'' ``Studios want sizzle, they
want movie stars. And television is dealing with the society we're
living in.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, would his colleague Pollack be able to make ``They
Shoot Horses, Don't They?,'' his provocative 1969 film about a
Depression-era dance marathon. ``Never in a million years,'' said
Levinson. ``It's a downbeat picture. People would look at it and
say, `This is a downer, how do you sell it, it doesn't fit into an
easy genre.'''
</P>
<P>
   But flexibility, creative freedom and art are hardly the only
factors motivating movie makers to move into television.
Extraordinary amounts of money are being earned there, largely
because of the sale of syndication rights. Paul Reiser and Helen
Hunt, the stars of ``Mad About You,'' recently renewed their
contracts for $1 million per episode. Producers like Marcy Carsey
and Tom Werner (``The Cosby Show,'' ``Roseanne''), Steven Bochco
(``L.A. Law,'' ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'') and Jerry Seinfeld and Larry
David (``Seinfeld'') are far wealthier than, say, Hollywood's
producer-director of the moment, James Cameron (``Titanic'').
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
