<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6592 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-3RDTA     07-15 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOVIE-ACTORS-3RDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: (``Titanic.'')  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As powerful as the flow from films to television is, the hunger
among writers and directors _ not to mention young and not-so-young
actors like DiCaprio and Sarah Michelle Gellar, George Clooney and
Helen Hunt _ to voyage the other way is still great. Films are
still seen as _ sexier. And no matter how lucrative and creatively
freewheeling television may be, some agents, stars and writers
still condescend to the medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so ironic _ you can create a half-hour situation comedy
that makes $600 million in profits or make a movie called `Slasher
Bunnies 2' and the sitcom is treated with disdain by some movie
people,'' said Matt Williams, the executive producer of
``Roseanne'' and the creator of ``Home Improvement.'' ``To do a bad
slasher movie has more prestige than a quality half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true that television has sent gifted stars, directors and
writers into movies, but the degree to which these people have been
able to influence the way movies are made is difficult to gauge.
Often mentioned as the paradigm is Brooks, the creator of shows
like ``Taxi,'' The Mary Tyler Moore Show,'' ``Lou Grant'' and ``The
Simpsons.'' He moved into films with successes like ``Terms of
Endearment,'' ``Broadcast News'' and ``As Good as It Gets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that television does,'' Brooks said with a
tone of nostalgia. ``If you're doing a series it happens so quickly
that it's much more informal and less self-conscious, and
self-conscious is the enemy of creativity. Personal writing is
taken for granted. If a show is successful the bosses go away. You
come in on Monday morning and someone says, `A funny thing happened
this weekend,' and you say, `Let's put it on the show.'''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this sense of improvisation, informality and
risk-taking stamps Brooks' films, but it's perhaps less evident in
the work of other television directors who successfully made the
transition into movies, like Ron Howard, Michael Mann, Penny
Marshall and Rob Reiner. For all these directors' distinctiveness,
the impact of television is not especially evident in their films.
Similarly, the movie stars who began on television, like Clint
Eastwood, Steve McQueen, John Travolta, Tom Hanks, Eddie Murphy,
Robin Williams and Jim Carrey, are perceived as movie stars, not
actors who gain anything by being associated with the other medium.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question of whether the new intertwining of
television and movies will yield a new kind of star, whose energy,
presence or mystery will somehow differ from that of yesterday's
kings and queens of Hollywood. Will this new star _ Lithgow and Ms.
Hunt may be the prototypes _ be able to go back and forth regularly
from small screen to large without being condescended to? Will he
or she be a more intimate acquaintance for viewers?
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they really know you on television _ you're familiar
and comfortable to them, not like a movie star at all,'' said
Angela Lansbury, who moved from a long career in MGM films to
Broadway shows like ``Sweeney Todd'' and ``Mame'' to a hugely
successful 12-year-run on CBS' ``Murder She Wrote'' as the
endearing mystery writer Jessica Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come up and touch me,'' she said. ``They feel they
really know Jessica, they feel that intimacy. It's scary and very
dear. To be honest, I avoided television like the plague. I felt it
burned actors out. I used to think familiarity bred contempt. But I
was so wrong. Familiarity bred trust. And an enormous audience.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
