<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAULS-SOAPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO DIVERSE ADDITIONS TO `B&AMP;B' CAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The long and the short of it is that ``The Bold
and the Beautiful,'' the most-watched daytime drama around the
world, has just added two Pauls to its cast: Agoura actor Paul
Satterfield, a hunky Christopher Reeve look-alike, and Paul
Williams, the Oscar-winning songwriter who makes his home above
Sunset Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   It's a visually unlikely on-screen pairing for the two, who play
best friends and business partners on the CBS soap. Satterfield is
6 foot 4 inches tall; Williams stands 5 foot 2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say it's like lighting two different shows,'' joked
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the physical attributes we possess, we have to try
not to play Mutt and Jeff, Abbott and Costello,'' Satterfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' appearance on the soap marks his first acting gig
eight years into sobriety. During his recovery from a decade of
alcohol and cocaine abuse, he abandoned acting and music to become
a UCLA-certified drug and alcohol counselor.
</P>
<P>
   The stint on ``B&AMP;B'' is a return to soaps for Satterfield, who
previously appeared on daytime's ``General Hospital'' and the
nighttime serial ``Savannah,'' and just finished playing the lead
in an independent theatrical film, ``Duty Dating,'' set for release
next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Both actors have signed on with the show for two years.
</P>
<P>
   Satterfield portrays Pierce Peterson, a multimillionaire
motivational speaker (much like real-life infomercial king Tony
Robbins) who arrives to energize the other folks on ``B&AMP;B.''
Williams, as Bailey Masterson, plays the guru's buddy, confidant
and business manager, who is also a recovering alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville-born Satterfield, who has guest-starred on
``Veronica's Closet,'' Murder One,'' ``7th Heaven'' and other
prime-time shows, appeared in a couple of best-forgotten films
before ``Duty Dating.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, in which he stars with Lauren Sinclair as his love
interest, allows fans to see Satterfield's chiseled features
differently for the first time. ``To do this, I didn't have to be
handsome,'' he said. ``My hair's kinda long and scraggly. I wear my
glasses. You'd think, `This guy would never get the girl.' But I
get the girl. It was a romantic comedy, a lot of fun to do.''
</P>
<P>
   After finishing the film, he got a call from ``B&AMP;B,'' which his
agent turned down at first because he thought Satterfield would
view daytime drama with disdain. He was wrong; Satterfield was
thrilled. ``I never said I wouldn't go back to daytime,'' he said.
``It's a great gig.''
</P>
<P>
   For Williams, a return to acting signals the beginning of a
whole new life without chemical stimulation. The lyricist, who was
nominated for Best Song Oscars six times and won in 1976 for
``Evergreen,'' and also acted in the ``Smokey and the Bandit''
movies, descended into a nightmare of alcohol and cocaine during
his peak songwriting years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you've got a problem when you lose a whole decade,
and I lost the '80s,'' Williams said. ``There's a fine line between
use to abuse to addiction, and I don't know where I crossed it. I
always said I got better at showing off than showing up. I became a
chronic and habitual liar to hide my addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a look at what his life had become put him on the road
to sobriety. He went from being a patient at various rehab centers
to being a counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slowly but surely, I sort of fell in love with music again,''
said Williams, who penned Diamond Rio's ``You're Gone,'' which rose
to No. 28 on the country charts last week. ``Then I started doing
the occasional acting job. Then I got a call from (`B&AMP;B' head
writer) Brad Bell, saying, `How would you like to play a recovering
alcoholic before 350 million people a day?' How can you turn that
down?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
