<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yearwood's poignant `Road' turns misery into beauty
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trisha Yearwood looks like the all-American girl who grew up
singing along with Linda Ronstadt albums in her bedroom and now
should be approaching middle age in a pretty suburban house with a
couple of kids in the yard. But Yearwood has figured out that most
of us don't wind up with storybook endings, and now, a decade into
her phenomenal career, the onetime Monticello, Ga. schoolgirl has
produced a poignantly beautiful album about growing older, losing
lovers and watching dreams evaporate faster than credit card debt
goes away.
</P>
<P>
   No one can take lyrics like these from ``Heart Like a Sad Song''
and wrap her pipes around them any better: ``There's a wedding
picture she still keeps / Of the girl she was and the man he seemed
to be. / He left her the house with the picket fence / And walked
away with her innocence.'' If anyone has inherited Ronstadt's
mantle as the Mistress of Misery, it's Yearwood, who can belt 'em
out even better than her hippie-era predecessor. And, unlike
Ronstadt, Yearwood has an uncanny ability to pick great material,
then interpret the songs with a sophisticated style as timeless as
Patsy Cline's ``Crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, tunes such as the Top-40ish ``There Goes My Baby'' and
``Powerful Thing'' are more pop than country, and introspective
Mary Chapin Carpenter could have recorded the ethereal ``Never Let
You Go Again,'' a rainy-day, piano-based weeper. But Yearwood seems
to have found her niche in Nashville, and while it may not be the
house with the picket fence, it's a more realistic place to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Your Road Leads''
</P>
<P>
   Trisha Yearwood. MCA. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Mistress of Misery belts it out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
