<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beastie Boys grow up a bit with CD worth deep listen
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As one of the few outfits to successfully bridge the worlds of
hip-hop, indie-rock, New York's noise underground and, of late, the
Dalai Lama, the Beastie Boys have sustained themselves by observing
a certain distance from the fleeting fortunes of the pop
marketplace. The once-bratty trio never sold more records than at
its most willfully callow _ the hair-raising, if now innocently
pre-``gangsta,'' 1986 debut ``Licensed to Ill'' _ and a subsequent
decade has seen the group mature into a kind of art project not
limited to fractured breakbeats. There's a Beastie record label,
Grand Royal, whose roster includes longtime pals Luscious Jackson,
a magazine also called Grand Royal, a publicity agency called Nasty
Little Man (hence this new album's title) and a charity pop event,
the Tibetan Freedom Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello Nasty,'' the group's fifth full-length album, goes with
this flow. It's more a consolidation than a departure, shamelessly
old-school in its eager display of urban roots (the time-tested rap
introduction ``I don't mean to brag / I don't mean to boast'' is
resurrected on the second cut), scholarly in its ransacking of
record racks for novel samples and sound effects (the steel drums
on ``Body Movin''' are an especially canny touch).
</P>
<P>
   The trio's sonic conservatory begs for deeper listening than its
familiar surface _ loungy exotica on one track, squiggly synths on
another _ seemingly might require. Guest vocalists arrive
unexpectedly from far-off planets (as does reggae wizard Lee
``Scratch'' Perry on the dubwise ``Dr. Lee, Ph.D.''), and there's
always a laugh-out-loud rhyme lurking like a sucker punch: ``I'm
the king of boogie, there is no higher; / I get 11 points off the
word `quagmire.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello Nasty''
</P>
<P>
   Beastie Boys. Grand Royal/Capitol. 22 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: One-time beat brats turn hip-hop classicists.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
