</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: the word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge, Doug Hamilton, Al Levine, Sonia Murray,
and Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight No Chase''
</P>
<P>
   P.A. DreamWorks. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, mom and dad. This isn't the incredibly offensive
record you might expect from an act called Parental Advisory,
a.k.a. P.A. The only thing violent about P.A. is the Atlanta-based
rap trio's obvious influence: Quentin Tarantino movies. Spaghetti
guitars, soul and rock propel this sample-free and cinematic
sophomore effort. So take a seat and experience their skillfully
detailed and more than likely imagined adventures (``The Lick''),
pleasures (``China White'') and boasts (``Like We Do''). And if,
halfway through, this starts to feel like a Goodie Mob or Outkast
rerun, it's probably because they all share a connection to
production trio Organized Noize.
</P>
<P>
   -- DANCE
</P>
<P>
   ``HereHear''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Wink. Columbia. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Like a techno-savvy Fred Sanford, Josh Wink presides over a junk
shop of electronic music forms on his second album. The
Philadelphia producer and disc jockey dabbles in acid jazz (``Hard
Hit''), high-energy house music (``Sixth Sense'') and clangy
industrial beats (``Black Bomb,'' with vocals by Trent Reznor of
Nine Inch Nails). The result is a bit disjointed and not exactly
forward-looking, but Wink does reach sonic bliss on occasion. The
lovely, liquid drum-and-bass number ``Young Again'' sets sail on a
warm sea of keyboard washes, while ``I'm on Fire'' features the
seductive vocals of former This Mortal Coil singer Caroline Crawley
trickling over a slow-grind trip-hop groove.
</P>
<P>
   -- COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Burnin' the Roadhouse Down''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wariner. Capitol. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   What do you do to keep busy when you're not selling many
records? For Steve Wariner, the plan went something like this: Sing
a duet with Anita Cochran (``What If I Said'') that goes to No. 1.
Write a tune for Garth Brooks (``Longneck Bottle'') that gets all
over the airwaves. Pretty soon, the record labels notice. And so
here is Wariner back after a three-year hiatus, sounding as strong
as ever. He's all over the board stylistically, from the
sentimental ``Holes in the Floor of Heaven'' to the Texas roadhouse
swing of the title cut. The younger hat acts should take notes.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Vertical Man''
</P>
<P>
   Ringo Starr. Mercury. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   With a little help from his friends, Ringo Starr just might have
one or two hit singles here. ``Vertical Man,'' the former Beatles
timekeeper's first album of new pop in years, boasts strong
material and appearances by ex-Beatles Paul McCartney and George
Harrison, plus Brian Wilson, Scott Weiland, Steven Tyler, Joe
Walsh, Ozzy Osbourne and even Alanis Morissette. This wisely used
Starr power produces some juicy musical assistance, such as Tyler
and Morissette's soulful contributions to the album's cover of
Dobie Gray's ``Drift Away.'' A great example of irony finds Starr
and friends rockin' on ``Love Me Do,'' a song cut by the Fab Four
before Ringo joined the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try Whistling This''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Finn. Work/Sony. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Known for a Paul McCartney-esque way with melodic hooks as
leader of Crowded House, Neil Finn broke up the band to go it
alone. On his first solo album, his voice has a raspiness and his
delivery an intensity that reminds us for allthe world of ... John
Lennon. That's progress. Fans of the New Zealand singer-songwriter
shouldn't be confused by the title. ``Try Whistling This'' has its
fair share of aural experimentation, but it's more in the densely
layered mode of ``Sgt. Pepper'' than anything dissonant. Finn's
lyrics deal with love and regret, but the interesting darker notes
(``King Tide'') help balance the expected sweet ones (``She Will
Have Her Way'').
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
