<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monica shows mastery of sass and substance
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 17-year-old who can connect both the classic ``Misty Blue''
and the slickest urban contemporary music can't be simply
explained. It takes time to understand and appreciate the
progression that Monica has made from her less vocally challenging
debut singles, ``Don't Take It Personal'' and ``Like This and Like
That,'' to the fellow million-seller ``For You I Will'' from the
``Space Jam'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   You also have to be able to believe that she is as sincere about
persuading a boyfriend to stop selling drugs (``Street Symphony,''
with the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra) as she is when catching that
guy's eye ``Cross the Room.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, here's the simple part: Monica just does it.
</P>
<P>
   Slinky and danceable fun music like ``The First Night,'' the
first single from this album, and ``Ring Da Bell,'' a song about a
girl learning that her boyfriend is having a child with another
woman, are approached with equal emotional depth. The only
disappointing thing about this follow-up to the Atlantan's
million-selling debut is that there aren't a whole lot of songs as
weighty as the compelling talent singing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boy Is Mine''
</P>
<P>
   Monica. Arista.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``The Boy'' is Monica's, and so is the best voice
among young R&AMP;B singers today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
