</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ABC's ads may be better than new fall shows
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pasadena, Calif. _ ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The check is in the mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   That trio of lyin' lines is part of ABC's current ``We Love TV''
promotional campaign, an extension of last season's ``TV is Good''
schtick. You remember: those school-bus-yellow billboards with
simple _ some said simple-minded _ messages, hyping the medium of
television not as the destroyer of civilization but as its savior.
</P>
<P>
   Although ABC took some hits for the campaign from literal-minded
critics, it worked, arguably better than the network's shows
themselves last season. (ABC was beaten not only by NBC but by Fox
in the crucial demographic of viewers aged 18 to 49.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be smart, urban, fresh and funny,'' ABC
Entertainment chairman Stu Bloomberg said Tuesday to TV critics
meeting here to preview the fall season. ``We think this campaign
establishes that.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's promotional spots _ some of which have already
appeared with another wave coming soon to a TV set, bus or
billboard near you _ include:
</P>
<P>
   ``If TV's so bad for you, why is there one in every hospital
room?''
</P>
<P>
   ``TV: So good they named a frozen meal after it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before TV, two World Wars. After TV, zero.''
</P>
<P>
   The tongue-in-cheek ads last season were named one of the Top 10
ad campaigns of the year by Time magazine, despite the fact that
they appeared not to help ABC at all in the ratings. The network
has been spiralling steadily down since being bought by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   And there's not much about ABC's new fall shows to suggest the
network will halt the slide. Among its new series:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fantasy Island'' _ An updated version starring Malcolm
McDowell instead of Ricardo Montalban, but with the same basic
premise (9 p.m. ET Saturdays);
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Two of a Kind'' _ A new sitcom with those too-sweet twins
Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen of ``Full House'' (8 pm. ET Fridays);
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cupid'' _ Starring ``Ellen's'' Jeremy Piven as the god of
love made flesh, trying to bring people together in a world of
singles bars and ``The Rules'' (10 p.m. ET Saturdays);
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Hughleys'' _ A comedy about a black family moving into
an all-white suburb, one of two shows this falls with that premise
(the other is ``Living in Captivity'' on Fox). It will air at 8:30
p.m. ET Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Vengeance Unlimited'' _ A surprisingly violent drama given
its early time period (8 p.m. ET Thursdays) that stars Michael
Madsen (``'Reservoir Dogs'') as a thinking man's vigilante who
exacts justice for those who don't get it in court.
</P>
<P>
   Or as ABC's ad campaign will soon be telling you: ``Hello? It's
free.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   ``60 Minutes II'' names excutive producer
</P>
<P>
   After much gnashing of teeth by those at ``60 Minutes,'' CBS
will indeed clone TV's most honored newsmagazine. ``60 Minutes II''
will debut in early 1999. Jeff Fager, who has executive produced
``CBS Evening News with Dan Rather'' since 1996, will be lead the
new newsmag team.
</P>
<P>
   Coming up next on ``Nightline''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, ABC's ``Nightline'' (11:35 p.m. EDT) starts a two-part
look at the reunion in Washington of the Boys Nation class of 1963.
It was during this class that President Clinton, then 17, met
President Kennedy in the White House Rose Garden (film footage of
their greeting was shown at the 1992 Democratic National
Convention). Part two airs at 11:35 p.m. EDT, Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in August ``Nightline'' will go prime time. It will
run for five consecutive Thursdays at 10 p.m.EDT starting Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Personnel moves at ``GMA''
</P>
<P>
   Jazz great David Sanborn is joining ``Good Morning America'' and
will do regular music reports. Sanborn will also sometimes play his
saxophone with musicians he profiles. Also joining ``GMA'' will be
fitness guy Bob Greene, best known as the personal trainer of Oprah
Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   Smits to stay with ABC
</P>
<P>
   ABC has yet to announce the fate of Detective Bobby Simone on
``NYPD Blue,'' but actor Jimmy Smits, who plays Simone and will
exit the popular cop drama, will stay at the network, according to
The Hollywood Reporter. Smits will star in a future series for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Bob Longino , c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
