<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Palmetto's' noir served with a sunny Florida twist
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a journalist played by Woody Harrelson leaves prison after
serving time for a crime he didn't commit, we watch him wander into
a setup wearily familiar from a hundred film noirs. You may wonder
how many times we can watch this story of a guy lured into a
double-cross by a standard-issue femme fatale. But director Volker
Schlondorff plays the story with an occasional, self-conscious wink
to the watcher. And his movie has a few genuine twists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palmetto'' exchanges noir's dark urban streets for the sun and
sea breezes of Florida. And it casts against type by giving sunny
Elisabeth Shue the bad-girl role. The wealthy young wife of a dying
tycoon, she asks Harrelson to play the ``voice on the phone'' in a
fake kidnap scheme she's cooked up with her stepdaughter (Chloe
Sevigny). All he has to do is call the tycoon and pretend to have
nabbed his stepdaughter, then the three share the ransom. Simple
enough? Nope. At nearly two hours long, ``Palmetto'' can be as lazy
as one of its own summer days. But it earns its second-act
surprises, and gives noir a new life. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Other Harrelson movies: ``The People vs. Larry Flynt,'' ``White
Men Can't Jump,'' ``Natural Born Killers,'' ``Welcome to
Sarajevo,'' ``Wag the Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
