<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video Mini Reviews: The latest out on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``Nil by Mouth'' (R) _ There's only one problem with Gary
Oldman's riveting debut as a director: Half the time, you can't
understand what anybody's saying. Focusing on a dysfunctional
blue-collar British family, the drama chronicles the ups and
especially the downs of Ray Winstone, whose wages go primarily for
the drugs and alcohol that keep him alternating between rage and
stupor. As might be guessed, this movie's not exactly an upper. But
it features remarkable acting, especially by Kathy Burke, who won
an award at Cannes for this film, as Winstone's beleaguered wife.
Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Illtown'' (R) _ Director Nick Gomez (``Laws of Gravity'')
takes a mythological tone with this surreal drama about a couple of
South Florida drug dealers (Michael Rapaport, Lili Taylor). Their
easy, middle-class operation (recruiting kids to sell their stuff
at clubs) turns bloody when old friend Adam Trese shows up from up
North with an old score to settle. Gomez deconstructs the film,
using the sun-drenched, dreamy setting to odd effect, and throwing
in allegorical references to John Milton and the Bible. Even when
it isn't convincing, the movie is compulsively watchable. And where
else do you get to see Tony Danza play a gay drug lord who's also a
gardener?
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Phantoms'' (R) _ This horror film is packed with ominous
shots of sink drains. That makes sense: It seems to have been
edited by a garbage disposal. For reasons unexplained, two sisters
(Rose McGowan, Joanna Going) end up in a tiny mountain town beset
by an unnamed, oily evil living in the ground. The movie draws on
tabloid mythology and some H.P. Lovecraft monsters. But after a
spooky, jarring start, it moves at a quick, incoherent pace,
becoming a clumsy hybrid of ``Outbreak'' and ``It.'' Ben Affleck
and poor Peter O'Toole are also in the cast. Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Sphere'' (PG-13) _ A mind-numbing mess that turns Dustin
Hoffman, Samuel L. Jackson and Sharon Stone into B-movie actors and
proves that director Barry Levinson (``Wag the Dog'') shouldn't
dabble in sci-fi. The stars play members of an ad hoc team sent to
the ocean floor to examine what appears to be a spaceship that
crashed 300 years ago. Inside is a floating sphere that soon begins
to exert a spooky power over them. The movie never quite decides
what the sphere is _ good or evil, man-made or alien _ and the
actors are drowned by shoddy special effects and a script that
spins in circles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Zero Effect'' (R) _ Writer-director Jake Kasdan shares some
of his pop Lawrence's interest in oddball human behavior, quirks
and mystery. But as a first-time director, he paces this off-kilter
comedy-mystery with killing slowness. We get an updated riff on
Sherlock Holmes and Dr. Watson in Bill Pullman's brilliant, phobic
detective Daryl Zero and the frazzled intermediary (Ben Stiller)
who has to deal with his employer's quirks. Investigating a problem
for tycoon Ryan O'Neal, Daryl runs into (and falls for) a paramedic
(played with fatal lack of charm by Kim Dickens). The movie has
intelligence and craft, but its identity never congeals. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``The Winter Guest'' (R) _ An icily pristine character study
starring Emma Thompson and her real-life mother, Phyllida Law. It's
the dead of winter in a tiny Scottish seaside town. Hell hasn't
frozen over, but the ocean has. Law plays the mother of Thompson,
who's recently widowed and considering moving with her teenage son
to Australia to escape her grief. Desire is at the root of this
bleak, subtle film: the desire for human connection in whatever
form it might take. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
