<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These joints will be jumping
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lineups for ``(Re)soundings,'' the Jazz Summit at the
National Black Arts Festival in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Hill Auditorium, Woodruff Arts Center
</P>
<P>
   -- Wadada Leo Smith Quartet: The trumpeter, who doubles on flute
and the traditional African instrument the mbira, evokes Asian
themes with virtuoso detail. With Harumi Makino Smith (poetry),
Adam Rudolph (percussion) and NBAF artistic director Dwight Andrews
on reeds and flute.
</P>
<P>
   -- Alexander von Schlippenbach Quartet: The German pianist leads
an international combo of British (reeds player Evan Parker,
drummer Paul Lytton) and American (bassist Reggie Workman)
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   -- DKV Trio with Fred Anderson: One of the most electrifying
live acts in jazz _ Ken Vandermark (reeds), Hamid Drake (drums) and
Kent Kessler (bass) _ connects with tenor saxophonist Fred
Anderson, Chicago living legend.
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   2 p.m. Renaissance Atlanta Hotel
</P>
<P>
   -- Free symposium: A panel discussion about improvisation with
poet and critic Amiri Baraka, jazz educator John Armwood,
Chicago-based critic and producer John Corbett, musicians Wadada
Leo Smith, George Lewis, Peter Brotzmann and Evan Parker.
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Hill Auditorium
</P>
<P>
   -- Peter Brotzmann Trio: The monolithic yawp of the German tenor
saxophonist's horn inspires a sense of awe that's rare in jazz any
more: its sonic tremors make you feel you've wandered into the Land
of the Giants. With Chicagoans Hamid Drake (drums) and Fred Hopkins
(bass), however, the musician explores a gentler side.
</P>
<P>
   -- George Lewis' Voyager Project: The veteran trombonist deploys
the computer program he designed for improvisatory purposes, joined
by a pair of peerless reed adventurers, Evan Parker and Roscoe
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   -- Trio 3: This trilateral improviser's collective features
Andrew Cyrille (drums), Oliver Lake (alto saxophone) and Reggie
Workman (bass).
</P>
<P>
   Midnight, Hill Auditorium
</P>
<P>
   -- After-show screening: Michael Snow's ``New York Eye and Ear
Control,'' experimental short film with improvised soundtrack by
Albert Ayler, Don Cherry and others. $1.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   11 a.m. Cannon Chapel, Emory University
</P>
<P>
   -- Free workshop: Techniques in improvised music discussed and
demonstrated by Andrew Cyrille, Reggie Workman, Oliver Lake, Peter
Kowald, Conrad Bauer and Gunter ``Baby'' Sommer.
</P>
<P>
   -- Andrew Cyrille-Peter Brotzmann Duo: Two major figures in the
avant-gardes of America (drummer Cyrille) and Europe (saxophonist
Brotzmann) trade chops.
</P>
<P>
   -- Bauer-Kowald-Sommer Trio: Longtime compatriots in the
European free improvisation movement join forces: Konrad Bauer
(trombone), Peter Kowald (bass) and Gunter ``Baby'' Sommer (drums).
</P>
<P>
   -- Roscoe Mitchell's ``L-R-G'': Historic 20th-anniversary
performance of Chicago composer Mitchell's pointillist composition
for three horn players: Leo Smith (trumpet, fluegelhorn), Roscoe
Mitchell (various reeds) and George Lewis (trombone, B-flat
sousaphone).
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. Goethe-Institut Atlanta, Colony Square
</P>
<P>
   -- Co-sponsor of the event hosts a post-concert screening of
``Peter Brotzmann's 50th Birthday Party'' documentary. $1
admission.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
