<HEADER>
A6655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NBAF-DRUMMER-COX     07-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBAF-DRUMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Popular jazz drumer to perform at three day summit
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- James Brown's timeless exhortation to ``give the
drummer some`` is nearly redundant when the percussionist in
question is Hamid Drake.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, the Chicago-based musician is an emerging master whose
versatile skills and quicksilver intuition have made him one of the
most in-demand collaborators inthe sometimes amorphous field of
jazz and improvised music.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be no musical vectors he hasn't traveled: Drake
has been a frequent member of tenor saxophonist Pharoah Sanders'
outfits; toured as a teenager with the late trumpeter Don Cherry
and, later, with the ``Rockit''-era Herbie Hancock; and fostered a
fertile partnership with the master kora player Foday Musa Suso. He
gigs and records with multiple combos in his hometown, including
the fluid and sometimes ferocious DKV Trio, which features
fire-throwing multi-reedist Ken Vandermark. He's hopping flights to
Europe on a routine basis, where he has a steady job with the
fabled German saxophone colossus Peter Brotzmann.
</P>
<P>
   As such, few artists amplify the theme of the 10th anniversary
National Black Arts Festival _ ``Art Beyond Borders'' _ quite like
Drake, whose polyrhythms populate all kinds of cultural crossroads.
This week, his path leads to Atlanta, and a unique, three-day
fest-within-the-fest billed as ``(Re)soundings.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tonight, this international jazz summit is a lively,
far-reaching survey of avant-garde concepts as they originated in
Chicago, New York, New Haven, Conn., Great Britain and Germany in
the 1960s and '70s, and how those ideas evolve and mutate in the
ever-present ``now`` of performance.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as abstract as it might sound, insists Drake, whose
global percussive range _ and a narrative knack for creating vivid
scenarios in tone _ capably balances even the most volatile
instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music, it's about methodologies by which we can come to
some sort of understanding of various truths,'' says Drake, who
performs tonight with DKV and the unsung Chicago tenor great Fred
Anderson, and again on Friday with the often volcanic Brotzmann.
``It's not necessarily the Truth, but the various truths that might
be operating inside of each human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Louisiana and raised in the Chicago suburb of Evanston,
Drake was not initially drawn to percussion; rather, it was thrust
upon him. ``Lots of schools have these stage bands,`` he says,
reflecting on that fateful day in every young musician's life when
they first get to ``pick'' an instrument. ``But who wants to be in
the back playing the bass drum and the snare drum? I really wanted
to play the trombone but there were only a certain number
available. I still love the trombone, I love that sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Drake reasons that he was compelled to play the drums, he
quickly established a presence _ even while in high school. ``He's
the kind of young man that's very visual,'' reckons Anderson, a
69-year-old elder statesman of the Chicago tenor tradition who was
close friends with Drake's father, and began playing with the
drummer in the 1970s. ``He's sees a lot of things, and listens to
what the horn players are playing, and complements them.``
</P>
<P>
   That's an especially valuable role when the music slips free of
conventional time signatures and pursues open structures. Drummers
not only have to sustain a sense of pulse, but engage in a kind of
game with the other musicians that's part tug-of-war, part
tightrope walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the best drummers I've ever seen,`` says Bruno
Johnson, a Chicago bartender and music fan who founded Okkadisk, an
independent record label, to document his favorite players. Drake
appears on no less than six different titles. ``There is so much
happening so quickly that it can be frightening sometimes. It's
something you don't really expect to ever see.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, jazz drummers are supposed to be dynamos. Drake,
however, reaches deeper. Like the best of his peers, he seems to
tap a pipeline directly into his nervous system,
</P>
<P>
   a gift magnified through casual showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a compelling percussionist to watch,`` says Tad
Hendrickson, jazz and world music editor for CMJ New Music Report,
a national trade publication for college radio stations. ``He's got
a smile on his face, he's working his way around the drum kit. His
music comes out of his limbs. There's no difference between what's
going on in his soul and what you hear in the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Drake agrees, playing drums is like writing
autobiography. ``It's an extension of me,`` he says. ``Telling my
story, my joys and ups and downs and pursuits. My fears, my
insecurities, what I'm confident in. It's a way for me to express
my life, my voice, through sound and to somehow go deeper and
deeper into what it is to really be a human being ... and to have
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Re)soundings: The Global Realm of Jazz and Improvised Music
at the End of the Century''.
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Tonight, Friday. Hill Auditorium, Woodruff Arts Center,
1280 Peachtree St. N.E. 2 p.m. Saturday. Cannon Chapel, Emory
University, 515 Kilgo Circle, N.E. $12. 404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
