<SLUG> BC-CIR-SLEEPLESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET TAKES TIME AWAY FROM SLEEP, TV AND MUCH ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most of us know that Internet use is up. But what is down?
</P>
<P>
   With only 24 hours in a day, is cyberspace stealing time from
sleeping, stepping on the Stairmaster, watching television or
working? The answer, according to a new survey, is all of the
above.
</P>
<P>
   The activity taking the biggest hit is television- and
VCR-watching, according to the survey by Strategis Group, a
Washington-based research firm that studies patterns in
telecommunications use. Nearly 65 percent of 500 Net users surveyed
said they had sacrificed time in front of the TV for time in front
of the computer monitor. Forty-eight percent said they spent less
time reading, and 29 percent said they slept less.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results, issued at the end of June, seemed to
validate a trend reported in a similar poll last year by a New York
research company, Cyber Dialogue. It found that in addition to
spending less time with their television sets, 22 percent of
Internet regulars were also spending less time making long-distance
phone calls. Cyber Dialogue further found that 16 percent of Net
surfers were spending less time reading newspapers; an identical
percentage spent less time reading magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Now for the more difficult question: What do these data mean?
</P>
<P>
   John Zahurancik, director of Internet and telephony at Strategis
Group, said the findings that the Internet was stealing time from
other media meant that the Net was sharing their stage. ``The Net
is becoming a mainstream medium,'' he said. ``It is a competition
to all these other traditional sources of entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   But scratch beneath the surface and the lessons are not so
obvious or clear-cut, said Stuart Gibbel, director of marketing for
Cyber Dialogue. Gibbel said it might be years before it is known
what activities will suffer, diminish or even die because of the
new medium. For instance, Gibbel said, a computer user may go
online to reinforce outside interests, like checking out a Web site
for background on a favorite television show or ordering a book.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Milford, who owns a New York art-management software
company, Artsystems, and is an inveterate Net surfer, said that
when he first encountered cyberspace, it was a black hole. ``The
Internet took from everything, including reading books, a social
life, sleep,'' he said. ``It's such a deep lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Milford says the Net now saves him time because it helps
speed information gathering and other tasks, and that time can be
spent on other activities. Further, Milford, who is 39, says he has
mastered the art of simultaneously watching television and surfing
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Television executives are seeking to capitalize on this sort of
crossover viewing. NBC, for example, hopes to use its television
network to steer Net surfers to its Web site, and vice versa,
according to Edmond Sanctis, senior vice president and general
manager of NBC Digital Productions. In other words, if NBC is going
to lose viewers to the Net, it wants to lose them to its own Web
pages, where visitors can also be directed back to NBC. ``This is a
profound opportunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that is certain is that the Web is being rapidly
adopted by Americans. Allen Goldberg, vice president for business
development at Relevant Knowledge, a research company based in
Atlanta, noted that it took 40 years for radio to gain 50 million
domestic listeners and 13 years each for television and cable
television to each acquire 50 million domestic viewers. While
acknowledging that the population is larger now, Goldberg said it
was nonetheless noteworthy that it has taken only four years for
the World Wide Web to reach that same plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Editor and Publisher magazine recently noted that people were
going on line more frequently, with 61 percent of Internet users
surfing the Net at least twice a week, up from 53 percent last
year. However, that may not mean that people are spending more time
on the Net. Cyber Dialogue found that the total time spent on line
each week _ five hours _ did not change from the beginning of 1997
to the beginning of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
