<HEADLINE>
THE TRANSFORMATION OF A HOME AND ITS OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As plots go, it is pure Barbara Cartland. Friends
arrange a blind date between a model (J. Crew, Victoria's Secret)
and a telegenic swain (``The Today Show''). The expected chemistry
fizzles. The intended part amicably, only to give romance another
chance a few days later. Today, a year after their disastrous first
date, there is a pear-shaped diamond the size of a small almond on
Annette Roque's left hand, compliments of Matt Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   But the wedding date is shrouded in secrecy, OK?
</P>
<P>
   The only detail of the pending event that Miss Roque would
divulge is the dress: Think of Audrey Hepburn, in ``Roman
Holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be exactly like this,'' Ms. Roque said, showing a
clipping of a ballerina-length gown from a Martha Stewart wedding
guide. ``I'm not an off-the-rack kind of girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Roque, 32, has a not-off-the-rack apartment, too, a
two-bedroom penthouse in TriBeCa. Riding the crest of today's
fascination with multiculturalism, it is exotic without looking
anything like Trader Vic's, thanks to the skills of that newly
minted American arbiter of haute-bohemian chic, Countess Muriel
Brandolini d'Adda. The two women met back in the early '90s, when
Mrs. Brandolini was a photo stylist and Miss Roque was hired to
model for Rodier, the upscale French knitwear company.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Roque may not be this season's It Girl, but she is surely
It by association. The model, with her fresh-scrubbed but exotic
visage, will come down the aisle sometime this fall to marry Lauer,
who is 40. To the continued amusement of his Dutch-born fiancee,
Lauer is a celebrity. ``We don't have television personalities in
Holland,'' Miss Roque said. ``We have people who work in
television.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Roque (pronounced rock) is a working model as opposed to
the supermodel variety. Hailing from a celebrity-immune country,
whose royal family rides bicycles through the city streets, Miss
Roque is plainly intrigued by her fiance's fame. ``People are
always coming up to him in restaurants to say hello,'' she said.
``The attention is really bizarre.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why she wants to walk down the aisle without the
hoopla and hovering helicopters that attended the recent nuptials
of Barbra Streisand and James Brolin. ``Are you crazy?'' she asked.
``I want this to be perfect. I've never had a wedding before. The
only problem is we're having 100 guests. Someone's bound to slip
up.''
</P>
<P>
   She grins and laughs in a sort of breathless way she describes
as ``so girly.'' Girly is a designation that Miss Roque uses
frequently and without respect to gender. Anyone enthusiastic,
funny and given to teasing can be an honorary girl. Even Brian
Williams, the gravely serious MSNBC reporter who is apparently a
cut-up off camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a girl,'' Miss Roque said, who recently met Williams and
his wife through Lauer.
</P>
<P>
   Until they move into Lauer's apartment on the Upper East Side,
where the decor is midlife bachelor, Miss Roque and her two
ankle-hugging Burmese cats will continue to live in the abstract
jungle in the sky that Mrs. Brandolini created for her. ``I'm
really going to miss this place,'' Miss Roque said, looking out to
the terrace where a wooden tub of yellow day lilies were just
coming into bloom. The furniture will go into storage, until the
newlywed Lauers find larger digs in a year or so. And when they do,
Mrs. Brandolini will be ready to tackle that apartment, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brandolini, 38, struck out on her own as a decorator a few
years ago, and since then has been racking up esthetically
broadminded clients like the Italian millionaire Andrea Botta, the
makeup artist Moyra Mulholland and Liz O'Brien, furniture dealer to
the stars.
</P>
<P>
   The decorator's freewheeling brand of supersensuous tropicality
was not exactly the environment that Miss Roque anticipated when
she bought her apartment three years ago. It was typical real
estate Zen: white walls, blond floors, no cornices, big glass
windows, spacious but bland. It was, however, sunny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with the light, that's all,'' Miss Roque said.
</P>
<P>
   She had no particular fondness for TriBeCa _ it was the
preference of a former boyfriend _ and though the Edwardian
building was graced with big stone columns in front, all the
historic character had been removed from the interiors. The
boyfriend fell by the wayside, and along came Mrs. Brandolini, who
proceeded to remake the apartment _ in her own image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always loved Muriel's apartments and wanted to live exactly
like that,'' Miss Roque said. ``They're whimsical but not precious.
Everywhere you look is a surprise. Nothing is matched, nothing is
boring.'' And though they did not pay much attention to it at
first, Mrs. Brandolini's Vietnamese, Venezuelan and French ancestry
struck a chord with Miss Roque, whose mother is Dutch and whose
father, the director of human resources for the city of Amsterdam,
is Indonesian, Chinese and French.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are both cocktails, you know?'' said Mrs. Brandolini, an
earthy, effervescent woman. Still, she can strike fear into the
hearts of the chronically indecisive. Instinct is her guide, and
she cheerfully admits, with an expressive grimace, that she doesn't
know the first thing about sketching out a scheme or plotting a
floor plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do comes from the inside, and if it feels right, I just
do it,'' she said. The result is a multicultural tango that is one
part wire act to two parts real genius. The Upper East Side town
house she shares with her husband, Nuno, her children, Brando and
Filippa, and a Welsh corgi called Saigon is a prime example. Room
after room of hand-locked fabrics designed by Mrs. Brandolini and
manufactured in India rest contentedly alongside 1940s mock-Chinese
furniture, Oriental bronze candlesticks, button-tufted Victoriana
and made-to-order curiosities like a mauve and sage-green painted
armoire topped with an outsize pineapple designed by R. Louis
Bofferding. A vast Chinese bed dominates the dining room (it
doubles as guest quarters), and the ceiling of the den is a quilt
of mismatched sarongs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
