<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-CSIBLEY-COLUMN19     07-15 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-CSIBLEY-COLUMN19 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: New piano puts music in home, town in the dark
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to a friend in New Jersey, my son was getting a new
piano. We all rejoiced, because the one he lovingly but awkwardly
played came from the Salvation Army thrift store.
</P>
<P>
   He had to rehabilitate it, with a book on pianos in hand. The
innards of the piano gave him some difficulty, but he was helped by
his sister, who sent the book and persuaded a friend to let her
have ivory covers for the keys, which a previous owner had
slathered with paint.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, it was a make-do piano, but I thought it was
serving pretty well until the musical friend in New Jersey came
through with a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   He had found a marvelous deal on pianos, and, as my daughter,
his former pupil, assured us all, ``Gus really knows pianos. He has
seven or eight of his own _ and if he says this is a deal. ...''
</P>
<P>
   So after some finagling and financial hocus-pocus, the new piano
was on the way. I wished I could be there to greet it because, as I
explained to a friend, it was the greatest excitement in Alford,
Fla., since Mr. Hamp Pickles' old mule was hit by a freight train.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement was greater than I knew. The piano was days
getting there. When the driver of the big tractor- trailer called
and said he was ``somewhere north of Dot-ham, Ala.,'' we recognized
that as New Jersey pronunciation of Dothan, the big town nearest
Alford, and called one another on the telephone, silly with
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Jimmy is doing,'' his sister in Omaha said.
``It's just like we all do when a baby is due. He's waxing the
floor. I swept the driveway all day before my piano from Georgia
arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   I remembered. I washed woodwork and curtains before my last baby
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But the piano ... a brief 43 miles up the road ... ah, the
to-do, ah, the elation, ah, the tumult!
</P>
<P>
   The report I got was secondhand, because I couldn't hang around
Alford any more days and wait for the piano. The big
tractor-trailer arrived on Jimmy's street, a pretty dirt
thoroughfare until a few years ago, and two big strong, amiable men
deftly got the piano off the truck, and into the yard, after
pulling up the gate post. They laid a ramp up the front steps and
suddenly the long-awaited miracle of music was in the house.
</P>
<P>
   My son went out to bid the truckers goodbye and saw there was a
tangle of wires on their rear bumper and a power pole down and
dragging after them. He ran to catch up with them. They stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Their rig had caught a cable and the whole electrical system of
that end of Alford was on the way to New Jersey. The lights were
out _ and so were the town's fire truck, ambulance, police force
and state patrol. So were the neighbors, plunging out of their dark
houses to see what a new piano in town had wrought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was afraid the truckers were going to be in trouble,'' Jimmy
told me. ``But it turned out all right. The police said, after all,
they were making an important delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   And how was the piano? Jimmy said it is beautiful, with a sound
</P>
<P>
   so rich and fine it might have appeased the neighbors waiting
for their lights to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   He had to light candles to play it, he said, but by the gentle
candlelight he could discern the name on the case: Steinway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
