<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDOLINI-DESIGN-2ND     07-15 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDOLINI-DESIGN-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: mismatched sarongs. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That volcanic collision of colors and textures appealed
immediately to Miss Roque, who was raised in Alphen aan de Rijn, a
comfortable but uninspiring suburb of Amsterdam. ``I grew up
between the tulips and the cheese,'' she said. ``Everybody has
white curtains in the window, parted in the middle, and a geranium
on the windowsill.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Roque's family, however, rebelled against the prevailing
cultural humdrum. ``In my family, being different is a plus,'' she
said. Her parents furnished their house with butterfly chairs and
an aquarium full of tropical fish. So when Mrs. Brandolini asked
for carte blanche, Miss Roque eagerly acquiesced and left for three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When she returned to her apartment, she admitted sheepishly, ``I
freaked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The pristine white walls, blameless reflectors of light, had
been upholstered in an almond-green Indian cotton scattered with
tiny deep blue carnations. Lined with ice-blue cotton, the same $62
a yard material _ one of several of Mrs. Brandolini's designs that
are carried at Le Decor Francais, a shop on Lexington Avenue _
curtained every door and window. The blonde floors had gone pale
green, and an aggressive leopard-print sofa lurked in one corner.
The walls of the guest bedroom, lacquered blood red, were in the
midst of being stenciled with 48 larger-than-life-size purple
Siberian irises. (Mrs. Brandolini had found the image in a book
about the botanical drawings of the 16th-century artist Daniel
Rabel and blown it up to dinner-plate proportions.)
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed, Miss Roque issued a stop-work order.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Brandolini was nonplused. ``She told me, `Make this
apartment like yours, make it cozy,''' Mrs. Brandolini recalled.
``Well, I did it.'' Alas, one woman's cozy _ curtained doors and
Sensurround patterns _ was another's claustrophobia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I just went nuts,'' Miss Roque said, laughing. ``But
Muriel just kept at me, convinced me. And you know, after a while,
I went along with it. She's not really a decorator. She's an
artist, and you really can't stop an artist, especially when you
know what they're doing is right.''
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, Miss Roque realized that her desires for coziness
had been answered, and more subtly than she had imagined.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the apartment didn't seem smaller; strangely, with all
the patterns it seemed larger. The patterns diffused the planes of
the rooms, giving them a sort of vaporous unreality that belied the
mathematics of the floor plan. The floor, as green and shimmering
as a rice paddy just recently irrigated, stretched into infinity.
That landscape-like mirage is enhanced, too, by a pair of lacquered
tables _ one candy pink, the other the green of new leaves _ that
Mrs. Brandolini designed to resemble Pop Art waterlilies.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of spindly see-through bookcases rise from floor to
ceiling like stalks of verdigris bamboo, separate the living room
from a small television viewing area. And as for the light that
Miss Roque was afraid of losing to Mrs. Brandolini's lavish
upholstery, it has only been enhanced. Now instead of blaring into
view, it slinks through the curtains like sun through a canopy of
rain-forest trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels right, here in my soul, though I never really gave it
much thought,'' Miss Roque said. ``It's like when I went to
Indonesia for the first time, where my father is from. I knew
nothing about the country but when I stepped off the plane, I felt
like I had come home in some way. I felt very grounded.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, it is the South of France that is on her mind.
In one week, Lauer (who once described himself as ``a geek with an
overbite'') is to meet the entire Roque family for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be wonderful,'' his soon-to-be bride said. ``They will
be crazy about him. He can be such a girl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
