<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOELESSJOE-COX     07-15 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOELESSJOE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reconsidering Shoeless Joe: Supporters seek to have the baseball
great inducted into Hall of Fame
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JULY 19: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lyn Riddle
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C.-- The folks who leave bats and balls and white
socks on his grave at Woodlawn Memorial Park have not forgotten
Shoeless Joe Jackson. Nor have those who drive past the tidy brick
house where he died.
</P>
<P>
   Neither have the aspiring athletes taken under the legendary
outfielder's wing in those years when he ran a liquor store on the
unrefined side of this northwestern South Carolina city, the years
he spent banished from baseball.
</P>
<P>
   They want Jackson inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame, an
honor unbestowed because Jackson and seven White Sox teammates were
accused of accepting bribes to intentionally lose the 1919 World
Series. (This year, five will be inducted into the Hall of Fame in
Cooperstown, N.Y., on July 26.)
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame campaign gained strength with the help of
former Red Sox batting ace Ted Williams and Indians pitcher Bob
Feller, both Hall of Fame honorees. They have asked Major League
Baseball to reinstate Jackson. If it does, Jackson is virtually
assured a place in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   To help promote the cause, Jackson's hometown has declared July
to be Joe Jackson Month and has opened an exhibit in the City Hall
lobby detailing Jackson's career.
</P>
<P>
   Considered the greatest natural hitter ever, Jackson's .356
batting average remains the third highest in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In their application to the baseball association, Williams and
Feller argue that Jackson's banishment ended when he died in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for a pardon,'' Williams said. ``We're asking
for a little swing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson started his baseball career at 13 on the dusty sandlot
outside Brandon Mill here. The oldest son among eight, Jackson
started walking down the hill to sweep floors in the mill at age 7.
The family needed his income. He never learned to read or write,
but he learned how to swing a bat.
</P>
<P>
   At the turn of the century, baseball was a respite from the
harsh world of the cotton mill. Every mill had a team. Jackson made
some extra cash each game because with every blast over the
outfield fence, his brothers passed a hat in the audience. Many
nights the Jackson boys took home $25, more money than could be
made in the mill in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Jackson was playing for the Greenville Spinners, a minor
league team, and before too long, he was signed by the major league
Philadelphia Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe had a hard time,'' said Joe Anders, one of the young men
Jackson tutored in his retirement. ``He didn't like the North. The
veteran players made fun of him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was traded to the Cleveland Indians and in his rookie season
batted .408, the best average for a first-year player in the
history of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson went to the Chicago White Sox in 1915. The 1919 World
Series scandal remains a much-debated subject. Some say Jackson
admitted he was part of the fix. Others say he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Anders said that as Jackson was dying, he said, ``I'm going to
the greatest umpire of them all and he will know I'm innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would someone say that on his deathbed if it weren't
true?'' said Anders.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was the Sox's leading hitter in the eight-game series,
had 12 hits and batted in six runs. But Jackson did admit to having
$5,000 given to him by pitcher Lefty Williams. Jackson was
acquitted but barred from baseball for life.
</P>
<P>
   With a settlement for back pay from Sox owner Charles Comisky,
Jackson returned to the Brandon Mill area and opened a liquor store
and a pool hall in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Anders remembers seeing Jackson standing in the doorjamb at the
little liquor store on Pendleton Street many, many times before the
teenager had the nerve to talk to him. Jackson immediately took an
interest in Anders, who came up the same as him in Brandon Mill
Village. Jackson gave him tips on batting (level swing, eye on the
ball) and fielding (always use two hands). And every so often,
Jackson and his wife, Katie, went out to watch Anders play for the
Greenville Spinners in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   Anders ultimately passed up a chance to play for the Brooklyn
Dodgers to stay here and draw a bigger and steadier paycheck
managing and playing textile baseball. Jackson died of heart
disease in 1951 at the age of 63. Anders and seven others lifted
his copper-plated casket through the window of Jackson's Anderson
Street neighborhood home for viewing and stood by as hundreds
flocked to Brandon Baptist Church for the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he wasn't Shoeless Joe, country bumpkin. He was still a
baseball legend, Greenville's finest athlete whose dark bat _ Black
Betsy _ rocketed balls into outfields in Brandon and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to give something back to Joe, for what he gave me so
long ago,'' said Anders, now 77, of the Hall of Fame effort. ``Joe
Jackson was ridiculed, called illiterate, dumb. He was not dumb. He
was the best there was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
