<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBSITE-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO CURE A HANKERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hankering to visit Arlen?
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Fox's ``King of the Hill'' can tell you all about Arlen,
Texas: Tom Landry Middle School, Mega-Lo Mart, guys with farmer
tans swilling beer in front of their homes, occasionally grunting
``Yup.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Seal of Ruston, La., is such a fan that he created a
chamber-of-commercelike Welcome to Arlen, Texas
(members.tripod.com/\Pbradseal/arlen) page that brings the
fictional suburb to life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was created to help people learn about the town where the
TV show takes place,'' Seal said.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Arlen, Texas is not quite virtual reality, but it's a
start. Since May 1997, Seal has been building his concept of Arlen,
going so far as to declare himself mayor and name a library for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Arlen, Texas doesn't quite follow the show _ no
Mega-Lo Mart, no Landry Middle School _ but it is one Louisiana
State University football fan's look at Texas life.
</P>
<P>
   Examples are in the Arlen High School profile in the section
about education. Seal writes that acceptable alibis for excused
absences are Dallas Cowboys games or trailer-park accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Texans will point out that the Cowboys play Sundays, Monday
nights, Thanksgiving or the rare Saturday, so that alibi won't fly.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Help Bruce Willis and Demi Moore find new spouses at Hollywood
Online's Bruce &AMP; Demi Matchmaker poll (www.hollywood.com). For
Willis, the choices are Elizabeth Berkley, Cher and Phyllis Diller
(Phyllis Willis, get it?). For Moore, it's either Rob Lowe, Brad
Pitt or Jonathan Demme (Demi Demme, get it?).
</P>
<P>
   _ Musician Ray Charles is scheduled to chat live at 8 p.m.
Sunday on America Online Live (keyword: NetNoir) in collaboration
with Rhino Records and NetNoir.
</P>
<P>
   IDEAS THAT'LL GROW ON KIDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tell the kids that you need help in the garden this summer.
</P>
<P>
   No response? Tell them you want to make tussie-mussies or
hollyhock dolls.
</P>
<P>
   Some response? Mention bugs and pond creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Let them know that these topics are a few of the kid-friendly,
hands-on gardening subjects available for children at Garden.com
(www.garden.com).
</P>
<P>
   The Austin-based site has a series of projects that appear as a
regular feature called Kids' Gardening Camp. The projects focus on
the education beyond gardening, from vocabulary to reading
comprehension to measurement and math.
</P>
<P>
   This week's project: making hollyhock dolls. _ Tommy Cummings,
(817) 390-7397 dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
