<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6683 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-15 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHUT UP AND DEAL': GLIMPSES OF THE GAMBLER'S ABYSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Publication notes appear at the end of the review.) 
(th) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse May is a professional poker player. He was so obsessed
with the game that he gave up studying philosophy at the University
of Chicago to play it full time. He loves the game so much that he
has written a novel about it, ``Shut Up and Deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But you won't learn much about the fundamentals of poker from
his book. You won't learn technique or the rules of the different
games or how to rank hands. You won't even learn what the following
passage from the novel means: ``I mean I'm on the button in
Pot-Limit Hold'em and there's a $25 live blind out and the action
goes call call call fold call to me. I mean really.'' If you could
ask May what this means, he would probably tell you, ``Shut up and
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for his reticence on poker fundamentals is that May
(or rather Mickey, his protagonist) considers playing (not winning)
so easy. Anyone can walk into the poker room of a casino and play.
The dealer will tell him what to do and, if he's still in at the
end, whether what he's holding wins or loses.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, May writes: ``Poker is a combination of luck and skill.
People think mastering the skill part is hard, but they're wrong.
The trick to poker is mastering the luck. That's philosophy.
Understanding luck is philosophy, and there are some people who
aren't ever gonna fade it. That's what sets poker apart. And that's
what keeps everyone coming back for more.''
</P>
<P>
   May imparts these lessons by narrating a series of poker bouts
in casinos like Foxwoods in Connecticut and the Taj Mahal in
Atlantic City. They take place in a timeless vacuum in the 1990s,
when poker had been changed by ``a bunch of things'' that happened
in the late 1980s ``all in a row.'' As Mickey describes them: ``The
Mirage, California, here come the Indians. And the invention of
limit Texas Hold'em poker.''
</P>
<P>
   This meant that the typical game went from a private ante-up
get-together of friends around the dining room table, with each
player chipping in for refreshments, to an anonymous gathering of
professionals at 10-man casino tables, with the house taking a cut
of every pot. And the objective changed from fun and relaxation to
busting your opponent's willpower and pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut Up and Deal'' vividly reflects these changes. Instead of
neat examples of play, you get shapeless stories of obsession.
Instead of charming characters amusing one another, you get
borderlines behaving destructively. Instead of guarantees that
poker is fun, you get assurances that the game is ``all about
cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   Or about the revelation of some character flaw. ``This guy
Vaughn is like a lot of people who play poker,'' Mickey explains.
``Most of the time they limit themselves to two options: either
they win a little or they lose a lot. Most of this has to do with
ego. They want to be able more than anything to say that they beat
the game. This is why they're happy to take small wins _ hit and
run as it may.''
</P>
<P>
   What holds your attention reading ``Shut Up and Deal'' is the
bleakly cynical prose. ``All I can tell you,'' Mickey advises an
acquaintance who's considering turning pro, ``is that it's lonely
out there, real ... lonely, and your play doesn't matter so much as
how tough you are and whether or not you fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey himself is tough enough to develop systems. He charts his
rate of winning and ponders the talk of mathematicians on the
subject of standard deviations. ``Then I go on a losing streak''
and ``question everything I know about poker _ no, everything I
believe _ and consider giving up and be scared to go in the card
room and not know when to fold or when to raise or when to play or
when to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he arrives at a bedrock truth. ``You can say what you
like. I maintain winning poker is the changing of chaos to order,
of always perceiving order. But everything associated with casinos
and their effect on people has to do with the loss of order,
perceptions of chaos _ no clocks, no windows, free alcohol, bright
lights, bells. It's the same with gambling, the drug produces chaos
_ rapid heartbeat, adrenaline pumping, things moving fast, chips
instead of money, in, out, bad judgment. And it's tough keeping
yourself under tight control night after night, which is why in the
gambling world there's an entire vocabulary for losing control.
Tilt. Going off ... steaming, hot, the bonkers monster.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mickey's narrative, the bonkers monster eventually wins.
Mickey backs a player he admires, lending him $19,000, only to
learn that the player is blowing his mind apart with cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Shut Up and Deal'' is not a romance. It fails to instruct
in the narrow sense of the term. But it offers a glimpse of the
abyss that threatens every gambler, which is that the chaos will
always get you in the end, and that casinos are ``dirty ...
underneath all the glitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that such revelations will discourage the serious poker
addict. As May concludes:
</P>
<P>
   bitterness and denial aren't
</P>
<P>
   realistic ways
</P>
<P>
   to deal
</P>
<P>
   with something that happens again and again
</P>
<P>
   never to know exactly when
</P>
<P>
   but that the only stop is not to play.
</P>
<P>
   but to play
</P>
<P>
   that's the thing.
</P>
<P>
   shut up and deal.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SHUT UP AND DEAL'
</P>
<P>
   By Jesse May
</P>
<P>
   217 pages. Anchor Books/Doubleday. Paperback, $12.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
