<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, July 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Searing heat will intensify over much of the interior West
during the next few days as an unusually strong zone of high
pressure strengthens and expands over the region. Sunshine will be
plentiful in most areas west of the Rockies, except for the
northern Washington coast where some cloud patches will linger.
Afternoon temperatures above 100 degrees will be common in many
valleys from western Colorado to California. A few thunderstorms
will develop along the eastern slopes of the Rockies during the
heat of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The central and southern Plains will stay very warm, but
humidity will be moderate. Most of the region will have a mixture
of sunshine and a few clouds. A stalled front near the Missouri
River will be the focus for scattered strong thunderstorms during
the afternoon and evening. Farther south, a few thunderstorms will
form in the more humid air from central Texas to the western Gulf
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   An onshore flow will bring tropical moisture toward the
Southeast coast encouraging clusters of clouds and thundershowers
from the Carolina coast to Florida. Clouds and showers will also
surround weak low pressure from the eastern Tennessee Valley to the
southern Appalachians. Weak high-level winds will result in
slow-moving thunderstorms that can drop copious rain in isolated
areas.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of showers and thunderstorms will develop in the
warm humid air ahead of a front in the interior Northeast. In the
wake of the front, less humid air will spread across the northern
Mississippi Valley and Great Lakes States.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Baked Boston
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was the hottest day in Boston since March 31. The
mercury rose to 90 degrees, marking the first time this year that
it has surpassed this level. On the final day of March, an
extraordinary spring heat wave brought the temperature to a monthly
record 89 degrees. However, for the last 104 days, the mercury had
not been able to break the 90 degree mark. In a typical summer,
Boston notices readings in the 90s on thirteen occasions. Balmy
breezes from the Southwest have directed the hot air to the New
England coast, but an approaching cool front should curtail the hot
weather on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
