<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-BUGS16-COX     07-15 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-BUGS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANEL URGES CAUTION TO AVOID MICROBES FROM SPACE
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Plans by the U.S. space agency to retrieve samples
from the surface of Mars and other places in the solar system must
include strict precautions to avoid contaminating the Earth with
extraterrestrial microbes, the National Academy of Sciences said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although an academy committee of biologists and astronomers said
the risk of encountering ``living entities'' on some asteroids and
in interplanetary dust particles appear to be negligible, it warned
of ``a significant potential'' that life forms could be found in
samples from two of Jupiter's moons.
</P>
<P>
   And too little is known about some asteroids to rule out the
possibility that biohazards exist there, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the committee said it had a ``high degree of
confidence'' that no special containment and handling are warranted
for material from the Earth's moon, Jupiter's moon, Io, and certain
types of comets.
</P>
<P>
   With less confidence, the committee said no special containment
practices were necessary for the Martian moons Phobos and Deimos,
Jupiter's moon Callisto and material from still other classes of
asteroids, comets and space dust.
</P>
<P>
   The committee repeated advice from an earlier report that while
it thought it unlikely that Martian soil samples would contain
living organisms, the possibility cannot be ruled out and the
material should be handled as though they were ``potentially
hazardous.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also said the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration (NASA) needs to collect data on environments where
some of Earth's toughest microbes are able to survive in order to
better assess the chances of survival in space.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has scheduled four missions aimed at retrieving material
from elsewhere in the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Stardust,'' to be launched next year, would visit the comet
Wild-2 (pronounced ``vilt-two''), when it is 242 million miles from
the Earth to take pictures and try to snag about 1,000 grains of
the dust that swirls around it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Genesis,'' which would attempt to trap charged particles
that make up ``solar wind,'' would be launched in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``MUSES-C,'' a collaboration between NASA and the Japanese
space agency, would land a tiny craft on the asteroid 4660 Nereus
and attempt to catch material kicked up when pellets are fired into
the surface. The craft would be launched in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A mission to Mars planned for 2005 would attempt to retrieve a
sample of the Martian soil.
</P>
<P>
   NASA spokesman Don Savage said that although ``there have been
discussions'' inside the agency of possible missions to retrieve
material from Europa, one of Jupiter's moons, none has been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Indications that Europa may be surrounded by a relatively thin
sheet of ice overlaying a deep ocean, along with the fact that
gravitational stresses from Jupiter may give it heat, suggest that
two of the main conditions for life exist there, the committee
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended that samples from Europa, its fellow
moon Ganymede and some asteroids be treated with the same
precautions it recommended for material and spaceships returning
from Mars. They are that no uncontained material, including
spacecraft surfaces exposed to the Martian environment, be returned
to Earth until it had been sterilized en route.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Orgel, a research professor at the Salk Institute in San
Diego, Calif., and chairman of the committee, said in an interview
that if material were returned to earth from Europa, a body only
slightly smaller than the Earth's moon, it should be handled
``extremely carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
