<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF CHRISTIAN BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``GodStories''
</P>
<P>
   By H. Stephen Shoemaker
</P>
<P>
   Judson Press, $16
</P>
<P>
   Depicted on the cover of H. Stephen Shoemaker's ``GodStories''
is a statue of the prophet Elijah. But the cover could have used a
drawing of a sack of oranges and lemons _ a mixed bag, in other
words, for that is what the book sometimes is.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth minister's latest work explores some of the
best-known tales and personalities of the Bible. Shoemaker can
provide exquisite bits of insight or commentary; he notes, for
instance, that like the ancients, we have our Baal worship: ``It is
the religion of success (if it works _ do it), self (if it serves
me _ do it), and sensuality (if it feels good _ do it), that is, of
pragmatism, egoism, and the pleasure principle.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``GodStories'' is also prone to the occasional statement
that is questionable at best: that Jesus' 40 days in the wilderness
were ``a kind of `vision quest,' '' for instance, or that ``God not
only understood what Tamar (who seduced her father-in-law, Judah)
had to do to survive; he called her righteous. She had done nothing
evil in the sight of the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   There are good things to be found in ``GodStories.'' Just be
sure to sort the fruit carefully.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep Your Mind on Jesus''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Mass Choir
</P>
<P>
   CGI Records
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the Chicago Mass Choir has established
itself as one of the better mass choirs in the country, mainly by
standing true to traditional sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The old school gospel styles are still here on this, the group's
latest CD, but there are more modern touches _ and mainly to the
good. ``Keep Your Mind on Jesus'' is a strong CD, one that can
appeal to both older and younger gospel fans, although the former
will probably enjoy it a bit more, as some of the more modern
touches (synthesizers draped everywhere, funk bass lines) come off,
at times, as just a touch underwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   The choir's strengths, however, outweigh these slight glitches.
The vocal arrangements are sure, and the group does an uncommonly
good job of picking the right lead vocalist for a given song:
Shanta McSwain, for example, provides just the right mix of
understatement and fire for the opener, ``I Promised the Lord,''
and Teddy Campbell's big, rich pipes give the stomping,
traditional, organ-driven ``Keep Your Mind on Jesus'' the kick it
needs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
