<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6757 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-THEATER-COPENH     07-15 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-THEATER-COPENHAGEN-$ADV19-(850)-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECULATING ON SCIENCE, HITLER AND THE BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 19)  
 (JT)  
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Why did Werner Heisenberg, the German who formulated
the uncertainty principle, pay a visit to Niels Bohr, the Dane who
made key discoveries in quantum theory, in the occupied Copenhagen
of 1941? A layman might think this the sort of topic that
history-of-science students come up with when their search for a
doctoral thesis is getting desperate. Yet the meeting of the two
Nobel Prize-winning physicists could help explain why you and I are
not now living in a world controlled by Son of Hitler and his
cybernetic Gestapo. It certainly supplies Michael Frayn with the
material for one of the boldest, meatiest plays the Royal National
Theater has staged this decade: ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   Frayn has been creatively quietish in the 1990's, but he had his
successes in the previous two decades, notably with the sublimely
funny ``Noises Off,'' which crossed the Atlantic in 1984 to
brighten a notably gloomy Broadway season. That's a farce about a
touring theater company's attempts to perform a nonsensical but
technically demanding piece of dramatic knockabout, and, on the
face of it, is about as different as could be from ``Copenhagen,''
which is a dryly witty but ultimately somber post-mortem on
Heisenberg and his possibly deliberate failure to develop an A-bomb
for the German war machine. Yet there are moments even in ``Noises
Off'' when Frayn hints at what has always been his overriding
theme: our feverish, frantic, invariably frustrated efforts to
bring order to the world's chaos and give shape to its confusions.
That's the idea at the very core of ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a philosophical play, then, but it's not dry, not
impersonal and, despite a forbidding set, not abstract. True, Peter
J. Davison has transformed the Cottesloe auditorium into a blend of
debating chamber, physics lab and war crimes tribunal, with part of
the audience sitting like jurors behind actors who pace a spare
white circle. True, mesons, protons, cyclotrons and names like
Wirtz, Diebner, Houtermanns and Pauli drop as easily from the
scientists' lips as talk of ``Titanic'' and Leonardo DiCaprio does
from Hollywood groupies. But the emotional stakes for the two main
characters are high, since Bohr was Heisenberg's mentor, surrogate
father and, after that fateful meeting in 1941, estranged
ex-colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Since Heisenberg was also the head of Hitler's nuclear program,
the future of the planet is an issue too, which is about as high as
stakes can reasonably get. Intellectually taxing though the piece
can be, it is more engrossing than Tom Stoppard's 1988 play
``Hapgood,'' which drew jokey analogies between the behavior of
particles in quantum mechanics and the similar unpredictability of
Le Carre-style spies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copenhagen'' _ already seen for several performances in the
United States in June as part of the International Festival of Arts
and Ideas in New Haven _ occurs in the future. However, the
dialogue veers between past and present tenses as Matthew Marsh's
wan, tense Heisenberg, David Burke's genial but wary Bohr and Sara
Kestelman's tough, spiky Mrs. Bohr remember, argue and revisit key
events from the limbo they now inhabit. These restless shades want
to make sense of all that preceded and followed their meeting in
1941, and, Frayn being Frayn, there are more questions than
answers. It seems to be common ground that Heisenberg asked Bohr if
it was ethical to exploit atomic energy and that Bohr speedily
terminated the conversation. But what was the German's aim in
raising the subject and what else was said?
</P>
<P>
   Conceivably, Heisenberg wanted to recruit Bohr or to pick his
scientific brains. Maybe he hoped to learn what if anything the
Allies were doing with nuclear fission. Perhaps he planned to use
Bohr to get a surreptitious message to his fellow physicists in
America. Maybe he wanted to tell them that Germany had made so
little progress on the Bomb that they could save their consciences
by scaling down their program.
</P>
<P>
   All and more of these possibilities have been suggested by
biographers and are repeated in the play. In the end, you don't
know if Heisenberg was a loyal German who failed to make a crucial
calculation out of sheer incompetence, a heroic anti-Nazi who
prevented Armageddon by subtly sabotaging his own work, or, as the
cynical Margrethe Bohr suspects, a boyish showoff who came to
Copenhagen to brag of his importance to a man he worshiped.
</P>
<P>
   The play is packed with subtleties and ironies, not least that
Heisenberg's physics never hurt a fly, while Bohr, acknowledged by
all as a good and great man, escaped to Los Alamos and helped
design the trigger that set off the Nagasaki explosion. It leaves
you feeling what ``Constructions,'' the book of pensees that Frayn
published in 1974, persistently suggests. We're always trying to
find coherence in human experience that is too intricate and
elusive for explanation of any kind: ``Our complexity is such that
we can understand many things. But not our own complexity!''
</P>
<P>
   Memory is so subjective, motives so mixed and thoughts so
evanescent that nobody, not even the man himself, can finally say
why Heisenberg went to Nazi-occupied Copenhagen. In other words,
the scientist might almost have been a particle in one of his own
quantum experiments, a weird, inscrutable dot capable of morally
existing in two places at once. As Margrethe says, he is ``here,
there, everywhere, nowhere.'' The play's accomplishment is to make
such ideas fascinating and concrete. The achievement of Michael
Blakemore's robustly acted production is to convince you of the
exhilaration of scientific discovery and the torment of the
scientists themselves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
