<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONDON-THEATER-COPENH     07-15 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-THEATER-COPENHAGEN-2NDTAKE-$ADV19-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LONDON: scientists themselves.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the National's Lyttelton auditorium there is a play, or
rather a stage adaptation of a well-known book, that is also much
concerned with teachers and pupils, parent figures and those they
influence. But in ``The Prime of Miss Jean Brodie'' it is the guru
who seems contaminated by fascism.
</P>
<P>
   The title character of Muriel Spark's novel is an Edinburgh
schoolteacher of the 1930's who proudly proclaims, ``Give me a girl
at an impressionable age and she is mine for life.'' That's fine
when it's Renaissance painting that she is impressing on their
unformed minds, a little less fine when it's her own love life, and
positively sinister when it's Mussolini, Hitler or Franco. The
result of her naivete is that the dopiest of her acolytes goes off
to the Spanish Civil War and is killed; her favorite pupil betrays
her to her great enemy, the dourly unimaginative head of Marcia
Blaine Academy _ and Miss Brodie ends up a broken woman.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the denouement slightly distorts Muriel Spark's
original; but in all other respects the American writer Jay Presson
Allen's new adaptation is more faithful to the original than her
own earlier versions for stage and screen. That is one
justification for reintroducing Jean Brodie to London only some
three years after the lady last appeared on a West End stage. The
others are the energy of Phyllida Lloyd's production, which packs a
sparsely furnished stage with schoolgirl bustle and scattiness,
and, especially, the skills of the principal performer.
</P>
<P>
   Fiona Shaw isn't as well known in America as she should and
surely will be (her acclaimed one-woman stage version of the T.S.
Eliot poem ``The Waste Land'' was presented all too briefly in New
York in 1996), but any visitor to London would do well to see her
Brodie. She is more serious than Maggie Smith, who comically winced
and minced her way through the role on the screen in 1969, and less
chilling than her most recent stage counterpart, Patricia Hodge,
who came across as the steely Eva Braun of Scots education. In Ms.
Shaw's charismatic, scarlet-clad Brodie, warmth and teacherly
commitment are so strong that you're ready to overlook the
narcissism, the perverse romanticism, the dangerous misuse of power
and all her other faults: which makes Ms. Allen's play, like Ms.
Spark's novel, a reproach to those who like good and evil glibly
packaged.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Globe _ meaning the loving replica of
Shakespeare's most celebrated theater that now stands across the
Thames from St. Paul's Cathedral _ has opened its second season,
most impressively with Lucy Bailey's brisk, sprightly revival of
``As You Like It.'' Anastasia Hille, seen at the Brooklyn Academy
of Music in 1995 as Webster's doomed Duchess of Malfi and at the
New Victory Theater last year in ``The Two Gentlemen of Verona,''
begins by looking a bit like the wan, tall, pinched maiden in
distress in Uccello's famous picture of St. George and the dragon:
which is apt, for the court of David Rintoul's grim Duke Frederick
is peopled by sleazy aides in reptilian doublets. But when she puts
on male clothes and cavorts in the Forest of Arden with Jonathan
Bond's lithe, nervy Orlando, the red comes to her cheeks and the
fun to her eyes _ and she skips about as exuberantly as some
innocently sexy teen-ager in her first nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   It's nice to see so able an actress on a stage that has still to
attract many of Britain's brightest and best performers and has not
yet proved it can bear Shakespeare's weightiest plays.
</P>
<P>
   The Wooden O's open roof, thrust stage and yardful of
groundlings below combine to make subtlety difficult and audience
participation inevitable, at times worryingly inevitable.
Reportedly, Norbert Kentrup's Shylock, who appears in a production
of ``The Merchant of Venice'' running in rep with ``As You Like
It,'' has sometimes been booed during the performance. Let's
presume that is less a display of anti-Semitism than of distaste
for a potential butcher.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, when spectators hiss villains who join in the fun
by making menacing gestures back at them, or chorus ``ahhh'' when
events get poignant or characters look forlorn, there is reason for
concern. But what is harmless enough in the case of ``As You Like
It'' or last year's ``Two Gentlemen of Verona'' may turn out to be
catastrophic when the theater eventually risks a tragedy. Angry
heckling when Iago threatens to destroy Othello? Sympathetic groans
when Lady Macbeth rubs at the invisible spot on her hand? Oh, dear.
Oh, no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
