<HEADLINE>
LATIN BANKING LESSON
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international and ``f'' financial files.) 
 By SCOTT MORRISON 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    TORONTO _ Scotiabank's foray into Latin America has been
something of a rude awakening for Chairman Peter Godsoe. The bank
got off to a poor start in the region in the early 1990s when it
acquired an 8.4 percent interest in Mexico's Grupo Financiero
Inverlat for US$110 million. Scotiabank got two seats out of 50 on
its partner's board, leaving the Canadian bank with virtually no
voice.
 &HT;    To make matters worse, the quality of Inverlat's outstanding
loan portfolio became all too apparent following the 1994 Mexican
peso crisis, forcing the bank to write off its investment. The bank
spent millions of dollars more and now has a 55 percent share. In
Argentina, the bank found itself in a similar situation when it
took full ownership of Banco Quilmes last year in order to
recapitalize it. The bank's experience in both countries exposed
many of the pitfalls foreign bankers face in the region. And the
Bank of Nova Scotia, widely known as Scotiabank, certainly learned
its lesson, says Godsoe, 60, who has been chairman since 1995. He
joined the bank in 1966.
 &HT;    Lesson number one: Scotiabank will move more aggressively to
gain control of its acquisitions, or, at the very least, have
substantial influence over its partners. Such a strategy may have
given the bank enough time to fully review Inverlat's outstanding
loans and corrected problems prior to the bank imploding, says
Godsoe. Lesson number two: Scotiabank will insist on conducting
more extensive due diligence of prospective partners. The strategy
was put into practice recently when the bank backed away from
acquiring Banco Bandeirantes because the Brazilian bank would not
meet Scotiabank's terms.
 &HT;    The painful, costly lessons learned in Latin America have not
soured the bank's taste for doing business in the region, says
Godsoe, who says the Brazilian banking market remains top priority.
Godsoe says he will focus on closing a ``do-able'' deal at the
right price, even if it means again taking a minority position. But
it would insist on an arrangement enabling it to increase its
investment over time.
 &HT;    Analysts say the time Scotiabank spent learning its lesson may
have cost them precious market share. Spanish competitors Santander
and Banco Bilbao Vizcaya are spending billions in acquisitions,
placing them as leaders in several Latin American markets. In
comparison, Scotiabank has invested $750 million to acquire
holdings in seven Latin American countries.
 &HT;    Industry observers say niche markets exist for smaller
institutions specializing in corporate banking or wealth
management, but only the top five retail banks in each market will
thrive. Not so, says Godsoe. ``You can do very well even if you are
not number one or two because you get higher spreads and strong
growth (in Latin America),'' says Godsoe.
 &HT;    Godsoe remains confident, citing recent policy reforms, reduced
government intervention, increased domestic savings and a vastly
under-banked market. He notes that in Argentina, for example, only
25 percent of the population even has a bank account, meaning that
plenty of opportunities exist to grow.
 &HT;    Godsoe expects Latin American revenues to grow by about 15
percent annually, adjusted for inflation, due to rapid growth and
