<HEADER>
A6794 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN16-COX     07-15 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Triple threat to homer record worries Aaron
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ You might have overheard someone at the water cooler
mention in passing this Mark McGwire fellow. He's hit a few fly
balls over guys' heads this season _ 40 of 'em, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you've seen a clip of Ken Griffey Jr. booming one of his
37 homers into the nether reaches of stadiums here and far. He's
got pop. And Sammy Sosa's 35 long balls are longer than the ivy at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Women are swooning. Fifty-year-olds are taking gloves to
ballparks. Kids want to be just like Mac. And the Kid. And Sammy.
Three sluggers in chase of history and the 37-year-old record of 61
home runs in a season. This chase of Roger Maris is, in a word,
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   But what really gets the heart pumping for one senior vice
president of the Atlanta Braves, what really fills his tank are ...
are ... triples.
</P>
<P>
   Triples?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come out and take a survey of 1,000 people in the
stands and ask them what they'd rather see, I'd bet 90 percent
would rather see a home run,'' the front-office executive said by
telephone Tuesday. ``Me, I get more excitement out of a triple. It
lasts longer. Fans have more time to cheer. When you hit a home
run, it's out of the park, you cheer, that's the end of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A triple is like a guy breaking away from the 1-yard line and
running 80 yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, but what does Hank Aaron know? Well, he knows a thing or
two about home runs because he hit more of them than anyone who
ever wiped pine tar on his hands. Don't get him wrong. Baseball's
all-time home run king didn't hit 755 balls out of stadiums without
developing a lasting appreciation for his sport's equivalent of the
touchdown bomb or the coast-to-coast slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   But the 64-year-old Hall of Famer who made Babe Ruth the most
famous runner- up in sports history gets juiced every time he sees
Jose Offerman and Delino DeShields leg out a three-bagger.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron is to be forgiven if he considers homers more mundane than
tarp crews. Triples are much more rare, as his 23-year career with
the Milwaukee/Atlanta Braves and Milwaukee Brewers can attest. He
spliced in only 98 triples among his 1,477 extra-base hits, but
once had 14 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   He never approached Maris' home run record _ the most he ever
hit in one season was 47 in 1971 _ but no one could approach his
consistency. Aaron hit at least 30 home runs in 15 seasons and
topped 40 homers eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron recognizes the public's fanatical obsession with
gargantuan shots, no matter if it's drooling over John Daley's
drives or John Elway's bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pennant races are practically over with, but fans have
always been fascinated by people hitting the ball out of the park,
and they always will be,'' Aaron said. ``We've got one of the best
pitchers in baseball in Greg Maddux, who's having a fantastic year,
but he can't put a dent in the publicity. It's second-page stuff.
Home runs just have that mystique.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron likes the possibility that Maris' record will fall, but he
is hoping it doesn't crumble. Triples thrill him, but he doesn't
think that applies to the treasured home run mark.
</P>
<P>
   A three-headed champion would make the record seem too
commonplace, unbefitting the swell of attention. Aaron marvels at
McGwire's prodigious power, Griffey's consistency and Sosa's
improved knowledge of the strike zone, but he thinks to catch
Maris, they have to be at least five homers ahead of the Yankee's
pace entering September.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very good chance it will be broken,'' he said,
``because McGwire hits 'em in bunches. The sad part about it is if
all three break the record, it would take away some of the hype. If
Griffey hits 65, Sosa hits 63 and McGwire hits 68, it wouldn't be
the same. It'd be better if one broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their pressure cooker won't begin to compare to Aaron's assault
on Babe's 714-homer mark, when he had to shrug off death threats
and register at hotels under assumed names. Even so, Aaron
considers Joe DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak and the 57-year gap
since Ted Williams became the last hitter to bat .400 more
unreachable standards than 61 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron watched a reluctant Griffey win the home run contest at
the All-Star Game in Coors Field. Aaron has never cared for such
theatrics, even though he outdueled Maris and Mickey Mantle and won
$30,000 in the Home Run Derby filmed in Los Angeles, money he used
to buy his father a grocery store in his hometown of Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   That was six times his major-league salary when he broke in with
the Milwaukee Braves in 1954. Although Aaron pulled down $250,000
before he retired in 1976, he wonders if today's sluggers will have
the perseverance for such longevity records, given their enormous
paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   While he gives Griffey the best chance of dethroning him as the
career home- run champion, the 28-year-old Mariner would have to
average about 40 homers for the next 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Does a four-year, $34-million contract diffuse Griffey's will?
Aaron played to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``These players have enough money to buy a city,'' Aaron said.
``It's not that players aren't capable of doing all these things,
but they're making so much damn money they can't keep their eye on
the prize. If I had to pick one or the other, I'd still take the
longevity because money and a fool part quick, and there are some
things you can't put a value on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-14-98 2352E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
