<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6796 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN16-COX     07-15 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Let's get the manslaughter out of hockey
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A thug pleaded not guilty recently in Plymouth, Mich., to a
felony charge of assault to do great bodily harm less than murder.
</P>
<P>
   The thug's name is Jesse Boulerice. He's 19, and a prospect with
the Philadelphia Flyers. During an Ontario Hockey League playoff
game in Apri46 Boulerice, playing for the Plymouth Whalers,
apparently took violent exception to a check delivered by Andrew
Long of the Guelph (Ont.) Storm.
</P>
<P>
   According to a wire-service report on police review of the
incident, Long, a 19-year-old Florida Panthers prospect, was
skating away after the check when Boulerice swung his stick in
baseball fashion. Long, knocked unconscious, went into convulsions
and was hospitalized with blood on the brain and a broken nose,
nasal cavity and cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty stitches were required to close a gash from the tip of
Long's nose to his lip.
</P>
<P>
   Read the charge again _ assault to do great bodily harm less
than murder _ and shudder one more time at the reality that those
nine words actually exist within the context of a law.
</P>
<P>
   The felony carries a penalty of up to 10 years in prison and a
$5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is about to go on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Because if Boulerice's unconscionable act doesn't result in
substantial change of hockey's rules as they apply to everything
from fighting to retaliation, then the message is clear _ on ice,
anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest hockey reduce itself to a polite
exercise. It is a physical game, and anyone able to gain an edge
through intimidation establishes a considerable advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But that edge can and should be gained through checks delivered
hard and clean. There is no place, or shouldn't be, for even one
stick-swinging player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect guys who play tough and straight-up,'' said Long in
a telephone conversation Tuesday night from Guelph, Ontario, where
he says he is fully recovered from the injuries. ``But this almost
seemed like a psychotic rage. It's a scary thing when you've grown
up dreaming of being a hockey player and realize someone can take
it away from you in a second.''
</P>
<P>
   A no-tolerance line needs to be drawn. Immediately. Make it
simple _ no swinging the stick with the intention of making contact
with another player. No more ankle chops. No more swipes at the
back of a leg. No more using the butt end, either.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little chance such strict rules will be adopted. K
The unfortunate assumption is that hockey needs to be savage beyond
its natural ferociousness. The unfortunate accompanying and
prevailing attitude is that bruta 7/8ity has a place in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think so?
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary hearing awaits Boulerice, who is serving a
one-year OHL suspension. According to reports, Boulerice's
attorney, James Howarth, has suggested that his client's actions
are nothing out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens everywhere from pee-wee to the NHL,'' Howarth has
been quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   He's absolutely correct.
</P>
<P>
   Stick-swinging does happen everywhere from pee-wee to the NHL.
That's precisely the point.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to change the notion that it's permissible, even
reasonable, to use a piece of equipment as a weapon. It's time to
abandon the idea that an ambush is to be expected, even tolerated,
from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Or settle on the chilling concept that, in hockey, anything less
than murder is OK.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
