   AIRTRAN-PROFIT _ AirTran in the second quarter logged its first
profit since the carrier, then called ValuJet, resumed flying in
late 1996. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IWORLD _ Coverage of keynote speech from sprint CEO talking
about the advantages of high speed connections to the net, and
interview with Media One executive about broadband. Will tie them
together for one of this conference's hot topics _ the broadband
future. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TIMEWARNER _ Time Warner's top executives discuss the company's
current finances, including those of Turner Broadcasting.
Second-quarter earnings tripled, surpassing analysts' expectations
of a loss, helped by strong advertising at its cable television
channels and magazines and rising TV program distribution revenue
at the company's Warner Bros. Unit. Net income rose to $101
million, or four cents a share. Analysts had expected a loss of
four cents. The company earned $30 million, for a per-share loss of
nine cents, in the year-ago period. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WACHOVIA _ Wachovia's second-quarter earnings were a penny ahead
of analysts' expectations. (Chambers, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ Fortune and Forbes prove once again that two objects _
in this case corporations _ can occupy the same space at the same
time. The space is first place on their annual lists of the world's
500 biggest corporations. One thing is certain, whichever one it is
it's a General Motors on Fortune's list, General Electric on
Forbes.' (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HBO _ McKesson Corp., the largest U.S. drug wholesaler, said it
has ended merger talks with HBO Co., a maker of computer
information systems for the health-care industry. Neither would say
why. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GMSUPPLIERS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Amcast Industrial Corp., which
makes wheels and other parts for GM, announced Wednesday it has
ceased most North American production as a result of the ongoing
UAW strikes at GM. (Wagner, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   CAPITAL-METRO _ AUSTIN _ Capital Metro is ``a dysfunctional
organization'' that has become mired in a culture of lax spending,
inefficiency and complete lack of accountability, the state
comptroller's office says in a report to be released today. The
250-plus page performance review cites numerous problems, from poor
planning to negligent accounting and spending of taxpayers' money.
Examples include spending more than $25,000 for a casino-theme
employee Christmas Party, and six-figure consulting contracts that
have produced little useful data. (Hiott, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-SWISSBANKS _ TALLAHASSEE _ Bill Nelson affirmed that he
is prepared to ask for sanctions against Union Bank of Switzerland
and Credit Suisse if the banks do not reach a satisfactory
settlement with Jewish groups.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Nelson, Florida's insurance commissioner, mentioned
the possibility of sanctions to The Palm Beach Post in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those banks don't treat people correctly, I'm going after
them,'' Nelson said. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
