<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPITAL-METRO16-COX     07-15 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPITAL-METRO16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report: Cap Metro ran out of control
 &HT;    By Debbie Hiott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Capital Metro is ``a dysfunctional organization'' that
has become mired in a culture of lax spending, inefficiency and
complete lack of accountability, the state comptroller's office
says in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
   The 250-plus page performance review cites numerous problems,
from poor planning to negligent accounting and spending of
taxpayers' money. Examples include spending more than $25,000 for a
casino-theme employee Christmas Party, and six-figure consulting
contracts that have produced little useful data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Capital Metro's board and managers have made expensive,
embarrassing mistakes,'' the report states. ``More to the point,
however, they have been allowed to go on repeating them, year after
year, with no consequences and no apparent ability to learn from
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   While previous reviews and audits have pointed out problems,
today's report by State Comptroller John Sharp's Texas Performance
Review team discloses numerous problems that have never been made
public.
</P>
<P>
   Among the revelations in the report:
</P>
<P>
   The agency is top-heavy, with administrative costs consuming
18.1 percent of its $70 million annual operating budget. In 1995,
when administrative costs were 19.7 percent of the budget, the
costs were 23 percent higher than the average in a group of 18
comparable transit authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Spending is excessive and inefficient because of a lack of
accountability. The agency was unable to locate $79,000 worth of
assets, such as computers and printers, during a recent inventory.
For a 1996 Christmas party at a local hotel, the agency spent
almost $19,000 on food for 650 employees and nearly $7,000 for
other costs. The report also cited excessive travel costs, $60,000
worth of cellular phone use last year, and spending on perks
ranging from from movie tickets to $8,000 for shirts and caps.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Metro has exaggerated its ridership figures. The agency
estimated there were 29 million passenger boardings last year,
which may be inflated by 6 million. Capital Metro reports 120,000
boardings a day, but because the agency counts transfers from one
bus to another, the actual number of people riding the buses each
day is closer to 42,000, the review says.
</P>
<P>
   There are significant and unexplained discrepancies between
farebox reports of revenue collection and actual cash collected.
Capital Metro does not routinely investigate such discrepancies,
which can be as much as 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Operating costs have risen in recent years at a higher rate than
ridership. Board decisions ``have been based largely on a simple
desire to increase ridership with little or no examination of the
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor planning has resulted in hundreds of thousands of dollars
in wasted consulting work.
</P>
<P>
   The human resources department ``has repeatedly failed to meet
the most basic expectations for its mission.'' Training and
performance processes are ``largely ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   Capital Metro has not managed its railroad well, using public
money to do work on the tracks that the review team suggests should
be done by the rail freight operator, Longhorn Railway. In
addition, the agency is unable to account for the leases and
licenses that allow others to use the railroad right-of-way.
</P>
<P>
   The staff and board have been slow to complete strategic plans
that outline long-term goals and performance measures for the
agency as a whole and by departments.
</P>
<P>
   The report makes several recommendations. Capital Metro would
save $4.2 million in the upcoming budget year and $22 million over
five years if it applied the recommendations, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   While the report appears to blame most problems on previous
administrators and board members, the current management and board
have much more work to do to turn the agency around, it says.
</P>
<P>
   Interim General Manager Gerald Robichaux, who reviewed the
report last week but had not seen a final copy or recommendations,
said many issues it raises have been corrected or are being
corrected under his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critical, but it's nothing really different from what
we'd been told in several other audits,'' he said. ``If that's read
to believe those things still exist, I have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance review comes at a crucial time for the agency,
as it tries to regain community credibility before presenting a
light-rail system to voters as early as next spring. The transit
authority is not obligated to comply with the state team's
recommendations, but board members, who had not seen the review
Tuesday, have said the review would be valuable in their efforts to
improve the transit system.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Metro's credibility has suffered amid allegations of
mismanagement and an ongoing FBI investigation into its business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Metro requested the review in part to stave off critics,
including some in the state Legislature who considered legislation
to allow voters to reduce Capital Metro's 1-cent sales tax levy.
The agency collects about $90 million a year, an average of $350
from each household in its service area.
</P>
<P>
   The report acknowledges recent improvements: a new contracts and
procurement manager who is improving the problem-plagued
department, a more aggressive board that has begun to streamline
spending, better budgeting, and recent work to begin compiling data
on riders and routes. At the root of many of Capital Metro's
problems, according to the review, is a failure to make management
and employees accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers generally do not face any consequences for
substandard performance,'' the review states. In addition, ``with
its growing stream of local tax revenues, Capital Metro has had the
luxury of complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   To curb wasteful spending, the review recommends reinstating an
internal audit position that was eliminated this spring. The review
says former auditor Tony Tegbe told top management about examples
of waste, but that his reports were rarely acted upon.
</P>
<P>
   The position should be strengthened by allowing the auditor to
report directly to the board instead of to the general manager, the
review states.
</P>
<P>
   Capital Metro will spend the next few weeks looking over the
report's findings and recommendations, Robichaux said. He said the
critical report is another difficult blow for a staff that has been
battered by more than a year of controversy, from major management
overhauls to the FBI investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep our heads up and keep turning this around,''
he said. ``A lot of this stuff these people (still at the agency)
were not involved with. They're involved with turning this
around.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth coverage of Capital Metro's continuing troubles,
visit Austin360.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
