<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-SWISSBANKS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida insurance commissioner ``did not know'' Swiss bank
connection to Holocaust victim money
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ Bill Nelson affirmed that he is prepared to ask
for sanctions against Union Bank of Switzerland and Credit Suisse
if the banks do not reach a satisfactory settlement with Jewish
groups.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Nelson, Florida's insurance commissioner, mentioned
the possibility of sanctions to The Palm Beach Post in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those banks don't treat people correctly, I'm going after
them,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he did not know about accusations that the banks
stole Holocaust victims' assets when he signed off on contracts for
them to provide credit to a state insurance concern.
</P>
<P>
   He was unaware, Nelson said, that a lawsuit against the banks
had been filed four months before he approved the second contract
in 1997. The suit did not exist when the first contract was
approved in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The banks have offered $600 million to settle Holocaust claims
but negotiators are asking for $1.5 billion. California has banned
the banks from state business and New York is threatening do so by
Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Union Bank of Switzerland became the lead bank or
``syndication agent'' in a consortium of international banks
providing $1.5 billion in credit to Florida's Joint Underwriting
Association, a state-created home insurer of last resort. The
agency can tap the money to pay claims in the event of a hurricane.
Fees to the Swiss banks total an estimated $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he has asked attorneys to explore his legal powers
to ask the JUA to stop doing business with the banks. The current
contract runs through 1999 and Nelson said he would consider
breaking that contract if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Tuesday he did not recall signing any documents
mentioning Swiss banks in 1995, but Union Bank of Switzerland is
mentioned in a one-page document he signed on Sept. 7, 1995
certifying the credit arrangement. J.P. Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.
of New York served as managing agent for the banks in both
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Jewish groups favor sanctions. Nelson said he would also
have to consider the financial best interest of the 270,000
homeowners protected by the JUA before making any final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the banks said sanctions would be the wrong move
considering the progress that has been made to rectify a
50-year-old problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-14-98 2054E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
