<SLUG> BC-RENO-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS BLAST RENO, CHARGE COVER-UP IN CLINTON FINANCE
PROBE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno drew unrelenting fire
from Senate Republicans on Wednesday as she sought to defend her
decision not to call for an independent counsel to investigate
alleged campaign finance violations by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, in which Republicans suggested she may be part of a
White House cover-up, became so intense that Reno told Senate
Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, ``You don't have
to be so fierce at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, rejecting the cover-up charge, said she has called for
independent counsel examinations of Clinton, including allegations
about the failed Whitewater land deal and his purported affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch asked the attorney general how she could expect Clinton's
own Justice Department to investigate the president vigorously and
said Reno has an apparent conflict of interest in overseeing such
an examination of her boss. He said Reno's failure to seek an
independent investigation of Clinton would forever mar her
otherwise laudable tenure as attorney general because people would
wonder if she was part of a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, in my opinion, is going to be your legacy,'' said Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reno responded, ``I didn't come into the job for my
legacy.'' Saying an attorney general's job is to follow the
evidence and the law, Reno added she has yet to see evidence that
would require her to call for a special investigation under the
independent counsel statute.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general also took strong exception to Hatch's
reading from an editorial in Wednesday's New York Times that
suggested she was trying to protect the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do things based on editorials,'' Reno said. ``I don't
do things based on pressure ... I am going to always listen to you,
but not when you wave editorials at me.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said she reconsiders her decision every day
and would call for an independent counsel only when the evidence
and law indicated one was necessary. However, she declined to
specify what evidence she has seen, citing the department's policy
of not commenting on pending investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven Democratic donors have been indicted as a result of the
Justice Department's investigation of alleged campaign finance
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel statute, the attorney general must
ask a panel of three federal judges to name an independent counsel
when a Justice Department investigation indicates an administration
official might have committed a crime; the law also states that an
attorney general may seek an independent counsel when a conflict of
interest between the department and the president suggests one
should be named.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier at the hearing, Sens. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., and Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., criticized Reno for failing to name an independent
counsel to investigate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson faulted the attorney general for discounting the advice
of FBI Director Louis Freeh, who called it a conflict of interest
for the Justice Department to investigate alleged presidential
misdeeds. As chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
Thompson held hearings that were unable to prove Clinton received
illegal contributions from the Chinese government during the
president's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Specter presented a chart showing alleged White House
contributions from several of the 11 indicted donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the contributors are indicted,'' Specter said. ``What
about the recipient?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Reno replied that ``informed judgments should dictate public
policy. I've seen a lot of evidence other than that chart.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
