<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-HOME-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERY PLACE GIVE GLIMPSE OF LIFE IN 19TH CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNANDALE-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Situated high on the eastern bank of
the Hudson River in Annandale-on-Hudson, Montgomery Place, a
434-acre estate, remains one of the best-documented architectural
landmarks of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery Place is the prototype of the American Country
Seat,'' said J. Winthrop ``Winty'' Aldrich, a descendant of Robert
Livingston, the First Lord of Livingston Manor. Aldrich is co-owner
of nearby Rokby, another historic riverfront mansion that has been
in his family for 11 generations. Aldrich serves as deputy
commissioner for Historic Preservation for the New York Office of
Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montgomery Place was a working enclave. You see the property
in evolution and refinement, reflecting the taste of the era for
nearly 200 years. In its own way, Montgomery Place has always been
recognized for the importance of the people who lived there, who
shaped its design,'' Aldrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Named in memory of Gen. Richard Montgomery (1738-1775), the
first hero of the American Revolution, who was killed in the battle
for Quebec, Montgomery Place features a Classical Revival mansion,
open-to-the-public farm market, woodland hiking trails, historic
gardens and fetching views of the Hudson River and distant Catskill
Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   In continuous family ownership since 1805, Montgomery Place was
given to Sleepy Hollow Restorations (now Historic Hudson Valley) by
descendents of the Delafield family, the last clan to live there,
in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. John Ross Delafield, a Livingston relative born in 1874,
inherited Montgomery Place in 1921 and lived there summers with his
wife, Violetta White Delafield (1875-1949), until his death in
1964. Then, various descendants used it on a summer basis.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Place became a National Historic Landmark in 1992; it
has been open to the public since June 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion has been retained the way the family heirs left it,
rather than the way it was originally built by the general's
(Richard Montgomery) 59-year-old widow, Janet Livingston Montgomery
(1743-1828).
</P>
<P>
   A working farm at the time, she built a straightforward
Federal-style house at the terminus of a half-mile-long allee of
deciduous trees and fruit orchard. Many of the trees stand today.
She named the homestead Chateau de Montgomery in memory of her
husband, the French a reference to her brother's tenure as minister
to France from 1801 to 1805.
</P>
<P>
   Black locust trees that are 200 years old and 75 feet tall line
the west side of the house and are fragrant when in spring bloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dutch considered these trees good luck,'' said Lucy
Kuriger, site manager of Montgomery Place. ``They actually act as
lightning rods. They take hits all the time. Even if they get split
they just keep on growing.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a tulip poplar tree that could easily date back to the
virgin forest, before colonial settlers, according to Timothy
Steinhoff, director of horticulture for Historic Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The facade of the house started out as stuccoed fieldstone, to
make it look like stone blocks, with a five-bay window front view
and center door with slender side-light windows flanking each side
and a six-bay river (west) front topped by a hipped roof. It was a
simple rectangular house with no flanking wings.
</P>
<P>
   The floor plan consisted of two equally shaped rooms on the
(west) river side and two rooms to the front on the east side. The
center-hall entrance does not go all the way through to the west
side of the house. The spacious front center hall was used as a
receiving room before ushering guests into the library or drawing
room.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the stairway to the second floor was placed off of
a hall to the left side of the main entrance hall, making for a
clean, stairless front entry decorated with large oil portraits of
family members and furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   The hall was heated in winter with a large, ornate Federal-style
cast-iron stove that was placed at the end of the hall between the
formal dining parlor (as it was traditionally called) and the
parlor (drawing room). The stove pipe went up through all the
floors and out the roof.
</P>
<P>
   The original exterior entrance to the center hall was never
sheltered. The elegant semi-circular portico, with composit
capitals, that graces the front was added in 1863, as part of the
first phase of renovations designed by noted American architect
Alexander Jackson Davis, who based his design on the Temple of
Vesta in Tivoli, outside Rome. This portico was only a fraction of
the embellishments that Davis would add to this once-plain
Federal-style house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The yellow drawing room is one of the most exquisite in the
Hudson Valley,'' said preservationist architect Doug Bucher, with
the Albany firm of John G. Waite Associates, who did the historic
structures report for Montgomery Place.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Many of the current wallpapers are probably French,
as the family spent a great deal of time in France and other parts
of Europe. They cover several other layers of papers that were
applied through the years. To clean up the white background on the
paper, you can see where they spruced it up with white paint or cut
out new pieces and applied them in an attempt to make repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The brick-and-wood kitchen, with its full brick fireplace that
was used for cooking, stood over a sub-basement that was most
likely used as a root cellar originally and later for perhaps a
wine cellar or furnace.To muffle the sounds of cooking and clinking
of pots and pans, the floor between the kitchen and first-floor
dining room above is padded with mud and straw to absorb any
noise.The kitchen also included a stewing stove, which is a very
old cooking device.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   ``You burn charcoal in it to cook delicate sauces that you could
never make in a fireplace,'' said Bucher. ``They provided a slow,
refined way of cooking delicate things such as sauces. The French
used these in the 18th century, and the Romans had similar kinds.
They are usually built of brick under a window and contain two to
five openings covered with little metal grills. Montgomery Place
has four openings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used this stewing stove as the model for the Octagon House
in Washington. The one at Montgomery Place is one of the few to
survive in the country. These weren't unusual. Thomas Jefferson had
one at Monticello, because he had a French cook.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Janet Livingston Montgomery's guidance, Chateau de
Montgomery was transformed into a lucrative year-round working farm
with orchards, gardens, nursery and greenhouse in a sylvan setting.
</P>
<P>
   But with no direct family heirs, Janet left it to her youngest
brother, Edward Livingston (1764-1836), mayor of New York City,
U.S. representative and U.S. senator from Louisiana and secretary
of state and minister to France under Andrew Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   His worldly widow, Louise Livingston (1782-1860), a
French-speaking native of Haiti, and their daughter Coralie
Livingston Barton (1806-1873) used it as a summer retreat. It was
during this 40-year period that Montgomery Place, as they renamed
it, would enlist the services of noted American architect of the
romantic movement A.J. Davis (1803-1892) and further enhance the
property.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1842, Davis would make several changes, including
the addition of a conservatory, beautiful flower gardens and
several architectural follies.
</P>
<P>
   He also added porch extensions to the east, west and north sides
of the house. It was the open-arched columned porch on the north
side of the house that was designed for use as an outdoor room.
A.J. Downing (1815-1852), landscape architect from Newburgh, served
as consultant on the gardens and other landscape and statuary
features of the property and believed this to be the first outdoor
living space in America.
</P>
<P>
   An enclosed wing was added to the south side of the house, and
to link these all together, Davis designed classical detailing and
ballustrades along all of the roof lines, including the original
hipped roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current exterior creamy beige paint scheme with dark green
shutters was also designed by Davis,'' said Bucher. ``These colors
were meant to make the house rest comfortably in the landscape. The
porches were also painted with a sand-based paint to give it the
rich texture of stone like the rest of the house. This was a
trademark of Davis'.''
</P>
<P>
   The second phase of renovations, by Davis, began in the early
1860s. During this time he would design a classical-style coach
house, an Italianate farmhouse and a Gothic Revival-style Swiss
cottage on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   It was Coralie Barton who designed the ornamental flower gardens
surrounding the conservatory, carriage roads, bridle paths and
nature trails that were designed for walks for different times of
the day that were also marked with follies and resting spots.
</P>
<P>
   The repeating floral patterns and examples of symmetry are often
repeated inside the mansion, which can be seen on furnishings,
fabrics, porcelain and wallpapers.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, who was perhaps the foremost American writer on
landscape and garden subjects, wrote extensively about it.
``Montgomery Place is second as it is to no seat in America, for
its combination of attractions . . . all its varied mysteries of
pleasure-grounds and lawns, wood and water,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery Place would experience a brief decline during the
post-Civil War period, when it was occupied by relatives who never
owned it outright, but lived there under life tenancy. In 1921,
Gen. John Ross Delafield, a Livingstone descendant, inherited
Montgomery Place and used it as his country house to escape the
heat of his family home in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. John Ross Delafield's wife, Violetta White (1875-1949), was
an accomplished botanist. She created the terraced landscaping on
the west side of the house, looking out to the west and the open
river and to the north to Tivoli South Bay. She was also
responsible for the roses, herbs, perennials, artificial stream and
woodland plants and ellipse pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Delafields also brought the house into the 20th century by
adding electricity, plumbing and heat, without altering much else
in the house,'' said Bucher. ``They also added a clay tennis court,
squash court and greenhouse. The woodland walks were restored and
orchards improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``While renovating the house, they also started preservation of
Montgomery Place by cataloging everything and keeping extensive
records, which even included early receipts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Delafield family left the house to Historic Hudson Valley
fully furnished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is way too much to fit in all the rooms and still
leave room for visitors and guides to get around,'' said Kuriger,
site manager. ``Interior designer Mark Hampton selected all of the
pieces for the rooms, taking the house up to the Empire period.''
</P>
<P>
   Every family member who ever lived at Montgomery Place had a
huge attachment to the house and left their personal mark.``As each
family inherited Montgomery Place, they would make tasteful
additions that would build on past improvements to the house and
grounds,'' said Kathleen Eaagen Johnson, curator of Historic Hudson
Valley. ``They continued to create this incredible playground that
people still enjoy today. It's a very happy place, with interiors
filled with family memories and personalized belongings from each
family that lived here.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said that the second floor still has to be restored
before it can be open to the public, and some sort of safety
decision must be made concerning access, as there is only one
staircase. So for now, the second floor serves as storage for
furniture amassed through the years. The third floor, which is also
closed to the public and filled with furnishings, had served as
servants quarters.
</P>
<P>
   But the public has full access to the grounds for picnics,
walks, guided moonlight tours through the gardens. There's also an
abundance of fresh produce from the farm which is 46 acres in
actual production and 100 acres of open field at a stand that's
open seven days a week to the public from late June through Oct.
31. There you can buy fresh-picked peaches, apples, pears,
apricots, plums, four kinds of raspberries, seedless table grapes
and jams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite special when you stop and think about it,'' said
Wint Aldrich. ``That the farm stand has been publicly accessible
and operating for 190 years as a fruit farm. When Janet Montgomery
began, there was just a peach orchard. It was never a family
enclave that was closed to the outside world. There were always
people coming and going, including lots of family and house
guests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
