<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      07-15 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: DOES SYNERGY REALLY WORK? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most writers, synergy is just a word in the dictionary. It's
the buzzword, to be sure, in book publishing and other media in
this era of conglomeration and consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   But nonetheless, to those churning out magazine work, the
concept of an article's or a short story's growing into a book and
then a movie or a television series _ all within the same company _
has been little more than a whimsy. And that doesn't seem likely to
change despite Hollywood's ravenous need for material.
</P>
<P>
   Still, last week Tina Brown pumped new hope into the fancy. She
quit as editor of The New Yorker to start up a company affiliated
with Disney's Miramax Films to create a monthly magazine that would
then be the main strand in a wickerwork of books, films and
television shows. Synergy. Upward from the magazine piece. So far,
the details have been nil, but writers, worried about the loss of
outlets because of the recent mergers of book publishing companies,
may feel a bit better having this new publishing venture as an
added consumer, no matter what it turns out to be.
</P>
<P>
   Will the synergy work? It hasn't anywhere else, and most people
in book publishing feel it can't, although Ms. Brown's creativity
always gives hope where others have failed. What marches against it
is the very way in which a writer's writing is sold.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when a magazine buys a story, 99 percent of the
time what it has purchased is its one-shot publication in North
America. Nothing more. All other rights for that work _ overseas
sales, expansion into a book and its sale, movie and television
sales, electronic rights _ are retained by the writer, if the agent
is not in a coma. (The same is mostly true if the work starts out
as a book rather than a magazine article.)
</P>
<P>
   This simple system allows for a lucky writer to wallow in
multiple bidders offering increasing amounts of cash as they try to
buy the property for movie development, etc.
</P>
<P>
   The synergy faith, in essence, says, Give up all this for some
more money up front, and hope you'll someday see your work on the
screen or the tube. In fact, there would have to be a lot more
money in the beginning to buy up all these rights, plus a movie
guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Newberg, an author's agent, summed up the simple economy
of it all this way: ``Why would I ever wrap up a client's work in
one place? The first time a writer is called by a movie company and
told, `Too bad you didn't retain those rights; we would have paid
you more,' that's trouble for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gottlieb, an agent, said: ``This is the difference
between wishful thinking by the synergists and reality. I never
want to find that I've given up all the rights up front and the
author is sitting somewhere two years later asking me, `What's
going on?,''' wondering where is the movie. ``That's why we refused
to give the publishers electronic rights because of fear of their
warehousing them.''
</P>
<P>
   And that refusal to give away rights is why few, if any,
articles in Time Warner's array of magazines and few, if any, books
from its book publishing houses have become movies for Warner
Brothers or television shows for HBO or TNT, all of which it owns.
Similarly, Disney's magazines and its Hyperion Books have provided
nearly naught for Disney movies; nor has HarperCollins been able to
use synergy to whip books into movies or television mini-series for
Fox. (Disney-owned ABC-TV does get first crack at buying
Disney-produced movies, and TNT gets first look to buy Warner
Brothers movies, but that's synergy of a different kind.)
</P>
<P>
   Is there a way out of this box for the new company? Jean Naggar,
an agent, thinks probably not, except perhaps for a work by or
about a celebrity. She said that if the new company saw from the
first that the piece it was buying for its magazine could be made
into a movie, it might make the deal for the whole package right at
the start. But that, of course, means paying a lot more up front
than is given to even the highest-paid magazine writer.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, Ms. Brown could probably buy the right to top the
highest bidder, Ms. Naggar said. ``But an agent is going to retain
a maximum amount of rights; and to be willing to give away any of
those rights, the agent needs to be convinced it's good for the
author's career,'' Ms. Naggar said. ``It's not just about money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb said that synergy was ``a great Wharton business school
idea, but welcome to the entertainment world.'' He added that this
could work only if Miramax actually made a commitment to MAKE the
film, not just put it into development. ``It takes a tremendous
amount of energy and money to develop something into a movie,'' he
said, ``and you can't put too many into development.''
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, most movie projects never get out of development, if
they actually get that far, even when the story idea was purchased
in a flurry of competition. This year Miramax itself actually
produced about 14 of the 38 movies it distributed. Will the new
company get a Disney commitment for Miramax to make even more
movies, those growing out of the magazine?
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems for the writer in the synergistic
world. With Ms. Brown's fame, for instance, she could very likely
get some writers to consider giving her topping privileges, but
that could dampen the enthusiasm of other movie companies to make
meaningful bids if they know the bids could be topped.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, what happens when the writer is required to have the
manuscript run past the new company's movie-making machinery, and
it's rejected? The rejection would be no secret in Hollywood; the
writer is then left exposed and vulnerable, since another studio
will not often jump to buy what has been turned down by a
competitor. And television executives are even less prone to risk
taking than movie people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to have aggressive ideas on how to create a new
pipeline into the development of features, but the mechanics of
publishing and movies are very different, and only so many articles
or books can make it into development,'' Gottlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   Synergy, if it would ever work, would certainly be corporate
friendly, but for a writer it would be like being handed a mitten
to shake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
