<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6831 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROOKING-COX     07-15 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The modest millionaire
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- His newest passion is the sport of golf, and while
Keith Brooking continues to learn the nuances while strolling the
links at Chateau Elan, he has yet to find out how it feels to lose
a $5 golf bet.
</P>
<P>
   Bogeys are frustrating enough for Brooking, a first-round draft
choice of the Atlanta Falcons. He can afford to lose a bet or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a kid who suddenly has a lot of money, and his biggest
concern is like, 'Can I buy a new pair of jeans every month?' ``
said agent Gary Wichard, who negotiated Brooking's landmark
five-year contract totaling $7.9 million. ``Most guys who are
first-round prospects, very early in the process, are worrying
about a line of credit, a new car or whatever. Keith was just
totally oblivious to the money element. And, believe me, that is
the exception.''
</P>
<P>
   So for the inquiring minds who privately wonder what it is like
to turn out the lights a member of middle-class America and wake up
the next morning a millionaire, this bit of advice: It would be
better to find out from a lottery winner than from Brooking, a
former Georgia Tech linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster who could buy just about anything hasn't spent a
penny of his $3.8 million signing bonus -- the most the Falcons
have ever paid a rookie. Outside of the new Lincoln Navigator sport
utility vehihicle he leased a couple weeks before the draft, and a
dark $500 suit purchased from a Men's Wearhouse store so he'd look
good on the banquet circuit, there have been no luxuries for
Brooking or his family.
</P>
<P>
   The suit expense still bothers him. ``Still a lot of money for
something that you aren't going to use very much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking refused to get the Navigator, recalled Wichard, until
he completed his on-campus workout for league scouts and was
assured by personnel directors that he rated as a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Richie Rich of The Flats is more like the Scrooge
McDuck of Suwanee, his trademark football savvy perhaps equalled by
a dollar-wisdom rare for his age.
</P>
<P>
   On the day the Falcons signed Brooking, coach Dan Reeves
suggested that maybe too much attention was being paid by others to
the player's money matters. One element in the Falcons' selection
of Brooking, however, was the likelihood that his work ethic and
passion would not be diminished by sudden wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I can't see myself doing anything outrageous,''
Brooking said earlier this week. ``When I was growing up dreaming
about playing in the NFL, I thought to myself, 'Gosh, that's all I
want to do is be like those guys.' I can't ever recall thinking,
'Hey, I wonder how much money they make in the NFL.' Even though
this is my livelihood now, I never think about the money, except in
terms of how, if I'm smart with it, I should never have to worry
about a payday when I'm done playing. After 10 or 12 years, if I do
the right things, I'll be able to sit back and enjoy (the money)
then.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of the modern NFL is filled with stories of
prospects who squandered big money from short careers. Brooking
said he has read those stories. He vows not to become another
chapter (seven).
</P>
<P>
   During training camp, he will continue to live in the tiny
second-floor room of the Falcon Inn that he has shared with wide
receiver Tim Dwight, a fourth-round pick. He may move to an
apartment close to the team's complex at the beginning of the
season and then hunt for a townhouse next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives aren't surprised that Brooking has
eschewed the instant gratification provided by material
possessions. Raised by middle-class parents, Brooking learned at an
early age the ``sweat equity'' process and readily embraced the
concept.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Brenda Hembree of Senoia, and father, Harvey
Brooking of Forest Park, both agreed recently that their son has
simple tastes and appreciates the little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was in school, I think it was the 10th grade, we
surprised him with a Blazer,'' said Harvey Brooking. ``It wasn't a
new one, you understand. But it was pretty sharp, and he loved that
thing. ... I don't think Keith ever wanted for anything as a kid.
But if he did, he sure never asked for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking plans to buy both parents a new car, and he's thinking
of other ways to enhance their middle-class lifestyle. But first,
he'll have to come to grips with the fact that he has enough money
to make a difference in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It won't come easy. Somewhere amid the rubble of his room in
Suwanee is a color photocopy of his bonus check. The original was
sent via overnight delivery to Judd Rothman, a Long Island,
N.Y.-based financial planner who will help secure Brooking's
future. Two weeks after signing, Brooking still has a problem
comprehending his new tax bracket and what it means.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the government took something like $1.4 million out
of my bonus, and that's probably more money right there than I ever
thought I'd make in a lifetime,'' he said. ``I still shake my head
thinking about it. Then I still have (Wichard's) commission to pay
and some other management fees, so it all adds up. I'm realizing
that if you aren't careful, all those zeroes run out in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking, a management major at Tech, has instructed Rothman to
grow his nest-egg conservatively. ``I guess,'' he joked, ``I'm 'Mr.
Low-Risk.' `` He said he will be satisfied to live off just a
fraction of his annual base salaries, which start at $550,000 for
1998.
</P>
<P>
   That conservative bent is refreshing to Rothman, who manages
dozens of professional athletes, many of whom don't share
Brooking's restraint. A lot of Brooking's bonus money already is in
tax-exempt bonds. Much has been invested in low- to moderate-risk
stocks and bonds that won't yield as much in a strong market, but
won't suffer significantly if the economy suddenly spirals
downward.
</P>
<P>
   Rothman said he was retained by another young client about the
same time Brooking hired him. One of the first things the other
youngster did with a bonus was to purchase a $12,000 sound system
for his car. Brooking went for a few options on the Navigator, but
nothing extravagant.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he seems to know, unlike a lot of guys who miss the
obvious, is that his playing career won't last forever,'' Rothman
said. ``Because of the way Keith was raised and the discipline he
has, he doesn't need as much as some other guys. It's kind of like
this for him: He's not going to crave a lot of material things to
make him happy in life, because he is pretty happy with how his
life is already.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
