A6832 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-PROFIT-COX     07-15 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-PROFIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran taxis into profitability, looks forward to growth
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- AirTran Airlines completed a long climb back to
profitability in the second quarter, and the carrier's chief
executive said he expects a ``meaningful expansion'' of flights
from Atlanta later this year.
</P>
<P>
   D. Joseph Corr, who has led the revival of the former ValuJet
under a new name and marketing strategy, declined to say how many
flights or new destinations AirTran might add.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're busy in the planning of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran now has 120 daily departures to 28 cities from Atlanta,
which remains the focal point of its operations despite a
headquarters move to Orlando last winter. That followed the merger
of the old ValuJet and Orlando-based AirTran Airways, and the
formation of a new holding company, AirTran Holdings Inc. The
carrier has 24 daily flights from Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger, the airline rolled out a new marketing plan
that includes business-class sections, full travel agent booking
links and slicker advertising. Behind the scenes, it improved
computer systems controlling the number of seats offered at certain
fares.
</P>
<P>
   Corr said the moves produced ``dramatic improvement this past
year in load factor, yield and overall unit revenue, particularly
at our Atlanta hub.'' Favorable industry conditions of heavy travel
demand and low fuel prices have helped.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran Holdings said it had second quarter net income of $8.6
million, or 13 cents a share, compared with a loss of $9.2 million,
or 17 cents, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $124 million from
$47.8 million. For the six months, AirTran's income rose to
$686,000, or 1 cent a share, compared with a $27.7 million loss, or
51 cents. Prior-year results include only the old ValuJet.
</P>
<P>
   The profit ended eight consecutive losing quarters since the
carrier resumed flying in fall 1996. It was shut down by federal
regulators that summer, following the Flight 592 tragedy that was
later blamed on mistakes by a contractor and ValuJet's lax
oversight of the work. The company survived on cash reserves, which
stood at about $170 million at the time of the shutdown and now
total $66 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have taken an airline that was shut down and had
a very, very negative image and brought it back,'' said analyst
James D. Parker of Robinson-Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker remains ``a bit cautious'' because AirTran still is
filling fewer seats than other carriers. ``Revenue is a bit soft
relative to the industry,'' he said. Corr, who joined the airline
after the restart, predicted the second quarter profit, which
exceeded analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran stock rose 37 1/2 cents to $7.12 1/2 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
