<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurt shoulder leaves Lehman uncertain
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ It figures. After battling winds and
beating balls out of the heather for three days, American Tom
Lehman, 39, strained his right shoulder when falling on it while
``messing around with his kids'' Tuesday night and jeopardized his
status for today's first round of the British Open at Royal
Birkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Lehman's right arm was put in a sling after receiving treatment
from Dr. Michael Allen, chief medical officer of the Royal &AMP;
Ancient Golf Club. Although Lehman earlier in the day said the
shoulder was OK, indications Wednesday night were that he might not
be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how the shoulder feels today, Lehman has some extra
time to recover. He goes off at 2:45 p.m. (9:45 a.m. EDT) with Mark
James and Ernie Els.
</P>
<P>
   Watson interests tabloids
</P>
<P>
   Five-time champion Tom Watson's personal life has been
significantly more turbulent than his golf game in recent months,
having been in the midst of a divorce from his wife Linda. Watson
also has quit drinking, fueling speculation that it had reached a
problem stage. Asked about his ``battle with alcohol,'' Watson
said, ``I don't want to discuss that. It's a private thing with
me.'' ... Told he was listed at 50-1 in local odds and asked how
much he might bet on himself, Watson said, ``I would go out and put
20 pounds on it.'' ... Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, who shot an
opening 76 last year at Royal Troon and never seriously contended
at his home course, admits to feeling less pressure at Royal
Birkdale. ``I've put a lot of pressure on myself in the past,''
Montgomerie said. ``I've learned that I do play better when I'm
more relaxed.'' ... England's Lee Westwood, who probably would have
been Britain's favorite even without a win at Loch Lomond last
week: ``I'm not afraid of winning; I'm not afraid of losing. If I
don't win the Open this year, it won't be the end of the world to
me. I would dearly love it, but it's not life and death.''
</P>
<P>
   Love says backimproved
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III's problems this week have been more with
fractured travel plans than with his tender lower back. Love got to
the Jacksonville airport Monday for a flight to Manchester only to
discover he had forgotten a travel wallet that contained his ticket
and passport. ``I was already packed,'' Love said, ``and then Drew
(his son) wanted to throw and hit some baseballs. I just got
distracted and forgot it.'' Love arrived Tuesday and received
treatment on his back from Columbus physical therapist Tom Boers.
It felt strong enough Wednesday for Love to hit range balls after
his round. ``I feel like I'm ready to go,'' said Love, who tied for
33rd at the Masters and missed the cut at the U.S. Open. ``Now I
think I can really get after it. He (Boers) just had to get all
that inflammation and pain out of it first.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly, wife back together
</P>
<P>
   John Daly, always a favorite with the British tabloids _ and why
not with three marriages, a weight problem, alcoholism and a Claret
Jug on his resume? _ said Wednesday he has been back with his wife
Paulette for the past two months. She had filed for divorce after a
March 1997 incident at The Players Championship, when Daly went on
a drunken rampage in Jacksonville Beach, Fla. Daly said he has lost
about 20 pounds, dropping from 247 to about 225, but still looks
quite heavy. ``Actually, my right arm hugs this fat belly here,''
Daly said of his backswing. ``When I lose weight, it flies all over
the place.'' ... All vehicles were searched in parking lots
Wednesday by Merseyside police as a precaution against a possible
incident. The Grand National horse race at nearby Aintree last year
was postponed because of a bomb threat phoned in by the IRA,
prompting Merseyside police to be ``better safe than sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
