<SLUG> BC-WACHOVIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wachovia follows leaders with double-digit earnings
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Like the other major banks doing business in Atlanta,
Wachovia reported a double-digit earnings gain, posting a 17
percent rise in second-quarter operating income.
</P>
<P>
   From operations, which exclude non-recurring charges, the
Winston-Salem-based banking company earned $230.3 million vs.
$196.8 million a year ago, and $1.09 per share, a penny ahead of
the First Call consensus estimate, against 98 cents last year, on
more shares.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia wrote off acquisition costs of $30.8 million, which
reduced second-quarter net income to $209.9 million, or $1 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Wachovia, with total assets of $64.7 billion, earned 1.44
percent, up from 1.38, percent on all its money-making assets, and
had a 17.7 percent return on equity, or the shareholders' stake,
down slightly from 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Along with its peers, Wachovia got a big lift from
non-traditional banking revenue, such as financial services fees,
which rose 15.6 percent to $486.1 million. The higher personnel
costs associated with these business lines helped boost
non-interest expenses 23 percent to $517 million. Overall, however,
Wachovia only spent about 53.5 cents for each dollar of revenue it
captured, unchanged from a year ago and an indication it managed
overhead efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many peers, Wachovia posted a two-digit increase in loan
revenue, banking's traditional bread and butter business. Net
interest income rose 14.5 percent to $514.3 million. Also bucking
the trend, Wachovia improved the spread between what it pays for
money and earns from money, to 4.21 percent, up from 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for these gains is Wachovia does a lot of profitable
credit card lending, but the downside is a relatively high
percentage of slow-pay and no-pay customers. Charge-offs increased
8.2 percent to $68.2 million. Excluding credit card losses in the
quarter, Wachovia's write-offs would have declined 43.3 percent to
$5.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Non-performing loans rose 30.2 percent, to $127.4 million
because of acquisitions, and Wachovia increased its provision for
loan losses 8.6 percent to $68.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   For the six months, Wachovia's operating income was $448.4
million, or $2.13 per share, versus $390.3 million, or $1.94 per
share. Net income was $405.2 million, or $1.93 per share, in the
latest quarter.
</P>
<P>
   On a day many bank stocks were down, Wachovia closed at $86.18
3/4 down 56 1/4 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
