<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELLOW JERSEY ELUDES HINCAPIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The yellow jersey in the Tour de France once again eluded
American rider George Hincapie, who started the day just two
seconds back and is now separated from the race's overall leader by
11 seconds. Still, his third-place position keeps the team
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain hopeful,'' said team spokeswoman Margot Myers from
France Wednesday night. Besides, she said, look at Erik Zabel, the
leader three days ago who is now a minute back. In other words, in
the race where every second counts, leaders can fall _ or be
created _ in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's 157-mile stage, the longest of the three-week Tour,
started in Plouay in the Brittany region and made its way southeast
over flat roads to the finish in Cholet.
</P>
<P>
   Jeroen Blijlevens of the Netherlands raced to the sprint finish
in 5 hours 45 minutes, while Australian Stuart O'Grady took over
the yellow jersey. He became the fourth different rider to lead the
overall standings in the five days of racing, and only the second
Australian _ besides Phil Anderson _ to wear the jersey.
</P>
<P>
   And even though O'Grady finished eight seconds behind in the
main pack, he won two of the three sprints and came in third in
another to gain an extra 14 seconds that moved him to the top of
the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   Hincapie took third in the first sprint of the day, but later
crashed when the pack piled up around a tight corner just two miles
from the finish. Still, he and most of his US Postal Service
teammates finished with most of the pack that was eight seconds
behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
   O'Grady's lead was especially satisfying for his GAN team after
Chris Boardman, who won the prologue and held the yellow jersey for
a day, crashed Monday and is out of the race. He is recovering from
a concussion and cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   The mostly flat course seemed tailor-made for O'Grady, a sprint
specialist who has won cycling medals on the Olympic track events
and was a world team champion with Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's 142-mile stage that moves farther east is again flat.
And like Wednesday, the race has three bonus sprints that Hincapie
can hope to capitalize on to move up in the overall standings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the racing at the Tour, the drug controversy
involving the Festina team continued. The team's main sponsor, the
Festina watch company, is threatening to leave the team if there is
evidence of drug use among the riders.
</P>
<P>
   Last week a Belgian member of Festina's team was arrested after
police found a large quantity of performance-enhancing drugs in the
Festina car he was driving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
