<SLUG> BC-MCI-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH FIRM AGREES TO BUY MCI'S INTERNET BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless PLC of Britain said Wednesday, as expected,
that it had agreed to acquire MCI Communications Corp.'s Internet
business for $1.75 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was also accompanied by the Justice Department's
approval for MCI's pending $37 billion acquisition by Worldcom Inc.
The Federal Communications Commission is the only major regulatory
body that has yet to rule on the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department had been worried that a combined MCI and
Worldcom could dominate the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The main beneficiary of those concerns has been Cable and
Wireless, which under its first American chief executive, Richard
Brown, has been trying to expand into the U.S. market and into
cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   By buying MCI's Internet operation, Cable and Wireless, which
has far-flung telecommunications interests in Asia and the
Caribbean, would immediately become a significant player in the
American Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a transforming deal for Cable and Wireless,'' Brown said
in an interview. ``We pick up over 3,000 major U.S. corporate
accounts where we have the Internet contracts, and being as global
as we are we can build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said MCI and Worldcom had agreed to refrain from trying to
win back those customers for 18 months. Brown said he expected the
Internet unit to generate revenue of about $650 million in the
fiscal year beginning next April.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said the sale was the largest corporate
divestiture in merger history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger as originally proposed would have given
Worldcom/MCI a significant proportion of the nation's Internet
traffic, giving the company the ability to cut off or reduce the
quality of Internet services that it provided to its rivals,'' Joel
Klein, the assistant attorney general who runs the department's
antitrust division, said in a statement. ``This divestiture
benefits anyone who relies on the Internet because it preserves
competition among major Internet service providers.''
</P>
<P>
   In May MCI agreed to sell its wholesale Internet unit to Cable
and Wireless for $625 million. That operation provides high-speed
cyberspace links to smaller Internet providers. But regulators in
the United States and Europe insisted that MCI also sell off its
units that provide cyberspace services directly to business and
residential customers.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.75 billion price includes the previous $625 million.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union signed off on Worldcom's acquisition of MCI
earlier this month. Few telecommunications experts expect the FCC's
review to hold up the deal for long.
</P>
</TEXT>
