called the nation's first women's rights convention at the Wesleyan
Chapel. On the 150th anniversary of that meeting, First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton opens a four-day celebration of women's
rights and achievements. By Mary Leonard. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ-EARNS (Undated) -- Still struggling to meld Digitial's
disparate services into its computer business, Compaq reports that
it eked out a second-quarter profit, just beating expectations that
it would only break even on the reporting period. By Joanne Muller.
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL-EARNINGS (Undated) -- Financial services companies
report strong growth in the second quarter. Banks and asset
management companies are reaping gains by offering
investment-related products. By Lynnley Browning. 650 words.
</P>
<P>
   POLAROID-NBS (Undated) -- In a bid to boost its identification
card business, Polaroid buys rival cardmaker NBS Imaging Systems
for $12.9 million. By Chana Schoenberger. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-WHITESOX-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RYAN-COLUMN (Boston) _ They held a luncheon at Fenway to
trumpet the 1999 baseball All-Star Game and the ratio of
non-baseball people to baseball people in attendance was about
10-1. In other words, just about the modern norm. By Bob Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COMMENT (Undated) _ By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-DC-REVOLUTION (Foxborough, Mass.) -- By Jim Greenidge.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ALBERT (New York) -- Madison Square Garden hires Marv Albert.
By Howard Manly.
</P>
<P>
   CYC-TOUR (Undated) -- The yellow jersey in the Tour de France
once again eluded American rider George Hincapie. By Susan
Bickelhaupt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
