<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6847 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATM-FEES-HNS &LR;      07-15 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-FEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE OFFICIAL SAYS BANNING ATM FEES HELPS CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Stands for D'AMATO-BANKS on budget.)  
 (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Connecticut's attorney general told Congress
Wednesday that his state's experience banning automated teller
machine fees shows that banks wouldn't be hurt by a federal ban on
such charges.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal told the Senate banking committee that banks
are doing a flourishing ATM business in Connecticut, despite the
fact that the state bans all ATM transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``ATMs in Connecticut are as common as in other states,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal testified in favor of pending federal legislation
that would prohibit extra transaction fees incurred when a consumer
uses another bank's ATM machine.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, a customer using an ATM at a bank where the customer
doesn't normally do business incurs two transaction fees, one from
his or her regular bank and one from the bank whose ATM is being
used.
</P>
<P>
   Not all banks levy the extra charge. According to a 1998 survey
by the General Accounting Office _ the investigative branch of
Congress _ 64 percent of banks with ATMs charge transaction fees on
at least some of their ATMs, up from 39 percent in 1997. In
addition, the number of ATMs with fees increased from 59 percent in
1997 to 79 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the ATM fees also increased, rising from an average
of $.69 in December 1997 to $1 in February 1998, according to the
GAO report.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers would benefit from the federal ban, Blumenthal said,
because they would not have to search for ATM machines that do not
charge transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said the fees are unnecessary because the ATMs save
banks money by reducing the payroll for tellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fees are nothing more than an additional bite at the
consumer's financial apple,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., a sponsor of the legislation, said
additional ATM fees ``continue to spread like a plague across the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that the only choice the consumer has is to pay
up or go home,'' D'Amato said, adding that he will bring the bill
to the Senate floor later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience of ATMs has made them extremely popular. The
number of ATMs rose from fewer than 100,000 in 1993 to over 165,000
in 1998, according to the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Foes of the bill say the fees are necessary to finance ATM
access around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   John Ward, representing the Consumers Banking Association, an
organization with approximately 750 members from financial
institutions, testified that the additional fees help pay for ATMs
in locations outside of banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicago's Wrigley Field had just a single ATM before the 1997
advent of (transaction fees) in Illinois,'' he said.``There are now
at least five at the park. This sort of relentless competition
clearly benefits consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted consumers have other methods of avoiding the
additional charges, including cashing checks and using ATM machines
that do not have transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   Government interference would ``only distort the marketplace and
hurt both banks and their customers,'' Ward added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TUNJAV-NEIGHBORHOO     07-15 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TUNJAV-NEIGHBORHOOD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME ON THE WILD WEST SIDE: CALL IT TUNJAV
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Meat trucks growl, shifting their gears as they
lumber down the avenues around the Lincoln Tunnel. Empty taxis dash
across West 36th Street in a race to the corner gaseteria. Carriage
horses plod the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Toward 10th Avenue, brick tenements overlook the tunnel ramps,
their fire escapes silhouetted against huge warehouses. The
late-afternoon sun bathes a dozen parking lots, and rush-hour packs
thousands of cars into the crawling jam that nudges commuters back
and forth from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As commuters edge into the tunnel, few are likely to ponder the
fate of the buildings around them. But some 6,000 people live in
this 16-block area hemmed in by the Lincoln Tunnel, the Jacob
Javits Convention Center and two of Manhattan's most famous
thoroughfares, 34th Street and 42d Street. And the population is
growing, slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In this gritty pocket, a sense of comradeship and
interconnection is emerging. There is also an awareness sprouting
like a seed through rocky ground that something is happening. The
city is abuzz with often-warring proposals for megadevelopments,
although plans to expand the Javits Center to 42d Street seem less
likely now that the owner of a key site said on Monday that he
would start to build 1,800 units of housing in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Developers have greedily eyed the tenements and parking lots;
one has four proposals on his desk. Two weeks ago, a bright orange
lozenge of a sign went up for new loft rentals on 34th Street
between 10th and 11th avenues _ a first. While the high-tech lofts
(with marble baths) will rent for $4,000 to $6,000 a month, that's
still 33 percent below comparable places in Chelsea and TriBeCa.
There's new pressure to change the zoning to allow river-view
apartment towers and loft conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Among residents, a play is unfolding: 6,000 Neighbors in Search
of a Neighborhood. There's a new community garden and a new
playground on West 39th Street, and rooftops with sunflowers
growing in wooden kegs. New-style residents, like Jene and Kitty
Highstein, a sculptor and a nurse, have rented here in the last
year. Chelsea, to the south, was their first choice; but this
place, they say, is more authentic, more peaceful _ and cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The new people brag about buying quail and skate and
fresh-ground paprika in the shops along Ninth Avenue; about finding
the perfect late-night car service; about making friends. They
fancy they've discovered the place; but some famous names in
architecture _ Richard Meier, Lella and Massimo Vignelli, Charles
Gwathmey and Robert A.M. Stern _ carved out offices here years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vignelli calls her part of town the Wild West. Others call
it Clinton South. Or Hell's Kitchen. One enterprising realtor dubs
it Chelsea Heights. Call it TunJav: between the Lincoln Tunnel and
the Javits Center.
</P>
<P>
   Leni Schwendinger, a lighting designer who lives on West 35th
Street, helped found the Hell's Kitchen Neighborhood Association,
which estimates the area's population at less than 6,000. In the
bleaker blocks toward the Javits Center, Ms. Schwendinger said,
``There's been a change in both spirit and energy within the last
seven years.'' She points to volunteer cleanups, community gardens
and 50 sidewalk trees planted by her group. ``We're becoming more
connected,'' she said. ``We're becoming a small village.''
</P>
<P>
   Until March, Antonio DaMotta, a Brazilian-born furniture and
interior designer, lived in the heart of chic: Manhattan's flatiron
district, at 22d Street and Broadway. ``It was wonderful for the
first five years,'' he said. ``Then it became so overrated, so
overcrowded.'' When his lease was up, he and Robert Ketterman, a
public relations consultant, decided to team up.
</P>
<P>
   The designer wanted a two-bedroom apartment with light and
outdoor space _ and a rent under $2,000. ``Well, that's kind of
tough,'' his real estate agent conceded, ``but because you're a
designer, there is one place that isn't even on the market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it was a wreck,'' DaMotta said, as he surveyed his
now-elegant decor from a splendid oversize tomato-red damask couch
that he designed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took one look at it and said `No way!' '' Ketterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Their apartment is at 525 West 36th Street, a late-19th-century
brick row house that has been gut-renovated and painted blue-green.
An ornate wrought-iron door has been added by the landlord, a
filmmaker who lives there and runs his business from next door. The
building is a name tag's throw from the vast black-glass convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't kid you,'' Ketterman said. ``It's a shlep when you
need a quart of milk sometimes. But in the morning, I just yell out
the window to Hanna's across the street, and if she has some,
she'll send a delivery boy across the street with it.''
</P>
<P>
   DaMotta added: ``I'm glad it's weird. It's like leaving town _
it feels like you're someplace else. But with Chelsea encroaching
up and Disney encroaching down, this is the only place for anything
to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm foreseeing this great development,'' he speculated. ``And
I'll grow sick of it all and have to move out.''
</P>
<P>
   He is on the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that parking lot,'' said Robert Skolnick, the development
director for a large Queens-based real estate organization, as he
cruised by the corner of 38th Street and 10th Street in his black
Mercedes. ``Parking and signage, parking and signage,'' he recited
like a mantra, referring to the big billboards over the lots.
``Underutilized,'' he explained. ``This area is ripe for housing.
Imagine the river views. Condos, rentals, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Skolnick said that at least a half-dozen developers were
interested. ``I keep running into the same seven or eight
characters,'' he said, smiling. He has four proposals for housing
developments, he said. ``Three new construction and one rehab.''
</P>
<P>
   The community board has filed recommendations with the City
Planning Commission to change the zoning from predominantly
manufacturing to mixed use, including midrise residential.
Otherwise, developers of new housing are limited to 42d Street and
most of 34th Street, Ninth Avenue and a part of 11th Avenue that
includes the Imperatore land.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Joseph Rose, director of the commission, said the
area ``has the potential for a new wave of development.''
</P>
<P>
   But residential zoning changes will take a back seat to
decisions about a new Pennsylvania Station, Javits Center
expansion, Yankee Stadium and job creation. ``It's an important
growth corridor,'' he said. ``It's something we're looking at
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
