<HEADER>
A6853 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TUNJAV-NEIGHBORHOO     07-15 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TUNJAV-NEIGHBORHOOD-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: at carefully.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While City Hall considers, apartment prices are soaring. Vera
Lightstone, president of the co-op board at a loft building on West
37th Street, says prices have tripled since she bought in the
mid-1980s. And Michael Goldenberg, sales director of the Halstead
Property Company's Greenwich Village office, said owners are asking
for the moon. The price of an 1,850-square-foot loft in Ms.
Lightstone's building is $625,000; a five-story walk-up with 20
rent-stabilized apartments on West 36th Street is $675,000. A
vacant two-story commercial building on West 36th Street is $3.1
million. Five years ago, he said, prices might have been less than
half.
</P>
<P>
   But TunJav will never be TriBeCa, with its unbroken rows of
magnificent late-19th-century cast-iron commercial buildings. There
are too many parking lots and nondescript tenements. Like TriBeCa,
however, the district still feels very bleak _ although it doesn't
feel dangerous, even on a Tuesday at midnight in July. The
community board said crime has decreased substantially in TunJav,
with drug-dealing down about 85 percent in the last two years. Ms.
Lightstone, who retreated to the Upper West Side for a year, moved
back. ``The crack was so bad,'' she said. ``Now it's safer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lella and Massimo Vignelli, the internationally known designers,
work on the top floor of a 1906 warehouse building on 10th Avenue.
``The situation has improved quite a lot,'' said Ms. Vignelli, as
she moved across her charcoal grey carpet to look down on what is
now a fairly well-groomed lot. ``When we first came, the lot was
overgrown, and the streetwalkers used it to turn their tricks.
There was an old sofa, and sometimes they would look up and see us
all staring down _ and the woman would shake her fist at us!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And now we really do have a Wild West,'' she said with a
laugh. ``Did you see that log cabin and the saloon across the
street?'' They're part of the new wave: a bar called The Gold Rush,
complete with cacti, and a log cabin, Christinae's Country Kitchen,
complete with water wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Massimo Vignelli is convinced that ``the entire Hudson River
over the next 50 years will become like Rio de Janeiro, apartment
houses all the way down to the Battery, sensational.'' Along with
almost everyone interviewed, he hopes that Yankee Stadium isn't
built in the area, once the favorite plan of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. ``See that parking lot?'' he said, peering out the
window. ``At four o'clock, the roads will look just like that
parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, people are moving in. Isabelle Bosquet, 32, looks out
at the ramp of the Lincoln Holland Tunnel from her rented studio
apartment. Unlike DaMotta and many of the loft dwellers, she lives
in a white brick, postwar building on West 34th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bosquet, who is French, is a flower arranger whose business,
she says, is just starting to take off. She wanted to live in
Chelsea, to be near the Flower District, but she didn't want to pay
the high prices. Here, her L-shaped studio isn't dirt-cheap but it
is affordable: $1,075.
</P>
<P>
   Jene and Kitty Highstein moved into the building next door to
DaMotta. Highstein, a sculptor, tracked down the rental himself.
``I spent several days a week just walking up from 14th Street.''
he said, ``following construction workers into buildings, asking
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   When he first saw his two-bedroom apartment, he said, it was
rubble. Although Highstein had lived in TriBeCa for 25 years, he
and his family had moved to the country. ``Then I decided the
schools in New York City were better for my sons, 8 and 12,'' he
said. The boys were accepted into magnet schools. Highstein, a
rugged-looking man who wields a mean-looking sculptor's hammer,
praised his surroundings. ``It's a cul-de-sac with no through
traffic, so everybody knows you on the street. There's a dry
cleaner right on 34th Street, and there's a great health club on
43rd Street.''
</P>
<P>
   After snagging the apartment, Highstein found a cavernous studio
only two buildings away for $1,600 _ the only artist in a classic
industrial loft owned by an auto-parts dealer.
</P>
<P>
   His windows overlook his family's apartment, including their
brand-new picket-fenced deck with a blue and white tablecloth on
the table. ``This is a neighborhood,'' he said. ``This is basic New
York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
