<HEADER>
A6855 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAT-THEHEAT-TEX     07-15 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAT-THEHEAT-TEX </SLUG>
 
A survival guide for a record-breaking summer 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT HEAT DOES TO YOUR BODY
</P>
<P>
   When July temperatures soars above 100, the heat index is
usually 5 to 10 degrees above that. But it gets worse: The heat
index, which factors in the relative humidity to tell us what it
really feels like out there, is measured in the shade. Walk through
an unshaded area _ especially a sidewalk or parking lot _ and you
can add 15 to 20 degrees to that heat index.
</P>
<P>
   After the heat index hits 105, the body loses its ability to
cool itself properly. And when the temperature outside is higher
than body temperature, it's more difficult for the body to release
heat. In fact, the body starts absorbing heat.
</P>
<P>
   High temperatures can cause two health conditions: heat
exhaustion and heatstroke. Both are serious, but heatstroke is
life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Sufferers of heat exhaustion feel hot, but their body
temperature isn't any higher than normal; they are sweaty and tired
and may complain of dizziness or nausea.
</P>
<P>
   To treat heat exhaustion, take the victim out of the heat and
provide plenty of cool fluids. Cold water or a cold wet towel will
help cool the body.
</P>
<P>
   With heatstroke, body temperature is higher than normal.
Sufferers are not alert and may not be aware of what is happening
around them, or they may faint. Other signs are hot, dry skin _ you
stop sweating _ and paleness. Heatstroke victims should be given
fluids, cooled down and taken immediately to an emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO DRINK
</P>
<P>
   Lots of water. You need 32 ounces an hour in weather like this,
no matter what you're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Sports drinks are also beneficial because they replace
electrolytes and other materials that keep the body in balance.
</P>
<P>
   Soft drinks and tea don't help; the caffeine acts as a diuretic,
which gets rid of fluids, and the carbonation in soft drinks does
nothing to replace the body's fluids.
</P>
<P>
   Don't drink alcohol. Alcoholic beverages also take away fluids,
and the heat speeds up its effect on the body.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO WEAR
</P>
<P>
   Lightweight, light-colored and loose clothing. Light colors
reflect the sun's rays, and loose clothing keeps air circulating
around you.
</P>
<P>
   A hat. It's the same concept as wearing a hat in winter to keep
warm: You lose heat through your head, and you absorb heat through
your head as well.
</P>
<P>
   Sunscreen _ at least SPF 15. Any part of your skin that's not
covered up should be protected by sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO FEEL COOLER
</P>
<P>
   If you have a kiddie pool, break it out. Fill it with water and
soak your feet, sit in it, dunk your head. Throw in some ice blocks
and play ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardware stores sell misters for less than $20 that transform a
stream of water from a garden hose into a cool, wispy mist.
</P>
<P>
   The low-tech approach also works. A wet towel or cloth on the
back of your neck will bring your body temperature down.
</P>
<P>
   Zoos keep polar bears cool by freezing fish in blocks of ice.
You may not want to eat uncooked frozen dinners, but frozen treats
like an Astro Pop or a fudge bar will keep you cool. Ice cream
melts too fast.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS AND HEAT
</P>
<P>
   Parents watching their kids play outside should remember that
the children are more active and will begin to suffer from the heat
sooner than adults.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to how kids are acting. If they're acting abnormal
or confused, check it out: If they have a fever, especially if
they're not sweating, they should receive emergency care for
heatstroke.
</P>
<P>
   Never lock a child in a car for any amount of time. Within
minutes, the temperature inside a car can reach the outside
temperature and beyond, as high as 120 to 150 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING PETS COOL
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor dogs, especially those with dark coats, need a good
breeze. If possible, place a fan to blow on your dog's resting
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs need plenty of water and shade. A plastic kiddie pool
filled with clean water every day is perfect for dogs to lie in, as
long as they don't chew the pool to shreds instead.
</P>
<P>
   Run the sprinkler for a while to cool off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Or give outdoor dogs a thorough soaking with the hose in the
morning. They might not like it at first, but they'll be a lot
cooler through the day. Experts say never to put ice-cold water on
a dog.
</P>
<P>
   Outside cats are usually OK with high temperatures, as long as
they can find a shady spot to hide in and have access to clean
water.
</P>
<P>
   Never leave a pet in the car or a hot house. Trapped in a car,
even with windows cracked, a dog or cat will bake very quickly.
Inside the house, they need just a little bit of air conditioning
to be comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Shaving a dog in summer can do more harm than good. One vet said
that doing that to a long-haired dog is comparable to taking all
the insulation out of your home's attic. It increases the risk of
heatstroke. Remember, dogs don't sweat; they pant for self-cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Birds shouldn't be moved repeatedly between inside and outside.
When inside, they should be kept out of direct sun and away from
direct vents. Be sure to give birds lots of fresh water and food
daily.
</P>
<P>
   BEYOND AC
</P>
<P>
   Some tips to cool your house, besides running the AC for 24
hours a day:
</P>
<P>
   In ancient India, people hung damp floor mats in the doorway
that received the most wind.
</P>
<P>
   Other ancients sprayed water on the walls of their huts.
</P>
<P>
   Plant trees. Many older homes, built before air conditioning,
used natural shade. It can feel 10 degrees cooler in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   Quick-growing vines and flowers, such as morning glory or
hollyhocks, will provide a cooling effect around windows and doors.
</P>
<P>
   Insulated window shades and awnings can keep the heat out. Even
a bedsheet hung over a window will help.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget to daydream about snow. Studies show that the
body reacts to daydreams. So cool your thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   CAREFUL, HOT CAR!
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the best way to cope with no air conditioning in your
car is to have your friends drive. But here are some survival tips
for when you have to go your own way:
</P>
<P>
   When getting into a hot car, lay something over the vinyl seats.
A large T-shirt can fit nicely over the back of a bucket seat.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a beaded seat cover, take it out. It'll make your
bare skin itch.
</P>
<P>
   If you choose to drive naked (legal unless you're lewd about it
or offend someone), bring something to cover yourself in case you
must use a drive-through window, or a thin-skinned trucker passes
you.
</P>
<P>
   Drive with an icy drink in hand. At least your hand will be
cool. (But be careful with the slushes. Gulping can cause brain
freeze, which can make ordinary driving difficult.)
</P>
<P>
   When you park, use a sun shield in the windshield. The blockers
can be awkward, but they'll keep your car a little cooler.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Rob McDonald, Robert Philpot, June Naylor
Rodriguez and Alyson Ward
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
