<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-BOXWOODS-NYT &LR;      07-15 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-BOXWOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMING BOXWOODS IN CHANGING COTILLION OF GREEN
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLDWICK, N.J. _ Say ``boxwood,'' and what comes to mind are
Colonial Williamsburg's precise edgings, green billows at English
country houses _ in short, an air of tradition and control. Boxwood
has tempted the gardener's shears since Egyptians first clipped
formal hedges around 4000 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   The plant's origins are wilder than its conventional image
suggests. Buxus sempervirens, the best known species, originated in
the forests of southern Europe and the Caucasus and can still be
seen, airy and glittering, in the woods of the Luberon, in France.
Garden hybrids like Suffruticosa, called dwarf edging box, are
denser and more compact.
</P>
<P>
   Easygoing boxwood can live for three centuries. It needs a half
day of sun and prefers no cultivation because it has delicate
surface roots. But for many gardeners the plant's overriding
attraction is that deer don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   For Claire and George Weiss, the need for a cash crop inspired a
three-quarter-acre field in Oldwick planted with slow-growing
boxwood that endorses change and succession, a sharply contemporary
notion. Come back in five years, and the severe, serene patterns of
boxwood will have changed, as plants are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Weisses' landscape architect, Margie Ruddick, whose company
is in Philadelphia, was responsible for dragging boxwood into the
1990s. Her early '80s Harvard landscape training led her to be
suspicious of what she calls ``heroic projects, closed systems and
single viewpoints.''
</P>
<P>
   In its pristine practicality and quotidian layout, the Weisses'
10-acre property in Hunterdon County was a joint project by Ruddick
and Steven Harris, an architect who worked the new luxurious
compound around a spare farmhouse that dated back to 1797.
</P>
<P>
   Selling boxwoods allows the Weisses to benefit from New Jersey's
Farm Assessment Program, which entitles landholders who sell plants
and produce to a sizable tax break. In a former pasture, 850 small
boxwoods are laid out in two patterns, which intersect and merge
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The first pattern, a grid, evokes farm fields and echoes the
agricultural forms Harris used for the 3,500-square-foot house and
outbuildings. The second pattern, a diagonal, forms two
forced-perspective allees that widen from four feet near the house
to eight feet at their terminus, reversing the usual effect of the
optical trick by telescoping distance instead of lengthening it.
</P>
<P>
   Allees are part of ``power gardening,'' a style that dates to
Louis XIV, when far horizons seen from a central point symbolized
royal power. But here these long axes are used as a playful, ironic
commentary. They don't emanate from a central point, turning
perspective on its head, and they refuse to lead anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said she feels as if the boxwoods ``are moving with me''
when she walks through the boxwoods. Sometimes both patterns seem
to disappear, like moire fabric. ``It's like a dancer,'' Ruddick
explained. ``You are involved in one pattern, and when you
encounter another pattern, that encounter changes the first one.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss looks at the farm every morning from the window at her
upstairs dressing table. ``It's like an aerial shot of a ballroom
scene,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rows are spaced at least four feet apart so the mower can get
between them. (Even a dream farm's design must bow to the
everyday.)
</P>
<P>
   Ruddick recommended crosses of Korean littleleaf boxwood, Buxus
microphylla var. koreana, with Buxus sempervirens, choosing the
hardiest cultivars and the ones most in demand: Green Gem, a
two-foot mound; Green Mountain, a pyramidal oval five feet tall,
and Green Velvet, a slightly larger version of Green Gem. (A good
cultivar guide is the ``Boxwood Handbook: A Practical Guide to
Knowing and Growing Boxwood''; $15 from the American Boxwood
Society, P.O. Box 85, Boyce, Va. 22620.)
</P>
<P>
   Three bigger Suffruticosas stand on a stone terrace at the heart
of the farm as permanent witnesses to what will be a ceaselessly
changing harvest of their fellows. It's this bracing brush between
agriculture and ornamental gardening that makes the boxwood farm a
work of art. Farm pattern is based on change _ crops are reaped and
replanted. Ornamental gardens have always represented a struggle
for permanence in the face of aging, their most touching aspect.
</P>
<P>
   The Weiss farm, which is also a garden, celebrates the
subversive but lovely truth that every garden is what Ruddick calls
``a series of gardens over time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
