<SLUG> BC-FORD-EARNINGS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD'S PROFIT UP 6.7 PERCENT IN 2ND QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. said Wednesday that its operating profit rose 6.7
percent in the second quarter, easily surpassing Wall Street
estimates despite a decline in car and truck sales.
</P>
<P>
   The robust report, however, also included some cautionary notes,
including Ford's projection that domestic auto sales were not
likely to continue at the blistering pace of the second quarter and
confirmation that sales in Latin America and Asia were weak. In
addition, the company's market share fell in both Europe and North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford's market share is something to watch,'' said David
Bradley, who follows the auto industry for J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that its decline in market share _ to 24 percent from
25.6 percent in North America and to 10.4 percent from 11.7 percent
in Europe _ reflected a deliberate reduction in low-margin fleet
sales and the elimination of foundering products like the Aspire,
Probe and Aerostar so that it could concentrate on its more
profitable products, like light trucks. Devine noted that the
company's North American share had climbed back to 25.5 percent in
June and that July had started well.
</P>
<P>
   Ford sold 1,786,000 cars and trucks in the quarter, down nearly
5 percent from sales in the quarter a year earlier, and revenues
from those sales fell 4.6 percent, to $31.31 billion. But pretax
income from the automotive business jumped 16.5 percent, to $3.01
billion.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Ford earned $2.38 billion, or $1.91 a diluted
share, compared with $2.23 billion, or $1.82 a share, in the
quarter a year earlier before one-time items and earnings from
Associates First Capital, a finance company spun off to
shareholders earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   With those items, which included a $269 million profit on the
sale of 19.1 percent of Hertz Corp. to the public, and a $169
million charge to streamline manufacturing and sell its heavy-truck
business, Ford earned $2.53 billion, or $2.06 a diluted share, in
the quarter a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent results topped Wall Street forecasts of earnings
of $1.81 a share, according to a survey of analysts by First Call
Corp., which tracks company results.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ford fell $1 Wednesday, or 1.7 percent, to $59.50. For
the year, Ford's shares are up 84.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Total revenue for the company, including Ford Credit Corp. and
Ford's share of Hertz's results, fell 7.4 percent, to $37.29
billion, from $40.27 billion in the quarter a year earlier, because
of lower automotive sales and the spinoff of Associates First
Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the biggest surprise was the strong improvement in
Europe, where automotive earnings jumped to $310 million from $153
million in the quarter a year earlier. The company, which has lost
money in Europe for much of the last decade, appears to be on track
to finish in the black there.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force in the strong quarter was the North American
market, where automotive earnings hit a record $1.7 billion for the
quarter. The popularity of the new F-series Super Duty truck, the
phasing-out of poor performers and a reduction in sales to rental
car fleets helped lift the average profit margin on vehicles in
North America to 7.3 percent from 6.2 percent in the period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of a more profitable mix of products were
reinforced by cost-cutting measures in manufacturing and purchasing
that saved $900 million compared with spending rates in the second
quarter of 1997. Total cost reductions in the first half reached
$1.3 billion, well ahead of the $1 billion goal Ford had set for
the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a company making tremendous strides in gaining control
of its costs,'' said Maryann Keller, an analyst with Furman Selz.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Devine, the company's chief financial officer, said that
Ford would announce a plan later this year to reduce its salaried
work force through a buyout program to encourage voluntary
retirements. That program will result in a charge against earnings
toward the end of the year once details are worked out, Devine said
in a conference call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   One of Wall Street's chief questions is what Ford plans to do
with its cash reserves, which grew to more than $14 billion in the
second quarter from $9.87 billion in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to be very careful in how we spend the cash,''
said Devine, deflecting questions about increasing Ford's
investment in its Japanese affiliate, Mazda; buying all or part of
the financially troubled Kia Motors of South Korea, and other
possible investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
