<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's inaction on offer from Turner upsets Pitts
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Atlanta City Council President Robb Pitts says he is
``embarrassed'' for the city and hopes to revive the Turner
Foundation's offer to finance a $1.5 million conservation program
that could save taxpayers at least $3 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts is the only Atlanta official to call the Turner Foundation
in the wake of the revelations the city ignored the organization's
repeated efforts to finalize plans for the energy program. ``I
haven't heard from anyone in the administration,'' said Peter
Bahouth, executive director of the Turner Foundation. ``We have
gotten calls from everyone but the city,'' said Bahouth, who added
it would be difficult to resurrect the initiative at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Since a story appeared in the newspaper last week, dozens of
people have called the Turner Foundation to express their concern
about the city's rejection of the proposal. The foundation even got
a call from an official at Fulton County expressing interest in
having the program implemented there.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell initially embraced the program, even
highlighting it in his state-of-the-city address in January 1997.
But the proposal fell through the cracks at City Hall as key people
left the administration, others changed positions and the mayor
focused attention on his re-election. A Turner official called the
city's chief administrative officer 47 times over several months
last fall without getting a call back.
</P>
<P>
   The Turner Foundation, frustrated by the lack of response from
the city, withdrew its offer in January, only to receive a
rejection letter in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened never should have happened,'' said Pitts, who
may sense political opportunity in the embarrassing episode for the
Campbell administration. Pitts has called executives of the Turner
Foundation to apologize for the city's lack of responsiveness to
their offer. ``It is a loss for us, and it is an embarrassment,''
Pitts said.
</P>
<P>
   Pitts asked the foundation ``whether there still was any
opportunity'' to proceed with the original contract. The foundation
is sending him a copy of the drafted contract for his review. Pitts
said he believes the City Council could pass legislation to act on
the Turner offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to see if we can work something else out,'' Pitts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know if we could revive it at this point,'' said
Bahouth. ``There were several other groups involved. We were all
stepping off the curb at once, and we were left standing in the
road. People have moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Turner Foundation would need assurance from Campbell
and his administration they are committed to working with the
energy conservation program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would need to have a commitment,'' Bahouth said. ``There's
nothing that says to me that things have changed and the city is
going to want to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Bahouth said the foundation remains open to
discussing ideas with the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to use the Turner resources to make the
community a better place and to improve the quality of life in any
way we can,'' Bahouth said. ``We always stand ready to look for
ways to help make the city a better place to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
