<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Think small' among latest investor themes
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The mid-year review of investment strategy continues
in the business press.
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor (August) explains most stocks never attract
the attention of financial analysts. They may be too small to show
up on Wall Street's radar screens, but such ``stealth stocks''
could have growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier for a $50 million company to double (in size) than
a $1 billion company,'' the magazine says, listing five ``off the
radar'' companies: Aasche Transportation (ticker ASHE), Deb Shops
(DEBS), DSP Technology (DSPT), InKline Pharmaceutical (INKP) and
Laser Technology (LSR).
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine (August), which rates and
ranks 3,000 mutual funds, suggests investors take a page from the
playbook of many mutual fund managers _ don't try to predict the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, set a course and stick to it. To protect yourself,
invest conservatively for short-term needs and aggressively for
long-term goals _ those 10 or more years down the road,'' the
magazine suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds Magazine (August) looks at a new trend: ``focus''
funds, which include only 25 or 30 stocks, unlike the typical fund
that may have 150 or 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theory is that the managers of those funds can limit their
portfolios to their very best investment ideas, creating greater
market-beating potential,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Examples are Stein Roe Large Company Focus, Mosaic Focus, Janus
Twenty, PBHG Large Cap 20 and Neuberger &AMP; Berman Focus.
</P>
<P>
   Who's on first: second act
</P>
<P>
   Forbes (July 27) and Fortune (Aug. 3), which disagreed on which
was the biggest domestic corporation earlier this year, now
disagree on which global company is biggest.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune, which ranks 500 companies by revenue, says it's General
Motors _ which, logically, also tops its domestic list.
</P>
<P>
   Just as logically, Forbes, which ranks 500 companies according
to a five-component score, says it's General Electric, its domestic
leader.
</P>
<P>
   They do agree on the revenue the companies reported.
</P>
<P>
   New retirement rules
</P>
<P>
   Many tried-and-true formulas no longer apply, Business Week
(July 20) says in a special edition on retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   People are living longer after they retire, which puts a strain
on finances. And baby boomers retire from one job only to start a
second career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transformation of retirement from kick-back-at-60 to a
more active period of life can give you a new degree of flexibility
in planning your financial future,'' says Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
