<SLUG> BC-TV-DIANA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REAL DIANA': DIANA RETURNS, WITH HER MUSEUM
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Time, channel are for New York area. Check local
listings.) 
(nk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Princess Diana's brother, the ninth Earl Spencer, is seated in a
wicker chair on the grounds of Althorp, the family estate,
recalling the walk last September through the streets of London
behind his sister's coffin, alongside Princes Philip, Charles,
William and Harry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult part was feeling everyone's grief weighing
down on you,'' he says, ``and not being able to look right or left
to see where it was coming from.'' The crowd's reaction seemed to
be different on every block, he said. ``It was very traumatic,
actually.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the most gripping moments in ``The Real Diana,''
Thursday night's premiere episode of News Corporation ``Fox
Files,'' that network's hourlong news-magazine program. The
producers have been unable to resist voice-over pronouncements
about ``Diana, as you've never seen her before,'' and ``the
conspiracy theories that refuse to go away'' and melodramatic
camera movement now and then. Interviewer Catherine Crier tells
viewers a little more than most will want to know about her own
reaction to Diana's death last Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   And Earl Spencer may have agreed to the exclusive interview
partly for the opportunity to show off the new museum he has
created at Althorp in Diana's honor. The home movies, advertised as
never having been seen by the public before, are charming, although
many scenes are shown again and again, as if to fill time. But in
the end, there is enough insightful, thoughtful material here to
satisfy Diana's many admirers, ranging from kindergarten teachers
to high-powered businesswomen who all profess to feel intense
connections with the Princess of Wales in some way.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Spencer is on his best, most admirable behavior, wisely
declining to answer questions about what he would say to Diana if
he could speak with her again and what he thinks of comments made
by Mohamed al-Fayed, the father of Dodi Fayed, who died with Diana
in that Paris car crash. But Earl Spencer is straightforward when
he chooses to address an issue, like the astonishing depth and
breadth of public mourning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost some spiritual reaction, I think,'' he says,
pointing out the relatively small role that organized religion
plays in English life these days. ``I just wonder if people had to
connect with a part of themselves that was probably dormant.'' And
of course with their own mortality, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's other exclusive is a brief interview with Diana's mother,
Frances Shand Kydd, who says absolutely the right thing when she
notes: ``I think that far too little has been said about what
people all over the world gave to her. They nourished her. They
made her smile. They gave her strength.'' Mrs. Shand Kydd recalls
her own similar experience, taking ``enormous comfort'' in being
near the crowds at Kensington Palace, Diana's home in London, in
the days after her death. ``We were sharing,'' she says, ``a very
deep hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month London newspapers ran articles about the
``cult of Diana.'' It continues to grow.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE REAL DIANA'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Thursday on Fox
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
