<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOL-HEAT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOL IT TO BEAT THE TEXAS HEAT WAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GALE M. BRADFORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOL, Texas _ It was high noon and scorching hot, and a Mineral
Wells welder sat in the only cafe in this tiny town sipping iced
tea from a quart Mason jar served by Cool city officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool's the place to be,'' Matt Schnabel said as he finished
his lunch at The Farmhouse, south of the blinking yellow light on
U.S. 180 about 12 miles west of Weatherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always 2 to 3 degrees cooler in Cool,'' Mayor Marsha
McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When settlers came here in the early days at the turn of the
century, they found it to be just a little cooler. Folks would
gather on porches here on Sunday afternoons and talk, and it was
always cooler than in Weatherford or Mineral Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald and her business partner, City Secretary Cindy Serrano,
spent about two years renovating the old Army barracks and
converting it into a diner, said former Cool mayor and lunchtime
regular Jim Heineman, who noted that the Parker County town is not
alone in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Star-Telegram ran stories about our city some years
ago, we found out that there was a Cool, Calif., and they contacted
us asking to be our sister city,'' Heineman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still write us a couple of times a year,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   The cities have similarities. Both are described as ``wide spots
in the road'' with blinking signal lights, and both have had
trouble keeping their ``Cool'' city limit signs from being stolen.
</P>
<P>
   But because of El Nino, summer has just arrived in Cool, Calif.,
Postmaster Jeff Greene said in a telephone interview yesterday. He
said temperatures just recently reached the mid-90s in the town of
4,000, a metropolis compared with the Texas Cool and its population
of 238.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the same old little quiet place, except it does have
a deli and a pizza place now,'' Greene said of the unincorporated
community that has no city officials.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas Cool, folks still gather on front porches, where
it's usually cooler than nearer the Metroplex, said cafe customer
Jim Williams of Weatherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a business meeting here on the front porch last week
and it was comfortable. There's plenty of shade, and it was really
pleasant,'' Williams said. It was so cold inside the cafe one day
that he asked for the air conditioner thermostat to be adjusted, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their city positions and cafe jobs, McDonald and
Serrano are both teachers, McDonald in Mineral Wells and Serrano in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald's mother, Peggy McDonald, 69, makes some of the cafe's
specialties: biscuits, pies, and peach and vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her pies bring folks back again and again. She's one of the
reasons we count this 2-week-old venture a success,'' Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our largest crowds on the hottest days,'' Serrano
said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because it's cool in Cool, McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
