</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-BISHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '91 Baker-Finch's last hurrah
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England -- One of the voices you shall be hearing
from the British Open this week will have a touch of Australia in
it and will belong to Ian Baker-Finch, who is exempt to play,
rather than to be talking, of the British Open through the year
200l. It is a matter of some significance, for Baker-Finch stands
as a symbol of how fragile life at the top can be in the
teeter-totter world of golf. This is one of the rare occasions, if
not the first, on which the player who won the British Open has not
returned to the scene of his triumph to defend his honor.
</P>
<P>
   (No, on second thought, Tony Lema, who won at St. Andrews in
1964 was killed before he could get back again.)
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch's is a tragedy of another nature. His game went
away. Almost like overnight. Mark O'Meara, who was paired with him
on the Sunday round in 1991 here at Royal Birkdale, was speaking of
it yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just Ian's day. He played a tremendous round of golf,
about as good a nine holes as I've ever seen on the front side.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch went out in 29 and won by two strokes over Mike
Harwood, another wallaby. O'Meara shot 69 and felt like a marker, a
playing scorekeeper. Baker-Finch never won again, except for one
tournament in Australia. It's pure irony that Harwood has faded
from the scene as well, but for other reasons. Domestic turmoil led
to a divorce that ripped his life apart. Baker-Finch is still well
married. It was his swing that divorced him.
</P>
<P>
   As I hear it, this is what happened: So elated was he after
winning the Open here that he wanted to win more. He decided he
needed to get more length off the tee, parted company with David
Leadbetter, his mentor, and went off to another coach in Australia.
After about six months he was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing in his swing that I recognized,'' Leadbetter
has said. The curse was upon this handsome, intelligent gentleman,
now 37 years old and a rookie in the telecast booth of the ABC
network.
</P>
<P>
   Baker-Finch had one last fling at it a year ago at Royal Troon.
As the story goes, the fellow Aussie, Peter Thomson, who won the
British Open five times, twice at Birkdale, convinced him he should
give it a go. Not cave in to failure. ``Carry on, stiff upper
lip,'' and all that stuff. It could hardly have been more
embarrassing. Baker-Finch shot 92, looked awful doing it, should
never have been on the course. He withdrew, hasn't attempted to
play since, hasn't earned a dime on tour since 1994 and turned to
the broadcast side in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   There is no harder field on the planet to make than the British
Open. The Masters, for instance, is by invitation. Here, they come
from all over the world, some with faint chance, but always
nurtured hope. They are required to play two hard rounds of
qualifying on adjacent courses, and this week the wind blew and
rain lashed them. Even Larry Mize, a Masters champion, and David
Frost had to qualify; Philip Walton, Christy O'Connor, David
Gilford and Howard Clark, stars of Ryder Cup, and Wayne Riley and
Carl Mason, Scottish Open champions. Only Walton and Clark made it.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Michael Campbell and Steven Bottomley finished
in a tie for third at St. Andrews. Campbell's game has gone to seed
but he managed to qualify. Poor Bottomley, played the wrong ball
and was DQ'd, wouldn't have made it if he hadn't. Jarmo Sandlin,
the Swede who challenged O'Meara's honor, flunked. Three years ago
Paul Broadhurst was knocking on the door, England's hot new hope.
He failed. Some oddball Americans made the trip for nothing, Mac
O'Grady and Howard Twitty. An Argentine named Jose Coceres turned
in a round of 105 at the Hesketh course. This guy is no turkey. He
plays the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   So I was walking the course with Mark McCumber, a player of some
prominence on our side, onetime Players Championship winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago I was second to Tom Lehman at Royal Lytham,'' he
said. ``Now I'm walking the course with a mike in my hands.''
Something happened to his spinal column and he's just hoping he
doesn't lose the ability to walk. Makes Baker-Finch look the lucky
one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
