</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISHOPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nicklaus absence felt by fans
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ Just off the Royal Birkdale practice green
Wednesday, A.D. Hadley of Wolverhampton sensed that clearly
something was missing. A British Open without Jack Nicklaus, he had
decided without hesitation, hit him squarely as fish without chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the aura that he had,'' said Hadley. ``We've had
Tigermania here today, but if Jack walked in here right now, Jack
would would be better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   No disagreement came from his older friend, William Campbell of
Belfast, who termed it ``very disappointing'' that Nicklaus, 58,
decided to end his string of 154 straight major championships
because of an arthritic hip that will not allow contending up to
his standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best golfer in the world ever,'' said Campbell, ``and
I've been coming to Opens since 1963. Winning 20 majors, that
speaks for itself, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus is not gone from British Opens forever. He'll probably
get his moment to wave on the bridge at St. Andrews' 18th, the same
as Arnold Palmer did in 1995. Barring any physical deterioration,
Nicklaus plans to play all four majors in 2000 _ the Masters, the
U.S. Open at Pebble Beach, the PGA at Valhalla and the British Open
at St. Andrews, where he won in 1970 and 1978.
</P>
<P>
   A special moment that will be for Hadley, who met Nicklaus at
the Open at Royal Lytham in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood next to him as close as I am to you,'' said Hadley,
who wore a purple Royal Troon sweater. ``I shook Jack Nicklaus'
hand, and I don't mind telling you, just talking about it right now
brings a bit of a flutter to me heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came last week from Nicklaus' Golden Bear
offices in North Palm Beach,Fla., but apparently word did not reach
all parts of the British Isles. Ken and Joy Woodward of Southport
came to Royal Birkdale and said Wednesday, ``We were just looking
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Having heard vague rumors of a Nicklaus withdrawal, they were
not totally stunned. Still, they had not planned to draw only on
memories of a young Nicklaus, blond hair blowing in the breeze,
prowling the fairways of Royal Birkdale four times before.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend of mine told me many years ago, 'You need to see this
young American and the way he strides up Birkdale's fairways like a
Goliath,''' Ken Woodward said. ``We always watched him and we so
much liked his terrific personality. We loved seeing him coming up
to the last green waving to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a certain charisma, didn't he?'' Joy Woodward
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was perhaps no better than some of his competitors,'' Ken
Woodward said, ``but it was his persona that was different. He was
all go.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Nicklaus was in nearby Chester, England, this week to
open a new golf course designed with son Steve at the Carden Park
Hotel and to play an exhibition. Maybe it offers some solace to
those who miss Nicklaus that he feels it's time to spend time with
his family _ especially if his game is suspect. Although there are
indications Nicklaus might have regretted his decision to skip the
British after his hip improved last week, it's doubtful he has the
strength to handle the heather and high grass of the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm almost 60,'' Nicklaus told reporters this week. ``I'm not
going to compete against the kids. That's silly.''
</P>
<P>
   A great rival and friend of Nicklaus, Tom Watson said flatly of
the man's absence, ``It's sad. It's sad that it has to end, but I'm
sure that if he was in good health, he'd be here. I don't think the
streak is as important to Jack as it is to feeling like he can
compete. If he can compete, he'll be here again.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of the streak are staggering even to Watson, who
believes he had a streak of 66 from 1975 to 1996. Two years ago
Nicklaus even briefly contended at Royal Lytham.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the great thing about the game over here,'' Watson
said. ``They embrace somebody who plays well, no matter where
they're coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the millennium appearance at St. Andrews, Watson said,
``He'll be at St. Andrews for that if he has to play in a
wheelchair. That's his favorite golf course over here.''
</P>
<P>
   For a player not entered in the Open, Nicklaus has been high
profile. A typically tabloid story in Wednesday's London Daily Mail
had Nicklaus fearing that money might ruin Tiger Woods. Many
columnists reflected on Jack's past performances.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the Nicklaus streak and his impact on golf, Woods
said this week, ``He has put a level of expectation on all of us
and what we are trying to achieve. He's a living legend, like
Michael Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he feels bad missing it because of the streak and what
it means to everyone else,'' said Davis Love III, ``but it's going
to take one of the best players in the world to win on this golf
course this week. Which Jack was, but he would have struggled
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, it seems, that wouldn't have bothered A.D. Hadley of
Wolverhampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they said Jack Nicklaus wasn't going to be coming,'' he
said, ``it was like a part of the Open was not here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
