<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USAF-PILOT-TRAINING-A     07-15 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USAF-PILOT-TRAINING-ART-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMED SERVICES MEETING RESISTANCE TO NEW AND EXPANDED BOMBING
RANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Idaho, Nev., Ore., Texas, N.M., Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN HOME, Idaho _ As it scrambles to find new or expanded
places to train fighter and bomber pilots, the Air Force is running
into intensifying opposition from ranchers, environmentalists,
sportsmen and Native Americans who believe the roar of fast,
low-flying jets is disrupting some of the nation's last refuges of
peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of legal and political challenges, the Air Force has
already had to scrap several recent efforts to build new bombing
ranges or to carve out more space in the nation's increasingly
crowded skies for exclusive military use. Virtually every proposal
now on the table faces opposition.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, McCoy Land &AMP; Cattle Co. filed suit in May to block
plans for a new low-level training route over its property, arguing
that the jets upset the cows. In New Mexico, ranchers and
environmentalists have teamed up against a proposal to expand areas
used by pilots at Holloman Air Force Base, including a squadron of
Germany's Luftwaffe. The Air Force's plans to locate a new range
for its big bombers at one of three spots in New Mexico or west
Texas have already stirred outrage, even though no decision has
been made.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition to the Air Force's expansion plans has raised
alarms among the service's top commanders, who say the need for
additional airspace and bombing ranges has become one of the most
critical issues facing them today.
</P>
<P>
   They fear further restrictions on their training space at a time
when new tactics and new weapons _ including missiles that can be
fired 20 or 30 miles from their targets _ are creating new demands
for more room. Right now, they say, they do not have enough
training space for the F-22 fighters that are supposed to start
rolling off the assembly line in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the service's two largest training ranges _ the
Nellis Range in Nevada and the Barry M. Goldwater Range in Arizona
_ require new leases by 2001 from the Bureau of Land Management,
which controls public land use. And that means new environmental
studies, opening the door for what are expected to be strong legal
and political challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you send combat airplanes and crews into harm's way, if
they are going to survive and emerge victorious, they require
rigorous training day to day,'' Gen. Richard Hawley, commander of
Air Combat Command, said in an interview at Langley Air Force Base,
on the southern coast of Virginia. ``In order to do that, you've
got to have a place for them to train.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in Idaho, the Air Force has proposed enlarging the vast
expanse of desert that pilots from Mountain Home Air Force Base use
to hone their skills, attacking a mock airport, evading ``enemy''
missile batteries and fighting air-to-air duels. Although the base
has free run of 7,000 square miles over Idaho, Nevada and Oregon,
the Air Force says it needs still more room and new ``targets'' to
better simulate today's warfare.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely coalition of opponents, however, has rallied against
the proposal. They say the expansion would worsen the already
constant rumble and roar of jets in the area, which encompasses the
Owyhee Canyonlands, one of the largest undeveloped wildernesses
outside of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   After the Air Force announced its proposal in March, a group
calling itself the Greater Owyhee Legal Defense went to court to
block it, contending that the service had not adequately studied
the impact the changes would have on the scattered residents and
abundant wildlife, including sage grouse and California bighorn
sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is some of the most incredible, remote wilderness left,''
said Roger Singer of the Sierra Club's Idaho chapter in Boise. ``It
shouldn't be a bombing range.''
</P>
<P>
   With the overarching threats of the Cold War having passed,
people seem far less willing to tolerate jets skimming 100 to 500
feet off the ground, not to mention the quake of sonic booms, which
can shatter windows and crack walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War, we said, `Hey, I need this for training,'
and you got it to train the troops,'' Hawley said. ``There has been
a shifting in priorities. And the other issues, which we try to
accommodate, tend to get a more sensitive hearing sometimes than
our needs do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force and, to a lesser extent, the Navy, Marine Corps
and Army are all having to vie against new and competing claims on
the nation's increasingly crowded airspace, as well as on the
public lands needed for bombing itself.
</P>
<P>
   The steady growth of commercial airline traffic has increased
pressure on the Federal Aviation Administration to free up routes
reserved for military use. Also, small cities once located far from
training areas have sprawled, bringing residents much closer to the
jets. Las Vegas, for example, has virtually overrun the boundary of
Nellis Air Force Base, established in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have also raised objections to the noise and
the impact of flares and chaff, the small aluminum coated fibers
jets jettison to confuse incoming missiles. One of the Air Force's
biggest headaches at ranges in the East has been trying to not to
disturb the red-cockaded woodpecker, an endangered species.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force _ and the Army's Air Forces before it _ have been
training pilots here in southern Idaho since 1942. The conditions
are ideal: The weather is clear, the skies uncrowded, the land
beneath it sparsely populated.
</P>
<P>
   From the cockpit of an F-15E, roaring back and forth over the
buttes and rolling hills, the sparse desert seems to stretch as far
as the eye can see. For the Air Force, though, it stretches not
nearly far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The existing airspace and the bombing range within it, known as
Saylor Creek, date to the Vietnam era, and that, the base's
commanders said, is the problem: They were designed for slower,
less agile jets with shorter ranges.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, though, Mountain Home has been the base of the 366th
Wing, with 80 F-16 and F-15 fighters, B-1B bombers and KC-135 air
tankers. The ``composite wing'' is the only one of its kind,
created to allow pilots and crews of different aircraft to work and
train together. Those jets, according to the base's commander,
Brig. Gen. Randall Schmidt, need more space.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion proposal is the fourth since 1989; among other
things, it would expand the air space by 7 percent, create a new
12,000 acre bombing range and place 30 transmitters throughout the
area to simulate anti-aircraft batteries. The Air Force abandoned a
similar proposal three years ago after a legal challenge by the
same coalition fighting it now.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Land Management initially opposed the plans, but
relented after extracting promises to restrict low-level flights
over the area's canyons and rivers, especially during the spring,
when the bighorn sheep give birth in the canyonlands and the rivers
are full of kayaks and canoes.
</P>
<P>
   Now the fight has turned to Congress. Sen. Dirk Kempthorne, a
Republican who is running for governor of Idaho in November, pushed
through an amendment last month that approved the Air Force's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky to have the composite wing in Idaho,'' said
Kempthorne, whose Democratic opponent in the election, Bob Huntley,
opposes the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., called the expansion ``an absolute
waste of taxpayers' money and citizens' air space.'' He said the
Air Force plans to spend $31 million to expand an existing range,
when pilots could easily train at ranges in Nevada and Utah only a
few minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   The House has not yet taken up the issue. The FAA, meanwhile,
must still consider whether to approve the Air Force's request for
the airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Although the area is remote, it is not uninhabited. About 1,500
members of Shoshone-Pauite Tribes live in the Duck Valley
Reservation, right in the middle of the training area.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Gibson, one of seven members of the reservation's
governing council, said the Air Force did not appreciate the land's
significance. The tribes' homelands, he explained, included most of
the Owyhee Canyonlands, and the area is peppered with burial sites,
as well as plants and animals considered part of a spiritual world.
The jets, he said, sorely disrupt that, though the Air Force has
promised never to fly below 5,000 feet over the reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To them, this is all desolate _ rocks and scrub land,'' he
said. ``But to us, this is our bible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
