A6903 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-RELIGIONS-TEX     07-15 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-RELIGIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE CHURCH OF CHRIST, SCIENTIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   History: Christian Science developed out of the writings and
leadership of founder Mary Baker Eddy, who recovered from a serious
injury in 1866 after reading a biblical account of Christ's healing
of a man with palsy. Eddy soon began informally teaching a
scientific approach to divine healing; she did not plan to
establish a denomination, but hoped to spread her message through
existing churches.
</P>
<P>
   In 1870, Eddy published a booklet, ``The Science of Man.'' Soon
after she published ``Science and Health With Key to the
Scriptures,'' a textbook that explained the beliefs of Christian
Science. Eventually, Eddy sought dismissal from the church in which
she was raised and founded the Christian Science Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Christ, Scientist, was established in Boston in
1879; the church dissolved 10 years later but was reorganized in
1892. The church's bylaws, called the Church Manual, were developed
in 1895. The Church Manual and Eddy's textbook are key documents in
Christian Science today.
</P>
<P>
   Membership: The church has approximately 2,500 congregations
worldwide, most of them in North America. No formal membership
statistics are published because Eddy believed that statistics do
not reflect the church's true spiritual growth.
</P>
<P>
   Beliefs: The Church of Christ, Scientist, identifies itself as
Christian in essence. The church's tenets affirm its members'
belief in the Trinity and in the Bible as the guide to eternal
life.
</P>
<P>
   The key element in Christian Science is the belief that all God
creates is good, so evil does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reality of sin, sickness or death is the awful fact
that unrealities seem real to human, erring belief, until God
strips off their disguise,'' Eddy wrote in ``Science and Health.''
``They are not true, because they are not of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing, therefore, is considered not miraculous but natural.
Humans are not mortal and material, Christian Scientists believe,
and viruses and germs are false causes of sickness. Disease is
considered to be a mental fabrication, a delusion that can be
eliminated through prayer and full spiritual understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy has surrounded the Church of Christ, Scientist,
because of its spiritual healing practices. Courts have both
limited Christian Science healing and given it legal protection as
a form of worship.
</P>
<P>
   Church members revere Eddy as founder but carefully distinguish
her as discoverer of Christian Science from Jesus as Savior.
Likewise, Eddy's textbook is a key part of worship but is not
considered a second Scripture or an authority equal to the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Daily life: Worship at local branch churches is led by two
elected readers who read from the Bible and Eddy's textbook,
``Science and Health.''
</P>
<P>
   Baptism is not a traditional Christian Science ceremony; it is
considered a continuing individual spiritual experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christian Science Monitor'' is the most famous publication
of the Church of Christ, Scientist, but the church publishes
numerous other periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Encyclopedia of American Religions, Handbook of
Denominations in the United States, Religions of America
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
