<SLUG> BC-WEBSITE-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEN ANY BAD MOVIES LATELY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're one of those who finds fault with any kind of movie,
the creators of Bad Movie Night (www.hit-n-run.com) might be
looking for you ... as a reviewer.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Movie Night is a clearinghouse for reviews of bad movies and
bad impressions of good movies. A movie can be either an overhyped
summer release or a 49-cent rental from the local video store.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Movie Night was created last fall on the night that movie
buffs Ken Wilson, Chris Bjuland and Scott Murdock, of Kansas City,
Mo., saw ``I Know What You Did Last Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We began making it our goal to see a bad movie each week and
post our reviews,'' Murdock said.
</P>
<P>
   The site's stated goal is to create a Bad Movie Academy, an
elite group of 100 people who are allowed to post movie reviews on
the site and participate in other events such as the annual Bad
Movie Night Awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``To become a member, a person must complete a rather difficult
100-question trivia quiz and then submit a sample movie review from
a list of bad movies of our choosing,'' Murdock said.
</P>
<P>
   The site is similar to the Golden Raspberry Award Foundation,
which tracks the worst movies and performances of the year and
awards its Razzies. The difference is that Bad Movie Night
maintains a database of bad movies.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Movie Night isn't the only site to examine bad movies. A
sampling:
</P>
<P>
   Oh, The Humanity! The Worst Movies on Earth
(www.ohthehumanity.com): This elaborate site takes a different
tack: It posts reviews of B movies, not A movies that are bad.
</P>
<P>
   Ken's World of Awful Movies (www.nrx.net/badmovies): This
well-organized site has lots of reviews of B movies and the best
network of links, including a couple to B-movie queen Chesty Morgan
worship pages.
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Turkey Awards:
(members.tripod.com/\Pcosmics/TurkeyAward): This site is for
B-movie fans who want to look up the Turkey Awards given by Harry
and Michael Medved, authors of ``The Fifty Worst Films of All
Time.'' _ Tommy Cummings dragon\Nstar-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6915 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-15 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A LONG-RUNNING BETRAYAL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A teen-ager, concocting a lie and hoping to make it
convincing, smears feces on herself, scrawls racial slurs on her
body and crawls half-naked into a filthy garbage bag. She does this
outdoors in the cold of November. Her story is that a gang of white
men abducted and raped her.
</P>
<P>
   When Al Sharpton, C. Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox realized that
Tawana Brawley's story had been made up, that it was all a lie,
they should have recognized that this was a very disturbed child, a
child in deep psychological trouble and in need of immediate
professional help, and they should have seen that she got it. They
claimed, after all, to be ``advisers'' to her family.
</P>
<P>
   Instead these grown men clambered gleefully onto Tawana's wild
tale and rode it for all it was worth. They became stars, trailed
by television cameras and cheered by their supporters as if they
were heroes. They had a fine time making their outrageous comments
and crazy charges, and seemed unconcerned that they were defaming
people, damaging lives and further poisoning race relations. In the
process they betrayed and exploited a teen-age girl who really
needed their help.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to know about their relationship with Tawana
Brawley is contained in a comment Sharpton made a few months ago.
He said he had never questioned Miss Brawley about the alleged
rape. As he put it: ``I would not engage in sex talk with a
15-year-old girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The three so-called advisers were never interested in what had
really happened. The spotlight beckoned, and not one of them had
the strength of character to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley's most recent public appearance was at a church in
Brooklyn last December. At 25, she still looked immature, even
childlike. It was both weird and painful to watch her continue to
insist after all these years: ``I'm not a liar. I'm not crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brawley was not the only one betrayed. Maddox, Mason and
especially Sharpton have proclaimed to all who would listen that
they were ``leaders'' of the black community in New York. To some
extent that was true. Without question Sharpton stepped into a
leadership void, running for office, comforting families victimized
by police excesses, paying attention to some of the powerless and
voiceless people that politicians of all backgrounds have largely
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again I have heard black residents say of Sharpton:
``At least he bothered to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of leadership did he provide? It's awfully hard to
make the case that you are serving the interests of black New
Yorkers by spending more than a decade's worth of energy in the
service of a mammoth and destructive lie.
</P>
<P>
   When it suits him, Sharpton offers himself as a statesman. He
had the opportunity to be one in the Brawley case. When he found
out that Miss Brawley was lying, he could have met with his inner
circle and explained why it was necessary and much better in the
long run to 'fess up.
</P>
<P>
   He could have taken the lead in securing the help Miss Brawley
needed. He could have explained to the public, truthfully and
convincingly, how the story of a troubled teen-ager had spiraled
dangerously out of control and what he and his colleagues were
doing to curtail the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's base of support among black residents would not have
been hurt by that kind of admission. And it is very likely that
such an example of tough leadership would have gained him admirers
among the wider public.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not Al Sharpton. He is drawn to the quick score, the
reckless remark, the provocative radio or TV appearance, and most
of all the laughter and applause of the crowd. His supporters get
plenty of entertainment but no real leadership.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people have said they continue to support Miss
Brawley because she is a latter-day example of the black women who
have been systematically raped by white men over the centuries. I
disagree. This case is a mirror image of those many terrible cases
in which black men were falsely accused of rape by white women.
Sharpton, Mason and Maddox are all deeply aware of the tragic
consequences of those cases.
</P>
<P>
   But that awareness did nothing to temper their behavior. If they
learned anything from history, it was the worst possible lessons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1913EDT &QL; 
