<SLUG> BC-KODAK-EARNINGS-270&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHIFT, EASTMAN KODAK CITES BIG EARNINGS GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak Co. reported nearly a 35 percent gain in
second-quarter earnings Wednesday, reversing a six-quarter-long
decline.
</P>
<P>
   The photography giant, based in Rochester, N.Y., earned $495
million, or $1.51 a diluted share, compared with $368 million, or
$1.11, a year earlier. Even excluding a one-time gain of 13 cents a
share, from the sale of Kodak's stake in Gretag Imaging, the
earnings were well above the $1.13 a share that Wall Street
analysts had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Although losses from digital photography remained high, and
total revenue declined 4.9 percent, to $3.7 billion, investors
reacted as though the quarter had been perfect. Kodak's shares
soared $8.75, or nearly 12 percent, to $82.50, as analysts pushed
up their earnings estimates for all of 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured they could beat us, but never by this much,'' said
Jonathan Rosenzweig of Salomon Smith Barney, who had expected the
quarter's earnings to reach $1.15. ``I am a very happy camper.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, analysts took the figures as proof that Kodak was making
good on its pledge last fall to cut research costs, stanch its
hemorrhaging digital portfolio and eliminate almost 20,000 jobs _ a
fifth of its work force. The company's stated goal was to reduce
$500 million from costs both this year and next. Costs are already
down $350 million for the first half of 1998, putting Kodak ahead
of schedule. Indeed, even its line of writable compact disks, which
lost $100 million last year, is nearing the break-even point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even over $100, this wouldn't be an overvalued stock now,''
said Peter Enderlin, an analyst with First Albany Corp.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The quarter did have disappointments. Kodak's domestic film
volume in units was up 10 percent, but continued pressure on prices
kept revenue growth to just 3 percent. Sales in emerging markets,
which had been one of Kodak's fastest-growing areas, plunged 14
percent, in good part because of Asia's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from digital cameras was down about 5 percent, and the
company's digital-photography portfolio lost $64 million for the
quarter _ much reduced from the $102 million it lost in the second
quarter of 1997, but up from a $55 million loss in 1998's first
three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two growth levers just didn't deliver for us,'' said
Harry Kavetas, Kodak's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Kavetas maintains that these are short-term setbacks. Kodak
continues to pump money into emerging markets, particularly China,
and expects growth to resume there soon.
</P>
<P>
   It is working with Intel Corp. to create photo-writable CDs, and
with America Online to allow the Internet access provider's
customers to receive digital versions of photographs by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   More important to analysts, Kodak is quitting ancillary products
and businesses. It sold a chain of photofinishing stores that it
had bought less than two years ago, aborting a retail strategy that
was pushing it into competition with its photofinishing customers.
It trimmed slow-moving products from its digital-photography line,
and folded its graphic arts business into Kodak Polychrome
Graphics, a joint venture with Dainippon Ink &AMP; Chemicals of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And it bailed out of sundry small businesses _ Cineon, which
makes special-effects equipment for movies, is one example _ that
served as little more than a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got rid of businesses we never even knew they were in,
and they got rid of them fast,'' said Ulysses Yannas, an analyst
with Mercer, Bokert, Buckman &AMP; Reider.
</P>
<P>
   Many Kodak-watchers also see happier news in the domestic film
picture. Although Kodak continues to reduce prices on packs of
slower-speed film, it is maintaining its price on the higher-priced
APS and high-speed Max lines. Indeed, Max films accounted for 31
percent of film sales, up from 27 percent in the second quarter
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Max lines cost a few extra grains of silver to make, but
they get more than double the price,'' Yannas said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the general euphoria remains tempered by basic worries
about the outlook for the photography business. ``It's one thing to
stem digital losses or to steal film share from competitors,'' said
Jack Kelly, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs. ``To really make money,
they've got to find a way to get people to take more pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Kavetas acknowledged that Kodak's revenue needed help. ``We
can't save our way to long-term growth,'' he said. ``But this
quarter has finally confirmed that we're getting our act
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
