<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT-305&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS AREA GRAPPLES WITH DEADLY HEAT WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CAROL MARIE CROPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ With 16 deaths here already tied to the heat this
summer and with temperatures of 100 degrees or more for 10 days in
a row, county health officials have declared a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency measures were imposed Tuesday after eight
heat-related deaths were reported in two days, said Betty
Culbreath, the director of the Dallas County Health and Human
Services Department. Most of the victims have been the elderly who
had other health problems, Ms. Culbreath said, although children 5
and under are also at risk. ``People are taking better care of
their children than their elderly,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave has been blamed for more than 50 deaths in all,
including 23 in Texas and 20 in Louisiana. Oklahoma's state
epidemiologist, Mike Crutcher, said he had received reports of six
heat-related deaths in the past month, compared with four for last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The county health agency has set up a hot line so the elderly,
the disabled and the poor can call to get air conditioners
repaired, to receive a free fan or to get help in paying utility
bills, Ms. Culbreath said. City recreation centers and other public
buildings were open during business hours to people who needed a
place to cool off, and six of the centers were prepared for
overnight use if needed, she added.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 deaths in Dallas are the most heat-related fatalities in
recent memory, Ms. Culbreath said. In comparison, for all of last
year there were 17 heat-related deaths in the entire state, said
Doug McBride, the public information officer with the Texas Health
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service also reported that the Dallas area,
through Wednesday, has had 23 days when the high reached or topped
100 degrees. But that is far from the record set in 1980 of 69 days
of temperatures of 100 degrees or more.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Michael Foster, a meteorologist at the National Weather Service
in Fort Worth, said the recent heat wave has been caused by an
upper-level high pressure system that covers the area, preventing
cloud formation and rainfall and blocking other weather patterns
from moving in. Laredo, Texas, on the border with Mexico, recorded
a high Tuesday of 113 degrees, Foster said, the highest reading.
</P>
<P>
   The heat, combined with a lack of rain, has already cost Texas
agriculture $1.5 billion _ which translates to a $4.6 billion loss
to the state's economy _ as cotton plants shrivel and ranchers are
forced to sell hungry livestock, the Texas Agricultural Extension
Service reported. The losses could go higher unless there is
cooling rain soon, an agricultural economist said, perhaps
surpassing the record $1.9 billion in losses from the drought of
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, most Dallas residents, accustomed to summer
temperatures in the mid-90s, went on with business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Rodriguez, a 91-year-old who received national attention
last year when a drive-through bank was built around his modest
house, said he sat under a shade tree in his back yard Sunday,
watching the bank's time-and-temperature sign as the temperature
rose to 110 degrees. The weather service said that temperature
broke a record for the date, set in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   At Sammy's Bar-B-Q, a smattering of diners sat on the covered
area outside to eat barbecued beef and brisket, potato salad and
fried okra. ``We're accustomed to it,'' said Jane Mills, 37, who
moved to Dallas from Boston in that sizzling summer of 1980. ``I
remember my first summer in Texas, eating Popsicles and laying on a
bed and thinking, `I'm going to die.' Last weekend, I was playing
tennis and it was 105.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though a 23-year-old man died after bicycling in the heat
here, John Lauck of Plano, Texas, took his customary noontime run.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to stay well hydrated and stay in the shade to
run,'' Lauck said. ``I haven't missed a day yet because of the
heat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
