<SLUG> BC-TUMOR-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUMOR-STARVING DRUG FOUND TO BOOST RADIATION TREATMENT IN MICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angiostatin, a tumor-starving drug from the laboratory of
Harvard's Dr. Judah Folkman, dramatically boosts the anticancer
effect of radiation treatment in mice without causing additional
side effects, researchers are reporting today.
</P>
<P>
   When the experimental drug was combined with standard doses of
radiation, human tumors implanted in mice stopped growing or shrank
to a far greater degree than with either treatment alone, say the
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   If effective in humans, the synergistic combination ``could make
radiation much more effective at providing local control of
cancer'' including prostate, brain, head and neck cancers,
soft-tissue sarcomas and others, said Dr. Ralph Weichselbaum,
chairman of radiation oncology at the University of Chicago, and
lead author of the report in the current Nature.
</P>
<P>
   The other authors are from Harvard Medical School and
Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center, and Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   Angiostatin was discovered in Folkman's laboratory at Children's
Hospital in Boston. It is one of the most potent of substances
known as ``angiogenesis inhibitors'' that work by blocking the
growth of small blood vessels tumors need to grow; the drugs don't
directly attack tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Angiostatin has not yet been tested in humans, but it and
another drug from Folkman's lab, endostatin, have shown powerful
tumor-shrinking effects in mice. The drugs are being developed by
the National Cancer Institute and a biotech company with hopes of
initial human trials sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd give it to patients tomorrow'' if it were available, said
Weichselbaum of angiostatin. He noted that the substance, a natural
protein found in the body, is apparently non-toxic in mice and that
it worked even when given for only a few days.
</P>
<P>
   At present, angiostatin is available only in minute amounts from
researchers who make it through a laborious process in their
laboratories. It won't be available for testing in combination with
radiation or other therapies until it passes stringent safety tests
in a small number of patients, which will be in 1999 at the
earliest. The angiostatin used in the experiments was made at
Northwestern University, said Weichselbaum.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists tested radiation and angiostatin separately on
mice, some that had mouse lung cancers and others that had human
tumors created by injecting them with human cancer cells. The
resulting tumors were large, in some cases weighing as much as 5
1/2 percent of the animal's body weight.
</P>
<P>
   Then the researchers combined injections of angiostatin in low
doses with radiation therapy. In one group of experiments using
mice with transplanted human larynx cancers, the combination
treatment shrank tumors by an average of 64 percent compared with
reductions of 16 percent and 18 percent respectively with
angiostatin alone or radiation alone.
</P>
<P>
   When they carried out autopsies on the mice, the researchers
discovered something surprising: the angiostatin and radiation had
shrunk the tumors by destroying the blood vessels, not by killing
the cancer directly. This was a surprise, said Weichselbaum in a
telephone interview, because radiation usually works by damaging
the DNA, or genetic material, in cancer cells _ not by targeting a
tumor's blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The angiostatin, he said, apparently made the blood vessels more
sensitive to radiation, so that the radiation ``really poops out''
the vessels and causes them to shrivel away.
</P>
<P>
   The results point in the future to combining angiogenesis
inhibitors not just with radiation but also with other DNA-damaging
agents like chemotherapy drugs as a new way to increase the potency
of cancer treatment without adding toxic side effects, said
Weichselbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman, in an interview, termed the findings ``a beautiful new
phenomenon'' that underscores the likely role of angiogenesis
inhibitors as team players in future cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking well-known conventional therapies (such as
radiation), which are OK in themselves but have a lot of side
effects, and increasing their power'' through angiostatin's ability
to focus the radiation damage on the tumor's blood vessels, while
sparing the surrounding normal tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they're doing,'' Folkman said of the report's
authors, ``is making anti-angiogenic radiotherapy'' _ in effect, a
new form of cancer treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
