<HEADER>
A6958 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS &LR;      07-15 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MANAGED-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OVER MANAGED CARE HEATS UP AS SENATE GOP UNVEILS PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The political battle over managed care intensified
Wednesday as Senate Republican leaders unveiled their own
legislative ``patient bill of rights'' to rein in cost-conscious
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate GOP measure sets up a procedure for patients to
appeal when their health plan refuses to cover a particular
treatment. Patients could first appeal to officials of the plan
and, if not satisfied, take their complaint to an independent
appeal body that the plan has arranged for. The outside body's
decision would be binding.
</P>
<P>
   If they are still not satisfied, patients could sue the plan.
</P>
<P>
   This procedure contrasts sharply with a Democratic plan,
introduced in March, that permits lawsuits against health plans
without the appeals process when coverage decisions lead to more
illness or death.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Democratic measure, the Republican plan would make
the cost of health insurance fully tax deductible for the
self-employed. And it envisions a dramatic expansion of special
savings accounts for medical needs, which are encouraged through
tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP appeals plan and its expansion of medical savings
accounts would cost the U.S. treasury about $11 billion over 10
years, said Sen. William Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in a position to say how we will pay for it,'' he said
at a news conference at the U.S. Capitol. ``But we will pay for it
in a non-controversial manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacking the Democratic proposal, the Senate Republicans said
their measure addresses concerns about managed care without the
Democrats' government mandates that they said would drive up
premium costs and lead employers to drop coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in the political game,'' said Sen. Don
Nickels, R-Okla., chairman of the Senate Republican task force that
developed the Republican alternative. ``We're interested in
improving quality health care.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said
he intends to bring the GOP plan to the Senate floor before the end
of the month. At the news conference, Nickles said Republicans are
willing to consider the Democratic measure and vote on it as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been asking for it,'' he said. ``We're willing to
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   A major difference between the GOP and Democratic Senate
proposals is that the Republicans would leave most regulation to
states and cover only those patients whose health plans are exempt
from state law.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' bill would cover all people in a managed care
plan, regardless of whether their health care is exempt from state
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican plan focuses almost exclusively on the 48
million Americans who receive health coverage from so-called
employer self-insured plans. These employees represent about a
third of the estimated 150 million Americans covered by some kind
of managed care plan.
</P>
<P>
   In these self-insured plans, employers can contract with managed
care companies to provide health care for employees, but it is the
employers _ not the health plan _ that assumes the financial risk
if, say, a worker comes down with a rare form of cancer that
requires costly treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, the employer self-insured plans are exempt
from state regulation and state court lawsuits for damages.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Senate plan would rely primarily on state
regulations to address the complaints of those 100 million or so
Americans in so-called fully insured plans, in which a managed care
company contracts with an employer to provide health care coverage
and assumes all the risk.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would amend federal law to permit workers in
self-insured plans to receive obstetric or gynecological or
pediatric care without a referral from a primary care
``gatekeeper.'' It would also require such plans to cover most
emergency room service in hospitals not affiliated with the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Self-insured employers also would have to offer employees a
so-called point-of-service option, in which a patient pays extra to
choose a doctor outside the plan's physician network.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic bill would make these guarantees part of all
health plans.
</P>
<P>
   At the GOP news conference, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, offered an
impassioned plea for expanded medical savings accounts, saying they
guarantee that patients can see the doctors of their choice _ a
major complaint about managed care _ without the Democratic bill's
reliance on government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under our bill, when you want to see a doctor, you don't have
to call a gatekeeper, you don't have to get a lawyer, you don't
have to see a government bureaucrat,'' he said. ``You simply have
to call up and say, `Do you take Visa or Master Charge, or do you
take a check?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm drew laughter when he said President Clinton, Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., and other Democrats ``draw back from (medical
savings accounts) like a vampire from a cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at a separate news conference, Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., called medical savings accounts a ``disaster''
that favors those who are well off and healthy over those who are
poorer and less healthy. When asked to respond to Gramm's reference
to vampires, Daschle said the GOP proposal, if adopted, would
result in ``sucking the blood out of the American health care
system.''
</P>
<P>
   After Daschle spoke, Kennedy, the primary Senate author of the
Democrats' bill, said of the GOP version: ``(It's) not a bill of
rights; it's a bill of wrongs.''
</P>
<P>
   With most polls showing high levels of voter anxiety over
managed care, Republican senators were under immense pressure to
release a plan in order to avoid being caught empty-handed and open
to Democratic finger-pointing on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care now accounts for more than 80 percent of
employer-based health care coverage in the United States. Under
managed care, health plans monitor services provided to patients to
ensure they are medically necessary. Increasingly, however,
patients are complaining that managed care too frequently denies
them thorough medical attention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS _ STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both pro-regulation consumer groups and anti-regulation managed
care industry representatives reacted negatively to the Republican
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pollack, executive director of Families USA, a leading
proponent of managed care regulation, said the GOP measure was
``much ado about very little.'' The bill's emphasis on medical
savings accounts is ``great for the healthy and wealthy, disastrous
for everyone else,'' he said. Refusing to permit lawsuits by
patients against managed care companies means ``there's no
deterrent effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Benefits Coalition, representing more than 30 managed
care companies, insurance firms and employers, said the Republican
bill would ``only increase health care costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Association of Health Plans, which represents more
than 1,000 such plans, said that while the GOP bill avoids some of
the ``micromanagement'' of the Democratic plan, it ``still relies
heavily on government mandates.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the managed care front, President Clinton took part
in a roundtable discussion with doctors, nurses and families who
described problems they have encountered with the system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said horror stories of denied coverage showed that
Congress needs to pass a patient's bill of rights this session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a political issue, and anybody who has personally
experienced it feels the same way,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clinton is expected to attack the GOP measure when
he goes to Capitol Hill to join Democratic lawmakers and
representatives of the American Medical Association and the
American Nurses Association to pitch for passage of the Democrats'
bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
