<HEADLINE>
ANTIPSYCHOTIC DRUG COSTS IN US TWICE THOSE IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Promising new drugs to treat schizophrenia, depression, and
other severe mental illnesses typically cost twice as much in the
United States as they do in the rest of North America and in
Europe, according to a study released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The US price was higher for each of eight drugs sampled _ more
than six times higher in one case. And while the study focused on
antidepressants and antipsychotics, its authors say the disparity
in prices likely is as stark for antibiotics, heart drugs, and
other medications.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of people, if not tens of thousands, for
whom the impact of this price gouging is that they don't get
treated,'' said Dr. Sidney M. Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's
Health Research Group, a Washington nonprofit that conducted the
study.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan F. Holmer, president of the Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers Association of America, said that ``our companies
take on the extraordinary risk of drug discovery because the
American free-market system offers incentives and potential
rewards. In other countries around the world, especially Europe,
when the free market is stifled by price controls or patent piracy,
the lights in the laboratories go out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Public Citizen study was prompted by anecdotal reports of
big gaps in drug prices between Europe and America, said Dr. E.
Fuller Torrey, a psychiatrist and one of the authors. The reports
dealt with the new generation of drugs to treat mental illness, he
added, and since his organization long has been concerned about
problems of the mentally ill, he and others decided to run an
in-depth study.
</P>
<P>
   Five antidepressants and three antipsychotic drugs were selected
for the survey, and the costs to pharmacists in the United States,
Canada, Mexico, and 14 European countries were compared for an
average 30-day supply of each medication available there. The
findings were dramatic: For most drugs in most countries there was
a relatively narrow cost difference. The big exception was the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The widely touted antidepressent fluoxetine (Prozac), for
instance, cost an average of $317.03 in America and $111.20 on
average in the 16 other countries. Fluvoxamine (Luvox), used to
treat obsessive-compulsive disorders, was 2.3 times more expensive
here, while clozapine (Clozaril), used for schizophrenia, cost 2.9
times more.
</P>
<P>
   Why the huge differences?
</P>
<P>
   All the other countries have national health insurance of some
form, which gives them clout in negotiations with big
pharmaceutical companies, the study authors say. That same clout
applies in the United States in the case of agencies, such as the
Veterans Administration, that get drugs at prices as low as those
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturers of the drugs studied earned more than $12
billion annually in profits in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States they basically can charge what the market
will bear,'' said Torrey. ``These are not drugs just to enhance the
quality of your life, like Viagra. These are drugs people need to
not be suicidal, to not be homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Tarutis, a board member of the National Alliance for the
Mentally Ill, was equally alarmed by the findings. ``Why should the
same product cost twice as much in this country as it does in
European countries?'' he asked. ``That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holmer, whose group represents the makers of the eight drugs
studied and the rest of the US pharmaceutical industry, said that
some of the price differences may be a result of the
newly-strengthened position of the US dollar, differences in costs
of living in countries studied, variations in medical practices,
and other methodological issues involved in the Public Citizen
study.
</P>
<P>
   Price controls like those in the other countries, he added,
``are a dagger aimed at the hearts of America's patients. If price
controls are imposed there will be less investment in research and
development and far fewer new cures and treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe, however, said that drug companies ``use research
blackmail to cover everything. ... Those companies would neither go
out of business nor would they have to retrench on their research''
if prices to US consumers were brought in line with those of our
industrial partners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
