<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINA-FLEET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET FINANCIAL'S HIRING OF LATINAS CITED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Latina Style magazine has named the Boston based
Fleet Financial Group on its list of 50 companies that offer
Hispanic women the most career opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based magazine, aimed at professional Hispanic
females, released the Latina Style 50 Wednesday in its July-August
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet was noted for having 11 Hispanic vice presidents, mentor
programs, 12 weeks of maternity or adoption leave, career
counseling, and training for Hispanic female employees, said Anna
Maria Arias, the magazine's publisher and editor. Fleet was the
only company that has its headquarters in New England to make the
list.
</P>
<P>
   Arias said the survey was based on questionnaires and interviews
with Hispanic women employees from Fleet and about 200 other
Fortune 500 businesses that cater specifically to the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``After years of hearing the same thing from Hispanic women
about how hard it was to find a good job or to find one they're
happy with, the magazine decided to conduct this survey to let our
readers know which companies are best for Hispanic women,'' Arias
said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine used reader questionnaires to find out what
Hispanic women thought were the most important characteristics of
employers, and judged the businesses according to those qualities.
Arias said readers' top concerns included the number of Hispanic
women executives, child care, maternity leave, and mentor programs.
</P>
<P>
   Christie DeMichael, Fleet's director of diversity, said that the
company pays managers bonuses forreaching diversity goals, and that
Fleet has a diversity council. She also pointed to flexible work
programs and time off for volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs and policies make Fleet an employer of choice
for Latinas, one that offers challenge, support, and the
flexibility we all need to grow personally and professionally,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   To help select the top 50 businesses, the magazine also
conducted anonymous interviews with Hispanic women who work at each
of the companies surveyed, Arias said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times companies look really good on paper, but when
it gets down to the day-to-day experience, Hispanic women are not
getting the treatment or opportunities they deserve,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bard, the magazine's director of public relations and
marketing, said although the survey is geared toward Hispanic
women, it should apply to other groups as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanic women are generally among the lowest in pay, rank,
and benefits, and if companies are good for them, they should be
good for all women and for men as well,'' Bard said.
</P>
<P>
   Helping Hispanic females find the best companies to work for is
important, Arias said, because the women have been known for being
loyal to their employers more than to their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanic woman usually do not leave their jobs unless
something really bad happens to them or unless they hit the glass
ceiling,'' she said. ``So we're trying to help these women get
their careers off to the best start possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Arias said she hopes businesses take heed of the survey and use
it to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a heck of a lot of companies that are having a hard
time recruiting Hispanic women or keeping the Hispanic women that
are working for them, and this survey can help those businesses see
what they need to do to change that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of word of mouth in the Hispanic culture,''
Arias said. ``When one company is bad-mouthed or praised, word gets
out pretty fast, and people listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Other companies on the list include Ford Motor Co., General
Motors Co., NationsBank Corp., SBC Communications, State Farm
Insurance Cos., The Walt Disney Co., and McDonald's Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
