<SLUG> BC-NETSCAPE-VERSION4.5-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW NETSCAPE BROWSER AVAILABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Netscape Communications Corp. unveils Thrusday a preview version
of its latest Navigator Web browser, on the heels of a new study
that claims the company is still losing market share to bitter
rival Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Navigator 4.5 will be available free by downloading from the
Netscape Web site and numerous other sites on the Internet. The new
browser is being rolled out in conjunction with a major upgrade of
Netscape's Netcenter Web site. Indeed, some features of the new
browser are designed to keep the user coming back to the Netcenter
site. Netscape hopes to establish Netcenter as a popular portal to
the Internet, thus attracting millions in revenues from companies
wishing to display ads on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Navigator 4.5 will include a ``smart browsing'' feature that
will let the user go to a Web site without having to type long and
complicated addresses. Instead of http://www.boston.com/globe, the
user could type the words ``Boston Globe.'' The new browser would
connect to Netcenter, which stores a listing of 1.5 million proper
names, linked to particular Web pages. Netcenter would look up the
right Web address and send that information to the browser.
</P>
<P>
   The new Netscape browser will also have an e-mail program that
automatically looks up a person's e-mail address by checking a
Netcenter database. And it will contain a new feature that lets the
user store personal information at Netcenter, such as a personal
address book and bookmarks for favorite sites. A user could store
this information on Netcenter, instead of carrying around an
address book or laptop computer. Then he could get access to the
information by logging onto Netcenter from any Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Herendeen, Netscape's director of client marketing, said
that the company's decision last year to give away its browser for
no charge has slowed a sharp decline in market share. Netscape
formerly charged between $29 and $79 for versions of the browser,
while Microsoft gave away its Internet Explorer software.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Herendeen confirmed recent survey data that found
that Navigator, which once held 80 percent of the browser market,
is now hovering in the 50-percent range. Indeed, according to the
Internet advertising firm AdKnowledge, Netscape now holds about 52
percent of the market, with Microsoft at 45 percent and gaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6969 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUERTO-ECONSCENE-600&AMP;     07-15 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTO-ECONSCENE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: PUERTO RICO AT A CROSSROADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To most Americans, the idea of a government-owned telephone
system is no doubt as alien, say, as driving on the left side of
the road. But to Puerto Ricans the proposed privatization of the
state-run telephone company is a fighting issue, with a majority
apparently preferring Big Brother to big business. ``We're children
of the New Deal,'' explained Marcos Rodriguez-Ema, president of the
government Development Bank for Puerto Rico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More is at stake here than political symbolism, or even the
efficiency of the telephone system. Puerto Rico is under enormous
pressure to hew more closely to the capitalist road, in part
because it is losing special tax breaks and welfare subsidies from
Washington, and in part because no island can remain an island in
the increasingly integrated global economy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of whether the Puerto Rican economy will
change, but how and when,'' said Jose Berrocal, a director of BT
Wolfensohn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Telephone Co. uses modern digital switching
equipment and, it is widely agreed, provides good service.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't particularly efficient. The company operated 204
lines per employee in 1996, compared with more than 300 at Bell
Atlantic. The return on capital is far below that of mainland
providers. And ominously, it has rapidly lost share in cellular
phones, the fastest-growing part of the business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when Congress opened local and intra-island telephone service
to competition in 1996, Puerto Rico's government decided to auction
it off. ``Our primary concern is that the managers of the
government enterprise didn't have the vision for a deregulated
market,'' Rodriguez-Ema said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to sell the system to GTE Corp. for $1.85 billion
(challenged at the 11th hour by another bidder, Spain's Telefonica
Internacional) led to a strike by the telephone workers' unions.
Last week, the strike made headlines nationwide when 50 other
Puerto Rican unions staged a two-day sympathy walkout that shut the
airport in San Juan, along with major shopping centers. And polls
show that the strikers enjoy considerable support in their
opposition to the sale of the ``national patrimony.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (According to news reports, one of the two telephone unions will
vote Thursday on ending the strike, though both still oppose
privatization.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a protest against a style of government,'' argued
Heidie Calero, an economic consultant in San Juan who favors
privatization but objects to the government's ``high-handed''
manner in decreeing the sale without bothering to explain the
necessity.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government of Puerto Rico is apparently holding fast to the
decision to sell the phone company _ though the unspecified bid
from Telefonica does put in doubt who will end up with the prize.
And whoever does buy it will likely go partway to relieve the
union's anxiety about job security. ``The buyers will need labor
peace, and they know it,'' Rodriguez-Ema acknowledged. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more formidable challenge, illustrated by the resistance to
telephone privatization, is to shake the economy out of its
dependence on government. While the island's gross domestic product
per capita is one-third that of the mainland, transfers through
Medicaid, Medicare, Social Security and a variety of other social
programs keep living standards within hailing distance. Indeed, a
combination of the social safety net, the application of the
national minimum wage and federal tax breaks for manufacturing keep
competitive wages quite high. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Therein lies a rub. High wages make it difficult for Puerto Rico
to compete with the rest of the Caribbean in both tourism and
labor-intensive products. Unemployment, now at 14 percent, topped
20 percent for much of the 1980s. Yet the tax breaks, which led to
the development of a huge pharmaceutical and electronics
manufacturing sector _ not to mention the creation of tens of
thousands of white-collar jobs _ will be phased out over the next
six years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez-Ema plays down the impact of losing these so-called
Section 936 benefits, which the current, statehood-minded
administration of Puerto Rico viewed as a crutch. ``The
pharmaceutical makers are hiring, not firing,'' he pointed out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is hard to look at economic trends and come up an
unalloyed pessimist. Total employment, below 700,000 as recently as
1985, now hovers around a million. Per capita income is close to
$8,000 and has been growing more rapidly than on the mainland for
several generations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in Berrocal's view, Puerto Rico is at a crossroads. The
welfare state, he acknowledges, has provided good jobs for a
minority and an adequate living standard for the majority. But it
has also robbed the island of the opportunity to break out
economically. And it has created vested interests with a great deal
to lose from change.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The world is not standing still, though, and the repeal of
Section 936 suggests that Congress isn't either. ``We've just got
to declare it isn't going to be business as usual,'' Berrocal
concluded. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
