<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ REPORTS LOSS FOR QUARTER DUE TO DIGITAL ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (rm)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. reported a second-quarter loss of $3.63
billion Wednesday, resulting largely from its acquisition of
Digital Equipment Corp.. But Compaq eked out a tiny operating
profit that beat analysts' expectations of a break-even quarter.
</P>
<P>
   While the quarterly results had few surprises, Compaq, analysts
said, appeared to have made progress at reducing the excess
inventory at distributors and dealers that has eroded earnings in
recent quarters. The challenges now are to maintain sales momentum
amid tough competition and to successfully integrate Digital into
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, based in Houston, said last month that it was closing
six plants overseas and eliminating 5,000 jobs, including 1,000 at
its Houston headquarters. The company is planning to cut 17,000
jobs as it absorbs Digital, and another recent acquisition, Tandem
Computer. The cuts will leave Compaq with a work force of 67,000.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter, Compaq lost $3.63 billion, compared with
earnings of $257 million, or 17 cents a share, fully diluted, in
the quarter a year earlier. Revenue rose 7 percent, to $11.52
billion, from $10.79 billion in the second quarter of 1997. Second
quarter 1998 earnings include charges of $3.63 billion related to
the Digital acquisition; without these charges, Compaq had earnings
for the quarter of $32 million, or 2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts expected the company to break even,
according to a survey by First Call Corp., an investment research
company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Compaq ended down 12.5 cents, at $33.5625, in very
heavy trading on the Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq has struggled to compete with Dell Computer Corp., which
sells direct to customers, builds each computer to order, maintains
very little inventory and thus has lower costs. Last year Compaq
announced it was moving to a build-to-order business model but
retaining the dealer channel, and that it would reduce its
inventory. In the transition to the new model, however, Compaq
flooded the dealer channel with product, leading to a glut of PCs
and fierce price cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made good progress in driving down the inventory
during the quarter, but my sense is it needs to come down a little
further,'' Todd Bakar, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist of San
Francisco, said. He said he was also concerned about ongoing
pricing pressure. ``A lot of the sell-through in the quarter came
with very aggressive pricing and promotions, so you have to ask
what sort of unit growth they can sustain going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq executives said the third quarter would be a transitional
one as the company managed the integration of Digital and worked to
bring that company's cost structure in line with its own. Analysts
noted that at 24 percent of sales, Digital's sales, general and
administrative costs were roughly twice those of Compaq, and would
have to be reduced sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the decisive steps taken to position our products
competitively in commercial channels worldwide and reset goals for
the newly combined companies, we are now moving aggressively to
achieve targeted levels of performance and growth,'' Earl Mason,
Compaq's senior vice president and chief financial officer, said.
``We continue to believe earnings for the combined companies will
be accretive as early as the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
