<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ARTS-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN ARTS FESTIVAL MAKES FUSION ITS FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAHAMSTOWN, South Africa _ Africa's premier arts festival, 24
years old this year, is having a little trouble defining itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Grahamstown Festival, which ended July 12, was founded as a
fortress of the English language when professors of English and
politicians feared that the Afrikaner nationalists in power would
subsume their tongue. It started life as a Shakespeare festival,
but now presents the country's _ and sometimes the continent's _
best in jazz, classical music, film, theater, opera, dance and
visual art.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the fastest-growing festival in South Africa is
the much smaller, four-year-old Oudtshoorn Festival, in an
ostrich-farming town not far away. It was founded to celebrate the
Afrikaans language, which Afrikaners fear will fade away. The
government is slowly but steadily removing it from official
documents, army marching orders and the national airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel threatened, especially when they see Afrikaans
taken off television,'' said Karen Meiring, the coordinator of the
Oudtshoorn festival, who was visiting its larger rival. Her
festival is trying hard to appeal to mixed-race ``coloreds,'' most
of whom speak Afrikaans as a first language.
</P>
<P>
   And a small festival of Sotho-language work is planned for
September.
</P>
<P>
   Balkanization of the arts isn't a serious threat because
virtually every educated person speaks English. That leaves
Grahamstown more grand dame than guerrilla, but it clearly reigns,
with 400 works performed up to 5 times each in 11 days.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, it was at its hottest in the 1980s when it was
full of anti-apartheid theater. The police attended plays but never
shut any down in this remote town around Rhodes University, where
white liberals could be left to shout slogans at each other. That
way the government that banned books and censored newspapers could
boast that free speech was alive.
</P>
<P>
   In attendance, Grahamstown's biggest year was 1996. Now there is
a sense that the festival, lacking the camaraderie produced by
linguistic or political threats, is groping for a theme.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's artists are sick of the question: What are you
going to write about now that apartheid is dead?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the answer has been emerging for a while. Formerly
taboo subjects like gay and lesbian love are common. Crime, in a
country where political violence has given way to hijacking, murder
and rape, is a popular topic. And last year there were two major
dramas about the Truth and Reconciliation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But the theme clearly on the rise is the one the festival had
hoped would emerge: the tentative fusion of two very disparate
South African cultures _ black and white.
</P>
<P>
   There were always such possibilities _ jazz, for instance, where
whites and blacks have long played together. And in dance there is
an interesting phenomenon: white South African ballet companies
always had plenty of female dancers but few males, while black
township troupes were almost strictly for men. Now the two are
beginning to fuse.
</P>
<P>
   And the fusion theme has been explored in new South African
movies. In one darkly funny film, ``Sexy Girls,'' a white man
trying to kill himself with exhaust fumes is kidnapped from a
``colored'' neighborhood by a girl gang that needs his car to
escape a shootout.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger budget film, ``Letting Go,'' features a black South
African woman who grew up in Los Angeles and returns to South
Africa, where she learns about her roots from a ``white Zulu,'' a
hunky anthropologist born deep in Zululand who not only dances but
also rescues her in a stick fight from the overbearing Zulu prince
who wants to marry her. Unfortunately, the movie quickly
degenerates into a mawkish travelogue with lines like, ``That's the
real Africa that I love,'' and overt plugs for soft drinks and
hotels that underwrote the film.
</P>
<P>
   In theater, Aubrey Sekhabi, an emerging young black playwright,
twisted the audience's expectations by writing a grim drama in
which four young black professionals catch a desperately poor
Afrikaner burglarizing their house during a bachelor party and
debate whether to treat him as they would once have been treated:
beat him to death.
</P>
<P>
   But the festival's most coveted ticket was to ``Ipi Zombi?'' by
Brett Bailey and his Third World Bunfight troupe, a musical so far
off Broadway that it is conducted around a fire in an abandoned
power station before an audience squatting on milk crates.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is a young white South African given a grant by Standard
Bank, the festival's chief sponsor, to build a theater troupe in
Grahamstown's black township. Before that, festival participation
by blacks in the area was limited to guarding parked cars, waiting
tables and singing and dancing on street corners for pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's first production of ``Ipi Zombi?,'' in 1996, had 60
actors, including a chorus of 20 and 5 sangomas, the health
professionals formerly known as witch doctors. He has now cut his
traveling Bunfight to 15 actors, the number that can pack into a
minibus and his pickup.
</P>
<P>
   His text comes from a real 1995 event. Twelve schoolboys were
killed in a bus crash, and a rumor spread that 50 naked witches
beside the road had caused it. Mass hysteria spread, like that
during the witch trials in Salem, Mass., and in the next three
months two local women were ``sniffed out'' as witches and
murdered; many more were forced to flee. The boys' friends halted
their funerals, saying their spirits were walking the earth as
zombies. The killings only ended when the bodies were chopped up to
release their souls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bailey-Bunfight production led to a tempest in the
festival's in-house paper, which is produced by Rhodes University
journalism students, but dragoons the country's top critics into
writing and editing.
</P>
<P>
   The first review called it ``a work of genius.'' An angry
response from a critic for The Sowetan called Bailey a racist, and
wrote, ``If you are into seeing black people portrayed like savage
morons tinseled with calabash boobs and a dance on a coffin, then
go ahead, indulge.'' A Rhodes student counterattacked, calling the
play ``a true picture of African spirituality.'' Because
professional theater in this country was long made by whites for
white critics, the paper's editors were relieved to have three
black critics in the fight, which then split along a new South
African schism, urban black sensibilities versus rural ones.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who speaks perfectly rationally although he appears for
interviews with an orange fright wig atop his shaved head, shrugged
off the dispute, saying: ``We live in an ideological minefield. No
matter what step you take, you get into conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he added, ``the festival's Young Artist of the Year is
a black guy working with white classics, and he's being hailed.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to Bongani Ndodana, a 22-year-old classical
composer whose oratorio ``Uhambo: The Pilgrimage'' was one of the
festival's most heavily publicized events. Ndodana's work was based
on the epic poem ``Pilgrimage to Dias Cross'' by Guy Butler, the
80-year-old professor of English at Rhodes University who founded
the festival. It mixes images from 400 years of Grahamstown
history, including the stone cross erected in 1488 by Portuguese
navigator Bartholomeu Dias and the apocalyptic visions of
15-year-old Nongqause, the Joan of Arc of the Xhosa, a tribe whose
dreams of driving out British settlers led disastrously to the
Great Cattle Killing of 1857, which destroyed the Xhosa nation.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, for its 25th anniversary, the festival will take
fusion even further, lengthening its run to two weeks and spending
a bigger budget to bring in artists from all over Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1939EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
