<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUNS-BOS &LR;      07-15 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALLAS, KHRISTICH, TAYLOR COULD BE HEADED FOR ARBITRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ Bruins goalie Rob Tallas and forwards Dmitri
Khristich and Tim Taylor have elected to file for arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   If the players, who gave up their Group 2 restricted free-agent
status to file, can't come to an agreement before their hearing
dates next month, an arbiter will decide how much they will make
next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed three players today,'' said Bruins president-general
manager Harry Sinden. ``We just don't know for how much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said assistant GM Mike O'Connell plans to take another
stab at reaching an agreement with Taylor, and that Taylor was just
protecting himself by filing. Two other players, Steve Heinze and
Ted Donato, were also eligible to file. Donato opted not to and
Sinden said he hadn't heard about Heinze as of late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' history with arbitration has proven to be a mixed
bag. Ray Bourque filed prior to the start of the 1993-94 season and
found out on opening night that he had lost. Since then, the Bruins
have had a reputation as being a formidable opponent in arbitration
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you talk to Al Iafrate, he might have a different
perspective,'' said Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   Iafrate is one of the few who has beaten Boston in arbitration;
he was subsequently traded to San Jose for Jeff Odgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hit-or-miss when you get a third party deciding your
affairs,'' Sinden said. ``They can't evaluate a player in terms of
his value to the team except through statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and their agents use a comparable theory method when
trying to formulate their demands. For example, if Player A thinks
he's as good as Player B from another team and Player C from a
third team, he will use that formula to come up with a salary
demand. Sinden said the Bruins won't do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't dare base it on comparables,'' he said. ``Or we'd be
broke like the other 25 teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he'd be open to discussing a resolution before the
hearings in any of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always open to that,'' he said. ``One thing is we've
made up our mind we're not going to run away from arbitration. Too
many people in the league fold before arbitration. The teams either
give them what they want or they compromise for a little less than
what they think the arbitrator is going to give them. We've done
our homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said this season may represent a high for potential
arbitration cases with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it reflects what the players think the market is and
what the agents think the market is, and what they think they can
get through arbitration,'' he said. ``But this is not a giveaway
stop on the way through their careers. If they want a giveaway
stop, they'd better not stop at 617. We're not going to give it
away without a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Donato's attorney, Mark Witkin, said he plans to get together
with the Bruins soon to discuss his client's status with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's in our mutual interests that he play a lot,
whether it be in Boston or somewhere else,'' said Witkin.
``Sometime soon we'll sit down with the Bruins. I think it's in
everyone's best interest to keep talking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
