<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMBURG-BALLET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMBURG BALLET: WAR'S SORROW AND THE JOY OF FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Hamburg Ballet from Germany, which made its
Manhattan debut on Tuesday night with a crop of striking young
dancers as part of Lincoln Center Festival '98, is essentially a
creative outlet for its American director, John Neumeier.
</P>
<P>
   As a choreographer, Neumeier is hardly an unknown. Many of his
ballets have been seen here in American and foreign companies,
including American Ballet Theater. The Hamburg Ballet, which he has
directed since 1973, performed at the Brooklyn Academy of Music in
1983 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, his works have been more popular in Europe than in
the United States; he is, one suspects, a choreographer who wants
less to count to the music than to ``feel'' it, to quote Antony
Tudor. Americans have not always shared his taste for the kind of
symphonic-philosophical ballet that is his signature.
</P>
<P>
   But sensibilities and even choreographers can change. This first
of two programs, enthusiastically received at the New York State
Theater, was devoted to Neumeier's favorite composer, Gustav
Mahler, and it showed the choreographer in firmer command than ever
of an expressive vocabulary. ``Soldier Songs,'' the shortest
ballet, is especially strong in its emotional impact and was
exceedingly well led by Rose Gad and Lloyd Riggins.
</P>
<P>
   The company itself looked fabulous, thanks to an international
influx of highly trained classical dancers (including Americans).
Some come from the Royal Danish Ballet and the Kirov Ballet and
some, recruited as winners in the Prix de Lausanne Ballet
Competition in Switzerland, have been groomed by Neumeier to
project a clear individuality and distinctive fluency.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Hamburg Ballet's last visit to New York in 1985,
Neumeier has choreographed seven of Gustav Mahler's symphonies: the
Brooklyn Academy seasons included his ballets to the third, fourth
and sixth. The last included film clips from ``Gone With the
Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   The current program, entitled ``All Our Yesterdays,'' begins
with ``Soldier Songs,'' choreographed to 10 of the songs Mahler set
to folk poetry from the ``Wunderhorn'' anthology, and is completed
by ``The Fifth Symphony.''
</P>
<P>
   The link between the two ballets is tenuous, but the anti-war
images of ``Songs'' are occasionally recapitulated in the first two
movements of the symphonic ballet, and the occasional soldier from
the first work is seen passing through the second.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, Neumeier uses whatever program content exists in
the music as a springboard for his own scenario. Created in 1989,
both pieces are related to political events, according to
Neumeier's program note. World War II, which began in 1939, is
remembered 50 years later in ``Soldier Songs,'' with its images of
generic soldiers (no side indicated) in battle and in death,
mourned by women left behind. ``The Fifth Symphony'' ends with a
marvelous jumble of dancers in white tunics and tights (posing
casually or raised high in staggered lifts) that Neumeier relates
to the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this scene recalls the jubilation in Berlin. The program
note, ``The opening of borders and boundaries inspired the ballet's
end _ endless movement!,'' conveys the striking tone that follows
the somber first two movements and the ensuing pas de deux.
Neumeier originally choreographed it for Natalia Makarova and Erik
Bruhn at Ballet Theater in 1975, to Mahler's over-played Adagietto
from this symphony (``Death in Venice'').
</P>
<P>
   That duet in the fourth movement is now danced with a muscular
plasticity by Anna Polikarpova, a statuesque dancer once with the
Kirov, and Otto Bubenicek, who like his twin, Jiri Bubenicek in
``Soldier Songs,'' exhibits a dynamic quality that shows him
plunging into the movement and partnering with finesse. At the end,
Ms. Polikarpova lay arched over her partner's lap, her head resting
on the floor. The Ballet Theater version looked more refined and
elegiac, but the sensuality and passion of the Hamburg dancers work
on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   The conductor Klauspeter Seibel (Marin Alsop will conduct the
Mahler program later in the week) gave Mahler's rambling Fifth
Symphony the swirl and contrast that dancers require. Anna Grabka,
Laura Cazzaniga and Joelle Boulogne led a mainly female corps in
the first movement before the ensemble in the second and third
broke up into couples. Ivan Urban and Heather Jurgensen (once with
New York City Ballet) exhibited the new fluency, full of spiraling
configurations, that colors Neumeier's brand of neoclassicism.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its use of toe work, the effectiveness of ``Soldier
Songs'' stems from a fusion of ballet and modern dance idioms.
Starting a bit simplistically with its marching soldiers and women
in white frocks, giggling over a panel serving as a fence, the
ballet gains in emotional intensity. One remembers Urban's
passionate dancing, and the flow in the formal structure as the men
lie down one by one to die. There is the way Gad slips to the floor
and lies prostrate after Riggins exits and ends their tender and
shattering duet. Yvi Janicke and Dietrich Henschel were the fine
singers in a moving ballet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
