<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADAM-THEATER-REVIEW-N     07-15 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADAM-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ADAM RESURRECTED': ONE MAN'S DILEMMA _ PERFORM OR DIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The show must go on, even in a death camp. Adam
Stein, formerly a Berlin circus star, is ordered to perform for the
concentration camp commandant. Told to play a clown, he plays a
clown. Ordered to impersonate a dog, he does that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a Jew won't do,'' the commandant sneers, ``for a bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowd-pleasing acts of humiliation are what the degraded,
taunting Nazi is after in ``Adam Resurrected,'' a lavishly
hallucinatory rendering, by the Gesher Theater from Israel, of one
man's Holocaust odyssey, from a sheltered existence as a popular
German entertainer to his postwar confinement in an Israeli
psychiatric hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Subtlety is not the Gesher's strong suit: to illustrate the
depth of Adam's moral dilemma, for example, the director, Yevgeny
Arye, has him walk a tightrope that extends the length of the
stage. And yet, overall, the company's treatment of this dense and
abstracted material, adapted from a 1968 novel by the Israeli
author Yoram Kaniuk, is frequently ingenious and occasionally
inspired. Staged in an air-conditioned tent adjacent to the
Metropolitan Opera House, the nearly three-hour production is a
wildly evocative excursion through the three houses of the absurd
in which Adam spends much of his life: a circus, a concentration
camp and an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The three staging grounds are reflections of aspects of Adam's
tortured psyche, where, in a sense, all of ``Adam Resurrected''
takes place. It is not a play told in conventional style, but
through the re-creation of the kind of interior narrative everyone
composes in the course of their lives, that highly personal
assortment of analytical musings, warm and traumatic memories and
recurring nightmares, that amount to a running existential
conversation with some idea of God.
</P>
<P>
   What gives order to this chaotically conceived life story are
the difficult ethical issues posed by the novelist and his adapter,
Alexander Chervinsky. After the terrible complicity forced upon him
in the camp, where he entertained the inmates, including his own
wife, as they were herded into gas chambers, can a man like Adam
reclaim his humanity? Is he worth the time and attentions of a
nation filled with so many victims of less dubious standing?
</P>
<P>
   Arye's central image for the joyless events of ``Adam
Resurrected,'' presented as part of Lincoln Center Festival '98, is
that of the circus ring, which may not be the most original
metaphor, but it is nonetheless useful here in releasing the
Gesher's creative energy. Through the center of the ring,
inventively realized by Elena Stepanova, runs a set of railroad
tracks onto which the troupe places the rolling stock of props,
from hospital beds, prison cells and animal cages, to Adam's
performance platforms and the Nazi officer's black leather couch.
The tracks, of course, are also a monument to death, the skeletal
remains of the cattle cars that transported millions of Jews to the
camps.
</P>
<P>
   The production, in Hebrew with simultaneous English translation,
is a panorama of oppressiveness. Nazis in black patent-leather
raincoats and fishnet stockings, performing innocent-sounding
novelty numbers about springtime in the Fatherland and, even more
menacingly, cutting off granny's long braids, are refugees from the
Kit Kat Klub; the nod to ``Cabaret'' in general and Sam Mendes'
outrageous revival in particular, seems conscious, even if it
isn't. The Jews, meanwhile, wear the faded stripes of the camps,
whether they are inmates of the camp or the Israeli hospital, where
the patients are under the pathetically misguided delusion that
Adam is the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   Adam, played vigorously by Igor Mirkurbanov _ the vibrant Gesher
Theater, a seven-year-old company, is made up primarily of Russian
Israelis _ vaults from country to country and era to era on the
high-flying trapeze and other apparatus that Arye and Ms. Stepanova
supply. Mirkurbanov, sleek and agile, wanders pitiful and
ashen-faced across the landscape of his own life (he begins the
play in clown's makeup), unsure whether his fate is to be counted
among the Nazis' martyred victims or their soulless collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of ambiguity, he turns for advice to the play's most
bizarre character, Mrs. Seizling, a garish American Jew portrayed
in drag by the excellent Vladimir Halemsky. Having given $6 million
to the psychiatric hospital in memory of the six million dead, she
is anything but conflicted over the Holocaust. For now that she,
too, is dead, she is hoping that the donation will make her a
favorite when the Messiah does return.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Seizling, who pops up in the strangest places, is a
touchstone figure, the real clown of ``Adam Resurrected,'' and the
embodiment of the most trivial aspects of Holocaust
memorialization. The play itself, however, never sinks to
triviality. A smart and empathetic ensemble, led by Mirkurbanov and
also featuring other such expressive performers as Israel (Sasha)
Demidov, Yevgenya Dodina and Nelly Gosheva, brings a deep sense of
passion and commitment to this mini-epic under the big top. And
they effortlessly surmount barriers of culture and language that
could have made a mess of this extreme and ambitious material.
</P>
<P>
   Some playgoers may be put off by the overwrought qualities in
the writing and the stagecraft. But given the subject matter, it's
hard not to forgive a theater company, forged in the Jewish
homeland by Russian refugees, for going overboard now and again.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ADAM RESURRECTED'
</P>
<P>
   By Alexander Chervinsky; based on the novel by Yoram Kaniuk;
directed by Yevgeny Arye; assistant director, Elena Krendlin; sets
and costumes by Elena Stepanova; music by Avi Benjamin
(Nedzvetsky); lighting by Niv Sade; choreography by Valentine
Menuhin; stage manager, Tatyana Suchanova; company manager, Victor
Sokolov. Gesher Theater. Presented by Lincoln Center Festival '98.
At Damrosch Park.
</P>
<P>
   With: Igor Mirkurbanov (Adam Stein), Yevgenya Dodina (Gretchen
Stein), Maria Gamburg (Ruth Stein), Israel (Sascha) Demidov
(Commandant Klein and Dr. Gross), Vladimir Halemsky (Mrs.
Seizling), Nelly Gosheva (Elder Schwester) and Natalia
Voltulevich-Manor (Fraulein Klopfer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
