<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-SENECA-BOS &LR;      07-15 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SENECA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
150TH ANNIVERSARY OF WOMEN'S RIGHTS MOVEMENT OBSERVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SENECA FALLS, N.Y. _ Change is an infrequent visitor to Seneca
Falls, but it makes a very big statement when it comes.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet, close-knit village has had its days on the short-end
of history _ engineers, seeking a better water route to the Erie
Canal, flooded the river valley in 1915, submerging some 200
factories and homes and Seneca's namesake falls.
</P>
<P>
   And in its vanguard. For it was here that five uppity
housewives, led by displaced Bostonian Elizabeth Cady Stanton,
called the nation's first women's rights convention in 1848 at the
Wesleyan Methodist Chapel in Seneca Falls.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when ladies were seen but rarely spoke out in public,
when social mores were as constricting as the tight corsets they
wore, the women stood before a hastily assembled audience and
bitterly recited what men's tyranny had denied them: education;
employment; property; citizenship; legal standing in divorce in
custody; a role in the church; and the vote. They demanded equality
``because women do feel themselves aggrieved, oppressed, and
fraudulently deprived of their most sacred rights,'' and they
launched a suffrage movement that took 70 years to enfranchise
American women.
</P>
<P>
   July 16 is the 150th anniversary of that historic meeting as
well as the Declaration of Rights and Sentiments it ratified. First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, joined by a host of dignitaries, will
speak at Seneca Falls, opening up a four-day festival of women's
achievements that promises to swell and swamp this
spit-and-polished village (pop. 7,600) and its lovingly maintained
historic sites with 100,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The commemoration is also a reminder that so much of what both
genders now take for granted _ from the professions to the playing
fields, to politics and the pulpit _ started out with some
scandalous talk around a mahogany tea table in central New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every anniversary has been a touchstone, a time for
individuals and groups to reconnect to the tradition of radicalism
that is so well represented here,'' said Vivien Rose, historian at
the Women's Rights National Historical Park, one of those sites.
``It's a time to reflect on the condition of women in society and
plan how to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The moment comes at an intriguing time for the women's movement.
A cover story in Time magazine recently asked the question ``Is
Feminism Dead?'' Women's rights groups, preoccupied with abortions
fights and distracted by gay rights, seem to be searching for
relevance and strugglng to make their case to stressed out soccer
moms and as well as those single, 20-something women for whom
feminism seems a dated or even a dirty word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our foremothers would be delighted with the work we've done in
furthering their dream,'' Eleanor Smeal, a former president of the
National Organization for Women, told a boisterous NOW rally
outside the restored Wesleyan Chapel Tuesday, ``but they would be
disgusted that women still don't have full equality under the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of modern-day feminism say the women's movement has
achieved most of its goals _ and certainly, they say, it's good to
have the vote _ but at the terrible cost of undermining marriages,
forcing women to work, and denigrating motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This enormous social experiment to make women legally and
economically equal to men has not resulted in a net increase in
women's happiness,'' said Danielle Crittenden, editor of the
conservative Women's Quarterly. ``We have simply replaced one set
of problems with a new set of problems that arise from freedom and
equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Seneca Falls isn't a bad place to ask how well this social
experiment has worked. It's largely an Italian community,
traditional in its values, heavily Roman Catholic, almost
completely white, and solidly middle class. Republicans run the
all-male village board, right-to-life groups years ago drove the
Planned Parenthood office out of town, and, until the
preservationists got a hold of it, the Wesleyan Chapel, birthplace
of the women's movement, was a laundromat.
</P>
<P>
   But it also a community where, as in much of America, the social
and legal gains of women are thoroughly woven into local life.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, lured by the town's awesome history but not
sure how warm the welcome would be, Becky Bly moved to Seneca
Falls. She runs a company, Woman-Made Products, as well as the
Coalition for Lesbian Visibility. Tuesday morning, she instructed
her teenaged daughter on her constitutional right to distribute
fliers for Woman-Made Products at the NOW rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Long Island, people used to break my windows because I was
a lesbian,'' Bly said. ``Here, they may gossip behind my back, but
mostly they just let me be.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Caraccilo, the village barber, sits outside on the stoop,
waiting for customers who probably aren't going to fight the
unusual congestion on Fall Street for a haircut. Until Seneca Falls
became the American mecca for feminist pilgrims, he hadn't thought
much about the women's movement or its impact on his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I say _ holy smoke! _ would my wife have retired with a
pension, would may daughter have been an All-American soccer
player, if those women hadn't started it all right here in Seneca
Falls?'' Caraccilo asks. ``I've gotta believe it's a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob's nephew, Fran Caraccilo, is the village planner. Fran's
wife, Gail, is president of the local Elizabeth Cady Stanton
Foundation, which raised $50,000 to purchase and restore the white,
frame farmhouse that belonged to Cady Stanton _ a frustrated
intellectual who raised seven small children on 150 acres downwind
from the mills while her husband, Henry, was off spreading
anti-slavery zeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here,'' Fran Caraccilo said, ``wasn't luck or an
accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Seneca Falls was much more than a rail, water, and
turnpike hub and one of the nation's fastest-growing manufacturing
towns in the mid-nineteenth century. It also was boiling in the
cauldron of reform fervor that was unique to central New York _ a
potent mix of religious revivalists, temperance preachers, utopian
visionaries, and impassioned abolitionists. Add to that Quaker
communities and local Iroquois tribes, both with traditions of
equality for women, and the table was set for a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Literally. Over tea with Lucretia Mott, a Quaker and antislavery
activist from Philadelphia; Martha Coffin Wright, Mott's sister;
Mary Ann McClintock; and Jane Hunt, of nearby Waterloo, Stanton
``poured out...the torrent of my long-accumulating discontent with
such vehemence and indignation that I stirred myself, as well as
the rest of the party, to do and dare anything,'' she later wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary idea to hold a women's rights convention was
hatched that afternoon. In a little over a week, the women not only
persuaded 300 people, including some 40 men, to meet for two days
at the chapel, but they also produced a blistering feminist
manifesto modeled on the Declaration of Independence that accused
men of ``endeavoring to destroy (a woman's) confidence in her own
powers, to lessen her self-respect, and to make her willing to lead
and a dependent and abject life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratifying the declaration turned out to be the easy part, though
it took a persuasive speech by Rochester newspaper publisher
Frederick Douglass, a former slave, to pass the very controversial
suffrage resolution. What followed was public ridicule and abuse of
Cady Stanton, who only later was joined by the more famous
suffragist, Susan B. Anthony. It became so intense that Cady
Stanton stopped wearing the loose-fitting pantaloons popularized by
Amelia Bloomer, another Seneca Falls sister.
</P>
<P>
   The suffragists moved on from Seneca Falls and so did the
industrial boom. The village lost sight of its rich heritage until
the late 1970s, and even then there was a good deal of debate about
whether designating a historic district, creating a Women's Hall of
Fame, or letting the federal government build a $12 million
monument to the women's movement made much sense.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Barbieri, associate director of the Seneca Falls
Historical Society, is an advocate. Her wake-up call as a woman
came years ago, she said, when her dream of attending the
University of Notre Dame was shattered by what was then a
single-sex rule. The 150th anniversary, Barbieri said, ``has been a
wake-up call to the community for anybody who still asks 'why would
anybody come to Seneca Falls?'''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration has posed certain challenges for a small town.
Among them: food, drink, and toilets for 100,000, and finding 120
pairs of white sneakers for the entire Seneca Falls Youth Chorus,
which is singing ``It Takes a Village'' for the First Lady. And
then there was a bit of political theatre after New York Lt. Gov.
Betsy McCaughey Ross, the state's highest-ranking woman
office-holder, found she had not been invited to share the
opening-ceremony stage today with Mrs. Clinton and New York Gov.
George Pataki. (McGaughey Ross hopes to unseat Pataki in the fall
elections.)
</P>
<P>
   For Maria Granger, the local commotion is worth the price. A
stay-at-home mother, Granger visited the Women's Rights Historical
Park for the first time last week, and she took her three young
daughters with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my girls to know that there are some reasons why they
have rights and choices,'' Granger said. ``Living here in Seneca
Falls, it's not something you should take for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
