<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-SCHOOLS-ART-80     07-15 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-SCHOOLS-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL FINDS WORKERS' LACK OF EDUCATION HAMPERING ECONOMY, GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `f' category) 
(ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(JT) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACAJUS, Brazil _ When Antonio Gomes da Silva found school a
bore at age 11, there was no grown-up within hollering distance
urging him to stay. Not the grandfather rearing him, who raised
cattle and saw little use for grammar. Not the father who abandoned
him and went to live in Sao Paulo, 2,000 miles away. Not the mother
left behind years earlier when his parents separated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If just one adult had said to me, `No, don't drop out, you
need an education,' it would have changed my life,'' Gomes da Silva
said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 15 years since, the landscape in northeastern Brazil
_ traditionally the poorest, most precarious swatch of this diverse
country, which is bigger than the continental United States _ has
begun to change, with subsistence farms giving way to factories.
And in the lightning switch from ox carts to the post-industrial
age, survival for workers like Gomes da Silva, a supervisor at a
box factory, depends on hitting the books to make up for lost time.
</P>
<P>
   Along with 30 other employees of Rigesa, the Brazilian
subsidiary of the Westvaco Corp., the paper company based in New
York, Gomes da Silva now spends five nights a week in voluntary
classes learning the basics of reading, geography and mathematics.
A blue jeans factory owned by Vicunha Ltda., a large Brazilian
textile manufacturer, that sits across the street from Rigesa also
sponsors elementary school classes, as do the other concerns in the
Pacajus industrial park, some 25 miles from the Ceara state
capital, Fortaleza. It is all part of a tax-incentive package the
state government offered to industry to create jobs outside large
urban areas in places like this, a city of some 37,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Though the contrast between old and new is starkest here in
Brazil's dusty northeast, the same shift is being played out across
the country, from Sao Paulo to Rio Grande do Sul, where the opening
of the world's eighth-biggest economy is expected to lure $17
billion in direct foreign investment this year _ the highest of any
emerging market. Foreigners are buying up state-owned industries,
and putting their money in everything from car factories to
pharmaceutical subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   But companies investing in Brazil are finding that severe
shortcomings in the educational system, and the poverty that forced
many workers to quit school early, hamper productivity and efforts
at quality control. And as factories come to rely more on advanced,
computer-controlled machines, they need fewer workers, but more
capable ones: workers who can read the screens and make sense of
what they see.
</P>
<P>
   A wide-ranging 1997 study of industry in Brazil found overall
productivity running at 27 percent of the United States level, with
even the more advanced sectors, like the automobile industry, only
30 percent as productive as in the United States and 21 percent as
productive as in Japan, the best in the industry. The report, by
the McKinsey Global Institute in Washington in conjunction with its
Sao Paulo office, largely blamed Brazil's protectionist legacy and
business' lack of reinvestment. But it noted that workers in Brazil
had an average of six years of schooling, compared with 11 to 13
years in Korea and Japan, and encouraged companies to invest in
basic education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to Asia, it's a disaster,'' said Riordan Roett,
chairman of the Latin American studies program at the Johns Hopkins
University School of Advanced International Studies. ``In terms of
globalization and competitiveness, education and job training are
absolutely critical, and Brazil falls way behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the lack of investment in basic education,'' Roett
continued, ``that is holding, and will hold, Brazil back.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The American Chamber of Commerce in Brazil, which began focusing
on education early in the decade, found that the average worker in
the Sao Paulo area had only a fourth-grade education. And the
quality of even that level of schooling was open to question.
</P>
<P>
   Through diagnostic tests, the chamber found that 90 percent of
newly qualified primary school teachers had mastered barely 10
percent of the required curriculum, ``which meant the perpetuation
of the problem,'' said Silvio Tichauer, who runs the organization's
Institute for Quality of Teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber is now putting together a 50-volume, 15,000-page
``School Kit,'' for the continuous remedial instruction of teachers
in Brazil. It also runs educational programs and has introduced
standardized tests, a novelty in Brazil, at five primary and
secondary schools in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had instances where we've wanted to start up
computer-controlled machines, and we've found workers have a
tremendous lack in logic and mathematical skills that we had to
supplement with our own specific training,'' said Tichauer,
executive manager in Brazil for the FMC Corp., the food packager
based in Chicago. Tichauer, who is based in Sao Paulo, added, ``If
it's bad here, it's probably worse everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses are doing the same. Banco Bradesco S.A., a
major Brazilian bank, finances nearly 50 primary and secondary
school classes for workers and children scattered around the
country. Fiat S.p.A., the Italian car maker, which built a factory
in Minas Gerais state a few years ago, has had to open classes as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Guilherme Reis, president of the National Council of Industries,
based in Rio de Janeiro, said the longstanding government failure
to supply decent public education and health care has increased the
burden on industry, raising the price of doing business in Brazil
beyond the legendary ``Brazil cost,'' which covers excessively high
financing costs, fees for the use of ports and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Brazil, beyond the taxes you pay, you have to pay more, a
kind of hidden charge, for education in areas where public services
fall short,'' Reis said.
</P>
<P>
   While John Mein, president of the American Chamber of Commerce
in Brazil, said that companies were not yet avoiding the country
because of the low level of education, Reis said that a ``large
share'' of the industries his council surveyed ``expect to have
problems in a few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McMahon, the president of Rigesa, is among those who see
difficulties on the horizon. ``As we modernize our mill and box
plants, the equipment is much more sophisticated,'' he said. ``The
whole logic will be based on computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's president, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, who is running
for re-election in October, spent the early part of his four-year
term focusing largely on privatizing government-owned industries
and opening Brazil to foreign investment. Efforts to shore up
education began only in the latter part of his term. The government
has taken steps to force municipalities and states, which are
responsible for primary and secondary school education, to spend a
minimum of about $260 a year for each student in the classroom, up
from $208 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, however, the problem has not been primarily a lack
of money. Though Brazil has spent nearly 20 percent of the federal
budget on education, among the highest levels in the world, money
has not bought quality. Only one in three students finish the
eighth grade in Brazil, compared with two out of three in Bolivia,
which spends two-thirds less than Brazil on education.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the investment in education is one whose benefits may
take a decade or more to appear. And critics say the showcase of
the government drive to improve education _ installing televisions
and computers in each school _ overlooks the core of the problem,
which is poor teacher training. In regions like the northeast,
public school teachers typically earn $50 a month, less than half
the legally established minimum salary.
</P>
<P>
   David Fleischer, a political science professor at the University
of Brasilia, who writes a newsletter called Brazil Focus, said
televisions and computers ``are nice, but in a lot of these
schools, the teacher has a second-grade education, at best.''
</P>
<P>
   Tichauer was blunter still. ``More than half of those TV sets or
computers are just gathering dust,'' he said. ``If you don't have
someone in the schools who's going to be helping the school use
these tools, it ain't going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 30 percent of the entire education budget is
earmarked for public universities, according to government
statistics. That, said Roett of Johns Hopkins, comes at the expense
of primary education and reinforces the country's already heavily
skewed distribution of income. Unless students come from families
that can pay for private primary and high schools, they are
unlikely to gain admission to the best universities, which are
public.
</P>
<P>
   When it started operations in Pacajus nearly three years ago,
Rigesa demanded an eighth-grade education for the 160 or so jobs it
was offering, most paying the minimum wage of $110 a month. But it
quickly had to lower its requirement to the fifth-grade level. The
company has spent about $50,000 here on its educational program,
which relies on videotapes developed by a Brazilian television
network to teach the courses and a ``facilitator'' to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
