<HEADER>
A6997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-MILITARY-SEX-6     07-15 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MILITARY-SEX-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAPE REPORTS SHAKE MORALE OF CANADA ARMED FORCES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ When Judith Taylor of Toronto marched into a
recruiting station last month to enlist in the Canadian Army, she
simply ignored a flurry of recent news reports that women in the
army had been sexually harassed and even raped by fellow soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm strong-minded,'' Ms. Taylor, 22, said, ``and things like
that don't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   But reports about sexual assaults at gunpoint and a widespread
acceptance of crude behavior toward women in the military have
upset many Canadians, including the country's top soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been deeply embarrassed and disappointed by these
cases,'' the armed forces Chief of Staff, Gen. Maurice Baril, wrote
in an open letter to military officers. ``Canadians demand a higher
standard of behavior from members in uniform, and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   The reports are just the latest scandal in recent years _
including the death of a Somali teen-ager in 1994 at the hands of
Canadian peacekeepers in Somalia _ that have shaken the morale of
the 60,000-member military and increased concerns about the cost of
maintaining a peacetime force.
</P>
<P>
   The sexual assaults were first reported in May in a series of
articles in MacLean's, a national news magazine. After the articles
were published, other women, including Ann Margaret Dickey, 25, of
Gagetown, New Brunswick, came forward with their accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dickey said she was raped at gunpoint in 1996 by two
officers in her first week of basic training. She said her
superiors had confined her to barracks and ordered her not to
report the attack to the military police.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has gone public with the accusations, however, she
said the army is trying to undermine her credibility. ``They're out
to prove that I'm lying,'' Ms. Dickey said in a telephone interview
from her home. ``The military has lost its honor. I'm embarrassed
to say I was a member of the Canadian armed forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dickey, who had served 18 months in the Army Reserve before
enlisting in the regular force and entering basic training, said
that after she talked to reporters last month in Ottawa about her
assault, the army released her medical files, which she said
included false information about her mental state. She is asking
the Royal Canadian Mounted Police to investigate her case.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the army, Capt. Alain Bissonnette, refused to
comment on Ms. Dickey's statements, except to say the military was
investigating them.
</P>
<P>
   Although many soldiers have called the MacLean's articles about
rape in the military unfair and inaccurate, other soldiers have
said they were not surprised that such abuses occurred because of
officers' pervasive indifference to such concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to the staff, Baril recognized the existence of
such attitudes and lashed out at those who see such harassment as
an inevitable consequence of having women in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not allow the Canadian Forces to become a refuge or a
training ground for thugs and brutes,'' Baril said.
</P>
<P>
   But the general himself now appears to have been caught up in
the accusations. The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation has reported
that the military police are looking into assertions that Baril was
told in 1996 about the sexual harassment of a woman at a military
base in Kingston, Ontario, but did nothing about it. Baril has
refused to comment because the incident is being investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the military police are pursuing 80 sexual
assault complaints, Bissonnette said. The head of the military
police, Col. Patricia Samson, has said the articles about rapes in
the military could lead to many more incidents' being reported.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Maclean's articles vividly described how women had been
raped while serving in the military. A retired air force major, Dee
Brasseur, one of the first Canadian women to become a fighter
pilot, told the magazine that she had been raped and coerced into
having sex with an instructor to advance her career.
</P>
<P>
   For Brasseur, who retired in 1994 after 21 years in the service,
the worst aspect of the harassment was the disillusionment that it
caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something you love betrays you in that fashion,'' she
told the magazine, ``it is the deepest psychological wounding you
can have.''
</P>
<P>
   The military police have reviewed the 26 episodes reported in
Maclean's and have decided to investigate or reopen all but three.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll suggests that most Canadians do not trust the
military to pursue the allegations fully. Only 27 percent of those
polled by The Globe and Mail and CTV television said the armed
forces could adequately investigate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations of sexual abuse are being made just as the
National Defense Forces completed their most ambitious drive yet to
recruit women.
</P>
<P>
   Some 6,800 women serve in the Canadian military, 11 percent of
the regular force. Some 16,000 women are in the reserves, 19
percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor, the new enlistee, is one of more than 300 women who
have applied for entry into combat units since April. But since
most did so before the sexual assault allegations became public, it
is not possible to determine what effects the reports have had on
recruitment, said Michael Whittaker, a civilian spokesman for the
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   While the charges are being investigated, the military has taken
several steps to deal with the problem, including requiring all
armed forces members to go through training to prevent sexual
harassment and setting up a telephone line for soldiers to report
incidents without going through the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain, however, is that the army's reputation has been
tarnished again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one girl at a school say to me, `Am I going to get raped
if I join the army?''' said Capt. Kenneth I. Charles, a military
career counselor with the recruitment center in Toronto who speaks
at job fairs and before university students.
</P>
<P>
   Charles said recruiters responded to such frank questions with
tough, direct answers. ``They say, `It has happened in the past,
and these are the steps we have taken to stop this,''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
