<HEADER>
A6999 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-SENATE-NAT     07-15 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SENATE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        LLOYD NOT EVEN BREAKING EVEN IN FUNDRAISING
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 15 -- While he was laying in a hospital bed
recovering from heart surgery, Sen. Arlen Specter's campaign went
ahead with a gala fundraiser in Philadelphia, attended by 17 Senate
Republicans but not Specter.
</P>
<P>
   In that one early June night, Specter raised more money from his
hospital bed than his opponent, Democrat William Lloyd, did over a
three-month span.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1 to June 30, state Sen. Lloyd, D-Somerset, raised
just $13,674 for his uphill battle to unseat Specter, according to
reports filed Wednesday with the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   All told, Lloyd has raised $46,634, and has just $1,262 left in
his account -- and that's not counting the $60,500 his campaign has
already accrued in debt. Without more money, Lloyd's staff say it
will be difficult to get his message out to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have money coming in drips and drabs,'' said Peter Wiley,
spokesman for Lloyd's campaign. ``(But Lloyd's) not going to give
up. He wants to campaign until he drops.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear exactly how much Specter raised at his June
fundraiser, but Wiley said the senator at least doubled in one
night how much money Lloyd was able to raise in three months.
</P>
<P>
   From April to June, Specter raised $701,174 for his bid to
become Pennsylvania's first four-term senator. That put him over
the $6 million mark for total contributions raised over the last
few years of fundraising for the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Specter has already spent $1.05 million on his
campaign, a lot of money by most measures but a total that his
campaign considers to be barely noticeable. His top aide noted that
Specter did not have many commercials up on the air during the
primary race against a few religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent wisely and cautiously,'' said Kent Gates, Specter's
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said that a few fundraisers were cancelled over the
five-week period of Specter's recuperation. Specter returned to
work last week, and said he will be able to hit full campaign
stride before Labor Day, the traditional kick-off for the most
heated periods of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Even since winning the May primary, Lloyd's campaign has not
been able to pick up any steam as Specter was out of commission. In
what Wiley termed a ``political Catch-22'', he said that
contributors have been reluctant to give money to the fledgling
campaign because he hasn't raised enough money to demonstrate that
he is a viable candidate -- in other words, he needs money to get
money.
</P>
<P>
   But Wiley said Lloyd held a few fundraisers over the July 4th
weekend, money that would not show up on the new FEC reports,
during which he raised about $12,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
