<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ POSTS SMALL SECOND-QUARTER PROFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. put its house in order last quarter, and
is now turning its attention to a bigger challenge: squeezing more
profits out of its newly acquired Digital Equipment Corp. unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston-based computer company posted a small profit before
charges for the second quarter _ more than analysts had expected _
by slashing prices on machines that had clogged distribution
channels since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's operating profit was $32 million, or 2 cents a share,
compared with $465 million, or 30 cents a share, a year ago.
Revenue climbed 5.7 percent to $5.83 billion, which included
Digital sales since the buyout closed on June 11, from $5.52
billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company's earnings were pounded by several factors,
including the slowdown in Asia, pricing cuts, and indications of
slowing PC sales in this country. Nevertheless, operating earnings
were slightly above Wall Street forecasts, which called for Compaq
to break even in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Previously announced one-time costs associated with the Digital
acquisition resulted in a net loss of $3.63 billion, or $2.33 a
share, for the period. The charges included $3.2 billion for the
write-off of technology, $291 million for restructuring related to
job cuts and closing of facilities, and $139 million for other
``operating adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Mason, Compaq's chief financial officer, said the key
challenge last quarter was to clear out excess merchandise that
piled up when corporate demand for PCs slackened, hurting Compaq's
first-quarter earnings. By cutting prices, Compaq succeeded in
reducing its inventory at distributors to 3 1/2 weeks' worth from
as high as 10 in January, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Compaq's earnings received a small, unexpected
boost from Digital's services business, which he said has the
highest backlog of orders in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 33 million Compaq shares were exchanged Wednesday, but
the price didn't move much. That's because Compaq stock had already
been on the rise for weeks. It climbed about 30 percent since the
beginning of the second quarter as the company assured investors
that inventory problems were being addressed. Wednesday, Compaq
fell 1/8 to 339/16, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Compaq's biggest challenge is to smoothly meld
Digital's operations into its own, while wringing out excess costs.
</P>
<P>
   Employees of the former Digital, especially in New England, are
bracing for layoffs and other cutbacks. Compaq has said it will cut
17,000 jobs _ 15,000 of them at Digital _ as it integrates the two
companies' operations. But so far, it has announced only 5,000 cuts
related to the consolidation of its manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the other 12,000 jobs coming from? That's the
biggest issue,'' said Louis Mazzucchelli, a stock analyst with
Gerard Klauer Mattison in New York. ``There's no way to sugarcoat
that, and it's not going to be pretty. But they've got to get that
done sooner rather than later.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason said the remaining job cuts will occur over the next year,
but declined to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzucchelli and other analysts said Compaq will have a tough
job trying to blend Digital's culture into its own while paring
costs in the highly competitive computer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to get back to a growth posture as soon as they can.
And everyone's going to be shooting at them as they become a more
visible target.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
