<HEADLINE>
FLEET, STATE STREET MAKE STRONG SECOND-QUARTER SHOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Lifted by a robust economy and expansion into different
corners of the investment arena, Fleet Financial Group, Inc. and
State Street Corp. reported Wednesday strong second-quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The gains come in a consolidating financial services environment
that is slowly remaking some firms, like Fleet, into one-stop
financial service houses, and positioning others, like State
Street, as overseers of international wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, the nation's 10th largest bank, saw net income soar 13
percent over three months ending in June to $393 million, or $1.29
per diluted share, from $347 million, or $1.17 a share, a year ago.
Much of the growth at New England's largest bank came from its
credit card, mortgage lending, and brokerage businesses _ all areas
in which traditional banks are expanding in order to compete and
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from Fleet's investment services, mainly from its Quick
&AMP; Reilly Group, Inc. discount brokerage, soared 34 percent. Net
interest income nudged up 5 percent, mainly due to Fleet's purchase
of the Advanta Corp. credit card company earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   State Street, a bank-holding company that is mainly a
back-office processor for asset management firms around the world,
said second-quarter earnings rose 18 percent to $108.6 million, or
$0.66 per diluted share, compared with $92.1 million, or $0.56 a
share, in the year-earlier quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It cited heftier fees from its core business of investment
mangagement, record-keeping, accounting, price reporting, and
securities processing. Expenses grew 21 percent to $507 million,
but analysts said the number was justified as State Street prepares
to serve more investors abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The healthy numbers at both companies reflect a convergence
between financial services companies, as banks increasingly tread
on asset managers' traditional turf. Fleet is not nearly as big a
provider of processing services as State Street, but it does sell
some of products and services vended by investment companies. The
gains also reflect the booming stock market and economy, which have
lifted the boats of most investment management companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the financial services companies have really broadened
their product array,'' said Fleet's chief financial officer, Eugene
M. McQuade. ``Now is the payback time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, where assets under management now exceed $100 billion for
the first time, also reported 14 percent growth in its traditional
lending operations last quarter. ``Overall they're the best numbers
we've seen in a long time from the company,'' said analyst Sandra
J. Flannigan at Merrill Lynch Global Securities. Fleet beat Wall
Street expectations for second-quarter earnings by $0.03.
</P>
<P>
   At State Street, where earnings met expectations, chief
financial officer Ronald L. O'Kelley credited blossoming investor
markets around the globe for buoying business. While Asian economic
turmoil had dented operations at the company's State Street Global
Advisors asset management unit, strong European stock markets and
growing opportunities for foreigners to buy mutual funds had
helped. SSGA is the third-largest US money manager, with $459
billion in total assets.
</P>
<P>
   About 72 percent of State Street's business comes from fees for
serving institutional investors. Revenues from non-US clients
account for nearly one-quarter of total revenues. Overall, the
company has $4.5 trillion in assets under custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is hitting on all cylinders,'' said analyst George
A. Bicher of Bankers Trust New York. There are only six big players
in the global asset servicing business, but with many markets high
_ Asia, of course, an exception _ there are increasing volumes of
securities for State Street to process.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet, whose stock has grown at an annualized rate of 22.6
percent since 1980, also announced Wednesday a two-for-one stock
split for mid-September. The company's stock eased 7/16 to end
Wednesday at 85 11/16. State Street nudged up 1/8 to close at 73
1/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
