</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCA-COLA-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: BIG COKE BOTTLER FINDS ITS PLACE IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc., the bottling company that
is ever the bridesmaid to the giant Coca-Cola Co., is getting a
turn in the spotlight after all.
</P>
<P>
   While the Asian economic crisis deepens, stock in the bottler
provides a brand name that investors trust without the added
exposure to Indonesia, Thailand, Japan and other countries whose
bubbles have burst.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign sales account for 80 percent of Coca-Cola's total
business, and the company's profits have been crimped slightly as
falling currencies reduce the value of those sales.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sales in the United States are skipping along, with
growth of about 10 percent annually, impressive for a mature market
in which Coke products are already consumed at the rate of slightly
more than one eight-ounce serving a day for each man, woman and
child.
</P>
<P>
   And Coca-Cola Enterprises, the largest bottler in the Coke
system, accounts for 65 percent of Coke's domestic sales volume.
The bottler also handles Dr Pepper, the No. 6 soft drink in the
United States, and gets about 32 percent of its business from
Western Europe and Canada. For the last 18 months, it has been on
an acquisition binge, snapping up Coca-Cola Bottling of New York,
Coca-Cola Bottling of Canada and Coca-Cola Southwest, as well as a
$2 billion British bottler. Last month, it announced plans to
acquire Great Plains Bottlers &AMP; Canners Inc., a Midwest bottler,
which handles Dr Pepper and Coke products.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Carton, director of investor relations for Coca-Cola
Enterprises, says that even without the acquisitions, the company
will meet its goal of 10 percent growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   All this leads to new-found respect in an industry in which the
bottlers, clinking angrily under their breath, have long had to
take a back seat to the soft-drink companies.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, shares in Coke Enterprises were trading at $21, up
from a split-adjusted offering price of $5.50 in 1986. In April,
the share price popped through the $40 barrier for the first time
and leaped higher a few days later after an announcement that
company president Henry Schimberg had pledged to stay on two more
years as chief executive, and three subsequent years as a
consultant. Chairman and chief executive Summerfield Johnston
agreed to remain as chairman for an indefinite period.
</P>
<P>
   In May, two stock analysts speaking at a beverage-industry
conference recommended the stock, even over Coca-Cola. And last
month, at the Coca-Cola Company's biennial presentation before
investment bankers and portfolio managers, officials of the
bottling company were included onstage for the first time. Stock in
the bottler gained 25 cents Tuesday, to close at $40.75, ahead of a
scheduled earnings report today from Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened interest in Coke Enterprises can be attributed to
several factors besides concern about of the Asian crisis and
management savvy. First of all, a bottler bonded in any way to
Coca-Cola Co. ends up looking good, simply because Coke is, as the
saying goes, running on all cylinders. Volume is up, both worldwide
and in the United States. Marketing has never been better
organized; witness this summer's relentless promotion of ``Coke
Cards,'' 55 million of which were distributed to teen-agers and
college students. The cards combine entertainment discounts and
other offers with the purchase of a Coke or Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Coke Enterprises has been through a series of
consolidations and aligned its marketing and business strategy with
Coke. One of 11 anchor bottlers around the world (Coca-Cola
Beverages, which has operations in central and Eastern Europe, went
public in London just this week), Coke Enterprises is a pillar of
strength when it comes to local marketing and execution, the twin
forces that increase sales.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Co., which has a 42 percent stake in the bottler,
benefits directly from the bottler's success, and the two have
reached a mutual understanding, mostly under the leadership of
Coca-Cola Co. chairman and chief executive M. Douglas Ivester, a
former chairman of Coke Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, companies like Coke and Pepsi had a fractious
relationship with their bottlers. ``You might call it constructive
tension,'' says John Sicher, publisher of Beverage Digest, a widely
read industry newsletter. He added, however, ``In the last couple
of years, Coke has really listened well to its big bottlers.''
</P>
<P>
   The model looks pretty good, but, much like the Coke that
dazzles investors today, it took years to assemble. The bottler
staggered for its first five years. A 1991 merger with Johnston
Coca-Cola Bottling Co. turned things around. Centralized management
was replaced by one based in the field. And the merger brought in
Schimberg and Johnston, who get rave reviews from money managers
and bottlers alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry is one of the most gifted executives in this industry,''
Sicher said. ``He really has few peers. He has such a deep,
intuitive understanding of the marketing and distribution of soft
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their linked agendas, Coke Enterprises must be regarded
as a totally separate species from Coke, said Emanuel Goldman, a
beverage stock analyst with Paine Webber in San Francisco. And if
an investor worries about debt, Coke Enterprises may provide cold
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coke is a concentrate company with a balance sheet that has
effectively no debt,'' Goldman said. ``Coke Enterprises is
extraordinarily top heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke's long-term debt is just $801 million, on shareholder
equity of $18 billion, according to its 1997 annual report. The
bottler has about $8 billion in debt on shareholder equity of $1.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bottler's stock is trading at more than 100 times
earnings, twice the multiple of Coke's stock, Goldman noted.
Dividends aren't much to write home about either, only about 16
cents a share annually.
</P>
<P>
   More important, though, may be the role played by its principal
shareholder. ``Coke in a sense stands behind the company,'' Goldman
said. ``It's not official. But when you have 60 percent of the
volume, you can be pretty sure Coke cares.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
