<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7021 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS &LR;      07-15 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAYNE CUSTRED  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
SOUTHPORT, England _ It will take more than a straight driver and
solid iron play to master the links of Royal Birkdale Golf Course
this week in the 1998 British Open.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fact, Tom Watson will tell you it is the intangibles, not
what is carried in the golf bag, that determine who will win and
who will lose the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three things that are most important to win the
Open,'' said Watson. ``First of all, you have to have guts. Then
you have to couple that with desire. And I think you have to be
dedicated to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson has shown five times that he has all those
characteristics and more in Open Championships, with his last
victory coming at Birkdale in 1983. Here in the British Isles,
Watson has become an adopted son for the European fans. He holds
their hearts and, as is obvious by his great success in their
national championship, the key to winning here as well.
</P>
<P>
   For Watson, winning No. 6 this weekend is not out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a belief I can win this tournament,'' he said. ``It is
not a question of if I think I can win, and I am playing well
enough where I think I can. It takes some strategy on this golf
course to win, with the wind blowing the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a pretty good concept of what to do and how to
get to the greens, of how to fit the balls into the greens or into
the fairways with the wind. I think some players who haven't played
the golf course enough don't have that _ they won't have that
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it be enough? There is a long list of favorites this
week at Royal Birkdale. The Europeans are counting on veteran Colin
Montgomerie and rising star Lee Westwood to contend. The U.S.
players to watch include Tiger Woods, David Duval, Mark O'Meara and
defending champion Justin Leonard, while South Africa's Ernie Els
is high on all lists.
</P>
<P>
   With conditions at Royal Birkdale remaining windy and difficult,
most players are going into the tournament with high hopes but
cautious attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really just have to go out and see what's what,''
Montgomerie said. ``I cannot say (this course) suits my game, apart
from anyone else's. I'm glad the fairways are quite narrow, and I
look forward to trying to hit them along with everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience, of course, will be at a premium. A little luck, as
well, especially keeping the ball out of the gorse, thorny shrubs
and long, reedy grasses known as whin that line the Birkdale tract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you win a tournament, there are other things involved
rather than just hitting the ball good and putting good,'' Leonard
said. ``It is hitting good shots at the right times. It is missing
shots but being able to recover, and that's the big difference
between challenging and trying to win a tournament and finishing in
30th place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit some good shots when I needed to, and the shots that I
missed, I got away with last year. And, you know, that's real
important when you're trying to win a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara can certainly attest to that. He is often mentioned as a
favorite this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of course Mark can play very well,'' Watson
said. ``I think the left side of this golf course on certain holes
fits very well with his game. He will have to be careful on the
par-3s with his draw, but I think Mark can play this course very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara also has the confidence necessary to battle Birkdale and
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my juices are flowing pretty good, and I have pretty
good expectations,'' O'Meara said. ``I am just trying to stay a
little bit low-keyed.''
</P>
<P>
   While the European players certainly have more experience than
the Americans on links-style courses, that hasn't helped them in
the more recent Open Championships. John Daly won the 1995 Open at
St. Andrews, Tom Lehman took the title in 1996 at Royal Lytham, and
Leonard got the Claret Jug last year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the wind continues to blow, even O'Meara couldn't help
but give the nod to those golfers most at home on this type of golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wind blows, there's no question that it's a bit of an
advantage toward the European side because they're much more
accustomed to playing that type of golf,'' he said. ``But I think
the Americans enjoy coming over and playing this type of golf,
because in America we don't get the opportunity to play different
types of shots all the time. The creativity comes out a little bit
more.''
</P>
<P>
   The first indication of just who will be up to the test of Royal
Birkdale under any conditions will come today. While shooting an
extremely low first-round score is not a must, carding something on
the high side could be impossible to recover from in the Open
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Unless conditions change for the better, most golfers would take
even-par and wait it out in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind stays the way it is, the winning score is not
going to be far from par,'' Watson said. ``Even-par is going to be
a tremendous score on this golf course. Of course, if we keep on
playing with the same wind here and all of a sudden the wind
changes directions, that will throw a monkey wrench in everybody's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happened in 1983, and it's one of the reasons I
won. I successfully negotiated the wind change. So I hope it does
change. I hope it's a variety of wind conditions here.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the bookmakers in London have Watson going off
at 50-1 odds, the same as Leonard last year. That's a bet Watson
was advising fans to take.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go out and put 20 pounds on it,'' Watson said with a
grin. ``Actually, I'd put more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
