<SLUG> BC-IWORLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet access captures convention spotlight
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Bigger, faster, better, stronger. The advent of
high-speed access is the No. 1 topic on the minds of many of the
20,000 plus attendees at Summer Internet World this week at
Chicago's McCormak Place Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   Broadband access is shaping up to be the least glamorous but
most important aspect of Internet development as Web developers,
cable companies and telecommunications providers look toward the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint CEO William Esrey set the tone for the conference in his
keynote address Tuesday where he talked up Sprint's Integrated
On-Demand Network. Sprint's ION service will use a single line to
handle voice, video and Internet data. It will roll out to select
U.S. cities including Atlanta, New York, Chicago, Kansas City and
Denver before the end of the year. In five years, 90 percent of
traffic will be data transmissions, Esrey predicted. ``What you
need is a made-for-data environment. We will go from being the No.
3 long-distance company to the No. 1 integrated data network.''
</P>
<P>
   To play, or not to play
</P>
<P>
   He challenged the Baby Bells including BellSouth, as well as
other phone and cable companies who make up the ``last mile''
Sprint needs to completely deploy its service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local networks can play ball and be in the game or not
play ball and get left out,'' he said. ``If the Bell companies
really want to get into long-distance, they should view Sprint as a
partner rather than a competitor.'' He said Bell South, Ameritech,
GTE and Southwest Bell were among the local phone companies
considering an alliance with Sprint. MediaOne Express, a show
exhibitor, was also promoting high-speed access. MediaOne's cable
modem service is available in selected areas of Atlanta, Boston and
other MediaOne cities. Internet marketing director Kelly Ruebel
says the challenge is to get users educated and excited about
high-speed access. ``If someone isn't a heavy Internet user, you
have to show them what high speed means so they can understand the
value in it,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
