<SLUG> BC-TIMEWARNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time Warner, Turner perform
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time Warner released second quarter results Wednesday
that showed its Atlanta-based Turner Broadcasting unit continues to
prosper under the world's largest media concern. And so does Ted
Turner, the founder of the Atlanta unit.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's shares have more than doubled in value over the
past 12 months, with about half of those gains coming since the
beginning of this year. Time Warner lost $49 million or 9 cents a
share a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chairman Ted Turner, the company's biggest shareholder now
holds more than $5.18 billion worth of stock, including 50,110,101
shares held directly and 5,537,191 shares held indirectly,
according to CDA/Investnet. Included in the indirect holdings are
386,000 shares owned by Turner's wife, Jane Fonda. Those shares are
worth nearly $36 million, based on Wednesday's closing price of
$93.12 1/2. The shares hit a 52-week peak of $96.43 3/4 earlier in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Only nine months ago, Forbes magazine estimated Turner's net
worth at $3.5 billion, making him America's 28th richest person.
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting's second quarter revenues rose nearly 21
percent, helping to boost its parent's earnings to $23 million or 4
cents a share. Time Warner president Richard Parsons estimated that
Turner Broadcasting _ bought for $9.3 billion 18 months ago _ is
worth nearly twice that now.
</P>
<P>
   In a Wednesday briefing, Time Warner chairman Gerald Levin said
his company's percentage growth would range between the middle to
upper teens for the rest of the year. And he said the contribution
made by Turner Broadcasting was so strong he considered it Time
Warner's ``crown jewel.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin also said Time Warner had no interest in buying an company
that serves as a gateway to the Internet such as America Online or
Yahoo!. Levin said his company was considering letting others use
its cable systems to offer local and long distance telephone
service. Time Warner has a cable system in northwestern metro
Atlanta with 50,000 subscribers. It is currently upgrading that
system to handle digital TV, high speed access to the Internet, and
telephone service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, our cable plant will be used by somebody to
provide local. telephone service,'' added Time Warner Cable
President Joe Collins. `` If not AT&AMP;T, then someone else who wants
to take on the regional telephone comapnies.''
</P>
<P>
   While its earnings are small, Time Warner's underlying
financials continue to strengthen. Its operating income before the
amortization of intangible assets, or EBITA, rose 17 percent to
$1.16 billion in the quarter. In the media business, EBITA is
considered one of the key indicators of company's financial health.
Turner Broadcasting's EBITA was $198 million, up 20 percent from
165 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's quarterly revenue was $6.53 billion, of which $906
million was contributed by Turner Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
