<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW OFF 11.07 IN TURBULENT SESSION; TECH STOCKS STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were mixed Wednesday, with the
technology-heavy Nasdaq index jumping to another new high, while
the Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of
500 stocks finished lower after rising earlier in a day of volatile
trading.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, Dell Computer and Intel pushed the Nasdaq higher,
with Intel rebounding after its second-quarter earnings, which were
reported after the market closed Tuesday, came in a little under
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak, which jumped 8}, to 82{, added about 37 points to the Dow
after it reported that its second-quarter earnings beat forecasts
by a striking 25 cents a share. But that was not enough to offset
some disappointing earnings news.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar said that earnings rose 2.5 percent, to $1.20 a
diluted share, 4 cents a share below the forecast by analysts
surveyed by First Call Corp. The company said that earnings were
hurt by weak Asian sales. Caterpillar's stock fell 4\, to 52.
</P>
<P>
   And even strong earnings from Ford Motor did not help it. The
company reported profits that beat estimates by 10 cents a share,
but the stock dropped 1, to 59{. Even so, the stock is still up
84.5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq index rose 26.13 points, or 1.33 percent, to
1,994.54, leaving it just a few points shy of the 2,000 level. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 2.77, to 1,174.81, while the
Dow dropped 11.07, to 9,234.47. During the day, the Dow topped
9,300 for the first time, but was pulled lower by Caterpillar and
by declines in some of Tuesday's better performers, including J.P.
Morgan and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, the price of the 30-year bond rose 7/32, to
106 2/32, snapping a three-day slide. The yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 5.70 percent from 5.71 percent Tuesday.
The long-term yield is still more than 10 basis points, or
hundredths of a percentage point, higher than it was a week and a
half ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the outlook for a turnaround in Japan and Russia
has improved recently in some investors' eyes. Russia has been
helped by a $17 billion bailout from the International Monetary
Fund, the United States and Japan. And Japan is searching for a new
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   One of the concerns some analysts have about the stock market is
that while it is rising, the rally is limited to the bigger-company
stocks. This means that the so-called breadth of the rally is not
wide. One indicator of the lack of breadth is the number of
advancing stocks compared with decliners. On the Big Board on
Wednesday, decliners lead advancers 1,543 to 1,443.
</P>
<P>
   Another indicator is the fact that the main index of smaller
company stocks is still well below its high while the major indexes
have all bounced back. The Russell index of 2,000 stocks rose 2.55,
to 461.98 Wednesday, but it is still 6.4 percent from its high of
491.41 on April 21. And while the Nasdaq is up 27 percent this year
and the S&AMP;P 500 has risen 21 percent, the Russell 2,000 index is up
just 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big-cap rally,'' said Marshall Acuff, the equity
strategist at Salomon Smith Barney. ``The lack of breadth makes you
scratch your head. You have to build the breadth. You've got to
have the earnings to build the breadth and companies like
Caterpillar don't have the earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, ``if people really felt good about earnings they
would be driving the midcaps and small-caps higher.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for this disparity in performance is that
price/earnings ratios are so high that investors only want to pay
up for bigger company stocks that have long-term records of coming
close to earnings expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts argue that the rush of new money from
Americans and foreigners into the stock market is going to be
enough to offset concerns about the high cost of stocks and the
comparatively lackluster earnings performance this year _ low
single-digits compared with double digits last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
