<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CBS-60MINUTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OFFICIAL: `60 MINUTES' GETS DOUBLE
</HEADLINE>
   (also moving in `e' category) 
(rm) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ CBS made it official Wednesday: ``60
Minutes,'' the oldest and most successful news program in the
history of television, will expand to a second edition early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The new program, to be called ``60 Minutes II,'' will include
many elements of the original, including some appearances by its
veteran correspondents and the familiar opening of a ticking
stopwatch, while introducing a new lineup of reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision comes after a long, behind-the-scenes debate over
whether a new ``60 Minutes'' would dilute the appeal of the
original by spreading its brand too widely. Andrew Heyward,
president of CBS News, said the new program was intended to be
``not a clone, but a respectful offspring'' of the original.
</P>
<P>
   The chief connection between the new edition and the original
will be updated segments of what CBS is calling ``classic'' reports
from the original show, presented by the cast of the Sunday night
``60 Minutes.'' They may also appear in follow-up segments on the
second edition if something reported on Sunday needs updating.
</P>
<P>
   No new correspondents were named Wednesday, but the executive
producer will be Jeff Fager, currently the executive producer of
the ``Evening News With Dan Rather,'' who previously spent six
years as a producer on ``60 Minutes.'' Fager was called the crucial
piece in building the new program by several CBS News executives,
including Rather, who said, ``I don't think there could be a `60
Minutes II' without Jeff and the credentials he brings to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Fager will be replaced at the evening news by Al Ortiz, the
chief of CBS's Washington bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Fager said Wednesday that he hoped to have the show on the air
by mid-January. ``One of the great advantages I have is that I
don't need to go around looking for new music or building a new
set.''
</P>
<P>
   The look of the new show will be very much the same as the
original, Fager said, as will the style of reporting. There will be
no anchor, he said, just a lineup of correspondents, as on the
original ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The other crucial player in the development of the new program
is Don Hewitt, the creator and executive producer of ``60 Minutes''
for the past 30 years. Hewitt will serve as a consultant on the new
edition, CBS announced.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Hewitt and the correspondents long associated with
the show, like Mike Wallace, Morley Safer and Ed Bradley, had been
one of the sticking points in what became a long negotiation over
the second edition. Hewitt had said that he had been asked numerous
times over the years to expand what has been the CBS network's most
valuable franchise, but he always resisted, seeking to protect the
almost hallowed status of the original.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the correspondents had expressed their own
reservations about the potential risk to the reputation of the
original. But CBS's management pushed the expansion to take
advantage of the ``60 Minutes'' name. News magazines are some of
the most dependable profit centers for networks, which are under
increasing economic pressure because of a dearth of new hits and
escalating costs for entertainment programs produced by Hollywood
studios.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who declined to comment, said in a statement released by
CBS, ``I think that under Jeff Fager, `60 Minutes II' is a natural
to be the second best broadcast of its kind on television. Inasmuch
as I can help, without shortchanging the first best broadcast of
its kind on television, I'm hoping to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, president of CBS and the man responsible for the
network's prime-time schedule, had long made clear his enthusiasm
for a second edition of the most reliable ratings-getter on CBS.
``This is very important for us,'' he said. ``If you just look at
the summer, `60 Minutes' has been the top-rated show in television
three of the last four weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the new edition will likely be scheduled on a weeknight
at either 9 or 10 p.m. and may be pitted against an existing news
magazine on another network ``just because it's so hard to avoid
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward declined to speculate on which correspondents might be
under consideration for ``60 Minutes II'' but said of two part-time
contributors to the original show, Christiane Amanpour and Bob
Simon, ``We're looking for experienced broadcasters with superb
talent and those are certainly people with those qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
