<HEADLINE>
BEDTIME FOR BILLY?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Touring  &UR; Thomas Edison &LR; 's laboratory with  &UR; Hillary Clinton  &LR; on
the ``Today'' show Tuesday,  &UR; Maria Shriver &LR;  came upon a cot that
Mrs. Edison had put there to allow her busy husband to relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever want to put a cot in the Oval Office?'' Shriver
asked the first lady, who muttered a quick yes and immediately
moved the conversation to other matters.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. In the gift shop of the Prado museum in Madrid, there's a
photograph of  &UR; Bill Clinton  &LR; wearing one of the ties on sale there,
says  &UR; Holly Pierce &LR; . The pattern on the neck wear is based on
Goya's painting ``The Mannequin,'' described in the gallery guide
as an ``allegory of women's dominance over men.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARING, SHMARING IN ENGLAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a literary festival in England, British social
historian  &UR; Ann Glyn-Jones &LR;  said it was time to face the truth: The
``enormous excess'' of concern about  &UR; Princess Diana &LR; 's death ``did
not translate itself into any real social concern,'' she said. ``It
was like being a bit player in a real theatrical weepie.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, said media studies expert  &UR; Mandy Merck &LR;  of the
University of Sussex, there were public expressions of admiration
for the princess' sympathy for the underdog, but they soon died
down. ``When Eastern European Gypsies came to Britain shortly
afterwards, there was a mass public outcry and they were sent
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Merck also said that  &LR; Prime Minister  &UR; Tony Blair &LR;  had sided with
the royal family against the tabloid press, &LR;  in an attempt ``to
conduct a P.R. exercise for the House of Windsor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Yasmine Bleeth &LR; , who owes her fame to ``Baywatch,'' told
Detour magazine that  &UR; David Hasselhoff &LR;  is always shot from the
knees up because ``he has these skinny little bird legs that make
him look like a stork.''
</P>
<P>
   In other avian news, the Sebastiani family, producers of Viansa
wines, proudly announced this week that the Kenwood Wildlife Center
released 24 black crowned night herons and 36 snowy egrets into the
90-acre wetland bird sanctuary at the Sonoma County winery.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Tony Reveaux &LR;  is entranced by the bumper sticker ``I am a
dopeless hope fiend.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An exhibit by  &UR; Lisa Levy  &LR; at Webster Hall in New York features
items stolen by the performance artist, including a baby's milk
bottle, a prosthetic leg and half of a liverwurst sandwich. Each
item carries a tag marked with the date it was stolen; videotapes
of some of the thefts are played during the show. Levy links her
work to dadaism and, according to the curator of the show,  &UR; Baird
Jones &LR; , sees all art as a ``revolutionary anarchistic and
anti-establishment movement based on an underlying
disillusionment.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Dan Esch &LR;  was impressed by the sign in the new Rite-Aid on
24th Street in San Francisco that says, in letters two feet high,
that the company is ``A Family Tradition Since 1299.'' It must have
made a fortune on aspirin during the plague.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT TO CLEANLINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Italian clothing designer  &UR; Kean Etro &LR;  has scrapped plans to
play a recording of  &UR; Pope John Paul II &LR;  singing a Gregorian chant
as models parade down the Spanish Steps of Rome. Vatican Radio,
which has rights to the recording, had threatened to sue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self magazine sends word of Marketplace Ministries, a company
that ``places beeper-equipped chaplains in corporate settings
across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Passing the Semicon West convention in San Francisco every day
on his way to work this week,  &UR; Stephen Vincent &LR;  found divine
inspiration in the sign ``Wafer Processing.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Marina Maggiore &LR;  was inspired to read, in the newsletter of
the St. Francis Solano Parish of Sonoma, of a Special Anointing
Mass to be celebrated on July 19,  &LR; utilizing ``a small amount of
holy water from a priest in Boston who has literally confused the
medical world with his miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never bored. If I ever am, I just start planning menus.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Socialite Nan Kempner in the New York Observer.
</P>
</TEXT>
