<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-15 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE'S EARNINGS EXCEED ANALYSTS' EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Confounding the skeptics yet again, a resurgent
Apple Computer Inc. blew by Wall Street analysts' earnings
estimates Wednesday for the third consecutive quarter. Apple said
it sold a record number of its G3 Macintosh computers and that
profit margins improved in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Apple reported its results after the market's close, but in
anticipation of a strong quarter, Apple shares closed at $34.44, up
$1, a new 52-week high, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the company's revenues were as expected, but that
higher margins boosted earnings due to Apple's selling a greater
percentage of high-end machines. Revenues might have been higher
had the company been able to meet demand for its new Powerbook
laptop models.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great quarter,'' Steve Jobs, Apple's interim
president and chief executive, said in a telephone interview.
``Operational excellence has returned to Apple.''
</P>
<P>
   For its third fiscal quarter, which ended June 26, Apple
reported earnings of $101 million, or 65 cents a share, fully
diluted, compared with a loss of $56 million in the comparable
period a year ago. Revenues dropped 18 percent to $1.4 billion,
from $1.7 billion in the third quarter of fiscal 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's third-quarter 1998 earnings included a $26 million net
gain from nonrecurring items, including an after-tax gain of $33
million related to the initial public offering of ARM Holdings PLC,
and a $7 million charge related to the acquisition of technology
from Macromedia Inc. Without these nonrecurring items, the
company's net income for the quarter would have been $75 million,
or 50 cents per diluted share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Apple to earn 33 cents a share, according
to First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said Apple could
continue to outperform expectations in the quarters to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing a pretty good job building excitement around the
iMac,'' he said, referring to a new $1,299 Macintosh for the
consumer market. ``They've created an atmosphere in which people
want to buy the Macintosh again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One measure of Apple's new discipline as a business is that the
company increased inventory turns from 13 to 22 in the quarter,
which helped drive down costs and lowered its exposure to declining
component prices. Fred Anderson, Apple's chief financial officer,
said in a conference call with securities analysts, that the
company's goal was to increase inventory turns to 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talking a Dell-style balance sheet,'' said Kunstler,
referring to Dell Computer Corp.'s industry-leading minimal
inventory levels. ``From a shareholder's perspective, that's got to
be very sweet to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Macworld convention this week in New York, Apple answered
a number of concerns that had been raised about the iMac,
announcing that it would include a 56K modem rather than the slower
33K device it had originally been shown with, and unveiling three
external floppy disk drives. In addition, Apple said software
developers had announced commitments for 177 new programs or
upgrades for the Macintosh since the iMac was introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more comfortable with the iMac proposition than I
did before Macworld,'' said Charles Wolf, an analyst with C.S.
First Boston. He said he expected Apple to sell 275,000 iMacs to
schools and home consumers in the fourth quarter; 400,000 in the
December quarter and 1 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than anything Compaq has for the consumer market
under $2,500,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the launch of the iMac would bring Apple's profit
margins down by a couple of percentage points, but he added that
the company expected a substantial gain in unit volumes from the
new machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sights are set on a very aggressive foray into the
consumer market,'' he said during the call with analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Although in the past Apple has discovered after launching new
products that it had miscalculated demand or had encountered
production difficulties, Jobs said the company was gearing up for
the iMac launch and would be ready this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make a lot of iMacs this quarter,'' he said.
``Even making a lot, there's no way we will meet demand this
quarter. We hope to meet demand next quarter. That's just the way
it is when you have a hot product.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 10 million existing home users of the
Macintosh, and new computer users who want to get access to the
Internet, Jobs expects the iMac to win back customers from the
Wintel camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``A thing to remember is many of them were not born with a PC in
their mouth,'' he said. ``Many of them defected from the Mac and we
can win some of them back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
