<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LEGISLATION WOULD BLUNT JOB DISCRIMINATION BAN AGAINST GAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans say they will vote next week on
legislation that would nullify President Clinton's executive order
banning job discrimination against homosexuals working for the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., said in an interview Wednesday that
he plans to offer an amendment to the Commerce Department spending
bill that would prevent any federal money from being spent to
implement, administer or enforce the president's executive order.
</P>
<P>
   ``With me this is not a gay fight, it's a fight about executive
orders and about carving out particular classes,'' Hefley said.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley said presidential executive orders are meant to be used
for emergencies, not for trying to circumvent Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He said that with this order, which was issued in May, the
president decided ``with the stroke of a pen, I'm going to be a
dictator ... The president directly thumbed his nose (at
Congress.)''
</P>
<P>
   Hefley said Congress has signaled that most of its members don't
want to add a new category based on sexual orientation to the civil
rights laws that apply to minority and disabled federal workers and
grant recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not promoting discrimination, but there are many civil
rights laws to deal with discrimination,'' Hefley said. ``I don't
think the American people want additional protected classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hefley said he has support from Republican leaders including
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, House Majority Leader
Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, House Rules Committee chairman Gerald
B.H. Solomon, R-N.Y., and House Appropriations chairman Bob
Livingston, R-La.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., who chairs the National Republican
Congressional Committee, which works to elect Republicans to
Congress, said in an interview he would support Hefley's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than take things through the House and go through the
normal process, he thinks he can makes laws by himself,'' Linder
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hefley had planned to offer the legislation Wednesday as an
amendment to the Treasury-Postal Appropriations bill, but said he
changed his strategy for fear of offending Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz.,
the only openly gay Republican in Congress, who heads the
appropriation panel's Treasury Postal Subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to bash Kolbe,'' Hefley said, adding that he
hopes that moving the issue away Kolbe's panel will reduce the
chances that it will become a gay issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least it might not be so prominent if I'm not sticking my
finger in Kolbe's eye,'' Hefley said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kolbe pledged to fight Hefley's amendment and predicted
an ugly battle over the issue of whether gays should be protected
against job discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a very tough debate with a lot of
difficult things said,'' Kolbe said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   One critic of Hefley's amendment said the Colorado
representative was attempting to appease conservative religious
groups in his home district, which includes Colorado Springs. One
of those groups, Focus on the Family, headed by James C. Dobson,
has pushed for months to block the languishing nomination of San
Francisco gay rights advocate James Hormel, Clinton's choice to be
ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Tafel, executive director of Log Cabin Republicans, a group
that represents gay Republicans, said, ``It's out and out anti-gay.
It's pandering to the religious right and gay bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hefley's amendment comes as a broad coalition of conservative
religious groups has launched a campaign against homosexuality,
hoping to communicate that it is a disease that can be cured with
counseling and therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition has taken out ads this week in national
newspapers, such as one that told the story of a former lesbian who
says she changed her sexual ways through religion.
</P>
<P>
   The ads follow recent remarks by Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., who compared homosexuals to alcoholics,
kleptomaniacs and sex addicts. Gay groups responded to the ads by
purchasing their own full-page ads.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif., one of six House Democrats who
joined with six House Republicans Wednesday evening to send a
letter to all House members defending Clinton's executive order,
said she would fight Hefley's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, the majority is trying to enliven their base,'' at
the expense of gays, Tauscher said in an interview. ``It is an
attempt to keep the traditional Republican social conservative
right-wing base enlivened. They want to keep the money machine
going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
