<SLUG> BC-SPACE-FUNDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE STATION OPPONENTS RALLY AROUND PROPOSAL TO SCUTTLE PROJECT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional opponents of the international space
station rallied Wednesday around a proposal by Rep. Tim Roemer to
pull the plug on the multibillion-dollar project.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Democrat said his annual effort to end funding for
the orbiting laboratory has received a boost from NASA's
acknowledgment of cost overruns and launch delays, along with the
failure of Russia _ one of 16 partners in the project _ to pay its
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel that the evidence continues to pile up to finally
put this space station out of its misery,'' Roemer said at a
Capitol Hill news conference attended by four other House members,
representatives of two science organizations and three taxpayer
groups, all opposed to continuing U.S. participation in the
project. A recent GAO report set the total cost over the project's
lifetime at $96 billion with development and construction to cost
$24.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA has no answers for the cost overruns and scheduling
delays that now plague the station,'' Roemer said. ``Congress
should end this fiscal black hole now before it consumes other
worthwhile scientific projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Roemer's proposal, which he plans to offer as an amendment to a
funding bill for Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban
Development, is similar to legislation the Senate killed, 66-33, a
week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Roemer's amendment is scheduled for debate and a vote by the
full House on Thursday. He wants to delete about $2.1 billion
earmarked for NASA to spend next year to launch and assemble
several components of the space station. His amendment would
provide a maximum of $500 million to close down the project, which
is being developed at the Johnson Space Center in far south
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The first component, a 20-ton control module financed by NASA
and built by the Russians, is to launch Nov. 20. Two weeks later, a
space shuttle carries aloft a unit called Node 1, which will attach
to the control module and serve as a port for future components.
NASA's timetable calls for the facility to be complete and
operational by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nick Lampson, a Texas Democrat whose district includes JSC,
called Roemer's effort to kill the space station ``misguided.''
Lampson said NASA contractors have completed work on 75 percent of
the U.S. share of the hardware for the space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we backed out of the station now, and severed the
relationship we have with the Russian space agency, we ... would
have a really difficult time building another friendly project with
them. This would set back our international relations a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with the traditional argument that scrapping the space
station would cost jobs, Roemer acknowledged that his task is more
difficult because of lobbying by space contractors and lawmakers
whose states stand to benefit from the project. ``I'm not going to
kid you. This is a very difficult thing to overcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To counter the economic argument, Roemer points out that three
states _ Alabama, California and Texas _ receive 85 percent of the
benefit from contracts to develop, launch and operate the space
station. He also noted that the latest redesign cut the space
station's capability to two scientific missions, down from eight as
originally envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space station simply provides too little bang for the
buck,'' Roemer said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
