<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Galarraga has 2 HRs as Braves rout Mets
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1996 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the New York Mets wish to make a race of the
National League East, they apparently never read the manual.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves and Mets now have played 47 innings, and New York has
yet to hold a lead. Wednesday afternoon, the Braves bid the Mets
farewell until Labor Day weekend, and Andres Galarraga left the
``Amazins'' looking like Beetle Bailey after Sgt. Snorkel adjusts
his attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Riding Galarraga's sixth multi-homer game of the season, the
Braves pummeled New York 12-1 and swept a two-game set at Shea
Stadium. Ryan Klesko added a solo homer, Andruw Jones drove in two
runs, and Denny Neagle (10-7, 3.17) allowed one unearned run during
six innings to join Atlanta's five-man 10-win club on his third
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``How should I put this?'' asked Neagle. ``I was receptive to
getting that many runs today.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, who matched his season high with five RBIs, was just
as happy to furnish them. He hit a two-run homer off New York
starter Masato Yoshii in the first and added a colossal three-run
shot off Bill Pulsipher in the fourth that landed in a grassy area
40 feet beyond the Braves' bullpen. That made it 9-1, and Bobby Cox
soon started emptying the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job,'' said Galarraga, who now has 31 homers, 11 shy
of his 1997 total in Colorado. ``I played four games in Miami last
weekend and didn't get an RBI. So now I got somebody on base and
finally have some RBIs in the second half. Maybe I make up for the
first four.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga has homered in just five of his last 27 games but has
now hit two home runs in four of those games. Wednesday marked the
25th multi-homer game of his career, and the long blast over the
bullpen was his fifth three-run homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He finally got some pitches to hit,'' said Cox, who called off
batting practice while the Braves crawled from their beds for a
12:10 p.m. start.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle, who had given up three runs in his last two starts and
couldn't win, limited the Mets to four hits. More important, he
stranded four Mets in the first three innings while the lead was
being built. When he got the lead, he appeared stronger, allowing
just one runner past first base in his last three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning of the season everyone is saying we got the
division easy,'' Galarraga said. ``I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is a little easier now than it was two days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
