<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1-for-22 slump has Tucker riding bench
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- There was a notable absentee from Wednesday's
Flushing Wood Fest. Michael Tucker never came out of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those days,'' Tucker said, ``where if I went up
there and didn't get a hit, I might kill somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's slump, at 1-for-22 and holding, convinced Bobby Cox to
keep his right fielder on the bench and start Curtis Pride on his
second day off the DL. Pride went 1-for-3 and scored, and Eddie
Perez, who later batted in Pride's (and Tucker's) seventh spot, had
a pinch-hit RBI single. Cox thought it was something Tucker ought
to see while the Braves ran up 16 hits, their highest total in 43
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He chases (bad pitches) like everybody else when they're not
hitting the ball real solid,'' Cox said. ``He's swinging at some
balls he really shouldn't be swinging at. These are things people
go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after a .256 June, Tucker was riding an eight-game hitting
streak that brought him to July 4 still hitting .281, with 19
doubles and 11 home runs (his respective career highs are 25 and
14). But in his six games since, he has one double and five
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things aren't going that great,'' he said. ``There's not much
you can do about it. Everybody goes thought it. Chipper went
through it. Klesko went through it. Andruw went through it at the
beginning of the year. All you can do is keep going up there and
swinging. Things just aren't clicking right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullpen adjustment
</P>
<P>
   With Mark Wohlers scheduled to make a last appearance Wednesday
night with Class AAA Richmond, the Braves plan to put off
activating him until Friday to avoid forcing him into back-to-back
appearances. That postpones by 24 hours the decision on whom
returns to Richmond to make room on the 25-man roster. Management
is still debating the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Seanez is a likely choice, but with a respectable
performance in nearly seven weeks with the club (1-0, 3.00 ERA), he
is also out of options, and the Braves would quite possibly lose
him to the waiver wire, given the current quality of relief work in
the majors. That could nominate right-hander Mike Cather (2-2,
3.92), who finished Wednesday's game but made just his third
appearance in 16 games. Just beginning his second year of service
time, he retains his minor league options.
</P>
<P>
   Shifting times
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets are determined to use an infield overshift
against Chipper Jones, when he is batting left-handed and the bases
are empty. The ploy didn't help much in Wednesday's romp. Jones
went 2-for-4 and scored three times, but shortstop Rey Ordonez did
rob a single from him Tuesday night. Jones wound up 4-for-8 against
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
