<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: Milwaukee Brewers
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: Tonight and Friday at 7:40 p.m.; Saturday at 7:10 p.m.;
Sunday at 1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: Braves Network (WUPA) will televise tonight, and TBS
will televise the next three games. 750-AM will broadcast all four
games.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: Tonight: RHP Greg Maddux (12-3,
1.57; 1-0, 1.69 vs. Brewers) vs. RHP Cal Eldred (4-7, 4.80; 0-0,
1.50 lifetime vs. Braves). Friday: LHP Tom Glavine (12-4, 2.85;
1-0, 2.83 lifetime vs Brewers) vs. LHP Brad Woodall (4-4, 3.61;
0-0, 18.00 lifetime vs. Braves). Saturday: RHP Kevin Millwood
(10-4, 4.28; first appearance vs. Brewers) vs. RHP Steve Woodard
(6-5, 3.47; 0-1, 5.40 lifetime vs. Braves). Sunday: RHP John Smoltz
(7-2, 3.62; first appearance vs. Brewers) vs. RHP Jeff Juden (7-8,
4.73; 1-4, 5.74 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Series history: In their first season of National League
membership, the Brewers are 1-4 against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Past meetings: The Braves outscored the Brewers 19-3 and swept a
three-game series in Milwaukee June 1-3. The clubs opened the
season with a two-game set at Turner Field, Milwaukee getting a 1-1
split by scoring six runs in the last three innings during an 8-6
victory April 2.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers leaders: Avg. _ Mark Loretta (.321); HR _ Jeromy Burnitz
(20); RBIs _ Burnitz (65); SB _ Fernando Vina (13). W _ Jeff Juden
(7); ERA _ Mike Myers (0.53). Strikeouts _ Cal Eldred (80). Saves _
Bob Wickman (13).
</P>
<P>
   Quickly: After finishing the first half in a five-game losing
streak, Milwaukee went 3-3 out of the break and remains mired in
the middle of the Central Division. But they have been consistent,
remaining at or above .500 since June 10. ... The Brewers are
under-powered with a team slugging percentage (.394) that is 10th
in the NL and a run-scoring rate (4.48 per game) than ranks ninth.
While the starters have gone 27-33, the bullpen has been a
strength, once Bob Wickman took over closing duties.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
