u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR16-COX     07-15 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For solace, Wohlers can look to Blass
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- The inquiry from Atlanta, home to the Gordian knot
that is Mark Wohlers, was hardly unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime anyone has control problems, I get a call,'' Steve
Blass says to your correspondent. He does not say so wearily. He
does not sound pained at being asked to pick at a 25-year-old scar.
He is a man who understands his place as a living, breathing point
of reference.
</P>
<P>
   As Wohlers lost touch with the strike zone, going from World
Series savior to troubled enigma, some mentioned that he had come
down with Steve Blass Syndrome. Or, others defended him by saying
that he was no Steve Blass. Wohlers is scheduled to make his return
to the Braves today; and we shall discover on which side of the
Blass analogy he finally falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only one of two ballplayers who's had a disease named
after him. Me and Lou Gehrig. Not bad company,'' is Blass'
oft-repeated one-liner on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wohlers, Blass recorded the last outs of a World Series. He
was the catalyst to Pittsburgh's 1971 victory over Baltimore, the
starter who had complete-game victories in games 3 (a three-hitter)
and 7 (allowing just four more hits). The next season, he won 19,
walking only 84 in 250 innings. He practiced a form of laser
surgery before it became common among medical types.
</P>
<P>
   Then, for reasons he still does not comprehend, Blass melted
down. At 30 (Wohlers is 28), Blass could not control the pitch's
destination. The more he fought it, the more imprecise he became.
He went 3-9 in '73, with an ERA of 9.81. There was but one major
league start in 1974 _ five innings, five hits, seven walks _ then
down to the minors. In the fourth inning of a 1975 spring training
game, Steve Blass said farewell by walking in six runs.
</P>
<P>
   A Pirates broadcaster, Blass is at the stage now where he can
dull the memory with regular injections of humor.
</P>
<P>
   He tells of the time Mackey Sasser, a catcher who became
strangely unable to throw the ball even back to the pitcher, passed
through Pittsburgh. ``I told him we would have made a heck of a
battery,'' Blass said. ``They'd need a bag of balls every time we
were out there. He'd throw the ball into center field, and I'd
throw it into the concession stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is nothing funny about the malady as it worms
its way through a player's brain. ``Once you can't rely on your
instincts,'' Blass said, ``you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn a lot about yourself. I had a horrendous two years.
I don't think anything will get to me again, because I survived
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He does not make a great effort to follow those who currently
are afflicted. Of Wohlers, the Connecticut-born Blass knows this
much, ``He's from the New England area too, right? (Yes, Holyoke,
Mass.) Must be something in the water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd encourage him to try every conceivable thing, no matter
how ridiculous it may seem at the time. When it was over for me, I
was at least satisfied that I had tried everything,'' Blass said.
</P>
<P>
   And circle the wagons with your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just hang in there. All pitchers are going to go through their
streaks of wildness. Most of them get over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him I've been through it and I'm rooting for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
