<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PSCR sanction for new series
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Professional Sports Car Racing (PSCR), a member club
of the American Competition Committee of the United States (ACCUS),
was named the sanctioning body for the recently announced American
Le Mans Series, and William Donaldson was named executive director
of the sports car series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped for and certainly encouraged a unification of the
PSCR and USRRC (the Bill France-owned United States Road Racing
Championships) since January of this year. This has not occurred,
and we need to move forward with the organization of our American
Le Mans Series,'' said Don Panoz, Chairman of Panoz Motor Sports
and originator of the American Le Mans Series.
</P>
<P>
   PSCR, based in Tampa, currently sanctions a series of races in
the United States, and for 1999 will focus its attention on as many
as 11 races in the American Le Mans Series.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, currently president of Premier Management Group (PMG)
of Indianapolis, will headquarter the series in Indianapolis.
Donaldson spent 19 years at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway,
leaving last September as its executive vice president to form PMG.
</P>
<P>
   Formula One
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line of Sunday's British Grand Prix is that Michael
Schumacher won it, but here is the final version of how he won it.
The McLaren team protested Schumacher's victory, claiming he should
have taken a 10-second penalty for illegal overtaking. Three and a
half hours after the race finished stewards withdrew the penalty
because of a technicality _ they had informed the Ferrari team more
than the mandatory 25 minutes after the incident, thus it never
happened. So, officially, Schumacher won by 22.4 seconds, not 12.4.
Wins like that are why Schumacher gets the big bucks that stagger
even the imagination of NBA hopefuls. The 29-year-old is expected
to sign with Ferrari for another two years for $85 million, and
that information came before the British Grand Prix win.
</P>
<P>
   Legends
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Olympic swimming gold medalist Steve Lundquist held off
former New York Giants safety Myron Guyton to win the celebrity
Legends match during last week's ``Thursday Thunder'' at Atlanta
Motor Speedway. Reed Sorenson of Peachtree City continued his
dominance of the Young Lions division, taking his fifth straight
victory. Other winners: Chargers, Tim Pafford, Leesburg; Masters,
Stephen Dale, Fayetteville; Bandolero, Kyle Kennedy, Preston; Pro,
Doug Stephens, McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   Drags
</P>
<P>
   Phil Sexton of McDonough turned an 8.59 elapsed time (154.12
mph) in his 1996 Mullis Dragster to win the Pro/Super Pro division
of last Saturday's Sears/Craftsman series at Atlanta Dragway. Other
winners: Sportsman, Toby Barnes, Peachtree City, 1968 Camaro, 12.25
ET, 109.49 mph; Trophy, Cliff Donald, Lawrenceville, 1967
Barracuda, 14.77, 92.03; Motorcycle, Jay Rhyne, Athens, 1981
Kawasaki, 14.36, 91.09.
</P>
