<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDS AT BRITISH OPEN HEIGHTEN THE CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHPORT, England _ As a five-time British Open champion, Tom
Watson knows a thing or two about the world's oldest major. So when
asked to name the three most important ingredients for a British
Open champion, Watson did not hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, you have to have guts,'' said Watson. ``You have
to couple that with desire. And I think you have to be dedicated to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With those thoughts in mind, Watson will join the world's
greatest golfers at Royal Birkdale Golf Club to test themselves
against the elements, the pressure and a demanding golf course when
the British Open begins Thursday. The year's third major is hard to
handicap, and it will be even more difficult to play, particularly
if the wind blows as forcefully as it has for much of this week.
</P>
<P>
   While several golfers like Lee Westwood, David Duval and the
defending champion, Justin Leonard, have been mentioned
consistently by their peers as favorites this week, other prominent
players may have difficulty contending because of injuries. They
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tom Lehman, who, according to several players and caddies,
strained his right shoulder Tuesday night when he fell off an
amusement park ride. Lehman reportedly felt better Wednesday
morning, and he has a late tee time Thursday (2:45 p.m. local),
giving him extra time to receive treatment. ``I'll definitely be
O.K.,'' Lehman told The Associated Press Wednesday. ``I was just
messing around with the kids.'' However, if Lehman is severely
hampered by the injury, it may force him to withdraw, or seriously
damage his chances to win.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ernie Els, who has still not fully recovered from the bad back
that forced him to withdraw from last month's Buick Classic. Els
did not look good at last month's U.S. Open, and he may take a
month off after this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nick Faldo, who withdrew from last week's Loch Lomond
tournament with an injured right elbow. Faldo said Wednesday that
he would play, but he wore a cast for three days last week, and the
injury interrupted his preparation. ``I played a full round today,
didn't hold back,'' said Faldo. ``That was a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even healthy players may feel a little uneasy after playing
Royal Birkdale this week. Today was the calmest day of the week,
with temperatures in the low 60s, and winds gusting to 15 miles per
hour. Earlier this week, wind gusts approached 40 miles per hour,
and the weekend forecast calls for wind gusts of more than 20 miles
per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Par could be a winning score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the holes play either into a wind, or with a stiff
crosswind,'' said Duval, the top money winner on the PGA Tour, who
will be seeking his first major championship. ``There doesn't seem
like there are many breaks. It beats you to death.''
</P>
<P>
   Birkdale demands accurate shots off the tee, because the
fairways are narrow and hard. Balls that land in the fairway with
speed are still in danger of rolling into the thick grass, bunkers
and dunes that await errant shots. Most players, particularly long
hitters like Tiger Woods, John Daly and Davis Love III, will only
use their driver sparingly, preferring to hit irons off the tee.
Putting is always crucial, but anyone who has a poor week off the
tee will not win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course is so hard,'' said Daly, who won the 1995 British
Open at St. Andrews. ``I had a better chance at St. Andrews, where
I hit a driver on a lot of holes. Here, you can't do it. You miss a
fairway here, you can't advance the ball unless you get a good
break or a good lie. You miss the fairway, you're dead.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Guts, which Watson talked about, will come into play
particularly on crosswind holes, where players will have to aim for
trouble, trusting the wind to push their ball back to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has taken me two days to figure out how far the ball is
being pushed by the wind,'' said Lee Janzen, who won last month's
U.S. Open. ``Normally, in the states, we still aim for the edge of
the fairway. Here, I think you have to aim sometimes 20 yards off
the fairway, into deep trouble, just to get the ball to go in the
fairway. It is going to eliminate a lot of guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire that Watson talked about will be evident on the
weekend, when the contenders separate themselves from the field.
The last two winners, Leonard last year and Lehman in `96,
discovered that they had what it takes to win a major. For top
players who have yet to win a major, particularly veterans like
Colin Montgomerie and Phil Mickelson, the pressure will be even
more intense if they find themselves in contention.
</P>
<P>
   The last 15 majors have been won by 15 different players, so the
list of potential winners is much wider than the fairways at Royal
Birkdale. Considering the havoc that the wind could cause, almost
anything could happen. But the challenge of dealing with the
conditions is part of what makes the British Open special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to rank them, but this is one I would dearly like to
win, and probably the one I get most excited for,'' said Love.
``This is probably the greatest championship in the world. Each
major has got something special, but this one is probably the one
most guys want to win more than any other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
