<SLUG> BC-POLAROID-NBSI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID BUYS ID CARD RIVAL FOR $12.9 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHANA R. SCHOENBERGER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid Corp. has bought its closest rival in the market for
advanced identification cards, paying $12.9 million for NBS Imaging
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid expects the acquisition of NBSI, a division of NBS
Technologies Inc. of Toronto, will consolidate its position in
driver's licenses and other so-called secure cards.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid has struggled to rebound from a decline in sales of
instant cameras and film, its core business. While expansion into
medical imaging has met with mixed results, the Cambridge, Mass.
company remains the biggest player in the market for photo ID
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid said Wednesday it currently supplies secure licenses to
27 states, giving it the largest market share in the industry.
After the acquisition, Polaroid will hold license contracts for 50
US, Mexican, and Canadian states and provinces, as well as
contracts for identification documents in several other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBS is really their number-one competitor in terms of US
driver's license contracts,'' said analyst Gibboney Huske of Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``They have a pretty dominant market share in
this business.''
</P>
<P>
   The photo equipment giant plans to fold NBSI, of Fort Wayne,
Ind., into its own card business, according to Polaroid spokesman
Robert L. Guenther. No new jobs will be created in Massachusetts as
a result of the sale; NBSI personnel will be relocated to Polaroid
ID card production sites around the country, Guenther said.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid said it expects the acquisition to cause a slight
increase in 1998 earnings. NBSI reported almost $25 million in
annual sales in 1997. Polaroid had $2.1 billion in sales during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the sale would have a small but beneficial impact
on Polaroid's financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to expand that business,'' said analyst B. Alex
Henderson of Prudential Securities. ``It's not a material event in
terms of earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Secure ID cards combine pictures with special laminates,
holograms, and sometimes biometrical security features to make the
cards fraud-proof. In Georgia, where Polaroid runs the largest
biometric ID card program in the world, the state's driver's
licenses carry fingerprint-verification information directly on the
card, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid's stock gained 5/8 to close at 35 5/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
