<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-RICHTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO RICHTER, RIGHT PLACE TO BE IS WITH RANGERS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TARIK EL-BASHIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After all of the posturing and hard-line negotiating
tactics, it took a face-to-face meeting between Mike Richter and
Neil Smith on Monday for both to realize that New York was where
Richter belonged.
</P>
<P>
   And so late that night, after an afternoon of meetings and
bargaining, Richter settled for less than he originally wanted but
ended up with the team he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of opportunity when you become a free agent,''
Richter said at a news conference Wednesday to announce the deal.
``But staying where you are happy and where you have a chance to
win another championship is what's most important. And for me, that
is with the New York Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Richter's contract, a four-year deal worth $21.8 million, makes
him the National Hockey League's third-highest-paid goaltender
behind Dominik Hasek of Buffalo and Curtis Joseph, who was also
pursued by the Rangers but ended up signing a four-year, $24
million contract with Toronto Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When it came down to it, Mike and I worked things out,'' said
Smith, the Rangers' president and general manager. ``That's the way
it should be.'' Richter's agent, Herb Pinder, was also involved in
the negotiations, but it ultimately came down a compromise between
Richter and Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith added: ``Free agency is not all it's cracked up to be, as
Mike will tell you. Sure, it makes you a little bit richer, but it
pulls on your heartstrings. I can't tell you how emotional it got.
Mike has been our goalie for nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by John Muckler, the Rangers' coach; Brian Leetch, the
team's captain, and Dave Checketts, the president and chief
executive of Madison Square Garden, Richter sat at a table with
Smith and signed the new contract before dozens of reporters and
flashing cameras in a short ceremony at the Garden, the arena
Richter will call home through the 2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   But before the deal was struck late Monday, Richter was prepared
to board a flight for Florida, where the Panthers wanted him to
replace John Vanbiesbrouck. Then, with no more than an hour to
spare, Smith called Richter with an offer, the one to which they
eventually agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Richter and Smith said there were no hard feelings despite
the sometimes ruthless tactics used by both sides over the last
month. ``I wouldn't call it easy,'' Richter said. ``But that's
business. I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had been negotiating with Joseph since last Friday
and were apparently close to signing a deal. But negotiations with
Joseph broke down on Monday morning because of a division over
money and the length of the deal. Smith picked up the phone and
called Richter, who was close to working out a deal with the
Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith treated the signing as a victory, and in some ways it was,
if retaining a front-line goaltender can be considered a victory.
Certainly the team would have been worse off if Richter had left
and no replacement was available. But will the Rangers be a better
team? After all, they missed the playoffs with Richter in net this
past season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for the rebuilding Rangers, keeping Richter was important
for several reasons. First, no team is going to make the
post-season without a top-flight goalie. Richter is that. Second,
Richter will serve as a bridge to the future, tutoring a young Dan
Cloutier until he is ready to take over. Third, re-signing Richter
was proof to veterans like Leetch, who will become an unrestricted
free agent next summer, that winning is still a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very important for this organization if it wants to make
a quick turnaround,'' Leetch said. ``Everyone knows that starts
with a great goaltender.''
</P>
<P>
   The next priority for the Rangers is re-signing Leetch. Despite
his subpar performance last season, Leetch is still viewed as a
premier defenseman and is the core of this team. ``I'd like to get
it done as soon as possible,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch was also hopeful that something could be worked out
before the season. ``I don't see anything in the immediate future
with my contract,'' he said. ``But I would like to get it done
sooner rather than later. It can be a distraction if you're talking
during the season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
