<HEADLINE>
TAX-CUT MEASURE SAILS THROUGH HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an unusual show of election-year bipartisanship, the
House Wednesday unanimously passed a $700 million tax-cut package.
</P>
<P>
   The plan doubles the exemption for earned income, saving about
$131 for a single filer and $262 for joint filers; and cuts in half
the 12 percent tax rate on interest and dividend income.
</P>
<P>
   The new tax rate for unearned income would be phased in Jan. 1,
1999. Interest and dividends gained this year, therefore, are not
subject to the lower 5.95 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
   As for the doubling of exemptions, taxpayers will be able to
receive 75 percent of the phased-in savings on their 1998 tax
returns and 100 percent of the savings the following year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also increases the size of the stabilization, or rainy
day, fund, from 5 percent of current revenues to 7.5 percent,
allowing reserves to grow from $950 million to a maximum of $1.42
billion. That item alone could cost $475 million.
</P>
<P>
   Further, the proposal would reduce unemployment insurance rates
by $116 million and add another $18 million for a workforce
development program.
</P>
<P>
   And the state tax code would be brought in line with the federal
tax code in several areas, including Roth and educational
Individual Retirement Accounts; and capital gains on the sale of a
principal residence.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not include Acting Governor Paul Cellucci's
proposal to lower the income tax from 5.95 to 5 percent, which
would cost more than $1.2 billion when fully phased in by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   For a family of four earning $50,000 a year, Cellucci's plan
would save them $384, and a family of four earning $75,000 would
save $600; a single parent earning $30,000 a year would save $213;
and a single person earning $25,000 would save $198.
</P>
<P>
   However, the plan passed by the House Wednesday would save a
family of four $262 a year in personal exemptions when fully phased
in. A single parent would save $202, and a single filer would save
$131.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the gap between the two proposals, Citizens for
Limited Taxation and Treasurer Joseph D. Malone called on Cellucci
and other Republicans to reject the plan and hold out for a larger
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republicans joined the House Democrats in passing the
package 150-0. And Cellucci is expected to sign off on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperation is the name of the game,'' said Representative
David M. Peters, a Charlton Republican and minority leader. ``We
supported the tax cut based on its merits. Was it everything we
wanted? No. But we voted for it because we felt it was a good
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, CelluccI had been scheduled to testify before the
Joint Committee on Taxation Wednesday during a hearing on his
income tax reduction plan. But the acting governor did not appear,
and the committee held his bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a disgrace,'' said the committee's Senate
chairman, Warren E. Tolman. ``This is a guy who, if I listen to my
TV, he's fighting hard for a tax cut. But when the bill is heard,
not only does he not show up, but he doesn't even send a
representative to debate and discuss this important public-policy
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Cellucci was in New Bedford announcing a grant for
the local jail. They said the Legislature did not notify his office
that the hearing was taking place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0435 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-GORE16-COX     07-15 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-GORE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE TO ANNOUNCE BLACK-ORIENTED LOAN PROGRAM
 &HT;    440&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reaching out to the African American community,
Vice President Al Gore will announce Thursday a new partnership
between the NAACP and the Small Business Administration as part of
a $1.4-billion loan initiative to assist black-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's announcement, scheduled in a speech at the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People convention in
Atlanta, is an attempt to spur economic development in black
neighborhoods. The NAACP would help steer black applicants for
business loans to the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration hopes that boosting the number of
loans in the African American community will strengthen the black
middle class, according a spokesperson for the SBA. While African
Americans represent 12.5 percent of the total population, they own
just 3.6 percent of all businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Clinton administration approved 1,810 loans to
African American businesses valued at $226 million. By comparison,
in 1992, the last year of the Bush administration, the SBA approved
709 loans to the African American community valued at $124 million.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership with the NAACP is only one part of Gore's
speech, which will have the theme of ``closing the opportunity gap
in America,'' according to a White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Building upon a speech he delivered earlier this year at the
Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta, which has historic connections
to slain civil rights leader Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., Gore is
expected to emphasize this theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all our progress, we know that too many never get into the
winner's circle of this new economy,'' Gore will say Thursday,
according to a prepared text of his remarks. ``I believe we must
use today's prosperity to expand that winner's circle _ by closing
the opportunity gap in our schools, by closing the opportunity gap
in our workplaces, and by building stronger families and
communities across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to address education by urging Congress to
support a program called the ``E-rate,'' which offers Internet
connections to public schools in impoverished areas at steep
discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about it: if we put computers and the Internet in every
classroom and school library in America, along with teachers who
are trained to use them, all of our children, from the poorest
inner-city schools to the most remote rural school districts, will
have access to the same vast store of knowledge,'' Gore's text
states. ``Some in Congress are trying to block the E-Rate. I
believe it is wrong to unplug our children's education.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech also serves to court African American voters as he
prepares to run for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Political scientists say that to win key Southern states such as
Georgia, Gore will need to energize African American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past seven months, Gore has announced a series of
programs on behalf of the White House that would directly benefit
minorities. They include expanding tax credits to encourage the
construction of low-income housing, encouraging U.S. automakers to
increase subcontracting to minority businesses, and new funds for
modernizing and building public schools in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Many African American leaders welcomed the news of the SBA loan
program, to which the NAACP would help steer black business owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is very good news for the African American
community, but it's also good for the whole American community,
because it will create jobs and when you have jobs, you have less
discrimination,'' said Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is empowerment at its best,'' said Freman Hendrix, the
deputy mayor of Detroit, where 78 percent of the population is
black. ``This will absolutely touch the local economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, saw the new program as a case of spending money
to solve racial problems, which they say will only heighten
tensions between the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start throwing money at races of people, you turn
them into a special interest group,'' said Shelby Steele, a senior
fellow at the Hoover Institution at Stanford University and author
of an upcoming book on race titled, ``The Dream Deferred.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to throw money at white people to get them to
stop being racist?'' Steele asked. ``In the end you end up with
white resentment.''
</P>
<P>
   But that theory was quickly dismissed by those who have worked
with Gore on other initiatives aimed at tearing down the racial
barriers that still exist more than 30 years after the Civil Rights
Act was passed.
</P>
<P>
   As she canvassed the South with Gore following the fires of
black churches, the Rev. Joan Brown Campbell, general secretary of
the National Council of Churches, saw the way the vice president
was received and heard the promises that he made.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of soul,'' Campbell said. ``The black community
is very good at ferreting out those who don't keep their promises,
and he makes promises that people can hold onto.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
