<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATORS INCLUDED IN SKILLS TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Prospective teachers, whose widespread failure on
first-ever certification tests sparked a public and political
outcry this spring, will be joined by would-be principals and
administrators in testing rooms this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sept. 1, anyone applying to be administrators, guidance
counselors, psychologists, nurses, or school social workers will
face the same communications and literacy skills tests that sparked
such controversy for teacher candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The State Board of Education made the decision June 22, but the
news was lost in the flap surrounding another controversial
decision that day: to lower test standards to allow many failing
teacher candidates to pass. That decision was later reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of criticism that teachers had little time to prepare
for their tests _ which were not originally intended to count in
April's first round of testing _ the board began spreading the word
this week to prospective administrators and support personnel.
Officials notified news organizations, education associations,
posted the information on the board's Web site, and even plan to
make public service announcements to get the news to educators well
before the first test on Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure there was a lot of notice for this
one,'' said Alan Safran chief of staff for the Deparment of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Certification will be required for those applying after Sept. 1
and only for new candidates. Though teacher candidates also face
tests of their subject matter, the board said the certification
test will be required for administrators and support personnel,
whether or not a test is in place for their certificates by that
time.
</P>
<P>
   Now, every prospective educator will have to satisfy the
requirements for communication and literacy skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board and department are committed to setting high
standards for all those involved in teaching our children,''
Education Commissioner David Driscoll said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators are unlikely to balk at being held to the same
standards as their staffs, some said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they understand that if we're going to hold teachers
to that standard, it would only be reasonable to hold
administrators to that standard also,'' said Peter Finn, executive
director of the Massachusetts Association of School
Superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   But Nadya Aswad Higgins, executive director for the
Massachusetts Elementary School Principals Association, said she
hopes the debate over the quality of education will not be obscured
by the politicized testing issue, which has become a touchstone for
controversy in a gubernatorial election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a problem in having someone pass a
literacy test,'' she said. ``But I do think too much of an emphasis
on it is undervaluing what it really takes to become an effective
principal,'' said Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   While it remains to be seen how professionals like social
workers will deal with mandatory literacy tests, Safran said the
board wants all professionals to be held to the same standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are school support personnel who have contact with kids
and contact with parents,'' he said. ``That communication has to be
articulate, clear and model excellent communications ability as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, only cafeteria and janitorial staff and substitute teachers
will be exempt from the testing, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
