<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-LOSS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ POSTS SECOND-QUARTER LOSS, OFFERS GLIMPSE OF FUTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional ending) 
 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Compaq Computer Corp.'s purchase of Digital Equipment
Corp. gave the Houston-based computer maker its first quarterly
loss since the dark days of 1991.
</P>
<P>
   But the earnings report issued Wednesday also offered an
intriguing glimpse into Compaq's future.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq posted a loss of $3.62 billion, or $2.35 a share, for the
second quarter of the year. That number almost matches the $3.63
billion charge related to the acquisition of Digital, which was
completed June 11.
</P>
<P>
   The company warned earlier this year that its second quarter
would be much like the first quarter, with profits and sales flat
due to deep price cuts necessary to move a glut of business
computers out of inventory.
</P>
<P>
   That warning proved accurate. However, before the Digital
charge, Compaq actually earned a small profit _ $32 million, or 2
cents a share, on sales of $5.8 billion. That compares to a profit
of $257 million, or 17 cents a share, on sales of $5.5 billion in
the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   But that small gain would not have happened without the
additional sales from owning Digital for just over two weeks.
Digital brought $1.1 billion to Compaq's coffers in that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Compaq Classic (Compaq without Digital) was a
disaster in this quarter,'' said Ashok Kumar, an analyst with Piper
Jaffray in Minneapolis. ``The good news is that they can't do much
worse. They can only go up from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Earl Mason, Compaq's chief financial officer, disputed Kumar's
characterization, saying that Compaq had met its goals for the
second quarter and would concentrate in the third quarter on
integrating Digital into its operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A neat part of that story is that, after we paid for Digital,
and took the Digital debt off the balance sheet, we still have $4.6
billion in cash, and that's significant,'' Mason said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Compaq has reduced the number of desktop, notebook and
file server computers sitting on the shelves of its resellers to
about 3 1/2 weeks of inventory, while the goal for the quarter was
four weeks. In order to accomplish that, Compaq shut down its
Houston factory for two weeks in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But Kumar said his own checks of resellers show that inventory
of high-end file servers is closer to 10 weeks, and consumer
systems sold in retail stores is about five weeks. The server glut
is made up of systems that use older technology such as Intel
Corp.'s Pentium Pro processors, Kumar said, and thus is harder to
sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to take it,'' he said. ``You have companies like
Dell coming in and selling Pentium II servers at Pentium prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts were not as glum.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Poyner of Oppenheimer in New York said Compaq has gotten the
worst of its inventory problems behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tactically, the focus is going to be on doing what they said
they'd do with the consolidation, putting the companies together,''
said Poyner. ``They're going to have to spend the quarter blocking
and tackling and getting everything done just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mason has said Compaq will spend the current quarter working on
integration issues, and by the fourth quarter will begin to see
financial benefits. He held to those predictions on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because Compaq executives said in advance that the company would
post a loss, investors weren't alarmed. Compaq's stock closed
Wednesday at 33 9/16, down 1/8, after being up on early trading.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first red ink in Compaq's history as a public
company. Compaq posted an 82 cent-a-share loss in the third quarter
of 1991, the year the company's financial situation imploded.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.63 billion Digital charge is made up of three components:
$3.2 billion to write off in-development technology, $291 million
for shutting down Compaq facilities and laying off Compaq workers
and $139 million for other ``operating adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Another $2 billion in charges has also been taken, but it was
rolled into the $9 billion price Compaq paid for Digital, a company
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq expects to lay off 17,000 people worldwide as a result of
the Digital merger, with 2,000 of them being from the ``Compaq
Classic'' work force. About 1,000 of those layoffs will take place
in Houston, though those have nothing to do with Digital. Those
layoffs are the result of Compaq's moving to a ``built-to-order''
system in its local factories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons Compaq bought Digital was for its $6
billion services and support operation. The figures released
Wednesday show that division already is having a significant impact
on Compaq's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of last year, Compaq's services business _
the installation, design and support of computer systems _ was just
$110 million. For the second quarter of this year, that number
jumped to $460 million, mostly due to the brief period that Compaq
owned Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Compaq expects to earn between $12 billion and $15
billion annually in service revenues after the turn of the century
as a result of the Digital purchase. At the time of the
acquisition, Digital's services arm was bringing in about $6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that number has been flat for several years,'' said Kumar.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Compaq expects services to account for 20 percent of
its overall revenues. Poyner said those will be be high-profit
revenues, because the service business has margins averaging about
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
