A7077 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REINSURANCE16-COX     07-15 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REINSURANCE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISASTER REINSURANCE POOL APPROVED BY HOUSE PANEL
 &HT;    By DANIELLE SHOOK
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ States could receive federal insurance coverage for
a natural disaster such as a hurricane or catastrophic fire under a
bill passed by a House committee Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved 33-12 by the House Banking Committee, would
establish a federal insurance program to be administered by the
Treasury Department. The program would cover earthquakes, fires,
volcanoes and hurricanes that cause $2 billion in uninsured
damages, or damages from a storm so severe that it would take place
only once in 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   An outgrowth of Hurricane Andrew and Hurricane Iniki, which
devastated South Florida and Hawaii in 1992, and California's
Northridge earthquake in 1994, the bill is designed to protect
homeowners by providing backup insurance for state insurance pools.
These pools were developed after hard-hit companies dropped
coverage or refused to renew policies due to the enormous costs
involved.
</P>
<P>
   The states would pay a premium into the reinsurance fund to
cover catastrophic disasters. Federal money would be used only when
the loss exceed the money in the reinsurance fund. The federal
liability would be limited to $25 billion a year. The program would
be available to all states, but is expected to primarily help
Florida, California and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation responds to a growing dilemma experienced by
both consumers and the financial service sector. The impact of
insufficient capital to adequately address homeowners insurance
availability at affordable levels for the consumer when paying
premiums, the insurer when purchasing reinsurance to cover
significant losses and the lender attempting to protect its
collateral,'' said the committee chairman, Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
