<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-HEALTH-HNS &LR;      07-15 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS UNVEIL HEALTH CARE PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Clearly worried that health care may be high on
voters minds in November elections, Senate Republicans on Thursday
unveiled a plan aimed at giving consumers of some managed care
plans more rights to medical service and greater ability to appeal
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Key elements of the proposal would allow some patients to appeal
medical decisions to outside experts, to use emergency rooms
without always getting permission from insurers and expand Medical
Savings Accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately pounced on the plan, arguing that it only
offered modest protections to a minority of those enrolled in
managed-care plans and did not give patients the right to sue their
Health Maintenance Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disappointment. We were hoping they would come up
with something more real than this,'' said Senate Minority Leader
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., who hosted a forum where several medical
people who had bad experiences with HMOs testified.
</P>
<P>
   The health care issue is expected to dominate the congressional
agenda over the next several weeks. Prodded by pollsters telling
them that voters are upset about their managed-care plans, House
GOP leaders have drafted legislation similar to the one proposed by
the Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has also made the issue a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday he talked with patients about their negative
experiences with HMOs at a forum sponsored by the American Medical
Association. The president on Thursday is expected to attend a
rally with Democrats on Capitol Hill to exhort Congress to address
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The president last fall proposed his own patient bill of rights,
but he has endorsed Democratic congressional proposals that are
more far-reaching than the Republican plans, giving people more
access to specialists and allowing them to sue their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton refrained from attacking the Senate plan,
Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala dismissed the
GOP blueprint as ``too little, too late.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the offer of any bill represents a major turnaround for
conservatives such as Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and Sen. Don
Nickles, R-Okla., who earlier this year had vowed to oppose any
government mandates regarding health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday both Nickles and Gramm stood with a number of more
moderate Republican colleagues promoting the bill they expect to
vote on before Congress leaves for summer recess in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in political games. We're interested in
quality health care,'' said Nickles, the Senate majority whip who
presided over the health care task force.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate GOP plan would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Give consumers of employer-sponsored health-care plans the
right to appeal medical decisions both within the HMOs and to
outside experts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow consumers of self-insured employer-sponsored plans the
ability to use emergency rooms without always getting permission
from their providers and to see gynecologists without getting a
referral from their health plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give consumers of employer-sponsored, self-insured health
plans the ability to pick their own doctors if their employer has
more than 50 workers and offers only one HMO plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prevent health insurance plans from using genetic information
to deny patients coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expand Medical Savings Accounts and tax breaks for those who
are self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the Senate GOP plan does far less and covers far
fewer people than advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the provisions only apply to the 48 million consumers
who are enrolled in health plans self-insured by their employers.
They represent less than a third of the 170 million Americans in
employer-sponsored health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans said they restricted regulations to plans that
cannot be regulated by states.
</P>
<P>
   The external appeals process in the GOP plan would also be
limited. Only those who had been denied medically necessary
procedures costing over $1,000 or who needed experimental
procedures could use the system.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been questions about the impartiality of the
outside appeals, since the medical expert who would hear the case
would be appointed and paid for by the health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Although the arbitrator could not have a financial interest in
the health plan or hospital involved in the procedures, critics
said that person could not be truly independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the fox is guarding the henhouse,'' said Kim Ross,
legislative director for the Texas Medical Association, which along
with the AMA and other doctors' groups around the country are
opposing the Republican plans.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, complaints against HMOS are currently heard by doctors
appointed by the state Insurance Board.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas doctors are particularly disturbed that the Republican
plans do not give patients in employer-sponsored health-care plans
the right to sue for punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Texas Legislature in 1997 approved giving consumers
the right to sue their HMOs, that law is being challenged in
federal court in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that such lawsuits would drive up health
insurance costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great boom for trial lawyers,'' said Nickles.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say that the ability to sue is the only way to hold
the plans accountable. And as evidence that the provision would not
be abused, they point to the fact that since the Texas law was
passed in 1997 there have been no lawsuits against HMOs in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats are also likely to clash on the issue
of Medical Savings Accounts, which allow workers to bank their own
money and funds contributed by their employers in tax-free accounts
intended to pay for medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the government is overseeing an experimental program
that restricts these accounts to 700,000 individuals who work for
small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans want to greatly expand the MSAs, while
Democrats claim that the program siphons off wealthy and healthy
people from the insurance pool, making it more expensive to pay for
those left in conventional plans.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions creating more savings accounts and allowing the
self-employed to deduct health insurance expenses would cost
federal government $11 billion over 10 years. Republicans conceded
they had not figured out how to pay for those tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
