<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-375&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ASKS GM AND UAW TO SET ARBITRATION DATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ A federal judge on Wednesday asked General Motors
and the United Automobile Workers to schedule a date for the
arbitration of strikes at two auto parts factories here as top
negotiators from the automaker and union talked face to face for
the first time in three days.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Paul Gadola Jr. did not grant GM's request for an order
that arbitration begin immediately. But he urged both sides to
agree by Tuesday on a date to meet with an arbiter, Robert Thomas.
GM and the UAW said they would comply.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides said they were satisfied with the decision, it
still amounted to a small victory for GM, which has suffered
heavily from the strikes, which began on June 6 and have shut down
26 of the automaker's 29 assembly lines in North America.
</P>
<P>
   GM had accused the union of stalling on any arbitration, and
while the union had denied this, union officials had said as
recently as Tuesday that they saw no need to speed up the
arbitration process. GM wants the arbiter to rule on whether the
walkouts here are local strikes, which are allowed under GM's labor
contract, or a national strike, which is not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Shoemaker, the UAW's vice president for GM issues, said
the arbitration process would slow a settlement here. Some UAW
officials involved in talks with GM at factories outside Flint are
now needed to prepare for arbitration, he said.
</P>
<P>
   GM has said that before any deal can be reached in Flint, the
union must withdraw threats to strike at parts factories in
Indianapolis and Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jaworski, a GM lawyer who represented the company in
federal court in Flint on Wednesday, said GM thought that the
issues in the strike needed to be settled by negotiations but also
wanted arbitration. Once the two sides meet with an arbiter, it
could take as little as a week for Thomas to reach a ruling, labor
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Gadola did not rule on GM's contention that the strikes here
represent a national walkout. But he made a point of denying the
suggestion of some labor experts that no court in Michigan would be
willing to become involved in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, that's not the view of this court,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By an extraordinary coincidence of the sort that sometimes
happens in auto factory towns, Gadola is the son of the judge who
presided during the only other time GM and the UAW have confronted
each other in court during a strike.
</P>
<P>
   When UAW workers occupied Flint factories in late 1936 and
demanded that GM recognize the union, Paul Gadola Sr. declared the
strike illegal on Feb. 2, 1937, and ordered the strikers arrested
for contempt when they refused to leave the factory.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard was sent to Flint, but the strikers left the
factory peacefully after GM said it would bargain with the union.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Knechtel, GM's vice president for North American
personnel, returned to Flint on Wednesday morning to resume
bargaining with Shoemaker. The two had lunch in the restaurant of
the same Holiday Inn where they had negotiated for two weeks until
Sunday, when Knechtel returned to Detroit for lack of progress.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker said Wednesday evening that little progress had been
made at any of the sites where the union and GM are bargaining.
Knechtel declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives have taken an unusually strong stand during the
walkouts at the parts factories in Flint, citing a need to reduce
costs sharply to become more competitive. An annual report
Wednesday from Harbour and Associates Inc., the best-known
manufacturing consulting firm in the auto industry, found that
while GM had improved considerably, it still had a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   GM needs an average of 30.32 hours of labor to make each
vehicle, compared with 32.15 hours at Chrysler Corp. but just 22.85
hours at Ford Motor Co., according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign automakers' factories in the United States were the most
efficient, with Nissan requiring only 17.07 hours for each vehicle,
although its cars and trucks tend to be fairly small and easier to
assemble.
</P>
<P>
   The Harbour report found GM had greatly improved productivity in
stamping metal auto parts, a central issue here, but that the
automaker still lagged behind competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Further trouble for GM was developing Wednesday in Spring Hill,
Tenn., as workers at its enormous Saturn factory began preparing
for the first strike vote since production began there 12 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of GM's 29 assembly plants in North America, the Saturn factory
is one of only three still producing cars; the other two are in
Oshawa, Ontario, and Ramos Arizpe, Mexico, while a fourth assembly
plant in Pontiac, Mich., is preparing for pickup truck production.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bennett, the UAW's chairman, said the Saturn factory
produced more of its own parts than other assembly plants and had
found outside suppliers for the half-dozen small parts for each car
that it usually receives from the struck factories in Flint.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the strike vote is mostly coincidental with the
showdown here, he said; Saturn workers have been growing angry for
months at recent moves by GM to begin buying car doors, dashboards
and exterior body panels from outside vendors instead of producing
them in Spring Hill. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
