<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BOTCHED-RAID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON POLICE OFFICERS MAY FACE CHARGES IN BOTCHED DRUG RAID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (See optional trim) 
 
By S.K. BARDWELL 
and JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston police officers involved in a botched drug
raid that left a 23-year-old man shot to death earlier this week
could face criminal charges, sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief C.O. ``Brad'' Bradford said a preliminary
investigation ``raised serious concerns'' about how the officers
conducted the raid in which Pedro Oregon was killed. An officer was
wounded by friendly fire.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was disturbed by questions surrounding the incident,
Bradford added there were indications of ``serious departmental
violations, even violations of the law.``
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, family and friends of Oregon agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother wasn't a criminal,'' Oregon's sister Susana, 19,
said in his modest apartment, strewn with his soccer trophies,
photographs, religious verses and bullet holes. ``He was a
landscaper. He did a lot of planting and working on yards.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Oregon left a widow and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, assigned to the gang task force at HPD's Southwest
Patrol Division, told investigators they entered Oregon's apartment
about 1:30 a.m. after their confidential informant witnessed a drug
transaction inside.
</P>
<P>
   No narcotics were found in the apartment, and Susana Oregon said
her brother was not involved with drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about a police informant who was here,''
she said. ``That's just what they all say, but I don't think it's
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers said several people were inside the apartment when
they entered, and that Oregon ran into a bedroom and locked the
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only two people were here, the victim and a witness,'' said
Kevin Painter, a family friend.
</P>
<P>
   The unidentified witness told Oregon's family that police were
yelling for someone named Julio when they entered the apartment. No
one named Julio lives there, Painter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers just got really excited,'' he said. ``The witness
heard `bang, bang,' a kick, and then `bang, bang, bang, bang,
bang.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The police shot the lock and then kicked open the door. If the
kids had been sleeping in the bed, they would have been killed with
the first two shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers who broke into the bedroom said they opened fire
after Oregon pointed a pistol at them. More than 30 shots were
fired in the small space, sources said. Several shots hit Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Lamont E. Tillery, 30, was shot in the shoulder, but his
bulletproof vest prevented serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   Ballistics tests determined that Tillery was shot by a fellow
officer. A weapon was recovered from Oregon's bedroom, but no
investigator would say Wednesday if it had been fired.
</P>
<P>
   One source, asked what the raiding officers had done wrong,
said, ``It would be easier to ask what they did right _ the answer
is, not much.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers carried neither a search nor an arrest warrant,
that source said.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential informant the officers were using was not
registered with HPD, as now required of all informants, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said there is also a question about whether the
informant fit the department's criteria to qualify as an informant.
</P>
<P>
   The number of officers firing weapons in such a small space, the
number of shots fired, ``goes into the equation as well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police may have been looking for Oregon's brother, who does
belong to a gang, Painter said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also wondered if Oregon or his brother had been ``set up'' by
a gang member.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it takes is one informant from another gang to pretend to
be an informant for the police,'' Painter said. ``To tell police,
`yeah, I'll help you out,' and these stupid gang officers believe
everything the stupid informant is telling them and the informant
is really just using the police to get revenge.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The involved officers, relieved of duty with pay pending the
outcome of the investigations, are Tillery, a two-year veteran;
David R. Barrera, 28, a five-year veteran; Pete A. Herrada, 28, a
three-year veteran; David Perkins, 30, a four-year veteran; James
R. Willis, 28, a five-year veteran, and Sgt. Darrell H. Strouse,
34, with HPD for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are two investigations. One, being conducted by HPD's
internal affairs division, will determine whether the officers
violated department policies regarding use of confidential
informants.
</P>
<P>
   The other, being conducted by homicide investigators and the
Harris County District Attorney's civil rights division, will
determine whether any officer faces criminal charges in Oregon's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence will probably go to a grand jury when the investigation
is complete, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
