<HEADLINE>
BRITISH CONFISCATE WEAPONS, EVICT PROTESTANT PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland _ Police and British troops evicted
protesters and confiscated weaponry Wednesday from the hillside
next to the Drumcree parish church that has been the flash point
for violence across Northern Ireland over the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces in combat gear struck tents and turned up an
assortment of weapons including spent pistol rounds, catapults,
crossbows, gunpowder, a homemade submachine gun, bomb-making
chemicals and nuts, bolts and steel discs to be used as missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Protestant Loyal Orange Order of Portadown and
their followers have been camped at the site since July 5, when
they encountered barricades and troops placed in their way. They
are protesting a government order barring them from marching
through a Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators were told they could return once the all-day
security search was completed, but only after each person had
passed a police inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the opportunity to stop the violence and the only way
the Orange Order can control this is with limited numbers,'' said
Tom Craig, deputy chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
whose men have been bombarded for 10 nights by gunfire,
gasoline-filled bottles and nail bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The operation appeared to mark the end of another test period
for Northern Ireland's fragile new peace agreement, with sectarian
fire bombings and the shattering arson deaths of three young
Catholic brothers coming just weeks after hopeful votes to create
fresh structures for the British province.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who thinks that we are beaten and it's over is totally
misreading the situation,'' said David Jones, spokesman for the
Portadown Orange Lodge. ``We are still going to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Maginnis, the security spokesman of the Ulster
Unionists, Northern Ireland's largest political party, said, ``I
want the Orangemen to go home, primarily on the basis that they are
not able to control the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   And John Dixon, the Presbyterian Moderator, said, ``The violent
events now rightly associated with the continuing Orange presence
at Drumcree are wholly unsupportable by any Christian standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The haul of weapons from the churchyard and nearby fields will
be an embarrassment to the Portadown Orange Order, which prides
itself on its religious rectitude and dedication to nonviolence.
</P>
<P>
   The Portadown Orangemen brought the province to a perilous point
last weekend when they summoned tens of thousands of fellow
Orangemen to join them on Monday in their standoff. A year ago
intelligence predictions that 70,000 people were headed to Drumcree
caused the police to force the march down the contested Garvaghy
Road, and rioting engulfed the province. This year the Orangemen
were predicting a turnout of 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   But with news of the Quinn brothers' killings, the masses of
Orangemen never showed up at Drumcree. The Order's own chaplains
urged the Portadown local leaders to call off their protest and
abandon the hillside vigil out of respect for the three dead boys.
</P>
<P>
   Early Sunday morning, Richard, 11, Mark, 10, and Jason Quinn, 9,
were burned to death in their beds in Ballymoney in an arson
attack. Two Protestants have been arrested.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Orange Order has been opposed both to the peace settlement
reached in April after 26 months of negotiations and the creation
of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, whose 108 members were
elected on June 25. The Rev. Ian Paisley, leader of the hard-line
Protestants, and his followers saw the Drumcree showdown as a way
to build up the Protestant rejectionist front he now leads.
</P>
<P>
   His hope was to persuade wavering supporters of David Trimble,
the First Minister of the Assembly, to desert him, eliminating the
small majority of Unionist members who believe in the Assembly's
power-sharing principles. The Assembly is charged with setting up
cross-border organizations that will bring Northern Ireland closer
to the Republic of Ireland, a Catholic goal.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble was among those who in the aftermath of the Ballymoney
murders called on the Orangemen to drop their protest. Paisley
urged them to maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order's carefully cultivated image of unity,
determination and orderliness has been damaged at Drumcree. Their
protest was hijacked by young militants with nail bombs and
gasoline-filled bottles who went to war each night with troops and
policemen, and the defiant Orange rebuke to the government's
Parades Commission was exploited by Protestant paramilitaries
elsewhere in the province to go on violent rampages.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen also had an unaccustomed public falling out among
themselves over how to react to the murders of the three Catholic
brothers, and they did not succeed in their proudly stated ``line
in the sand'' demand to walk down ``the Queen's highway'' here.
</P>
</TEXT>
