<HEADLINE>
IT'S JULY, BUT AVALANCHE THREATS REMAIN IN SIERRA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONE PINE, Calif. _ A recorded message at the Mount Whitney
Ranger Station warns backpackers that avalanche conditions still
exist above 10,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   It's mid-July, for wafflestompers' sake, can this be right?
</P>
<P>
   You bet your boots it is, all because the Sierra Nevada mountain
range received twice its normal snowpack this winter and cool
weather has kept it from melting.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the backcountry has hampered hikers' summer plans,
especially for those with less technical ambitions. Ice axes and
crampons are considered musts to tackle passes over 11,200 feet,
including the Mount Whitney Trail. Many creek and river fords are
dangerous; some are impassable.
</P>
<P>
   You know things are bad when Canoga Park Boy Scout Troop 211
can't find an adequate four-day trip for its annual Sierra outing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to be aware of the fact that water is running high
and they are likely to find snow at elevations they wouldn't
normally at this time of year,'' said Al Nash, spokesman for
Yosemite National Park, where Tioga Pass Road (Highway 120) opened
July 1, the latest in recent history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly slower than usual (for backpacker traffic),''
Nash said. ``We may be running anywhere between four and six weeks
behind schedule for the backcountry.''
</P>
<P>
   High Sierra trails may have patches of snow or be uniformly
covered, with depths of up to four feet at spots. Some passes may
not be snow-free until late July or August.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is summer, winter and spring conditions exist in
the mountains,'' states the Mount Whitney Ranger Station's phone
recording.
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE &QL; 
Who to call for further information on backcountry conditions:
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Sierra
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Mount Whitney Ranger Station, Lone Pine, (760) 876-6200.
</P>
<P>
   White Mountain Ranger Station, Bishop, (760) 873-2500.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth Lakes Ranger Station, (760) 924-5500.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport Ranger Station, (760) 932-7070.
</P>
<P>
   Western Sierra
</P>
<P>
   Sequoia and Kings Canyon National Parks, (209) 565-3766.
</P>
<P>
   Yosemite National Park, (209) 372-0745.
</P>
</TEXT>
