<HEADLINE>
KREMLIN ASKS LEGISLATORS TO OK KEY ECONOMIC PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With billions in Western loans at stake, the Russian
government urged the lower house of Parliament today to pass a
package of tax, budget and economic measures, the strings lenders
have attached to any additional money.
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament passed several new laws designed to instill
discipline in the budgeting process and restore confidence in the
economy, including legislation that cuts corporate taxes,
encourages foreign investment and simplifies taxes on small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of $17.1 billion in new loans over the next 18
months has lifted Moscow's beleaguered stock market. Stocks rose
for the fifth day in line with rallies in the bond market that
began earlier this week. The hope that an international bailout
would head off a Russian cash shortage and currency devaluation has
raised prices of stock and bonds and lowered interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Important votes on personal-income tax rates and procedures
regarding value- added taxes are due Thursday or Friday.
Streamlining the arcane tax system and increasing tax collection
are cornerstones of the plan pushed by the government and the
monetary fund.
</P>
<P>
   If Parliament balks, the Russian government has warned that it
will adopt some of the measures by decree. But some measures,
including taxation rates, can only be enacted by legislation. And
the Kremlin would prefer to have as much Parliamentary support as
possible. The board of the International Monetary Fund is expected
to vote on Monday to approve $11.2 billion in new loans this year
for Russia. The Kremlin is rushing to ram the measures through
Parliament by then.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, President Boris Yeltsin has mounted a sort of
charm offensive to woo hard-line deputies. He even invited party
leaders to the Kremlin on Tuesday for tea, a sharp contrast to just
a few weeks ago when he threatened to dissolve Parliament when it
resisted his choice of Sergei Kiriyenko as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders said Wednesday that reports on the Kremlin
session with the president were manipulated to cast them as
toadies. And Wednesday they tried to show their independence by
denouncing the rescue package as a sell-out to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Government opponents say the spending cuts will increase the
burden on ordinary Russians already battered by economic reform.
The Communist Party leader, Gennady Zyuganov, told journalists that
the government's anti-crisis program ``will not resolve the
problems.'' But he also hinted at compromise, saying that his party
will support ``any measures that improve production and raise
responsibility and discipline, regardless of where they come
from.''
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing Tuesday, Anatoly Chubais, Russia's chief
representative in talks with the IMF and World Bank, brushed aside
concerns that the Parliament might reject some of the measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Duma will support the program,'' he predicted,
referring to the lower house of Parliament. ``Of course not all of
the measures require the Duma's support. There are measures which
can be passed by decree of the government and the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
