<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE CARS STILL TOPS IN CUSTOMER SATISFACTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AGOURA HILLS, Calif. _ Though their governments may collapse
with regularity, Japanese car dealerships in the United States
remain dependable, according to an annual J.D. Power and Associates
customer satisfaction survey.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released Wednesday, found that after a year of
driving their vehicles, owners of Toyota Motor Corp.'s Lexus and
Nissan Motor Corp.'s Infiniti automobiles had the fewest complaints
about service they received from their dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The two auto lines have dominated the top spots since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in a distant third this year was General Motors' Saturn,
followed by Ford's Jaguar and Mercury lines. Recent improvements in
Mercury vehicles helped boost the brand from a No. 17 ranking last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, customer satisfaction was higher across the board this
year, the study found, largely because cars continue to be built
better and require less service.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the report at its headquarters northwest of Los
Angeles, J.D. Power officials said quality service ultimately
translates into increased sales for dealers and noted that
customers who are satisfied with their dealership experience are
three times more likely to purchase another vehicle from the same
manufacturer. ``Customers clearly reward good service with loyal
patronage,'' said Joe Ivers, director of customer service research.
</P>
<P>
   With drivers taking better-built cars to the mechanic less
frequently, dealers must concentrate on the quality of service they
deliver in conducting routine maintenance such as oil changes and
tune-ups, Ivers said. The survey found that one-third of services
performed on cars still under warranty is done at independent
service centers such as Jiffy Lube and Midas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2057EDT &QL; 
