<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL ACTIONS ON ABORTION, BUDGET, CENSUS, FARM AID 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J., Md., N.C., Va., N.Y., D-W.Va., Wis., Plains
states)  (ART ADV: Photo with farm aid story is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN CHALLENGE TO CLINTON, HOUSE BACKS AN ABORTION CURB
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Daring President Clinton to cast an election-year
veto on a sensitive issue, the House voted Wednesday to make it a
federal crime for an adult to take a minor to another state for an
abortion to avoid a parental-consent law in the girl's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed that this latest measure in the recurring
abortion war in Congress would not become law. It might be blocked
in the Senate. If not, the White House said, the president's
advisers would recommend that he veto it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was approved by a vote of 276-150, well short of the
two-thirds majority that would be needed to override a veto. But
the meager prospects for enactment did not diminish the intensity
of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   The proponents, most of them Republicans, said the measure was
necessary to prevent unscrupulous adults from sidestepping the law
in the 22 states that require parental notification before minors
may have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate their belief that this happens thousands of times
a year, the proponents waved a poster of enlarged advertisements
from telephone Yellow Pages in Pennsylvania, one of the states with
a notification law, promoting abortion clinics in New Jersey and
Maryland, which do not have such laws. ``No Parental Consent
Required,'' the advertisements said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wrong, and it has to be stopped,'' said Rep. Sue
Myrick, R-N.C..
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., said that the violence of
abortion was compounded ``when strangers scoop up 12- or
13-year-old girls and usher them across state lines.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the bill, most of them Democrats, said that it
would be disastrous for pregnant girls with unloving parents and
would prevent grandparents and male partners from helping desperate
minors in their time of need.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in the bill would encourage parental involvement, said
Rep. Robert Scott, D-Va. He said that would mean that the pregnant
girls would ``have to go alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The real purpose of the legislation, said Rep. Louise Slaughter,
D-N.Y., is to give Republicans ``campaign sound bites'' in which
they could ``label opponents of the bill as anti-parent and
anti-family.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
<P>
   HIGHER SURPLUS ESTIMATE SPURS GOP TAX CUTTERS
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Congressional Budget Office on Wednesday more
than doubled its estimate of the federal budget surplus over the
next decade, emboldening Republicans who want to use some of the
money for tax cuts despite President Clinton's insistence that it
all be set aside until Social Security's financial problems are
solved.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO said it expects the cumulative surplus from 1999 through
2008 to be $1.55 trillion, more than double the $671 billion it
projected in March. The new estimate brings the CBO's outlook
roughly in line with the Clinton administration's most recent
projection of a $1.8 trillion surplus over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   With Washington having hardly had time to adapt to an era of
good fiscal news after decades of huge deficits, both parties
claimed credit for the good news in the budget office's report.
</P>
<P>
   But it was seized on especially by Republicans, who have been
pressing the budget office for months to adopt a more optimistic
view of the nation's fiscal condition to further their tax-cutting
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The CBO said Wednesdy it had detected a largely unexplained
increase in tax revenues and a slightly stronger economic growth
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried early this year to place the surplus off limits to
Republican tax cutters by saying that every penny should be
preserved until the two parties can agree on how to shore up Social
Security for the retirement of the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   His strategy has worked. But as the surplus has grown,
Republicans have begun asserting that it will be big enough to
accommodate tax cuts and a Social Security fix. With Wednesday's
estimates, Republican leaders became more explicit in rejecting
Clinton's ``Social Security first'' demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a whopping $1.5 trillion surplus over 10 years, we can
preserve, protect and strengthen Social Security while also passing
significant tax relief for hard-working Americans,'' said House
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are seeking $100 billion in tax cuts in the
next five years, including reductions in the so-called marriage
penalty paid by many two-income couples. Gingrich has also called
for a reductions in the capital gains tax and in estate taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and moderate Republicans in the House and the Senate
have said a tax cut of that magnitude is politically unrealistic
because it would require painful spending cuts that even
Republicans would not want to defend in a congressional election
year.
</P>
<P>
   But dipping into the surplus would at least partly solve that
problem and allow Republicans to further their efforts at reducing
the size of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the politicians in Washington aren't careful, the surplus
will be used to create more government spending,'' said Rep. Bill
Archer, R-Texas. ``To stop the politicians from spending the money,
I want to use the surplus to pay down the debt, save Social
Security and we should use a portion of it to cut taxes this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats warned that dipping into the surplus now would
jeopardize any chance of reaching a bipartisan consensus on Social
Security and would leave Republicans vulnerable to charges of
putting immediate tax cuts for the wealthy ahead of retirement
security for the baby boomers and their children.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS MONEY HELD UP IN BATTLE OVER METHODS
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Appropriations Committee on Wednesday
approved only half the money the Census Bureau needs to prepare for
the 2000 Census, withholding the rest until Congress and the White
House agree on how best to count the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
   The voice vote Wednesday was the latest skirmish in the
long-running battle pitting Congressional Republicans against
Democrats and the Clinton administration over the bureau's plans to
use statistical methods to supplement the traditional head count in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has said that the use of statistical samples
of the population to estimate the number of people not contacted
directly by census workers would produce a less costly and more
accurate tabulation, and would reduce the number of inner-city
blacks and rural Hispanic residents missed by traditional counting
methods. But Republicans have criticized the plan, saying it is
unconstitutional and is subject to political manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   The committee approved a $33.5 billion spending bill for fiscal
1999, which begins Oct. 1, for the departments of Commerce, Justice
and State, but voted to hold back half of the Census Bureau's
money.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill pays for such government agencies and
operations as the Federal court system, the FBI, the Immigration
and Naturalization Service, the National Weather Service and U.S.
embassies.
</P>
<P>
   In a party-line vote, the committee defeated, 31-22, an
amendment by Rep. Alan Mollohan, D-W.Va., that would have provided
the Census Bureau with its full funding of nearly $952 million
while the National Academy of Sciences determined whether using
statistical methods would produce a more accurate census than the
traditional attempt to count everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Mollohan said his amendment would allow experts to determine the
efficacy of using statistical methods and prevent the issue of the
census from degenerating into a ``barroom political brawl.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote stemmed from an agreement last November between
the White House and congressional Republicans. Details of the
agreement are now in dispute. Administration officials say the two
sides agree that the departments of Commerce, Justice and State
would be financed for half of the next fiscal year until the
dispute over the census is resolved. Republicans say they agreed
only that the Census Bureau would receive money for six months.
</P>
<P>
   _ By STEVEN A. HOLMES
</P>
<P>
   GOP SENATORS DEFEAT DEMOCRATS' FARM PLANS
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted Wednesday along party lines to
reject Democratic proposals to give more federal assistance to
struggling farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The main Democratic measure, billed as essential to keep
thousands of farms from going under in one of the worst years in
more than a decade, would have increased the amount of federal
money farmers could borrow with their crops as collateral and would
have extended the time for repayment.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic proposal, an amendment to a $57 billion bill to
pay for government agriculture programs in the next fiscal year,
was rejected, 56 to 43.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., joined all 55 Republicans in
opposition. All those who voted in favor were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope the vote will work against Republicans running
for election in farm states this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Plains states are a striking exception to the
generally booming national economy. Plunging wheat prices caused
primarily by reduced exports to Asia and a worldwide glut on the
market have crippled many small farms from Minnesota through the
Dakotas and west along the Canadian border to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first big test of the 1996 farm law, which phases
out government crop subsidies, placed a limit on how much farmers
can borrow from the government and ended government controls over
what farmers can plant and when they can plant it.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans believe farmers, like almost all other Americans,
fare best when the government takes a hands-off approach. Democrats
hold that farmers need a strong government safety net to protect
them in bad times.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the loans, the Democratic proposal would have
increased the amount that could be borrowed against a wheat crop,
this year alone, to $3.16 a bushel from $2.58, and would have
lengthened the maximum repayment period to 15 months from 9 months.
Farmers with other crops would have been entitled to similar loans.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, this would help farmers by enabling them to withhold
their crops from the market until the price rose.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM
</P>
