<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HBO &AMP; Co. shares surge after end of merger talks
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- HBO &AMP; Co. stock rebounded Wednesday, after it was
announced the Atlanta-based company had broken off merger talks
with San Francisco-based McKesson Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The leaked information that HBO, the largest U.S. maker of
health care company software, was in merger talks with drug
wholesaler McKesson had caused HBO stock to drop sharply Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, 31.2 million shares changed hands, and HBO was the
third most active stock on U.S. markets. It closed at $33.75, up
$1.68 3/4, or 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson approached HBO three weeks ago and proposed a business
combination that would have been controlled by McKesson, according
to analyst Charles Trafton of Adams Harkness and HBO spokeswoman
Beth Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson would have given HBO access to thousands of customers
for its products along with McKesson's software for managing drug
costs. Meanwhile, HBO's high-profit, high-growth software business
would have bolstered McKesson's slimmer profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HBO board of directors had a fiduciary duty to consider
this offer,'' Trafton said, ``but shot it down because it did not
want the company to be in the drug distribution business. ...
(Furthermore, the parties) could not agree on terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Trafton also said McKesson stock _ which on Monday hit a 52-week
high of $90.12 1/2 _ was probably too expensive, at a time when HBO
can be picky.
</P>
<P>
   HBO split its stock in June. Shares reached a 52-week high of
$38.37 1/2 Monday, the day before HBO reported record
second-quarter earnings that exceeded expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company has no debt, a half-billion dollars in cash and a
$13 billion market capitalization, widely credited to the efforts
of Chief Executive Officer Charles McCall.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, HBO reported net income of $144 million on sales of
$1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now that talks with McKesson have broken down, HBO is likely to
look for another acquisition, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The McKesson deal would have given HBO a presence in every
single area of health care, said Sharon Corr, a Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
analyst. However, she said, HBO could buy a pharmacy software
vendor or some sort of information services company that would be a
better fit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
