<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION TRIES TO BLOCK STARR SUBPOENAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration moved quickly Wednesday
to block subpoenas seeking grand jury testimony from the
president's personal security detail as his private attorneys and
press secretary fired verbal broadsides at independent counsel
Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers from the Justice Department and Starr's staff met behind
closed doors for almost an hour with Chief U.S. District Judge
Norma Holloway Johnson, who oversees the grand jury investigating
an alleged presidential affair and cover-up. The attorneys declined
comment when they emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was prompted by subpoenas Starr issued Tuesday
summoning Larry Cockell, chief of the president's security team,
and six other Secret Service officers to appear Thursday before the
grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has been investigating whether Clinton or his associates
tried to illegally cover up his alleged sexual encounters with
former White House aides Monica Lewinsky and Kathleen Willey.
Clinton and Lewinsky have denied under oath engaging in sex.
Clinton also has denied any inappropriate behavior involving
Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private lawyers, Robert S. Bennett and David Kendall,
accused Starr of going after Cockell in an effort to ``intrude'' on
confidential conversations between the president and his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Cockell frequently stands at Clinton's shoulder when others are
present and rides across from him in the presidential limousine.
Cockell was present when attorneys for Paula Jones questioned
Clinton under oath about alleged sexual liaisons, including with
Lewinsky and Willey, and rode with the president and Bennett to the
White House following the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Bennett and Kendall said Starr was trying
to ``invade the president's right to consult'' with his personal
attorneys. ``Any backdoor attempt by this prosecutor (Starr) to
invade the president's right to consult with personal counsel will
be aggressively and firmly resisted,'' the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Mike McCurry also criticized the
subpoenas from Starr saying it would be wrong for members of the
president's security detail to testify about what they overheard
while protecting him. ``Those are tactics that are certainly
questionable, and that is a mild way of putting it,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential spokesman also accused Starr's staff of
``outrageous and venomous'' behavior and blamed the prosecutor for
a television news report Wednesday suggesting that Secret Service
agents played a role in the president's alleged extra-marital
liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   NBC News reported that Starr's investigators believe some Secret
Service agents ```facilitated' for President Clinton,'' then drew
parallels to accusations that while serving as Arkansas governor
Clinton used state troopers to approach women about possible
liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is utterly outrageous and venomous for Ken Starr to allow
his staff to impugn the integrity of the president of the United
States and people who are required by law to protect him, and if he
had any ounce of decency today, he would tell them to knock it
off,'' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sneering at the president of the United States is common sport
here in Washington now,'' McCurry said. ``But the Secret Service
agents who protect the president of the United States with their
lives are dedicated, serious professionals, and they should not be
slimed by Ken Starr and his operatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr spokesman Charles Bakaly did not return telephone calls
seeking comment on McCurry's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoena for Cockell and the six Secret Service officers was
served Tuesday as the Justice Department asked the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia to overturn a ruling
compelling Secret Service employees to appear before the grand
jury. That order dealt with an attorney for the agency and two
uniformed officers who were not members of the president's personal
security detail.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has argued that forcing testimony by the
officers might cause presidents to be more wary and push them away
when engaged in confidential business, thus increasing the danger
of assassination.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing Wednesday before the Senate Judiciary
Committee, Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch questioned Attorney General
Janet Reno's decision to appeal the ruling and suggested her agency
was part of a ploy to delay Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to appeal at this time calls into serious
question the real motivations of both the Department of Justice and
the Secret Service,'' Hatch told Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said the ruling by a three-judge panel was
appealed because the department believes it is wrong. ``I tell you,
Mr. Chairman, with all my heart, it is not done for delay,'' Reno
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
