<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I-75 bust nets 150 pounds of cocaine, Atlanta couple
 &HT;    By Ron Martz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- With their three children in the back of a motor home
and a station wagon in tow, Frances and Marlinda Barthelemy of
Atlanta appeared to be nothing more than an average family on the
way home from a Florida vacation.
</P>
<P>
   But law enforcement officials said Wednesday that the couple was
part of a major drug distribution ring that supplied large amounts
of cocaine in the Vine City area. On a recent trip to Florida,
authorities said, the Barthelemys picked up about 72 kilograms
(more than 158 pounds) of the drug, wrapped it in duct tape and
stuffed it under a bed in the back of the motor home.
</P>
<P>
   The trip ended late Tuesday, just before the Barthelemys and
their cargo of cocaine _ with an estimated street value of $1.5
million to $3 million _ reached Atlanta. A multi-agency task force
of local, state and federal law enforcement officials had been
investigating the drug ring for more than six months and watching
the couple on their trip to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Agents swooped down on the northbound Winnebago on I-75 in
Forest Park, seized the cocaine and arrested the husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Barthelemy, 34, and Marlinda Barthelemy, 27, are being
held in the Clayton County Jail on federal drug trafficking charges
and awaiting a bond hearing later today. Their three children, sons
ages 4 and 14 and a daughter, 7, have been turned over to
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   A.B. Llewellyn, assistant special agent in charge of the Atlanta
FBI office, said Frances Barthelemy, who owns a small auto repair
shop in south Atlanta, is also wanted in Dooly County on a 1990
bench warrant for failure to appear on a cocaine trafficking
charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Barthelemys were major distributors of cocaine in the
Atlanta area and part of a larger network, Llewellyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people on both ends of the pipeline'' that are still
under investigation, and more arrests are expected, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Deputy Police Chief C.B. Jackson called Tuesday's bust
``a very, very large seizure'' of cocaine for the city.
Investigators believe much of the cocaine was destined to be
processed into crack cocaine for eventual distribution in an area
of Vine City known as ``the Bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a problem area of the city,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the drugs and motor home, law enforcement
officials seized five cars, including a 1998 Mercedes-Benz station
wagon; two pickup trucks; a Harley-Davidson motorcycle; a Land
Rover; and a Sea-Doo personal watercraft from the Barthelemys' home
and business.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
