<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beating the drum for New Orleans
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS -- This city is enjoying a renaissance _ the economy
is recovering from the devastation of the oil bust, and violent
crime, the city's most nagging nemesis, is down dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Residents give a much of the credit to Mayor Marc Morial, the
dapper, 40-year-old son of the city's first black mayor, Dutch
Morial, who served from 1978 to 1986. The younger Morial is
settling into his second term as mayor, a position given to him in
February by more than 80 percent of the voters. His landslide
victory was almost unprecedented here.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent lunch in Morial's private dining room, the mayor
talked about the future of the city as he took bites of chilled
avocado soup heavily laced with Tabasco sauce. And he talked about
his own future, which could include a third race for mayor. That
would mean convincing the voters to change the city's charter,
which sets the limit at two terms. His father tried to change the
charter twice and failed. Morial says he's thinking about trying
anyway, because, simply and not so modestly put, a good mayor is
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a good mayor is tough,'' he said. ``It's very hard to
run these major cities and sustain your popularity and get things
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Q:Even though New Orleans is on an economic rebound, it lags
behind other Southern cities. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A:There's a tension here between tradition and progress, but the
best way to build New Orleans is to blend the two. We're not
Natchez, we're not Charleston. We are a large population center.
But Atlanta, Houston, Dallas, Miami, they catapulted past us in
many ways, because you had a more progressive spirit than you had
here. We are unique, and our uniqueness is something we are going
to preserve. We don't want to be a city that's defined by glass and
steel, by new buildings, but we have to have progress.
</P>
<P>
   Q:There's a fear here that development along the Mississippi
Gulf Coast in connection with the casinos will encroach on New
Orleans' tourism. Is that something you worry about?
</P>
<P>
   A:We can't get angry about competition. We need to expand our
entertainment opportunities. That's why we are building Jazzland _
an amusement park in eastern New Orleans _ and allowing limited
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Crime and police corruption are this city's black eyes. You
fought to keep Police Chief Richard Pennington when he was offered
a chance to return to Washington, D.C., to be that city's chief.
Why was he worth the huge pay raise you gave him to stay here?
</P>
<P>
   A:I think it was an important fight. When you rebuild an
organization like we're rebuilding the police department, you
rebuild it like a team _ around your franchise player. And
Pennington has the confidence of the public. It has been a long
time since we've had that.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What is the hardest issue the police here struggle with?
</P>
<P>
   A:Drug-related murders. They're unpredictable and hard to
police. And we need help from the federal government _ the FBI, the
Drug Enforcement Administration, the ATF. We've got a port out
there. We're a transportation hub. Keeping dope from coming in from
the port _ that's a job for customs and DEA.
</P>
<P>
   Q:New Orleans is on an economic upswing. What are some of the
projects that have happened?
</P>
<P>
   A:There's the (land-based) casino on Canal Street (which went
bankrupt but is now set to reopen), a $250 million expansion of the
convention center downtown, the $80 million Jazzland. And there are
several other projects on the drawing boards, including converting
an old contaminated industrial site _ the American Can Building _
into apartments. There are two new hotels _the Ritz-Carlton is
moving into the old Krauss department store on Canal Street. The
streetcar line is going to be expanded, and we are in the midst of
the three-quarters-of-a-billion (dollar) airport expansion. We're
benefiting from when times got bad. Now, as we rebuild, we are
diversifying our economy.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Beyond possibly running for a third term as mayor, what other
ambitions do you have?
</P>
<P>
   A:Maybe running statewide, possibly for governor. But I'm
realistic _ I don't run for offices I can't win.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
