<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7133 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-FARM-COX     07-15 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-FARM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glickman vows support for farmers
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Even though he is the target of a $2.5 billion race
discrimination lawsuit, Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman joined
with leaders and delegates to the nation's largest and oldest civil
rights group in voicing his support for black farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe what is happening to black farmers, and to America's
small farm heritage is a moral crisis and one that we all have an
obligation to help resolve,'' Glickman told delegates to the NAACP
meeting in Atlanta Wednesday. While NAACP delegates were polite,
some of the farmers who had protested against him earlier in the
day continued their criticism at a news conference after Glickman's
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary reiterated his own findings that the U.S.
Department of Agriculture has discriminated against black farmers
in the past, ``and possibly now.'' Glickman said the legacy he
wants to leave is a department that ``has a better land base that
is diversified and not one of just conglomerate farms.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said he sees the demise of black farms at three times
the rate of farms generally. Twenty-six black farmers from Georgia
are among more than 500 nationwide who have sued Glickman and the
USDA, alleging that the agency discriminated in lending and federal
programs for decades. Black farmers maintain that because of
discriminatory practices, their numbers have dropped from more than
900,000 in 1920 down to 18,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman did not have checks with him Wednesday, telling the
group that Congress must change the law barring payments beyond two
years in discrimination cases involving lending.
</P>
<P>
   J.L. Chestnut, a lead attorney in lawsuits filed by hundreds of
the nation's black farmers, said the Department of Justice shares
some of the blame for holding up the payments to farmers. ``They
are scared because they are afraid it will set a precedent in
dealing with black folks and they will be showered with all kind of
lawsuits,'' Chestnut said in his speech to the NAACP delegation.
``Racism is rampant in the federal government. Regardless of what
Glickman says, the government is going to pay real money to black
folks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These farmers are so upset that if Glickman does not settle,
they will set up a tent city in front of his office until this is
resolved or he resigns,'' Chestnut said. Black farmers say more
than 2,000 discrimination complaints have been filed by black
farmers with USDA.
</P>
<P>
   Protesting black farmers and their supporters early Wednesday
morning said the secretary's rhetoric is not matching his
department's deeds. While several discrimination claims have been
verified by USDA investigators, monetary settlements have not been
made.
</P>
<P>
   John Boyd of the National Black Farmers Association, Gary Grant
of the National Black Agriculturalists Association and Ralph Paige,
director of the Federation of Southern Cooperatives, led a group of
about 100 in a ``march of support'' for black farmers through
downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no victory for Democrats in 2000 without the
support of the black farmers,'' Grant said. Boyd even had his mule,
named Struggles, in the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel less than a slave because I can't support my family,''
said black farmer Lynwood Brown.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP President Kweisi Mfume and Chairman Julian Bond said the
nation's oldest civil rights group stands with black farmers and
urges a repeal of the legislation barring the granting of loans to
any farmers that has experienced a loan restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Both voiced support for the full funding of the Minority Rights
Act, which would provide $10 million in technical assistance for
minority farmers, repeal of federal provisions that bar farmers
from making new loans if they've had old debts, lifting of the
two-year statute of limitations on filing discrimination claims in
lending and the implementation of the Civil Rights Action Team
report prepared at Glickman's direction that outlined 92 steps to
correct discrimination within the department and its field offices.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
