A7134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT16-COX     07-15 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-SPOTLIGHT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can Gore deliver? That's issue for new NAACP leaders
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter'
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The NAACP convention Vice President Al Gore comes to
address today has had its fiery moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the civil rights era, when the NAACP leaned more toward doing
battling segregation through the courts than some other
organizations, it would have been unusual for its president to
suggest a protest at the Supreme Court building, as Kweisi Mfume
did this week in calling attention to the high court's abysmal
record of minority hiring.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of increasing ethnic and political complexity, Mfume's
priorities have been to focus and energize the organization that
can still make the broadest claim to speak for black America, and
the outspoken former congressman from Baltimore has been very
effective in doing so.
</P>
<P>
   But the rousing convention also occurs as black political
leaders are growing increasingly pragmatic in endorsements and less
reliant on traditional litmus tests.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 15 years ago, it would have been a shock to see
Birmingham Mayor Richard Arrington take sides in an Alabama
Republican primary, as he did with his endorsement of Winton
Blount. (For that matter, it would have been a surprise to see
House Speaker Newt Gingrich weighing in on the side of a black
Republican in the 2nd Congressional District primary.)
</P>
<P>
   In the Georgia governor's race, the endorsement of Roy Barnes, a
legislator who once opposed the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday
bill, by black leaders such as Rep. Cynthia McKinney and former
Mayor Maynard Jackson also would have seemed an odd fit a few years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this year McKinney has been so staunch in her support that
when a flier attributing a racist remark to Barnes proved to be
inaccurate, McKinney went to a radio studio unannounced and cut a
spot she'd written, urging black voters to send a message to ``the
good old boys from the bad old days'' by voting for Barnes. It was
more than the Cobb legislator could have dared asked for, and he
hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black voters in my opinion are more interested in delivery
than in promises,'' Jackson said recently, reflecting on his
endorsement. Aside from a greater emphasis by black voters on equal
rights, he said, ``there is virtually no difference in what whites
and blacks want.''
</P>
<P>
   Black politics is becoming ``a bit more opportunistic'' than it
has in the past, said William Boone, a political scientist at
Clark-Atlanta University, with less emphasis on finding the
``morally correct'' candidates and more on those ``not necessarily
spotless'' who can bring home the goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a moving away from the broad kinds of issues,
toward the idea of talking about specifics and getting behind the
folks who can win and bring a degree of prosperity to the
community,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   This should be good news for a mainstream Democrat such as Gore,
who in any case has shown a surprising ability with the cadences of
the civil rights movement in speeches like the one he gave at this
year's King holiday observance at Ebenezer Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   But today's audience will be listening less for the rhetoric in
the upcoming race for the presidential nomination, and thinking
more about what the candidates can deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
