<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-BOOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWANS COMING BACK TO THE FUTURE ... AND HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(JT) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBUQUE, Iowa _ From the porch views of the Victorian-era houses
sitting high on the limestone bluffs over the Mississippi River, it
looked like a sad parade on the streets of Dubuque in the '80s, an
exodus of downhearted Iowans fleeing the farm-crisis economy.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, with unemployment rates over 14 percent, young
Iowans with roots five or six generations deep came to see their
future prospects here as hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Dubuque, a city of some 60,000 people, has a new and
enviable problem: too many good jobs and not enough workers. With
an employment rate below 4 percent, and a flurry of new and growing
Dubuque companies in the fields of computer programming, publishing
and marketing, employers lament a shortage of workers.
</P>
<P>
   So Dubuque civic and business officials have begun an aggressive
program to bring back its sons, daughters and grandchildren. The
campaign, ``Come back to your future _ come home to Dubuque,'' has
included a site on the Internet and mailings to high-school and
college graduates. There have also been newspaper and radio
advertisements directed at the parents and grandparents of former
Dubuquers, urging them to persuade their offspring to return.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's wonderful to be home,'' said John Link, whose wife, Teri,
and daughter, Tabitha, 2, are among the more than 30 families who
have returned to Iowa since the recruitment efforts began around
last Christmas. ``When I left, I never thought it would be
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The flourishing economy of Dubuque underscores the
transformation of the economy in the rural Midwestern states like
Iowa, which once depended almost solely on agriculture. Dubuque is
now home to three textbook companies, a far cry from when the local
economy was dominated by the John Deere tractor factory and a
meatpacking plant.
</P>
<P>
   Link, 30, left Dubuque after graduating from high school in
1986, eventually settling in the Northern Virginia suburbs, with a
job in a marketing department in Washington. Ms. Link, 31 and also
from Iowa, worked as a paralegal.
</P>
<P>
   For young families that have grown weary of life in congested,
expensive suburban settings, small cities and towns in the
countryside have lately become quite appealing, known for safe
streets and good schools.
</P>
<P>
   For employers in Dubuque, as in many smaller cities in the
Midwest, they need more technologically literate workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking $6-an-hour jobs here, but jobs that pay $15
and $20 an hour,'' said Mike Walker, the general manager of Dubuque
Data Services, a computer-programming company that has recently
grown to 56 people, from 38 in November, including 6 new hires from
Dubuque's Web site recruitment campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Links cherished living in a metropolitan area, especially
the sense of excitement and diversity. But they also found it
expensive, and more than a bit stressful, especially after the
birth of their daughter. With Ms. Link expecting another child in
the fall, the couple took a close look at Dubuque after hearing
about the job surplus and recruitment efforts. Link easily found a
good job in sales for an advertising company, and they moved back
to Dubuque in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is so much easier now,'' said Ms. Link, who added that
she could now afford to be a stay-at-home mother. ``Around
Washington, it took forever to get anywhere. Now I'm five minutes
from the countryside, five minutes from the mall. You just feel
like you can relax and breathe here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Links acknowledged that there were trade-offs for the
slower-paced life: fewer restaurants, stores, less cultural
diversity. Some acquaintances around Washington were dumbfounded by
their decision to move to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some would say, `Oh, I'm so sorry,'' Ms. Link said, referring
to people who assumed that her husband was being forced to transfer
to a job in Iowa. ``A lot of people don't even know where it is.
They get it confused with Idaho or Ohio. They think its some
desolate region with nothing but cornfields.''
</P>
<P>
   With architecture that goes back more than 150 years, Dubuque
can be postcard pretty, its steep hills and rugged bluffs
overlooking the nation's most storied river, the Old Mississippi.
Stylish boutiques and coffee shops line Bluff Street. And it takes
less than a half-hour to get to the Illinois tourist town of
Galena, 15 miles to the southeast, with its antique stores and
historical sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wake up in the morning and see a sky that's cobalt blue,''
Link said. ``You forget about what smog was.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also a much more affordable place for a young family. In
the Virginia suburbs, a cracker-box town house cost about $150,000,
Link said. Now the couple have a three-bedroom house with three
bathrooms, a fireplace, a two-car garage and a nice yard _ for
$108,000.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important than anything else, little Tabitha never
goes more than a day or two without seeing a grandparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spoil her rotten,'' Ms. Link said, confessing that she
and her husband had also got a bit spoiled. ``Now we've got baby
sitters whenever we want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
