<SLUG> BC-METS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS ARE PUT IN THEIR PLACE: FAR, FAR BACK  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After winning a surprising 88 games last year, the
Mets came into this season believing that they could finally
challenge the Atlanta Braves in the National League East. On May
31, fresh off their biggest trade in more than a decade and after
winning their ninth straight game, the Mets _ bolstered by the
addition of Mike Piazza _ trailed the Braves by just five games.
</P>
<P>
   But if Wednesday's embarrassing 12-1 drubbing at the hands of
the most dominant team in the league proved anything, it was that
the gap between the Mets and the Braves is widening, not shrinking.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt in anyone's mind, Andres Galarraga
pounded the point home with two 400-foot-plus home runs, one of
which cleared the retaining fence behind the left-field bullpen at
Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to improve to be as good as them,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine conceded after the Mets had lost for the 11th time in
their last 15 games. ``We have to pitch better, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of those losses have come in the Mets' first five meetings
with the Braves this season. And on the eve of a suddenly important
four-game set with the resurgent Philadelphia Phillies, the Mets
(46-43) have fallen a season-high 13{ games behind the Braves for
the third time this season. The Phillies, who lost, 3-2, in
Milwaukee Wednesday, also trail the Braves by 13{.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder, then, that trade talks involving third baseman
Robin Ventura of the Chicago White Sox appear to have heated up
again for the Mets?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' brightest spot Wednesday came when their forgotten
reliever, Mel Rojas, pitched two scoreless middle innings, with the
Mets behind by 9-1, in his first appearance in two weeks. Enough
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since their nine-game winning streak, the Mets are 15-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything,'' said John Franco, who allowed four
hits and three runs in pitching the ninth, the day before the
hearing of his three-game suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of mind-boggling. At one time, we were 11 games over
.500. It just shows how bad we've played the last six weeks. I
don't know if today was the lowest point of the season. But it's a
low point.''
</P>
<P>
   Can things sink much lower?
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to see how they could for Masato Yoshii (4-5), who
has not won since May 27 _ a span of nine starts. After allowing
seven runs and nine hits in three and two-thirds innings Wednesday
_ including back-to-back first-inning home runs to Galarraga and
Ryan Klesko as the Braves jumped to a 3-0 lead _ the Japanese's
right-hander's earned run average is 4.13.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Yoshii nor his best friend, Hideo Nomo, has a victory
since the Mets acquired Nomo from the Los Angeles Dodgers on June
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm pitching all that poorly,'' said Yoshii, who
was tagged for five hits in the fourth before Bill Pulsipher came
in. ``Maybe they're picking up on certain patterns of how I'm
approaching hitters,'' he said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga surely picked up on something from both Yoshii and
Pulsipher. The Atlanta first baseman's three-run moon shot off
Pulsipher closed the book on Yoshii, capped a six-run fourth and
gave the Braves the 9-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Galarraga, who has 30 home runs, was asked if the
Braves have invaded the Mets' collective psyche and convinced them
that they cannot beat the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, probably,'' Galarraga said. ``Especially with
beating them five times already. The more beatings, they get more
frustrated, we get more positive and that's the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was asked if the wild card was all the Mets have to look
forward to. ``It kind of seems that way now,'' said the catcher,
who drove in the Mets' only run with a third-inning double off
Denny Neagle (10-7). ``I think we have to get realistic and stop
looking at the big lead they have. We have to worry about doing
what we can to start going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who had just four hits Wednesday, had better start
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are at Shea beginning Thursday night and the
Pirates follow on Monday, before the Mets travel to Milwaukee and
Chicago. The Brewers and Cubs are both in the wild-card race, along
with the Phillies, Giants and Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hundley, who was out of the starting lineup for the first
time since rejoining the team last Saturday, described the Phillies
and the Pirates as scrappy teams. The Braves, he said, are a
quality team.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was asked what adjective he would use to describe the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good question,'' he said. ``Right in between scrappy and
legitimate contenders. We have to do the little things to become
legitimate contenders. Galarraga had an incredible day. They do the
big things.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
