<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADET-TRIAL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS EX-CADET WAS NOT PRESENT AT KILLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT THARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Calling it ``an all-or-nothing defense,''
David Graham's attorney told jurors Wednesday that the former Air
Force Academy cadet was not present when 16-year-old Adrianne Jones
was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Dan Cogdell said during opening statements in
the capital murder trial that Graham is guilty only of trying to
cover up for a ``terrible woman's vengeance,'' referring to
Graham's former fiance, Diane Zamora. He said Zamora believed
incorrectly that Graham had sex with Jones, triggering her death
wish for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The defense scenario contrasts with prosecutor Mike Parrish's
opening arguments that Graham and Zamora participated equally in
the beating and shooting death of Jones, a sophomore at Mansfield
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell would not say Wednesady whether his client will testify
durig the trial. Zamora, who was convicted of the killing, has been
subpoenaed to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's defense also contradicts Zamora's testimony during her
February capital murder trial. She testified that both were present
and that Graham killed Jones and forced Zamora to go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``David and Diane, the evidence will show, did this capital
murder together,'' Parrish said, raising his voice and placing his
two fists together on a table in front of the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish spent 20 minutes outlining the case against Graham,
which he said will include evidence that he and Zamora lured Jones
out of her Mansfield home on a school night, struck her with a
weight and shot her after she stumbled away and collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As defenseless Adrianne Jones lay in that field on the ground,
David Graham puts two bullets in her head,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cogdell said Graham loved Zamora so much that he agreed to
take the blame with her if she was caught. He said Zamora, a Naval
Academy midshipman at the time of her September 1996 arrest, was
consumed with jealousy because she thought Graham had sex with
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   During Zamora's trial, her attorney suggested that Graham and
Jones did not have sex, but no witnesses testified about the
matter. Parrish and Cogdell said in their opening remarks that the
two could not have had sex. One witness, a former cross-country
teammate of Jones and Graham, testified that she drove Jones home
from a track meet on the night that Graham said in his police
confession that the two had a tryst.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening remarks, Cogdell explained a late-night phone
call from Graham to Jones the night of her slaying by saying that
Graham wanted to warn Jones that Zamora might do ``something
terrible.'' Cogdell did not say how or why Jones would leave her
house with Zamora if Graham had warned Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane Zamora did kill Adrianne Jones. David Graham did not.
David Graham was not there,'' he said. ``... He didn't love her; he
worshipped her. She filled a void in him, a need, a hole that had
been with him a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, 20, pleaded not guilty to the charge of capital murder.
He faces life in prison if convicted of kidnapping and killing
Jones in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell told jurors that he will highlight differences between
Zamora's oral and written statements about the slaying, and show
that Graham's written statement is ``a piece of fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   By insisting that Graham was not present, Graham's attorneys may
lose the chance to argue that Graham is guilty of a lesser offense
than capital murder, such as murder or kidnapping, said Fort Worth
attorney Bill Lane, who has been analyzing the trial since jury
selection began last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you stand up and say `My client was not there,'
you're not going to have lesser charges,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell also attacked the way Grand Prairie detectives conducted
the investigation, saying they were more concerned about making an
arrest than properly investigating the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented nine witnesses on the first day of
testimony, including Jones' mother, Linda Jones. She described her
daughter _ often using the present tense _ as ``bright,
energy-plus, bouncing-off-the-wall happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after sitting down in the witness stand, Linda Jones
moaned and sobbed after spotting the handgun that was introduced as
evidence for a previous witness but that had not been removed from
the stand.
</P>
<P>
   Over defense objections, Parrish showed the jury more than a
dozen enlarged photos of Jones' body, as well as close-ups of the
gunshot and other wounds that Jones suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the jury of seven men, five women and one
female alternate took notes but displayed no visible reaction to
the photos.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
