<SLUG> BC-U.S.-INDIA-PAKISTAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTES TO WAIVE LAST SANCTIONS ON INDIA AND PAKISTAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate unanimously agreed Wednesday to give
President Clinton authority to temporarily waive most remaining
economic sanctions on India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed without dissent as an amendment to an
agriculture appropriations bill when its main opponent, Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, was in Cape Canaveral, Fla., training to be an
astronaut for his coming space mission.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the measure said it would give the United States more
flexibility in dealing with the spread of nuclear arms in South
Asia, and erase a penalty that hurt American businesses more than
the targeted countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unilateral sanctions rarely achieve their goals,'' said Sen.
Pat Roberts, R-Kan. ``They hurt American workers and diminish U.S.
strength in international affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to pressure from farmers, both the House and Senate in
the past week had overwhelmingly exempted grain sales from the
sanctions imposed on India and Pakistan after those two countries
conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan was scheduled Wednesday to put out for bid an order for
350,000 metric tons of wheat, a contract worth more than $40
million that American wheat farmers would have been barred from
bidding on had the sanctions remained in place.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clinton administration had also sought wider authority
to waive all other sanctions, except military aid, as a diplomatic
tool to entice India and Pakistan to curb their nuclear arms
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Senate agreed to give Clinton that power for up
to one year. Clinton would be required to consult with Congress on
his decision, and the Secretary of State would have to report to
Congress on the economic and national security developments in
Pakistan and India.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would allow Clinton to waive restrictions contained
in the Arms Export Control Act. It would restore financing from the
Export-Import Bank, and provide for the extension of loans or
technical assistance from international organizations like the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had already sidestepped some of those
provisions by defining certain assistance as humanitarian aid,
which is exempted from the law. Wednesday's action is the first
step toward enactment. The Senate still has to approve the
underlying appropriations bill. The House would also have to concur
and, if necessary, negotiate any differences in a conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Glenn, the author of the original sanctions
legislation, blocked the broader waiver authority from being
attached to the exemption on grain sales. Glenn said granting the
president that authority would render the sanctions effectively
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   With the grain sales exempted, however, senators acknowledged
that the largest and most painful penalty had been removed, leaving
little to punish India and Pakistan for conducting tests that drew
international condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Glenn, Jack Sparks, said the senator would
continue to fight the broader waiver authority. ``This bill still
has to go conference, and we can oppose it along the way,'' Sparks
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0473 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7147 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-CADET-HNS &LR;      07-15 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CADET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS FORMER AIR FORCE CADET LIED TO PROTECT ZAMORA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Prosecutors have called this the ``David
and Diane did it'' case, but when former Air Force Academy cadet
David Graham's capital murder trial began Wednesday, defense
lawyers offered a radically different version of events:
</P>
<P>
   Graham's ex-fiancee _ former Naval Academy midshipman Diane
Zamora _ did it all by herself, they said, acting out of jealousy
over a romantic liaison that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Graham, 20, said he lied when he told Zamora he had
sex with 16-year-old Adrianne Jones, and he lied again when he
confessed to helping Zamora kill the girl on the night of Dec. 4,
1995 on a remote road south of Grand Prairie near Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his client spent two hours typing out an elaborate
confession to the crime following his arrest in 1996, defense
attorney Dan Cogdell insisted Wednesday that ``David Graham was not
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In his opening statement, Cogdell conceded that his client had
telephoned Jones a few hours before her slaying. But rather than
luring her to her death, Cogdell said, Graham made a fruitless
attempt to warn her that Zamora was in a jealous rage because she
suspected Graham and Jones were romantically involved. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Graham later helped cover up his high school sweetheart's
crime, cleaning blood from the car and hiding the murder weapon,
Cogdell told jurors.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``He vowed to Diane that night that if they were ever caught,
he would confess along with her,'' the lawyer said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Graham and Zamora were arrested months later after Zamora
confided in her new classmates at the Naval Academy in Annapolis,
Md., and they turned her in. Both signed confessions saying they
plotted and carried out Jones' murder. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Zamora, 20, was convicted and sentenced to life in prison in a
separate trial in Fort Worth last February. Graham's trial was
moved to New Braunfels because of publicity. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; At the Jones family's request, prosecutors did not seek the
death penalty for either of the defendants. If Graham is convicted
of capital murder, he will receive a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors told the seven-man, five-woman jury Wednesday that
Graham and Zamora acted together to lure Jones from her Tarrant
County home late one Sunday night, then killed her for coming
between them.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers also conceded that a key portion of Graham's
confession _ his written account of a one-night stand with Jones
after a track meet about a month before her fatal shooting _ was
bogus, and they presented evidence to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Bartlett, a former Mansfield High School student who was a
cross-country teammate of Graham and Jones, told jurors the
encounter could not have occurred. Bartlett, who did not testify in
Zamora's trial, said Wednesday that she, not Graham, had given
Jones a ride home from school that night.
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said Graham had fabricated the story during an argument
with Zamora. The tale of the affair sent Zamora into a rage that
caused her to kill Jones, the lawyer asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors agreed that Graham's lie about the affair led to
Jones' death, but they said it was Graham who shot Jones twice in
the head after Zamora clobbered her with a lead weight. The murder
weapon was later found in the attic of Graham's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's untrue story to Diane is that ... the little harlot
(Jones) had taken advantage of him,'' said prosecutor Mike Parrish,
referring to Graham's confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a rage, she (Zamora) demands the death of Adrianne Jones,''
Parrish said. ``Inexplicably, he goes along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell told jurors that Parrish was only ``half right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Diane Zamora did kill Adrianne Jones. David Graham did not,''
he said. ``David Graham was not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cogdell said Graham later gave a ``false confession'' to help
his former true love, Zamora, whom he worshipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``She filled a need in him, a hole in him that had been there
some time,'' said Cogdell, describing Graham as somewhat of a loner
who had never done well in relationships with girls before meeting
Zamora.
</P>
<P>
   They met through a mutual interest _ the Civil Air Patrol _ and
vowed to get married in 2000 after graduating from their respective
military academies.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham came to learn that Zamora was a ``very jealous
woman,'' Cogdell said. ``She accused David Graham on a regular,
almost-constant basis of being unfaithful. She would create
scenarios and accusations in her mind that had no basis in fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``David would deny, deny, deny those accusations,'' but Zamora
``would fixate on them,'' he said. ``She knew David had a high
opinion of Adrianne Jones and she seized on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother, Linda Jones, provided the day's most
poignant moment the second she sat in the witness chair. Noticing
that the murder weapon, a Russian Army pistol, had been left on the
witness stand by the previous witness, Jones burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you move that?'' she asked sheepishly before asking for a
break to compose herself.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, she described her daughter as a bright,
happy sophomore whose goal was to earn a soccer scholarship to
college. She worked part time at a fried chicken outlet in
Mansfield, which is just southeast of Fort Worth, while dedicating
herself to athletics to overcome a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Jones told jurors that the last time she saw her daughter,
she was in her bedroom studying and getting her clothes ready to
wear to school the next day. The teen-ager apparently left the
house later, without her family's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, she was found shot to death in a rural area
near Joe Pool Lake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
