<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: NO STATUS IS RANGERS' STATUS QUO  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Up on the stage, the Rangers had their ducks all in a row: Mike
Richter, Dave Checketts, Neil Smith, John Muckler, Brian Leetch.
And now Smith, the president and general manager, stood at the
lectern and mentioned how it had been ``a very exciting and
nerve-racking'' few months.
</P>
<P>
   Exciting and nerve-racking months?
</P>
<P>
   Smith had to be thinking of April, May and June in 1994, when
the Rangers won the Stanley Cup with Richter as their goaltender.
Those months were exciting and nerve-racking, but since then almost
nothing about the Rangers has been exciting and nerve-racking.
</P>
<P>
   But no, Smith was talking about the prolonged salary
negotiations with Richter, no longer a free agent now that he has
signed a four-year, $21.8 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Exciting and nerve-racking? Maybe to Smith, who couldn't afford
to antagonize Ranger loyalists again after Mark Messier's departure
to Vancouver a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But to anyone else, the Rangers, in retaining Richter, merely
retained a segment of their status quo that no longer has much
status in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Rangers' hierarchy, this is what passes now for
exciting and nerve-racking. And with the Knicks temporarily out of
business in a summer of labor discontent in the National Basketball
Association, this is also what passes for exciting and
nerve-racking at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   If the NBA lockout delays the start of the Knicks' season or
cancels it, another bad Ranger team will be all the more glaring at
the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For his $21.8 million, Richter bought the annual party line,
saying that with the Rangers, he had a ``good chance of winning a
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, must have been thinking of the 1994 Rangers, not last
season's Rangers, who skated on a treadmill to oblivion, finishing
below even the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for Wayne Gretzky, last season's Rangers might not
have qualified for the American Hockey League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, retaining Richter was important. He is a good goaltender.
In the 1994 playoffs he was a great goaltender, but he might never
be that sharp again. If the Rangers don't get better as a team, he
will never need to be that sharp again.
</P>
<P>
   Retaining Richter did not improve the Rangers for Coach John
Muckler; looking back on the Messier mess, retaining Richter merely
improved their public relations.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were not wrong in not offering Messier a three-year
contract. Battered and bruised even before he turned 37 at
midseason, he wasn't worth Vancouver's three-year, $18 million
investment. But the Rangers had alienated their loyalists with the
way the Messier negotiations were mishandled.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Messier's mess helped Richter get all the
millions the goaltender wanted because Smith couldn't afford
another free-agent faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts, the Garden president, told of walking along Madison
Avenue on Tuesday as a Ranger loyalist leaned out of a car window
and yelled, ``Sign Richter.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Leetch isn't signed to a new contract by next July 1,
Smith will be confronted with another potentially explosive
free-agent situation.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Rangers are to be a much better team, Smith needs to
obtain a few better players, especially a goal scorer for Gretzky's
line. Their only free-agent acquisitions have been John MacLean,
the former Devils right wing, and Scott Fraser, another right wing.
Still out there are Ziggy Palffy, who had 45 goals for the
Islanders last season, and Scott Niedermayer, the Devils
defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Smith talked of making a trade or two before training camp opens
in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unreasonable to think that you're going to trade for a
superstar,'' he said. ``With 27 teams, there just aren't enough
superstars to go around, but I'm hopeful we can make some trades
that will make an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   While Smith endured his exciting and nerve-racking negotiations
with Richter, other teams were signing free agents with impact. The
Dallas Stars grabbed Brett Hull, the Chicago Blackhawks landed Doug
Gilmour and the Red Wings took defenseman Uwe Krupp.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Rangers' coming season (and playoffs?) do not
appear to be too exciting and nerve-racking.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
