<HEADER>
A7160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TIMESSQUARE-SUBWAY     07-15 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMESSQUARE-SUBWAY-ART-200&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES SQUARE SUBWAY STATION TO GET LONG-AWAITED RENOVATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Times Square subway station _ a bewildering snarl
of grime-encrusted tunnels that is the neglected basement of what
has become the city's most animated neighborhood _ is finally about
to receive the renovation that has been promised for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials requested bids this week for the first phase
of an eight-year, $180 million project to redesign and refurbish
the city's busiest subway station, widening corridors and adding
staircases and elevators for the thick crowds of workers,
theatergoers and tourists that have begun flooding into the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   The project will replace the station's filthy tiles and
gum-plated floors, seen by 500,000 riders a day, with bright walls
and nonslip granite, highlighted with stainless steel accents and
restored mosaics. Several major artworks will be installed,
including a 53-foot-long porcelain mural of a futuristic subway
that Roy Lichtenstein created for the station before he died last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority is scheduled to award
the contract for the first phase of the project in October, and
construction _ which will disrupt subway service on and off for
years _ should begin by spring 1999.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The project is a scaled-down version of a much more grandiose
plan that was unveiled in the early 1990s, before the recession
caused real estate developers to pull out of a plan to contribute
$90 million for a large rotunda and underground shopping plaza.
Now, despite the boom that has transformed the Times Square area
into a family-friendly arcade of theaters and shops, the MTA is
paying for the entire project itself.
</P>
<P>
   Several good-government groups have criticized the MTA for not
requiring developers who are profiting from the boom to build
escalators into the station or to contribute to its upkeep. But by
using public money for the project, transit officials say, they are
at least able to assure riders that this renovation will actually
take place, unlike the many false starts that have left the station
a decaying monument to the haphazard subway competition of the
early 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really it,'' said MTA Chairman E. Virgil Conway.
``It's really going to happen. No more diddling around.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTA has already begun closing off darkened corners of the
station to prepare for the construction, and telling underground
merchants to prepare for relocation. After 37 years of operation,
the Record Mart, a renowned Latino music store near the north end
of the N and R subway platforms, will have to move to make way for
an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not sure I believe it's real,'' said Jesse
Moskowitz, who has owned the store since its opening in 1961. ``But
this time they sound very serious. We're getting ready to move.''
</P>
<P>
   For most riders, the most striking change, in addition to the
new walls, ceilings and floors, will be the changes to the
mezzanine above the platforms, an area filled throughout the day by
nearly impassable streams of riders transferring between the
shuttle and the north-south lines. To ease pedestrian circulation,
the project will widen the main corridor under 42nd Street, at the
north end of the Seventh Avenue platform, by about 15 feet,
improving sight lines and removing sharp corners.
</P>
<P>
   Ventilation will be slightly improved, although no fans will be
installed. Elevators will for the first time make the station
accessible to the handicapped, and signs will be clearer, aiding
the thousands of tourists whose first venture into subway riding
often begins at Times Square and ends abruptly when they become
hopelessly disoriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finally going to make things the way we always would
have liked them,'' said William Madden, the program manager for the
project. He noted that the 94-year-old station was an agglomeration
of four lines originally run by two competing subway companies,
which accounts for its glued-together nature.
</P>
<P>
   The design of the project won high praise from riders' groups
and the Municipal Art Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very handsome, very intelligent,'' said Brendan Sexton,
the art society's president, who recently saw the completed plans.
``They've really taken into account pedestrian travel underground,
improving the lines of sight and way-finding.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sexton said he was disappointed that the MTA was letting
property owners off the hook by not requiring them to build
escalators and large entrances to the station, even though most
received tax breaks for building in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said he did not think that the extra staircases were
important enough to warrant seeking contributions from developers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
