<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLOMBIA TAKES STEP TOWARD PEACE AS GROUPS PLAN TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Although peace remains a distant goal,
Colombia seems to have made more progress toward ending its
34-year-old civil war in just six days than during the past six
years combined.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Colombia's second-largest guerrilla organization
and civilian groups agreed to hold a national convention somewhere
in Colombia before Oct. 12 in an effort to reach a permanent peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, leaders of the country's right-wing paramilitary
death squads, which have been attacking the guerrillas and their
civilian supporters, announced that they too are willing to open
peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel accord and the paramilitary statement came six days
after a historic encounter between President-elect Andres Pastrana
and the top commanders of Colombia's largest guerrilla group, the
Rebel Armed Forces of Colombia, known by its Spanish initials FARC.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana, who takes office Aug. 7, journeyed into the Colombian
mountains last Thursday for a secret meeting with the guerrilla
chieftains. The two sides agreed to initiate peace negotiations
before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of talks held in a 13th-century monastery near
the German city of Wurzburg, leaders of the rebel National
Liberation Army, or ELN, said they would consider ending its
practices of kidnapping for ransom and attacking the nation's vital
oil pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met and got to know the guerrillas. I think they are telling
us the truth,`` said a buoyant Jaime Bernal Cuellar, Colombia's
attorney general, who took part in the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an unexpected opening,'' added Leon Valencia, a
guerrilla, in an interview from Germany with the Bogota station
Radionet. ``It's a good beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombians were especially pleased because the pending peace
talks will be the first in six years. The last serious attempt at
negotiations between the government and rebels broke down in March
1992 shortly after they began in Tlaxcala, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the rebels have gained the upper hand in the war,
which has left tens of thousands dead and displaced 1 million of
Colombia's 32 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Few believe the guerrillas can overthrow the government. But the
insurgents, who number between 10,000 and 15,000, have dealt the
120,000 troops of the poorly trained Colombian army a series of
humiliating defeats. The rebels now maintain a presence in about
half of the country's 1,071 municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   During the past four years, the rebels refused to negotiate with
the government of President Ernesto Samper. They consider his
administration illegitimate because Samper was elected in 1994 with
the help of $6.1 million from the Cali cocaine cartel.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the 21-point agreement was signed by ELN
representatives and a delegation made up of some of Colombia's most
prestigious academics, business leaders, union officials and
clergy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ELN refused to disarm or to discuss a cease-fire,
the document includes provisions to ``humanize'' the war. For
example, the rebels agreed to refrain from using anti-personnel
mines in conflict zones and renounced the kidnappings of the
elderly, children and pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN said it would renounce kidnappings-for-ransom altogether
if alternative means of financing the organization were available.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the ELN and FARC rebels earned about $1.1 billion last
year through kidnappings, extortion and protection payments from
drug traffickers, according to a government document published last
week in the Bogota newsweekly Cambio 16.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues spelled out in the accord include holding a
nationwide forum to discuss Colombia's oil policies. The ELN
contends that foreign oil companies are robbing the nation's
natural resources and has dynamited pipelines more than 500 times
in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Once the forum begins, the ELN has promised to refrain from
attacking oil pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts believe that after more than three decades of
war, the rebels will ultimately reject the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Francisco Mesa of the Bogota group Pais Libre, which
assists the relatives of kidnapping victims, said the ELN's pledge
to stop snatching pregnant women and children means little since
they usually abduct well-to-do ranchers and businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Alfredo Rangel, a former security adviser to the Samper
government, said the guerrillas may be attempting to win political
favor at home and abroad as they prepare for war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dialogue (may be) part of a political tactic within a war
strategy,`` Rangel said. ``They will continue to develop their
plans for war.``
</P>
<P>
   Others are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to believe that, for the first time in a long time,
there exists a sincere desire for peace within the armed
insurgency,'' wrote columnist Enrique Santos Calderon in the Bogota
daily El Tiempo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
John Otis is a free-lance journalist who wrote this for the Houston
Chronicle. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
