<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JULY 16
</HEADLINE>
  Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and   dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CHERNOW-PROFILE-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 12,
about the author Ron Chernow and his best-selling book ``Titan: The
Life of John D. Rockefeller Sr.,'' omitted two words from Mr.
Chernow's comment about Rockefeller in an interview. Mr. Chernow
said, with the restored words shown by italics, ``Rockefeller was
(ital) vilified as (unital) the great corporate criminal of his
age.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of an editing error, the article also misstated the date
of the interview. It was on June 17, not last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a fax message pointing out these errors, Mr. Chernow also
disputed an assertion in the article that part of the reason the
Rockefeller family went to him for a biography was their interest
in Rockefeller's illegitimate sisters. He said the family did not
know of their existence.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-PROTON-DECAY-NYT (moved on Monday, July 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 13,
about theories on the end of the universe misstated the name of the
institute in Princeton, N.J., with which Dr. Frank Wilczek, a
physicist, is affiliated. It is the Institute for Advanced Study,
not the Institute of Advanced Studies.
</P>
<P>
   BC-LUCKYBASTARD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Sunday, July 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, July 12,
about Charles McCarry's novel ``Lucky Bastard'' misstated the year
of the Hungarian uprising against Soviet domination. It was 1956,
not 1955.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCHULZ-CROCODILES-NYT (moved on Monday, July 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 13,
about the Polish writer Bruno Schulz, reversed the publication
order of his two books of reminiscences. ``The Street of
Crocodiles,'' initially titled ``Cinnamon Shops,'' appeared first,
in Poland in 1934. ``The Sanatorium Under the Sign of the
Hourglass'' was published in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   BC-HAND-PAINTED-WALLPAPER-NYT (moved on Wednesday, June 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, June
24, about the growth of luxury wallpaper misstated sales figures
for the Imperial Home Decor Group's Van Luit line. They were $2
million in 1996, not $200 million, and the company projects sales
of $4 million for 1998, not $400 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
