r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAY-RIGHTS-TEX     07-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-RIGHTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY RIGHTS ISSUES BACK, NETTLING REPUBLICANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1997 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The stalled confirmation of a gay ambassadorial
appointee, a White House directive on gay rights and a new ad
campaign by Christian conservatives have forced lawmakers to revive
a once-taboo topic that inflames activists but draws a mixed
reaction from most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Normandy landing in the larger cultural war,''
said Robert Knight of the Family Research Council, one of the
conservative groups behind the ad campaign. ``We're basically not
going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   But most lawmakers are not exactly rushing to the front lines.
Some Republicans worry the issue will explode in their faces by
making the party appear intolerant. And while the debate energizes
Christian conservatives on behalf of the GOP, it also increases
support for Democrats in the wealthy and politically active gay
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``It energizes both bases, but the negative for them is it makes
them look extremist and mean,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
who is gay. ``We're not all orphans. As gays and lesbians have come
out, we've brought along our friends and our parents and our aunts
and our uncles. And it's not just gay and lesbian people and our
friends and relatives. It is people who do not feel comfortable
associating with bashers.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the most conservative Republicans are wary of
setting themselves up for criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be very careful to be very sensitive,'' said Rep.
Joseph R. Pitts, R-Pa., who is the House leadership's liaison to
Christian conservatives. ``I don't want to inflame emotions and
public animosity. I just think we should be careful not to
demagogue on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative ad campaign calls for a ``national discussion
of homosexuality'' with the goal of convincing gays to become
celibate or heterosexual. Full-page ads in The New York Times, The
Washington Post and other major newspapers urge gays to ``confront
the truth of their sexual sin.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads also praise Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who came
under fire last month for comparing homosexuality to alcoholism and
kleptomania. Lott's denunciation was echoed by House Majority
Leader Dick Armey of Texas and by Republican Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas, the No. 3 House leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side has been systematically, over time,
desensitizing the American people into thinking that this is an
acceptable lifestyle. It is not acceptable,'' DeLay said. ``It is
wrong. It is dangerous. It destroys families. It destroys people.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights groups countered the conservative ad campaign on
Wednesday with a full-page ad in USA Today featuring Dave and Ruth
Waterbury of Minnesota, whose daughter is a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We happen to be Republicans. But that shouldn't matter,'' the
Waterburys say. ``Fairness should be a concern of Americans of all
political stripes. It's as American as apple pie.''
</P>
<P>
   The dueling ad campaigns come as both the House and the Senate
confront issues involving gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, conservative Republicans have blocked James
Hormel's nomination as ambassador to Luxembourg, citing concerns
that the San Francisco philanthropist would pursue a homosexual
agenda in the foreign posting.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote next week on legislation
overturning a recent Clinton directive aimed at eliminating
discrimination based on sexual orientation in federal employment.
Opponents, led by Rep. Joel Hefley, R-Colo., contend that the May
28 executive order gave homosexuals special status that goes far
beyond existing civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those efforts, some Christian activists contend that
Republicans are cowed by the fear they will be labeled intolerant
or extremist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has been AWOL,'' Knight said. ``You really don't have
a parade of conservatives going to the microphone to take on this
issue. Everybody's afraid to get on the wrong side of gay
activists.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Ed Goeas said most voters fall in the middle
of the opposing views that are driving the debate in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very much like the abortion issue,'' he said.
``Basically, it's `don't get in my face.' Most people know someone
who is gay or work with someone who is gay and don't have a problem
with it as long as they are not forced to endorse the lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   With an election just around the corner, many lawmakers would
just as soon stay out of the crossfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend a lot of time on a lot of issues that the American
people and the church should resolve,'' said Rep. James Traficant,
D-Ohio. ``It was a closet lifestyle that's now out in the family
room. There's more tolerance. But there is still, to many, an
abhorrent feeling it is wrong. There are very strong sentiments on
both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
