<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLD-TOURNAMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION AND OWNERS DISCUSS PLAN FOR INTERNATIONAL EXPANSION  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 2000 Olympics and a World Cup type of baseball tournament
were among the topics discussed Wednesday at an unusual meeting
between union officials and owners. No decisions were made, but the
meeting was significant because it was the formal beginning of a
joint effort to expand baseball internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a very good, very productive and an exciting
meeting,'' said Paul Beeston, chief operating officer for Major
League Baseball. ``Don articulated the union's position, and it's
consistent with our position. We had six club representatives, and
they can see Don has a vision and a commitment, a plan that is not
at counter with anything we want to do. I think we can work very
well together.''
</P>
<P>
   Beeston referred to Donald Fehr, the head of the union, which
has been ahead of the owners in the desire to take baseball
worldwide. But in the year that Beeston has been in office, he has
worked to bring the owners even with the players in the
international effort.
</P>
<P>
   The new committee, Beeston said, discussed a variety of issues:
the all-star Japanese tour scheduled for November, the potential of
playing games, both exhibition and league, outside of the United
States and Canada; the qualifying rounds for the 2000 Olympics, the
type of players who could be in the Olympics and the future of a
worldwide tournament based on soccer's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Fehr also emerged from the meeting with the feeling that the two
sides are prepared to work together and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling that there's a lot of work to do and there's
an opportunity out there,'' Fehr said. ``We have to come up with an
operating plan.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest decisions the committee has to make is the
type of professional players who could play in the qualifying games
for the Australia Olympics. Those games are expected to be played
during the Pan-American Games a year from now. Major league players
are not expected to be available for those games or the Olympics.
The Olympics are scheduled for what will be the last two weeks of
the 2000 major league season. The minor league season will have
ended by then.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will also work on the feasibility of creating a
world tournament. There has been talk that the first one could be
held in three to five years, but that is speculative.
</P>
<P>
   Beeston and Fehr will be in Italy next week for the world
championships and a meeting of the executive board of the
International Baseball Association, the certifying body for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
