<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP-NOTES16-COX     07-15 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Youth urged to fight some some drug laws
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Parents of Kemba Smith, a young college student who
is serving 24 years in prison for minor involvement in her
boyfriend's drug ring, implored young NAACP delegates to work
toward changing the laws that put their daughter away.
</P>
<P>
   A National Association for the Advancement of Colored People's
legal defense team is representing the young woman. Smith, 24,
admitted to lying to federal authorities about her boyfriend's
whereabouts and transporting cash for him. Smith, a former college
student, did not use, deal or ferry drugs. She insists that she
lied because she feared for her life and her parents' lives.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday afternoon, Gus Smith asked teen delegates to get
involved in protesting the laws and his daughter's sentence. He
also implored them to pick their friends carefully and to terminate
the friendship if the friends are involved in illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
   Singer rouses audience
</P>
<P>
   The audience rose to their feet, cheering and shouting, as
recording artist Jennifer Holliday sang at the NAACP's 26th
national membership/life membership luncheon that gave awards to
chapters that had grown over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Holliday dedicated her song, ``I'm On Your Side,'' to the late
Jondelle Johnson, former executive director of the Atlanta NAACP.
She spoke of the friendship she and Johnson once shared.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker, former NAACP Executive Director Benjamin
Hooks, also received a standing ovation as he encouraged members to
continue the fight for justice and equality. ``We still have a long
way to go, the fight is not over,'' Hooks said. Hooks encouraged
members to help to teach youth to ``do the very best you can'' in
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Young, former mayor of Atlanta, Turner Broadcasting
corporate vice president Xernona Clayton and Julian Bond, chairman
of the NAACP, were also in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Artist guides students
</P>
<P>
   Frank Frazier, 55, a Dallas, Texas-based artist, is putting this
year's NAACP convention theme, ``Preparing Tomorrow's Leader's
Today,'' in action. The designer of six NAACP convention logos,
Frazier said he will give an ACT-SO student the opportunity to
design the art work in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then it's their turn,'' said Frazier, a 25-year NAACP
member. ``One of the reasons I'm involved in the NAACP is because
of ACT-SO and to help develop the future of our youth. It's
positive seeing all of the black youth.'' ACT-SO is a competition
for high school students in arts and academics.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier said he has been selling his work at NAACP conventions
for 35 years. He said he suggested the NAACP sell shirts and
posters of this year's design, featuring a man and woman in African
dress accompanied by two youths.
</P>
<P>
   Gwendolyn Harris, executive director of the Nashville NAACP
branch, said she tapped Frazier to design the logo for the 1992
convention. ``He was hot,'' Harris said. ``(The NAACP) has been
using my contact ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Staying on course
</P>
<P>
   Like many other delegates at the convention, Ophelia Averitt, a
national board member from Ohio, has belonged to the group for a
long time. And like many her age, she has been a member since she
learned to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Averitt's parents registered her when she was 3. A
self-described ``seasoned'' member who won't divulge her age,
Averitt has moved up through the ranks and is now president of the
Akron, Ohio, NAACP branch. ``You make the time,'' she said. ``If
you're a volunteer and committed to what the course is, then that's
your mission. You keep your eye on the prize. When you find out
that other people depend on you, that gives you a sense of being.
That makes you move forward, and no money can compare to the
service you do for others.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
