<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX     07-15 1965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-STURBIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS WRITING THEIR OWN TRANS-AM CHAPTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These hardly are the glory days of the NTB Trans-Am Series, home
to road-racing legends Mark Donohue, Peter Revson and Parnelli
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit factories have deserted the Sports Car Club of
America-sanctioned series, taking with them the upper-echelon
Chevrolet Camaros fielded by Buz McCall and the Ford Mustang Cobras
entered by Jack Roush and Tom Gloy.
</P>
<P>
   Even record-setting four-time Trans-Am champion Tommy Kendall is
without a full-time ride halfway through 1998. Like Kendall, 1989
Trans-Am champion Dorsey Schroeder also is logging air time as a TV
commentator this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The 33rd season of what is billed as ``America's longest-running
road-racing series'' has seen Paul Gentilozzi emerge to replace
Kendall _ winner of a record 11 consecutive races in 1997 _ as
Trans-Am's moving target.
</P>
<P>
   Amid whispers that his Rocketsports Chevy Corvette is equipped
with illegal traction control _ which also was the rap on Kendall
last year _ Gentilozzi has won five of seven races en route to a
sizable 41-point lead in the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, Texans Lou Gigliotti and Bill Saunders have kept
things reasonably entertaining with the first series victories of
their respective careers.
</P>
<P>
   Gigliotti, of Garland, won the rain and controversy-plagued race
at Lime Rock Park in Connecticut on May 25 in his Mustang ``concept
car.'' And on Saturday, Saunders _ who is Gentilozzi's AutoLink
teammate _ wheeled his Corvette to victory on the Burke Lakefront
Airport layout at Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Gigliotti and Saunders are joined only by the
geography of North Texas. Politically and financially, they stand
at opposite ends of the SCCA spectrum. But at the respective ages
of 48 and 51, Gigliotti and Saunders are proving that one way to
avoid a midlife crisis is to suit up, strap in and stand on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gigliotti's victory at Lime Rock came in his eighth Trans-Am
start, and third of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real proud of that,'' said Gigliotti, the SCCA World
Challenge champion in 1991, 1992 and 1996. ``There are a lot of
good drivers in this country who never get an opportunity. I love
racing. I'm addicted to it. The only way I get an opportunity is to
build and race my own cars. That's how I can afford to race.''
</P>
<P>
   Gigliotti's racing habit primarily is funded by LG Motorsports,
whose G2 Performance Parts are popular among the owners of Chevy
and Ford muscle cars.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders, meanwhile, has parlayed his position as president of
Dallas-based HighwayMaster with Gentilozzi's Rocketsports operation
into a Trans-Am career that is in its sixth year. Saunders' first
Trans-Am victory came in his 69th start, shattering Paul Miller's
previous record for persistence at 38 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Persistency pays off,'' Saunders said this week. ``They did a
piece not too long ago on ``Inside the PGA'' where they talked
about the golfers who go out, win and are up in the money, but you
never hear about them. I guess that's me. I'm a guy they're not
expecting to win a race _ especially at my age. But I love to race,
no question about that.''
</P>
<P>
   There also is no question, Saunders said, that the series now
sponsored by National Tire and Battery is not what it was a year
ago _ when Kendall duked it out against Schroeder, Brian Simo and
rookie Mike Borkowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference in the field this year,'' said
Saunders, who also finished second to Gentilozzi at Mid-Ohio on
June 14. ``It's hard to equate what Tommy Kendall did last year
against a field of top-notch drivers. Tommy dominated us.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gigliotti, whose love for Trans-Am dates to watching Donohue
and Jones bang fenders on the backstretch at Watkins Glen, N.Y., in
1969, said this is a series in transition. And it still is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Donohue and Dorsey Schroeder and Scott Pruett and Tommy
Kendall are not there anymore,'' Gigliotti said. ``But my answer to
that is I wasn't there last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that struck home after I won at Lime Rock was when I
went upstairs to talk to the officials and they had a plaque
listing every winner. The first name was Peter Revson and then Mark
Donohue. The next row at the top of the list, it will be Lou
Gigliotti _ right next to Peter Revson and Mark Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great for their time and they'll be great in my book
forever. But every year, a new chapter gets written.'' &QL; 
THE BUZZ &QL; 
NASCAR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials are reported to be considering a ban on
in-season testing in an effort to discourage the trend toward
multicar Winston Cup teams, like Jack Roush's five-car armada.
According to reports on ESPN2's ``RPM 2Night'' and in ``The
Charlotte Observer'', NASCAR might replace the seven in-season
tests it allows each team with a single extra day of practice at a
track at the start of the race weekend. For instance, teams would
be allowed an open practice day at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort
Worth on a Thursday, with Bud Pole qualifying on Friday,
second-round qualifying on Saturday and the race on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in favor of such a plan is three-time Cup champion
Darrell Waltrip, who sold his single-car Chevrolet team to Texan
Tim Beverley in March rather than fight the multicar outfits
fielded by Roush, Richard Childress and Robert Yates. ``It's dark
and lonely out there when you don't have a teammate,'' Waltrip
said. ``There's nothing you can do about the sport growing. But
when you talk about guys owning five and six teams, I don't think
that's healthy for the sport. That's where the sanctioning body has
to make it that everybody has got a fair shake. If they do open up
these joints a day early, then you wouldn't need test dates. That's
what we're hearing all the time _ `I don't have enough test days,
so I'll start a second team.'''
</P>
<P>
   Roush, meanwhile, genuinely was pleased to see rising superstar
Jeff Burton win his first race of 1998 in Loudon, N.H., on Sunday.
It also was Burton's initial victory in the No. 99 Exide Batteries
Ford Taurus with first-year crew chief Frank Stoddard. Stoddard
replaced the popular Buddy Parrott after Parrott's off-season
promotion to team manager of the Roush shop in Mooresville, N.C.
``Frankie and Jeff's story is pretty special,'' Roush said.
``Frankie and Jeff have learned together what they need to do now
to finish these races, and they're going to be something to deal
with in the future. Buddy Parrott has been a great teacher for
them. And there's just tremendous energy with this program.'' For
the record, Burton is 31 and Stoddard, who joined Burton's team in
1996, is 30.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR will do away with the Craftsman Truck Series' traditional
``halftime'' break for the Tempus Resorts 300K at Pikes Peak
International Raceway in Fountain, Colo., on July 25. The race
instead will feature Cup-style tire changes during pit stops.
Dennis Huth, NASCAR vice president of administration, said the
one-race change will be approached as a test. &QL; 
IRL/CART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Plano's Greg Ray says the only drawback to driving for A.J. Foyt
in the Pep Boys 400K at Dover (Del.) International Speedway this
weekend is a lack of practice time on the 1-mile, 24-degree-banked
concrete oval. ``I've never done a lap there, and A.J. hasn't
tested there,'' said Ray, who is subbing for the injured Billy Boat
in the Indy Racing League event. Ray said the No. 97 Dallara he has
been driving for car owner Thomas Knapp over the last year and a
half was purchased from Foyt in Houston. ``I've known these guys
for a while, and they know I wanted to drive for them,'' said Ray,
who has been fitted for the No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora. ``We
just haven't been able to get to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray also confirmed that he has spoken to Bobby Rahal about the
ride that will open up in the Miller Lite Reynard/Ford when Rahal
retires at the end of the FedEx Championship Auto Racing Teams
season. Other rumored candidates are 1996 CART champion Jimmy
Vasser, Gil de Ferran, Robby Gordon, former Formula One World
Driving Champion Damon Hill and Heinz-Harald Frentzen. Ray
indicated a preference for the IRL's all-oval format. ``I do miss
road racing, but they (CART) don't race on the type of tracks I
like for the most part,'' he said. ``I'm listening to all
opportunities, but I think the IRL is where I want to be.'' &QL; 
NHRA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mired in 11th in points, Eddie Hill of Wichita Falls is not a
factor in the National Hot Rod Association Top Fuel championship.
But Hill, 62, is one of only five Top Fuel drivers to have
qualified for all 11 races run this season. ``That's unusual,''
said Hill, the 1993 champion and driver of the Pennzoil Dragster.
``I was almost shocked myself when we ran across that stat.
Normally, all of the top 10 teams qualify at every race. I don't
remember having that many DNQs by top 10 teams in recent years.
We're way back down in the points, but we're No. 5 in qualifying
points. That shows we've qualified a lot better than we've raced. I
think the good qualifying will pay off during the last half of the
season.'' Points leader Cory McClenathan, Joe Amato, Kenny
Bernstein and Gary Scelzi are the other Top Fuelers to have
qualified at every national event. The second half of the 22-race
season resumes today with the Mopar Parts Mile-High Nationals in
Morrison, Colo. &QL; 
FAST LAPS &QL; 
TMS PLANS ANNOUNCEMENT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Texas Motor Speedway have scheduled a ``major
announcement'' for Wednesday at the infield media center.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be about the granting of a second NASCAR Winston Cup
race date to TMS?
</P>
<P>
   Track spokesman Gary Guehler said he could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major announcement, and there'll be a Winston Cup team
owner and driver here,'' Guehler said. ``We'll get some views of
the new surface.''
</P>
<P>
   The reconfigured and repaved 1.5-mile speedway passed its first
tests on June 5-6, when it played host to the NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series and Pep Boys Indy Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR traditionally releases its schedule for the coming year
no sooner than the Mountain Dew Southern 500 on Labor Day weekend.
Recent speculation is that the only addition to the 1999 Cup
schedule will be at the reconfigured Miami-Dade Motorsports Complex
in Homestead, Fla., raising the race count to 34. &QL; 
NUTS AND BOLTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup rookie Jerry Nadeau has been dropped as driver of
the No. 13 FirstPlus Financial Ford Taurus, co-owned by Bill
Elliott and Dan Marino. Nadeau qualified for 14 of 17 races, with a
best finish of 21st (twice). No replacement has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   CART regular Robby Gordon has been signed by Roehrig Motorsports
to drive the No. 19 Yellow Freight Ford at the Brickyard 400 on
Aug. 1 at Indianapolis. Gordon will be subbing for the team's
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series regular, Tony Raines.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football analyst and former NFL coach Jerry Glanville is
scheduled to compete in the Craftsman Truck Series events at the
California Speedway this weekend and Pikes Peak International
Raceway on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple World of Outlaws Sprint Car champion Steve Kinser won
his first race since late March on June 27 in Eagle, Neb. Kinser,
who has added crew chief Guy Forbrook to his Quaker State team,
took a 44-point lead over cousin Mark Kinser into last night's race
at Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Yates, son of two-time and reigning NHRA Pro Stock
champion Jim Yates, will make his driving debut at the Mopar Parts
Mile-High Nationals tomorrow. Jamie Yates, 21, will drive a second
SplitFire/Peak Pontiac Firebird. &QL; 
LAST WORDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to Denver and see the birds walking, you know the
air is thin.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Johnson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NHRA Pro Stock points leader, on competing in the Mopar Parts
Mile-High Nationals &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
