<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7186 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORDMANN-COX     07-15 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORDMANN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Limelight follows man's chance meeting
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTAHALA, N.C. -- Until lean, hungry Eric Robert Rudolph
emerged from the deep mountains nine days ago looking for food,
George Nordmann lived quietly. Now the murky role he played in
providing food and a pickup truck for Rudolph, a longtime
acquaintance, has thrust Nordmann into the media spotlight focused
on the manhunt for the suspect in the Jan. 29 Birmingham abortion
clinic bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have said that they have no evidence that
Nordmann cooperated in helping Rudolph avoid capture. Nordmann
called the Macon County sheriff's office Saturday and reported that
his pickup truck and some food had been stolen and that he believed
Rudolph was responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't ask for a better neighbor,'' said Jennifer
Solesbee, who hired one of Nordmann's daughters to babysit her two
young children.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances said Nordmann is a devout Catholic who is opposed
to abortion. When one of his daughters became pregnant out of
wedlock several years ago, he kept her at home during her
pregnancy. The daughter attempted to deliver the baby at home, but
emergency medical workers were called when the delivery ran into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not believe in abortion, but I do not think he would
try to kill anybody over it,'' said Pam O'Dell, who knows Nordmann
and attended school with several of his children.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann, 71, could not be located Wednesday. He didn't answer
knocks on the screen door of his small cluttered house, surrounded
by weeds, junk cars and chickens pecking in the dust. Nordmann's
house, perched on a winding road looking across the hazy
southwestern North Carolina mountains, is decorated by religious
pictures that Solesbee described as ``graphic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are pictures of Jesus and saints everywhere,'' she said,
explaining that some show the crucifixion of Jesus Christ wearing a
thorny crown and bleeding from nail holes in his hands and feet.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann has been divorced for many years and raised his
children, Solesbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann moved to the Andrews area from Florida in the late
1970s, when he took a part-time job teaching shop at Nantahala
School, said Principal Richard Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said he remembered seven of Nordmann's children. ``They
were kind, courteous, respectful, good academically.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he believes that religion played a role in their
upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann has lived alone for several months, after a daughter
who lived with him married and moved to Hayesville, Solesbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers of his business, The Better Way Health Food Store in
Andrews, said he is helpful and pleasant, although some of his
recommendations, such as coffee enemas to purge the body, are
unorthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if you smoke here, but please don't exhale,''
reads a sign on a bulletin board behind the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Macon County Sheriff Homer Holbrooks said Nordmann
and Rudolph ``have known each other for quite a while,'' as do many
people who live in the Nantahala community near Topton, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooks said authorities do not believe that Nordmann
aided Rudolph with the intention of helping one of the FBI's 10
Most Wanted fugitives escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he did the right thing,'' said Jack Daulton, the FBI's
chief in Atlanta, adding that, for now, Nordmann is under no
suspicion of unlawfully helping Rudolph. According to an account,
that Holbrooks said Nordmann gave sheriff's department officials,
Rudolph came to Nordmann's house during the day of July 7 and asked
for food.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph left, but returned two nights later when Nordmann was
not home. Rudolph took food and drove away in Nordmann's 1977 blue
Datsun pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Nordmann on Saturday reported the incident to sheriff's Deputy
Kenny Cope, who alerted Holbrooks. ``Homer, you are not going to
believe this,'' he told the sheriff. ``I got a gentleman here who
has been contacted by Eric Rudolph.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities discovered Nordmann's truck shortly after noon
Monday near Apple Tree campground, in the vicinity of the
intensifying manhunt that includes agents and dogs from the Georgia
Department of Corrections. In its new composite of Rudolph, a
32-year-old carpenter and outdoorsman also wanted for questioning
in three Atlanta bombings, the FBI said the suspect has lost weight
and has grown a beard and long hair pulled into a ponytail.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooks said that description suggests that Rudolph ``is
operating alone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody has been cooking corn bread and pinto beans, he'd
be in a little better shape than what he is,'' Holbrooks said. ``I
do not think anybody is helping him.'' Even so, the sheriff said
some residents have told him, ``If I knew where he was, I wouldn't
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Ratthe, owner of Back Porch Herb Shoppe in Andrews, said
some of her customers who oppose abortion support Rudolph despite
the felony charges against him:
</P>
<P>
   ``People have come in and said, `What is so wrong about what he
has done?' If they are strongly against abortion, they'd look at
him as a saint.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
