<HEADER>
A7187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SEWAGE-SPILL-ART-5     07-15 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEWAGE-SPILL-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRECAUTIONS IN EFFECT AFTER HUDSON WASTEWATER SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROTON-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ Three supervisors at a sewage treatment
plant in Yonkers run by Westchester County remained suspended
without pay Wednesday after 122 million gallons of wastewater that
had not been disinfected were released into the Hudson River on
Sunday and Monday, Andrew Spano, the county executive, said
Wednesday. The workers will remain suspended pending the outcome of
an investigation into why they did not alert senior officials or
use backup procedures to treat the water.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the wastewater prompted county officials to order
the beach at Croton Point Park here and another in Sleepy Hollow,
Philipse Manor Beach, closed for a second day while the water was
examined for harmful bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   A first round of tests for bacteria in the Hudson turned up no
unhealthful levels of E. coli, said Dr. Harold Adel, the county's
health commissioner. But Adel said the two beaches would remain
closed until results of follow-up bacteria tests become available,
probably on Thursday, he said. Boaters were also being advised to
avoid contact with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is strictly precautionary,'' Adel said. He added that he
thought the follow-up tests most likely would also show no problem,
with the flow of the tide and the dilution from billions of gallons
of river water quickly erasing any threat.
</P>
<P>
   Spano said problems first developed at the plant on Sunday, when
some pipes were clogged, disrupting the final stage of the
water-treatment process, the addition of chlorine to kill bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   For four hours on Sunday, wastewater that had not been
disinfected poured into the Hudson at the rate of nearly 4 million
gallons an hour. The workers fixed the problem, but no one notified
the plant manager or county environmental officials about the
release of the partially treated wastewater, Spano said.
</P>
<P>
   The chlorine-pumping system broke down again at 7 a.m. Monday
and was not fixed until Tuesday morning, bringing the total release
of potentially contaminated wastewater up to about 122 million
gallons, county officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Spano said, no one notified top officials of the
release so that neighboring communities could be alerted and
bacteria checks conducted. ``We have strict procedures in place for
this,'' he said. ``It just baffles me why they didn't tell
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of the suspended workers have not been released and
their union, the Civil Service Employees Association, was unable to
provide any information on the situation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, which handles an average flow of 92 million gallons
of sewage a day from 26 Westchester communities, generally has had
a good operating record, said Samuel Thernstrom, a spokesman for
the state Department of Environmental Conservation, which was
investigating the breakdown at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Along with county officials, the DEC was not notified within 24
hours of the spills, as it should have been under the terms of the
plant's permit, Thernstrom said. He said the county could be levied
a fine in the ``tens of thousands of dollars'' depending on the
outcome of the investigation.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Cronin, who investigates pollution problems for the Hudson
Riverkeeper Fund, a private environmental group, said his group did
not share the state's generally positive view of the plant's
operations, referring to a variety of lapses there over the years.
</P>
<P>
   He said there is no room for error at such a big sewage plant,
particularly one on a stretch of the river where the tides can
carry pollution many miles in both directions.
</P>
<P>
   At Croton Point Park Wednesday, which is 18 miles north of the
Yonkers plant, Spano surveyed the vacant beach and said, ``This
just kills me.'' People intending to swim said they were
discouraged to discover the beach closure notice at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Desiree and Dwayne Bland had driven up from Harlem to swim and
picnic at the broad, sandy beach with their two children. They
ended up instead at a playground in the park, where Mrs. Bland was
teaching her 3-year-old son, Khari, how to use a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to hear about it when we got here,'' Mrs. Bland
said. ``I came all dressed and ready,'' she added, indicating the
bathing suit under her sundress. ``I guess I'm all dressed up with
no place to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
