<SLUG> BC-FORD-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: FORD GIVES YOUNG &AMP; RUBICAM SOME GEMS AND OGILVY A
JOLT
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT 
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. has unexpectedly shaken up its agency roster
across Europe, shifting assignments with billings estimated at $175
million to $225 million to Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising from Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Fax edition of Advertising Age described the move
Wednesday as one of the largest ever in Europe. On Jan. 1, five
plum accounts are leaving Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Europe in London, part of
WPP Group , for Young &AMP; Rubicam Europe in London, part of Young &AMP;
Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford lines departing Ogilvy are the Ford Fiesta, with
billings estimated at $70 million; the Ford Ka, $50 million; the
Ford Explorer sport utility vehicle, $20 million, and the Windstar
mini-van, with a small budget. Before the reshuffling, Y&AMP;R Europe
had handled those brands only in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R Europe is also gaining the Ford corporate-image assignment
for Europe. Spending for it has been relatively modest but is in
line to grow to as much as $90 million with the arrival soon of a
new campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul in the Ford roster means that Y&AMP;R Europe assumes
the role of the lead agency for Ford of Europe from Ogilvy Europe.
The move came two weeks after Y&AMP;R Europe prevailed over Ogilvy
Europe for the assignment to introduce across Europe a model to be
named Focus, which will replace the Escort in the Ford lineup in 18
to 24 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Focus account, with billings estimated at $100 million,
represented the first assignment of a mainstream Ford brand to Y&AMP;R
Europe, Campaign, a British trade publication, reported. And the
assignment altered the balance of power between the two agencies as
they vied for Ford's favor in Europe, Campaign reported, tipping
the balance to Y&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the extent of how far the teeter-totter had tottered was not
evident until Wednesday, when Ford of Europe, based in Brentwood,
England, announced what was described as a ``major restructuring of
its advertising strategy,'' toward selling on a brand-by-brand
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are simplifying and clarifying the roles and
responsibilities of our advertising agencies,'' said Philippe
Mellier, vice president for marketing, sales and service at Ford of
Europe, ``which will provide our customers Europe-wide with a
consistent message about our products.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ford shake-up is indicative of a new wave of ferment roiling
agencies that have automotive accounts. The automotive category was
volatile earlier in the decade, with more than a dozen marques
changing agencies. That itchiness had faded as car and truck sales
increased after the improvement in national economies across North
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But the intensifying competitiveness in the automotive market is
leading marketers again to reassess their agency ties.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford roster makeover ``is key to our ongoing growth in the
European market,'' Mellier said, ``and is a cornerstone of our
strategy to take Ford into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other automakers that have also recently altered agency
rosters are Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America, which named Deutsch
Inc. in Marina del Rey, Calif., and New York to handle the
introduction of the 1999 Galant.
</P>
<P>
   According to the trade publication Brandweek, Mitsubishi will
change its American advertising theme, in a campaign planned to
begin late this month, to ``Wake up and drive'' from ``Built for
living.'' The older theme was created by the company's previous
agency, the G2 unit of Grey Advertising in Huntington Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R Europe has been trying to build its Ford business in Europe
for more than a decade. A breakthrough occurred in 1994, Campaign
reported, when Ford awarded the agency the Galaxy minivan account.
That was followed by assignments for Cougar, which in Europe
carries Ford's name, rather than Mercury's; Puma, and the Lincoln
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y&AMP;R is relishing the challenge of repeating for Ford's volume
brands the successes we've had in developing pan-European
advertising for the Galaxy and Puma,'' said Kevin King, account
managing director for Ford of Europe at Y&AMP;R Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ogilvy Europe is losing its large assignments to Y&AMP;R
Europe, the blow is being softened somewhat. It will continue
handling some Ford accounts, including Escort, until that brand is
phased out; Mondeo, the so-called world car, and Ford's commercial
vehicles. Y&AMP;R Europe had been handling those accounts in Germany,
and they now will be shifted to Ogilvy Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Mindshare, a media agency that like Ogilvy Europe is owned by
WPP, will continue to handle media buying for Ford of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Y&AMP;R Advertising handles the
Lincoln-Mercury division for Ford and Ogilvy is the Ford corporate
agency, responsible for the image campaign introduced in May that
carries the theme ``Better ideas. Driven by you.'' Ford division
vehicles are handled by J. Walter Thompson, another Ogilvy sibling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
