<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ SETS A NEW RECORD, WHILE DOW AND S&AMP;P FALL
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq index jumped to its sixth
consecutive new high, closing just shy of the 2,000 level at
1,994.54. But the Dow Jones industrial average and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index declined as investors took profits after
Tuesday's rally. During the day, the Dow topped 9,300 for the first
time, before closing lower at 9,234.47. The S&AMP;P index fell to
1,174.81. Strong earnings from Ford Motor failed to bolster the
stock market. Ford shares fell $1, to $59.50, but are up 84.5
percent so far this year. The company topped earnings estimates by
Wall Street analysts by 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   COMPAQ TOPS EARNINGS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Computer reported a second-quarter loss of $3.63 billion,
but eked out a tiny operating profit that surpassed analysts'
expectations of a break-even quarter.
</P>
<P>
   FED CONCERNED ABOUT LOAN POLICIES
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is concerned that lending standards at banks
are slipping, presenting dangers should the economy stall.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA MOVES ON AUSTERITY PLAN
</P>
<P>
   With billions in Western loans at stake, the Russian Government
urged the lower house of Parliament to pass tax, budget and
economic measures that are the strings lenders have attached to any
additional money.
</P>
<P>
   BIG EARNINGS GAIN AT TIME WARNER
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner said second-quarter earnings more than tripled, and
its chairman suggested that the company might lease some cable
properties to telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   CABLE AND WIRELESS BUYING MCI UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Richard Brown, the first American chief executive at Cable and
Wireless of Britain, has expanded that company in the United States
market and cyberspace with the acquisition of the Internet business
of MCI Communications. That deal cleared the way for the Justice
Department to approve MCI's pending $37 billion acquisition by
Worldcom. The Federal Communications Commission is the only major
regulatory body that has yet to rule on the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   DETAILS OF SPRINT'S NETWORK PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Sprint provided details of how it will revamp its communications
network to provide integrated data and video information at high
speeds.
</P>
<P>
   BANK PROFITS MEET OR TOP ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica and several other large banks met or beat
second-quarter earnings expectations as they generated higher fees
from consumers and corporations. Earnings at J.P. Morgan, the
nation's fourth-largest bank, rose 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE-FIXING TRIAL BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   In opening arguments, a Federal prosecutor said former senior
executives of Archer Daniels Midland were caught on tape recordings
conspiring with competitors to set the market prices for a feed
additive.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA ENTERPRISES GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises, the largest bottler in the Coke system,
has gained respect since it began a buying spree 18 months ago. As
a result, shares have climbed to $40.75 from $21 a year ago. Market
Place.
</P>
<P>
   CBS ADDING 2nd `60 MINUTES'
</P>
<P>
   As expected, CBS said that it would start a second ``60
Minutes'' next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
