<SLUG> BC-BOX-FOREMAN-HOLMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANCIENT GLADIATORS HOLMES AND FOREMAN TO MEET  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It could well be the last Fight of the Century. Two
gladiators with a combined age of 99 years. And that's the point,
George Foreman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won the Olympics in 1968; UCLA won the basketball
championship in 1968; the Jets won that year,'' he said. ``I loved
that Joe Namath. That's why I'm rooting for UCLA again, why I'm
rooting for that Super Bowl again.''
</P>
<P>
   For those reasons _ as well as $10 million _ Foreman announced
Wednesday that he would meet another aging former heavyweight
champion, Larry Holmes, on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   There is no title at stake these days. Foreman forfeited his
crown when he declined to fight various challengers after his
stunning comeback victory over Michael Moorer in 1994, which made
him the world's oldest champion at 45. Holmes was last a champion
in 1985. The bout, the first between the two, is being billed as
the Birthday Bash. Two weeks before the fight, Foreman will have
celebrated his 50th birthday. Holmes will turn 49 in November. In
deference to Foreman's age, and greater celebrity status, Holmes
will earn only $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you need the money, Larry?'' he was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody needs money,'' said Holmes, who colors his hair with
Just for Men to get rid of the gray.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-round fight will be held in either New York or Las Vegas,
whichever comes up with a better promotional deal, and will be
televised on a pay-per-view basis. So far there are two sponsors _
9 Net Avenue, an Internet company, and Kremlyovskaya, a Russian
vodka. But Foreman already has more than $1 million in a trust fund
from the promoter, a Briton named Roger Levitt. And that up-front
money, suggested Foreman's longtime lawyer, Henry Holmes, helped
make the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand, especially young people,'' said
Foreman, seriously considering the question of age and why he
fights. ``When Archie Moore was champion, he was a closet athlete.
He had to hide his age. Sonny Liston had to conceal his age, too.
It was as if, once you mentioned their age, their careers were over
and no one would take them seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, turning to the baby-boom generation of which he and Holmes
are a part, Foreman added: ``Something happened after World War II.
There were kids born that weren't like other children. I'm part of
that now. Why are we doing things our age group never did before?
Someone smarter than me will have to explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
