<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-PLANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT IS LAYING OUT DETAILS OF PLAN TO REVAMP NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. has been laying out fresh details of an ambitious
program to revamp its communications network to provide integrated
data and video information at high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, the No. 3 long-distance telephone company, announced the
plan amid much fanfare last month, but investors were largely
underwhelmed because the company provided few financial and
technical details of its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it was building an advanced network but offered
little to explain how it wanted to deploy and market the service
and how it intended to work with local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Sprint has made deals with Ameritech, BellSouth, GTE
and SBC Communications to use those local companies' fiber optic
networks within cities.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is continuing to try to negotiate deals with the
remaining Bell local phone companies and with big competitive local
phone providers including AT&AMP;T Corp.'s Teleport unit and Worldcom
Inc.'s MFS operation.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday, William Esrey, Sprint's chairman,
said that deals with existing local phone companies could allow
Sprint to reach 70 percent of its target business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint intends to begin offering big businesses access to the
integrated network later this year. The service will be generally
available to business customers near the middle of next year and to
consumers late in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said Sprint would aim at between 30 million and 35 million
of the nation's roughly 100 million households for the new service.
He said he expected that families who sign up for the service,
which would combine local and long-distance telephone service with
high-speed access to the Internet and video capabilities, would
spend about $125 a month.
</P>
<P>
   With each subscriber generating that kind of revenue, Esrey
said, Sprint could turn a profit with as few as one million
residential users.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's deals with the Bells and GTE do not address the
question of how Sprint's services actually get into homes and
offices. Esrey would not say how much Sprint anticipates spending
to upgrade individual phone lines to carry the new service, but
analysts generally estimate that figure at between $500 and $1,000
a line.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey said Sprint's costs could end up being lower than
estimated because of the geographic concentration of the target
market. Of the roughly 26,000 local telephone central offices in
the nation, Esrey said, about 4,000 of them would allow Sprint to
connect to 70 percent of the target households.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey also said that Sprint would continue to pursue alliances
with cable television companies. He said that if AT&AMP;T succeeded in
acquiring Tele-Communications Inc., then AT&AMP;T should have to resell
access to TCI's cable television network to competitors like
Sprint. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
