<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7222 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUDOLPH16-COX     07-15 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUDOLPH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rudolph hunt leads to N.C. lookout point
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANDREWS, N.C. _ Federal agents searching for Birmingham bombing
suspect Eric Robert Rudolph have found what they believe was an
observation point where the fugitive watched the Nantahala
residence of a man whose help he tried to enlist for food and other
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   They believe Rudolph watched the house of 71-year-old George
Nordmann for several days before approaching the health food store
owner July 7.
</P>
<P>
   According to a federal document, Rudolph approached Nordmann,
described as a ``nodding acquaintance,'' and presented him with a
list of provisions and five $100 bills. Investigators said the
items requested included batteries, oatmeal, beans and raisins.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph, a 32-year-old itinerant carpenter who lived for a while
in western North Carolina, is being sought in the fatal bombing of
a Birmingham abortion clinic and three Atlanta-area bombings.
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 federal agents and scores of other law enforcement
officers were searching the area Wednesday around where Nordmann's
pickup was found Monday afternoon. Agents of the Georgia Bureau of
Investigation were involved in sealing off and searching the Apple
Tree campground near Topton.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also brought in a U.S. Customs helicopter equipped
with infrared viewing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nordmann did not report to authorities he had seen
Rudolph or that his pickup was missing until Saturday, he is not
believed to have supplied the suspected bomber with his truck or
with food.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not changing from what we originally said _ he (Rudolph)
took it,'' said Jack Killorin, head of the Atlanta office of the
U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms. Responding to media
reports that explosive residue was found in the vehicle,
authorities said they don't know where Rudolph went in the truck,
but they have found no evidence of explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are running forensic tests,'' Killorin said of the truck,
which was taken to the ATF lab in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be determined if Rudolph used the truck to haul the
food to some lair or if he carried the load or stashed it.
</P>
<P>
   The food, which included canned goods, is estimated to weigh up
to 100 pounds, Macon County Sheriff Homer Holbrooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are unlimited places to dump food around here,'' the
sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   Killorin joined in a chorus of federal officials Wednesday in
saying that Nordmann is not considered to have been aiding Rudolph
in eluding capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small community,'' Killorin said. ``There is some
militia activity up there, and this is where the guy lived. Eric
Rudolph is a dangerous fugitive and informing on him is a matter of
concern. But what did he do at the end of the day? He did come
forward. He did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0511 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS EAGER TO SPEND STATE'S RECORD SURPLUS OF $3 BILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Whether it is pork-barrel promises or just good
public policy, Texas's Democratic and Republican politicians are on
a spending spree this year, the likes of which hasn't occurred
since the oil-boom days of the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is talk of ``scrubbing the budget'' and no new taxes from
the years of revenue shortfalls. Politicians are appealing to
voters this year with expensive promises they can afford to
fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   And the price of those promises may go up Thursday after
Comptroller John Sharp announces a state revenue surplus of about
$3 billion, a state record.
</P>
<P>
   From Republican Gov. George W. Bush to his Democratic challenger
Garry Mauro to the lieutenant governor showdown between Democrat
Sharp and Republican Agriculture Commissioner Rick Perry, the
spending promises are flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this election is about is: `The money is there. How are
you going to spend it?' '' Mauro said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This election is an unprecedented opportunity to
`reprioritize' where Texas goes in the 21st century,'' Mauro said.
``Revenues are up 24 percent since Bush has been in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Perry, within the framework of fiscal conservatism, said
there is room for additional state spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do feel good about the economy in general,'' Perry
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I hear out there during this period of good times is:
Let's improve our public education ... fix our roads and bridges
and ... let's make sure our criminal justice system is funded
properly,'' Perry said. ``But once you get those basic needs
addressed ... they (taxpayers) want their money back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush used part of a $2.4 billion surplus in the current budget
last year to deliver a $1 billion property tax cut to homeowners.
But almost half that cut was eaten up by local school district tax
increases.
</P>
<P>
   For his re-election campaign, Bush has spent almost every day
during the past two weeks touring rural county courthouses
promising that if re-elected he will renovate them at a cost of
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has promised to spend another $203 million on a
reading initiative to fulfill his pledge to end the social
promotion of ill-prepared students in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is proposing cutting state revenues $100 million a
year with a research and development tax credit to encourage
high-tech businesses to move to Texas. The proposal would require
another $17.8 million to target community college students for
training needed by the high tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Perry are promoting a plan to exempt 176,000 small
businesses from the state franchise tax at a cost of $37 million to
the state during the next two years. Sharp has a plan to exempt an
additional 56,000 small businesses at a cost to the state of $58
million.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has a spending plan that he calls Putting Families First.
Mauro said his plan will improve education and the lives of average
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has proposed eliminating the state's motor vehicle sales
tax at a cost of $3.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro also has proposed spending $2.6 billion to give each of
the state's teachers a $5,000-a-year raise. He wants to spend $200
million to restore cuts in the state's contribution to the Texas
Teacher Retirement System that were made during the budget-crunch
days of the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Another Mauro plan would borrow $2 billion from the principle of
the Permanent School Fund to build new classrooms in Texas schools.
The state would repay the money with interest over 30 years. Bush
has called this plan an ``irresponsible'' raid on the school trust
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said he is not against Bush's courthouse renovation
proposal. But Mauro said the time Bush has spent campaigning on it
shows a difference in their priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``His priority is to rebuild $200 million worth of
courthouses,'' Mauro said. ``I don't think that's the first place
we ought to be spending money. We ought to tear down the temporary
buildings (at schools) and build permanent classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was unavailable Wednesday, but his campaign spokeswoman,
Mindy Tucker, said Bush is for responsible spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, he's committed to fully funding public education, and
he's always looking for additional ways to cut taxes,'' Tucker
said. ``He believes we must find responsible ways to continue to
cut taxes and at the same time leave the state in a solid financial
position for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said Mauro is a ``liberal's liberal'' who wants to spend
all of the state's money on new programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the lieutenant governor's race, Sharp is proposing a college
scholarship program that would pay for the college tuition of high
school students with a 2.8 grade point average. The cost would be
$485 million a year and has Mauro's backing.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp also wants to reduce the effect of the so-called ``Robin
Hood'' school finance plan by increasing state spending on public
education by $700 million a year. That would reduce the amount of
money wealthy school districts have to transfer to poor school
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Perry's education proposals include spending $70 million a year
to give teachers who take specialized training as reading teachers
a $5,000 bonus. They would receive an additional $2,000 a year if
they teach in schools with low achievement scores.
</P>
<P>
   Perry also wants to develop an experimental voucher program to
give public-school students money to attend private schools,
secular or religious. Perry has not put a price tag on that
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   While campaigning in the Rio Grande Valley this week, Perry also
proposed building a South Texas medical school, at a cost of $66
million over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said his approach to the state's budget surplus and
returning excess tax dollars to the state's citizens is different
from Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent has taken the Bill Clinton approach to this
campaign: You pander, promise and spend until it hurts,'' Perry
said. ``I reject that crass politics of just promising everybody
whatever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said his programs do not amount to increased state
spending because he plans to propose budget cuts to pay for them.
Sharp said budget-cutting proposals he has made in the past seven
years as comptroller have saved the state $8.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no different than any other year, and I'm doing what
I've always done _ coming up with ways to improve education while
suggesting cuts to pay for my proposals,'' Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
