<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSPERITY-SUSTAINABI     07-15 2488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSPERITY-SUSTAINABILTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ensuring prosperity for future generation
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- What will the Miami Valley look like in 20
years?
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, it depends on what we do now. The current wave of
prosperity has placed richer, fuller lives within the grasps of
thousands of people here, but like a nagging thought that won't go
away, there is a feeling, a sense that the region as a whole could
be doing much better.
</P>
<P>
   Serious problems remain at its foundation: a growing disparity
between rich and poor, a shortage of skilled workers, an education
system under fire and persistent concerns over the quality of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Those problems could still be here in the year 2020 and beyond,
unless ways are found to translate the current prosperity into a
solid economy and society for the future.
</P>
<P>
   How can prosperity be deepened and broadened, and also be made
more long-lasting? It is a question that people are wrestling with
here as well as in cities and towns around the country. And it is
one for which there are no easy answers.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has developed a blueprint for a thriving
21st century economy, urging communities to build on their
strengths and shore up their weaknesses. Called Sustainable
America, it's a clunky phrase but a concept that's creeping more
and more into public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the idea of sustainable development is like a
triangle, with economic growth on one corner, environmental
protection and social justice on the other two.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton formed the Council on Sustainable Development
in 1993 with the idea that all three goals are compatible and can
be accomplished together.
</P>
<P>
   Your great-grandfather might have passed it along as a bit of
folk wisdom: Don't eat your seed corn.
</P>
<P>
   Like grandfather's advice, the founding principle of the council
is: ``Each generation is entitled to interest on the national
capital, but the principal should be handed down unimpaired to
future generations.'' The Chattanooga plan: Improving image and
environment. Cities like Seattle and Chattanooga have already
adopted it as their game plan. The idea, in its widest scope, has
yet to catch on in the Miami Valley, where study after study in the
last decade lists uncoordinated planning as one of the chief
obstacles to progress. But even here there are plenty of
sustainable projects to build on and _ as a central tenet of
sustainability _ everybody can pitch in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become what they call garage-door communities; you hit
the button and shut the world out,'' said Mike Wood of Kettering
Medical Center, who stepped down from a vice president's job to
have more time for his family, church and community. ``People need
to take a personal responsibility to make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga is often held up as a model of sustainable
development. Once derided as the most polluted city in America,
Chattanooga found a way to improve its environment and the city's
image.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Chattanooga, like Dayton, saw development of its
riverfront as a key element of the city's revitalization. Today all
but two miles of a 22-mile stretch of the Tennessee River has been
developed as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The city has spent $150 million and has 20 new projects totaling
$316 million under way, according to the River Valley Partners, a
mix of public and private leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Aquarium has pumped up the tourist industry
downtown and housing values are skyrocketing on the north side of
the river, according to city planner Gordon Mellencamp.
</P>
<P>
   A system of free electric trolleys downtown has eased some of
the city's air pollution problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the riverfront development has done a lot to affect
the attitude of people here,'' Mellencamp said. ``It has improved
our self-image and allowed the community to feel it had a real
input into decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Vogler of the River Valley Partners said business
executives looking to relocate are always given a tour of the
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who have seen cities all over the country,''
she said. ``They always comment on how impressed they are that the
city has re-invested in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Chattanooga has had some business successes _ a new AT&AMP;T call
center, a $350 million expansion of the DuPont plant _ but faces
the same intense competition for jobs as other cities in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth in population is steady, but not large _ about 1.5
percent a year,'' Vogler said. Seattle's 40-point check list
Seattle, with thousands of people flocking there, has the opposite
problem: coping with tremendous growth. The city has been working
on sustainable development since 1992, and created a 40-point
checklist of what makes up a healthy community. It is that
checklist that is serving as a guidepost for at least 10 other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the items on the checklist seem odd. Gardening. Library
usage. Hospital emergency room use. Biodiversity. Wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   But sociolgists are finding that simple activities like
gardening clubs and bowling leagues are the sinew that holds
together a community, giving it muscle and energy.
</P>
<P>
   Other indicators, like hospital emergency room use, may signal a
lack of widespread health care insurance, a situation that may
prove more costly in the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Sustainable Seattle's latest report, delivered on Earth Day last
spring, shows mixed success, underscoring the difficulty of the
task.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle and King County's streets and highways are still
chronically clogged with traffic, and trends show people driving
more and using more gasoline. There has been a 9 percent rise in
voter participation _ one of sustainability's goals _ but still
only 22 percent of eligible voters go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   However, the report lists as successes a 12 percent drop in
water consumption and the 49 percent of young people who do some
kind of volunteer work in the community.
</P>
<P>
   About 46 percent of the 500 people who responded to a Dayton
Daily News poll said they do some volunteer work, while 53 percent
said they do none.
</P>
<P>
   Studies such as the recent 20/20 Vision report prepared by
Dayton list education, regional decentralization, concentration of
poverty and economic change as problems facing the Miami Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that the Miami Valley is one of the 10 most
decentralized metropolitan regions in the country. It also has one
of the highest concentrations of poverty in the central core.
Twenty-five percent of the population of Dayton lives below the
poverty line. The rate is just 6 percent for adjacent suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But Dayton is hardly alone, even within its own region. Of the
25 poorest Zip Codes in the Miami Valley, more than half are
outside Montgomery County.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity in the '90s has helped most of us to a more
comfortable lifestyle, but those shut out by age, social
environment, education and, yes, lack of initiative are being left
in Nowheresville as the money train streaks past without slowing
down.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity can create a vacuum that hurts some areas. For
example, 77 percent of Dayton's housing is older than 35 years.
Statistics show that during good times people opt for new and
better housing rather than rehabilitating older housing stock.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that worries about schools, crime and crowded living
conditions and Dayton _ along with similar cities throughout the
country _ is left treading water while the wave of prosperity
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities, like Indianapolis and Cleveland, have made
remarkable comebacks in the 1990s by providing a reason to go
there. Cities like Dayton won't revive without similar efforts.
Getting better, not just bigger. Tom Traynor, an economics
professor at Wright State University, said allowing Dayton _ and
its downtown _ to deteriorate further would make the city a
``wasted resource.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dayton is unique in some ways,'' said Traynor. ``It is unusual
to see a city develop to this size without a harbor, oil or some
sort of resource. Dayton's resources were its patents and
inventors.''
</P>
<P>
   Communities must look for ways to get better, not just bigger,
says the Rocky Mountain Institute, a Colorado think tank, in its
Guide to Economic Renewal .
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's plans for riverfront development and the proposed minor
league baseball stadium are attempts at a ``big win'' solution to
some of the city's problems. Other solutions, aimed at Sustainable
America's goals of economic growth with a cleaner environment and
more widespread opportunity, may come in smaller doses.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownfields'' redevelopment of old, abandoned factories in
Dayton. The city recently became part of a nationwide project which
includes more than 60 cities around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton received a $250,000 grant that it's using to help
redevelop the former GHR Foundry, 400 Detrick St., near the Great
Miami River. Revitalizing abandoned industrial sites into new
businesses could help alleviate the city's poverty rate by
providing low-skill manufacturing or service jobs close to
impoverished neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The PRISM project, which brings citizens, environmental
regulators and General Motors engineers together to look for more
ecologically sound manufacturing techniques. Called cradle-to-grave
product responsibility, it is a key element in Sustainable
America's plan for the future. The PRISM project could turn GM and
other area plants into models for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's effort at farmland preservation. Food processing is a
$5.6 billion industry in the state, and the legislature has begun
attempts to preserve the large and diverse farm sector that
supports it.
</P>
<P>
   The National Center for Composite Systems Technology in
Kettering, where research into advanced, lightweight composite
materials may someday help government and industry in the goal of
developing an 80-mile-per-gallon car. The U.S. Department of Energy
is pushing hard for high-mileage, low-polluting vehicles.
Lightweight body construction, which composite technology promises
to deliver, is essential to creating those vehicles. Composites
also have the potential to help with the nation's crumbling
infrastructure, with new ways to repair bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Tool Town, the plan to create a educational research park for
the machine tool industry, incorporates a number of sustainable
ideas. It would revitalize the GHR Foundry, a formerly polluted
downtown industrial site, and address the shortage of skilled
workers in the trade. Dayton is already the fourth-largest
tool-and-die center in the country; Tool Town could make the city a
national destination for workers in the trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Lower Great Miami River Watershed Council's ongoing plan to
map, monitor and protect the region's water resources. The council
is made up of government and environmental leaders from all over
the Miami Valley who are working together to preserve what may be
the region's most valuable resource.
</P>
<P>
   Urban planners warn that unless steps are taken to shore up the
region's basic strengths _ and eliminate some of the weaknesses _
the recovery could be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing well in the short-term sense,'' said John Weiler,
director for the Center for Business and Economic Research at the
University of Dayton. ``There is a very different look for Dayton
now. In the 1960s the economy was 47 percent manufacturing. Today
it is 20-22 percent. Companies don't seem to want to move here,
stay here or grow here.''
</P>
<P>
   In its heyday in the '50s and '60s, Dayton was filled with
factories and workers. While that produced one of the most solid
economies in the United States, the central city also inherited the
leftover problems in the form of toxic waste sites like the old
Dayton Tire, Valleycrest and Pinnacle Road landfills.
</P>
<P>
   The President's Council's first report stated: ``Some things
must grow _ jobs, productivity, wages, profits, capital and
savings, information, knowledge, education _ and others _
pollution, waste, poverty, energy and material use per unit of
output _ must not.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics think it is an unworkable goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustainable development is just another word for no
development,'' said Sam Staley, an economic analyst for the Buckeye
Institute for Public Policy Research, a national conservative think
tank located in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sustainability is being used in the wrong way, it assumes we
know what is sustainable,'' Staley said. ``The market is still the
best determiner of what people want. When you inject the political
process, it gets much messier.'' Reversing a powerful trend. UD's
Weiler observed that sustainable development in the Miami Valley
would be asking the region to ``reverse quite a powerful trend.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With urban flight we have a very decentralized economy here,''
Weiler said. ``I have sympathy for Dayton, but the only real hope
for Dayton is growth in the region. For that reason I think it
should become a strong advocate for regional development and hope
its fortunes rise with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Places like Portland and Seattle have resurrected the idea of
urban service boundaries, basically a line drawn around a city to
spur development within and preserve farmland and open space
outside. The rapid rise of new suburbs in the counties surrounding
Dayton, however, threatens to further decentralize the region and
make it that much tougher to pull communities together for
solutions to common problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton's opposition to the proposed beltway through western
Montgomery County, Ohio 892, and concern over new water-pumping
plants in the suburbs are examples of two prime weapons _ water and
land use _ being up for grabs in the '90s free-for-all over
development.
</P>
<P>
   So where to go from here?
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley may never be a Silicon Valley or a Golden
Triangle of high-tech manufacturing and education. Perhaps Dayton
will continue its decline without much protest from its suburban
neighbors. But there are some ventures being talked about and put
into action that benefit the entire region.
</P>
<P>
   Tool Town and a brand new research park in Beavercreek are
moving ahead. Former military bases in Miamisburg and Kettering are
being transformed into research parks that exploit the region's
aeronautic and nuclear expertise in private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   And the bikeways and green spaces are gradually being linked
together in an effort to build and expand a Miami Valley asset that
will be around long after the '90s fade from memory.
</P>
<P>
   An entire, as yet unimagined, form of economic development could
emerge from these efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Ford took the emergence of electric power and made
incredible increases in productivity,'' said Traynor. ``We still
haven't figured out how to use the computer to make other things.
If we do, there could be this explosion of productivity again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
