<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7246 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-COURTHOUSES-BOS &LR;      07-15 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURTHOUSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE TO SPEND $700 MILLION TO REFURBISH COURTHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After years of delay, legislative leaders have reached
agreement on a deal to spend almost $700 million renovating
courthouses across the state, restoring some of the oldest and most
dilapidated public buildings in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham and House Speaker Thomas
M. Finneran hammered out a compromise that allows the project to go
forward, three years after it was first proposed. Birmingham and
Finneran agreed that some of the major projects will be performed
by union labor, resolving the main issue that had delayed the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The $685.3 million bond issue has been a priority for years
among court workers, lawyers, and judges who have argued that the
poor condition of Massachusetts courthouses impedes the
administration of justice and puts workers and the public at risk
every working day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been in courthouses around the state and the notion
that justice can be dispensed in some of these venues is hard to
imagine,'' Birmingham said. ``I thought the courthouse in Chelsea
had to be the worst, then you go to Worcester and they are
conducting criminal trials in what looks like a big walk-in
closet.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of the courthouses in Massachusetts are over
50 years old, and 13 are more than a century old. None of them has
ever seen a renovation crew. Horror stories abound among all those
who spend their lives in court.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Leahy, the general counsel of the Massachusetts Bar
Association, said the renovations are badly needed. ``We really are
dealing with horrendous conditions that they must even work in or
come into contact with as users,'' Leahy said. ``The courthouses
are antiquated and this is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   The major sticking point had been the role of organized labor in
the projects. Under the deal hammered out Wednesday, four major
projects _ with a total cash value of $270 million _ will be
subject to ``project labor agreements,'' which mandate that union
workers perform the work. The other projects will not require
union-only labor.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements also spell out work rules, including wages and
hours, and generally prohibit strikes or other job actions.
Essentially, unions agree not to delay projects _ and run up costs
_ in return for guarantees of work.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has languished since former governor William F. Weld
vetoed an earlier version of it last year on the grounds that the
labor agreements discriminated against minority workers, who have
historically made up a tiny percentage of the organized labor force
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Outraged proponents of the bill immediately accused Weld of
blocking the bill because it was too favorable to labor, while
wrapping his opposition in the mantle of equal opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The measure, which does not require a vote by the full House
or Senate, will likely reach Acting Governor Paul Cellucci this
week. Cellucci will certainly sign it, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Landolfi, the spokesman for the Office of Administration and
Finance, said the plan is to allocate $70 million to $100 million a
year until the project is completed. The schedule for the project
has not yet been worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with this,'' Landolfi said. ``This is a
priority,. This is good news for the taxpayers and, of course, for
the courthouses.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill had already passed both chambers of the Legislature and
was technically referred to a conference committee. But rather than
appoint a committee, Birmingham and Finneran simply cut the deal
themselves, as they have on other major bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
