<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 7/15/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MOUNTAIN HOME, Idaho -- July 15, 1998 --
USAF-PILOT-TRAINING-2, 7-15 -- Terry Gibson, of the governing
council of the Shoshone-Pauite Tribes in the Duck Valley
Reservation in Idaho. Gibson says that the United States Air Force
does not appreciate the land's significance. ``To them, this is all
desolate -- rocks and scrub land,'' he says. ``But to us, this is
our bible.'' The Air Force is running into opposition from
ranchers, environmentalists, and Native Americans who believe the
roar of fast, low-flying jets is disrupting some of the nation's
last refuges of peace and quiet. (Glenn Oakley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) MOUNTAIN HOME, Idaho -- July 15, 1998 --
USAF-PILOT-TRAINING-1, 7-15 -- In southern Idaho, F-15 fighters
practice bombing runs at the Saylor Creek bombing range, which the
United States Air Force says was built in an era of older, slower
jets. The Air Force is running into intensifying opposition from
ranchers, environmentalists, sportsmen and Native Americans who
believe the roar of fast, low-flying jets is disrupting some of the
nation's last refuges of peace and quiet. (Glenn Oakley/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1998 -- CONGRESS-RDP, 7-15 -- The
Senate voted Wednesday along party lines to reject Democratic
proposals to give more federal assistance to struggling farmers.
Reps. Sanford Bishop, of Georgia, far left, and Earl Pomeroy, of
North Dakota, and Sens. Byron Dorgan, and Kent Conrad, both of
North Dakota, and Max Baucus of Montana, were among the Democrats
from farm states who met with President Clinton about the
legislation to help farmers. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ROME, Italy -- July 15, 1998 -- FASHION-VATICAN, 7-15 --
Gai Mattiolo's models outfitted in Roman sandals and angel wings
during Rome's fashion week. If in the '60s and '70s the fashion
industry was echoing a social mood of rebellion and nonconformism,
today's designers say they are seeking to tap into the culture's
yearning for spiritual values, and in so doing happen to get the
publicity they are after. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland -- July 15, 1998 --
NIRELAND, 7-15 -- British troops clearing the fields near the
Drumcree parish church in Portadown, where members of the
Protestant Loyal Orange Order of Portadown and their followers have
been camped out since July 5. The demonstrators are protesting a
government order barring them from marching through a Catholic
neighborhood. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- July 15, 1998 -- TRAVEL-MAINE-AZR-2, 7-15 --
Pemaquid Point Light, 16 miles from the U.S. 1 turnoff from
Damariscotta, is breathtaking. The tower is only 38 feet tall, but
its placement on a rocky ledge gives it a focal plane of 79 feet.
Pemaquid tower flashes a white, 11,000-candlepower light beam every
six seconds and can be seen up to 14 miles. The lighthouse was
commissioned by John Quincy Adams and built in 1827. (Juanita
Welsh/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) YORK, Maine -- July 15, 1998 -- TRAVEL-MAINE-AZR-1, 7-15
-- An East Coast vacation to Connecticut easily can accommodate a
detour to Maine and a sampling of at least two of its treasures:
lobsters and lighthouses. The Cape Neddick Lighthouse in York on
the coast of southern Maine, dates from 1879. (Juanita
Welsh/Arizona Republic Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1998 -- DOWNLOADING-MUSIC, 7-15 --
Andrew Rasiej, founder of the Irving Plaza club in Manhattan, wants
to distribute club performances digitally. Performances could be
cybercast live or maintained as archives, with royalties going to
clubs and performers. ``You could create a chat room, collect your
old friends from college and watch and participate in a concert.
But you might not be able to slam dance against one another,'' says
Rasiej. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1998 -- HAMBURG-BALLET-REVIEW, 7-15
-- From left, Otto Bubenicek, Joelle Boulogne and Jiri Bubenicek of
The Hamburg Ballet from Germany, in ``All Our Yesterdays.'' As part
of the Lincoln Center Festival '98, the company itself looks
fabulous, thanks to an international influx of highly trained
classical dancers, including Americans. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- July 15, 1998 -- TROPHIES, 7-15 -- At left, is
GQ's Man of the Year Award made of picture show glass. At right, is
MTV Movie Award. Some say that he trophy glut reflects the growing
cultural obsession with heroes, celebrities and winners. (New York
Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- July 15, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT, 7-15 --
Lining a closet with aromatic cedar strips is an easy and
worthwhile project for any homeowner to undertake. The fragrance
will keep clothes smelling fresh and the natural resins in the
cedar, although not insecticides, will repel moths. Unlike moth
balls, the cedar will not have to be replenished. (Edward R.
Lipinski/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- July 15, 1998 -- PRISON-GARDENERS, 7-15 --
