<HEADLINE>
ALBERT, MSG NETWORK PUT CREDIBILITY ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ In the end, Dave Checketts was like a barker at a
circus.
</P>
<P>
   As president and CEO of Madison Square Garden, he oversees the
operations of four professional sports teams, most notably the New
York Knicks and New York Rangers, as well as Madison Square Garden
Network and Fox Sports New York.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts was presiding over Wednesday's return of Marv Albert,
who was hired by the MSG Network to anchor a nightly sports show
and do radio play-by-play on New York Knicks games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marv Albert is one of Madison Square Garden's stars,''
Checketts gushed. ``He is one of the elite broadcasters in the
history of the sports industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts was not lying. Albert is blessed with a glorious set
of pipes and over the years has received a truckload of awards for
being judged the best play-by-play announcer in New York City and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But since last September, Albert also has truckloads of unseemly
baggage, namely his guilty plea to a misdemeanor charge of assault.
Albert did not serve any jail time, but his sentence has been
public humiliation and embarrassment over what his own defense
attorney, Roy Black, described as unconventional sexual practices.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts talked about Albert's ``loyalty'' to MSG and
rhetorically asked how long a person should be punished. With these
emotional and philosophical issues addressed, Checketts also talked
about the real deal _ ``good business'' and ``improved ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   What Checketts really was saying: Good broadcasters are
virtually a dime a dozen, but a man who wears women's underwear and
bites his sexual partners against their will? Now that's something
New Yorkers want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. Have it your way. By restoring Albert to his profession,
Checketts has provided yet another example of why Charles Darwin's
theories are so utterly misplaced in today's televised sports
jungle. It's no longer survival of the fittest; it's survial of the
spectacle. In this twisted view, credibility doesn't matter
anymore, just as long the ratings are good and advertisers pay.
</P>
<P>
   But credibility does matter, and Albert has little. He is a liar
and despite Wednesday's apologetic words, he remains laughable,
unable to change the snickers and whispers that follow him
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Albert has no one to blame but himself. Before his trial on
felony charges of forcible sodomy, Albert stood strong and almost
defiant. ``I am confident that I will be completly exonerated when
these allegations are addressed in a public courtroom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert told a different story in court. He pleaded guilty to the
misdemeanor charge of assualt.
</P>
<P>
   The most damaging testimony _ which remains undisputed _ came
from P.J. Masten, a Hyatt Hotel executive. She told the Virginia
court in graphic detail how Albert tried to sexually assault her on
two occasions, the second of which occurred in 1994 in a Dallas
hotel room. Masten claimed Albert wore only a garter belt, was
``exposed'' and ``aroused'' and tried to attack her. She escaped,
but only after pulling off his toupee.
</P>
<P>
   Albert says he is a changed man. ``What I did was wrong,'' he
said Wednesday without really explaining what he did. He attributed
his change to therapy. He said he will continue the sessions
because they have helped him to get to know himself and feel
better.
</P>
<P>
   Albert conceded that it will take viewers a while to take him
seriously when he debuts on MSG network's ``SportsDesk'' Sept. 14.
But he remained confident that one day they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't control (the viewers),'' he said. ``But they will
understand that what I have to say is credible.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Credibility is not like a sport in which one day a team wins and
another loses. A person has it or he doesn't. Albert lost his, and
while Checketts and his assorted minions tried to put a happy face
on Albert's return, they clearly were anxious about public
reaction, especially from potential sponsors. Checketts said that
he informed a few sponsors and feels ``good'' about his business
decision. Checketts and Albert repeatedly claimed their excitement
for such a talent to be back on air.
</P>
<P>
   It will be exciting, all right _ just as exciting as watching
any other freak at the local circus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Manly covers sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
