<HEADLINE>
MATTERS IN JAPAN NOT AS DIRE AS SOME THINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Japan's political shake-up isn't a big deal, but for
Americans to understand why, they must understand a key political
difference between the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In America, presidents, senators and representatives are truly
movers and shakers attended by a retinue of policy experts. This
mass of brainpower employed in the service of Washington's elected
elite provides a counterbalance to entrenched bureaucratic power.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's system, however, lacks similar political equilibrium
because its elected representatives don't have the support system
enjoyed by their U.S. counterparts. If members of Japan's national
legislature, for instance, need guidance on economic reform
alternatives, they are as likely as not to end up seeking out the
bureaucrats who have created the system that needs reforming.
</P>
<P>
   The practical result of this lack of staff resources is a system
controlled by the bureaucracy. While this is true to some extent
for all governments, the power of Japan's bureaucracy is something
most Americans can't fully appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, when Japan's prime minister resigned after his
party's disappointing election showing, the future of economic
reform wasn't affected as much as most Americans probably inferred.
Reform will happen in Japan when the bureaucrats running the
country allow it to happen, and not a moment before.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, outgoing Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto wasn't
all that effective. While he talked a good game and looked good
playing his part on the international stage, nothing much good and
a lot bad happened on his watch. His recent waffling on the
structure of economic revitalization policies was typical of his
indecisive style of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The election losses that led to his departure mostly reflected a
dissatisfaction by the Japanese people with economic conditions.
That's not the same thing, however, as voting for radical change.
The Japanese aren't into radical change any more than most members
of other settled, stable societies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it's not as though the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party has lost its power completely. What it lost was a great deal
of face, which is no small thing in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. stock market seemed to take only momentary notice of
what had happened in Japan, going from mixed on Monday to a strong
rally Tuesday. The smart money apparently understands Japan better
than the pundits, and Wall Street's message was that profits at
home count for a lot more than political machinations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, though, on the bond-trading side, the Treasuries
market swooned Monday on speculation that the situation will get
better in Japan sooner than conventional wisdom anticipates. This
was a momentary triumph of wishful thinking, perhaps, and probably
won't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Meaningful change in Japan depends on the bureaucracy,
particularly the Ministry of Finance. There have been no
indications so far that the bureaucracy is keen to embrace the sort
of changes needed.
</P>
<P>
   What will change things eventually, however, will be the
financial market deregulation that recently got under way in Japan.
Events will overtake bureaucratic inertia and the second-largest
economy on the planet will increasingly operate in response to
market forces.
</P>
<P>
   All of which will take time, lots of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
