<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-HOMETOWN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN REALLY PUTS ON THE DOG FOR MICKEY MOUSE, WALT DISNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC WESLANDER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARCELINE, Mo. _ An inflatable pair of mouse ears the size of a
Volkswagen teetered over the gazebo in Marceline's downtown park on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Mouse flags flew everywhere, from Briggs-Cupp Chevrolet
to the Busy Bee Florist. The famous mouse ears perched on signs
along Kansas Street, renamed Main Street U.S.A. for the day. And
Mickey, Minnie and the whole gang paraded through creator Walt
Disney's boyhood hometown, greeted by a crowd of more than 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The event was to promote Tuesday's release of Walt Disney Home
Video's ``The Spirit of Mickey,'' a compilation of early Mickey
Mouse adventures from the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   But it also gave Disney an opportunity to reconnect itself to
the wholesomeness of small-town America.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Kough, manager of special events for Walt Disney Home Video,
acknowledged he crafted the event with an emphasis on small-town
America values in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``That includes values like family, togetherness, happiness, joy
and children,'' he said. ``Walt Disney wants to continue to provide
quality entertainment for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Even while maintaining its role as a leader in family
entertainment, the Disney empire has found itself embroiled in the
social, political and economic controversies of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Popular animated films have on occasion generated controversy in
recent years. Arab groups, for example, vigorously protested
characters in ``Aladdin'' and persuaded Disney to change one song's
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as Disney spins off subsidiaries and joins other
media empires, its name has become attached to a more diverse range
of projects _ some of which have upset defenders of family values.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax, one of Disney's spinoffs, produced movies such as
``Pulp Fiction'' and ``Kids,'' a raw look at teen-age sex. ABC-TV,
a new addition to Disney's fold, broadcast ``Ellen,'' which
featured a lesbian lead character.
</P>
<P>
   That type of programming, and Disney's offer of benefits to gay
and lesbian partners of employees, prompted boycotts from groups
such as the Southern Baptist Convention and the Assemblies of God.
Just this month, the Texas School Board voted to sell its Disney
stock.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, that meant some people saw Disney as
anti-family.
</P>
<P>
   In Stockton, Mo., about 100 miles southeast of Kansas City, the
high school canceled a band trip to Walt Disney World because of
what one school board member called Disney's ``pro-gay'' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   One national researcher said the Marceline event was no doubt
carefully planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't done accidentally, that's for sure,'' said Stephen
Hess, a senior fellow at Brookings Institute, a Washington think
tank. ``You could be sure that somewhere in Southern California
there were a group of people sitting around discussing (the
company's image). That's what they're paid to do. They're in the
image business.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Marceline reveled in its Disney roots.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformed cheerleaders from Marceline High danced in sync with
Chip, Dale, Goofy and the rest of the characters. Football players
wearing their Marceline jerseys helped control the crowd. Mayor Joe
Fotenos and the high school pep band greeted Mickey at the local
airport. In the park, the local band the Martin Family played ``God
Bless the U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The town will be the site of more Disney festivities soon. In
September, Gov. Mel Carnahan is expected to announce plans for big
festivities in 2001 to honor the 100th anniversary of Walt Disney's
birth.
</P>
<P>
   If the company is looking to improve its image as a family
corporation, Marceline is the place to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better spot,'' said Kaye Malins, who lives
on the edge of town. ``In Marceline, the gift that we give all our
children is a sense of place. They know they are responsible for
their town. There's no graffiti; there's no trash.''
</P>
<P>
   Business owners in the town of 2,700 spent the last few weeks
painting their storefronts and changing addresses on their windows
to read ``Main Street U.S.A.,'' after the main drag in Walt
Disney's Magic Kingdom theme parks. Marceline resident Shane Ware
said he counted eight ladders downtown Sunday on his way to church.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest crowd we've had that I've ever seen,'' he
said as he sat on a bench outside Hazen's drugstore, wearing a
Mickey Mouse T-shirt and looking a bit overwhelmed. ``This has
always just been my hometown. I've never thought of it to be this
big of a deal until today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just your basic small town. Everybody's friendly to
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   If Walt Disney's beloved Marceline is Main Street U.S.A., then
perhaps the fast-paced world of billion-dollar conglomerates, where
Snow White and Quentin Tarantino's foul-mouthed ``Pulp Fiction''
characters can live under the same roof, can be seen as
Tomorrowland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walt designed his parks so that everyone who went in would go
down Main Street U.S.A. and experience Marceline,'' Malins said.
``After that, you could decide whether you wanted to go to
Tomorrowland or Fantasyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone in Marceline who wanted a copy of ``The Spirit of
Mickey'' video had to leave Main Street U.S.A. and go to the
nearest Wal-Mart, a dozen miles away in Brookfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Residents can, however, watch the film at the Uptown Theater,
where it will be shown for one week.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Oscar Avila contributed to this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
