<HEADER>
A7261 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-A     07-15 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTHCARE-ART-1STLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs 9-12th grafs for new clarifying information, re-editing; subs
7th graf to correct time element, making it Wednesday, not
Thursday) 
SENATE REPUBLICANS INTRODUCE THEIR OWN BILL TO PROTECT PATIENTS'
RIGHTSs 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Republicans proposed legislation to protect
patients' rights on Wednesday, joining the battle with Democrats
and the American Medical Association who have sought much more
sweeping protections, including the right to sue managed care
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan, to be followed Thursday by a bill from House
GOP leaders, seeks to give patients a greater choice of doctors and
provide tax breaks to make insurance more affordable. But the
Democratic plan would cover 150 million people; most of the GOP's
patients' protection provisions would affect only one third as
many.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said he plans
to bring the measure, which is still being written and finalized,
to the floor before Congress leaves for vacation the first week of
August. But prospects for either the Democratic or Republican plans
remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not really interested in political games, we are
interested in serious quality health care,'' said Sen. Don Nickles,
the second-ranking Republican and chief architect of the bill.
``Some of the other proposals, particularly the Democratic
alternative, is well-intended, but the net result would be that it
would greatly increase costs, reduce access, and frankly, it would
increase the bureaucracy and the regulations by unbelievable leaps
and bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats reacted swiftly and forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary of health and human services, Donna Shalala,
called the Republican plan ``too little, too late,'' but added that
she hoped the two sides could compromise on a bipartisan bill. And
Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts, who helped draft the
Democratic bill, called it ``Gingrich lite,'' deriding it as even
weaker than the version House Speaker Newt Gingrich described last
month.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, at a round table discussion on Wednesday at
the offices of the American Medical Association here, listened to
the heart-wrenching stories of patients and doctors who described
their personal run-ins with health maintenance organizations and
pressed Congress to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, this is about even more than health care; this is
about how people feel about America,'' Clinton said. ``These
stories are not the kind of stories any American of conscience
would ever want to be told in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there are many similarities between the Democratic and
Senate Republican proposals, there are also stark differences.
Generally, the consumer protections in the Republican proposals
would apply only to federally regulated health plans in which
employers directly assume the financial risks for workers' medical
care, so-called self-insured plans. About 48 million Americans are
covered by such plans, most of them working for large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 million consumers belong to health plans that would
continue to be regulated by state laws, which vary widely in the
protections they offer patients. The Democratic proposal would
extend patient protections to all 148 million.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance and HMO groups did not waver in their opposition to
all the managed care bills, including Wednesday's proposal by
Senate Republicans. But they said they liked the ``new approach''
of limiting most of the protections to patients covered by
companies that insure themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the point of view of compliance and and costs alone, it's
attractive,'' said Bill Gradison, the president of the Health
Insurance Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican announcement comes just as Democrats are
ratcheting up the pressure to overhaul managed care plans in
Congress and on the campaign trail. In a rather lackluster election
year, managed care has emerged as one of the more tantalizing
issues before the November elections, and Democrats have seized it
to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbying by special-interest groups, including the American
Medical Association and insurance organizations, has been intense
since early this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the AFL-CIO announced it would launch a nationwide
radio and television advertising campaign backing the Democratic
bill. ``Insurance companies and HMOs are turning health care into
big business,'' one of the labor federation's flyers claimed.
``They get the profits _ and too often we get stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   For months Senate and House Republicans tried to sidestep the
issue of regulating managed care, which is unpopular with business
and insurance groups. But they found the issue was too popular and
politically perilous to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans organized a task force early this year to
begin studying the issue, but maintained there would likely be no
bill this year. That changed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to steal the Democrats' thunder, the Senate Republicans
virtually adopted the Democratic bill's title for their own. The
GOP measure is called ``The Patient Bill of Rights.'' The
Democratic bill is called ``The Patients' Bill of Rights.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans contend that the Democratic bill, sponsored by Sen.
Tom Daschle of South Dakota and Rep. John Dingell of Michigan,
would drive up costs and the number of uninsured, as well as lead
to unnecessary regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican proposal, which was released as an
outline, shares some common ground with the Democratic bill. Both
bills require that patients be allowed to see a doctor outside an
HMO without paying the entire cost and see that health plans pay
for urgent emergency room care.
</P>
<P>
   They also stipulate that pregnant women and terminally ill
patients can continue seeing their doctor, at least temporarily,
even if that doctor leaves the health plan, and they would permit
unfettered communication about care between patients and
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike the Democratic bill, those protections would apply
only to employees in self-insured plans. Republicans argue that
state laws already protect the other 100 million consumers, but
Democrats maintain that state laws are not uniform on protections
and patchy at best. And the Republican plan only permits direct
access to only permits direct access to three types of specialists:
obstetricians. gynecologists and pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than open the process up to lawsuits, the Senate
Republican plan would allow all privately insured consumers to
challenge the denial of medical services by filing appeals, first
internally, and then with an independent reviewer selected by the
managed care company. The decision by an outside reviewer would be
binding and would apply only to procedures that cost more than
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You simply cannot sue your way to better health care
quality,'' said Sen. Susan Collins of Maine, a member of the GOP
task force.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to conservatives, the Senate plan also includes several
new tax breaks. It would greatly expand medical savings accounts,
special tax-free accounts for medical care that are now available
on a limited basis. Democrats steadfastly oppose the savings
accounts, saying they will lead to inferior health care and are
designed for the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal also allows self-employed people to
deduct the full cost of their health insurance starting next year.
Sen. William Roth of Delaware, the chairman of the Finance
Committee, said the taxbreaks would be paid for in a
``noncontroversial manner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
