<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARATHON-SWIMMER-ART-     07-15 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-SWIMMER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ORDINARY GIRL,' UNTIL SHE ENTERS THE WATER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 (nk) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Nobody recognizes me with my clothes on'' is a
statement few people get to make with plausibility and a straight
face.
</P>
<P>
   But the marathon swimmer Shelley Taylor-Smith says it
matter-of-factly when asked whether she is recognized on the street
when she returns to her hometown, Sydney, Australia, usually after
winning a race or breaking a world record in a far-flung waterway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I walked around with my bathers on and goggles, greased up,
they would all go, `That's Shelley Taylor-Smith,''' she said.
``With jeans on, I'm just any ordinary girl.''
</P>
<P>
   A modest way of putting it, but it's a safe bet that no one who
has ever met Ms. Taylor-Smith walked away with the impression that
she was ordinary. Last Saturday, at 36, she won the 28.5-mile
Manhattan Island Marathon for the fifth time, seizing the lead from
two men in their 20s who were half a mile ahead. (She called it
``catching up the boys.'')
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, she set the record for both men and women for the
circuit around Manhattan, completing it in 5 hours 45 minutes 25
seconds and breaking the women's record she had set a decade
earlier. Five months before that, she had set another record (she
has set 15 of of them) for a grueling 53-mile swim from Sydney to
Wollongong, a steel town to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Taylor-Smith broke those records the same year she was told
that she had chronic fatigue syndrome, which she believes she
developed after contracting dysentery while competing in a polluted
river in Argentina. Instead of letting herself recover, she plunged
back into a 16-mile daily training regimen, kept racing and
eventually ended up hospitalized with fatigue, jaundice and a
series of infections, unable even to get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time, in a life built around overcoming
physical challenges, that Ms. Taylor-Smith had been forced to
listen to her body.
</P>
<P>
   And last February in Perth, the western Australian town where
she grew up, she hit a crisis point. She had begun training again
for a final Manhattan marathon but was exhausted. One day in her
car, she said, she slumped her head against the steering wheel and
struck a bargain with her soul: ``I said, `I'll listen to you; just
get me around Manhattan one more time.'''
</P>
<P>
   In what her friends call ``true Shell'' fashion, it was not a
deal she intended to keep; she scheduled other races through the
end of the year. But on Saturday, when she passed the Chelsea piers
in the lead, she said it all seemed too perfect. She would hang up
her goggles for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden I'm coming down Manhattan, and I'm winning,''
she said over breakfast on Tuesday in her flat, friendly Australian
twang. ``Never in my wildest dreams did I think I would end my
career on such a fairy tale note.''
</P>
<P>
   She admits that accepting retirement will be something like
going through the stages of mourning. Her career, which has made
her one of Australia's most popular sports heroes (a ferry line was
just renamed in her honor) has always been about pushing ahead
precisely because someone told her to stop.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Ms. Taylor-Smith had scoliosis, a spinal curvature
that required her to wear a back brace. In the water, one of the
few places she could be without the brace, she exhibited ``all the
grace of a wounded buffalo'' while her younger sister excelled, she
wrote in her autobiography, ``Dangerous When Wet'' (Allen &AMP; Unwin,
1996). But she kept at it when her sister lost interest, and she
was soon winning races.
</P>
<P>
   She received an athletic scholarship from the University of
Arkansas in Fayetteville, where she sold peanuts at college
football games and worked as a head waitress in a faculty dining
room to make ends meet. (She waited several times on Bill Clinton,
who was then the Governor of Arkansas.) When her back began
bothering her again, she ignored it and awoke one day from a nap
partly paralyzed, with a collapsed vertebra pinching a nerve.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pivotal point in her life. Before she healed, she lost
her scholarship. So when a former coach suggested that her stubborn
determination would make her a perfect marathon swimmer, she tried
it, and by the next year she had set her first record around
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Swimming for a living has never been glamorous or comfortable.
She blames her career for the breakup of her marriage to another
swimmer, Peter Smith. Advertising contracts and endorsements are
scarce in marathon swimming, which has never received the attention
of its counterpart on the land. So she has had to struggle to raise
enough money to live and travel to races.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike swimmers who compete in pools, Ms. Taylor-Smith has
also constantly worried about disease and injury in clogged,
polluted waterways. Over the years, she has been cut, bruised and
badly infected with dysentery.
</P>
<P>
   Though she says the waters around Manhattan are now among the
cleanest of those she competes in, for many years she assigned a
crew member on her follow boat to look out with binoculars for
hypodermic needles, condoms and other flotsam.
</P>
<P>
   There are few water horror stories she likes to recount, but she
will tell one: When she broke the Manhattan record in 1985, she
went back to someone's house to shower after the race. ``And I had
a noodle in my belly button, like from soup,'' she said. ``It was
disgusting. I was, like, how did that get there?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
