<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7351 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FERRARO-FUNDRAISING-5     07-15 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FERRARO-FUNDRAISING-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERRARO'S FUNDRAISING LAGS IN BID TO TAKE ON D'AMATO
</HEADLINE>
   (rm) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Geraldine Ferraro, who has repeatedly portrayed
herself as the dominant Democrat in the race for Senate in New
York, is struggling to raise money, trailing far behind both Sen.
Alfonse M. D'Amato and one of her Democratic rivals, Rep. Charles
Schumer, according to reports made public Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly two months to go until the primary, Ferraro, who
said when she entered the race that she would need $5 million for
the primary, has collected just over $2 million, with $701,000 of
that coming in over the last quarter. By contrast, D'Amato, the
Republican incumbent, has raised about $20 million, and Schumer,
$11 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the most direct measure of her financial position as she
enters the most competitive period of the primary campaign, Ferraro
has, after expenditures, just $1.1 million in the bank. Schumer has
$7.2 million on hand, while D'Amato has $12.1 million. Mark Green,
the third Democratic candidate, has the same amount of money on
hand now as Ms. Ferraro: $1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, in a statement on Wednesday night, sought to put the
best light on her fund-raising efforts, saying the combined
contributions to all the Democrats this last quarter _ including
Schumer and Green, the New York City public advocate _ were
equivalent to what D'Amato had raised, ``which means that Democrats
are just as competitive as Republicans this election cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed to polls that show her far ahead of Schumer and
Green, and said voters were not concerned with a candidate's
fund-raising efforts. ``Frankly,'' she said, ``what I'm finding is
that they're concerned about how much is in their bank account, not
how much is in my bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ferraro's financial report came at what clearly is
a difficult time in her campaign. Her campaign manager, David
Eichenbaum, quit last week, and many of her supporters have
expressed concern that her candidacy seems adrift. And the report
came after a period in which her advisers said she had kept a
relatively low public profile because she was spending her time
fund raising, both in New York and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The release of the financial reports was on a day in which
Ferraro, a former congresswoman and vice-presidential candidate,
had an unusually packed campaign schedule, which, intended or not,
distracted attention from campaign finances. She spent the morning
campaigning in the Bronx, where she was repeatedly recognized and
embraced.
</P>
<P>
   She attacked D'Amato's record on the elderly at a forum at the
Jewish Home for the Aged, at one point asserting, to some murmurs
of concern, that the senator supported placing part of the Social
Security system under private control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of problems with privatization,'' Ferraro said.
``The president doesn't support it. I don't support it. By the way,
Al D'Amato does. But let me say to you that _ or at least he did.
He may have changed his viewpoint rather recently, because he tends
to do that when he's running for re-election.''
</P>
<P>
   A D'Amato spokesman, Harvey Valentine, said the senator had
never supported such a step. An aide to Ferraro later said she had
misspoken and was referring to his efforts to change the Medicare
system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the other major race to be decided this year, it appeared
increasingly likely there will be a four-way Democratic primary for
governor on Sept. 15. Lt Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross and James
Larocca said Wednesday night that they had gathered enough
signatures to earn them a spot on the Democratic primary ballot
with Peter Vallone, the New York City Council speaker, and Charles
Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, who state Democratic leaders
had put on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to McCaughey Ross said she had in excess of 50,000
signatures, or more than three times the requirement of 15,000.
Larocca is said to have considerably less than that, though he
declined to release an exact number.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that may not matter; all four candidates said they were
not planning to raise legal challenges to knock a rival off the
ballot, though others could with the private encouragement of a
candidate. The deadline for filing petitions is today.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross also released a 30-second television
advertisement Wednesday, signaling the start of a long-awaited
television campaign from the former Republican who is seeking to
challenge her boss for his job. The ad is directed at women voters,
stressing McCaughey Ross' record on abortion rights and day care,
reflecting the calculation of her advisers that her biggest
strength in the contest is being the only woman in a field of men.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign finance statements showed two Democrats _ Eliot
Spitzer, who is running for attorney general, and McCaughey Ross _
are to a large extent using their own money for their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer has now raised $3.6 million, including $3.2 million in
personal funds. McCaughey Ross has raised a total of $3.6 million,
including $1.2 million in the first six months of this year. Almost
$3 million of that money came from her husband, the investment
banker Wilbur L. Ross Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor, George Pataki, reported that he had
collected $15.5 million. Vallone has raised $3.6 million, while
Hynes has raised $450,000. Larocca did not release his fund-raising
figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0532 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
