<SLUG> BC-MISSING-MILLIONAIRE-GRAPHIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY CLUES, NO ANSWERS IN SEARCH FOR WIDOW, 82 
 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) (rm) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Law-enforcement officials scoured the three New York
metropolitan airports and parts of northern New Jersey Wednesday in
their search for Irene Silverman, the 82-year-old widow who
vanished 11 days ago, but Police Commissioner Howard Safir said
investigators had found no hints of her whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity
said investigators searched parts of Newark International, Kennedy
International and La Guardia Airports. Safir, who would not confirm
the airport searches, said police had searched six acres of
undeveloped land in Mount Olive, N.J., owned by Silverman, but
found no new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of leads and lot of holes,'' Safir said. ``This
is a big puzzle.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir also said that traces of blood found on the sidewalk
outside Silverman's Upper East Side town house could not be used as
evidence, because they had been too damaged by sunlight to be
analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   One of Silverman's former tenants, Kenneth Kimes, 23, and his
mother, Sante Kimes, 63, are the leading suspects in her
disappearance, according to the police. Law-enforcement officials
have said the Kimeses, who were arrested on an unrelated federal
warrant accusing them of writing a bad check in Utah, may have been
trying to defraud Silverman out of her East 65th Street town house.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator who spoke on the condition of anonymity
Wednesday said that the police discovered blank deed forms and two
bank checks among Kenneth Kimes' belongings. The checks, one for
$1,500 and another for $5,600, were payable to the New York City
Department of Finance. The checks were dated July 2, three days
before Silverman's disappearance, and had not been used, the
investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   James Moses, a spokesman for the city Department of Finance, had
no comment on the checks. The department includes the city
register's office, which handles property titles, as well as
numerous other divisions. The Kimeses' lawyers, Jose Muniz and
Matthew Weissman, did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a search warrant prepared by the Manhattan district
attorney's office, investigators discovered a good deal of
potential evidence in the Kimeses' car last week. Investigators
said they are awaiting the results of DNA tests on a saliva-stained
pillow and a hair found in a large black duffel bag discovered in
the car's back seat.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to start up a laptop computer that was found in the car,
as well as inspect and check for fingerprints on hundreds of pages
of documents found in the car, also continued Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
