<HEADLINE>
DEAD MAN FEARED CRIME-SPREE SUSPECT, HIS LAWYERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MISSING-MILLIONAIRE) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortly after a Los Angeles businessman began to
suspect that Sante Kimes had taken out a fraudulent $280,000 loan
in his name, he received an ominous visit from a mysterious woman
and several phone messages from Ms. Kimes before he was murdered
last March, the man's lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   These contacts mark the first direct links that have been
disclosed between Ms. Kimes, the suspected mastermind of a wild
spree of swindles and murders, and the businessman, David Kazdin,
in the weeks before his death. One of the lawyers, Phillip Eaton,
said Kazdin had long feared that Ms. Kimes was ``crazy'' and would
``do anything,'' and investigators think that she and her
23-year-old son were attempting a similar swindle against Irene
Silverman, an elderly New York socialite who disappeared on July 5
and is presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   In Kazdin's case, the new information suggests that Ms. Kimes
was trying to persuade him to lie to cover her involvement in the
suspicious loan, which was being investigated by a bank in Florida
_ and that Kazdin wanted no part of what seemed to be an elaborate
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton and another lawyer, Martin Handweiler, said Kazdin
immediately suspected Ms. Kimes as soon as he became aware of the
loan. After Kazdin told the bank that he had not applied for the
loan, a woman who appeared to be working with Ms. Kimes knocked on
the door of his house in Granada Hills, Calif., the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Handweiler said Kazdin later told him that in this brief visit
in February, the woman simply said that ``you know you're
responsible for that loan'' and walked away without identifying
herself. After that, Kazdin received several messages from Ms.
Kimes on his telephone answering machine, though the lawyers would
not detail what she said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 14, Kazdin was shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Kazdin, who owned a document-copying business, had known Ms.
Kimes and her husband, Kenneth Kimes Sr., a wealthy motel owner who
died in 1994, for more than 20 years. The lawyers said Kazdin had
become caught up in Ms. Kimes' dealings only because he had once
done a favor for her husband and allowed him to list Kazdin as the
owner of one of several of the Kimeses' houses _ this one in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said they did not know why Kazdin had done this
favor. But Eaton said Kazdin came to regret it when the elder Kimes
told him _ probably in 1993 or 1994 _ that tenants had damaged the
house and that the Kimeses needed Kazdin to cooperate in filing an
insurance claim. Kazdin refused to make the claim, and he later
told Eaton that Kimes promised to take his name off the title.
</P>
<P>
   But Kimes died shortly after that, and unbeknown to Kazdin, his
name remained on the title until early this year. Detectives in Las
Vegas and Los Angeles now believe that Sante Kimes forged Kazdin's
name on the loan documents in late 1997 and got them notarized
improperly.
</P>
<P>
   After she collected the $280,000 in loan proceeds, she switched
the title of the five-bedroom house in January into the name of a
homeless man. Investigators say she also took out a home insurance
policy in that man's name _two weeks before the house burned in
what fire inspectors say was a clear case of arson.
</P>
<P>
   These transactions are at the heart of theft, arson and murder
investigations of Ms. Kimes and her son, Kenneth, that stretch from
Los Angeles to the Bahamas, where a banker disappeared in 1996
shortly after meeting with Ms. Kimes. Investigators suspect that
Ms. Kimes planned the swindles and pulled her son along with her.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
