<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNCIL HEARS TESTIMONY BUDGET SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Laying the groundwork for a lawsuit against Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, the City Council heard testimony Wednesday from
budget experts who said the city had far more money than the mayor
anticipated in his budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came a month after Giuliani vetoed $200 million
from the council's budget plan, saying it included reckless
spending that would create deficits. When the council swiftly
overrode the vetoes, Giuliani threatened to use his considerable
powers to hold down spending. He started two weeks ago when he
asked every city agency to look for ways they could cut their
budgets by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Council members have said that the mayor's actions were a
political vendetta against them, and that city agencies should not
suffer when the economy is flourishing. The hearing Wednesday, held
by the council's Finance Committee, was part of a strategy to force
Giuliani to start spending the extra money the council has allotted
for various programs and for paying off debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city shouldn't squander this opportunity to dramatically
improve its fiscal standing,'' said Thomas McMahon, director of the
council's finance division. ``You can't escape the fact that the
city is way underestimating its revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Newman, a deputy city comptroller, told the Finance
Committee that his office was expecting the city to reap at least
$800 million in extra revenues this year. Kathleen Grimm, a deputy
state comptroller, said her office was anticipating well over $600
million, while Douglas Criscitello of the city's Independent Budget
Office predicted an extra $685 million.
</P>
<P>
   The council also released figures showing that Wall Street had
reaped nearly $7 billion in profits during the first half of this
year, $1 billion less than Giuliani had projected for the entire
year. The taxes on those profits are one of the city's most
substantial sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the budget experts who testified warned against
spending the extra money, saying it should be saved to plug holes
in future budgets. They also warned that the economy could take an
abrupt turn for the worse, saying extra money should be used only
for capital projects, paying off debt and building up savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is not yet in hand,'' said Raymond Horton, president
of the Citizens Budget Commission, a nonprofit group that monitors
the city and state budgets. ``It is important to remember that
economic fortunes sometimes change in unanticipated ways, and
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for operations, said the
administration purposefully underestimates revenues every year in
hopes of creating a surplus. He said the city should save any extra
money to address projected deficits in the coming years. Lhota also
said the council had no grounds for a lawsuit, because city law
gives the mayor the power to ``determine how things are spent and
when they are spent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this bravado is a continuing effort to get Peter
Vallone's name in the newspaper,'' he said, referring to the
council speaker, a Democrat who is running for governor. ``This is
the beginning of the summer of silliness on their part, all because
it's an election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lhota said the council had been reckless in overriding
Giuliani's vetoes, and particularly in tucking a tax cut worth $200
million this year and $500 million in future years into its budget.
</P>
<P>
   While Giuliani often asks city agencies to find ways to trim
their budgets, he did so with more urgency than usual this year
because of the council's spending plan, Lhota said. The
administration will announce whether spending cuts are necessary
next month, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
