<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU, YANKS MAUL TIGERS 11-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Hideki Irabu loves sushi, all kinds, tuna and white
fish, and the night before each of his starts for the Yankees, he
goes for the soft stuff, his own ritual. On the mound, however,
Irabu's back to the hard stuff.
</P>
<P>
   His good fastball is back, and with it Irabu shut out the
Detroit Tigers on Wednesday night, 11-0, the Yankees' 16th victory
in their last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   It was Irabu's best outing in more than a month, and after
flirting with demotion last week, he once again is firmly
entrenched, after generating the Yankees' fourth shutout in their
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada had two hits, including his ninth home run, and
Chuck Knoblauch hit his third home run in six games. In six games
against Detroit this year, the Yankees have outscored the Tigers,
44-15.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (67-21) continue to match the 1902 Pirates stride
for stride: The teams now share the mark for the best 88-game
record in the game's history. If the Yankees won just half of their
remaining 74 games, they would finish the year with 104 victories,
more than any season since 1963, when the Yankees won 104.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Yankees complete the final four games of this 11-game
road trip, they will play 42 of their remaining 70 games at Yankee
Stadium, where they've won 33 of 39 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his start July 10, Irabu had concentrated on correcting
his arm angle, which had dropped _ from 12 o'clock, on the hands of
a clock, to about 11 o'clock _ and the velocity of his fastball had
increased somewhat. Afterward, Yankees Manager Joe Torre said he
thought Irabu had improved, but that there was still work to be
done.
</P>
<P>
   So, in his bullpen session last weekend, Irabu continued to
refine his fastball and also addressed his diminished command of
his split-fingered fastball: When he's most effective, Irabu gets
ahead in the ball-strike count with his fastball and then throws
his split-fingered fastball in the dirt, forcing hitters to chase.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a team he routinely overmatches, Irabu was at his best
Wednesday night, back to the form he had in April and May, the
scouts' radar guns behind home plate brightening with red, glowing
numbers like 93 mph and 94 mph.
</P>
<P>
   He threw strikes with all of his pitches, getting ahead in the
count enough to keep the hitters honest and then throwing his
split-fingered fastball, which had more movement than at any time
since the summer solstice.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu pitched into trouble only once in the first five innings,
walking Geronimo Berroa on four pitches with two outs, before Gabe
Alvarez pulled a double down the third base line, Berroa stopping
at third base.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu spun a curveball with his first pitch to the next batter,
Paul Bako, and it broke over the plate _ too low, according to home
plate umpire Marty Foster. Jorge Posada, the catcher, threw the
ball back to Irabu, who caught it head high and held his glove in
place for a moment or two, glaring in at Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu beat himself at times in this manner last year, obsessing
on the mound over ball-strike interpretation. Wednesday night,
Irabu climbed up the mound, paused, and then stepped to the back,
picking up the resin bag, juggling it a bit, looking down.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the rubber again, Irabu dropped the bag to the side _
last year, he would fire it down _ and returned to the business of
pitching to Bako. Irabu threw another curve, this for a strike,
pumped a fastball past him and then dropped a curve over again for
a called strike three, perhaps the first time this season Irabu has
finished off a hitter with his curveball. End of inning, and
perhaps for Irabu, the end of his in-season crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu had allowed at least one home run in each of his six
starts since June 4, a total of 12 home runs in that span. But he
did not give up a home run Wednesday night, and the Tigers' only
extra-base hit was Alvarez's rolling double. Irabu is 3-0 in four
starts in his career against the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Greisinger, Detroit's square-shoulder 6-foot-3-inch
starter, shut out the Yankees through the first four innings. In
the fifth, however, Posada singled and Chad Curtis walked.
Greisinger tried blowing a fastball past Ricky Ledee, and Ledee
offered a defensive swing, leaning back on his heels as he reached
out with his bat _ and poked a hit just inside the third base bag,
into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Posada scored, Curtis stopped at third, Ledee at second, and
both Curtis and Ledee subsequently scored on sacrifice flies,
giving Irabu a 3-0 lead. Tim Raines and Curtis had RBI hits in the
sixth inning to finish Greisinger. Posada blasted a two-run homer
in the eighth inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
