<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BATES-SIDEBAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATES SAYS PLAY WAS MOTIVATED BY TICKET BUYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVE IVEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Through the 15 seasons he endured savage
hits, broken bones and torn ligaments in the NFL, Bill Bates was
never playing merely for his own personal glory or just to support
his family.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when superstars often shun their responsibilities as
role models, Bates understood he was also playing for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect from the fans is all I have ever really wanted in my
career. They pay the money to come to the games and watch,'' Bates
said yesterday. ``Having the fans behind me, that has meant
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes beyond wanting to be liked, which he is without
question.
</P>
<P>
   If he just wanted to be popular, he did not have to play through
intense physical pain. During the 1994 season, for example, Bates
broke his left wrist against Detroit, and fractured his right thumb
against Washington. He remained in the game both times.
</P>
<P>
   That dedication, toughness and work ethic got the undrafted free
agent from the University of Tennessee through a Cowboys
record-tying 15 seasons and should help him in his new role as an
assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think of me as this gritty, hard-working stiff who
stuck around despite limited ability, that's fine with me,'' Bates
said. ``That's maybe one of the best compliments I could get.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he worked so hard, why he never quit despite being
written off so many times, he gave a thoughtful answer.
</P>
<P>
   He said to try to imagine that there is a guy out there
somewhere, a solid high school player with a chance to play college
football. But he never played in college, or even went to college,
because he had to take care of his family at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that those guys, if they were me, they would work just
as hard for this as I've done,'' he said. ``I want those guys to be
able to look at me and say, `Hey, I'd be doing the exact same
thing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bates, 37, never took anything for granted. Even after recording
84 tackles as a rookie in 1983 and being selected as the NFL
special teams player of the year, he tried to become a better
athlete the next year, and the next.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you lift the weights and run up and down the
hills,'' he said. ``I don't have the greatest athletic ability, but
God has given me a body that has been good enough to run with these
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Tex Schramm, the Cowboys' president when Bates joined the team,
noticed one quality that enabled Bates to run with anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Bates was one of those special people that made all he
has possible because of his heart,'' Schramm said. ``He didn't have
spectacular athletic ability. He just played because he had such
raw determination, will to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was last there, and the eight or nine years that
proceeded that, he was the one that wasn't going to make it. But he
had such a will and determination that you couldn't let that type
of person off the team.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Bates was the first NFC player to go to a Pro Bowl as a
designated special-teams performer. He recorded his career highs
for interceptions (four) in 1985 and sacks (five) in 1984. He
became the starting strong safety in 1986 and held that position
for three consecutive seasons. Bates was selected special-teams
captain in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, he is one of the toughest guys ever to strap
on a helmet and knock heads,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said.
``Bill is one of a kind. He will bring the same intensity to the
sidelines that he always brought onto the field, day in and day
out.''
</P>
<P>
   At virtually every training camp this decade, Bates has been the
subject of retirement rumors. But he kept making the cut, in spite
of the constant influx of younger, faster and stronger bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year ... the media has always anticipated whether I
would be on the field again. Every year, I have made it a personal
challenge to try to stretch it out one more time, one more year,''
he said. ``This year, I have the chance to be out on the field once
again and be part of a team that has meant so much to me and my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he will miss playing, a future possibility that hasn't
been totally ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision not to play for another season would be a tough one
for me, no matter when it was. Now is the right time,'' he said.
``I believe I will be as much a part of this team as a coach as
I've been as No. 40.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Kevin Lyons contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
