<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Casino tribes put money on Mauro
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Indians fighting to keep their casinos
open have pumped $54,000 into Garry Mauro's long-shot effort to
unseat Gov. George W. Bush, who believes the tribes' slot machines
are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's campaign finance report, filed Wednesday, shows that the
Tigua Indian Reservation in El Paso was among his largest donors
this year, coming up with $39,000 for the Democratic challenger.
</P>
<P>
   The Kickapoo tribe of Eagle Pass pitched in with $15,000 for
Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tiguas and the Kickapoos are law-abiding citizens who
operate within the law and obviously they support Garry Mauro's
vision for Texas,'' said Billy Rogers, Mauro's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Both Indian tribes, thanks to their casinos, are new to
high-dollar contributions to statewide candidates. Tribal officials
signed on with Mauro earlier this year after Bush urged legal
action aimed at the slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro went to Speaking Rock, the Tigua casino, in May to
criticize Bush's efforts and urge the governor to sign a deal in
which the state would get a portion of the profits. The tribes
claim their operations are legal under federal law allowing Indians
to operate any type of gambling that is legal in their home state.
</P>
<P>
   The tribes claim their machines are similar to games offered by
the Texas Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very evident that Garry Mauro will probably represent
the best interests of the Kickapoos better than Governor Bush,''
said Isidro Garza, a tribal spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kickapoo officials are due in Austin on Friday for a meeting
with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Tigua officials, unavailable for comment Wednesday evening, have
filed a federal lawsuit to get a ruling on their machines. A
similar suit filed by the Kickapoos produced a ruling last month
that their devices are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Kickapoo casino is remaining open while the decision is
appealed.
</P>
<P>
   The tribal money is crucial to Mauro, who is up against a
money-raising machine. Bush has almost 66 times as much money on
hand as does the challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has more than $14.5 million. Mauro has $221,659.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's report showed he raised $1.6 million in the first half
of 1998, including a $100,000 loan from Houston businessman and
former state party chairman Billy Goldberg. Mauro spent $1.7
million, more than half of which was for TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's top contributor in the first six months of this year was
Houston businessman Tilman Fertitta, who gave $60,000. Waco
insuranceman Bernard Rapoport, a longtime Democratic financier,
gave $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, whose report covered March 1 through June 30, showed
contributions of $4.4 million and expenditures of $3.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's top donors were Houston businessman Thomas
Soriero and A.J. Perenchio of Los Angeles, each of whom gave
$50,000. Perenchio is the owner of Univision, a Spanish-language
television network.
</P>
<P>
   The reporting periods for the two gubernatorial candidates were
different because Bush faced token opposition in the primary. Mauro
was unopposed and has not had to file a report since Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic challenger said the numbers look good and the
future looks bright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have built a solid foundation to raise an additional $4
million in the closing months of this campaign,'' said Mauro, the
state land commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said Mauro is not taking any cost-cutting steps. Joe
Cutbirth, the press secretary, left the campaign Wednesday, but
Rogers said it was not a financial decision. Cutbirth is returning
to Mauro's staff at the General Land Office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his substantial edge in the money chase, Bush wants
more. A current Bush fund-raising letter offers a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You and I must make certain the campaign has enough money to
withstand any assault by the governor's opponents,'' Don Evans of
Midland, chairman of the Bush committee, said in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript printed to appear hand-written, Evans added:
``Mauro has already gone on TV in selected markets and is moving
around Texas aggressively _ both signs that the national Democrats
and big labor have promised him more than enough resources to
sustain an all-out assault on the governor. We need your help
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reports indicate otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's cash on hand will not buy a significant TV campaign for
the home stretch. And the president of the Texas AFL-CIO said Mauro
probably cannot count on a major cash infusion from labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given what we think is probably close to our max,'' said
Texas AFL-CIO President Joe Gunn, adding that the group has given
Mauro about $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's latest report shows $37,000 from labor groups, as well
as $21,000 from the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gunn said he believes Mauro is a long shot, at best, he
wants the Democrat to put up the best fight possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think somebody ought to oppose (Bush). At this point, nobody
is opposing him but Garry Mauro,'' said Gunn, overlooking minor
party candidates who could wind up on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people go to Las Vegas, they play the long shots all
day,'' Gunn said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lieutenant governor's race, Democrat John Sharp reported
Wednesday that he raised $2.6 million this year, bringing his
overall total to $7 million. Sharp said he has $5.4 million in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   GOP nominee Rick Perry reported Monday that he collected $3.5
million this year, for an overall total of $6.7 million. The Perry
campaign declined to pinpoint how much he has on hand, but said it
was close to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
