<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS QUICK FEDERAL HELP FOR HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAX B. BAKER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ As temperatures topped 100 degrees for the
10th straight day, Gov. George W. Bush urged the federal government
Wednesday to expedite requests to declare more than 100
drought-stricken counties disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
   Of the counties seeking aid, only Terrell County in West Texas
has been approved, state officials said. A disaster declaration by
the U.S. Department of Agriculture would make farmers and ranchers
eligible for low-interest loans.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas counties that have asked for the aid include Ellis
and Denton.
</P>
<P>
   The drought has cost agricultural producers statewide about $1.5
billion in lost revenues, with a ripple effect on Texas' economy of
an estimated $4.6 billion, the Texas Agricultural Extension Service
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The losses are staggering. When you combine the loss with
1996, our farm economy is taking a serious hit,'' Bush said,
referring to the drought of 1995-96, one of the worst on record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a serious situation in Texas,'' said Bush, who was in
Fort Worth to speak to about 6,000 people attending the opening
session of the Future Farmers of America's 70th annual state
convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission is working
with water districts drowning under demands for service, Bush said.
The governor discussed the drought with the state's top water
officials Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency has identified about 150 systems that, because
of months of high demand, are reporting problems such as pumps
going out and water pressure going down, making it difficult to
deliver water to their customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to see demands (for water) in June that we
typically see in August,'' said commission Chairman Barry McBee of
Austin. ``But it stopped raining and got hot earlier and stayed
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures since May have been unusually high statewide. The
extension service's $1.5 billion estimate of agricultural losses _
triple the estimate in June _ shows that this year's drought is on
its way to becoming as economically painful as the $5 billion
drought in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some regionwide crop losses are approaching 100 percent on
nonirrigated dry-land fields, particularly in the major cotton- and
grain-growing areas of the northwestern High Plains and the western
Rolling Plains, the extension service said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pressing hard. Like a lot of times with the federal
bureaucracy, we press and press and press, and hopefully we get
some response,'' Bush said. ``The long-term remedy is pure and
simple: rain.''
</P>
<P>
   The USDA is moving as quickly as possible to process the
requests it has received for disaster relief, said Larry Mitchell,
a spokesman for the federal Farm Service Agency, a division of the
Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell County filed its request for help in late April. By
Tuesday, requests from 65 other counties were pending before the
U.S. Agriculture Department. Bush had requests from 13 counties on
his desk, and 32 counties were preparing their appeals, state
records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those applications were prepared in June and July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very aware of the problems in Texas and the surrounding
states and are moving as quickly as we can ...'' Mitchell said.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell County learned Tuesday that it had been declared a
disaster area. Because they border the disaster area, Brewster,
Crockett, Pecos and Val Verde counties are also eligible for
emergency aid, a state official said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency loans that the counties will receive may be used
to cover expenses incurred to continue farming operations. Loan
repayment time is usually one to seven years but may be up to 20
years for production losses. Those applying must be able to
document at least a 30 percent crop loss, according to federal
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our farmers and ranchers it is very crucial, realizing
that quite a few producers took it on the chin in 1996 with that
drought,'' said Beverly Boyd, a Texas Department of Agriculture
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, some of the counties waited four months for
approval.''
</P>
<P>
   To help water systems that are struggling with the drought,
McBee said his agency is providing technical expertise as well as
identifying adjacent systems to which they can attach if a serious
water availability problem arises.
</P>
<P>
   The conservation commission may also expand a program being used
in the Rio Grande Valley to encourage water conservation, McBee
said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, the agency asks people to take shorter
showers, not to water their lawns in the heat of the day and to
wash their vehicles at car washes where the water is recycled, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Advice on how to conserve water is distributed in water bills
and through public service announcements on television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to look at as many ways as we can to make sure we are
thinking about every drop of water and if we are using it wisely,''
McBee said.
</P>
<P>
   To protect drought-stricken rural areas, Bush is also providing
$200,000 to the Texas Forest Service to fund matching grants to
purchase up to 400 dry hydrants, which offer rural firefighters
quick access to fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   Dry hydrants are nonpressurized pipes that are permanently
installed at water sources such as lakes, ponds, water storage
tanks and irrigation wells. The hydrants are invaluable to Texas'
40,000 rural volunteer firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
