<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-BATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATES BECOMES FULL-TIME COWBOYS ASSISTANT, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The intense work ethic and competitive
fire that first earned Bill Bates a job with the Cowboys as an
undrafted free agent 15 years ago put off yesterday's emotional
announcement for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   After laboring over a request by Cowboys owner Jerry Jones in
June to end his playing career and join the coaching staff, Bates
accepted a position as a special-teams coach, it was announced at a
news conference yesterday that opened the Cowboys' 1998 training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   One year short of setting a team record for most seasons played,
Bates said he wanted to play another year but realized the move
might be in the best interest of the Cowboys and himself. Bates,
however, did not call it a retirement and plans to continue working
out with the team. Jones said the Cowboys would consider re-signing
Bates as a player if there is an opportunity to help the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play,'' said Bates, who read an emotional speech
that nearly moved him to tears a couple of times. ``But to not play
another year would be tough on me, no matter when it was. I think
this is the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates added, ``You did not hear a retirement speech. I will
train and get ready to play. So if the opportunity (arises) I will
be ready. But I'm not focusing on that. I'm focusing on helping
this team win as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the attitude that led the former safety and special-teams
star to make the Cowboys as a rookie free agent in 1983 and become
one of the most popular players in team history, Jones said it was
imperative to keep Bates in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bates will also help coach defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those skills that helped him do that I think could make him be
the chairman and president of many corporations in this country,''
Jones said. ``If you were in my shoes you wouldn't want to let him
leave your sights. You would want to keep him somehow associated
with your organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys wanted to make this move during the team's minicamp
in June. Bates resisted the offer then, as he clung to hopes of
getting a chance to make the team as a player and breaking the
service record. Bates holds the honor of 15 seasons with Ed Jones
and Mark Tuinei.
</P>
<P>
   Bates blamed part of the situation on his $325,000 veteran
salary, understanding that a team can sign two rookies for his
salary. He also cited the team's poor play last year, which
resulted in a host of changes.
</P>
<P>
   But because of his love of the Cowboys and his appreciation for
what it has done for him, he said he had no problem accepting a
coaching position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone who knows me and followed my career knows how
important it is for me to be a Cowboy,'' Bates said. ``I've always
tried to make a contribution and been willing to take on whatever
part I was asked. After meeting with Jerry and head coach Chan
Gailey and discussing how I could make the most important impact on
the Cowboys, I decided to accept a whole new challenge and become a
part of the coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates carved out a legacy, on and off the field, that dwarfs his
6-foot-1, 200-pound frame. He appeared in 217 regular-season games
_ second all-time for the Cowboys _ and recorded 701 tackles while
playing for each of the three previous Cowboys coaches _ Tom
Landry, Jimmy Johnson and Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   He was selected NFL special-teams player of the year in 1983 and
1984. In 1984, he became the first NFC player to be selected to the
Pro Bowl as a special-teams performer, and his play in that arena
is credited as a reason the NFL added special-teams players to the
Pro Bowl roster.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Brandt, the Cowboys' former director of player personnel,
said Bates had a way of making people notice him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Bill's first camp with us,'' Brandt said. ``We had
a bunch of guys trying out, about 20 defensive backs. Bill's
40-yard dash time was not that good, and if you didn't have
scrimmages he wouldn't have made the team because people would look
at him and say he wasn't fast enough. But he worked hard to excel
and he stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, Bates has done work for many charity
organizations and he gained attention as host for annual Cowboys
pep rallies at the Bill Bates Cowboys Ranch north of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Jones acknowledged that the decision on Bates was not based on
talent. He said he believes that Bates could win a roster spot over
a first- or second-year player. Jones, however, said the move was
in the team's best interest for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys are anticipating tough roster decisions
to get down to the regular-season limit of 53, making it tough to
carry Bates. Jones also said he will not hesitate to re-sign Bates
if the need arises, but ruled out a ceremonial move during the
season just to allow Bates to get the service record.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to, and we would like him to, make an on-the-field
contribution this year and do some things that would mean a lot to
all of us and extend the playing record,'' Jones said. ``But this
isn't a token thing we are talking about, because this isn't a
token season about anything. We are trying to win a Super Bowl.
Bates will make a valuable contribution one way or another.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Kevin Lyons contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
