A7416 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAHN-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAHN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Rising From the Ashes of Borland   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
For Philippe Kahn, redemption fits in a shirt pocket.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three and a half years after being crucified over the troubles
of Borland International, Kahn has rebounded, thanks to technology
that runs a credit card-sized personal organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The organizer, called Rex, uses an operating system from
Starfish Software, the company that Kahn sold to Motorola this week
for several hundred million dollars. Motorola plans to build Rex's
information-sharing technology into millions of cellular phones and
pagers in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout lifts the mantel of failure that Kahn has carried
ever since Borland _ the company he built into one of the largest
software-makers in the world _ ousted him as chief executive in
January of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the 46-year-old French-born Kahn found himself in
the media spotlight for the first time since the dark days when
Borland was going down the tubes and the media was clamoring for
his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to managing all these phone calls anymore,'' he
said jokingly as he juggled two calls during a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Borland cut him loose, the Scotts Valley company had
been losing gobs of money for two years and its revenues were
falling steadily. It was apparent that though he was a technical
whiz (with two degrees in mathematics), Kahn didn't have the right
stuff to manage a nearly $500 million company with 3,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   He was guilty of strategic blunders, such as trying to
under-price Microsoft products, and his decision to acquire
Ashton-Tate turned into folly because of delays in producing a
Windows version of that company's popular dBase database program.
</P>
<P>
   Borland continued to skid after Kahn's departure. Today, it is a
small maker of software-development tools. It recently changed its
name to Inprise Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As his life at Borland was unraveling, Kahn co-founded Starfish
with Sonia Lee, a graphic designer whom he eventually would marry.
The new company, also based in Scotts Valley, gave him a chance to
do what he does best _ create technology in an intimate setting
where business didn't get in the way of science.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three and a half years ago, a lot of people were saying life
was over for Philippe,'' says industry analyst David Coursey, a
friend of Kahn's. ``But as soon as he settled into something
smaller and development-oriented, it was only a matter of time
before something good would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The past few years seem to have softened Kahn, who once called
himself the ``barbarian'' of the software industry. At the peak of
his fame in the early '90s, he was known for flying his own
airplane, playing jazz flute, staging a corporate toga party and
building a $100 million headquarters for Borland.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kahn disowns the ``flamboyant'' image that has followed
him around. ``Flamboyant!'' he says derisively, pronouncing it the
French way. ``I'm a very private person. Tell my kids I'm
flamboyant and they always laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kahn has maintained a low profile at Starfish, which has
just 100 employees. It kept its technology under wraps until it was
ready for market. ``It took us three years before Rex came out,''
he says, adding, ``Why would you want any publicity before you
build the technology?''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn has dubbed Rex, which was introduced last year, as the
first ``wearable computer.'' Manufactured by Citizen and marketed
by Franklin Electronics, it sells for for $180 (including a docking
cradle for a PC).
</P>
<P>
   The key technology in Rex _ the Starfish part that Motorola
coveted _ lets the device link up with other wireless devices such
as pagers and portable computers. It has the potential to turn cell
phones into smart phones that can store addresses, appointments and
other personal information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Kahn has scrupulously avoided any technology that would put
Starfish in competition with Microsoft, having learned at Borland
that it's tough to beat Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Kahn blames much of Borland's troubles on Microsoft,
whose spreadsheet and database software grabbed market share from
Borland products, including Quattro Pro and Paradox.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, people said the Borland guys were crazy, they
didn't know what they were doing, they were idiots,'' Kahn recalls.
``But what we've seen is that Microsoft became the Muhammad Ali of
the industry. A lot of great boxers lost to Ali, but that didn't
make them crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn says he has no plans to leave Starfish after Motorola takes
charge. ``Part of my mission is to help them pass all the
competition and be the market leader for digital wireless phones
and pagers,'' he says. ``And I really believe it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Coursey thinks Kahn will stay ``for a decent period of time. But
he adds, ``Something makes me think this is not Philippe's last
company.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
