<SLUG> BC-NY-TIMES-SQUARE-ZONING-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY COUNCIL PANEL OKS LETTING THEATERS SELL AIR RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Amid fractious negotiations with the theater
industry, property owners and neighborhood residents, a City
Council committee Wednesday scaled back, but then approved, a plan
to allow the sale of air rights from landmark theaters in the area
around Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, advocated by many in the theater industry as a way to
preserve theaters and promote small, high-quality productions, had
provoked passionate debate. On Tuesday, actor Tony Randall and
composer Stephen Sondheim testified in favor of it, and several
residents of Clinton, the neighborhood on the west side of the
Theater District, said they feared being overwhelmed by traffic and
new skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the version approved by the City Council's Land Use
Committee, and expected to be approved next month by the full
Council, was modified to placate Clinton residents and other
interests as well.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of Council members who said Broadway has
become alien territory to New Yorkers of modest means, the plan
included a provision that would dedicate some of the money raised
from developers to providing discount tickets for residents of
neighborhoods above 96th Street in Manhattan and in the city's
other boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had to confront very conflicting pressures,'' said
Council member Walter McCaffrey, chairman of the Land Use
Committee. ``This version strikes the best chord possible.''
</P>
<P>
   As an untested attempt to meld development incentives with
support for cultural institutions, the plan leaves large financial
questions unanswered. Chief among them is how much developers would
pay for the theaters' air rights, and if any such transactions
would occur.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, supported by both Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and
Council Speaker Peter Vallone, the owners of many theaters in an
area would be allowed to sell the development rights, or air
rights, above their buildings to developers who would build far
larger apartment buildings or commercial structures on the same
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   For any money that would be raised from the sale of those
rights, the plan provides broad outlines for how it would be used
to support the theater industry. Theater owners, whose financial
gain from the sale of their air rights could extend into millions
of dollars, would be required to turn over part of that gain _ $10
per square foot of development rights that they sell _ into a
city-controlled fund. The owners would also be required to operate
their buildings as theaters in perpetuity.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Money in the theater fund would be allocated for several
purposes. Part of it would be used to maintain the historic
theaters. Another part would be dedicated for programs to attract
more New Yorkers to plays; one possibility under discussion is the
creation of discount ticket booths in low- and middle-income
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Another component of the plan would reserve some of the money
for direct financial support of producers and theatrical companies
working on plays and small-scale musicals _ the sort of production
that would not necessarily be expected to attract large enough
audiences to make money but would still elevate the quality of
theater in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In that role, the plan brings the city into a novel coalition
with powerful forces in the theater industry, where a large group
of producers, theater owners, unions and actors' organizations has
formed an organization, called Broadway Initiative, to generate
funds from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Although that group has not disclosed its plan in final form,
Joey Parnes, the group's coordinator, said Wednesday that it
planned to start fund-raising programs before the end of the year
that might include collecting fees from within the industry based
on things like ticket sales or union dues.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan approved Wednesday wins final approval, its fund
would be separate from that of Broadway Initiative and controlled
by an eight-member Theater Subdistrict Council appointed by the
mayor and other elected officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
