<HEADLINE>
LITERARY LONG ISLAND  
 OLD-SCHOOL TYPES  
 TRASH TALK  
 COMMISH VS. COMMISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH ALEX KUCZYNSKI, MONIQUE P. YAZIGI AND DAVID
KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crowd at the party for Victoria Gotti's second
whodunit, ``I'll Be Watching You,'' split into two distinct camps:
literary types, who favored rumpled seersucker suits and
horn-rimmed glasses held together with Scotch tape, and a more
snappily dressed group that included Ms. Gotti's friends Diane and
Carl Gambino; her husband, Carmine Agnello, and her aunt, Mary
Gotti. A brother, John Gotti Jr., was invited. But isn't he in
prison, awaiting trial on racketeering and extortion charges?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes,'' a Crown spokeswoman said, ``but we thought we'd
better put him on the list. Just in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gotti seemed unconcerned, choosing instead to discuss more
pressing issues: her dress (a tight black satin sheath by Bob
Mackie that would have put Imelda Marcos to shame) and someone else
who was not there, the author Nelson Demille.
</P>
<P>
   His 1990 novel ``Gold Coast'' was about a WASPish family that
lives on a big estate on Long Island and is drawn into organized
crime's web. ``I'll Be Watching You'' is about a WASPish family
that lives on a big estate on Long Island and _ well, there is a
father-in-law with shady business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gotti said that she had read ``Gold Coast'' eight or nine
years ago. ``You can't say you know Long Island unless you've read
it,'' she said. But she said the similarities were superficial, and
DeMille said by telephone Wednesday that he agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But the two authors do have something in common: a Barnes &AMP;
Noble bookstore in Carle Place, N.Y. Of a chance meeting between
the shelves, he said, ``I remember a lot of blond hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Alumnae Reunion
</P>
<P>
   It was billed as a party for the National Women's Cancer
Research Alliance. There were hints that it might include a
performance by Sarah McLachlan of Lilith Fair, the summerlong
``celebration of women in music.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a few moments, anyway, it was nothing more than a
reunion of Manhattan private school alumnae from the 1980s, as
Gwyneth Paltrow, who went to Spence, chatted with Shoshanna
Lonstein, who went to Nightingale-Bamford. Ms. Lonstein said that
she wants to spend the post-Seinfeld era designing strapless
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Crawford was circulating with her husband, Rande Gerber.
The waiters served water in martini glasses after running out of
tumblers. And Ms. McLachlan, like Elvis, left the building. Without
performing.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Never Sleeps
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Siegal can expect nice new suitcases real soon.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, The New York Post reported that her boyfriend, the
financier Richard Nye, had packed clothes belonging to Manhattan's
high priestess of publicity into garbage bags, which then landed in
the driveway of his house in Southampton, N.Y. The Post said Nye
was angry that Ms. Siegal had been out working the Hamptons party
circuit on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, the two were laughing about the purported clothing
defenestration as they celebrated her 51st birthday at Elaine's,
the Upper East Side watering hole. In a toast, Nye promised her
Gucci luggage to eliminate the need for garbage bags. The crowd,
which included Dominick Dunne; Nora Ephron and her husband,
Nicholas Pileggi; Regis Philbin, and Vera Wang, roared with
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ms. Siegal denied that the garbage bag incident
had happened, and offered her version of how she spent her Saturday
night: ``I was at a party at Bill Richardson's, and the only people
who knew I was there were me, Richard and the houseman.'' She
paused. ``So much for the houseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Police Czar Speaks
</P>
<P>
   Even after two and a half years in the big office atop 1 Police
Plaza, Commissioner Howard Safir is still chasing the well-tailored
shadow of his predecessor, William Bratton. On Wednesday, Safir
found himself countering Bratton's ideas about how the Police
Department should deal with the drop in crime. New York magazine
quoted Bratton as urging a reduction of 3,300 officers and giving
the remaining 35,000 a $100-a-week raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bill's a little lonely,'' Safir said after dismissing
the idea as ``fuzzy thinking.'' He added that cutting the payroll
would forfeit federal funding for 6,000 other officers. Besides, he
said, whenever the force has been trimmed, crime has climbed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
