<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Levi's May Cut More Jobs   By Carol Emert  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is developing a cost-cutting and staff
restructuring plan that is expected to result in additional layoffs
over the next two years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sources close to the company said the effort is designed to cut
$200 million to $220 million in operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco clothes-maker laid off 7,400 workers and
closed 11 factories last year in an effort to save $288 million.
</P>
<P>
   All divisions of the company are evaluating ways to shift their
resources, including personnel, to put more emphasis on marketing,
said Clarence Grebey, the company's director of global
communications. He said, however, it is too early to say how many
jobs may be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worldwide we are looking at a cost reduction program over a
two-year period,'' Grebey said. ``I am not denying that the
potential exists for there to be a loss of jobs, but there is a
positive there as well in terms of ... opportunities for people to
do new things within the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Grebey said Levi's has not settled on a definitive cost-cutting
goal. ``I don't want to say that numbers in that ballpark ($200
million to $220 million) have not been used in internal documents,
but they are by no means definitive numbers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be unfair and not accurate to say Levi's is
looking to do this (cutting costs by that amount),'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Levi's employs about 30,000 people worldwide, including 18,000
in the United States and 1,500 in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Levi's USA division is expected to finish its
restructuring plan in the next two months, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Many current staffers are expected to receive new job
descriptions and an undetermined number will probably be let go.
The company will open some newly created positions to outsiders. In
the past, the company has tended to promote from within.
</P>
<P>
   Despite cost-cutting efforts, poor sales of Levi's flagship
denim products pushed 1997 sales down for the first time in 13
years, to $6.9 billion. And sales do not appear to be improving
this year, although the privately-held company has not disclosed
any 1998 numbers. Sources close to the company said Levi's is
suffering from serious supply problems. A retailer said he was
expecting a large shipment of cargo pants in July for the crucial
back-to-school season but was told last month that the pants will
not arrive until September or October.
</P>
<P>
   Another source said only a small fraction of the ``hard jeans''
slated to be on store shelves for a big advertising push in June
actually made it to the stores on time.
</P>
<P>
   Grebey admitted that there have been ``wrinkles'' in the supply
chain, but would not discuss details. He said demand is strong for
the hard jeans but would not comment on the reported inventory
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the restructuring, Levi's is attempting to change
its corporate culture by encouraging employees to take more risks
and be more innovative in their thinking, Grebey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
