<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Apple's Profit Beats Expectations   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Continuing a dramatic financial comeback, Apple Computer yesterday
wowed Wall Street by reporting a quarterly profit that was almost
twice what analysts were expecting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bolstered by strong sales of its Power Macintosh G3 and cost
cutting, the Cupertino computer-maker earned $101 million (65 cents
per share) during its fiscal third quarter ended June 26. Analysts
were expecting 33 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time items, Apple earned $75 million (50 cents) in
the latest quarter. In the same period a year ago, Apple lost $56
million (44 cents).
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely gratifying to see results that match the
talent at Apple,'' interim Apple CEO Steve Jobs said in an
interview yesterday. ``It was sad a year ago, when we had just lost
something like a billion dollars. Obviously, some people had to go
and we had a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Apple's third-straight quarterly profit came from cost
reductions. The company has laid off hundreds of people, integrated
its Claris software subsidiary into the parent company and closed
its Newton unit, which made handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's sales actually slid 19 percent, to $1.4 billion in the
third quarter from $1.74 billion in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   But profits grew largely because the company was selling more
computers with higher profit margins, namely the Power Macintosh
G3. The company has sold more than 750,000 of the speedy computers
since they were introduced last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs said Apple is also benefitting from better sales
forecasting, more efficient manufacturing and a smaller, focused
product line that doesn't intimidate consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterly profit was Apple's third in a row. The company
earned $102 million in the previous two quarters combined. The
latest profit is the largest since third quarter of June 1995, when
Apple made $103 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Apple can make money in the current quarter, the company will
post its first profitable year since 1995. The company lost nearly
$2 billion in fiscal 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give Jobs high marks for the Apple resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve is like the cleanup hitter who drove in the men that
(former Apple CEO) Gil (Amelio) put on base for him,'' said Lou
Mazzucchelli Jr., vice president of Gerard Klauer Mattison &AMP; Co.
Inc. ``Some of what you see _ the operational cuts and efficiency
in Apple's organization _ was started under Gil's watch and carried
out by (chief financial officer) Fred Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people questioned whether Steve would capitalize on
the situation, but he has,'' Mazzucchelli said.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts say the company is hardly home free. They
point out that Apple's quarterly sales and unit shipments are
lagging from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The turmoil of the last few years may have driven away too
many fence sitters to Windows machines,'' said analyst Steve Dube,
of Wasserstein Perella in New York. ``Apple's primary objective is
to stabilize its installed base. Right now, they would be happy to
avoid further erosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are also concerned about the company's middling market
share. Apple's share of the domestic personal computer market has
stalled at 4 percent, according to Dataquest Inc., a San Jose
market researcher.
</P>
<P>
   But Apple executives insist the company's market share will grow
with the August 15 introduction of its $1,299 iMac home computer.
``Our sights are set on an aggressive foray into the consumer
market,'' Apple's Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Market researchers predict the company could ship as many as
400,000 of its iMac home computers by the end of September. ``The
reaction has been off-the-charts,'' Jobs said, pointing out that
177 software programs have been designed or updated for the iMac in
two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The table has been set for growth,'' said Charles Wolf,
director of equity research at Credit Suisse First Boston in New
York. ``And we will see that when iMac sales begin to take off in
the September quarter. Finally, Apple has some focus _ and Steve
has everything to do with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Jobs' performance as CEO has led to a groundswell of
support among Macintosh enthusiasts, developers, Apple executives
and board members for him to drop the ``interim'' from his title.
</P>
<P>
   But the Apple co-founder insists he isn't ready to take the
permanent plunge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several months ago, I woke up and decided that ... &UR;  &LR; I will do
as best as I can for as long as I can and not worry about what
other people think,'' he said. ``My focus is on my family, Apple
and Pixar (where Jobs is CEO), in that order.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company's stock _ which had sunk to $12.94 per
share in December _ rose $1 yesterday to $34.44 _ a
two-and-a-half-year high. Trading in Apple was halted before
yesterday afternoon's announcement. It will reopen today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
