u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-SEXSHOPS-COLUMN-N     07-15 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-SEXSHOPS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: CAN YOU JUDGE A SEX SHOP BY ITS VIDEOS? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a big question about female wrestling movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the women wrestle topless. Sometimes they don't. In
the former case, it is pretty clear to see how the movies fall
afoul of the city's new sex shop zoning laws, which give a precise,
indeed to some sensibilities practically pornographic, account of
what defines an adult video. But what to do in the latter case?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they wrestle with tops, is it sports or sex?'' asked the
troubled owner of a midtown video store who spoke on the condition
of anonymity. ``There are a lot of gray areas. There's questions
about spanking movies, about tickling movies. I really feel
violated by a stupid law like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals issued a ruling
that could allow the city finally to begin enforcing its new sex
shop zoning laws as early as next week. But rather than simply
throwing in the G-string, as many city officials had predicted they
would, sex shop owners are scrambling to get on the right side of
the zoning laws. Which is to say, they are busily trying to devise
ways to continue to sell sex without having their stores
technically defined as sex shops, or, as the law more
diplomatically refers to them, ``adult establishments.''
</P>
<P>
   They are reducing their stock movies like ``Squeeze Play,''
picking up bargain-basement tapes of ``Jacques Cousteau,'' debating
the finer points of foot fetishism and pasties and ordering up
Potemkin tchotchkes. As a man behind the counter at the Playpen on
Eighth Avenue said, only half in jest: ``We're going to order some
nasty T-shirts that no one wants to buy. We're going to be the
cleanest dirtiest store in town.''
</P>
<P>
   When the City Council passed the sex shop zoning laws in 1995,
at the urging of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, pornography itself was not
the target but rather the stores that peddled it. Limits were
placed on ``adult establishments,'' which were legally defined as
those that either devoted a ``substantial'' part of their stock to
adult videos and books or ``regularly featured'' adult
performances.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this distinction, state and federal judges
consistently ruled in the city's favor despite the constitutional
protections on free expression. But also as a result of this
distinction, enforcing the new zoning laws is likely to prove an
enormous headache. Just what do the critical phrases
``substantial'' and ``regularly'' mean, exactly, when applied to
pornography?
</P>
<P>
   An often-cited memo from the City Planning Commission suggests
that ``substantial'' should be interpreted to mean that 40 percent
or more of a store's accessible floor area is devoted to adult
material. But this is merely a recommendation and is, in any case,
open to considerable interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Would a store, for example, that gave more than 60 percent of
its space to dusty, overpriced models of the Statue of Liberty but
did its real business in briskly circulating videos of ``Riding
Lessons'' and ``Georgia Peaches'' be considered in compliance?
</P>
<P>
   How about a store that operated a busy row of private viewing
booths that featured ``The Sound of Music'' on six channels and
``Debbie Does Dallas'' on the other four?
</P>
<P>
   City officials have been profoundly reticent about how the nuts
and bolts of enforcement would be applied. Ted Birkhahn, a
spokesman for the city's Buildings Department, which would have the
primary authority for enforcing the zoning laws, promised to
respond to questions about how compliance would be measured but did
not do so, even after half a dozen follow-up calls. Similarly, a
call to the Mayor's Office of Midtown Enforcement, which was
referred to the City Hall press office, went unreturned.
</P>
<P>
   Sex shop owners themselves complain bitterly that their requests
for information have been unavailing. One owner griped, ``We're
changing our inventory to be in compliance, but the city doesn't
know what compliance is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the sex shops and their clients who have followed
the zoning laws through their three-year legal odyssey say this
lack of clarity is only going to lead to a whole new round of court
cases as shop owners test the city's as yet obscurely defined sense
of what is and is not an ``adult establishment.'' As Beth Haroules,
a lawyer for the New York Civil Liberties Union who has represented
sex shop patrons, wondered aloud: How would you define women
dancing naked but slathered in latex?
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really going to happen,'' she predicted, ``is years and
years of litigation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
