<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-JAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM AIMS TO PUSH PAK OFF SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. _ Coming into the JAL Big Apple Classic,
which begins here on Thursday, Annika Sorenstam has found out what
a difference two weeks can make on the Ladies Professional Golf
Association tour.
</P>
<P>
   After winning her second tournament in a row in Absecon, N.J.,
late last month, Sorenstam was not only the leading money winner on
the LPGA tour but she was also acknowledged as the circuit's best
player. That was understandable because she had finished in the
top-10 in 10 of the 11 tournaments she had played in.
</P>
<P>
   But then Sorenstam, a Swede who has won 14 titles during her
five years on the LPGA tour, finished in a tie for 41st in the U.S.
Women's Open _ which she had won in 1995 and 1996 _ and skipped
last week's Jamie Farr Kroger Classic in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Se Ri Pak of South Korea won the Open and the Ohio
event, where she shot a 10-under-par 61 to break the LPGA record
for a tournament round and finished at a record-tying 23 under par.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Pak, a 20-year-old rookie, has pushed the 27-year-old
Swede out of the spotlight. But Sorenstam will have an opportunity
to get back on track this weekend at the JAL Big Apple, in which
she finished second to Michele Redman last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-hole tournament at the century-old Wykagyl Country Club
offers $775,000 in prize money, of which $116,250 will go to the
winner. The 144-player field includes 41-year-old Nancy Lopez, the
Hall of Famer and winner of 48 titles, who will be paired with Pak
during the first two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Se Ri will play very well here,'' said Lopez, who won nine
tournaments during her rookie year in 1978, the third of five
consecutive events being the Golden Lights Championship here at
Wykagyl. ``She's a good putter and she's aggressive, and that's
what it takes to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez did not eliminate herself or Sorenstam as contenders in
the JAL. Sorenstam said Wednesday: ``Now that I'm married, I've
taken a new approach and taken more time off between tournaments. I
water ski and have a lot of other interests now, including my two
cats. And I feel refreshed when I come back.''
</P>
<P>
   That formula seems to have worked well, even though Sorenstam
has been overtaken on the prize money list by Pak and Donna
Andrews, both of whom have played in 16 tournaments compared with
12 for Sorenstam, the fewest for any player in the top-25.
</P>
<P>
   But Pak's presence has dominated the pretournament conversation
and speculation. ``What she's done is incredible,'' Sorenstam said
of Pak's astonishing recent performances _ a triumph in the U.S.
Open and an earlier victory in the McDonald's LPGA Championships,
two of the four majors on the women's circuit. ``And I'm glad for
her because we need new faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez missed the cut in her last three tournaments. Last year,
she won one event and finished second in the Women's Open. She said
she was ``very excited'' about being paired with Pak for this
event.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez was asked if she thought Pak would be under pressure
playing with her. ``I don't think so, not the way she's playing,''
said Lopez, who has had two top-10 finishes in 13 tournaments this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, Lopez and Sorenstam are far and away the biggest names in
the JAL Big Apple. The tournament usually draws most of the world's
top players. But this year, only four of the top-10 money winners
and 10 of the top 15 over all are entered.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ritts, the LPGA commissioner, said he was satisfied with the
field and added, ``We try to encourage players to come here, but
the JAL is right between the Open and the du Maurier Classic _ the
fourth and final LPGA major, which is played in Windsor, Ontario _
and some of the top players chose this week to rest.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
