<SLUG> BC-DEAF-IMMIG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR AFTER BEING FREED, 13 DEAF MEXICANS GO HOME
</HEADLINE>
   ( rm ) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
  MEXICO CITY _ As some of them raised the two-fingered sign that
means ``Hello, I'm OK,'' and as others simply looked dazed and
uncertain, 13 deaf Mexican men and women, along with four babies
born to them while they were in the United States, returned to
Mexico Wednesday for the first time since they were discovered
living in virtual slavery a year ago.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am very happy to be back in Mexico,'' said Alberto Vasquez
Avila, 21, using sign language that was translated by an
interpreter. Like the others, he cannot speak or hear. He wore a
white T-shirt with the initials NYC over a print of the New York
skyline and looked healthy, although tired.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexicans arrived at Benito Juarez International Airport on a
commercial flight from Newark that dropped them off at a government
hangar early this afternoon. There they were reunited with their
families in private, before a few of them were taken to the main
airport terminal to meet with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As their 6-month-old son, Javier, cried loudly, Vasquez Avila
and his wife, Anna Bertha, 20, told reporters that they decided to
return to Mexico because of the brutal way they were treated by the
leaders of a smuggling operation who forced them to sell trinkets
in the New York subways and beat them when they did not bring back
enough cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the United States because I wanted to work, but they
didn't help me at all,'' Vasquez Avila said, referring to the
ringleaders who controlled the lives of 50 deaf illegal immigrants
who were forced to live in two cramped apartments in Queens, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were many problems, many arguments,'' Vasquez Avila
said. ``We were all forced to stay in the same room and sometimes
they came in and abused my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the abuse was committed by members of the Paoletti
family, some of whom have already been convicted on various charges
connected to the exploitation of the deaf workers.
</P>
<P>
   Using the testimony of the deaf Mexicans, prosecutors in New
York brought charges against 20 of the bosses. Of those, 18 have
pleaded guilty, and two are in Mexico awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   There are still 35 deaf adults and six children remaining in New
York, as well as two more adults who will leave shortly, officials
said. The Immigration and Naturalization Service had held all the
deaf Mexicans and their children in custody since the ring was
exposed last July.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the agency agreed to allow all the Mexicans to
remain in the United States. Those who decided to remain have
applied for S-type visas, a special category that the government
uses for people who contribute significantly to criminal
investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Pinto, the Mexican consul general in New York, said all
those who returned Wednesday had made their own decisions and were
not pressured in any way. He said that besides the 17 who arrived
Wednesday, two others had asked to return to Mexico but were
waiting until the woman, who is eight months' pregnant, delivers
her baby.
</P>
<P>
   Scott A. Rosenberg, a Legal Aid lawyer who has represented the
deaf Mexicans in New York, said that many of them were afraid to
return to Mexico because they had testified against the ringleaders
and feared retaliation if they returned to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But some for whom family ties were the strongest consideration
decided to go home anyway. ``They have family, children and parents
that have not seen them in a long time,'' Rosenberg said in an
interview in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as they left the airport, the members of the Vasquez
Avila family were driven back to their home in Santa Barbara
Azcapotzalco, a poor neighborhood in the northwest section of
Mexico City, for a homecoming celebration. They have been gone
since February 1997, and their families had heard almost nothing
from them since they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a birthday party here,'' said Pedro Avila Portillo,
Anna Bertha's father, in a telephone interview from the house where
the party was going on.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the families gave the newly returned couple exactly
what they asked for, ``a big reception filled with happiness, lots
of music and Mexican tacos.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear to Avila Portillo and others that to survive in
Mexico and keep from returning to a life of selling cheap trinkets,
his daughter and the other handicapped people who returned are
going to need the kind of training and assistance that they did not
receive before. The lack of such assistance was one reason many
left Mexico for the United States in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Elva Leonore Cardenas Miranda, a deputy director of the
Comprehensive Family Development program, known as DIF in its
Spanish initials, said that the returning deaf Mexicans, and any
others who decided to come back, would receive medical and
psychological screening from the government. They will be taught
Mexican sign language, which is different in some ways from the
signs used in the United States, and will be provided job training
to help make sure they do not end up on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all things that have been available since 1995, but
these people probably did not know about them,'' Cardenas Miranda
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Valladares, Alberto Vasquez Avila's father, did not
agree that such services had been available, a complaint of many
deaf Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was overjoyed that the Mexican government had
helped bring back his son and was willing to provide so much help
now, but he reminded the government officials that the deaf were
among the most forgotten parts of Mexican society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico really doesn't have the infrastructure with which the
deaf can develop,'' Valladares said. ``I hope that all this
experience means the government will give permanent attention to
the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
