<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-CONGRESSMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FOSSELLA GOES ASTRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vito Fossella of Staten Island got elected to Congress last
year with the help of nearly $1 million in ``soft money'' from the
Republican National Committee. Soft money flows through a loophole
in campaign finance laws that lets political parties collect
unregulated contributions from special interests. The grateful
Fossella is now eagerly assisting the Republican House leadership
in its effort to scuttle any serious campaign finance reform. The
parties want to continue raking in money from tobacco, casinos and
other industries in need of political favors, and recycling the
money into issue ads for their candidates this fall. But principled
Republicans have united with Democrats to press for a fair vote on
a campaign finance reform bill now pending before the House.
</P>
<P>
   This week Fossella successfully sponsored an amendment that
would ban campaign contributions by non-citizens who are legal
residents of the United States. The amendment was billed as a
response to scandals connected to the last presidential election,
when foreign contributors apparently used legal aliens as middlemen
in order to help the Clinton campaign. But in reality, it was
simply another ploy to undermine the campaign finance bill itself.
</P>
<P>
   Like all big contributions to political parties, those gifts
were soft money. The reform bill would ban them anyway, along with
all the funds that came Fossella's way via the same loophole. In
the unlikely event that it survived a court challenge, the only
practical consequence of his provision would be to prohibit
non-citizen legal residents, many of whom are in the process of
applying for citizenship, from making small personal contributions
to candidates they favor. Fossella's district includes many people
who are, or used to be, non-citizen residents. He ought to realize
that it is the soft money, not the legal aliens, that poses the
threat to open and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   Undesirable as it is, this provision is only a minor flaw in an
exceedingly important package of reforms. No member of Congress
should hesitate to support the bill because of the amendment. But
Fossella's constituents might be wondering why their brand-new
representative is so busy protecting the right of big-bucks
contributors to buy elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-98 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980715.0553 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-15 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7437 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANLUIS-AZR &LR;      07-15 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE YEAR AFTER PUBLISHER'S SLAYING, MEXICAN JOURNALISTS PLEDGE
SOLIDARITY
</HEADLINE>
 LUIS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN LUIS RIO COLORADO, Sonora _ A year to the day since a
muckraking publisher was gunned down outside his newspaper, jour
nalists from around northern Mex ico converged on this crime-ridden
border town demanding that justice be served.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to continue Benjamin Flores' brand of crusading
journal ism, they also vowed to defy the risks of aggressive
coverage on the drug trade and corruption that makes reporting the
news in Mexico a dangerous profession these days.
</P>
<P>
   But even among those who con tinue the mission defiantly, there
is increased caution.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing for his safety, Jesus Blancornelas, a Tijuana publisher
ambushed in an assassination at tempt at Thanksgiving, skipped the
gathering. Back in Tijuana, his sons continue to cover the news for
Blancornelas' weekly, Zeta, under constant police and military
escorts assigned to keep them alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad that in this country a journalist can't move about
freely without fear for his life,'' said Norman Navarro, a reporter
who represented the Inter-American Press Association. ``This is the
true Mexico, where journalists die for their words.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, gathering the news has become increasingly
risky in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Flores was one of three Mexican journalists slain while
Blancornelas survived a machine-gun assault that killed his body
guard. An additional five reporters were kidnapped, several were
beaten, and dozens received death threats or were slapped with puni
tive lawsuits, making it ``the worst year for attacks on the press
in Mexico in a decade,'' according to the New York-based Committee
to Protect Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters have fared better this year. So far, only one has paid
for his work with his life.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the risk is ever-present.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Barraza, who edited La Prensa after Flores' slaying and
has since resigned to open the weekly Pulso in San Luis, says
reporters on the border are the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The border is one of the most dangerous zones for journalists
in Mexico,'' he said from his un marked office inside a modest
home.
</P>
<P>
   These days when Barraza and his colleagues take to the streets,
they look around before stepping into their cars and constantly
check the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we are at risk, but we're meeting our mission, and we
don't plan to stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation by drug traffickers has become one of the primary
threats to reporters. Both Blancornelas and Flores angered drug
lords by contin ually spotlighting the narcos' activi ties.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in press attacks also has coincided with the emergence
of a more independent press in Mexico that has become openly
critical of the government since the assassina tion of presidential
candidate Luis Donaldo Colosio in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But covering government and police corruption also can be haz
ardous.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Luis Mario Garcia, a Mexico City reporter for a
small daily paper was shot to death outside a federal police
substation while being assaulted by eight police agents. He had
been writing about the sale of federal police commander posts.
</P>
<P>
   The growing violence against journalists has led reporters
around the country to seek strength in numbers. Recently, a
national group, the Society of Journalists, was formed. Members say
they plan to respond to attacks by setting aside competition among
rival media companies to highlight coverage of individuals or
agencies targeting journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a message to the dark powers that reporters
are not alone and that the political and social costs of attacking
one of us will be very high,'' said Jorge Zepeda, editor of the
Guadalajara newspaper Publico, who will be the group's first
president.
</P>
<P>
   In San Luis on Wednesday, re porters also pledged solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may have killed one of us, but they are not going to kill
us all,'' Navarro said.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary of Flores' death started on a somber note, with
a visit to his grave at the outskirts of town where chaotic,
burgeoning San Luis gives way to a still rural, agricultural
valley.
</P>
<P>
   There, employees from La Prensa, friends and family members
tearfully set a bountiful arrangement of roses, chrysanthemums,
daisies and carnations over the tombstone and remembered the
audacious Flo res.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a public forum to discuss his murder, they formed a
plan for action.
</P>
<P>
   One after another, they voiced dissatisfaction with the handling
of the case by the Sonora state Attor ney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Many San Luis reporters believe the man charged with the killing
is not the actual shooter and say two drug lords who planned the
murder and several accomplices remain free and are not being sought
by police.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Palafox, a state legislator who was a friend of Flores,
said he will propose that the case be turned over to the federal
government during a meeting of the Sonora state Legislature on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Palafox was among those who remembered Flores as a ``commu nity
conscience'' who voiced the fears, complaints and concerns of the
citizens in his daily column.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the journalists said they will not sit idle.
They, too, plan to form their own investigative project calling on
reporters from various news organizations to follow up on the
unanswered questions surrounding the murder. &QL; 
Graciela Sevilla can be reached at 444-4783 or at
grace.sevilla &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
