A7441 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIM-SYNC-NYT &LR;      07-15 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-SYNC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 A MAN FINDS SUCCESS IN A `WOMEN'S' SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the memorable moments of television comedy: Martin
Short on ``Saturday Night Live'' as a synchronized swimmer, an
uncoordinated man with a silly fixed grin trying to crash a women's
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was funny,'' Bill May said Wednesday, ``because
I know what synchronized swimming really is. People know what he
did wasn't real and was intended to be taken as a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   May should know that better than anyone else. At 19, he is
Martin Short's character come to life, the only man competing on an
elite level in this water-ballet sport. On Sunday and Monday, in
the first days of competition in the Goodwill Games, May will swim
in the duet and team competition at a new aquatics complex in East
Meadow, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He and his duet partner, Kristina Lum, are also on the
eight-member U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Synchronized swimming traces its roots to ancient Greece, where
only men competed. In modern times, Stephane Miermont won the
French duet title in 1991 and 1992, and 85-year-old Fred Wing of
Lynn, Mass., takes part in masters competitions along with his
wife, Louise, 83.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, women have dominated, none more than Esther Williams,
whose many movies in the 1940s and '50s introduced the public to
synchronized swimming. A few years ago, when she saw May in duet
competition, she was impressed. ``You bring a new romance to this
sport,'' she said, ``and this is what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   International rules governing synchronized swimming bar men from
the Olympics and world championships. But American officials hope
that next year's Pan American Games in Winnipeg, Manitoba, will add
mixed-duet competition. If that happens, they will try to have
mixed duets added to the 2000 Olympics in Sydney as a demonstration
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Synchronized swimmers often hold their breath for a minute while
keeping their heads under water. In 10th-grade biology class, May
said, he once held his breath for three and a half minutes. On
Wednesday, after a team practice at the Asphalt Green AquaCenter at
York Avenue and 91st Street, May talked about being a man in a
woman's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot of support from my family and friends,'' said
May, who is 5 feet 9 inches tall and 150 pounds. ``The only thing
they say is that I'm so lucky to swim with all those women. I think
I've been received very positively. This is good for the sport
because a lot of the time it gets a bad rap. Some people don't
think it's a real sport, but it is. It takes hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   May grew up in Cicero, N.Y., near Syracuse. When he was 10, he
was in a swimming class, and his 7-year-old sister, Courtney, was
in a synchronized swimming class. Their mother would drop them off
together, and he had to sit through his sister's class before he
could swim. One day, he tried synchronized swimming and liked it,
and he switched to that.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school junior, he moved to Santa Clara, Calif., to
train with the Santa Clara Aquamaids, America's leading team. He
shares an apartment there with two teammates, Tuesday Middaugh and
Anna Kozlova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this sport because I loved it,'' he said. ``I love
the competition. I love creating new things. I love performing. It
didn't occur to me that not many men were doing it. Now I think I'm
just another member of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, May was paired with Lum as a duet, and they won
the national championship this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's exciting,'' Lum said. ``Hopefully, we're starting
a new era in synchronized swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   His U.S. teammates enjoy having him on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have the strongest people, and he's one of them,''
Becky Jasontek said. ``It's different. It took a little while
getting used to, just knowing I'm swimming with a man. I've been
swimming 17 years and I've never done that before.''
</P>
<P>
   And Carrie Barton said: ``It's great. It adds so much strength
to our sport. We're so used to change, and we want the best on our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone seems to like May, except for a few athletes who
say he is taking the berth of someone who could swim in the
Olympics. But he has heard only one person booing him. ``It was in
Tonowanda, N.Y.,'' May said. ``I was 15. I just won a competition,
and this one man in the stands booed. Then someone told me I had
just beaten his daughter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
