<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEE-PITCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S THE PITCH: YANKS' STARTERS BEST
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ On the nights he doesn't pitch, Orlando Hernandez sits
outside one end of the New York Yankees' dugout, his cap pulled
low, his eyes watching everything carefully, like a sheep dog
monitoring the flock. David Cone often stands in a corner of the
dugout, overseeing the mound, particularly when Hernandez pitches.
David Wells retreats to the clubhouse to watch Andy Pettitte, the
other left-handed starter, on a big-screen television.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' starting pitchers study each other and analyze
themselves to great effect. Manager Joe Torre's rotation, expected
to be the team's weakness at the season's outset, is its strength.
The Yankees' starters lead the American League in earned run
average with a 3.47 mark _ more than a run below the league median
of 4.71 _ and a 50-15 record.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' rotation went from good to exceptional on June 1,
about the time that Hernandez replaced Ramiro Mendoza as a starter.
Since then, the Yankees' rotation is 23-6 with a 2.60 ERA,
including seven complete games; it has allowed three or fewer runs
in 31 of the 37 games; it has allowed 72 walks and struck out 209,
a strikeout-to-walk ratio of nearly 3 to 1. Since June 1, opponents
are batting .178 with runners in scoring position against the
Yankees' starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I wasn't very happy with some of the mistakes they
were making,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach.
``But lately they've just been outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Joe Girardi said: ``They all have ability to bear down
and turn it up a notch when they have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre believes his starters compete with one another, that
a good performance by Cone will spur Wells. Pettitte said that part
of his frustration in May stemmed from the fact that he seemed to
be the only starter who was losing games.
</P>
<P>
   They watch each other, learn from each other. Stottlemyre
believes that the other starters have benefited from witnessing
Hernandez's ability to read the body language of hitters. Cone says
he is amazed how Hernandez is determined to make great pitches when
he is behind in the count _ ``he's absolutely fearless'' _ and Cone
has followed suit. They have all seen how Wells thrives with his
aggressive approach of challenging hitters with fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Cone is 13-2 over all, leading the major leagues in victories.
Since May 19, he is 8-1 with a 1.87 ERA. He has 111 strikeouts and
27 walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is that he's gotten his arm strength back,''
said Torre, who did not plan on having Cone until May 1 at the
earliest after the veteran pitcher had shoulder surgery last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The additional arm strength has enabled Cone to control his
slider, the pitch that is the foundation of everything he does.
Against left-handed batters, he deploys the slider to get ahead in
the count. Against right-handed batters, Cone uses his slider as
the coup de grace, the pitch that generates strikeouts and weak
swings. His fastball is consistently clocked at 90 to 91 mph, and
once as high as 92 mph last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was younger,'' said Frank Howard, a coach with the
Tampa Bay Devil Rays after years with the Mets, ``he had great
power stuff, just electric. But he's made a complete transition to
being a very smart pitcher with good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu led the league in earned run average into the
middle of June before slumping. Interestingly, the Yankees believe
that Irabu's problems were caused by his decision to try different
arm angles and different pitches, having seen the effectiveness of
Hernandez. Irabu had taken to throwing more two-seam fastballs,
having been impressed by the movement on Mendoza's two-seamer.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu was better in his first start after the All-Star break,
and he took the mound Wednesday night against the Tigers, watched
closely by his brethren. In his best start in a month, Irabu
shutout Detroit, 11-0, giving up only one extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, Pettitte was 6-5 with a 4.88 ERA, and his wife,
Laura, had just given birth to the couple's second child, in Texas;
Pettitte admitted to being bothered by his family's absence
throughout May. But he has turned around his season, winning six
straight decisions, with a 1.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi, who often catches Pettitte, said that the left-hander's
control is the best it has ever been. His cut fastball is chopping
at the hands of right-handed hitters, Girardi said, and his
changeup and sinker ``have never been better.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said, ``I've got a lot of confidence right now.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees signed Hernandez, they thought he would be a
No. 3 or No. 4 starter, good enough to be competitive, but not
dominant. Others teams saw less in Hernandez, projecting him as a
middle reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Little more than a month into his big-league career, the Yankees
and rival executives and scouts _ having seen his vast repertory
and the intelligent manner in which he pitches _ now think the
Cuban defector has the stuff to be a front-line starter on a
first-division team, and the Yankees have him locked up to a
four-year, $6.6 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   An American League scout who saw Hernandez pitch on Monday said,
``He's the best athlete for a pitcher I've ever seen, and he's got
a much better fastball than what everybody was saying in the
winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, the American League's starting pitcher in the All-Star
Game, has allowed as many walks (20) as home runs, and he is 11-2,
with a chance to win 20 games for the first time in his career.
Cone and Stottlemyre both believe that Wells gained something
intangible from pitching his perfect game on May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Stottlemyre suggested last week, it reinforced to Wells
just what a good pitcher he is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
