<SLUG> BC-NBAF-LATEEF16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yusef Lateef's ``The African American Epic Suite'' debuts in
Atlanta
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- That urge to merge concepts of jazz improvisation
with the compositional structures of classical music can tend to
produce work that awkwardly bends to one form or the other without
properly serving either.
</P>
<P>
   But sooner or later, the most ambitious jazz composers take
their crack at it, and even the flawed or messy efforts of an
Ornette Coleman or Charles Mingus can generate sparks amid creative
tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``The African American Epic Suite'' (1993), which had its North
American premiere Wednesday night in an Atlanta Symphony Orchestra
program part of the National Black Arts Festival was, in contrast,
smooth and tidy despite its often slow-moving 45-minute length. The
subject, nothing less than the 400-year history of African-American
life from pre-slavery roots to the post-civil rights era is more
easily evoked than realistically condensed in such a setting.
(Wynton Marsalis took three hours to deal with slavery alone in
``Blood on the Fields''). As such, this four-part suite worked best
not as comprehensive saga but in moments where musical ideas most
beautifully or jarringly cohered.
</P>
<P>
   It was composed by Yusef Lateef, the 77-year-old tenor
saxophonist and educator whose multi-instrumental gifts and
investigations into African and Asian traditions marked him as a
pioneer long before ``world music'' was a voguish marketing term.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the orchestra, he was joined onstage by his
four-piece Eternal Wind ensemble (Charles Moore, Ralph Jones, Adam
Rudolph and Adam del Monte), which played an encyclopedic array of
percussion and reed instruments, touching on cultures from North
Africa to the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   The effect, initially dramatic, felt somewhat routine by the
suite's final note; more stirring was Lateef's soulful outbursts on
the tenor, stark and ruggedly sculpted against the stately swell of
violins.
</P>
<P>
   Also purposeful was Charles Moore's solos on flugelhorn, which,
with the orchestral backdrop, reflected some of the chilled
grandeur of 1960s Miles Davis-Gil Evans teamings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
